<HEADLINE>
HACKETT'S FAST PACE A CHANGE FOR TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC coach Paul Hackett chose some familiar
adjectives as his first official day of training camp concluded
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enthusiasm. Energy. Positive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those were Hackett's quick impressions on day one of USC's
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The same could also be said of Hackett, who constantly paced
around the practice fields, supervising drills. He's walking so
much that he wears a pedometer to record the distance he travels
each day to determine if it will serve as sufficient exercise.
</P>
<P>
   If Hackett's constant energy is a change for the Trojans, his
decision to hold camp at UC Irvine certainly has shaken the team
out of its regular routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a change of pace,'' linebacker David Gibson said. ``This
year we're trying to do a lot of things different and this is the
start of it.''
</P>
<P>
   So were there any surprises on day one?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Carson Palmer had an excellent first day and Jason
Thomas made a nice recovery from when he couldn't go,'' Hackett
said, referring to his true-freshman quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas missed the morning practice after spraining his ankle
during Saturday's freshman workout but returned in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rendon suspended: Senior kicker Adam Rendon has been
indefinitely suspended and will not attend training camp, Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out,'' Hackett said. ``I'll visit where we are when we
get back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is not academic-related, and involves violating
team rules.
</P>
<P>
   Another kicker, Jeff Weichman of Santa Monica, is no longer with
the program after being sidelined with colitis.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury report: As usual, there were a few players nursing
minor injuries as camp opened.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Chris Claiborne is practicing only once a day to rest
a sore knee. Center Matt McShane and tackle Ken Bowen did not
practice Monday. McShane hurt his shoulder trying to move furniture
in his apartment; Bowen is sore after his car was rear-ended over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Darnell Lacy, who was academically suspended from the
Purdue game, has a herniated disc and might not return until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Antuan Simmons did not practice because he needed to
take his physical in Los Angeles. Offensive guard David Pratchard
of Canyon High School practiced in the afternoon session; he is
recovering from offseason back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're OK. There's a couple of bumps and bruises,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Receiver woes: With Rod Perry transferring and Windrell
Hayes' arrival pending, Hackett said he is concerned over the
Trojans' dwindling numbers at wide receiver. Since USC has a glut
of running backs, Hackett said he might move one over to receiver _
at least for practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get by with eight to 10 receivers,'' Hackett said.
``We need 15.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Soward speaks: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward's self-imposed
media blackout lasted all of 24 hours before he reversed field and
again spoke to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do it,'' a good-natured Soward said, after being told
by officials it would be wiser to speak than remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   __ Goux returns: Among those attending the first day of practice
was longtime USC assistant Marv Goux, who served on the staff with
Hackett in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   __ Iacenda ready: Fullback Ted Iacenda of Hart has completely
recovered from a pair of shoulder operations and will be ready to
participate when full contact drills begin Thursday. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
