<SLUG> BC-BBN-JOHNSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE WAS TOUGH ON JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He was the cornerstone of a franchise, a catcher
with exceptional skills, home-grown and full of promise, the symbol
of a city's baseball hopes and dreams. In time, he was expected to
bring a fistful of World Series rings home and an era would be
defined by his name.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was unceremoniously jettisoned, traded 3,000 miles away.
Incensed fans cursed the corporate suits who cut the deal and
mourned the departure of their irreplaceable hero.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza?
</P>
<P>
   No, Charles Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   When the Marlins traded Johnson to the Dodgers in the May 15
deal for Piazza, Florida fans lost more than the best defensive
catcher in the game. They lost a family member.
</P>
<P>
   Reared in Fort Pierce, Fla. Played at University of Miami.
Became the expansion Marlins' first-ever first-round draft pick in
1992 and proclaimed, ``This is like a fairy tale.''
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from their farm system and immediately began
collecting Gold Gloves upon entering the majors in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He belonged to us. He was one of us,'' a Miami columnist
eulogized at the time of the trade. ``He should have been the one
Marlin deemed untouchable in the fire sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotions ran deep for Johnson, too. And will again today,
when he faces his old team _ what's left of it, anyway _ for the
first time as the Marlins arrive for a three-game series at Dodger
Stadium. Johnson will then make his first return to Florida for a
two-game set next Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be very exciting,'' Johnson said. ``It's the place
where I grew up and had a chance to make it to the big leagues with
the Marlins. And the fans are great there. They treated me well.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months after the trade that shook major-league baseball
and two franchises, Johnson is sentimental about Florida but
grateful to be playing for a team with money to spend, a commitment
to winning and a realistic shot at the postseason. His old team is
sporting a league-low $6 million payroll, and the fairy tale that
took the Marlins to the World Series has become a B-grade horror
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The trade saved Johnson from a season of agony. But it also
pulled him a continent away from home, from his parents and from
his baseball roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Johnson said. ``But once I got out here, I
realized it's a better situation for me, because I have a chance to
contend here. The Marlins, they were in the process of getting rid
of all their guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Johnson, shipped along with Gary Sheffield, Bobby
Bonilla and Jim Eisenreich to the Dodgers for (temporarily) Piazza
and Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the Marlins in the process of dismantling, Johnson
hoped he might survive the salary purge and remain a Marlin, for
obvious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family,'' he said. ``My wife was eight months pregnant and
I was pulling her away from her family. And my mom and dad live
down there. It was difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But everything is settling into place for Johnson now. Rhonda
Johnson gave birth to Brandon, the couple's first child, July 27.
And the personal and professional challenges associated with the
move have begun to fade into the background. Not coincidentally,
Johnson's offensive game _ criticized by some fans and critics of
the trade _ is coming around.
</P>
<P>
   Through Sunday, Johnson had hit safely in 12 of his previous 21
games, batting .257 during the stretch. He hit his 16th home run in
Friday's win over Pittsburgh and went 3 for 4, with the game-tying
RBI, in Saturday's victory over the Pirates (``A very good sign,''
said manager Glenn Hoffman). His batting average for the season is
.209, but while fans fret, teammates are unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's down on his hitting, but the guy can hit,''
pitcher Darren Dreifort said. ``He was in a slump when we first got
him, but you've got to understand the transition that he went
through, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got rid of Piazza, what's he done offensively? He's got 20
home runs right now, CJ's got 16,'' Dreifort said. ``Just leave him
alone and let him hit. He'll hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Dodgers expected a .300-30-100 guy when they
obtained Johnson, a defensive gem but career .241 hitter. The job
of replacing Piazza's offense fell to Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who understood the game, they understood the trade,''
Johnson said. ``I didn't come by myself. So it was disappointing
that some people didn't realize that, but at the same time, the
players understood the trade... I came here to do what I do best.''
</P>
<P>
   Namely, defense. Throwing out 30-plus percent of baserunners,
blocking pitches in the dirt, calling the right pitches. The
result: Dodgers pitchers have a 3.62 ERA in their last 76 games and
have lowered the staff ERA from 4.10 on May 15 to 3.77 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just exceptional at everything he does back there,''
Dreifort said. ``He calls a great game, he mixes up the pitches,
location-wise he mixes it up real well. He's always thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Johnson will be thinking about his past as he steps onto
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I wanted to stay (in Florida),'' Johnson admited.
``I mean, that's my home. Who would have dreamt that this would
happen to the Marlins? But that's baseball. Baseball's all about
adjustments and you just learn to adjust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
