<SLUG> BC-FBO-RECRUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGER MANNING RAISES EYEBROWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ His father is the most revered football
player in the history of the University of Mississippi. And for the
past four years his brother turned the University of Tennessee into
Peyton's Place.
</P>
<P>
   But chances are that Eli Manning, a senior quarterback at
Cardinal Isidore Newman High in New Orleans, won't be spending his
college days in Knoxville, Tenn., or Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eli is his own person,'' said Archie Manning, Eli's father,
All-American at Ole Miss and former NFL veteran. ``It will be
strictly his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the favorite to land the 6-5, 185-pounder comes
from among Texas, LSU, Florida State or Ole Miss. But Eli has a
wish list of 10 to 15 schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for the best fit for me,'' said Eli, who turns 18
in January. ``It doesn't matter if it's north, west, east or
south.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Eli will equal Peyton's accomplishments _ including
challenging for a Heisman Trophy and becoming a first round NFL
draft pick _ remains to be seen. But, at this point, Eli, who
sports a B average and 1,070 score on the SAT, compares favorably
physically and statistically to his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Peyton threw for 7,190 yards and 92 touchdowns
in his three years as a starter. In his two seasons, Eli, who's an
an inch taller than his brother at the same stage, has compiled
4,887 yards and 50 touchdowns for the Division 2-A (the second
smallest) private school in an upscale section of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect this type of quarterback to come through your
school,'' said Tony Reginelli, Cardinal Newman's athletic director
and former coach. ``And you sure don't expect it twice. It's
unheard of, really. Both kids are once-in-a-lifetime kids.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Another son rising Another sought-after quarterback with a
well-known surname is Chris Simms of Franklin Lakes Ramapo High in
New Jersey. The 6-5, 215-pound Simms, whose father, Phil was a
Super Bowl-champion quarterback with the New York Giants, might be
the top quarterback prospect in the country. He's considering Penn
State, Ohio State, Texas, Michigan, Miami and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Buckeyes, 'Horns on roll: Ohio State and Texas continue to
lead the nation in early commitments with 11 each. But, with no
early signing period, there is plenty of time for recruits to be
swayed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Each player on Ohio State's list is from the state and all of
Mack Brown's Longhorn commitments are from Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
