<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-robertson-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Problems of spring &QL; 
a distant memory
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BACK in the spring, when the Astros' desperate need for pitching
help first surfaced, obvious solutions to their arms crisis simply
didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   You'd hear names, but none of them got a rise. At the time, the
Astros appeared about as far removed from the Randy Johnson raffle
as the Durham Bulls. Actually, Durham might have stood a better
chance of acquiring Johnson in March.
</P>
<P>
   The caliber of addition Houston could reasonably contemplate was
more along the lines of Bill Pulsipher, once a top Mets prospect
whose career had flatlined to the point that he was taking Prozac
to keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Hunsicker, who has a soft spot for anything Mets after
years spent in that organization, took a hard look-see at Pulsipher
anyway, then decided to pass.
</P>
<P>
   If Chris Holt and Ramon Garcia didn't come around, the Astros'
general manager figured, surely the Astros could piece together a
viable _ albeit reed-thin _ rotation with Jose Lima, Sean Bergman
and either Pete Schourek or John Halama in support roles behind the
post-Darryl Kile co-aces, Shane Reynolds and Mike Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. They could. The Astros climbed into first place in
early May and have been ensconced there ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Lima and Bergman are 10-game winners already _ the latter goes
for No. 11 tonight _ and Schourek did a serviceable job after the
rookie Halama was sent down, holding down the fort until none other
than Mr. Johnson miraculously landed in our laps.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher matches Hampton
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher ultimately made his way to Houston, although he came
wearing a Brewers uniform Monday night. He was the best Milwaukee,
the epitome of middle-market malaise, could do to bolster its staff
before the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   We in Houston know how that goes, having been a have-not for too
long.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pulsipher shut out the Astros for five innings before
giving up a two-run homer in the sixth to Moises Alou, who whacks
one of those practically every night.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher's six-inning effort was his longest stint of the
season, and he pitched at least as well as Hampton, whose
second-half doldrums have limited him to one victory since he
pulled a hamstring in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   That slump hasn't hurt, though, has it? The Astros held a
two-game lead over the Cubs the evening Hampton got hurt. It grew
to eight after Monday's 5-2 victory over Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, just another day, another comeback, another victory
provided by a home run _ Sean Berry's three-run blast in the
eighth. As manager Larry Dierker had joked the previous day, all
the winning is almost getting tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, right.
</P>
<P>
   This latest script was chock full of good stuff, an
embarrassment of riches indeed. Hampton had his best outing since
the DL hiatus, although one mistake to pinch hitter Brian Banks
cost him a chance to gain the win and possibly go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   At least he looked more like the Hampton of last year instead of
last month, when he was 1-2 with a 6.43 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Much closer but still no win
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not all the way back,'' he said afterward, ``but it's a
start. I thought I did a pretty good job of changing speeds,
something I've been having trouble with.''
</P>
<P>
   No complaints about his offense, however. He smacked his fourth
double of the season to raise his batting average to .262. Could
there be a pinch-hit assignment ahead for him?
</P>
<P>
   Although Hampton could have used the ``W,'' Scott Elarton's
earning it in relief was a milestone _ his first as a
major-leaguer. He foretells a bright future every time he ambles to
the mound. When Johnson is long gone, Elarton may well be the
Astros' staff stud.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of studs, Billy Wagner was Billy Wagner for the second
time in two days. If there are lingering effects of his being
smacked in the ear by a vicious line drive last month, the Kid is
keeping them well hidden. He mowed down the Brewers 1-2-3 in the
ninth, striking out two for his 23rd save.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks fine to me,'' Dierker said. ``I don't know how he
could look any better. And having Randy around is going to help
him. They're different body types, but they're the same kind of
pitcher. I've asked Randy to help him (learn to) use his slider,
and you saw that he threw it several times effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's easier to have confidence with a three-run
lead than a one-run lead. But the more he tries it, the better he's
going to get with it.''
</P>
<P>
   So here the Astros sit, 26 games over .500 and poised to put a
premature end to the division race. Amazing, considering their
angst in spring training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
