r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      08-11 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Apple's Chief Marketer Reveals Secret Formula Behind the iMac  
   
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The guarded interview was almost over when Apple marketing chief
Phil Schiller leaned forward to disclose the secret formula behind
the new iMac computer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a passionate _ some might say neurotic _ attention to
detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many meetings we had on the trackball,''
Schiller said, ``how we passed it around to make sure it looked and
felt just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent hours debating the colors of the wires inside the
mouse cable because if you have a translucent cable, the colors of
the wires matter.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think it odd that top execs, right up to Apple interim
CEO Steve Jobs, should fuss and fret over such minutiae, then you
miss the point. To Apple, the iMac is not just another computer.
It's an electrically charged piece of industrial art.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know their friends tell our customers they're crazy for
getting iMacs when PCs are cheaper,'' Schiller said.
</P>
<P>
   But Apple doesn't care about the naysayers. Its target is the
passionate minority who belive that Macs are and always have been
better.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Apple's short-term future comes down to a bit of
human calculus: How many people willingly will pay more for a
computer that makes a statement?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this belief in my gut it'll be more than 3 percent,''
Schiller said, referring to Apple's overall share of the PC market.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Pinup boy? &LR;  Playboy photographers just finished an all-day
shoot at the Atherton mansion of Oracle Chairman Larry Ellison. No,
it's not what you might think. Oracle's co-founder and fearless
leader and everyone else involved remained fully clothed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his fashion sense is why Playboy shutterbugs jetted out
here to dote on Oracle's head honcho. Playboy editor-in-chief Hugh
Hefner has selected Ellison as one of the best-dressed men in
America for a photo spread in the magazine's December issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison isn't the only Northern California notable to make the
list. Playboy photogs also caught San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
last week, at his sartorial best.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say others on the list include actors Michael Douglas,
Matthew Broderick and Will Smith, as well as talk show host Matt
Lauer and John Sikes, president of MTV.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Billion-dollar man?  &LR; Netscape Communications should be
strewing flowers in the path of former Oracle executive Barry
Ariko. News that Ariko will become Netscape's chief operating
officer sent Netscape's shares up almost 25 percent yesterday. It
closed at $31.19, a $6.13 spike.
</P>
<P>
   That made headhunter Frank Poirier of San Francisco shake his
head in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he's a great exec, but no one individual warrants
that kind of increase,'' said Poirier, chalking up the spike to
``momentum buying.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems no accident that Ariko left Oracle shortly after Oracle
President Ray Lane took control of the company's U.S. sales force,
an indirect snub of Ariko.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost respect for Larry,'' Poirier said, ``but
anyone at Oracle will tell you, you're either in or out of the
inside crowd there.''
</P>
<P>
   So now Ariko, who is on the outs at Oracle, has become
Netscape's most valuable insider. Jeez, four more days like
yesterday and the whole Netscape crew can retire.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; WELL written? &LR;  If you've never gotten the proper recognition
for your cyber-musings, take heart. The WELL, the online community
based in Sausalito, will award four $500 prizes for the
best-written short works on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be bashful about nominating your own prose, even if it
never made it to the WELL. The only rules are that entries must
have been written for an online forum and cannot exceed 1,500 words
in length. See  &LR; www.well.com/contest &LR;  for details.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Women wanted: &LR;  Women in Technology International has posted a
survey on its Web site, asking women in high-tech firms 18
questions about what they do and don't like about their jobs, and
what companies need to do to keep them in the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Women who are not WITI members also are encouraged to reply.
(See  &LR; www.witi.org/Center/ &LR;   &LR; Surveys/0898.html &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate &LR; sfgate.com). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
