<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Sorting Out Cybershrinks  
   
 By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
In these cyber times, you can find love and lose it, gamble your
fortune away or shop 'til you drop a bundle _ all without leaving
your computer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now can you get help there, too.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of therapists are setting up online practices
that provide counseling over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not therapy, but it can be therapeutic,'' said David
Sommers, a Kensington, Md., psychologist who went online in 1995,
one of the first to offer counsel by e-mail. Although Sommers
eventually found his Internet practice too time-consuming, more
than 100 other psychologists have since hung out electronic
shingles. That's generating controversy in psychological circles,
where many worry about the lack of controls or research on online
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The types of therapy offered online are as varied as the
therapists themselves. Besides individual psychotherapists, there
are specialists in the problems of clergy, sex offenders and police
officers. Many sites promise help with sex or relationship problems
_ and, appropriately, some even specialize in problems with online
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Some counselors answer a single question by e-mail for a fee.
Others do ongoing electronic counseling. Still others offer group
or one-on-one chats. Fees range from $15 to $45 per e-mail query.
Therapy by keyboard is no substitute for the real thing _
especially for those with serious emotional problems. (It probably
isn't much good for the Web-addicted, either.)
</P>
<P>
   But cybershrinks say their services can be helpful, especially
for people who live in remote areas, disabled people, those who
travel a lot, and those too embarrassed or rushed to see a
therapist in person.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Web therapy has provoked fierce debate among psychologists.
The American Psychological Association (APA) set up a task force to
study the issue and has scheduled two discussions on it as part of
its annual convention in San Francisco beginning this Friday.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``I think it's impossible to be ethical and provide services
to new patients via e-mail,'' said Marlene Mahue, a San Diego
psychologist and a member of the APA task force. Mahue, who
publishes the online Self-Help and Psychology Magazine at
 &LR; www.cybertowers.com/ &LR;   &LR; selfhelp &LR; , said therapists are trained to
read visual and auditory signals from patients and can't properly
evaluate people based on written text only.
</P>
<P>
   She also worries about the anonymity of the Internet _
therapists have no way of knowing exactly who it is they are
treating. Likewise, anyone can set up a Web site and purport to be
a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no supervision and no research (on Internet therapy).
People are just doing it,'' said Thomas Nagy, a Palo Alto
psychologist who teaches ethics at Stanford University's department
of psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   Many online shrinks share such concerns, and they urge patients
to proceed with caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the Wild West era,'' said John Grohol,
president of the newly formed International Society for Mental
Health Online. Grohol, who runs free mental health chats online at
 &LR; www.grohol.com/chats.htm &LR; , collaborated with Martha Ainsworth, a
Princeton, N.J., Internet communications counselor, on a Web site
at  &LR; www.metanoia.org  &LR; that lists online therapists and checks their
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Grohol and others are still excited about the possibilities
offered by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet offers a great way of expanding treatment
options,'' said Jeanne Rust, a Tucson, Ariz., eating-disorders
counselor ( &LR; www.edrecovery.com &LR; ). Rust treats patients in such
far-flung spots as Australia, Malaysia and Switzerland via
real-time Internet chats. She's planning to open an
eating-disorders treatment center in Tucson that will offer two
months of online follow-up therapy.
</P>
<P>
   She also uses the Web to keep in touch with her local patients,
who e-mail her daily with lists of what they ate and how they felt
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people will write me things that would take months
to say in face-to-face therapy,'' Rust said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
