<SLUG> BC-ELECTRO-GE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRO RENT SEEKS REFUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Electro Rent Corp. said it has uncovered some
``material issues'' involving the computer and test equipment
rental business it bought last year from GE Capital Technology
Management Services, and those problems dragged down Electro Rent's
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   And now Electro Rent wants a partial refund on its $239.2
million purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Despite posting record 1998 fiscal profits Monday, the renter of
personal computers and test equipment said the undisclosed issues
in the balance sheet of the recently acquired business resulted in
increased costs and less-than-expected revenues for Electro Rent.
</P>
<P>
   That news sent Electro Rent shares down Monday $3.4375 to close
at $17.8125.
</P>
<P>
   The GE division, combined with the general downturn in the
overall computer industry and the ongoing Asian currency crisis,
pulled the company's bottom line below what Electro Rent officials
had anticipated, Chairman and President Daniel Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a tumultuous year and we couldn't avoid all the
fallout,'' Greenberg said. ``To that you can add the extra
complication of some unfinished business with the GE TMS
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg would not elaborate on the ``issues,'' the size of the
price reduction it seeks, nor other remedies to which Electro Rent
said it is entitled.
</P>
<P>
   John Oliver, a spokesman for Stamford, Conn.-based GE Capital,
said Monday that GE will make it plain to Electro Rent that the
sale price was fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned it was a fair business, fair price
done in good faith, and we're going to make it clear and
demonstrable to any reasonable observer,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   For the year ended May 31, Electro Rent posted net income of
$32.3 million, or $1.29 per diluted share, up 34 percent from the
prior year's $24.1 million, or 97 cents per diluted share. Total
revenues were $255.5 million, a 70 percent jump from $150.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter net income jumped 45 percent to $7.5 million (30
cents per diluted share) from $5.2 million (21 cents per diluted
share). Quarterly revenues more than doubled to $80.9 million from
$37.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too shabby,'' Greenberg said about the results.
``It's just one always wants to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   The company had expected fourth-quarter results to be closer to
those from the third quarter, when Electro Rent posted $10.6
million (85 cents) in net income on $85.2 million in revenues,
Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the first fiscal quarter ended Aug. 31 are expected
to exceed last year's $38.9 million, but net income is expected to
fall below the nearly $7 million it posted the same time last year,
because of the problems related to the GE business and the overall
weakened industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
