<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Microsoft Files for Dismissal of Case  
   
 By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Saying the government can't prove its case, Microsoft Corp.
yesterday officially asked a federal judge to throw out an
antitrust case against the software giant.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a detailed, 88-page filing, Microsoft argued that the
antitrust lawsuit filed by the federal government and 20 states was
legally undermined b a June federal court ruling on an earlier suit
that favored the Redmond, Wash., company. The Appellate Court
of &UR;  &LR; the District of Columbia said Microsoft was justified in its
decision to integrate its own Internet Explorer browser into the
market-dominant Windows 95 operating software.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, whose latest suit centers on the newer
Windows 98, contends that strategy is an illegal use of monopoly
power and harmed competitors such as Netscape Communications of
Mountain View, which makes a rival browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argues that even ``public interest'' favors its
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you step back from all the heated rhetoric and apply
well-established legal principles to the actual facts of the case,
it is clear that the government will not be able to prove its
case,'' William Neukom, Microsoft senior vice president for law and
corporate affairs, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's integration of Internet technologies into the
operating system has been good for consumers and good for thousands
of independent software companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts said Microsoft has almost no chance of getting
the case thrown out before the trial, scheduled for Sept. 8 in
Washington, D.C. Experts said the motion to dismiss the case was
more of an attempt to sway the ``court of public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way this case is not going to trial in September,''
said Rich Gray, an intellectual property attorney at Bergeson,
Eliopoulos, Grady &AMP; Gray in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson warned
that he was not inclined to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Experts who have followed the case said there weren't any
surprises in Microsoft's latest filing, which adhered to the legal
and public strategy it has followed to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft knows it has little chance for a summary judgment,
but wanted an opportunity to tell the judge how feeble the
government's case is,'' said Hillard Sterling, an antitrust
litigator in the Chicago office of Gordon &AMP; Glickson P.C.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued three main points:
</P>
<P>
   _That Windows 98 is a ``single, integrated product that includes
Internet Explorer technologies'' which can not be separated without
``seriously degrading the operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   _That integrating Internet Explorer benefits consumers, software
developers and computer manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   _That Netscape and Microsoft are vigorous competitors and that
Netscape was not prevented from distributing its Web browser to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft contended it had a strong case for dismissal based on
the June appeals court ruling. That court held that a 1995
agreement between the federal government and Microsoft allowed
integration of software applications like Internet Explorer with
Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But Gray said that court's decision did not take into account
the same monopoly issues and evidence that will go before Jackson
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court did not say whether or not Microsoft had
violated any antitrust laws, Gray said. ``It has some reasonings
that helps Microsoft's case, but it didn't decide anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape General Counsel Roberta Katz said Microsoft was ``using
the same tactics that a magician might use in getting you to watch
what's happening with the left hand so you don't see what happens
with the right hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued that Netscape's own statistics on how many
people use its browser prove it was a viable competitor and that
there was no illegal use of monopoly power.
</P>
<P>
   However, Katz said, Microsoft ``tried to cut off (Netscape's)
distribution through computer manufacturers and Internet service
providers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
