<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOVELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Novell Nears Acid Test With NetWare 5  
   
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The day of reckoning is close at hand for Eric Schmidt, the former
super nerd at Sun Microsystems who heads Novell.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Provo, Utah, company announced yesterday that NetWare 5 will
go on sale by September 20. It is the first major upgrade of
Novell's flagship product since 1994 _ and some believe its best
chance to stem Microsoft's headlong assault on a market that Novell
once dominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Novell is under significant pressure to have a very successful
product,'' said Dan Kusnetzky, research analyst with International
Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   NetWare 5 is built entirely on the technology of the Internet,
allowing companies to seamlessly blend their Intranets and
corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings down the barrier between them,'' said John Slitz,
Novell's senior vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In the year and a half since Schmidt became chief executive of
Novell, he has remolded the company to fit his vision of a future
in which all networking will revolve around the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he has trimmed 1,000 jobs _ about one-fifth of
the workforce _ while purging about half of the company's managers
and installing his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt has brought financial stability back to Novell, which
lost $122 million in the first full quarter after he took over. It
has made money in the past three quarters, and its stock hit a
52-week high of $13.50 last month. It closed yesterday up 6 cents
at $10.88.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues have been flat, however, and still are running at an
annual rate of about half the $2 billion that the company posted in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Novell's slide has coincided with the rise of Windows NT,
Microsoft's network operating software. Although NetWare still
boasts more than 80 million users, Windows NT now is outselling it
in new installations.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt made it clear that he intends to regain the momentum
that previous management squandered through a combination of
ill-fated acquisitions, poor marketing and product delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``With NetWare 5, customers leap ahead of the pack with smarter,
more manageable and efficient networks,'' he said. ``Novell has
regained its rightful place as the only networking vendor that can
get them there.''
</P>
<P>
   By emphasizing NetWare's integration with the Internet, Novell
hopes to counter Microsoft's argument that Windows NT works better
than NetWare in corporate networks that use Windows-based PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Novell is heavily promoting NetWare's directory feature, which
lets network administrators manage various parts of the network.
Novell generally is considered better than Microsoft in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Slitz said NetWare 5 also outguns Windows NT when it comes to
working on large network servers.
</P>
<P>
   But Novell isn't just battling Microsoft. It also must fight its
own past mistakes, especially the initial version of NetWare 4,
which was full of bugs and didn't always work with previous
versions of the software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Novell really needs something to set a fire underneath the
company,'' said analyst Bruce Raabe of Collins &AMP; Co. Whether
NetWare 5 can do that is unclear, but Raabe said that ``having a
product like this can't hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
