<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7384 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-MURDER-2NDLD-WRI     08-11 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-MURDER-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-275&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to expand; more info on children)  
 CHICAGO BOYS, 7 and 8, CHARGED WITH BRUTAL MURDER OF 11-YEAR-OLD By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a case that has sent chills across this city, two
boys, ages 7 and 8, have been charged with murdering an 11-year-old
girl _ striking her with a rock, sexually molesting her and
suffocating her with her own underwear _ apparently to take the
bright blue bicycle she had been riding, the police said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile justice experts said that they knew of no case in which
younger children had been prosecuted for murder in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and the police said on Monday that on Sunday evening
the boys confessed to the July 27 killing of Ryan Harris, an
honor-roll student who had just finished fifth grade. After killing
Ryan in an alley behind a building on Chicago's South Side, they
stashed her bicycle so they could retrieve it later, the police
said. Then, they said, the 8-year-old rode his bicycle home and
watched cartoons and the 7-year-old went home to play with a puppy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the boys appeared for a probable cause hearing in
Juvenile Court, their feet swaying above the floor as they sat
before Judge Gerald T. Winiecki.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-year-old's lawyer had him stand on a chair at one point so
a witness could see him better. The 7-year-old spent most of the
hearing drawing hearts, a house and a rainbow with colored pens on
one of his lawyer's yellow legal pads.
</P>
<P>
   Slayings by children in recent years have stunned the nation and
led many states to take a tougher approach to juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has seen several horrifying crimes involving children,
including a 1994 case in which two boys, 10 and 11, dropped a
5-year-old boy to his death from the 14th floor of a housing
project. But the Ryan Harris case has struck an especially painful
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era, the ages of these offenders is very frightening
to hear about,'' said Mayor Richard M. Daley. ``Children are
growing up much, much faster.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Winiecki ruled that there was probable cause to try the boys on
juvenile charges in the slaying and ordered them held overnight at
Hartgrove Hospital, a psychiatric hospital in Chicago. Winiecki
instructed reporters at the probable cause hearing not to disclose
the boys' names; The New York Times had decided not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In court and at a news conference, the police and prosecutors
described how they believe Ryan was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that the 8-year-old boy knew Ryan, who lived in
the working-class suburb of Lynwood just south of the city but who
was staying with a godmother in Chicago's impoverished Englewood
neighborhood this summer so she could attend a day camp at a high
school there.
</P>
<P>
   They said that on July 27, Ryan and the 8-year-old went to ride
their bicycles around the high school and ended up in an alley
behind a building.
</P>
<P>
   There, the police said, they were met by the 7-year-old, who was
a friend of the 8-year-old, and the boys began throwing rocks.
Detective Allen Nathaniel testified on Monday that the 7-year-old
told him he threw a rock that struck Ryan in the back of the head
and knocked her off her bicycle, apparently leaving her
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The detective testified that the 7-year-old told him that the
boys moved her bicycle to a wooded area about 20 feet away and
``they both took one arm of Ryan and dragged her to the same wooded
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the detective testified the 7-year-old told him, ``They
began to play with her. He said they began to play with her `very
softly.' He said they pulled her panties down. After he pulled her
panties down, he put them in her mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel said the 7-year-old told him he then began rubbing
leaves and branches around her nose and mouth. Police found pieces
of leaves stuffed in Ryan's nostrils. At some point, the police
said, one or both of the boys molested Ryan with what Nathaniel
called a ``small tubular object'' that ``caused a half-inch gash''
around her genitals.
</P>
<P>
   The detective said that the 8-year-old told him that when he saw
the 7-year-old play with her body, he ran off. The police said the
boys told them they had stashed Ryan's bicycle, a Road Warrior
model, in some weeds; but when the police returned to look for it,
it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's body was found on July 28, in tall weeds in the wooded
area behind the building. The cause of death was asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   The police initially questioned the boys as potential witnesses
in a door-to-door canvass of the neighborhood. The boys said they
saw a strange man lure Ryan into his car. But investigators became
suspicious when the boys changed their stories, providing details
that ``would only be known by the detectives that investigated it
and the perpetrators,'' said Sgt. Stan Zaborac.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, the oldest of six children, was a straight-A student, her
family said, and dreamed of playing professional basketball and
becoming a doctor. Her grandfather, Nathaniel Hamlin, told
reporters after her body was found that Ryan was so diligent she
would come home from school and tutor her brother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of the boys in the Englewood neighborhood described
them as well-behaved children. Several said they could not believe
these boys had committed such a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Blanton, who runs a corner laundry, said the boys would
help her with chores. ``They used to clean up for me,'' Ms. Blanton
said. ``I didn't even have to ask them. They'd just pick up a broom
and start cleaning. Anything for some candy money.''
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors said the boys were always offering to cut the
grass or pick up the garbage. They played basketball often at a
hoop in an alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they get the right person and don't charge those babies
for something they didn't do,'' said Glenda Tucker, a neighbor. ``I
just don't believe it and I think they're being framed.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who identified himself only as P.B. said: ``Those boys
don't even like girls. They play with Tonka toys and sit in the
dirt and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vallas, the chief executive officer of the Chicago public
schools, said the 8-year-old attended Parker Community Academy and
was an ``ideal student with good grades and few absentees.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the 7-year-old, a student at Wadsworth School, had
discipline problems in school.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile justice experts said on Monday that though they did not
know of any exhaustive record of juvenile killings they had not
heard of children any younger being prosecuted for murder. Roger
Lane, a professor of history at Haverford College and the author of
``Murder in America, a History'' (Ohio State University Press,
1997), said he believed that there were three 8-year-old boys
charged with murder in the 1800s and early 1900s, but none of the
boys was formally indicted or convicted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a 9-year-old boy named Cameron Kocher was charged with
murder in Pennsylvania and ultimately convicted. In 1996, in
Richmond, Calif., a 6-year-old was initially charged with attempted
murder in the beating of a baby, but charges were suspended and the
boy was put in a residential treatment center.
</P>
<P>
   Under Illinois law, children cannot be charged as adults until
they turn 13. If convicted in the juvenile system, they can be held
only until they turn 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan Harris case is likely to lead to debate about the
competence of children to understand their culpability in a crime.
Are children that young capable of recognizing the consequences of
their behavior? How should judges hold them accountable for
uncommonly depraved actions?
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for both boys said that their clients had not
been properly questioned, a charge that the police denied. The boys
were brought into the police station by their parents or
grandparents, but Nathaniel said under questioning that the adults
were not in the room when the boys confessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they made a statement, how voluntary a statement could it
be?'' said Catherine Ferguson, a public defender representing the
7-year-old. ``Can he waive his Miranda rights?''
</P>
<P>
   The police said their procedure was proper because youth
officers were present during the interviews with the boys and their
parents were informed immediately after they gave their statements.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Grant, the lawyer for the 8-year-old, said: ``My client
was a victim of the state's foolishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said that the 8-year-old's behavior, as described by
Nathaniel, was ``what a normal 7- or 8-year-old would do. He saw
another kid throw a rock. He got on his bike and he went home.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Michael Oppenheimer, sought to portray the boys
as being similar to any other defendant accused of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that you have a 7- and 8-year-old who are
charged,'' Oppenheimer said after the hearing. ``But the facts of
the case warrant the charge.''
</P>
<P>
   The family of the two boys sat in the courtroom on Monday and at
one point, the 8-year-old waved at his parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a baby. Look at him,'' the father murmured to the
mother.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Ryan Harris sat in the courtroom too, rocking with
silent sobs during parts of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven and 8 _ I can't see 7 and 8,'' Ryan's mother, Sabrina
Harris, said outside the courthouse Monday evening. ``She's got
sisters 7 and 8.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
