<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL SET TO INVESTIGATE CUTTING INCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said
Monday he expects the NFL to look into the details surrounding the
Michael Irvin-Everett McIver situation.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry could reveal whether Irvin intentionally tried to
harm McIver. If he did, it could lead to a fine or a suspension for
Irvin under the league's violent crime policy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McIver practiced for the first time Monday since
needing stitches to close a nearly 2-inch cut on his neck that was
caused, sources said, by Irvin with scissors in a July 29 dorm room
scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   McIver would not comment about the incident or a report that
Jones negotiated a deal for Irvin to pay McIver for his silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just talking football,'' McIver said. ``The questions are
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, however, was adamant that neither he, nor any of his
representatives, paid to keep McIver from talking or filing a
police report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not given anyone any money,'' Irvin said. ``I didn't
pay anybody anything. There has been no deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also continued to deny any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not aware of any deal,'' he said. ``I know of no deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the intense media scrutiny is the main reason that
the NFL will probably look into a situation that the Cowboys have
tried to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys owner said that the league's fact-finding mission
would probably be handled by Ben Nix, one of the NFL's security
representatives based in Dallas. Nix, who was in Wichita Falls on
Monday, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often, the NFL looks at what the media says and takes a
long look at it and when they find out nothing has happened, they
move on,'' Jones said. ``My contention is that most of it [media
speculation] is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he was not surprised that his name was linked to the
report of him brokering a payment because, ``I'm the general
manager, I get put into everything involved in the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said ``no comment'' when asked if the
NFL was looking into the situation.
</P>
<P>
   According to several sources with knowledge of the situation,
the incident escalated into a fight when McIver was getting a
haircut and Irvin wanted McIver to get up from the barber's chair
so he could get a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   McIver took exception and pushing and shoving began between the
6-foot-2, 200-pound Irvin and the 6-foot-5, 318-pound McIver. The
fight ended, sources said, with Irvin inflicting a cut near
McIver's carotid artery with a scissors.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey and Irvin have each said the
incident resulted from ``horseplay.''
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL investigation finds that Irvin violated the league's
violent crime policy, commissioner Paul Tagliabue could take
disciplinary action against the Cowboys' leading receiver in the
form of a fine or a suspension, regardless of whether there was an
arrest or conviction, according to the policy.
</P>
<P>
   McIver has not filed a complaint. If he does, and if Irvin is
charged and convicted, the consequences could be severe. Irvin is
already on probation stemming from a 1996 conviction for felony
cocaine possession. If he is found to have violated the terms of
his probation, he faces up to a 20-year prison sentence. Criminal
convictions or certain behavior problems would constitute a
violation of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas County's adult probation director said Monday that the
latest allegations of a cover-up or payoff don't change his stance
of last week _ that probation officials won't investigate unless a
criminal complaint is filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still dependent on police agency,'' Ron Goethals said.
``If a witness came forward, we would direct them to a police
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the original conditions of probation, the terms are that
the person on probation should not break the laws of this state or
any other state,'' he said. ``Ultimately, that will come down to a
determination by a law enforcement agency.''
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Manny Alvarez would determine whether or not to
revoke Irvin's probation based on a recommendation and
investigation by the probation department following a criminal
complaint, Goethals said. Alvarez sentenced Irvin to four years'
deferred adjudication in July 1996 after the wide receiver pleaded
no contest to felony cocaine possession. Alvarez is on vacation
this week and couldn't be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's probation could be revoked if a new criminal offense is
shown _ a standard component of most probation agreements, Goethals
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deferred adjudication agreement, if Irvin serves his
sentence to Alvarez's satisfaction, the Dallas County district
attorney's office will drop the charges, and Irvin's record will
show no conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Since the incident, McIver had not practiced with the team
before Monday. He came to practice 30 minutes after the rest of his
teammates took the field and worked out with the first team. Gailey
said the time McIver has missed will not cause him to lose his
starting job. McIver has missed each of the club's two preseason
games and last week's scrimmage against the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to get him in the one-on-one play, if not
the scrimmage'' Tuesday night against the New Orleans Saints in
Shreveport, La., Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little fatigued,'' McIver said as he walked off the
field. ``Any time you miss time heading into the season it is a
setback. I've got a lot to make up and I'm willing to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin has said there is no animosity between him and McIver. The
rest of the Cowboys do not appear to be distracted by the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been a concern of mine,'' Cowboys quarterback Troy
Aikman said. ``The media has said a lot about this, and maybe in
the past this would have taken away from what we do on the field.
But I don't think this has at all.''
Staff writers Clarence E. Hill Jr. and Mede Nix contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 0102EDT &QL; 
