<HEADER>
A7397 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astroslede-HNS &LR;      08-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Wagner closes the door 
after homer breaks tie
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Sean Berry's sense for drama and suspense may soon put him in a
class with the likes of Alfred Hitchcock and Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Berry might be too predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Stop us if you've heard this before. Berry's three-run homer in
the bottom of the eighth inning propelled the Astros to a 5-2
victory over the Milwaukee Brewers on Monday night at the
Astrodome. It was the third time Berry has won a game with a home
run this season and the 19th time the Astros have won a game in
their last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the situations everyone dreamed about when they were
little kids,'' Berry said. ``It's the best feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry's blast off Brewers reliever Chad Fox untied a 2-2 game,
and the last-minute run support gave rookie reliever Scott Elarton
the first win of his big-league career. Elarton followed starter
Mike Hampton to the mound and watched from the bench as closer
Billy Wagner struck out two of three batters he faced in the ninth
for his 23rd save.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, making his second appearance since returning from the
disabled list, had the crowd of 18,995 on its feet for most of the
final inning. It was the smallest Astrodome crowd since May 27, but
it wasn't lacking for noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the people cheer for you like that, it raises your level
and makes you a better player,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a difficult assignment to find an offensive player
better than Berry over the past two weeks or so. The streaky third
baseman is hitting .453 with three homers and 10 RBIs in his last
17 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a good streak right now,'' Berry said. ``In this game,
you're going to have good streaks and bad streaks. You just try to
stay hot for as long as you can and ride it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are threatening to ride off into the sunset with the
National League Central Division banner. Monday's victory
maintained their lead over the second-place Chicago Cubs at 7{
games. The third-place Brewers are in town for three more days
before the Cubs drop in for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where you can possibly get a streak going and benefit
from beating the teams you're playing,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hampton nor Mets starter Bill Pulsipher allowed a run
through the first five innings, and the Astros grounded into three
double plays during that span.
</P>
<P>
   But one bad pitch can make all the difference in a pitching
duel, as Pulsipher learned in the sixth when the Astros matched
their hit total from the previous five innings with three,
including Moises Alou's 31st homer and his second in as many days.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with every Astros homer hit in the Dome, General
Admission fired his cannon from the outfield seats, sending a cloud
of smoke into the air. Before the smoke had cleared, the game was
tied again.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton got two quick outs to start the seventh inning but was
tagged for three consecutive hits, including a two-run pinch-hit
homer to left by Brian Bates. It was Bates' first homer of the
season, and it came on Hampton's first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hampton) made two bad pitches with two out _ a fastball up
and a changeup up _ and that killed him,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who has won only one game since June 9, showed
improvement despite receiving the fourth no-decision in his last
six starts. He allowed nine hits and struck out three batters in
his 92-pitch performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to keep us in the game for seven innings, and the
bullpen shut them down,'' Hampton said. ``My last inning was
disappointing. I'm not going to lie and say it wasn't. But overall,
I was pretty satisfied with my performance. I felt good. I'm not
all the way back, but I'm getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton retired the side in order in the top of the eighth, and
Berry put on his hero's cap in the bottom of the inning after Jeff
Bagwell and Alou got things started with back-to-back singles.
Wagner fed the Brewers a steady diet of sliders in the ninth to
earn his first save since the highly publicized incident in which
he was hit in the head by a line drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like the Billy of old,'' Dierker said. ``He threw
some really good sliders. He made better use of that pitch than in
any of his other outings this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, who never had pitched in relief during his professional
career until this season, earned his milestone victory in his 14th
big-league appearance _ the last 12 of which have come in relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of trips to the hill (without a victory),'' said
Elarton, who is 1-0 with a 1.29 earned run average as a reliever.
``But when you're pitching in relief, you're not out there to get a
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought my first big-league win would come out of the
bullpen, but I'm not complaining. The bullpen is what has kept me
in the big leagues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
