<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS COACH SAYS MISTAKES `CORRECTABLE'
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the
sight of his team's play Saturday night on film was not as bad as
it looked in person.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey had little good to say about his team after the 16-3 loss
to the Raiders. He had a different take Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not nearly as disappointed after watching the tape as I
was after the game,'' Gailey said. ``The things that we did wrong
were correctable, fairly easily correctable. We just got to go do
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey attributed the poor performance to ``five or six''
things, including problems in concentration and preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we'll be working the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he conveyed the same message to the team in a
meeting before practice, however, he said he didn't take them
completely off the hook for their play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to make it all gooey that everything was OK
because it wasn't,'' Gailey said. ``We still made mistakes. The
thing I told them is the mistakes are correctable but the key is
not make them in the first place.'' EX-VIKING SMITH WORKS OUT
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys worked out former Vikings defensive end Fernando
Smith, but haven't signed him.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Smith had a good workout, but
said the team probably won't make a decision until after Tuesday's
scrimmage against the Saints in Shreveport, La.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is recuperating from a July 7 hernia operation,
stayed to watch practice after his workout. He said he liked the
situation with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would fit in great here,'' Smith said. ``They rotate
the front four \Rlike in Minnesota\S. And if they want me to be a
pass rush end, just come in on third down, that would be no
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who said he will make a decision tomorrow, is also
negotiating with other teams. Smith has visited Washington,
Jacksonville, Atlanta, Chicago and New Orleans. He has one more
scheduled visit with either San Francisco or Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys do decide to pursue Smith to help shore up their
weak defensive end play _ they will be hard pressed to compete in a
bidding war for Smith. The financially-strapped Cowboys would have
to rework a couple of player contracts to sign Smith, whose asking
price for 1998 is $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had 16 career sacks in four years with the Vikings. His
best year was in 1996 when he recorded 91/2 sacks. Smith was
hampered by the hernia injury last season and had four sacks.
ANOTHER COUNTRY HEARD FROM
</P>
<P>
   Mexican football player Marco Martos joined the Cowboys Monday
as a ceremonial addition for their American Bowl matchup against
the New England Patriots on Monday in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Martos, who played with the Broncos in the American Bowl last
season, said the game will be a bigger deal this year because the
Cowboys are more popular in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas is the team of Mexico,'' Martos said. ``Everyone in
Mexico loves Dallas. I think it's going to be 115 to 120 thousand
people in the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Martos knows his presence is more of a publicity stunt,
he is doing it for personal reasons. A football fan since age 7, he
hopes to eventually earn a spot on an NFL roster. Martos played
with the Barcelona Dragons in NFL Europe the past couple of years,
catching 42 passes for 501 yards and seven touchdowns. ANOTHER
BATES
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys released wide receiver Michael Hicks and signed
former Florida linebacker James Bates on Monday. Bates is the son
of Cowboys defensive line coach Jim Bates.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bates' second stint with the Cowboys. He originally
signed with the team last summer, but saw his dream of playing with
his father fade when he tore the Achilles' tendon in his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Bates said he never thought he'd get another chance and jumped
at the opportunity to play when the Cowboys called.
</P>
<P>
   Bates says football is his first love, however he created a nice
niche for himself during the year away from the game. He worked as
a college football commentator for the Sunshine network and did
some acting, including a small role in the next movie version of
the Addams's Family, which is scheduled to be released this fall.
BROOKS WORKS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Macey Brooks, who has missed nearly two weeks
because of testicular torsion, participated in limited workouts
Monday. He did some light running and was involved in some
individual drills. Brooks is expected to be out another two weeks.
GETTING A PEEK
</P>
<P>
   More than 25,000 tickets have already been sold to the Cowboys
scrimmage Tuesday against the New Orleans Saints in Shreveport, La.
Promoters are expecting 30,000 by game time.
</P>
<P>
   What those fans will get for their price of admission _ tickets
range from $15 to $35 _ is some kicking drills, some passing drills
and a series of controlled scrimmages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
