<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO HOP ON THE KITNA BANDWAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You can't say enough about Seahawks
quarterback-in-waiting Jon Kitna, so let's say some more. Like how
Kitna is exactly the kind of athlete who makes you remember why you
love sports.
</P>
<P>
   The guy makes it look fun.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Kitna is such a good guy. Honest. Fresh.
Confident, but not arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   So the question is: Why wait? Why not accelerate the
Kitna-as-Seahawk-quarterback-in-waiting plan? After all, Rick Mirer
once got the chance to lead the Seahawks to the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this should be Kitna's season. There is every reason to
suspect it would be exciting. And there is growing reason to
believe the Seahawks might be better served by getting Kitna
untracked now, this season, instead of waiting, even if a certain
Warren Moon decides to grace the Seahawks with his presence.
</P>
<P>
   Really. Why wait?
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren's 41. Maybe he needs more time off,'' Kitna joked the
other night, after his first home start for the Seahawks seemed to
prove the Tacoma native was ready for his close-up, Mr. DeMille.
</P>
<P>
   If Kitna is the quarterback of the future, and he's making eyes
pop open right now, why not turn the team over to him?
</P>
<P>
   If Ryan Leaf is the Chargers' starting quarterback from now
until whenever, then Kitna should get the same green light. If
Peyton Manning is the Colts' franchise-saving QB two weeks into
training camp, then Kitna deserves a promotion, too.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Kitna's first preseason start Saturday against
the Colts, one thing is abundantly clear: The kid can play.
</P>
<P>
   When we say Kitna's a ``kid,'' it's a compliment, since it
really means he plays with the sort of passionate, driving abandon
that you expect in a kid, even though his poise, presence and
strength more than demonstrate he is no kid.
</P>
<P>
   But like a kid, Kitna has fun. And he makes football fun to
watch and exciting, which is a good reason as any to show up at the
Kingdome this season and root for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike a certain 41-year-old veteran, Kitna has no other
agenda except to play his brains out, learn, be part of the team
and make his teammates look as good as they should.
</P>
<P>
   From running back Ricky Watters to receiver Mike Pritchard to
speedster Joey Galloway to tight end Deems May, don't think for a
minute these big-time talents could not rally around their man from
Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, winning is the bottom line. The Seahawks enter 1998 with
no alternative except to make the playoffs. There is too much
talent all over that roster, too many playmakers on Paul Allen's
pricey little whizbang, to think anything less than the postseason
is acceptable. So who cares if the AFC West is a bear that makes
the Seahawks' playoff route unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite this unsourced proclamation that the Hawks must get
to the playoffs in '98, there is a little more to the season than
just a playoff berth. The second-best thing to hope for in '98
would be plays. Big plays. Medium plays. Chain-moving plays that
make the Seahawks competitive each down, each half.
</P>
<P>
   As much as victories, Seahawk watchers should want to
consistently see plays that give the team momentum, because making
plays is the down-to-down turn-on. And so far, Kitna has shown that
when the ball is in is hands, the Seahawks are going to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   And, best of all, when Kitna can't find a receiver to throw to,
he knows instinctively when to break across the line and run for a
first down, like a Steve Young or a Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   That is a lot more than what Moon or John Friesz can do. Friesz
is a terrific guy who some days throws a good football. But after
all those seasons lost to injury and all that immobility in the
pocket, it's clear Friesz is not a No. 1 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   These comparisons of Kitna to Young and Favre might constitute a
bit of a stretch, they might be slightly premature, but quite
honestly, if you can't get gung-ho over an out-of-the-woodwork find
like Kitna, then who else are you going to get excited about?
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon? Where is he?
</P>
<P>
   The longer Moon decides he's not getting enough dough to come
and play football for the Seahawks, the more you want this season
to belong to Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says the Seahawks must have Moon to make it
serious this season. The longer Moon thinks $4.5 million is the
only way it's worth it to him to play football, the more heartily
you root for Kitna to get the chance to prove conventional wisdom
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna got the start Saturday night against the Colts and all but
made the $48 million franchise savior, Manning, look like the
rookie Manning is.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna wore a sly smile afterward, too. He knew he had done well.
He knew that everything Dennis Erickson wanted to see out of him
was on display. Good decisions. Audibles at the line. Accuracy,
strength, legs. Enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Hawks are back in Cheney, and Moon's timetable would
appear to be winding down. Moon could afford to be away from Cheney
for the first three weeks of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The way Kitna is showing he's ready for the show, the more we
should wonder if Moon would not indeed better serve the long-term
interests of the Seahawks by backing up this exciting young
quarterback with no blue blood or high-falutin' credentials, but
who possesses the one thing football fans love to see in their
quarterback. The kid's a winner, and you would root like crazy to
see him pull off a season full of big plays and victories.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested, jump on the Kitna bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
