<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWK CORNER THOMAS SETS SIGHTS ON IMPROVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ When Willie Williams couldn't play in Saturday
night's preseason game because of a sore ankle, the Seahawk coaches
didn't hesitate to insert Fred Thomas at right cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Thomas, whose first two seasons in the NFL have been
marked and marred by a series of big plays, the Indianapolis Colts
didn't hesitate in going his way.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was Thomas who had his way.
</P>
<P>
   The game began for Thomas like so many others have, with him
running stride for stride with a receiver but failing to make the
play at the last second. This time, it was a 46-yard completion
from Colts rookie quarterback Peyton Manning to Jerome Pathon, the
rookie receiver from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But before eyes could roll and those ``Here we go agains'' could
be muttered, Thomas made amends. Three plays later, he intercepted
a Manning pass and returned it 26 yards.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seahawk series stalled, it was Thomas who downed Jeff
Feagles' pooch punt at the Colts' 3-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Needing 5 yards for a first down on the Colts' next possession,
Manning went to 246-pound fullback Zach Crockett with a third-down
pass. But there was Thomas, all 5-foot-9, 172 pounds of him, to
push Crockett out of bounds a yard short of the first down marker.
</P>
<P>
   On the Colts' next possession, Manning again went to Pathon. But
Thomas made a jarring hit to drop the former Husky after a 4-yard
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the final play of the first half, Manning threw deep to
rookie receiver E.G. Green. Guess who was there to slap the pass to
the turf? Again, it was Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, coach Dennis Erickson called the effort the best game
Thomas has played for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, defensive coordinator Greg McMackin offered, ``Fred has
been having a great camp. He's been doing really well in practice,
and he needed to take what he's been learning in practice and use
it in a game. The other night, he did.''
</P>
<P>
   What's gotten into Thomas?
</P>
<P>
   Call it confidence. Call it a renewed faith in his talents,
which were abundant enough that the Seahawks selected him in the
second round of the 1996 draft. Call it the rebirth of a player
whose short career seemed to be on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, focus on something Thomas is working to rid himself
of _ double vision.
</P>
<P>
   While reviewing game video during the offseason, defensive backs
coach Willy Robinson detected something was wrong with Thomas, who
time and again was on a coverage only to flail one direction while
the ball and receiver connected in the opposite direction. The club
sent Thomas to see Dr. Alan Reichow, an assistant professor of
optometry at Pacific University, who immediately recognized Thomas'
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, I battled vision problems, something I was in denial
about,'' Thomas said. ``Once I got that treated, it was all about
me making plays. I see the ball better, I'm reading things
better.''
</P>
<P>
   And continuing to correct the problem that used to cause him to
see one ball split into two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't just ever go away,'' he said. ``But if I keep
treating it and doing my exercises, I'll keep it where I want to
be. But it's just something I've got to do every day.''
</P>
<P>
   So in addition to practice and meetings and more practice and
more meetings, Thomas does exercises to strength his weak eye.
Things like tossing a ball against the wall in his dorm room,
following it with both eyes and catching it with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me stay focused,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches and other players need Thomas to be focused. They
also need him to play more consistently than he has the past two
years. Although not listed as a starter, he plays in the nickel
defense at right corner, allowing Williams to slide inside and
cover a slot receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is striving to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I shouldn't read what the (preview) magazines say, but
they say I've been exploited and that I'm a target,'' he said. ``I
know to change that I've got to come out and play every game and
make the plays that come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Seahawks, Saturday night was a huge step in the right
direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
