<HEADLINE>
JONES, COWBOYS: SAME AS THEY EVER WERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   [ital]''For my part, whatever anguish of spirit it may cost, I
am willing to know the whole truth _ to know the worst and provide
for it.''[end ital] _ Patrick Henry
</P>
<P>
   Sad but true, Jerry Jones doesn't think you can handle the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Cowboys owner/general manager is doing his best Jack
Nicholson impersonation, in case you hadn't noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Nicholson as the arrogant U.S. Marine colonel,
screaming at defense attorney Tom Cruise from the witness stand in
``A Few Good Men?'' That was about a cover-up, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth?'' Nicholson ranted, smirking at Cruise. ``You can't
handle the truth!''
</P>
<P>
   It was the movie's signature line.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jerry, in his own way, is sending the same message to you
regarding the haircut heard 'round the world.
</P>
<P>
   He is, he'll swear, trying to protect you, trying to keep your
Cowboys safe and intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our fans,'' you can almost hear him say, his Arkansas
twang dripping molasses.
</P>
<P>
   For you. All for you.
</P>
<P>
   Because the truth, you see, might harm the Cowboys, and he's not
at all sure that you, the fans, can deal with that.
</P>
<P>
   I say he's underestimating you. I say he doesn't know you at all
and that he's using you as an excuse because it's his own ego, his
own pride, his own checkbook, that can't stand the light of the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   The saddest truth of all is that with one slimy, poorly handled
cover-up, Jones has undone all the hard work, all the damage
control, all the positive steps that the Cowboys organization had
taken in changing its image in the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   What fools we were to buy into that facade. Nothing has changed
because Jerry hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Jones might as well fire Calvin Hill, his symbol of change for
the good, because poor Calvin means nothing. He's just a
figurehead. Same goes for Chan Gailey. Gailey can have all the
family values in the world. He can be the country's No. 1 citizen,
but it means zilch if he has no input when something like this
happens.
</P>
<P>
   And if he's a part of this, then shame on Gailey, too.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones had meant it when he said this was a new era for the
Cowboys, then there would be no cover-up. You and I would know
exactly what happened in that dorm room, who was involved and what
the Cowboys were doing about it.
</P>
<P>
   That's how honest people deal with problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry wouldn't be hiding it from the news media. He wouldn't be
hiding it from you, the ticket-buying public. He wouldn't be hiding
it from the district attorney's office, campus police or Judge
Manny Alvarez. He wouldn't be hiding it from the NFL, which is
expected to begin an investigation into the incident.
</P>
<P>
   We wouldn't be reading about payoffs to Everett McIver, because
Michael Irvin wouldn't be in a position to surreptitiously bribe
himself out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   And if the truth costs this team Irvin's services, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   I say, as bad as that would hurt, you can deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   It's really simple, when you think about it. If Irvin's guilty
of something here, if he stabbed McIver in a fit of rage, or in a
fight, or whatever, then he needs help and he needs to be held
responsible. The Cowboys aren't helping him by covering for him, or
being enablers, which is what the drug and alcohol counselors call
it, of his aberrant behavior.
</P>
<P>
   And if he's not stopped here, then where? When does it end? If
he can get away with stabbing someone, for whatever the reasons,
what can he not get away with?
</P>
<P>
   And if Michael Irvin is guilty of nothing, then please tell us
that, too. We need to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this story is picking up steam nationally. Across
the country, they're giggling at the Cowboys' expense again.
Late-night talk show hosts are loading up the one-liners. The
Dallas Badboys are back in town.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever positive feelings had been built with the coming of
Gailey and his assistants, a strong draft, a sense that the team
had finally stepped away from the smoldering ruins of scandal and
deceit, have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Not because Michael Irvin might have gone haywire with a pair of
scissors. Who can predict something like that?
</P>
<P>
   No one expected perfection from every player. We understood that
problems would occasionally crop up. What we had hoped, what we had
prayed, was that how this organization reacted to those problems
would have changed.
</P>
<P>
   That's where we wanted and expected a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The truth? You can handle the truth. I'm absolutely certain of
it.
</P>
<P>
   It's Jerry Jones who just can't face it.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't at all mean that you don't deserve to hear it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
