<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTA'S NEWEST MILLIONAIRE KEEPS ROLLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Ai Sugiyama is far from a household
name in the United States. But if she plays tennis the way she has
of late, more fans might realize more about her.
</P>
<P>
   They might realize that Ai is Japanese for love, that Sugiyama
is ranked 16th in the world or that she hit a career milestone last
weekend in the Toshiba Classic at La Costa.
</P>
<P>
   Sugiyama topped the million-dollar mark in winnings after
reaching the quarterfinals by beating Steffi Graf and Jennifer
Capriati at La Costa, both previously undefeated there. Sugiyama
continues to play well as she beat France's Anne-Gaelle Sidot 6-4,
6-3 Monday in the opening round of the $450,000 Acura Classic at
Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the million-dollar mark, Sugiyama said, was not a
specific goal on the Corel WTA tour, but she is thrilled to have
reached it. She is one of 17 players at Manhattan Beach this week
to have accomplished that. With some of the cash from recent wins,
she plans to embark on business ventures at home, outside of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Sugiyama, 23, already has opened a sporting-goods store called
Belly Buttons and plans to open a cafe and flower shop. She has not
decided on names for the new stores, but she has an explanation for
the eyebrow-raising name of the sporting-goods store.
</P>
<P>
   ``The belly button is the center of you,'' she said. ``And I'm
the center of everybody back there who supports me.''
</P>
<P>
   The store is a type of dedication to those people.
</P>
<P>
   While Sugiyama plays in relative obscurity in the U.S., her
place in Japan is much different. ``If I walk here, nobody is going
to recognize me,'' she said. ``In Japan, some people know me. Some
people will come up to me for autographs.''
</P>
<P>
   She enjoys the attention from Japanese fans, partly because they
have a different attitude toward their sports stars than U.S. fans.
``They have respect,'' Sugiyama said.
</P>
<P>
   What might separate Sugiyama from other players on the tour is
her mental toughness. She has a steady ground game and says the key
to success is simply to cut down on unforced errors. But other
players recognize the psychological part of her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the toughest mentally of any player,'' said American
Kimberly Po, who is ranked 60th and is half Japanese. ``When it's
5-0, you know she's going to play as hard as any other point.''
</P>
<P>
   Sugiyama will need intensity in her second-round match against
third-seeded Arantxa Sanchez Vicario. About her chances against
Sanchez Vicario, Sugiyama said, ``I cannot miss a lot early.''
</P>
<P>
   ACURA CLASSIC NOTES
</P>
<P>
   __ Po sent packing: Former UCLA standout Po lost to Julie
Halard-Decugis 6-2, 6-4, but the Rolling Hills resident was not too
choked up about the loss. She is in the process of moving to
Hermosa Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least now, I'll have enough time to pack and move,'' said
Po, who blew a 4-1 lead in third set.
</P>
<P>
   Halard-Decugis will have a challenge in the second round when
she faces second-seeded Lindsay Davenport, who is trying to win her
third WTA event in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, like Po, grew up within short driving distance of
Manhattan Beach. Said Po, ``It's different playing here than
anywhere else. I mean I can drive from home to here. And I have
fans cheering for me, which on the other events that never
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Youth, experience qualify: Four qualifying matches concluded
on Monday morning to complete the first-round field of 28 players.
San Diego's Alexandra Stevenson, Latvia's Larisa Neiland,
Luxembourg's Anne Kremer and Italy's Adriana Serra-Zanetti
advanced.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, the four had to win three matches, which Stevenson
said is an advantage. ``It gets you warmed up, and it's great as
long as you don't lose,'' she said. ``I like getting ready in the
qualifiers but wouldn't want to be doing it my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, 17, is the tournament's second youngest player. Only
Serena Williams, 16, is younger. Neiland, 32, is the tournament's
oldest player.
</P>
<P>
   __ Battle of the ages: Williams and Neiland play a first-round
match today at 7 p.m., which highlights the day. Nathalie Tauziat,
fifth-seeded, will be the highest seed to play today. She meets
Chanda Rubin at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The highest seed to play on Monday, No. 6 Irina Spirlea, beat
Fang Li 6-0, 6-2. Li won her two games, after trailing 5-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
