<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-CLARK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE THRILL' SAYS HE WANTS TO REMAIN WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The heckler seated behind the visitors'
dugout on a July afternoon at Oakland Coliseum drew the ire of his
intended target.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers first baseman Will Clark responded twice.
</P>
<P>
   The sacrifice fly that sent Athletics outfielder Jack Voigt to
the warning track in center field was Clark's first rebuttal. The
second occurred as Clark returned to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with the contract!'' Clark barked tersely
toward the heckler, who suggested repeatedly that his performance
this season was a result of impending free agency. ``It has
everything to do with the fact that I can still hit!''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 34 and healthy, can hit, and he wants to continue hitting
for the Rangers after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that would be unfair to say,'' said Clark, whose
five-year, $30 million contract expires after the season. ``I think
that would be common sense. Why wouldn't I? I live here. I have a
house here. I enjoy the Metroplex immensely, and I've got a lot of
friends here. Plus, in the five years that I've been here, I think
this ballclub has improved each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty realistic, though. I know that I can't control
anything that's going to happen two months from now. Why should I
worry about it if I can't control it?''
</P>
<P>
   The people in control are Rangers general manager Doug Melvin,
president Tom Schieffer and owner Tom Hicks. Clark's status will be
addressed after the season, Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know my feelings,'' Clark said. ``They know my
sentiments. They know how much I love playing here and how much I
love being a part of this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers begin a two-game series with the Indians on Tuesday
at Jacobs Field. The matchup will lack a premier but injured first
baseman. That player is Indians first baseman Jim Thome _ not
Clark, who went on the disabled list five times in the previous two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's future with the Rangers beyond 1998 once appeared in
doubt because of his inability to stay healthy for 162 games. Yet
Clark and the disabled list are strangers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't able to do that the last few years,'' Clark said. ``I
had this black cloud following me, and I've been able to stay away
from it this year. The only thing I wanted to do was to be able to
play healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a toll on you mentally when you have to go out there
and play hurt every day. You're absolutely exhausted by the end of
the season. Here we are in August, and I feel just as good now as I
did a few months ago _ not only physically, but also mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark is on pace to hit .303 with 22 home runs and 106 runs
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a premier hitter when he's healthy,'' Melvin said. ``He's
got a chance this season to drive in 100 runs. He puts the bat on
the ball, uses the whole field and works the count well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark lacks the power of Red Sox first baseman Mo Vaughn, who
hit four home runs in the Rangers' four-game series this weekend at
The Ballpark in Arlington. Yet Clark provides legitimate gap power.
He's on pace for 36 doubles, ranks near the league leaders in
on-base percentage (.383) and is a veteran who plays the game right
despite physical limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who bats fifth in the lineup, also prevents opposing
pitchers from pitching around cleanup hitter/right fielder Juan
Gonzalez, who has six intentional walks despite leading the major
leagues with 119 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's respect for Will Clark,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization also must weigh the intangibles Clark brings to
the clubhouse when discussing his future.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore, who played for the Orioles in
1994, saw a ``noticeable change in the Rangers from the other
side'' after Clark arrived that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He notices everything,'' said designated hitter Lee Stevens,
who calls Clark his idol. ``He knows what everybody is doing.
That's why he's `The Sheriff.' They had him come on a road trip
with us last year when he was on the disabled list. That's how
important he is. They wanted him there for his presence. That
should pretty much tell you everything right there.''
</P>
<P>
   What would a Rangers' clubhouse be like without Clark?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be quieter, but there probably would be a lot more
stuff going in here that shouldn't be going on,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clark will continue to blurt his one-day-at-a-time
cliches about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like me, as much as we enjoy playing, there's going to be
a job if you want it, and we'll see what happens at the end of this
year,'' he said. ``I'm not looking past today or tomorrow, though.
I'm enjoying this ballclub too much right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying coming into the clubhouse every day and messing
with Rusty Greer and Mark McLemore and watching new teammates like
Todd Zeile and Royce Clayton do well. I'm enjoying this.''
</P>
<P>
   The day nears when the Rangers must decide whether Clark will
enjoy it here beyond this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
