<SLUG> BC-GOLF-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLUB PROS, REALTITY OF PGA CHAMPIONSHIP IS BIGGEST THRILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Must be a thousand things going through the
heads of Tiger Woods, Ernie Els, Mark O'Meara, Colin Montgomerie
and the other golf studs as they prepare for the pressure and
prestige of a major tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one worry they don't have:
</P>
<P>
   Getting worn out by walking the course.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't about Casey Martin, aka Cartman. He's not at
Sahalee. This is about the guys here who teach the game but don't
often play it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the last time I walked 18 holes,'' Jim
Schuman said Monday after a practice round in near-perfect weather.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you've played the Treetops golf course in Gaylord, Mich.,
where he teaches, you haven't heard of Jim Schuman. Unless a
miracle occurs on the order of Olive Oyl-beats-Holyfield, you won't
hear of him the rest of the week, either.
</P>
<P>
   He's among the 25 club pros in the PGA Championship who've spent
thousands of hours teaching mutts like you and me to keep our heads
down, while dreaming of one day walking an 18th fairway with a
major in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Schuman's typical day at Treetops is so consumed with curing
hooks and slices that he just doesn't play much golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do play, I'm riding a cart to get in before dark,'' he
said. ``Here, you have to pace yourself. I'd love to stay out on
the range and hit balls all day. Then Thursday (the first round)
would come and I wouldn't be able to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuman, a trim, good-looking 34-year-old guy, is out of shape
for this kind of golf. In fact, nearly all of his fellow club pros
are out of shape for this kind of golf, whether aerobically or
physically.
</P>
<P>
   Schuman got here Sunday, but mentally he's been here for weeks,
after qualifying for his first major by finishing in the top 25 of
the national Club Players Championship in North Carolina in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days couldn't go by quick enough,'' he said. ``But at
home, I'd have to give another (teaching) lesson, then another, and
another. I found myself saying, `I can't wait to get out there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's made it, the grin is threatening to split open his
head; none of that passionless cool of the touring pro for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge for me, unbelievable,'' Schuman said. ``There are
friends of mine, guys who've been on the tour for some years, and
have never made a major. This is a huge deal. As the days got
closer (to coming to Seattle), that's when I started feeling the
anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get here, the anxiety starts over again. There's the
clubhouse, there's the range, and pretty soon, I'm next to Nick
Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I knew I was here. I've seen him play in other
events, but I said, `Gosh, there he is.' You don't rub shoulders
with these guys that much.''
</P>
<P>
   The excitement that Seattle's golf community feels hosting its
first big-deal tournament is little different than the rush felt
here by the nation's Tin Cuppers, who are experiencing in practice
rounds the apex of their golf existence.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little like being Foghorn A&AMP;M in the NCAA men's
basketball tournament's field of 64: The week of anticipation is
far richer than the nearly inevitable Thursday blowout.
</P>
<P>
   When you're from Peru, Ind. (pop. 15,000), and your club is
called Rock Hollow, making this PGA field is mammoth. But since it
is the fourth appearance of club pro Todd Smith in the PGA, he's
not quite as slackjawed as he was that first practice round at
Bellerive in St. Louis in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got off the course and I didn't remember what I'd done and
didn't remnember what the holes were like,'' he said. ``I was just
glad it was over. Then I felt OK afterward. I even made the cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf on the home course and golf at the highest level are almost
two distinct games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest disadvantage for club pros is playing under these
conditions _ quick greens, high rough,'' Smith said. ``It's hard
for us to come out in one week and adapt. We might play two or
three events where conditions are similar, but these (touring pros)
play this a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sahalee's former club pro, Rick Acton knows the gig well. He
says the problem is more acute for pros from clubs in the Northeast
and Midwest, who are in the midst of their busiest time, unlike
their counterparts from Florida and hot climates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, all carry the home-club expectations, which are
enormous and unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel this obligation to go out and play well for them,''
he said. ``It's very hard to go to the PGA and, almost by
definition, fail. The big deal is not how they do at the PGA, it's
just getting here. For the touring pro, the end of their dream is
Sunday, not Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The hometown supporters) really don't understand. They don't
know how good the (touring pros) are. They know how well their club
pro plays in the pro-am every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shoot 68 on the home course and they think, `Well, four
68s, that's 8-under, that could win at the PGA.' But they don't
understand a 68 at Rolling Oaks golf course and 68 at a major is 20
shots difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The club pros know the distinctions intimately. So the smart
ones lower expectations to increase the enjoyment. Schuman is
inviting his parents out from Wisconsin, and he has a high school
buddy for a caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to share this experience,'' he said. ``I didn't want
to come out alone and just take pictures of how big these trees
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just today I made a few long practice putts on 18 and heard
people screaming and yelling. I couldn't explain that back home.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part this week, these guys will find themselves
lost in a strange Northwest forest. They won't be happy about it.
That doesn't mean they aren't immensely satisfied golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
