<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUZ BACK IN SWING WITH BLUE JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ You don't hear much about The Trade anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Randy Johnson-to-Houston swap remains fresh, but Mariner
fan reaction to the trade last season sending young left fielder
Jose Cruz Jr. to the Toronto Blue Jays for pitchers Mike Timlin and
Paul Spoljaric was the most unpopular in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comparison,'' one club official said Monday. ``When Cruz
was traded, we were bombarded with telephone calls, faxes and
e-mail from unhappy fans. There were only a few faxes and even
fewer phone calls immediately after the Johnson trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``When fans in Seattle saw Junior (Ken Griffey Jr.) come up 10
years ago and become a superstar, then watched young Alex
(Rodriguez) come up and do the things he has done, they thought
they were getting another Junior or Alex in Jose,'' Mariner manager
Lou Piniella said. ``But players like Junior and Alex come along
very seldom.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Johnson wanted out of Seattle. Cruz didn't.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, as the Mariners and Blue Jays begin a two-game
series at SkyDome Tuesday night, The Trade hasn't been as one-sided
as many predicted. Timlin has become Seattle's most dependable
closer since Norm Charlton in 1995, Spoljaric is being groomed as
Johnson's replacement in the starting rotation and Cruz slumped so
badly earlier this season the Blue Jays demoted him to the minor
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But Cruz, 24, is back. He's more relaxed, confident and
productive.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning July 30 from a two-month refresher course with
Class AAA Syracuse, Cruz has reclaimed the starting role in center
field and is batting .357. The latest of his two post-demotion home
runs came on Sunday when he slugged a game-winning, two-run homer
in the eighth inning to beat the Oakland Athletics, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called confidence,'' Blue Jays manager Tim Johnson said
of Cruz's resurgence. ``He worked really hard (at Syracuse) and did
what we asked him to do. He's relaxed and confident. You can see it
in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   You also can hear it in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is fun again,'' Cruz said in a telephone interview.
``I never really lost confidence in myself and am the same player I
was before. I know I can play up here and just needed to work
things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz went back to the basics of hitting: see the ball and hit
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just swinging the bat and letting things happen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Good things are happening again for the switch-hitter who
finished second in the American League Rookie of the Year voting
last season after hitting 26 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Stardom loomed. But then the bright lights dimmed this season.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, Cruz was batting .211 and hadn't hit a home run
since opening day. His defense was shaky. His mind seemed
bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   So it was goodbye Toronto and hello Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first got here, he was down and out,'' Syracuse
manager Lloyd Moseby recently told TruNorth Baseball. ``I felt bad
for him. But he worked hard and never came into my office and said,
`Hey, what's Toronto saying about me?'''
</P>
<P>
   After Cruz batted .298 with seven home runs and 23 RBIs in 40
games at Syracuse, the Blue Jays asked him to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He belongs in the majors,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everyone was saying the same thing last year when
Cruz, the Mariners' first-round draft choice in 1995, joined
Seattle on May 30 and became an instant contributor, hitting 12
home runs and driving in 34 runs in 49 games.
</P>
<P>
   But with the bullpen in disarray and their AL West title hopes
riding on improved relief, the Mariners dealt Cruz to Toronto on
July 31, the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner fans wailed. Blue Jay fans celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of expectations put on his shoulders, and it
really wasn't fair,'' Piniella said. ``In this business, you can't
put too much pressure on yourself, and that might have happened to
him. I think he needed to go back (to the minors), get his mind
together, work on his game and become hungry again.
</P>
<P>
   But Cruz said that wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get into all that stuff,'' he said. ``I just didn't
play well the first couple of months, and if I knew why, I would
have corrected it and played better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a humbling game, and if you let it, it will be bite
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz is biting back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have an outstanding major league career, and I'd
take him back in a second,'' Piniella said. ``In fact, when he was
struggling, Woody (Woodward, the M's vice president of baseball
operations) and I talked many times about getting him back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
