A7443 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WATERSAFETY-S     08-11 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WATERSAFETY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCING PLAN ON CONSUMER WATER SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will stand at the edge of a
reservoir that serves San Francisco Tuesday morning to announce new
regulations intended to inform consumers what is in the water they
drink.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, the Environmental Protection Agency will require
each of the nation's 56,000 water districts to alert their
customers to the presence of pesticides, solvents, metals,
micro-organisms and other regulated substances that are routinely
found in the nation's drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The information, which will resemble the nutrition labels
attached to most food products, will be sent to customers at least
once a year and will list the levels of benign trace elements such
as calcium, as well as parasites such as cryptosporidium, which at
high levels can lead to serious gastrointestinal problems.
</P>
<P>
   California is the only state that already requires suppliers to
tell consumers what is in the water. The federal guidelines will
provide customers with even more information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has pushed hard to provide consumers with
information about all kinds of pollution they may be exposed to on
the theory that sunshine . . . is the best disinfectant,'' Kathleen
McGinty, chairwoman of the White House Council on Environmental
Quality, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information in the hands of consumers is a very potent tool
that can bring about change,'' McGinty said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will make the announcement at the San Andreas Reservoir
in San Bruno, where San Francisco stores much of the water it pipes
from the Hetch Hetchy Reservoir in Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The president was scheduled to arrive in the Bay Area last night
as part of a three-day fund-raising swing that will bring in
several million dollars for Democratic candidates across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced that he will cut the trip short by
several hours to return to Washington late Wednesday to discuss
possible responses to last week's embassy bombings in Africa.
Officials said the president may also want to be on hand Thursday
morning for a ceremony for Americans killed in the attacks. The San
Francisco leg of the trip will not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Before he returns to Washington, Clinton is expected to raise at
least $1 million for Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, starting at a
$1,000-per-plate lunch Tuesday at the St. Francis Hotel. Clinton
leaves for Los Angeles Tuesday afternoon for two more fund-raising
events for Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The new water regulations were authorized by the 1996 Safe
Drinking Water Act. They call for for public water districts to
provide their customers at least once a year with a detailed list
of contaminants, something that California has required since the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Going beyond the state law, the new guidelines call for water
agencies to identify the likely source of the contaminants, and
include a special advisory for people who may be at special risk,
such as those with weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's water supply, like that of most of the nation,
is well within government regulations and is considered safe,
although it contains elements that in large doses can be a risk to
those with specific illnesses or weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of progress in cleaning up water across the
country,'' McGinty said. ``There is a lot of work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the president's announcement is part
of an effort to make the public aware of pollutants so they can
make more informed choices or work to alleviate the source of
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have really expanded the public's right to know in an
important area,'' said Dr. Gina Solomon, a scientist with the
Natural Resources Defense Council. ``People really care what they
put in their mouths, and they really care what is in their water.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said she is hopes most states will go beyond the federal
requirements and provide information on contaminants that are not
currently regulated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 0225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
