<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON     08-11 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN TALENT AND GREATNESS
</HEADLINE>
   By C.W. NEVIUS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They used to flock to Barry Bonds. When he was winning the MVP
award three times in four years, the national media came to him on
bended knee, asking for a moment, a quote.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Bonds blew them off. A Sports Illustrated
writer became so exasperated that he ended up writing a story on
how difficult it was to talk to him. Another writer from one of the
largest newspapers in the country tried for some time to interview
him, finally gave up and was on a pay phone, calling the editor to
say that the story would have to be canceled when Bonds walked by.
``Want to talk now?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   You never knew with Bonds, and we still don't. He's more
approachable now, but less likely to be approached. At one point
Bonds said he was glad to see that the Bay Area press corps was
allowing him his space. Actually, writers were ignoring him.
</P>
<P>
   This all matters because it is entirely possible that this week
Bonds will reach an amazing baseball milestone. With two more home
runs he can become the first player in the history of the game to
hit 400 homers and steal 400 bases.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stunning display of power and speed, but what does it
all mean? As the curtain starts to come slowly down on Bonds'
career, such milestones look more than ever like an empty string of
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Bonds is an almost certain first ballot Hall of
Famer, but _ unless there is an incredible run by the Giants in the
next two years _ when the rest of the bronze plaques start
comparing their championship rings, Bonds is going to have to
change the subject. He has never won it all, and his frustrating
record in the postseason (one home run and five RBIs in four years)
must eat at him.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't any question that Bonds wants to win. This isn't
some greedy jerk who is collecting a huge paycheck while
sleep-walking through his contract. His physical skills may have
slipped, but he is still  &LR; the  &LR; impact player on the Giants, the
hitter every team has to stop.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains convinced that his responsibility begins and ends
within the confines of his batting helmet. Anything that happens
beyond his narrow world view does not concern him.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a leader, on or off the field. He declines to bother
with mandatory team stretching before many games, and he has
exasperated generations of old-school baseball fans by refusing to
run out routine ground balls because he feels the pointless effort
takes too much out of him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he continues to steal bases at times when the only reason
can be to pad his stats. The whole fuss in Philadelphia two Sundays
ago, when Bonds stole second with the Giants holding a 9-2 lead,
was vintage Bonds. It would be fascinating to know how many of his
437 steals were cheapies like that one.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Phillies considered that steal, and that's why
pitcher Ricky Bottalico hit Bonds (in the leg, which is accepted
baseball protocol). Bonds, who said he was tired of getting hit,
charged the mound, starting one of baseball's famous bench-clearing
discussion groups.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is fine. The Phillies made their point, and so did
Bonds. The problem is, now Bonds is going to have to serve a
suspension soon, taking him out of the lineup in the middle of a
tense playoff run. To his credit, Bonds has said he was sorry, but
the damage is done. Bonds defended his masculinity, and the Giants
lose him for three games. How many like that tradeoff?
</P>
<P>
   They say no man is an island, but in the clubhouse, Bonds is a
notorious peninsula. He sits in front of his locker or in the
training room and rarely interacts with his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that may be for the best. When it comes to social
skills, Bonds' report card would be checked for, ``Does not play
well with others.''
</P>
<P>
   We got the annual Bonds dustup out of the way relatively early
this year, when he and 42-year-old pitcher Danny Darwin scuffled.
There was a similar incident years ago when Bonds and and former
Giants first baseman Mark Carreon exchanged punches. Then there's a
long list of people with whom he's had verbal confrontations,
including former third baseman Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The real puzzler is how Bonds seems to go after those who have
supported him. He talks of how he reveres his former Pittsburgh
manager, Jim Leyland, but while they were with Pittsburgh, the two
got into a shouting match at spring training, which was caught on a
television camera.
</P>
<P>
   And this year Bonds became upset at Giants manager Dusty Baker,
who has bent over backwards to defend his left fielder. Ironically,
Baker thought he was sticking up for Bonds at the time. Hearing
that the Dodgers intended to throw at Bonds in retaliation for his
post-home run antics in last year's season-ending series, Baker
issued a warning in the media. Bonds, upset that Baker did not come
to him first, told reporters that Baker could ``kiss my ass.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Barry Bonds that baseball will know. As his skills
erode, Bonds says he will play out his contract, which runs through
2000, and fade away. If so, he will be known as a player who was
just a notch below the greats _ talented but mercurial, an odd guy
who often annoyed his teammates and always mystified them.
</P>
<P>
   Nice numbers, though.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
