A7505 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDREN-PESTICIDES-S     08-11 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-PESTICIDES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UC BERKELEY TO GET PESTICIDE CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore announced Monday that the
first center to study the effect of pesticides on children will be
established at the University of California at Berkeley, part of a
federally funded initiative focusing on children's health.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a White House ceremony, Gore said UC Berkeley's School of
Public Health has been awarded $1.1 million in federal funds to
look at the impact of pesticide exposure on children living in
agricultural regions near Salinas in California's Salinas Valley.
</P>
<P>
   UC researchers will carry out the project in collaboration with
community organizations in the Salinas Valley, including La Clinica
De Salud Del Valle De Salinas and La Natividad Medical Center in
Salinas. They intend to follow 550 pregnant women in the Salinas
area over three years to examine the impact of pesticides on
children's development.
</P>
<P>
   Pesticide use in agriculture and for home and industrial
purposes has doubled over the past 30 years, according to ``Our
Children at Risk,'' a report issued last year by the Natural
Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children and infants are uniquely susceptible because of their
physiological immaturity and greater exposure,'' the report stated.
It noted that pesticides ``have been associated with certain
childhood cancers, found to adversely affect the nervous system,
and linked with birth defects and altered functions of the immune
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Gonzalez, director of El Colegio Popular, a community
organization in Fresno, welcomed the establishment of the UC
Berkeley center, saying ``it is long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was years before anybody started to document accidents and
rashes and connecting them to pesticides,'' Gonzales. ``It is still
definitely a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   During the current harvest season, approximately 250,000 workers
are picking a range of crops on California farms. Arcadio Riveros,
director of Salud Para La Gente, a health clinic in Watsonville,
said children in farmworker families run a greater risk of being
exposed to pesticides, even if they don't work in the fields
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, parents carry pesticides in their clothes,
which they wash along with their children's clothes. ``Regular
washing does not necessarily get rid of these pesticides,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal grant was one of eight to be awarded to universities
nationwide to establish ``Centers of Excellence in Children's
Health Research.'' The $10.6 million initiative comes in response
to an executive order issued by President Clinton in April 1997, in
which he directed all federal agencies for the first time to take
children's health into account when issuing regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The other centers will examine the growing incidence of
childhood asthma and respiratory problems. The University of
Southern California, for example, received $1.3 million to look at
the impact of secondhand tobacco smoke and other environmental
health threats, working together with community organizations like
Mothers of East Los Angeles. Another grant went to Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore to look at the impact of air pollutants and
rising ozone on asthma rates among inner-city children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
