<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     08-11 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 REP. YOUNG TAKES A PAGE FROM SEN. McCARTHY  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   Rep.
Don Young, R-Alaska, has created a new loyalty test for members of
the U.S. Forest Service:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Are you now, or have you ever been, a card-carrying member of
The Sierra Club? Are you now, or have you ever been, a dues-paying
member of the Wilderness Society? Have you ever had any contact
with environmental organizations?''
</P>
<P>
   On July 28, Young, as the chairman of the House Resources
Committee, wrote a letter to the Regional Forester of the
Southwestern Region Eleanor S. Towns of the Forest Service in
Albuquerque, N.M., asking her ``whether any of their employees are
members of'' or ``have any contact with'' any environmental groups
that have been involved in lawsuits against the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   The letter asks 19 separate questions, each of which would take
a month to answer fully, but this one _ question No. 13 _ stands
out as an unconstitutional infringement on the associational rights
of federal employees. The U.S. Supreme Court made it clear in
rulings from the 1960s and '70s that even federal employees have a
right to associate with whom they wish.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear from the letter that Young doesn't like the way the
Endangered Species Act is being implemented in Southwestern United
States. The Forest Service had reached an agreement with ranchers
to preserve the limited riparian areas in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Towns was given until Aug. 15 to respond to Young's inquiry.
Let's call the enviro-affiliation question what it is _ a
witch-hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Young's letter implies that enviros in the Forest Service leak
federal documents to environmental groups. Question No. 12 of the
letter: ``How does the U.S. Forest Service prevent conflicts of
interest involving their employees from arising in their
decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the old Joe McCarthy ploy _ guilt by association. The taint
of environmentalism is equivalent to the stigma of communism in
Young's equation.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Forest Service employee and a member of the
Southwest Center for Biological Diversity or any other
environmental group, you probably leaked Forest Service information
to give leverage to the environmentalists in lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The implication here is that if you are employed by the Forest
Service, then you had better not be a card-carrying member of any
environmental group. You shouldn't care about the environment.
After all, forests are timber waiting to be cut _ nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   The very question reflects Young's own position on the
environment _ the wilderness and forests are there to be exploited.
In the last few years he has voted against a bill to repeal the
lawless salvage timber sale program; against a bill to reform of
the hardrock mining; against a bill to eliminate funding for
subsidized timber logging roads.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Public Interest Research Group gave him a zero rating
on environmental issues in 1995-96. PIRGs are state-based
non-profit, non-partisan research and advocacy groups. In 1997, the
League of Conservation Voters, which educates voters on the voting
records of their elected officials, gave Young a mere 6 percent
rating out of a possible 100 percent on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Congress, Young is one of the best arguments in
favor of term limits _ currently serving his 13th term as Alaska's
only member of the House, he is tied into the economic power
structure. Bound, one might say.
</P>
<P>
   According to the non-profit, non-partisan Center for Responsive
Politics, in a short year and a half, from January 1997 to July
1998, Young has accepted $93,736 in campaign contributions from the
oil and gas, forestry, and mining industries.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Young doesn't see that accepting these funds might
constitute a conflict of interest for the chairman of the House
Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the two-year election cycle, 1995-1996, Young pocketed a
little more than $1.1 million in campaign donations _ $173,050 or
15 percent of that came from agricultural, energy and natural
resource industries.
</P>
<P>
   Young is well aware where his loyalties lie.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of disclosure _ which Young has asked from Forest
Service employees _ I suggest that before any member of Congress
votes on a bill, he or she state how much in total campaign
contributions have been received from industries affected by the
proposed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how different the votes on proposed legislation would be
if a member of Congress had to get up and confess: ``Hello, my name
is Don Young. I'm addicted to campaign donations from the minerals
and agricultural industries. In the past year, I accepted over
$100,000 in contributions from them. And now I vote in favor of
this bill that grants a tax break to these industries.''
</P>
<P>
   While campaign contributions may not constitute a quid pro quo,
a favor for a favor, a vote for a large donation _ still the vast
amounts of money do weigh heavily and create a steep inclined
plane, a slope that funnels the vote in the desired direction. An
upright member of Congress might have a problem not falling down
into it.
</P>
<P>
   At least our senators and representatives ought to be called on
the relationship between their votes and the donations they have
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Young might then be a little more cautious about accusing others
of conflicts of interest and so-called tainted associations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
