<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELARUS-INTERNET-0812     08-11 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-INTERNET-0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HELLO WEB, GOOD-BYE RED: BUDDING EAST BLOC ENTREPRENEURS COME TO
ATLANTA
 &HT;    EDs: See bottom of story for related web sites.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ In a dingy office not far from the intersection
of Lenin Avenue and Karl Marx Street, some serious capitalism is
being committed in the most Soviet of the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
   Belarus, a country of 10 million sandwiched between Poland and
Russia, has been noted for its repression and lack of free
enterprise in the seven years since the Soviet Union disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   Yet huddled around a computer terminal, Olga Zauyalova, 20, and
her partner Pavel Bintsarovski, 18, perform an uncanny exercise in
this country with little in the way of a market economy: They
create, produce, advertise and sell products, competing via the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, their company -- appropriately called ``Alien''
-- is mere fiction, and their profits are all on paper.
</P>
<P>
   But the whiz kids have excelled as part of an international
competition of young entrepreneurs. They are among eight teams from
six nations scheduled to compete in Atlanta on Thursday(Aug. 13) in
the Global Business Challenge, sponsored by Junior Achievement
International and the computer-equipment maker Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   The competition began in February with 648 students representing
teams from 39 countries. The contest via the Internet uses software
created by Junior Achievement to simulate the management of a
company and the factors that can affect the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The students compete for profit, sales, and market share by
setting product prices, determining production levels, planning a
market strategy and research and development budgets, and investing
in plants and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the high schoolers and college students from the
former Soviet Union are among the best.
</P>
<P>
   Only one American team, from Mill City, Ore., reached the finals
this year. Another team comes from Buenos Aires, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The six remaining teams are from lands once behind the Iron
Curtain -- Belarus, Ukraine, two teams from Lithuania and two teams
from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very interesting for us because it is so new,'' said
Zauyalova. ``We have a central economy, but in Junior Achievement
we get to deal in models of market economies. That is exciting. And
during Soviet times, we had no opportunity to communicate with the
world. Now, we're doing it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, each team will compete via computer simulation to
manufacture and market a fictional product called ``EchoPens,''
computerized pens that can remember and reproduce what they have
written.
</P>
<P>
   The non-profit Junior Achievement organization has long been
known in the United States as a booster of budding capitalists
through its after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   Its foreign activities exploded after the fall of the Soviet
Union in 1991, and with the growth of economies in Latin America
and Asia. Junior Achievement programs have been introduced in 103
countries outside the United States, reaching about 1 million
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're saying to the kids is: Go out there and create, you
don't have to wait on the government,'' said Sam Taylor, the chief
operating officer at the Junior Achievement headquarters in
Colorado Springs, Colo. ``It makes them feel that they are a part
of the (global) system, and I think that is a very powerful
incentive for democratic reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   That message has resonated loudly in Eastern Europe, where the
novelty of open markets has made Junior Achievement programs
popular, reaching about 250,000 students compared with some 60,000
in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the team from Belarus, profit-motive also is an
incentive. The $3,000 first-place prize money offered in Atlanta is
a fortune in a country were the average annual salary has most
recently been estimated at $800 or less because of massive
inflation and the stagnant, state-run economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all are real aliens in your life of prosperity,'' the team
from Belarus explains on the competition Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Belarus imposes rigid controls on its banking and commerce. It
has no equity markets and only about five percent of companies and
enterprises in the nation are privately owned.
</P>
<P>
   They are facts which lead to frustration for the young
enterprisers once the competition ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this knowledge, I just wish I could use it to get a good
job,'' said Bintsarovski, who competed in the 1996 finals in San
Francisco and -- subject to the rules -- will be relegated to the
role of observer in Atlanta. ``I think all my theoretical training
would be enough for me to start my own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Their adviser, Vycheslav Starikov, an economics professor and
head of the local Junior Achievement program founded in Minsk in
1992, predicts changes in his country now that young people have a
taste of Western-style freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I weren't sure about the future, I wouldn't have gotten
involved in this,'' he said. ``The younger generation will not live
in the same conditions we did. They simply will not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the potential,'' said Starikov. ``We just need the
conditions to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   For more information, readers may contact the following Web
sites:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.harvassoc.com/hpgbc -- or -- http://www.jaintl.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
