<HEADLINE>
BO DEREK BUCKS THE SEX SYMBOL FATE
</HEADLINE>
  1000 words, with color slides and black and white photos of Bo
Derek available)
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood has treated its sex symbols with a mixture of pride
and prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is still out on Bo Derek. In the l979 movie ``10'' she
became the world's perfect woman, and an instant corn-rowed sex
symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Today Bo is all of 41 years old and while men at that age can
continue to be box office icons, her sex symbol movie career is
virtually over. However, in October she's coming back _ to the
small screen. Still able to slip easily into a bikini, in ``Wind on
Water,'' a steamy new series on NBC, she's playing a beautiful
widow with two teenage sons, a strong woman battling to keep her
Hawaiian ranch. It's a kind of ``Dallas'' meets ``Bonanza'' via
``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Slugged:  &UR; BC-IVOR-IVOR-BO-DEREK-ART-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code e.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7835 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-BO-DEREK-ART-NYT     08-11 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-BO-DEREK-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BO DEREK BUCKS THE SEX SYMBOL FATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444. Overseas, contact Karl Horwitz in Paris at
33-1-47-42-17-11.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Bo Derek are available. 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Hollywood has treated its sex symbols with a mixture of pride
and prejudice. The history of the women who supply the glamour to a
glamour industry is for the most part a sad one.
 &HT;    For many, the more the flashlights popped, the more lines of
print their lives occupied, the less happiness seemed to come their
way. Rita Hayworth was the perfect screen goddess but she could
never quite cope with the adulation that came from her looks,
especially since the real woman behind the facade couldn't ever
measure up.
 &HT;    Marilyn Monroe, who parlayed pinups and calendars into the kind
of stardom even she probably never dreamed of, is now celebrated _
again and again in books and movies _ as a feminist icon. But at
the height of her success she was confused and abused and never
managed to surmount her miserable childhood.
 &HT;    Voluptuary Jayne Mansfield met an untimely end (in a car crash
in l967) before she could prove to anyone that she was anything
more than a superstructure.
 &HT;    Not all sex symbols however have crashed and burned: Raquel
Welch has worn well and is about to remarry at 57. Joan Collins
parlayed her over the top diva image into Our Lady of Perpetual
Glamor. Sharon Stone and Demi Moore are earning up to $12 million a
picture. Stone is happily married to a newspaper editor from San
Francisco while Moore's marriage to Bruce Willis has just bottomed
out.
 &HT;    The jury is still out on Bo Derek. In the l979 movie ``10'' she
became the world's perfect woman, and an instant corn-rowed sex
symbol. As Dudley Moore's fantasy, she ignited the sexual desires
of millions of men around the world.
 &HT;    Today Bo is all of 41 years old and while men at that age can
continue to be box office icons, her sex symbol movie career is
virtually over. However, in October she's coming back _ to the
small screen. Still able to slip easily into a bikini, in ``Wind on
Water,'' a steamy new series on NBC, she's playing a beautiful
widow with two teenage sons, a strong woman battling to keep her
Hawaiian ranch. It's a kind of ``Dallas'' meets ``Bonanza'' via
``Baywatch.''
 &HT;    Two decades ago while Derek had the world at her feet, her life
was hardly her own. Her world and everything in it belonged to her
Svengali _ her domineering director-husband John Derek.
 &HT;    Bo was in her teens when Derek 30 years her senior, who had made
an art of growing sex symbols and marrying them, spotted her and
recreated her to his own blueprint. From then on Derek called the
shots. But in May of this year after a 24-year marriage Derek died
of heart failure, leaving Bo with a huge hole in her life.
 &HT;    She is still a sexy lady, her skin apparently untouched by her
years in the California sun. Wearing tiny granny sunglasses to lend
maturity, her figure is exercise-trim in a gray silk pants suit
over a black blouse, her hair still California beach baby blonde.
She's still Bo, the 10, just a tiny bit older. But the strings are
still visible even though the puppeteer has disappeared.
 &HT;    ``We were together since I was l7,'' she explains seriously,
``and that was my adult life. Now he's gone it hasn't really hit me
yet. It's all very strange.''
 &HT;    Derek had spent his lifetime molding women to fit his preferred
image. A former actor, he did it with Ursula Andress, wife No. 2.
He then photographed Linda Evans, his third wife for sexy magazines
and gained control over Bo when she was little more than a child.
 &HT;    She was a typical California surfer kid named Mary Kathleen
Collins from Long Beach, when Derek first set eyes on her on the
set of an erotic film he was making in Greece. Her mother had come
along as chaperone. Derek called her The Kid because he said he
didn't like her name.
 &HT;    For the Kid, finding her own life distinct from the man who ran
the only one she's known for almost a quarter of a century is a
tough order.
 &HT;    ``It was a matter of either going back to work or jumping off a
cliff,'' says Bo, who still makes her home on the sprawling horse
ranch she shared with her husband in the Santa Ynez Valley, 150
miles north of Los Angeles in the rolling Santa Barbara hills _ far
from the influences of Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``It's an absolute blessing that I have to go to Hawaii to do
the series, '' she admits. ``They are going to tell me when to get
up, where to go and what to say and do. That's important to me
right now. I'm not good at making decisions.''
 &HT;    Ironically, she says before he died Derek tried to talk her out
of doing the show.
 &HT;    ``He shuddered at the idea of me taking the role. Coming back to
Hollywood playing a mother to two adults was not his idea of the
woman he was in love with. He always saw me as The Kid. He couldn't
figure out that I'd grown up. But I felt this was the right thing
to do. I took control of my own career. And that makes it easier
for me to live with now.''
 &HT;    While the evidence of it is all around, not least in everything
she says, she still denies that Derek orchestrated her every move.
 &HT;    ``He was a rebel and he wanted things the way he wanted them.
But we both danced to our own drummer. And we fought battles with
Hollywood. Some we lost, some we won. But it enabled me to sleep
well at night. But then I took my own life in my own hands. I'm not
l7 anymore. ''
 &HT;    Hollywood believed Derek was using his young wife, exploiting
her immaturity to stroke his own ego _ and boost his bank balance.
But Bo says it was never that big a deal.
 &HT;    ``I never took my screen image very seriously,'' she says.
``Blake Edwards (director of ``lO'') was responsible for it. Not me
... although I got a lot of credit for it. Even John got credit for
it, or the blame and he had nothing to do with it,'' she laughs.
 &HT;    The most she and Derek are guilty of, she points out, was going
with the momentum Edwards had started. ``I never made an effort to
change that image. I really didn't. I wasn't out to prove anything.
It was a blessing in my life and made my life an absolute fairy
tale. After '10' I could pretty much do anything I wanted in the
business. So it was my fault if I didn't go to another level. I was
responsible.''
 &HT;    But how does the dancer dance when the dance master is no more?
The new series, she says, will be her life line. ``Wind on Water''
has given her a new family structure.
 &HT;    ``I feel it came at the right time and place in my life. I
believe in the show but it's not about me. It's much bigger than
me. It's about the young people on the show, their problems, their
experiences. I'm just the mom. Mind you I'm never going to be the
sit on the porch kind of mom. ''
 &HT;    ------
 &HT;    
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
