<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-ISRAEL-$ADV13     08-11 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-ISRAEL-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: AMID CINEMA SEARCHES, EXPLODED PINATAS, A FOREIGNER
FACES ISRAELI SECURITY
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: This story is being resent for those who have not used
it, and to kick off a weekly installment of journals for Cox
Newspapers' foreign correspondents.
 &HT;    With photo of Kaplow placed in the International folder on the
Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Aug. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The waitress could see that my parents and I were
novices.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled with a few Israelis in the bathroom corridor of a
downtown sandwich shop, we waited for word that the suspicious
object down the street had been deemed harmless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this your first time?'' said our server with a big,
friendly smile.
</P>
<P>
   Such friendly smiles might be a rarity in this tense city, but
bomb scares are not.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, we were allowed back to our table. Israeli bomb
specialists were putting their armor vests back into their van.
</P>
<P>
   After a year as Cox Newspapers' Middle East correspondent, I
realized, during this visit from my parents, that I'm getting used
to conditions that most Americans would find unnerving and most
Israelis barely notice.
</P>
<P>
   Police sometimes deal with hundreds of bomb scares a day after
terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen a bomb squad seal off a pedestrian promenade and, with
ropes, carefully tug apart a mysterious paper box only to find a
cake inside. The day after a birthday party for a colleague's
child, the bomb squad blew up an unfamiliar object found in the
garbage -- a beat up pinata.
</P>
<P>
   Entering any mall or movie theater, guards search your shoulder
bag. They take your name and license plate number when parking at
the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Any doubt that this is necessary was erased a few months ago.
Israeli police said Palestinian terrorists had cased a Jerusalem
mall, passing through security with heavy bags of nails to test the
prospects of returning someday with nail bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide bombers killed 21 Israelis in attacks in July and
September of last year.
</P>
<P>
   These attacks rattle the Israelis, cause breaks in peace talks
and can unsettle the region. The omnipresent security may actually
relieve tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do we accept it, but we welcome it,'' said Rachel
Levy-Shiff, psychology professor at Tel Aviv's Bar-Ilan University.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide bombers have walked right past guards on the way to
their attacks. But Levy-Shiff said that security, even if it might
be an ``illusion,'' still makes Israelis feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Airline passengers here face questioning about who packed their
bags, who they met in Israel and whether they know any Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   It can take just a few minutes, or can lead to an item-by-item
inspection of luggage by large, multi-lingual, teams of young
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis or even American Jews often face just perfunctory
security reviews.
</P>
<P>
   When an Israeli Jew walked past a security ring in 1995 and
killed Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, police were accused of having
a ``blind spot'' toward the threat from their own people.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Palestinians will often be separated from the crowd
at the airport or on the streets for hours of questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Their resentment at this harsh treatment reminds me of
African-Americans in the United States who are needlessly hassled
by local police.
</P>
<P>
   My brushes with security have been understandable. An army
patrol flagged down my car and searched it as I drove away from the
family of a Hamas bomb-maker who had recently been killed.
</P>
<P>
   I've had to display articles in my lap-top computer to prove
that my travels in Arab areas were for journalism.
</P>
<P>
   These checks can be a nuisance. They are not going to eliminate
terrorism. But, on the way into the airplane or the movies, they
can also be a little reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
