<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRISTINA-BOOK-EXCERPT     08-11 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRISTINA-BOOK-EXCERPT-PART1-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``CRISTINA!: MY LIFE AS A BLONDE'': PART 1
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: Spanish translation available) 
 North American English-language print rights 
 By CRISTINA SARALEGUI  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't easy to be rich.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants the people who make it to have started at the
bottom. I didn't start at the bottom, I must admit.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather was a millionaire. In Cuba he was called the
Paper Czar because he was co-owner of the most important magazines
on the island and also held the monopoly for selling paper.
</P>
<P>
   I was born in Miramar, a wealthy suburb of Havana, where
everyone's main worry was to make sure that during hurricane season
his yacht was secured at the club. I lived in Miramar until we had
to emigrate to Miami in 196O, shortly after Fidel Castro's
revolution had overthrown the dictator Fulgencio Batista.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, I faced something I had never known:
prejudice. In those early days there were not many Latinos in
Miami. And even though I was blond, with light eyes, my accent and
behavior were unmistakably foreign to the ``natives.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't understand why I was called ``spic,'' until someone
explained that the word came from the way a Spanish speaker
pronounces the word ``speak,'' shortening the vowel to spic. But
then I couldn't understand why they said, ``Hey, spic, why don't
you go back where you came from?'' when none of the ancestors of
those ``natives'' were from the United States either.
</P>
<P>
   I enrolled in the University of Miami, where I studied
communications with a minor in creative writing. During the last
year of the course, the university required an internship with some
publication.
</P>
<P>
   I chose Vanidades because of my deep sentimental ties to that
magazine. My family had just sold it to a Venezuelan publisher and
his partner. I thought, All right, I'll work as an intern for a
year, and that's the last they'll see of me.
</P>
<P>
   I learned to write every kind of article, from pieces on beauty
and fashion to international news. Then when Frank Calderon, the
editor in chief of Buenhogar (the Spanish version of Good
Housekeeping) was appointed editor of Cosmopolitan en Espanol and
the first thing he did was to hire me from Vanidades as his first
staff writer.
</P>
<P>
   Like a good Cosmo girl, I was 26 and decided to move from our
home on Key Biscayne and rent a small apartment. My father was
going through one of his hard times and was trying to sell the
mansion on Key Biscayne to cut back on expenses. I moved, both to
be independent and not to be a burden on my parents.
</P>
<P>
   I must admit that I had a more difficult time than other girls
my age because I was totally spoiled and immature.
</P>
<P>
   My first excursion into cleaning consisted of buying two spray
cans of foaming cleanser: one for the bathroom, the other for the
oven. From time to time I mixed them up and cleaned the bathroom
with the oven cleaner and the oven with the one for the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   My mailbox was overflowing with bills. My money ran out because
I earned so little, and I began to lose my credit. My father was
now flat broke and couldn't help me either. I kept moving to
cheaper and cheaper apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually I realized my life was a mess, and I knew I had to
calm down.
</P>
<P>
   One of the young men I was going out with was named Tony
Menendez. He was a firefighter and real estate salesman. I told
myself, ``I need to slow down and have a baby. This is a good man,
and I know he will be a good father.'' I was that cool in my
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   I married him and a year later, at 29, had my first daughter,
Cristina Amalia Menendez y Saralegui, whom we called Titi. When our
daughter was born, Tony and I moved into a small house on Key
Biscayne.
</P>
<P>
   As time went by, I realized that my husband, although he was
working every day (and getting dressed every day in jacket and
tie), simply wasn't selling anything. We had to move into my
father's three-room apartment, with my dachshund, which was covered
with fleas that immediately infested my mother's carpet.
</P>
<P>
   One day my husband said, ``You have to get a job and help out.''
</P>
<P>
   I looked him straight in the eye and said; ``I left my job to
start a family with you. If you ask me to go back to work, you'd
better be ready for whatever happens.''
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't capable of working in an office from 9 to 5 and
trudging home like an automaton to pick up my life. That was work,
not a career. And for me it had to be a career.
</P>
<P>
   I went to Cosmo and visited my former boss. ``I'm sorry,'' he
told me.
</P>
<P>
   On my way out of the building, in desperation I turned and went
to see Elvira Mendoza, whom I had left in the lurch at Vanidades to
go work for Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elvira, I have a baby girl now. Here's her picture,'' I began.
</P>
<P>
   She answered, ``What a beautiful child!''
</P>
<P>
   Then it all poured out. I told her the truth and confessed that
I needed a job.
</P>
<P>
   Her reply was instantaneous. ``Well, of course, I'll give you a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   So I came full circle back to where I'd begun, because she paid
me almost the same salary I'd started at, the lowest scale allowed.
</P>
<P>
   I worked at all hours. I did anything they told me. The owner
suggested that I take on the additional responsibility of being
editorial coordinator for Intimidades, a new small-format magazine
in Caracas, Venezuela, that focused primarily on information about
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   I worked the whole day at Vanidades, writing and editing. Then,
at 5 o'clock, I would save my article on the computer, get into my
car, eat a sandwich as I drove, pick up my baby from the sitter,
put her in her car seat and take her to the home of my
mother-in-law, Marieta, a saint who worked at a factory that made
ballet and exercise clothing.
</P>
<P>
   I would run back to my office, sit back down at the computer,
and with that crazy schedule we got Intimidades under way.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day Frank Calderon, for reasons I don't know to this
day, banged his typewriter against his desk and walked out. The
management offered me his position as editor in chief of
Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   I was terrified. But I accepted for two reasons: hunger and
ambition. My daughter had turned me into a career woman. And
careers are like children: They grow! I had to dare to grow with
mine.
</P>
<P>
   That was MY CAUSE during the 10 years I directed Cosmopolitan.
Little by little I shaped the magazine to be a motivating force for
working women.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the things I've learned:
</P>
<P>
   _ List in a notebook the most important things in your life,
family, job, health, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the basis of those principles, define the goals you want to
reach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Every goal must have a deadline, whether 20 years or two
months.
</P>
<P>
   My goals have been varied because I am convinced that happiness
leads to success but that we are happy only when we achieve a
balance in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I divide my goals into categories:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cultural goals: Take classes in a foreign language, read a
book every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family goals: Have a lasting marriage and children who become
good men and women.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spiritual goals: Read everything that might open the eyes of
my spirit and help my soul evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning review your goals for self-improvement and keep
the last day of the month to check, point by point, what you have
done to reach them.
</P>
<P>
   Begin right now.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   Reprinted from CRISTINA! MY LIFE AS A BLONDE by Cristina
Saralegui
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Cristina Saralegui enterprises Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Published by arangement with Warnre BOoks, Inc., New York USA
</P>
<P>
   All rights reserved
</P>
