<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Summer camp an experience for the senses
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone tell me, what is that smell that gestates in a boys'
dorm at summer camp?
</P>
<P>
   Put 20 pre-pubescent males into one room, and I don't expect the
essence of rose attar. And yet, we're talking month-old road kill
here. Rotten underwear, rotten food scraps, rotten, rotten, rotten.
</P>
<P>
   If Mel Gibson and Danny Glover could release this odor on their
enemies, they'd truly have a lethal weapon.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting our youngest son's camp mid-week and getting one
whiff of the dorm, I have a new appreciation for asthmatics. Any
self-respecting pair of lungs would shut down after ingesting one
breath of that fog.
</P>
<P>
   I admit, I'm new to the vagaries of summer camp. I didn't get to
attend as a child, so I have no personal experience from which to
draw.
</P>
<P>
   And, at the risk of sounding gender-biased, I do think there's a
difference between boys and girls' hygiene habits. At least girls
seem to make more of an effort to disguise body odor.
</P>
<P>
   We also noticed at the camp that there is a marked difference in
the sounds emitted by gender. Boys are loud. Believe me, with three
sons, I know that boys are loud. They bellow, roar, belch and, in
general, rampage through life.
</P>
<P>
   Teeny, tiny testosterone in the wailing infant grows into
terrible tyrannosaurus Rex testosterone in the teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one thing I've never heard a boy do: Squeal. Girls
squeal. A lot. Loudly. At ear-piercing levels. Multiply that by 100
at the camp and it produces a weapon more lethal than the boys'
stench.
</P>
<P>
   So, between the noise and the odor, our son's summer camp
experience was a real ear- and eye-opener. I have unbounded respect
for all the camp counselors who volunteered their time and senses
(or lack thereof) for this weeklong experience. Of course, many of
them were quite young and probably just a shower or two removed
from their charges.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion for our visit was Talent Night. It was an
extravaganza Ed Sullivan would have envied. We saw spinning
basketball tricks, comedy skits and even a takeoff on the
``Saturday Night Live'' cheerleading routine. We heard musical
numbers and a memorable impersonation of Aerosmith. We heard jokes,
really bad jokes. We were assaulted with silly string. And
throughout it all, the boys roared and the girls squealed.
</P>
<P>
   One skit in particular drew a raucous response. The youngsters
were testing out an echo, presumably on a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   They yelled ``salami,'' and it echoed back ``salami.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they called out ``pastrami,'' or some such, and it was
echoed back.
</P>
<P>
   But when they yelled ``baloney,'' there was no echo. They tried
again, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Then they hollered a camp counselor's name, ``who's the best
counselor in the whole camp!'' You guessed it, the echo came back
``Baloney!''
</P>
<P>
   The whooping and hollering was deafening.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it was time to leave, and things suddenly became very
quiet. As we gave our son a hug and said goodbye, he looked up at
us with big, solemn eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the matter?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothin','' he muttered. Then, ``Two more days of camp, huh?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. Gonna make it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm. I guess,'' he answered, looking longingly at our car.
</P>
<P>
   But then, his friends came and whirled him away into yet another
frenzy of activity. We said our goodbyes and drove away.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, he arrived home a champion camper. Full of
stories and accomplishments, new songs and games, he regaled us
with bunk bed escapades and camp food descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I asked him, ``Glad to be back?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said. ``It smells like home.''
</P>
<P>
   After his dorm, that can only be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
