<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEST-DRIVE12-COX     08-11 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-DRIVE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chevy sedan may exit as product line is trimmed
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Less than 10 years after it was introduced as a 1990
model, the midsize Chevrolet Lumina sedan is one of the vehicles
reportedly headed for the ax if General Motors carries out the
talked-about thinning of its product line. Here are four reasons
it's been tagged a ``blue light'' special, a ``best buy'' and a car
that ``does most things adequately, but unexceptionally.''
</P>
<P>
   _ It has base prices of $17,795 for the unadorned sedan, $19,395
for the sensibly equipped LS version and $20,295 for the sporty,
spoilered LTZ four-door. The ``light driftwood metallic'' _ brown,
if you will _ test vehicle totaled $21,454 with its only missing
optional features of any significance being a sunroof ($700) and
leather seats ($695).
</P>
<P>
   _ Although classified a midsize sedan, the Lumina is the largest
four-door in the Chevy fleet. It weighs a trim 3,300 pounds, is
200.9 inches long with a 107.5-inch wheelbase and can seat six
persons, although the middle passengers are likely to squawk.
Headroom and legroom are decent both front and rear, and the trunk
has a fully usable 15.5 cubic feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   _ Its 16.6-gallon fuel tank gives the Lumina a cruising range of
more than 300 miles, and its EPA figures are realistic: 20 mpg in
the city and 29 on the highway. That's predicated on
non-jack-rabbit starts in stop-and-go traffic and a willingness to
let the Lumina proceed at its own pace instead of forcing a
downshift up hills and long interstate inclines. Regular fuel is
recommended, and the tester's performance wasn't notably enhanced
by premium.
</P>
<P>
   In LS trim, the Lumina has the basics of air conditioning, tilt
wheel, full instrumentation and a stereo with cassette player and
four average speakers. Its options were reasonably priced, with an
in-dash CD player costing $93 and steering-wheel-mounted stereo
controls adding $171.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior can hardly be tagged exciting, but it's pleasing
with a moderate use of brightwork and blackout. The interior
deserves better marks, because it's got an easily read
instrumentation pod, big and/or convenient controls and good
visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The seating, at best, is fair. The optional power driver's seat
($305) adjusted nicely to drivers of different sizes, but the lower
portion of the seatback proved uncomfortable to some. The rear
seating is, um, firm and sized more for children than full-size
adults.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, the Lumina is one of those cars that falls into the
easy-driver category, meaning little physical effort is required,
and it has a stable feel, as long as brisk cornering isn't asked of
it. The ride's comfortable, but not quiet _ the 160-horsepower V-6
goes willingly, but it does some serious wailing en route to its
6,000 rpm redline. Peak power comes at 5,200 rpm, while maximum
torque is developed at a comparatively hushed 4,000 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Given some styling perks, a refined drivetrain and better
seating, the Lumina could be more than the utilitarian
family/commuter sedan that it is. For now, however, it's a
workhorse that seems to be running out of time.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1998 Chevrolet Lumina LS front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $21,454 (base: $19,395)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, power anti-lock brakes
with front discs and rear drums, height-adjustable seat belts,
side-impact beams, daytime running lights
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 3.1-liter V-6 engine (160 horsepower), four-speed
automatic overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: LS package with keyless entry, cruise
control, power trunk opener, dual AC/heat controls, mats, $645;
six-way power driver's seat, $305; leather-wrapped steering wheel
with stereo controls, $171; rear child seat, $125; rear defogger,
$170; CD player, $93
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 20 mpg regular unleaded city, 29 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Russ DeVault writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
