 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, August 12, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ There's one real issue and a lot of partisan fog
in the reckless decision of the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee to cite Attorney General Janet Reno for
contempt of Congress. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ The absurdity of myriad airline fares
cannot be more graphic than in the rates at least one airline
charges to fly to Atlanta from two South Florida cities. Likely,
similar situations exist in other areas, on other airlines. Some
starched shirt at Delta, I am certain, would have an explanation
for this vast difference but it would be incomprehensible to me,
and to any other traveler. Howard Kleinberg is a former editor of
the Miami News. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ ``Saving Private Ryan'' is three movies.
The first is a searing depiction of Omaha Beach. The second is the
finding of Pvt. Ryan. The third is a fight for a French village,
every battle scene you've ever seen done better. Omaha Beach
carries the rest to greatness. But the middle film, the search,
deserves a weightier theme. Sadly there are few left to do WWII
justice. (Rosenfled, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ The summer of 1998 will go down in the books as
one of the hottest on record. But Sarah T. Hayes of Longview,
Texas, remembers when summers seemed even hotter _ back before
air-conditioning. Here's her story. (Murray, Cox News Service)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Herb Evans is a man is dying of ALS
_ Lou Gehrig's Disease. Every muscle in his body is failing. And
he's not sick enough for Medicare. Medicare knows exactly what's
killing this man, but under money-saving revisions approved by
Congress, he was informed he was no longer eligible for home-care
visits. (Young, Waco Herald-Tribune.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ Because current fashion excesses take their cues
from fashion excesses of the '70s and '80s, parents now are in the
peculiar position of seeing their children sent to the office for
the same styles that earned them the scrutiny of yesterday's
assistant principals. This makes the work of a fashion cop harder
both for enforcers and perps. (Lane, Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ ``Bill Clinton's having this big conference in
October,'' my friend reminds me, ``to find out why there is so much
violence in our schools. What a waste of time and money. Ask any
judge who deals with kids. Kids are enraged at having no parents.
And don't forget, almost all they know so far in their lives they
have learned from television.'' (Schuett, Cox News Service.) MOVED.
</P>
