<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gellhorn speaks: Hemingway was `complete egotist'
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Granta 62'' is a rich feast. Among the entrees are Richard
Ford on where writing comes from, an excellent short story by Dani
Shapiro and a stunning memoir of Martha Gellhorn by Nicholas
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, of course, Gellhorn is remembered, not as an utterly
fearless war correspondent, but as Ernest Hemingway's third wife,
which drove her up the wall. She refused to write or talk about him
for public consumption, but, in private, talked about him
constantly. Shakespeare dutifully took notes.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway, according to Gellhorn, was selfish, a mythomaniac, a
man who had to have sex every day but, in spite of all his
practice, was a lousy lover. She insisted that he was ``not gay,
none of that.'' He never took notes, because he had absolutely
total recall, from the feel of the weather to the texture of the
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare creates a picture of two people who were ragingly
jealous of each other's gifts _ Hemingway of Gellhorn because she
was braver and a better reporter; Gellhorn of Hemingway because he
happened to be a great writer, which she, hampered by a lack of
imagination, could never be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a complete egotist,'' remembered Gellhorn, ``but he did
liberate English prose from mandarins like Henry James and Edith
Wharton. He freed everyone into being able to write about what they
felt. After Ernest it was possible to use ordinary words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you feel when he killed himself?'' Shakespeare asks
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder is not that the marriage exploded; the wonder is that
they were ever together for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   WHODUNNIT . . . Avon hopes to catch even more of their share of
the mystery wave with Twilight, a new line that will feature both
new books and reprints. Elizabeth Peters' popular Amelia Peabody
mysteries will appear under the imprint, as will Carolyn Hart,
along with some lesser-known authors.
</P>
<P>
   Avon's mysteries have always tended toward the category known as
``cozies'' largely deriving from Agatha Christie _ who slipped
arsenic into the vicar's teacup after the Sunday service, etc.
Twilight hopes to slightly enlarge upon their brand identity by
launching a new series about murders in old Philadelphia and
another about an 18th century midwife.
</P>
<P>
   Who buys mysteries? Typically, mystery readers are women,
between 45 and 55, with a higher than average income and,
apparently, very little blood-lust.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``Wisdom, when acquired, proves
incommunicable and useless and goes with our learning into the
grave. The edges of it occasionally impinge on people, though, and
strike a little awe into them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ E.M. FORSTER
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
