<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enforce rules for HOV lanes or take them away
 &HT;    By Linda Sharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it was first announced we would be getting HOV
lanes on the freeways in metro Atlanta, I was less than impressed.
</P>
<P>
   My immediate response was it was a waste of time and taxpayers'
money. I have since changed my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Because I am traveling alone most of the trips I make through
downtown, I rarely get to use them. However, when I have had the
opportunity, I have found them to be not only efficient, but stress
reducing.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit when I am sitting in bumper-to-bumper traffic in
one of the non-HOV lanes, I long for the luxury of cruising
unencumbered.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I have noticed an increasing percentage of solo
drivers who are doing more than just lusting. They are hopping in
the HOV lanes in an obvious disregard for the posted rules and
regulations. I don't know about you, but this really gets my goat.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't seem to be one particular stereotype or vehicle
type, but they all seem to be well-schooled in knowing how to beat
the system. I see a lot of high-end luxury vehicles _ sedans to
full-size sport-utility vehicles _ who are offenders. But on the
other hand, there are just as many economy cars using the HOV as a
passing lane. The one thing they all have in common is a total
disregard for the law.
</P>
<P>
   In long, straight stretches, you'll see these offenders darting
in and out of the HOV lane to advance their position. They always
drop back in their proper lane just prior to a curve. Obviously,
they expect the law to be laying in wait just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Or if there is an accident, these drivers seem to take it as
their license to steal.
</P>
<P>
   While I would agree it is probably acceptable to pass the
accident scene, I don't think it permits it two or three miles
after that accident. It also seems a lot of out-of-state drivers
cruise in the HOV lanes. There are adequate signs and no excuse for
this.
</P>
<P>
   I do have some questions.
</P>
<P>
   While buses and motorcycles are allowed in HOV lanes, were they
really intended for motor homes pulling boats at 45 mph? Or, if you
aren't going to keep up with the flow of traffic in the adjoining
lanes, should you be allowed to create a roadblock in the HOV lane?
</P>
<P>
   One morning, I observed an officer ticketing a young woman for
traveling illegally in the HOV lane. As he wrote, she was putting
on her mascara. Sadly, it is a commentary on how a lot of drivers
perceive the HOV lanes and their regulations. No big deal.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, they ask other motorists to report offenders. I'm
not yet ready for the HOV militia. Rather, I would welcome a
substantial fine for violators and make it progressive. Each repeat
offense doubles the fine. Sooner or later, you will either get
these drivers' attention or they won't have any money left for gas.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, if we are going to have HOV lanes, then they need
to be enforced. Or we should do away with them and have an extra
lane for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
