<HEADER>
A7950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN12-COX     08-11 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Voluntary uniforms clothe dress-code crackdown
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are few better indicators of social change than school
dress codes.
</P>
<P>
   In times of prosperity, people get sillier in their dress. (It's
a known fact, so take some solace from the stock market's recent
dive.) And when widespread fashion silliness trickles down to the
classroom, administrators strike back.
</P>
<P>
   Because current fashion excesses take their cues from fashion
excesses of the '70s and '80s, parents now are in the peculiar
position of seeing their children sent to the office for the same
styles that earned them the scrutiny of yesterday's assistant
principals. This makes the work of a fashion cop harder both for
enforcers and perps.
</P>
<P>
   As one who was predestined to nerdhood from the time I first
laced up a pair of black hightops, I had few dress-code problems.
But when I did, it was a beautiful thing.
</P>
<P>
   My hair did it. I was not attempting fashion, I just didn't like
haircuts. Haircuts involved my father dragging me to places that
smelled of talc and cheap smoke and discussing my appearance with
men in white coats who called me ``Sport'' and ``Red.'' Even for
me, it was a visit to the geek factory. I fought it with the best
weapons at my disposal _ procrastination and laying low.
</P>
<P>
   But one day, it could be put off no longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop right there, Red,'' the assistant principal called out to
me in a busy, between-periods junior-high hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Surely he meant someone else. Like many nerds, I operated on the
assumption that I was invisible to authority figures, cool kids and
girls over 10. This belief was seldom challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Since my name was not Red, I kept walking. He couldn't mean me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean you,'' he growled.
</P>
<P>
   I was apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   I was officially informed on paper and in the office that I had
24 hours to have my hair tamed to requisite length. Preferably by a
man in white who would put down a tattered copy of Argosy and say
``Whaddle it be, Red?'' by way of introduction.
</P>
<P>
   I slunk back to class.
</P>
<P>
   Yet upon my return, I found something amazing had happened. My
social standing, which was about what you'd expect of someone who
could work a sliderule, had strangely altered. In the short time I
spent in the principal's office, I somehow had achieved outlaw
status. Cool kids spoke to me for the first time. Detention room
recidivists commiserated. Girls ignored me in an altogether more
pleasant manner.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the school day was way-cool. But the spell was
broken that afternoon as soon as I heard the phrase ``Whaddle it
be, Red?''
</P>
<P>
   I went back to being ultra-nerd for the next decade or two.
</P>
<P>
   That experience was on my mind, as I read the dress code that my
kids' middle school just mailed out to parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only hair colors which occur naturally in humans are
appropriate,'' I recited. The kids groaned, protested and noted
that the blue rinse favored by several older substitute teachers
may be out of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   More interestingly, the school also launched what they called
``an optional uniform policy.'' You can wear a uniform to school
but don't have to.
</P>
<P>
   This has an odd sound to it. Is a voluntary uniform really a
uniform? I can't imagine the Enterprise with half the crew in sharp
Star Fleet jumpsuits and the other in baggy jeans and backwards
baseball caps.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as dumb as the phrase ``voluntary uniform'' sounds, it is
good training for what we laughingly call The Real World. A place
full of voluntary uniforms. From the suits that mark one as a suit,
to the leather jackets that may mark one variously as a biker, a
mid-life crisis case or cold-weather slacker. There's khaki
voluntary uniforms of information-age workers. And, of course, the
real voluntary uniform of middle school boys: baggy and long shorts
with oversized T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad that's not the school's official voluntary uniform. That
could doom the voluntary uniform movement before it begins.
</P>
<P>
   But if the kids grasp the concept, they'll understand what's
going on when the time comes to strap on ties and pull up
pantyhose. This will put them ahead of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it seems a shame to hurry them there. We don't get to be
cool very long. And having been a cool kid for one day, I'm the
wrong one to rush anyone into voluntary uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
