<HEADER>
A7951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN12-COX     08-11 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Is it any wonder our children are so violent?
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ There's a two-foot banner of toilet paper
streaming from the top of the raspberry bush beside my garage door.
Kids did it last Saturday night, probably some of my students on a
sleepover. It means they like me _ I think.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, three teens were pulled over by police at 3:30 a.m.
for driving the wrong way on a one-way street. You'll never guess
what officers found in the truck: Silly String, Liquid Plumr,
aluminum foil, and plastic two-liter bottles. The boys were out for
a little harmless bomb throwing because they didn't like the way
their boss had been treating them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the would-be bombers told police they intended to
``terrorize'' the boss's house, make a smiley face in the lawn with
gasoline, take an ax to the shrubs, and throw a bomb on the lawn.
Nice going, guys; that ought to get your point across. Can't help
but wonder, wouldn't it have been a lot simpler just to look for
another job?
</P>
<P>
   But worst of all, I have this gut feeling that at least one set
of parents is denying their son has a problem and is referring to
the entire episode as a ``boyish prank''? Maybe because we've heard
it all before.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is really a good boy,'' we read when little Sammy
attempts to get even for an imagined slight by shooting up his
classroom, or decides to blow away his grandmother because she
makes lousy cookies. ``He's just a little troubled.'' Troubled?
Definitely. A good boy? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good boys'' don't feel the need to emulate Hagar the Horrible
when life doesn't quite meet their expectations; they don't become
terrorists when their boss offends them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good boys,'' my friend, a teen-court judge on the Oregon coast
says, ``are the lucky ones whose childhood has equipped them with
moral and ethical alternatives to such over-the-top behavior _
whose parents haven't joined the not so elite ranks of the
out-to-lunch parent bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Weekly, she deals with the results of parents acting more like
children than their offspring. ``A single father I know took his
son off to Utah and dumped him in a drug rehab program. It's good
the boy is getting help, but the reasons he's there are not. The
father has known for two years that his son has a drug problem, but
when I asked him why he hadn't taken steps earlier, why he hadn't
kept the boy at home instead of letting him hang out at the skating
rink where he knew drugs were rampant, his response was: 'He needs
to spend time with his friends.' I know what that translates to,''
she says, ``because I hear it every court session. What that parent
is saying is: I don't have time to keep my kid at home because I'm
busy making money and having a life.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the same guy,'' she reminds me, ``whose 18-year-old
daughter has been allowed to bring her boyfriends home for
sleepovers since she was 16. The father's reasoning? 'They're not
doing anything.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is, discipline takes time and energy
and it's a lot easier just to give in. Heck,'' she chuckles, ``I'm
56 years old and my mother's 87, and I can promise you if I showed
up at her door with a boyfriend, there'd be separate sleeping
arrangements that she wouldn't hesitate to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week I had a parent tell me the reason police couldn't
find her at 2 a.m. to notify her that her 15-year-old daughter had
just been picked up incoherent on the beach was because she (the
mother) was sleeping at her boyfriend's place. I asked why she
didn't sleep at home and keep an eye on her daughter. You know what
she said? 'Because I was poor and abused as a child so I don't know
about things like that.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The judge's advice to her was to get over it. ``You're all grown
up now and it's time to assume responsibility for your actions AND
those of your children.'' But she knows she's whistling in the
wind. This is the kid's third offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton's having this big conference in October,'' my
friend reminds me, ``to find out why there is so much violence in
our schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a waste of time and money; it's just another load of
'feel good' bull. Ask any judge who deals with kids. The pattern is
invariable. Kids are enraged at having no parents. And don't
forget, almost all they know so far in their lives they have
learned from television.''
</P>
<P>
   Well parents, it's up to us. What's it going to be? Toilet paper
on the raspberry bush or bombs on the lawn?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
