<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX     08-11 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Left holding bed pan by Medicare
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If only Herb Evans were sick.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the government told his health provider.
</P>
<P>
   If only Evans had pneumonia, or a bronchial infection _
something other than the fact that he can't use his arms or legs,
or that his lungs work only at 20 percent capacity.
</P>
<P>
   If so, if Herb Evans were sick, then Medicare would pay for
home-health visits as it had until a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is still well enough to chuckle at the irony in these
statements. His vocal chords still afford his usual loquacity. But
it's no laughing matter. The Waco man is dying of ALS _ Lou
Gehrig's Disease _ though at 57, seven years after his diagnosis,
he bucks the odds of this vicious killer each day he breathes anew.
</P>
<P>
   Every muscle in his body is failing. And it's not sick enough
for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't some bookkeeping screw-up. Medicare knows exactly
what's killing this man. But under money-saving revisions approved
by Congress, since he's not having an ``acute episode'' or any
complication that requires a licensed nurse, he was informed he was
no longer eligible for home-care visits under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is among hundreds of thousands of home-bound Americans cut
at the knees by limitations put on home-care benefits in the 1997
Balanced Budget Act. Some were affected by a cap placed on how much
assistance they could get in a year. What the act did was draw a
line at projected costs based on 1994 figures and say, ``No more
home-care beyond that.'' The objective was to curb the rapid growth
of home-care costs and to get at fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Congress didn't understand what was driving
up the cost of home care. It wasn't fraud. It was choice, and sound
decisions. People who otherwise would be in costly institutional
care choose home care, generally fending for themselves with loved
ones helping, and relying on professionals only for daily visits of
short duration.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a bargain, Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   In Evans' case such visits mean helping him out of bed once a
day _ to bathe, to use the bathroom _ and otherwise to check his
vital signs and make sure all's well. His working wife and a son
spend as much time as they can with him, but she can't hoist him
out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, sir. If only you were sick.
</P>
<P>
   As if his plight needs more irony, it came shortly after the bad
news set in about home care, which Medicare had been paying for
through Hillcrest Baptist Medical Center. The Evanses found out
that Medicare would pay for the same services, and more, through a
hospice program based on his terminal prognosis. He switched over
to the Hillcrest Hospice.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, Herb Evans will chuckle _ he can still do it this
week _ to report that being diagnosed terminally ill, and
qualifying for hospice, is his lucky break, home-care wise.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be necessary. Ears have been burning in Washington.
Finally policy-makers are responding. Leaders on both sides of the
aisle in Washington are urging a halt to Medicare cuts which had
fallen so unmercifully on home care.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Pyle, manager of the home care service that was helping
Evans until the limits came into play, said that taking care out of
the home will compromise people's health and cost more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to force a lot of people into nursing home
environments, a lot of people into acute care.'' It's also going to
drive some people into poverty and over onto the Medicaid rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Evans says it jokingly, but it's no joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to save Medicare, but wanted us to die.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
