<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-iMAC-HNS &LR;      08-11 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-iMAC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 FUNKY iMAC BRINGS NEW LOOK, HOPE FOR APPLE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPERTINO, Calif. _ A goateed, British-born industrial designer
used Apple Computer Inc.'s new iMac as a pulpit for his crusade
against computers designed more for computer builders than for
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't start with engineering dictates,'' said Jonathan
Ive, 31, Apple's vice president of industrial design. ``We actually
started with people.''
</P>
<P>
   The iMac began with an idea from Apple co-founder and interim
chief executive Steve Jobs: To make a computer that would follow
not only form, but fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first talked about this, we didn't talk about other
computer companies,'' Ive said. ``We talked about companies like
Swatch, companies that broke the rules, that viewed technology as a
way to the consumer, not the consumer as the path to the
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's latest _ some are saying last _ effort to again become a
force in home computing goes on sale Saturday. According to Apple,
the pre-orders for the $1,299 iMac are making this the largest
computer roll-out in the company's history.
</P>
<P>
   Key to this crucial comeback is iMac's look: A sleek,
translucent white and aquamarine all-in-one machine straight out of
a Jetsons cartoon. The look is the creation of a secret Apple
international design team gathered and headed by Ive.
</P>
<P>
   Apple used customer focus groups to help create the blueprint
for the new machine. The response was immediate, and clear, Ive
said: Today's computers are complicated, mysterious _ even
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   One person's comments still sticks in Ive's mind. ``She said, `I
want to be able to do this and that. I want to be able to do some
e-mail. Don't give me any of your megahertz. I don't need those.'
It's very sobering,'' Ive said, ``to see how the majority of people
see high-tech products.''
</P>
<P>
   To counter those reactions, a ``back to the future'' look was
chosen. Nostalgia paired with progress. More Jetsons, less Blade
Runner. It's a design, Ive said, inspired by Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve talked specifically about the `Jetsons,''' Ive said.
``How it showed a future that was comfortable, not dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's design team then set about coming up with a computer in
which ``form slavishly followed function.'' Instead of cables
snaking from a hard-to-reach rear, iMac's connections _ for a
keyboard, mouse and other peripherals _ are in a single large port
on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for cables to be in the back, except that
it's easier for the engineers,'' Ive said.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac was also has a giant top handle built into it, a
favorite Ive feature. ``It's great. You immediately see it and know
it's for your hand. The product immediately becomes usable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the iMac shipping container was ``designed obsessively,''
Ive said. A cutout in the foam packaging allows a new user to lift
the machine easily from the box. The mouse's cord is packed coiled,
not crimped, the better to keep kinks away.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the translucent plastic skin, the antithesis of
computer beige. According to Ive, the plastic was colored after
consultation with candy industry pros.
</P>
<P>
   The see-though covering _ which changes hue with the intensity
of the room lighting _ forced some fundamental design changes for
the interior of the iMac, including the elimination of
reinforcement ribs and interior nuts and bolts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to express the technology,'' Ive said.
``We're trying to express it as technology that can do a lot of
different things for different people.''
</P>
<P>
   One feature _ or lack thereof _ has raised some hackles in the
computer world: The iMac does not come with a floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you the best Apple answer on the lack of the
floppy,'' Ive said. ``I can give you my answer: When you move on,
you have to leave some things behind. The floppy drive, which I
will argue until I'm blue in the face, is really antiquated
technology. I've heard the complaints,'' he said, ``but if there's
not some sort of friction in a move forward, then your step is not
as consequential as you'd like to believe it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the perfect computer,'' he sighed, rubbing his
creation's cover protectively. ``But I think we've taken a
consequential step here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But is it too much, too late for Apple, which has seen its
market share plummet in recent years?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be the savior for the company,'' said
Forrester Research consumer technology analyst Tom Rhinelander.
``It's just a stopgap measure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass.-based analyst said Apple's less-than 5
percent market share is too weak to revive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer wars are over,'' Rhinelander said. ``Apple lost.
It's time for them to move on to other technologies that aren't
computer based.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Wolf, a director in the equity research department
at Credit Suisse First Boston, disagreed. ``Nobody knows what's
going to happen. The fact is, there's an enormous build-up for this
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said there were an estimated 10 million Mac users
worldwide, 30 percent to 40 percent of whom are using four-year-old
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 10 percent of Mac owners decide to upgrade to an iMac,
that's a million units sold,'' Wolf said. ``That's an incredible
performance. And after seeing the iMac, I think its doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer reported its third straight money-making quarter
in mid-July, earning $101 million (65 cents a diluted share) and
far outstripping expectations. That compared with a loss of $56
million (44 cents) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has been locked down in a design studio for the last
year, Ive said he was well aware of what is riding on the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I've heard all the numbers,'' he said, when asked about
Apple's minute market share. ``But that's what gave us some
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a lot to lose,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
