<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JULIE-KRONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY IS OLDER, WISER AND HAPPY IN SECOND PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Down the stretch, Awesome Again decided
it was quitting time. Awesome Again quit procrastinating, quit
letting all the people holding betting slips for the No. 7 horse
wonder if he was going to ever get around to living up to his name.
</P>
<P>
   With only mild urging from jockey Pat Day, Awesome Again pulled
away from the competition, toward the finish line, at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone knew what was going to unfold as she watched the 1
1/8-mile replay of the race on a television screen underneath the
grandstand at Saratoga Race Course. Krone had a close-up view from
her seat aboard Tale of the Cat moments earlier, yet she couldn't
resist getting caught up in the moment again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noooooooo!'' Krone shrieked at the television screen in agony
and ecstasy, because there she was, right back in the middle of a
big race at her idea of the summer place to be. Just like the first
time, Tale of the Cat finished three lengths off the lead Saturday
afternoon in the $400,000 Whitney Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most fun I had being second,'' Krone said, ``in
my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is what happens while you're trying to ignore everybody
around you getting older. Julie Krone _ the 4-foot, 10-inch,
100-pound sweetheart of Saratoga _ is 35 now. Can you believe it?
She has been riding winners and losers for nearly half her life,
and she has the scars to show it.
</P>
<P>
   A decade has passed since Krone cracked the top five in the
national jockey standings for the first time. Six Saratoga seasons
have come and gone since Krone came within one victory of tying
Mike Smith for first in the Spa's jockey standings. Five years have
elapsed since Krone and Colonial Affair were a winning combination
at the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Once Krone passed that rite of passage into horse-racing
history, nothing seemed out of reach. She had barely turned 30 when
she won five races in one day at Saratoga. Angel Cordero had been
the first to do it. Ron Turcotte, the jockey of Secretariat, was
the second. Krone was the third.
</P>
<P>
   The fall happened 10 days later.
</P>
<P>
   Off a horse. From grace.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has been the same for Krone since Aug. 30, 1993. Krone
was second in the riding standings when she went down on the final
day of the season _ her right ankle going snap, crackle, pop. She
returned nearly nine months later with two plates and 14 screws
still in her rebuilt ankle. She stopped winning as often as the
owners and trainers demanded. She stopped getting the mounts that
would let her win the way she and her fans had come to expect. She
dropped to the B list, unable to make her mark at Saratoga or any
of the other hot spots anymore. Last year, Krone decided that the
best way to rebuild her career was to take a step down to the
Monmouth Park circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through so much,'' Krone said. She said it with a
smile, without a hint of self-pity. She was back at Saratoga, if
only for a brief interlude. Her mount had traded the lead with
Awesome Again for much of the race, and she had heard the screams
of 30,665 fans. As Krone wound her way back toward the finish line
after the race, fans gave her a winner's welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was for the horse,'' Krone said. ``These people know what
they're looking at. They can tell that he ran as hard as he
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, they could tell that he had run as hard as Julie Krone
could ride him. People forget a lot of things, but the years
haven't done a thing to dim the memories that the Saratoga crowd
has for Krone. They remember the rise, the fall. They remember how
she tried to pick herself back up, and they let her know how much
they appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very fortunate when people react,'' Krone said. ``Here
is special.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not every place where fan after fan will tell a jockey
``Great ride'' after a second-place finish. People want to see
Krone in Saratoga, and they want to see her do well. She's a part
of the place, part of the rich history, even if it embarrasses her
for anybody to suggest that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's because of the success and the adversity,'' Krone
said. ``This is the place where I got beat by one for leading rider
and was at the highest point of competitiveness in New York. I'm
riding every day with Angel (Cordero) and Mike (Smith). It was
proving something, doing something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they witnessed me almost getting killed. It's like
everybody gets to go through it with me. Maybe they feel like it
shows a good side of them also _ that people are capable of
overcoming a lot. They recognize what I've been through, and it
makes them connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the emotional connections can get a little
complicated. Saratoga is where a love connection resulted in a 1995
wedding. Saratoga is also where Krone rode so high and fell so far,
so suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good when people ask me for my autograph and
stuff,'' Krone said. ``Then somebody will go, `I saw you fall. I
was at the hospital. It was so gross. Your ankle was turned
backwards.' I have to deal with that all the time. It's all part of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting easier, though. I've become better at blocking it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is what happens to you when people get older, and they go
through changes. Things always change _ sometimes for the better,
sometimes for the worse, sometimes for better and worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm at Monmouth, I switch between races,'' Krone said.
``And every race I see, I yearn to be here. I miss it a lot. I feel
drawn. It makes me feel very sad. Part of me stays here.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone managed a smile. This was a day for Krone to be
happy, to enjoy where she is and what she's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as fun as it can be,'' she said, ``running second.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
