<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THE WORLD'S A JOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Another columnist at the Boston Globe is biting
the dust. Just two months after Patricia Smith was forced to resign
for inventing people and quotes in her columns, Mike Barnicle has
been asked to resign for stealing eight jokes from a book by George
Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of this case is that they were such lousy jokes.
</P>
<P>
   At least Smith invented interesting characters, who spoke in
lively fabricated quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle borrowed such Carlin jokes as ``Some day I wanna see
the pope come out on that balcony and give the football scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's version used ``I'd love to'' instead of ``I wanna''
and baseball scores instead of football, but it still wasn't funny.
Maybe it was funnier when spoken by Carlin in a stand-up routine.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's excuse was that he'd never read Carlin's book and
someone had sent him the lines. Then a TV station produced a tape
of him recommending the book. So Barnicle said he had recommended
it without reading it.
</P>
<P>
   How long does it take to read it? It's a book of jokes, not
``War And Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think it's pretty low-grade for a columnist to
steal eight lousy jokes from a lousy book.
</P>
<P>
   After a careful review of my last 10 columns, I've discovered
that 42 of the lousy jokes were my own, and five of the lousy jokes
were stolen from previous columns by me.
</P>
<P>
   I believe in recycling. The secret, like recycling plastic, is
to form the material into something slightly different, if just as
inferior.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 good jokes in my last 10 columns, eight were from my
wife, and four were from colleagues. Look, I have to come up with
five columns a week, so if I hear a decent line or printable joke,
I use it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm fabricating the above numbers, because I thought
all jokes I used were great, even my own. There also were dozens of
puns and plays on words that were strictly my own, and also great,
in my own estimation.
</P>
<P>
   You'll never catch me fabricating modesty for very long.
</P>
<P>
   This is all in the interest of a new policy called ``being
honest with the public.'' Or, let's be really honest and call it
``being dishonest in a lively way.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what America wants. Look at this Clinton-Lewinsky thing.
</P>
<P>
   Every news-talk show in America is all-Monica, all-the-time. Are
the commentators honest about this, saying they are doing this for
ratings and prurient interest in fabric stains?
</P>
<P>
   No way. According to them, it's a constitutional crisis and a
test of a presidency. Then they go on repeating the same
allegations we all heard months ago.
</P>
<P>
   George Carlin jokes start to look good after this, even recycled
ones. In fact, Jerry Seinfeld was funny about this on ``Letterman''
last week, wondering why the president was in trouble for lying
about sex, saying, ``Without lying, there would be no sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Seinfeld stole that line from his own Broadway show, but acted
like he spoke it spontaneously, which is his job. As I said before,
if a line is good, recycle it. Wear it out. (Or use it in your
column, and then note that Seinfeld previously stole it from
himself.)
</P>
<P>
   The line I made up two weeks ago was ``Aren't people supposed to
lie about sex?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I really overheard a version of it in a conversation. It
wasn't as funny as Seinfeld's line. It's just true, so I didn't
count it as a borrowed joke.
</P>
<P>
   If everybody were completely honest, and the world didn't look
like the same bad joke over and over again, life would be easier
but very boring.
</P>
<P>
   For example, what a terrible world it would be if the Dallas
Cowboys really were a squeaky-clean America's Team, instead of
America's Most Wanted Team (that name has entered the public domain
_ I don't know who made it up).
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys once again are facing allegations of disorganized
crime (a dumb play on words I take responsibility for). Michael
Irvin (whole Web sites are devoted to Irvin jokes) reportedly
slashed teammate Everett McIver with a pair of scissors in a
dispute over who was next in line for a haircut, but the Cowboys
are downplaying the incident as ``horseplay'' (no joke, but funny).
</P>
<P>
   Ah, we're glad to read that the NFL has a violent crime policy
(again, no joke). If a player uses a deadly weapon in the
commission of a crime, he must undergo mandatory clinical
evaluation and counseling.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't a joke either _ except as a punishment.
</P>
<P>
   If you or I slashed a co-worker with scissors while on the job,
we'd undergo mandatory clinical firing and prosecution. But these
are the jock gods of football, and even if they plagiarize the
actions of street thugs, they are still making millions instead of
license plates.
</P>
<P>
   The above, of course, is what all Americans think when they hear
about Dallas Cowboys getting off easy. In a column, it is just as
hard to come up with an original moral lesson as it is an original
joke.
</P>
<P>
   Some day I'd love to see the pope appear on his balcony and tell
Dallas Cowboys jokes. Does the pope do off-color material? Does he
steal lines? No, it's unoriginal sin.
</P>
<P>
   Or did Father Guido Sarducci already use that line?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1241EDT &QL; 
