<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 PUTTING AN UGLY STAMP ON THE '70s  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While some good things happened to me during the
1970s _ I got a college degree, saw both Richard Burton and Rex
Harrison on stage, moved to San Francisco, visited Paris in the
springtime and first tasted Dom Perignon _ I tend to think of the
decade as a whole as a tacky, unfocused wash-out.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Postal Service has reaffirmed my suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its continuing ``Celebrate the Century'' project, the
Citizens' Stamp Advisory Committee has released its 30 nominees for
stamps that will commemorate the 1970s. As with previous decades,
Mr. and Ms. America get to vote and pick the 15 subjects that will
become actual stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 choices for the '70s, I can find only eight I'd even
consider voting for. And three of those would make mighty ugly
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The other 22, well, they include the Smiley Face, the Pittsburgh
Steelers, Tennis and _ dare I say it? _ Disco.
</P>
<P>
   When I remember ``People and Events'' of the '70s, I don't
remember much. The stamp nominees in that category back me up.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Rights Movement, Watergate, Earth Day, the Oil
Shortage, the Opening of China and the Bicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   Earth Day deserves a stamp. The Opening of China, too. They were
big deals then, they're big deals today. Which is more than you can
say for the Oil Shortage or Bicentennial. (Would you pay 32 cents
for an oil shortage stamp?)
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Rights Movement is good, except it began in the
'60s. As for Watergate, the post office says it doesn't commemorate
disasters. Who but Bob Woodward wouldn't call Watergate a disaster?
</P>
<P>
   Other categories for '70s stamps are Arts and Entertainment,
Sports, Science and Technology, and Lifestyle. The pickings within
are slim.
</P>
<P>
   True, I'd vote for stamps for ``Sesame Street,'' the National
Public Radio-Public Broadcasting System and for ``Roots.'' And
ditto the magnificent Triple Crown winner Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I believe they have become the Diversions That Ate
America's Brain, ``Monday Night Football'' and VCRs probably
deserve stamps for making their mark on the collective culture.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the end of the stamp worthy for me. What remains:
</P>
<P>
   In Arts and Entertainment _ ``The Godfather,'' the Spiral Jetty,
``All in the Family,'' ``A Chorus Line'' and Photo Realism. (I love
``The Godfather,'' but as a stamp, it's an offer I can refuse. I
hadn't a clue what the Spiral Jetty was so I looked it up. It's an
example of ``land-and-earth art'' by Robert Smithson. OK. No
stamp.)
</P>
<P>
   In Sports _ The aforementioned Steelers, Soccer Leagues, Tennis
and the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   In Science and Technology _ Jumbo Jets, Pioneer 10 and Medical
Imaging. (Noble, but imagine the stamp.)
</P>
<P>
   In Lifestyle _ Smiley Face, Postmodern Architecture, Jogging,
1970s Fashion, Citzens Band Radio and Disco.
</P>
<P>
   How can you get postmodern architecture onto a postage stamp?
Why would you want to put a CB radio on? And 1970s Fashion? That
flared, platformed, polyester mutant should never have been born
yet is back again here at the end of the '90s. Give it a stamp?
</P>
<P>
   Once again, I remind the Postal Service of its no-disasters
rule.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
