<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-PARIS-HUMOR-     08-11 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-PARIS-HUMOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AH-SO SICK IN GAY PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By CAROLEE B. MORRISON  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The hotel chambermaid stood at my door, my size 10 black German
leather sandals in her dainty right hand. I'd left them in the
workout room under the Cybex leg-extension machine _ something I'd
never do in perfect health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you! Where would I be without my shoes?'' I gushed,
fishing five francs out of my coat pocket. Giggling, she took the
coin and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   That night it was out with friends to their favorite pretty
little bistro. Till the wee hours, we feasted on rillettes de
sardines, Coquille St-Jacques in garlic and scallion sauce,
peppered pear dessert, sparkling wine and espresso _ and oui! _
massive quantities of billowing cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, my raw throat felt like a tractor had rolled
through it on caterpillar treads. My vision was blurred; I was
alternately sweating and freezing. Was I really going to be sick
all day? I glanced out the window. There was a huge poster for a
French opera company showing a sylph whirling in a pink tutu, and
someone had defaced it by spray-painting the giant words coming out
of her mouth: ``Bill Clinton, I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, for energy, I devoured the contents of my minibar: nuts,
chips, Toblerone, salami, cheese, yogurt (for the live cultures), a
banana. Then I fetched my PruCarePlus HMO Out-of-Network Service
Card. ``... Designated user must call provider immediately in case
of emergency ... if hospitalization or surgery is recommended,
please call 1-800- ...'' Another wave of nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily my friends were home by the phone. They told me that in
France there is an ``S.O.S.-doctor'' program for emergencies, ``a
really nice service you can't have in America because the doctors
are too afraid of being sued for malpractice.'' The physicians make
old-fashioned house calls, even to your hotel room, they said.
''Just ask the reception desk. Tell them you need a doctor. They'll
call one for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Er, okay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonjour, Madame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you speak English?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oui!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick. I need a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooooo ...''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, more torture. I imagined my mother's voice, saw her
forefinger waggling in my face: A strange man coming to my hotel
room? Why, he might be anyone! Maybe he was going to do terrible
things to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Mom. Right, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later I heard a knock, unbolted the door and
there, undoubtedly sent from heaven or Central Casting, was Doctor
Emile Mallereau, Medecine Generale: about 6 foot 3, firm square
jaw, wide shoulders, blue-green eyes, high forehead, ruddy skin,
wavy hair _ and yes, even a small black bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you zee patient?'' _ he entered with a flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, yes ... yes!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold?'' he winced. (Indeed, I had dialed the thermostat up as
far as possible and heaped three extra plaid blankets on the bed.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Im afraid so,'' I said, tugging at my bathrobe. ``Is it
uncomfortable in here?'' _ trying to be the gracious hostess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what ez zee problem?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You speak English?'' I asked, amazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But of course.'' (Read: ``You dope, we all speak English; so
few of you speak French.'')
</P>
<P>
   I proceeded to tell him I was an American journalist on a
European tour interviewing world leaders about NATO expansion and
the EU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah! A journalieeeste!'' he arched his noble eyebrows. ``But
NATO ... zee European Union'' _ shaking his head, the brow
furrowing _ ``Vee will hate zees single currency, zees Euro. Zees
eez bad for France. And why did not your Congress accept the bid
from Romania to join NATO? You take Poland but not Romania! Ah, it
makes me ill!''
</P>
<P>
   We adjourned to the mattress near the bedstand, which was
cluttered with my bottles of vitamins, antacids, melatonin,
chromium piccolate, calcium-magnesium tablets, aspirin and
sugar-free mints.
</P>
<P>
   Now Docteur Mallereau pointed to my robe and grey Hanes
sweatshirt. I took the hint. Over my head went the duds and there I
sat. Unphased, he began to poke and pummel my neck and arms _ as I
breathed deeply, inhaling, exhaling, sticking out my tongue,
coughing, turning, flexing my elbow, dilating my eyeballs _ as
doctors make you do the world over. ``Yes, ahem, oh my ....'' he
mumbled, wielding the cold stethoscope.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to tell him about my asthma, my chemical sensitivities,
how when the office cleaning lady uses polishes and sprays, I'm
always sure she's testing chemical weapons for a Third World army.
I wanted to tell him that perfume makes my face swell like a plum
and my mother chain-smoked and my brothers and I now can smell a
lit cigarette a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't say any of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so, Madame Journaliste, what do you think of zees Monica
Lewinskee affair? You Americans are so ztrange, you want to
assassinate a good president. You do not want him to be human? Zees
ez very bad for the rest of zee world. Prime Minister Mitterrand
had a daughter and a wife and a mistress and we French were very
sophisticated about zat. But you are so funny about sex. I think we
French are with money as you are with sex!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, er ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus all zees noise about Saddam Hussein and zee weapons of
mass destruction. Zees winter Mees Madeleine Albright coming to
Paris for zee dialogue with Monsieur Vedrine _ no? Zey go to zee
Foreign Ministry with cupids on zee moldings and crystal
chandeliers and French flags. Very beautiful. But eet eez clear
this is but a distraction from zee president's problems!''
</P>
<P>
   I managed to splutter, ``We reelected him knowing he had, er,
fidelity issues. But he was supposed to BEHAVE. Not do it with an
INTERN, for Pete's sakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah ... I see. Well, in any case, you have a bad bronchitis and
an influenza and a fever. You must stay in zees bed and watch your
TV,'' he motioned to the screen. Sound mute, it was on CNN
International.
</P>
<P>
   His prescriptions were for two bottles of effervescent aspirin,
a throat spray with a huge nozzle on top, cough syrup (the kind
that's so thick it warms your whole body after one swig) _ and 10
days' worth of 1,000mg packets of a strange orange-granulated brand
of erythromycin that looks like Tang. (You're supposed to mix it
with water and drink the fizz, but I found it tastier to eat dry
with a teaspoon.)
</P>
<P>
   ``And so you live in Manhattan?'' he was asking, as I handed
back his emergency-call forms filled in with my vital data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oui!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps you would know of a cheap apartment available for a
month in zee summer with a view of Central Park?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheap? Across from Central Park?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here eez a business card'' _ he reached in his pocket. ``You
will call me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oui! Merci!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Carolee Morrison (morricb(AT)nytimes.com), a New York-based
journalist, is international editor at The New York Times
Syndicate. She recently traveled extensively in Europe researching
EU and NATO expansion.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------- &QC;
</P>
