<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-AFFAIRS-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following op-ed-length articles from the July/August '98
issue of FOREIGN AFFAIRS, described in more detail below, have
moved on the wire _ in the ``k'' and ``a'' category codes _ from
The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   _ They are also available in full-text versions, which range
from 2,500 to 6,000 words. _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARE U.S. TROOPS NEEDED IN JAPAN? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Morihiro Hosokawa &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,300 words) Many Americans see the presence of U.S. troops in
Japan as a gracious favor meant to underpin Japan's security. But
most Japanese, while fond of the alliance with the United States,
would like to see fewer U.S. troops on their soil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Morihiro Hosokawa was prime minister of Japan from 1992 to
1993. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-JAPAN-U.S.-TROOPS-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREVENTING WAR in the TAIWAN STRAIT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Chas. W. Freeman Jr. &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,400 words) Taiwan seems convinced it can campaign for
independence with the military backing of the United States. If war
is to be prevented, Washington must convince Taipei as well as
Beijing that it is time for them to work out a mutually acceptable
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chas. W. Freeman, Jr., is co-chair of the United States-China
Policy Foundation. A former diplomat, he served as deputy chief of
mission at Beijing from 1981 to 1984 and assistant secretary of
defense for international security affairs from 1993 to 1994. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-REUNITE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROTECTING THE WORLD'S REFUGEES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Roberta Cohen and Francis M. Deng &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,200 words) Today's crisis of internal displacement is no less
acute than the refugee crisis that confronted Europe after World
War II. Africa today counts about 10 million internally displaced
persons, Europe and Asia some 5 million each, and Latin America up
to 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roberta Cohen is a guest scholar at the Brookings Institution.
Francis M. Deng is a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution and
has served as representative of the U.N. secretary-general on
Internally Displaced Persons since 1992. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-REFUGEE-FLOW-GLOBAL-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO ARE NETANYAHU'S STAUNCH SUPPORTERS? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Ehud Sprinzak &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,500 words) Benjamin Netanyahu's continued appeal is the great
paradox of Israeli politics today. Despite diplomatic blunders and
derailment of a peace process that is overwhelmingly supported by
Israelis _ nearly 60 percent, according to recent polls _ he
remains popular. Among his strongest supporters are Jews who left
the former USSR, and have painful memories of intense
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ehud Sprinzak, a professor of political science at the Hebrew
University of Jerusalem, is the author of ``The Ascendance of
Israel's Radical Right.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-POPULAR-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PALESTINIANS HAVE REACHED THEIR LIMITS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Khalil Shikaki &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,450 words) As the grand old man of Palestinian nationalism,
Yasir Arafat's personal influence and political wiles have let him
dominate and change Palestinian politics in a way no other figure
could. But Arafat will not live forever, and Hamas, the radical
Islamist group, will not stay on the sidelines forever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Khalil Shikaki is a professor of political science at an-Najah
National University in Nablus and Director of the Center for
Palestine Research and Studies. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-ARAFAT-HAMAS-FREEDOM-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POWER IN A TERRORIZED LAND &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Lahouari Addi &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1500 words) Horrifying reports of violence in Algeria are
seldom fleshed out with any firm explanation of motives and
lawbreakers. Many say it is not Islamist rebels, but rather the
army that is the culprit. Of late, Algeria's generals have blocked
an international investigation to uncover the truth about the new
spree of village massacres.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lahouari Addi, a visiting professor of sociology at the
Institut d'Etudes Politiques de Lyon, is the author of ``L'Algerie
et la Democratie.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-ALGERIA-AGONY-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   ..................................
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (The following articles are available for review. To see the
full-length texts or for purchase information, please contact your
New York Times sales representative, listed below.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KYOTO'S UNFINISHED BUSINESS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Henry D. Jacoby, Ronald G. Prinn and Richard Schmalensee &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (5,000 words) The Kyoto pact on global warming is neither a
battle won nor a costly burden _ more like a quick political fix
for the vast problems of climate change. Reducing greenhouse-gas
emissions requires including the developing countries who sat out
Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SMASHING THE IRON RICE BOWL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Neil C. Hughes &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (5,000 words) The symbol of the Chinese Communist Party's
economic policies has been an unbreakable iron rice bowl, standing
for cradle-to-grave social security. But with Beijing unable to
keep its state enterprises _ behemoths that employ about 76 million
workers _ afloat, China is teetering between economic reform and
social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA and the ASIAN CONTAGION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Nicholas R. Lardy &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (6,000 words) So far China has avoided Southeast Asia's
financial crisis, but it shares many of the underlying weaknesses
that brought on the panic. Although it lacks capital convertibility
that imperiled other countries its weak banking system has issued a
mountain of bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA'S BERLIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Ernest R. May &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (6,000 words) Paraphrasing John F. Kennedy, ``We are all
Berliners.'' Through the decades of the Cold War, even during the
1962 Cuban missile crisis, why was Berlin so important to the West?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BERLIN, the HAUPTSTADT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Gordon A. Craig &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (5,000 words) A certain special character has made Berlin a
haven, from the rise of Prussia through the Weimar era. And the
Nazis were strangely contemptuous of Berlin, even during their
disastrous rule.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPIES in BERLIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By David E. Murphy &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (3,300 words) For those engaged in World War II-era
intelligence, one of the most sensitive matters on which unique
data was available in Berlin was Soviet progress toward an atomic
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOSS of OCCUPIED GERMANY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Peter Grose &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (3,000 words) The American military governor of occupied Germany
during the Berlin airlift, Gen. Lucius D. Clay, was a towering
figure at the time, and he cannot be fit comfortably into any of
the Cold War stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERMANY MOVES ON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Christoph Bertram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (3,500 words) Looking ahead, what is the possible new meaning of
Berlin as it once again becomes the capital of a united Germany, in
the next turn of the Berlin kaleidoscope?
</P>
<P>
   .......................................
</P>
