<HEADLINE>
TRAINER, 45, AND LONGTIME JOCKEY JOIN RACING HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT GRAVES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A trainer who was accepted earlier than
any other and a jockey who rode for parts of five decades have been
inducted into the Racing Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mott, the youngest trainer ever inducted, and jockey
Jacinto Vasquez were joined at the awards ceremony Monday by
pioneer trainer Ansel Williamson and horses Riva Ridge, Bayakoa and
Fort Marcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was never planned, of course never expected,'' said Mott,
who became a household name while guiding the great Cigar to 16
consecutive victories in 1995 and '96. ``I'm very honored and
humbled to be inducted into a club like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mott, who just turned 45, is three months younger than Allen
Jerkens was when he was inducted in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Born in South Dakota, Mott began training horses with other
family members as a teen-ager. (That's why he was eligible for
induction; a trainer must be licensed for at least 25 years to be
considered).
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, he went to work for fellow Hall of Famer
Jack Van Berg, who made the trip to Saratoga Springs to present
Mott with his plaque.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have missed it if I had to walk here from
California,'' Van Berg said. ``If you raised a child, you wanted
him to grow up to be like Bill Mott.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Mott's first year of eligibility, and his selection was
popular with the crowd gathered for the ceremony. With Cigar alone,
he won 15 stakes for owner Allen Paulson, including the Dubai World
Cup and the Breeders' Cup Classic. Cigar retired with nearly $10
million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Other Mott trainees: Theatrical, Paradise Creek, Fraise, Ajina,
Geri, Wekiva Springs, Gaily Gaily, Heatherten and Lassigny.
Entering this season, Mott had amassed 2,330 wins and more than $80
million in earnings. Cigar (twice), Ajina, Paradise Creek and
Theatrical all were Eclipse winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people that are responsible for me being
here,'' Mott said, ``and, of course, it would take a day and a half
to begin to name everybody that's been a part _ mainly Jack Van
Berg, he was a big part of it. He gave me an opportunity to train.
He put some horses in my name and I got some recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Mott has won several New York Racing Association meet titles and
was the leading trainer at Saratoga for the past four years,
including a tie in 1997. He also has done well in Kentucky, and
holds the Churchill Downs record for most winners in a meeting, 54
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, the leading apprentice in his native Panama, rode from
1959 to 1996 and won the Kentucky Derby aboard Foolish Pleasure and
the filly Genuine Risk. He also was the rider of the ill-fated
superstar Ruffian, and twice rode horses who defeated the great
Secretariat (Angle Light and Onion).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great honor,'' said Vasquez, whose career was stained
by his implication in a race-fixing controversy at Saratoga, an
issue that likely delayed his induction. ``It's the ultimate in
racing, but without all those great horses, you don't have an
opportunity to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez rode more than 5,000 winners, including 268 stakes
victories over the last 20 years of his career. Other well-known
horses ridden by Vasquez included Princess Rooney, Manila, Risen
Star, Forego and What A Summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ansel Williamson, born a slave but later freed, was a Civil
War-era trainer. He trained horses for such renowned stables as
Woodburn Stud.
</P>
<P>
   In 1875, six years before his death, Williamson trained
Aristides and won the first Kentucky Derby. National Museum of
Racing and Hall of Fame historian Tom Gilcoyne, who uncovered much
of Williamson's background, accepted the plaque for him.
</P>
<P>
   Riva Ridge was a champion at ages 2 and 4 for Meadow Stable,
which simultaneously had Secretariat in training. Riva Ridge
compiled a lifetime mark of 30-17-3-1 for earnings of $1.1 million
from 1971-73. He ran second to Secretariat in the first Marlboro
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Bayakoa came from South America and won the Eclipse for older
females two years in a row (1989-90). Her overall record showed 21
wins from 39 starts, but her record in the states was 18-for-31 for
trainer Ron McAnally.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Marcy was a three-time national grass champion for trainer
Elliott Burch and Paul Mellon's Rokeby Stable with 21 career wins
from 75 starts, 18 seconds and 14 thirds for earnings of $1.1
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
