<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR ON GRAFT PAYS, MEXICO CITY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Imagine a local government that increases revenues
in one year by 216 percent. Then try to imagine a place where a
once-stagnant bureaucracy suddenly begins firing crooked building
inspectors, providing curbside services to small businesses, and
opening licenses for public review.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City may not be the first place that comes to mind. But
in the heart of this sprawling metropolis, better known for its
rogue police officers and bribe-loving officials, the street-level
fight against corruption is producing a surprising budget windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an institutionalized corruption network that
extended into the government and it's our responsibility to clean
it out,'' said Jorge Legorreta, head of the Cuauhtemoc Delegation,
an area of about 600,000 residents and one of 16 Mexico City
boroughs. ``The result so far has been a more honest government and
more money for other services.''
</P>
<P>
   Money collected in the district for building permits and
licenses since January has increased to more than $700,000 versus
$326,000 for the same period last year. But perhaps more important
than the revenues is the perception among many constituents that
the old ways are changing.
</P>
<P>
   The district that Legorreta oversees is best known for the
historical treasures that it holds. The borough includes the city's
historic district, the colonial-era government square known as the
Zocalo, the fine arts palace, and scores of museums and businesses.
But like other areas of this city once under the control of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the district was also fertile
ground for government payoffs and kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year voters elected an opposition party mayor, Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, who then appointed a new cadre of borough chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Legorreta, 50, an architect and sociologist, was a college
professor who had never worked in government before this year. But
he and his deputies immediately began a campaign to clean up the
borough, mostly by tackling corruption for government licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Several building inspectors suspected of taking bribes or
failing to report fees to the government treasury were fired. Other
workers were sent to training programs for refresher courses on
government service.
</P>
<P>
   Legorreta also changed the rules to require builders to apply
directly at the borough office, implemented a new public review
process, and last month began a new mobile service for area
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Diaz Hernandez, president of a group of local bar and
nightclub owners, said in an interview this year with a Mexico City
newspaper that many of his members have used the money they've
saved from bribes to pay taxes and other old debts, and to remodel
their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Experts assert _ and Legorreta agrees _ that there is more
pressure today than before on Mexico City officials to show
progress in reforming government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have an elected mayor before so there wasn't much at
stake for bureaucrats or other officials,'' said Felix Velez, a
public policy professor at the Autonomous Technical Institute of
Mexico. ``But now there is more incentive to be honest and more
reason for an opposition party to capitalize on corruption left
over from another administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Legorreta said one remaining problem is that many city laws on
licensing and enforcement are outdated. For example, he said, there
are no laws that restrict adult entertainment to certain
neighborhoods, and there is little enforcement of regulations
against prostitution and littering.
</P>
<P>
   These laws would have to be amended either by the city's
legislature or by the federal congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an imbalance between the laws and the reality today,
and I believe that has contributed to much of the corruption that
we find today,'' Legorreta added in an interview last week in his
downtown office, which is dominated by three images _ a bust of the
Indian Cuauhtemoc, a photo of Mayor Cuauhtemoc, and a picture of
the Virgin of Guadalupe.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in corruption, he said, is the low pay of
government workers. A building inspector makes about $204 a month
and a borough lawyer makes $170.
</P>
<P>
   The city and boroughs still have their share of problems.
</P>
<P>
   None of the other districts has yet shown the kind of success
Legorreta has had in combating corruption. Legorreta's district
continues to have problems with unlicensed street vendors who clog
streets and sidewalks. And Cardenas, the mayor, has floundered
recently in local polls over his attempts to control crime and
improve city services.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to dealing with the borough government, some
in the Cuauhtemoc district sound a little more hopeful that things
are getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when paying the (government) officer was a regular
event. It was part of our business schedule,'' said Carlos Gurria
Mendez, a gift shop manager. ``Now, when we see somebody from the
borough stop by, it's to give us new information, not to take more
money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
