<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer pnans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, Aug. 12, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   KITTY-BAD (Richmond Beach, Wash.) A visit with Bad Kity, four
high school girls with talent and 'tude who travel around in a limo
and hope to rock 'n' roll their way to the top.
</P>
<P>
   By M.L. Lyke. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Ed note: The following stories are part of the P-I's special
coverage all week of the 80th PGA Championship, which is being
played at Sahalee Country Club in Redmond, Wash. Features and spot
stories will move throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-PGA-WOODS (Redmond, Wash.) Tiger Woods comes to Seattle
still looking for the success universally predicted for him when he
won the Masters two years ago as a rook.
</P>
<P>
   By Angelo Bruscas. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-PGA-APPLEBY (Redmond, Wash.) Stuart Appleby is at Sahalee
Country Club tuning up for the PGA Championship, his first
tournament since his the death of his wife, Renay.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Moore. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-PGA-MAJOR (Redmond, Wash.) _ With all of the bluster and
hype, you would think the PGA Championship is ``Armageddon II.'' As
if Bruce Willis is going to swoop down on Sahalee in a summertime
sequel from Seattle. For our area, this golf tournament packs
significance because we have not had a PGA stop since 1966, let
alone one regarded as a ``major.'' But in a broader perspective, it
is not that big. The Masters is Michael Jordan. The PGA
Championship is John Starks. It is not the Masters, U.S. Open or
British Open, of course, yet every year the PGA gets an invitation
to the party.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Moore. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
