<HEADER>
A8038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PEQUOT-INTERAC     08-11 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PEQUOT-INTERACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERACTIVE DISPLAYS INFORM, ENTERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.R. Montgomery.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ The video experience at the Pequot Museum
is the creation of Tom Nicholson New York, a Manhattan company that
usually specializes in hot Web pages for cool corporations. Unlike
most museum interactive videos, the product at the Pequot museum is
not the museum curator's ideas translated by cyber-nerds. Nicholson
came up with the concepts, did the ethno-graphic work, recorded and
taped interviews with Native Americans and anthropologists, and put
the package on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Van Tuyl, a California native and a UC-Berkeley graduate
with a degree in American history, was working on Web sites at
Nicholson when the Pequot project started. Along with as many as 30
associates working full-time for more than two years, Van Tuyl
created two classes of video experiences. The first kind is
basically a filling-out and filling-in of two dioramas, the forest
scene and the caribou hunt. By navigating on a touch screen,
visitors can do everything from get close-ups of objects in the
diorama to interviews with the archeologists who authenticated the
substance of the displays. It is a very unusual museum experience.
You can take the display for what it is and ask for more detail, or
you can question the authenticity of what you are looking at and
hear real archeologists talk about the art and science and
imagination that goes into re-creating an extinct culture.
</P>
<P>
   The film clips in the videos are unusually high-quality for an
educational program. The speed and definition is achieved by
hard-wiring each video station to its own central processing unit:
39 stations, 39 cpus. ``Actually,'' Van Tuyl remarked, ``we
developed it all on Macintoshes, but the Pequots use IBM for all
their computing, so we had to convert it. The most expensive thing
we had to buy weren't the processors, it was the video cards,
they're $5,000 a shot, to get the quality and speed we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most creative, and if it's the right word, some of
the sweetest, material is entirely created by Van Tuyl and the
Nicholson team. Off in one corner of a small side room, far from
the complex and enormous dioramas, two video stations concentrate
on Native American languages. Van Tuyl found five native speakers
of languages related to the Pequot tongue, and has them each tell a
story _ a legend _ in their language. The audio is accompanied by
written text in the native language and a translation to English.
The effect is mesmerising. The native languages are musical,
complex, and have sounds totally unfamiliar to the English-hearing
ear. But with the translation scrolling along, you get the illusion
of sitting at an elder's knee, hearing, for example, how the world
was created.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one of the storytellers,'' Van Tuyl recalled, ``who
was getting upset with me for making him cut his story down by a
few seconds, something like from two minutes, 40 seconds to a
minute, 20. So I said to him, ``Now, if you wanted to tell the
story the long way, how long would it take?' And he waited a while,
and then he said: `Two or three days.'''
</P>
<P>
   After the stories are told (each is accompanied by stylized
graphics that resemble, but do not try to copy, the primitivism of
Cheyenne Ledger Books or paintings on hide), the viewer gets a
screen that invites looking up words in the several languages used
by the storytellers. You can ask for animals, get a screen of
perhaps two dozen birds, fish and beasts, and then choose to hear
them in the various languages. It is amusing, it is charming, it is
poignant stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Van Tuyl's favorites are the onomatopoeic ones _ the Micmac word
for ``turkey'' is a short gobble, for ``owl,'' the first part of a
great horned owl's call. This is so familiar to the English ear
(after all, we call turkeys ``gobblers'' and have birds that say
their name, chickadee being the most common) that just for a
moment, viewers have some sense that they have crossed over the
barrier between their culture and the Native American society and
language represented in the program. After all, once you've heard a
Micmac say ``turkey,'' you will never be satisfied with an
unaccented, unrhythmical, boring English pronunciation of
``gobbler.'' Language can seem the most difficult aspect of a
foreign culture. Perhaps it is, but just to overcome that problem
for a moment gives a whole new sensation to a goal like ``getting
to know'' a Native American.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. If you were wondering how the creation story ends, Muskrat
makes the world. When he goes down to get the bit of mud at the
bottom of the sea of all creation and brings it up and makes it
grow so that everyone can have a dry place to live, and when he
does this after Loon and Beaver and Otter have failed, you almost
want to cheer for Muskrat, who made no boasts, gave no promises,
but just went down and got the beginning of the world.
</P>
<P>
   It's a different kind of educational television. It's
emotionally rich educational television, a rare commodity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
