<HEADER>
A8041 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     08-11 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULARITY CONTEST LOOMS FOR NEW ENGLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what's it going to be, sports fans? The Patriots open at
Denver on Monday night, Sept. 7, while the Red Sox will be in the
third inning against the Yankees at Fenway. Which game are you
going to watch on television?
</P>
<P>
   Pigskins or hardballs? Route 1 or Kenmore Square? Ubiquitous Bob
Kraft or invisible John Harrington? Gil Santos or Joe Castiglione?
Players who love the Foxy Lady or players who love the Foxy Lady?
</P>
<P>
   What are we? That is the question. Are we a traditional,
peanuts-and-crackerjack baseball town? Or are we a trendy, yahoo
football nation? Are we the direct descendants of Nuf Ced
McGreevey's Royal Rooters, forever devoted to the Red Sox? Or are
we latecomer disciples of Mel Kiper Jr., Jerry Glanville, and John
Madden?
</P>
<P>
   There was a preliminary test Sunday night and there'll be plenty
more in the exciting two months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   If we're going to use television ratings as a barometer of fan
interest, then football has taken over the New England region. The
Patriots drew a 12.3 rating for an exhibition game against the
Minnesota Vikings that started at 7:30 Sunday night. The Red Sox,
starting a half-hour later, drew a 7.7 for their final game of a
12-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   These comparisons are difficult and unfair. The Pats play only
one game per week, so they would be expected to attract more
viewers than the local baseball team. But it's hard to explain more
fans for exhibition football than for a red-hot baseball team,
bound for the playoffs. New Englanders actually chose to watch a
28-0 preseason blowout defeat instead of a two-Mo-homer Sox victory
over the Rangers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's scary stuff for those who hold baseball sacred.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have a bye week on Sunday, Sept. 27, so there will
be no choice when the Red Sox end their regular season against the
Baltimore Orioles _ a game that could determine a playoff spot if
the Sox lose their wild card lead between now and late September.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if the Sox go to the playoffs? Suppose Sunday,
Oct. 4, features the Sox and Cleveland Indians in a fifth and final
game to decide who'll play the Yankees in the ALCS? Put that game
up against the Patriots at New Orleans and what have you got?
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the Pats play at home against the Kansas City
Chiefs and it could fall in the middle of an Armageddon seven-game
series between the Red Sox and Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any other split-screen choices for New England
sports fans. If the Sox make it to the World Series, none of the
games would go head-to-head with the Patriots. New England's first
mega-game with the New York Jets comes on a Monday night, Oct. 19,
between Games 2 and 3 of the World Series. The seventh game of the
1998 World Series would be played Sunday night, Oct. 25, several
hours after the Patriots have jousted with the Dolphins in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare that we've had to debate this issue, because both
teams have not often been good at the same time. The Sox have been
to the playoffs only once since the recent Patriots resurrection
and that came in 1995 when the Patriots were staggering to a 6-10
finish.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Red Sox look to be playoff-bound and the Patriots
are supposed to have the best talent in the AFC East. The Pats have
owned the town for the last couple of autumns, but if the Red Sox
make a playoff push, which team interests more fans?
</P>
<P>
   I will go to the grave insisting that a Red Sox World Series win
would mean more to the region than a Patriot victory in the Super
Bowl. Of course, given the Sox' history, we'll never find out
whether this is true or not.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that while football fans are more loud and visible _
driving sports-talk radio with moronic mumbling _ baseball still
grips the region more tightly any time the Red Sox contend. This
may not show up in television ratings, but the hardball game simply
crosses more demographic barriers.
</P>
<P>
   It is my experience that more women, children, and old people
are devoted to the Red Sox. Patriot Nation is, for the most part,
populated by stout-hearted men between the ages of 15-55. These are
the guys who control the clicker, buy the beer, and bet on the
games. And, God love 'em, they are the ones who watched every
second of Sunday night's 28-0 exhibition loss to the Vikings while
the Red Sox were busy winning the West.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
