<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8044 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITTY-BAD-SPI &LR;      08-11 1791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITTY-BAD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XXX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dreams, big dreams, roll down the highway in a long
white limo.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the four suburban ``chick rockers'' from Bad Kitty all
talk at once. Their eyebrows are tweezed to whispers, their lips
outlined in mocha, their nails painted blue and their 16-year-old
bodies dabbed with Bijon perfume and packed into clingy little
strap tops and tight pants.
</P>
<P>
   As the limo rolls, their words tangle over the rumble of the
road, four voices locked in one yearning thought, interrupted only
by the snap of bubble gum:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're headed for the top . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the top . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the way . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, really want to make it . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, like, our dream . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's all we want in in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Matthew Lyons, sitting a mile away at the steering wheel
of the limo, smiles at his proteges in the rearview mirror. The
babble of these ``boy magnets'' is mana to his ears. These girls
believe, man.
</P>
<P>
   And they are, like, on the verge. Totally.
</P>
<P>
   Their eight-song CD, ``Scratch,'' recorded at the same Robert
Lang Studios in Richmond Beach, north of Seattle, where Nirvana cut
its last unreleased songs, is set for release next month. They've
done their slam-glam shtick on local TV, where ``Northwest
Afternoon'' host Kent Phillips hyped the underage, overamped
quartet as ``an all-girl band from Richmond Beach about to take
Seattle by storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, they've landed their first big-city, big-time
gig at Seattle Hempfest '98 later this month. Crowds could be major
_ like, 50,000 _ and the girls are wired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, Hempfest is huge for these girls. Huge!'' says Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   These little kitties have come a long way, baby.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half ago, Shana Weber (guitar), twin sister Sarina
(drums), Katherine Karlsen (bass) and Kellie Rinkler (lead singer)
were playing three-note songs in a Richmond Beach basement, with
visions of femme rockers L-7 and Seven Year Bitch dancing in their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   The girls went by the name Vertigo. As in dizzy. As in what
happens when you're standing atop 6-inch platform sandals, feet
bedecked in toe rings, midriffs bared, belting out angst-ridden
lyrics and driving hormonally imbalanced teenage boys temporarily
insane.
</P>
<P>
   Kellie, a feline bottle-blonde with a smokey grrrrll voice full
of electric juice, hit up concert promoter Lyons at an Applebee's
restaurant, asking him to come hear them play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she was kidding. I was like, yeah, yeah, yeah,''
says the thirtysomething manager, who looks like a misplaced
California surfer in faded jeans, tie-dyed T-shirts and long, limp,
blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he tripped down for a basement session. The room, he
says, ``smelled sweaty _ like a girl's locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Willowy, dark-haired Sarina was pounding away on a drum set held
together by a bobby pin and bubble gum. ``That bobby pin, it really
got to me,'' Lyons says.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' amps were no bigger than school lunch boxes. Chord
progressions were, like, majorly minimal. But the music was
original.
</P>
<P>
   And it was loud, really loud. The girls could rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard them play, it was, like, whoa,'' says
Lyons. ``I really, really dug these girls.''
</P>
<P>
   He signed on as manager in October, raising funds for new
equipment, pouring dough into studio time, and buying the Lincoln
Town Car to escort them from classes at Scriber Lake High School in
Lynnwood, north of Seattle, to practice and recording sessions.
</P>
<P>
   At Scriber Lake _ a non-traditional public ``school of choice''
_ reaction to the glam rockers in the long white limo was mixed.
``Some kids at school were like, `You think you're the sh--,'''
says Shana.
</P>
<P>
   Dating prospects, however, improved markedly. ``Some of the
guys, like, kinda tagged along and bugged us,'' says Katherine.
``We weren't really mean to them, you know. It's like, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball was rolling. All the girls needed were a few gigs, tons
of practice and a new name.
</P>
<P>
   The name _ and the provocative image created with high-style
makeup and low-riding hip-huggers _ evolved from a sidelong party
comment by one of Lyons' buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend took one look at the girls and said to me: `Them are
some baaaaad kittens.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Bad Kitties have a definite edge to them. ``A serious
handful,'' one mother says.
</P>
<P>
   In full war paint, wearing filmy see-through shirts that reveal
a tattoo here, a tender bit of cleavage there, the 16-year-old Bad
Kitties could be 20-year-old Bad Cats. They have the 'tude to match
the talent.
</P>
<P>
   When they played at the Apple Blossom Festival in Wenatchee
earlier this summer, someone shouted, ``Are you the Spice Girls?''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Expletive) no!'' one of the girls yelled back.
</P>
<P>
   They order clothes from Frederick's of Hollywood, and they brag
that when producers on ``Northwest Afternoon'' asked them to button
up their shirts, they ``only pretended'' to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But as determinedly uptown as the girls may be, their fangs,
claws and purring poses can dissolve in an instant. All it takes is
one giggle, one tickle, one goofy tease, and all four _ sugared up
from Cherry Cokes _ tumble into a heap of silly, playful kids
wrestling on the floor crying uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the girls _ Katherine and the fraternal twins _ have
been friends since junior high. Kellie joined later. The ties are
strong, as only 16-year-olds' ties can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not like just four people together jamming to make
songs. They're a unit with a bond and a vision,'' says Chip Butler,
the engineer at Robert Lang Studios who helped the girls master
their CD.
</P>
<P>
   The kitties have even taken blood vows, carving small crosses in
one another's backs to seal their friendship for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're, like, 24-7,'' says Katherine.
</P>
<P>
   That's 24 hours, seven days a week. The girls hit the beach
together, party together, talk on the phone together, go to school
together, where all are above-average students, according to
Scriber Lake principal Karol Gadwa.
</P>
<P>
   `The girls are very creative,'' she says. ``The school is pretty
excited to have this group here.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the kitties practice together. Hour after hour. Night
after night. They say they're so busy practicing or recording they
don't have time to get in trouble. Some studio sessions have kept
them going from noon till 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   They spend so much time together, they talk in one long
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we get in little cat fights . . .,'' begins one.
</P>
<P>
   The others pick up on the thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, like married couples . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all, like, married . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't stay mad for more than a day . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stupid stuff . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stupidest you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   All are self-taught on their instruments. Katherine had eight
years of piano before picking up a bass guitar. Shana, who writes
most of the lyrics, and Sarina, four minutes older than her sister,
studied violin for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Kellie _ called the ``loose cannon'' and the ``wild kitty'' for
such onstage antics as belly-baring and stage-diving _ got her
start in church choirs. ``I've, like, been singing all my life,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Their sound is raw, aggressive, built on minor chords that moan
like a cat in heat, all cranked to maximum volume. Intensity
strains their faces as they play, and the simple words bleed
adolescent love and longing:
</P>
<P>
   Everything we had
</P>
<P>
   I thought it would never go bad.
</P>
<P>
   Oh you make me think for a while.
</P>
<P>
   It . . . makes me think . . . for . . . for a while,
</P>
<P>
   And you know all those memories
</P>
<P>
   And it's you I never could please.
</P>
<P>
   They call their high-energy sound ``bubble-gum metal.' Or
``chick rock.'' Or ``whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   And whatever it is, it has transformed their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, life was boring, boring, boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we started the band, I was, like, `What am I going to
do with my life?''' says Katherine, who has a sweet little
heart-shaped mouth. ``But now my life is more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, like, everything's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock groups come and go. The dreams that inspire them remain the
same: bright lights, searing decibels, celebrity, glitz and
glamour.
</P>
<P>
   For the four hard-working rockettes in Bad Kitty, the dream is
still new, wrapped in shiny paper with all kinds of fabulous
goodies inside.
</P>
<P>
   They're intoxicated with the thrill of the stage, the buzz of
the crowd, the rush of adrenaline that comes from performing.
``It's like you're up there and all these people are cheering for
you and it's cool _ it's like really, really, cool,'' says
Katherine.
</P>
<P>
   And they're totally psyched about playing Hempfest, a political
festival promoting medical marijuana use, agricultural hemp
production and reform of drug laws. One of the tunes they'll play
is a Bad Kitty original, a jaw-dropper called ``Weed'':
</P>
<P>
   Green and sticky and covered in resin
</P>
<P>
   It's weed
</P>
<P>
   It's all we need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls know that song will get them noticed _ it's the
controversy thing,'' says Susan Karlsen, Katherine's mother.
``They're just trying to be bad kitties.''
</P>
<P>
   She describes Hempfest as both a good cause and good exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for girls on the verge, 50,000 people could be
make-it-or-break-it time. ``I'm really excited _ but I'm even more
nervous,'' says Kellie. ``It'll be my first time performing for
such a big crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Headliners for the festival are Northwest bands Floater, Second
Coming and Local 808. Sharing the stage with them is a major break
_ and festival organizer Vivian McTeak knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad Kitty's a good band, a great band, and I like their music.
They're young and offer a very fresh perspective,'' McTeak says.
``Also, I'd like to see these girls succeed. I knew this event
would be a really good catapult for them.''
</P>
<P>
   How high they'll fly, no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   But these four howlin' kitties in the long white limo are
prepared for the moon.
</P>
<P>
   They know what they want, and it doesn't include any more
``sucky'' after-school jobs at fast-food joints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want fame . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame and fortune . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame and fortune and fun . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we just wanna have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds a suddenly serious Sarina:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, like, people forget about how when you're young you know
how to have fun. But when you get older, you, like, forget about it
and you have to do something you don't want to do just to make
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls all nod their heads. That is sooo boring.
</P>
<P>
   They're never gonna let it happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   They're 16, and anything's possible.
</P>
<P>
   They're 16, and everything's possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
