<HEADLINE>
`CORONADO'S QUEST' GETS EDGE IN HASKELL INVITATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took time, and a great deal of trouble, but Coronado's Quest
has finally taken over the spot near the top of the 3-year-old
rankings that he long seemed destined to hold.
</P>
<P>
   The speedy son of Forty Niner, kept out of the Triple Crown by a
bad disposition and a bruised foot, ran away from Belmont Stakes
winner, and Kentucky Derby and Preakness runnerup, Victory Gallop
to win Sunday's $1 million Haskell Invitational. With Derby and
Preakness winner Real Quiet out for the year, Coronado's Quest has
as good a chance to be 3-year-old champioon as any other sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop, who fell a little over a
length short when second in the Haskell, are slated to meet again
in the $750,000 Travers Stakes at Saratoga. At the demanding
Travers distance of a mile and one-quarter, a closing Victory
Gallop may have an advantage over an on-the-pace Coronado's Quest,
who could not be caught over the mile and one-eighth of the
Haskell. We shall see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very proud of the horse and extremely happy for the
owners (Stuart Janney and the Stonerside Stable),'' said trainer
Shug McGaighey, who has done a top job getting Coronado's Quest to
clean up his act. ``We'll go to the Travers and then I'll have to
make up my mind. Maybe the Super Derby (at Louisiana Downs Sept.
27).''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that this was a two-race series, the
Haskell and the Travers,'' said Elliott Walden, who trains Victory
Gallop. ``That day will be to our advantage. Victory Gallop is
still in the running for championship honors. His record speaks for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Between Oct. 26 and Nov. 30 of last year, Coronado's Quest won
the Cowdin, Nashua and Remsen at Aqueduct with great ease. Those
efforts established him as a true Triple Crown contender. He was
shipped to Florida to begin his 3-year-old campaign, but, between
Jan. 31 and March 14, lost the Hutchinson, Fountain of Youth and
Florida Derby. He acted badly in the paddock and post parade prior
to all three races.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after finishing fifth in the Florida Derby, it was
discoverd that he had an entrapped eppiglottis. He was operated on
and has not lost since, winning the Wood Memorial, Riva Ridge and
Dwyer prior to his success in the Haskell. He has not been
uncontrollable since the operation and McGaughey now believes that
it may have been the breathing problem that was causing his poor
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Both Real Quiet and Victory Gallop are overachievers. Real Quiet
was 8-1 in the Kentucky Derby, while Victory Gallop was 14-1. They
put on a nice show throughout the Triple Crown, but their duel
hardly resembled that of Affirmed vs. Alydar or Sunday Silence vs.
Easy Goer. Both horses are devoid of early speed and don't like to
be rushed from midpack, either. They always seemed susceptible to a
quality speed horse and Coronado's Quest fills that bill.
</P>
<P>
   Both Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop are going to have to
continue to run well in order to win an Eclipse Award. Real Quiet
still has a chance, even though a stifle injury has put him on the
shelf. Last year, Silver Charm did not run between the Belmont
Stakes June 7, in which he lost his Triple Crown bid to Touch Gold,
and the Malibu Stakes Dec. 26, in which he also finished second,
but he still was named 3-year-old champion. Touch Gold won the
Haskell to briefly take over the 3-year-old lead, but when he lost
the Pegasus and the Breeders' Cup Classic, Silver Charm vaulted
right back to the head of the class.
</P>
<P>
   What Silver Charm and Real Quiet have in common is that they are
both trained by the popular Bob Baffet and both narrowly missed the
Triple Crown. If Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop flop late in
the season, as Touch Gold did, then Baffert will have successfully
played the waiting game again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick, the 1997 Horse of the Year, won the Jim Dandy by
a nose in a driving three-horse finish on Sunday. The Jim Dandy is
Saratoga's prep for the Travers, but don't look for Favorite Trick
to take on Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop. Instead, Favorite
Trick's trainer, Bill Mott, is dropping broad hints he's headed for
the grass.
</P>
<P>
   It was nice that Favorite Trick proved he could win at a mile
and one-eighth, even if it was against Grade II opposition. But
compete against Grade I foes going a mile and one-quarter? Forget
about it. ``It's (the Travers) probably something that we're not
planning to do right now,'' said Mott. ``I do think that we will
stay away from that race, but we'd like to discuss it for about a
week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``He proved that he was a champion last year and he was named
Horse of the Year, and rightfully so. Grass is an option with him.
And it's something we may look to do down the line because he's
worked over it and we know he handles it. A flat mile may suit him
because we know, if we're thinking about the Breeders' Cup, we're
obviously not going to run in the mile and one-quarter Classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Day, regular rider of Favorite Trick, agrees with Mott that
their charge would have a problem with 10 furlongs, something he
demonstrated when he ran eighth in the Kentucky Derby. ``A mile and
one-eighth is probably as far as he'll want to go,'' said Day. ``If
I call on him early, he may come up empty. Favorite Trick has had a
pretty good year, but, obviously, he's not handling the competition
with the authority he did last year. But, he's getting the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Favorite Trick appears headed for the $1 million Breders'
Cup Mile, which is raced over the turf. If he can't handle that,
there's always the $1 million Breeders' Cup Sprint, where Favorite
Trick, a son of noted sprinter Phone Trick, would surely feel at
home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and Mike Pegram, who owns Real Quiet, have come up with
a nice 2-year-old filly named Silverbulletday. The daughter of
Silver Deputy took the $100,000 Sorento Stakes at Del Mar on
Saturday, beating Excellent Meeting, who is also trained by
Baffert, by two lengths over six and one-half furlongs in the time
of 1:17 2/5. Silverbulletday, who is ridden by Gary Stvens, broke
her maiden by 11 lengths in her debut and then won the Debutant
Stakes at Churchill Downs. Now 3-for-3, she'll get her chance at
the big time in the Grade II Del Mar Debutante Aug. 29. Baffert
will also start Excellent Meeting, who runs for the Golden Eagle
Farm, in that event ... Silver Charm, most recently last in the San
Diego Handicap July 25, worked five furlongs in :59 1/5 over Del
Mar's main track on Saturday. His previous workout was held on the
turf. ``He went well and came back fine,'' said Baffert. ``I'm
slowly getting him cranked up again, with nothing in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from track publicity departments was used to prepare
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
