<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE ROSE ABOVE LEADERSHIP _ WILL THE SENATE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Politically, it's like you just finished scaling
Mt. McKinley, got a soft pat on the head, and were told that three
days later you start on Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, your guides and leaders are being switched.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who supports an end to money politics as we know it _
and that includes most of the country, President Clinton, the House
of Representatives, and a recorded majority of the Senate _ the
near impossible, along with extreme frustration and the determined
delaying tactics of a desperate opposition, are the routine.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, though, that the stunning leadership and guts shown
in the House by Republican Chris Shays of Connecticut and Democrat
Marty Meehan of Massachusetts now return to the sidelines. Back
onto the stage will come the Senate's bipartisan reform duo _
Democrat Russ Feingold of Wisconsin and GOP maverick John McCain
(the real key because all Democrats are already aboard, but reeling
under heavy pressure from angered fellow conservatives).
</P>
<P>
   The easy way out, especially for possible presidential candidate
McCain, is to observe that last week's passage of real campaign
finance reform in the House is about to be followed by a collision
with an impervious stone wall in the form of a probably unbreakable
Senate filibuster. But the problem with the easy way out is recent
history, which contains a message of hope for the determinedly
quixotic.
</P>
<P>
   One element of it is the simple power of the core proposal,
which is based on the sound proposition that while the record of
government in any kind of regulation is spotty, there's no question
the government can ban things successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Getting rid of ``soft money'' literally gets rid of unlimited
donations from special interests and the wealthy, the main fuel
that has driven the stratospheric increases in partisan spending on
television propaganda this decade. And getting rid of outside
invasions by special interest propaganda in the closing weeks of
primary and general election campaigns does restrict these
laughably labeled ``issue ads'' to a period considerably removed
from election days.
</P>
<P>
   It is a truism that the American legislative process is designed
to make major change difficult and to empower minorities beyond
their numbers, as it probably should be. However, it is also true
that the system eventually bows to reform movements that attain
critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   With only a little time left to this Congress, the telltale clue
inside the Senate is the fact that several senators, primarily
Republicans up for reelection, do not want to vote on this issue
anymore. Several of them gave votes to Majority Leader Trent Lott
earlier this year to maintain the filibuster with eight votes to
spare beyond the 40 needed to gridlock the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is a fact that the critical votes came with the
expectation that blocking action would bury the issue for the rest
of the year because there was no way reform could succeed in the
House over the opposition of Speaker Newt Gingrich. That
expectation was dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, underdogs beat the leadership by different means in
the House and Senate. In the House, leadership wields much of its
power by playing traffic cop for legislation on its way to the
floor; with the filibuster and other rules, the Senate is less
dictatorial, but the power to schedule bills for debate is
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, organization can sometimes force a
leadership-opposed measure to the floor and keep it alive against a
variety of tricks. That is precisely how Shays and Meehan won,
attracting 61 Republican votes, roughly one in four, to their side.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, what is required is In-Your-Face-ism _ a
willingness to keep offering a blocked proposal as an amendment to
anything on the floor. With discipline, it can break down
commitments to a filibuster or tie the Senate in different knots or
both, as Senator Edward Kennedy showed two years ago in pushing an
increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   For this to happen on campaign finance reform, there has to be a
leader, which requires John McCain to take a deep breath and take
his colleagues on all over again. There also needs to be an early
convert, and the initial target of the advocates is New York's Al
D'Amato, whose ravenous hunger for cash is exceeded only by his
desire to be reelected. There are others. Some enjoy a reputation
for other than reflexive partisanship (in other words, they know
better): Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, Bill Roth of Delaware, John
Warner of Virginia, Slade Gorton of Washington. Others have a
history of interest in serious reform and opposition to
filibusters: former Democrat Ben ``Nighthorse'' Campbell of
Colorado, Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas, and Sam Brownback of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The history of uphill struggles in Congress by majorities
against leadership-led minorities shows that the real struggle is
against manufactured senses of futility. The truth is there is
almost always a way. The outcome is usually determined by will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
