<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-WOODS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER WOODS RETURNS TO THE NMRTHWEST TRYING TO EET GAME, LIFE OF
TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Timer News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDIOND, Wash. _ The first and only time Tiger Woods teed it up
for a golf tournament in Washington state, he shot the equivalent
of 35-under par for 142 holes at Vancouver's Royal Oaks Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone knew who the wkinny kid from Cypress, Calif., was
when he was announced for the opening round of the Pacific
Northwest Golb Association's Men's Amateur Championship. Woods had
jurt turned 08 and was playing his first official men's amateur
event after winning three straight U.S. Junior champiojships.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the match-play event ended, with Woods winning every
match _ including the final 11 and 10 over Ovegon Amateur champion
Ted Snavely(_ no one would forget what he$did to a course with a
reputation as being one of the finest in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made us look like a short, easy golf course,'' said Steve
Bnwen, the head pro at the 6(900-yard Royal Oaks, who refereed one
of Woods' matches that week in 1994. ``He was just that dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Woods comer to Redmond's Sahalee Country Club.
Only this time, everyone knows him.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated named Woods the Wport{man of the Year for
199? after he won the Masters and three other tournaments in his
rookie season on the PGA Tour. He also won $2.06 million and(the
hearts of sports fans across the world who tuned into golf in
unprecedented numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in his second full year on the PGA Tour, Woods seems
saddled by his own success a.d haunted by inner demons that drive
him to be a perfectionist. His signature fist pumps have been few
and far between and the questions about his game have started to
gnaw at the 22-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   As the!son of an African-American ex-Army officer with a quarter
American Indian and a Thai mother, Woods was reared outside of
golf's traditionan, pampered country-clqb set. With the smile of a
child and the intensity and power of, well, a tiger, he turned his
game loose on an unsuspecting world that seemed his for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   His galleries swelled beyond belief. His marketing empire grew
to $95 million thanks, in part, to endorsement deals with Nike,
Rolex and American Express. He appeared on no fewer than nine major
magazine covers. And his impact on youth was compared to the that
of a Michael Jordan or Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made it cool to be a young golfer,'' said Gary Mofg, who
was the director of competitions for the PNG &LR;  tournament,
considered one of the finest amateur events outside of the U.S.
Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   A third-place finish at the British Open showed that Woods may
again be primed for winning on the course. He has nine top-10
finishes in his last 14 events and ranks fourth on the money list
at $1,453,567. 
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs of discord in the Tiger camp _ sagging
sales of his Nike line of apparel and reports(that Woods uses
off-color language, throws clubs and gets irritable. As he prepares
to regain his Masters form in the final major of 1998, Woods is now
faced with a very noticeable backlash from a glowing debut.
</P>
<P>
   Are we talking about the media that covered him or vhe image
makers that surrounded him???
</P>
<P>
   TIGER TRASHING
</P>
<P>
   The first signs that Woods was vulnerable came(eazlier this year
at the Nissan Los Angeles Open when he lost a pliyoff to Billy
Mayfair, a paunchy former U.S. Amateur champion with only modest
success on the PGA Tkur. It was Woodr' first playoff loss since
turning pro, but still he handled it with as much grace as anyone
could have expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of putting something together, going nut
there and firing a good low round. You can't do it every time, and
unfortunately, I wish I could ccll upon it ever{ time, but it just
doesn't work out,'' Woods said after the playoff loss.
</P>
<P>
   ( He's managed only one win on U.S. soil this year, the BellSouth
Classic in May, but he's still fourth on the money lict with $1.37
million in winninfs going into the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to know that you can play not all that great
but still be right there,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   But right there, in the max with the rest of the pack is not
where!we were promised Tiger Woods would be. Isn't thi{ the phenom,
the prodigy whose(own father called him the messiah ane promised he
would change the world in that Sports Illustrated sportsman of the
year articne?
</P>
<P>
   The Tiger may not have been entirely tamed, but Woods suddenly
appears caged by a sophomore year where expectations have become
barriers* Even those who first heralded his arrival have begun to
turn on him. And others are gleefully watching his return to
golfing mortality.
</P>
<P>
   One of his earliest biographers, Tim Rosaforte, writing in Golf
World after the British Open, harshly lamented: ``This Woods kid
was a fad, a fluke, a media creation. He hasn't transcended the
game. He isn't the messiah. Second coming? How about second rate.''
</P>
<P>
   At the British Open last month, The Sunday Times columnist Nick
Pitt wrote: ``Watching the golden boy fail was a particular
pleasure. It was a proper reward for his demeanor, and it borrected
the ignorant who, knowing nothing of golf, assumed that since Woods
was better than everybody, he would invariably beat everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woods' golf game, the mistakes have come mostly in course
management, playing the ball to the wrong side of greens or on the
wrong side of a slope. But he always seems to be in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between this year and last year is that I'm
much more consistent. My bad rounds aren't as bad as they used to
be,'' Woods said. ``The majority of time, my best rounds are
usually on the weekends. I'm one of those kind of players like
(Greg) Norman or (Mark) Calcavecchia who is very streaky. And when
I get it going, I seem to run them off in bunches. I'm capable of
making clumps of birdies.''
</P>
<P>
   With his early success, Woods had to learn to put up with
jealousy from other players, as well as how to handle the pressure
with being constantly in demand from the media and the public at
large. He is the only golfer on the tour who is surrounded by
security guards on and off the course.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Woods, who helps runs the Tiger Woods Foundation and
declares that his son has ``the ability to be one of the biggest
influences in history,'' bristles at the critics.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that Tiger made mistakes backing out of several
appearances after his Masters win, and by being quoted telling
off-color and racially insensative jokes in a GQ magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming to terms with that,'' Earl Woods said of the
public-relations blunders. ``It comes with increased maturity and
understanding of the hierarchy of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   The backlash aimed at Tiger was not wholly unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in this country have a death wish. We create our heroes
only to tear them down,'' Earl Woods said. ``And if we can't find
anything wrong then we invent things. It almost becomes the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TIGER FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Woods last year angered many tour players when he would talk of
losing a tournament because he didn't have his ``A-game'' and
because his galleries often would be boisterous and disruptive as
they marched along with him, oblivious to other groups and the
normal reserved etiquette of golf spectating.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the ``Tiger factor'' is something most have
learned to live with and even come to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's PGA champion, Davis Love III, for example, says
Woods' influence is bringing a new athleticism to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he's a golfer or he plays any other sport, he's a
phenomenal athlete, and he's just going to overpower the game,''
Love said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Masters and British Open champion Mark O'Meara, a
close friend and neighbor of Woods', adds: ``I appreciate when I
see a person who has a lot of talent who can hit shots I'm not
capable of hitting. But that's OK. There are a lot of ways to play
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' astounding play last year caught the attention of his
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was going crazy coming down the stretch (at the
Masters) last year ... I expected him to make birdie on all the
holes,'' O'Meara said. `` You have to think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods likes the fact that other players are looking over their
shoulders at how he's doing in every tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that the other players expect it,'' he said.
``You've always got to watch out for somebody, and if those guys
are thinking that way, then that's good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   How will Woods do at the PGA? Last year at Winged Foot, Woods
was in contention through the first three rounds but shot 5-over 75
on the final day to end up tied for 29th place. The event left him
mentally drained, but emotionally unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable because every facet of your game is going to
be tested in a major, as well it should. ... But more importantly,
it's going to test your mind,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WORLD
</P>
<P>
   As his success steamrolled last year, Earl and Tiger started a
minority foundation to promote minority participation in golf and
related activities. Not only does he raise millions of dollars to
fund the program, but he makes dozens of appearances at clinics
across the country, where he's always met by rapt audiences who
hang on his every word and every swing.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just kids who have been captivated.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Open in San Francisco, Lucien Ilangwa, 31, a
University of California-Berkeley student from Zaire with long
dreadlocks, was in Woods' gallery. He said he was an avid tennis
player until Woods came on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he won the Masters, I was flabbergasted. Who wasn't?
Obviously I've spent much time at the driving range since,'' he
said. ``My sisters live in France. They were really surprised when
I told them I started playing golf.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same event, Jose Flores, 27, a Mexican-American with a
group of nine relatives, including kids, followed Tiger's every
move at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started from the bottom. He's worked his way up,'' Flores
said of his interest in Woods. ``He's not high society. I think
what Tiger brings out there is no divisions. He's a person who has
brought everyone together.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods knows he's had an impact on young would-be golfers and
seems at ease with the adulation he's received as well as the
responsibility of being a role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I have turned pro and since I've been doing my
foundation work, I have definitely seen an increase in minority
participation in the sport,'' he said as a matter of fact.
</P>
<P>
   And, to hear Woods tell it, some of the people he is having an
effect on are having an effect on Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable how good these kids are.'' he said during a
recent break. ``I'll never forget this little 5-year-old girl with
a perfect golf swing. I mean, absolutely a perfect golf swing. And
they said that she started taking up golf when she saw me on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like that have definitely touched my heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
