<SLUG> BC-VT-TUTTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT FILM ICON MILKS THE SPOTLIGHT IN BID FOR SENATE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUNBRIDGE, Vt. _ Fred Tuttle is a 79-year-old man who milked
cows all his life and paid for it with his knees. He quit school in
the 10th grade to work on the farm, and those bib overalls are no
prop. When he gets pensive, he lifts his hat and scratches the top
of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Think ``Being There'' in a feed cap.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Tuttle starred as himself in the 1996 arthouse flick ``Man
With A Plan,'' in which a retired dairy farmer gets himself elected
to Congress so he can pay his taxes and buy his father a hip
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fred Tuttle is running for the Republican nomination for
the US Senate. For real.
</P>
<P>
   And the truly wild thing? He might win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the strangest, most bizarre campaign I've seen in
covering Vermont politics for 18 years,'' said Peter Freyne, a
columnist for Seven Days, an alternative weekly newspaper in
Burlington. ``Fred has a great shot in the primary, definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   The quirky little movie made Tuttle a Vermont icon whose
beguiling mug is one of the most recognizable in the Green Mountain
state. His face is on milk-mustache posters in convenience stores.
``Spread Fred'' bumper stickers are must-have Vermont kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go anywheres,'' said Dottie Tuttle, Fred's wife of 37
years. ``We have no privacy. Everywhere we go, they want to take
pictures with him, they want his autograph.'' At last year's
Tunbridge World's Fair, Fred never did have time to eat a hot dog.
He was shaking hands double-fisted.
</P>
<P>
   And while his entry into the race has been acknowledged by both
Tuttle and his campaign manager (and movie producer) John O'Brien
as a gag and a way to publicize this fall's airing of ``Man With A
Plan'' on PBS, it has set Vermont politics on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle is running against Jack McMullen, a Massachusetts
millionaire who owns a ski house in Vermont but established
residency here last year.
</P>
<P>
   In McMullen, Tuttle may have found his perfect foil.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy from Massachusetts coming up here _ whoever he is _
will not get voted in just because he's from Massachusetts,'' said
Michelle Barnaby, who runs the till at The Village Store in
Tunbridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Fred wins just out of principle,'' said Barnaby. ``To
say maybe the average person does stand a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Fred Tuttle want to be a United States senator?
</P>
<P>
   ``Too old now,'' he said, in thick Yankee twang. ``If I was
younger I would like to go. I think most everybody in Vermont would
like to go and try to get things better. What's that Lewinsky thing
down in Washington? ... Costs what, $15 million of taxpayers'
money? I would stop all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle has pledged to spend $16 on the race. He spent the first
week of his candidacy recovering from knee surgery in the Veterans
Administration hospital in White River Junction, Vt. His doctor has
ordered him to stay home for a month. No matter.
</P>
<P>
   When he held forth from his front porch last week, the pack of
reporters was thick. He was on the radio three mornings this week.
He's already made The New York Times, The New Yorker, and the
British press. ABC called this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got used to it,'' said Tuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting here on the porch, as a brook of no particular name
flows through the valley, Fred Tuttle seems uncomfortable talking
about his opponent, or the primary.
</P>
<P>
   He will say this much:
</P>
<P>
   On Hollywood: ``Now, it's quite hard for the wife and I to find
a good movie on television. ... John's came out good. No actors in
it, no nothin'.''
</P>
<P>
   On crime: ``How we gonna stop crime? Educate your children.''
</P>
<P>
   On the death penalty: ``Like that boy out West that blew up that
thing out there,'' referring to Timothy McVeigh and the Oklahoma
City bombing. ``Why don't they execute 'im 'stead of lettin' 'im
live so long? Why feed 'im?''
</P>
<P>
   On Vermont: ``Orange County, Windsor County, a few counties
around here, and the Northeast Kingdom looks good to me. But around
Burlington, it's all gone to ski tows.''
</P>
<P>
   On class: ``The rich are ruling the poor. Am I right on that?''
</P>
<P>
   On his fame (lifting his cap, scratching his head): ``What have
I done to be the great person they think I am in Vermont? I'm just
an ordinary person.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever accused Fred Tuttle of being qualified for the
Senate. But that doesn't mean they won't vote for him anyway _
perhaps out of a certain comic cantankerousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him for 30 or 40 years,'' said Frank Boles the
other day, as he took a break from herding cattle in Royalton. ``He
had some good Jerseys when he was farming. ... I think he's going
to take the primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont has an open primary, which means people can pick which
primary to vote in. With a lack of exciting races on the Democratic
side, many Democrats are expected to cross over on Sept. 8 and vote
Republican, for Tuttle. The Republican nominee will face incumbent
Senator Patrick J. Leahy in November.
</P>
<P>
   When Tuttle entered the race, the Republican establishment in
Vermont could have laughed it off.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they had a bilious fit.
</P>
<P>
   The state party chairman derided the gag, then challenged some
of Tuttle's signatures as bogus. When the secretary of state
ordered Tuttle to come up with 23 more signatures to make the
requisite 500, Tuttle came back with 2,300. McMullen even called
upon Leahy to get Tuttle to quit. Leahy refused.
</P>
<P>
   At every turn, it was front-page news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not genius on our part,'' said the 35-year-old O'Brien, a
Harvard man who is masterminding the campaign and serves as a
justice of the peace in Tunbridge. ``Every comedian needs a
straight man. Jack McMullen and the GOP have played the straight
man to perfection. We're in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Stokes, the executive director of Vermont's Republican
Party, said the party's original reaction was not to Tuttle's entry
into the race, but to O'Brien's publicity stunt, and to the
assertion that Tuttle would endorse Leahy if he won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Tuttle is out of the hospital and able to speak for
himself, Stokes said, ``Mr. Tuttle is being treated as a serious
Republican nominee. ... He's a legitimate Republican candidate. I
hope the entry of Mr. Tuttle engenders good, constructive debate.''
</P>
<P>
   To some Vermonters, McMullen's recent challenge to Leahy to cap
spending at $1 million threw kerosene on the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we spending a million dollars on campaigns?'' the
67-year-old Boles asked, sneering. ``Fred's spending $16!''
</P>
<P>
   Despite numerous calls to his campaign headquarters, McMullen
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody in Vermont loves Fred Tuttle. Not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Many Vermonters are angry, saying that he and O'Brien are
mocking the political process. The two have been thoroughly
chastised in letters to the editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is received very well by upscale people,'' said
Frank Bryan, a University of Vermont political scientist. ``They
think he's cute. ... Vermont is becoming just kind of a theme park
of the past, and Fred is becoming a symbol of that and he's being
used to promote that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really very depressed that John O'Brien would use Fred
Tuttle like this,'' added Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   At this suggestion, the grizzly old dairy farmer bristles.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no, no,'' he said, and the italics are his. ``I don't
b'lieve that; do you, Dottie?'' Dottie does not. ``John and I are
great friends. No, suh! Not for one second.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tuttle said now that he will not endorse Leahy if he wins
the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said Leahy, who clearly is qualified to be a United States
senator, will beat either Republican handily. So Leahy can afford
to have some fun now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose about the one thing I'll have to do,'' if Tuttle
wins the primary, said Leahy, deadpanning. ``You know that cap he
wears that has `Fred' on it? If he wins, I'll have to go out and
spend some money and buy a cap that said `Pat' on it _ so people
know which one is which.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
