<HEADLINE>
STUART APPLEBY PLAYING DESPITE TRAGEDY OF WIFE'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Renay Appleby would have told her husband, in
spite of his grief and emptiness, to keep playing golf. It actually
would have been more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renay would say: `Get off your (butt), get back on the horse
and go,''' said Robert Allenby, Stuart Appleby's best friend now
that Appleby's wife is gone.
</P>
<P>
   At 25, Renay Appleby died in an illogical accident outside a
train station in London on July 23. Unloading a bag from her car,
Appleby was crushed between her car and a cab. The cab driver
thought he was in reverse instead of drive and hit the gas pedal
instead of the brake.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Stuart Appleby was at Sahalee tuning up for the PGA
Championship, his first tournament since his wife's death. He
declined interview requests but plans to talk to reporters at a
news conference today.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby looked like all of the other pros, striding down
Sahalee's cathedral fairways, checking out breaks on the greens.
Normally focused, his mind must have been elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some tough times, quiet times,'' Allenby said.
``He has been home with Renay's family and his family. This will be
the first week he has been on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Allenby flew from Greece to London to be with Appleby after the
incident. Other players have responded with their support. Nick
Price said a few nice words during his victory speech in Memphis
two weeks ago. Billy Mayfair dedicated Sunday's Buick Open victory
in Detroit to Renay Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby, 27, is known as the Australian with potential for
prominence, winner of two PGA titles with earnings of nearly $2
million in three years on Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Renay Appleby did not even want to play golf with
Stuart Appleby, much less marry him. She disliked the man who would
become her husband. An accomplished golfer herself, Appleby met
Stuart on a trip to the United States for a series of matches
against college teams.
</P>
<P>
   She was supposed to play with Appleby against Texas Tech but
balked because of her misperception about the boy who grew up on a
dairy farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought he was a stuck-up pig,'' Allenby said.
</P>
<P>
   Renay Appleby was funny, apt to crack a joke about anything.
Together, they were an inseparable tandem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would refer to them as the dynamic duo,'' said Carolyn
White, Renay's mother. ``Each one's weaknesses were the other's
strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Renay caddied for her husband for three months in 1996 and was
at most of his tournaments after that.
</P>
<P>
   Allenby figures that ``Stuey,'' as he calls his friend, will be
looking for her outside the gallery ropes this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be really tough for him,'' Allenby said.
</P>
<P>
   Known to playfully call his friend a country bumpkin from the
bush, Allenby used a different description Monday, referring to
Appleby as ``a tough bugger.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Appleby will make club selections and worry about life
choices later, grieving and grinding in the meantime at Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would rather be busy than thinking about it at home,''
Allenby said. ``This will keep his mind occupied.''
</P>
<P>
   It is tough for the reserved Appleby to open up in the best of
circumstances. He will admit that he can be a loner but
acknowledged that his marriage was highly influential, helping him
discover his bearings and goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was my own man for a number of years until I met Renay,'' he
told one publication. ``You need a degree of single-minded
direction of where you want to go. Sometimes you need to bump into
people to keep a clear track of where you're trying to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart and Renay Appleby were on their way to Paris for a second
honeymoon. Where is the destination now? And what about Appleby's
perspective? Without any of the answers, Appleby will respond to
those questions this morning, attempting to piece it together like
others have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my mom and dad,'' Fred Couples said. ``If I could have
them around 10 more years, I'd quit the game. Golf is very
unimportant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has a positive outlook on life,'' said Jesper
Parnevik, one of Appleby's friends. ``It's not like it's over. He
just has to live it differently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
