u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-BOS &LR;      08-11 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GRILL AND DRILL' SUMMER SCHOOL PROGRAM WORKS FOR CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It's not the sweltering classroom on the North Side
that is making 13-year-old Cherish Phillips sweat this summer. It's
the threat that she will be plunged into the student hell of having
to repeat a grade if she doesn't pass mandatory summer school.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite the lack of air conditioning in classrooms and the
strict ``grill and drill'' teaching method, Phillips says she is
working harder than at any time in the regular school year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Chicago's new system serves as a useful blueprint &UR;  &LR; for other
cities. While controversial, it is producing improved test scores
and being embraced by parents, teachers, and even students.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first my daughter was upset she had to go, but now, she
likes it. I was surprised,'' said Shirley Alejos, parent of
sixth-grader Linda Maldonado, one of about 40,000 Chicago public
school students in summer school.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, students from third, sixth, eighth,
and ninth grade have been required to attend summer school in
reading and math if they either fail those courses during the year,
or fail the Iowa Tests of Basic Skills.
</P>
<P>
   The teaching method is six or seven weeks of intensive drilling,
and there is no time for socializing. But school officials say it
works: About 54 percent of summer school students last year passed
the Iowa test when it was re-administered in August. Some students
jumped three grade levels in test scores after a single summer of
school, according to school statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, students say the summer program's intensity and
the concrete repercussions they face of having to repeat a grade if
they do not learn the material keep them focused in a way they are
not during the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids play around during the year _ I did. And now they know
they have to study, or be held back. That would be so
embarrassing,'' said Phillips, who failed the Iowa sixth-grade test
in May. As her classmates from the Bateman School took turns
reading aloud in a classroom so hot the lights were turned off to
make it cooler, she declared, ``It's not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door, sixth-grader Madiha Khan said, ``I'd rather be coming
here than sitting at home doing nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the intensely focused classes seem to motivate
students, critics charge they are not truly educating them.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of summer school, Khan's teacher, Carol
Schmitz, took the sixth-grade students' workbooks and wrote their
test scores on them in areas like comprehension and vocabulary, to
show exactly where they would have to improve to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what they are going to ask you on the test, in this
way,'' Schmitz told students recently, as she quizzed 16
sixth-graders on the metric system. Juice boxes were stacked nearby
_ school officials' incentive to children to make it through hot,
humid days with no air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Showing students a map of geographical regions of the United
States, she said, ``There are lots of things on the test about
maps. You need to know &UR;  &LR; this.''
</P>
<P>
   Such direct ``teaching to the test'' fuels some of the loudest
protests against the mandatory summer school program. Other critics
of required summer school have said it penalizes thousands of
students who try hard in school and must attend in the summer only
because their teachers did not teach them well enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are supposed to serve the students and be accountable to
them, and (Chicago) is putting children first in line to be
accountable,'' said Julie Woestehoff, executive director of Parents
United for Responsible Education in Chicago, a school reform group
dedicated to getting parents more involved in the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are only doing this to raise students' test scores. ...
I'd rather &UR;  &LR; summer school be fun, more captivating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the $52 million summer school budget here should be
used to better train teachers and improve the school day during the
school year.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, similar arguments helped delay a plan to begin
mandatory summer school next year for Grades 3, 5, and 8. As many
as 50 percent, or approximately 7,600, of students in those grades
could be required to attend summer school in 2000 if they fail
strict promotion standards approved by the School Committee in June
that include passing coursework, a standardized test, and
attendance requirements.
</P>
<P>
   While school Superintendent Thomas Payzant wanted to start
required summer school next year, a divided School Committee balked
at that proposal and decided only to recommend it next summer and
require it in two years. Boston school officials have no specific
plan as to how students will be taught, but say they want to design
a program that will feature one-on-one tutoring and enrichment
programs as well as teach test-taking skills.
</P>
<P>
   Although there had been a promotion policy for more than a
decade before the new policy was passed this spring, in practice,
Boston students have rarely been held back if they did not meet the
requirements. The result has been thousands of students being
``socially promoted,'' or moving on to higher grades without
knowing grade-level work.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, school officials say their students' poor academic
achievement makes moot any arguments about who should be
accountable for what children learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still learning math,'' said Bateman teacher Schmitz.
``They are &UR;  &LR; not learning anything that is not going to help them
for the rest of their &UR;  &LR; life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear that Chicago, where Mayor Richard Daley has
largely &UR;  &LR; controlled the schools since 1995, is a summer school
success &UR;  &LR; story. School officials' goal is to have half of the
system's children &UR;  &LR; reading at grade level by 2003. Currently, only
about 35 percent do. &UR;  &LR; And while student standardized test scores
inch &UR;  &LR; up each year, it is usually only by two to four percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Still, parents remain hopeful, largely because they say any
reform is &UR;  &LR; better than the dismal state of the schools five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not the best thing, but it's something,'' said
Sandras &UR;  &LR; Hurley, picking up her ninth-grade son from summer school
recently in front &UR;  &LR; of Bogan High School on Chicago's Southwest
Side. ``I'm hopeful. &UR;  &LR; But I won't know if it works until my
son &UR;  &LR; graduates and gets a good job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
