r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-PGA-MAJOR-SPI &LR;      08-11 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-MAJOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA TOURNEY TECHNICALLY A MAJOR, BUT DOESN'T CARRY THE SAME
PRESTIGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ With all of the bluster and hype, you would
think the PGA Championship is ``Armageddon II.'' As if Bruce Willis
is going to swoop down on Sahalee in a summertime sequel from
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   For our area, this golf tournament packs significance because we
have not had a PGA stop since 1966, let alone one regarded as a
``major.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a broader perspective, it is not that big. The Masters is
Michael Jordan. The PGA Championship is John Starks. It is not the
Masters, U.S. Open or British Open, of course, yet every year the
PGA gets an invitation to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Every golf professional grew up with goals of winning a major
tournament. It validates their careers more than, say, becoming
champion of the Quad City Classic.
</P>
<P>
   They revere Augusta. They persevere in the U.S. Open, hoping to
be the last survivor. They are blown around in the British Open,
coveting golf's oldest prize in the game's birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA? It is normally played in an oven. You will never hear
anyone _ with the exception of last year's champion, Davis Love III
_ say, ``I have always dreamed of winning the PGA Championship.''
It is always one of the other three.
</P>
<P>
   This ``major'' tournament business is overdone, particularly
when it pertains to the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The word itself makes these tournaments sound so important,
rendering the rest unworthy. Just keep in mind how wrong we are.
Bobby Ayala is technically a ``major'' leaguer. ``G.I. Jane'' was
considered a ``major'' motion picture.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA does little to distinguish itself, even though it is the
fourth and final major of the year. This clean-up hitter draws
walks and runs the bases but supplies insufficient power to the
gaps. Again, that's all right. But it is Tony Gwynn in a society
that wants Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest feat in golf is winning the Grand Slam, collecting
all four major championships in the same year. No one has ever done
it, but one player (Ben Hogan) was close and another (Mark O'Meara)
is threatening to win three this year.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how much the PGA and Grand Slam meant to Hogan. After
winning the Masters, U.S. Open and British Open in 1953, Hogan
declined to play in the PGA. In those days, the PGA was played one
week after the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, who had been in a serious car wreck in 1949, thought the
physical strain and travel demands of playing in two straight
majors was too overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Walter Hagen? He won four straight PGA
Championships in the 1920s and apparently forgot he was supposed to
be in Baltimore to try for his fifth in 1928. Tournament officials
scrambled and found him on an exhibition tour. Hagen ended up
playing in the '28 PGA but lost in the semifinals to eventual
champion Leo Diegel (the PGA was a match-play tournament then).
</P>
<P>
   The intent is not to diminish the PGA. It has a stronger field
than The Masters, which allows golfing geezers, as long as they are
past champions, in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA furnishes occasional drama _ in 1991, the big blond
bomber from Arkansas won his first tournament, cutting doglegs with
rocketing drives, creating the John Daly legacy. The tournament has
added intrigue at Sahalee with O'Meara looking to place the
Wanamaker Trophy alongside those he won at The Masters and British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   But basically, the PGA is Sandra Bullock acceptable, just not
Pamela Anderson provocative. PGA really stands for Pretty Good
Action.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins at Sahalee this year could be a journeyman, a
grinder, a nondescript lifer whose otherwise inglorious record will
be highlighted by a victory in a housing development on the
Sammamish Plateau where there are more speed bumps than residents.
</P>
<P>
   He will clutch the big silver cup known as the Rodman Wanamaker
Trophy, which is the size of a pony keg with handles. He will look
to the sky and rub rain from his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He will be heralded as one of the young guns who finally busted
through or a veteran who endured.
</P>
<P>
   It will in fact be a ``major'' accomplishment. But keep this in
mind: the PGA Championship is the picture-in-a-picture on your wide
screen, still visible, just not very prominent, much like Corvallis
in the Pac-10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
