<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-STITH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW MISSION FOR A `MAN OF HOPE' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (Attn.: Mo.; l and i coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Rev. Charles Stith, longtime activist and recently
named ambassador to Tanzania, is sitting in his Back Bay office,
his trademark bow tie around his neck, his cuff links securely
fastened, his checked sports jacket hanging squarely on the wooden
valet beside his desk. The oversize briefcase he uses as an
overnight bag, toothbrush and dirty clothes inside, rests at his
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Stith is just back from Washington, from a hurried trip to the
State Department crisis center monitoring the aftermath of the
bombings of US embassies in Dar es Salaam and Nairobi. Suddenly his
agenda the Monday morning after a three-week Caribbean vacation is
no longer winding up his tenure as head of the civil and economic
rights group he founded.
</P>
<P>
   Did that fax from the State Department arrive? What is the
telephone number of the Tanzanian ambassador in Washington?
</P>
<P>
   He may not roll up his sleeves or loosen his tie, but Stith the
ambassador is at work even though he doesn't move to Africa for
another month. He was on a plane to Washington early Sunday, 12
hours after he got home from St. Maarten. He is calling the
Tanzanian ambassador to the United States, thanking him for the aid
of the Tanzanian people after the bomb that killed 10 people in Dar
es Salaam. He is writing to Americans in various agencies in
Tanzania, thanking them for their efforts. He is considering how he
wants to start his tenure at a time when the embassy staff may need
as much pastoral care as diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A traumatic event like this, people are working 18 hours a
day. The adrenaline is pumping. It won't be until after this is
behind us in terms of the crisis mode that this is going to hit
home to folks,'' says the 48-year-old Stith. ``The other piece is
when you look at the plant, the physical plant itself, it is
nothing short of a miracle that more people were not killed. To
look at that physical evidence causes you to focus on your own
mortality. The need to really sort through some of that, to vent
and to heal, has got to be part of the agenda when I get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith is the preacher who led the historic Union United
Methodist Church in Boston's South End for 15 years, stylish and
savvy, outspoken and personable and ambitious (he prefers
``driven''), who became one of the most prominent voices in the
city's black community, involved in everything from registering
voters to protesting racial violence and apartheid to pressing for
affirmative action and equal credit opportunities for Boston's
minority residents. He made news _ and controversy _ last spring
when he led the protest that greeted Boston magazine's headline
``Head Negro in Charge'' over a story about Harvard's Henry Louis
Gates Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is what I am,'' Stith said in one of several
interviews before the bombings. ``And what I am is what I will be
because of the time in which I was born and the time I came of
age.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a St. Louis native who had no significant contact with
whites until he enrolled in Baker University in Kansas in 1971,
where, rumor had it, white fraternity brothers threw darts at a
photo of him. He had no white friends until he entered Harvard
Divinity School in 1975. Now he counts a president of the United
States, a white Arkansan named Bill Clinton, as a longtime friend.
Check a list of people who've slept in the Lincoln bedroom at the
White House and Stith's name is there. ``Hell,'' he says, ``it's a
hoot to have a friend who you refer to as `Mr. President.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's the civic missionary calling for banks in the inner city
and black faces in corporate offices who left his pulpit in 1994 to
work full time runing the Organization for a New Equality, which he
founded in 1985 after turning down an offer to succeed The Rev.
Jesse Jackson as head of the Chicago-based PUSH. Former Comptroller
of the Currency Eugene Ludwig, under whose tenure banks committed
$360 billion to poorer communities, calls Stith ``one of the
leaders in this country of the movement to economically empower
low- and moderate-income people.'' ONE's mission appealed to a
president who seeks to transform America's relationship with Africa
from one based on aid to one based on trade.
</P>
<P>
   Stith is as much part of Boston's social fabric as its political
fiber. He's half of one of Boston's more visible power couples. His
wife, Dr. Deborah Prothrow-Stith, associate dean at the Harvard
School of Public Health and former state health commissioner, is a
nationally known specialist on youth violence. They have two
teenaged children and also raised their nephew after the death of
Prothrow-Stith's sister in 1982. Prothrow-Stith's mother has lived
with them _ and has run their household _ since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Stith is classy enough to have a favorite corner table at the
Bristol Lounge of the Four Seasons Hotel and corny enough to
commemorate good times by leading his family in three rounds of
``hip hip hooray.'' When ONE honored Ludwig this spring, Stith paid
tribute by commandeering a roomful of bankers through the Stith
family cheer. When Stith's family and friends dined at Mr. K's
Chinese restaurant in Washington following his nomination hearing
in June, Stith's 19-year-old son, Percy, led the cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles is an original,'' says his longtime friend Ira
Jackson, executive vice president of BankBoston. ``He's flashy and
he's quotable and he certainly is notable. He ain't perfect, but he
sure is effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him operate in a number of venues and it's not obvious
unless you reach across the totality of those venues to understand
the magic he works. Some in Boston say where is his congregation?
Where are his disciples? But you go to that dinner for Gene Ludwig
and you see an extraordinary cross section _ people who were
previously adversaries and even enemies brought together by this
guy's savvy and charisma and interpersonal skills. He weaves a very
interesting mosaic.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been weaving that mosaic most of his life. In second grade,
his mother, Dorothy McLean, recalls, Stith was elected king of his
grammar school. In middle school, he was president of the student
body. In high school, he ran a social club called the Egotists _
the name, he insists, was the idea of a boy named Squeaky _ and in
college he headed the black student union. He and his wife have fed
everyone from former Massachusetts governor Bill Weld to
psychiatrist Alvin Pouissant at dinners known for spirited repartee
and post-supper songfests around the piano or heated games of
Scrabble.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gazing at Kilimanjaro
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The irony of his posting in Tanzania is that Stith decided to
enter the ministry _ and abandon any idea he had of becoming a
laywer _ when he was a college student building churches in Kenya.
``We were starting with boulders as big as these chairs,'' he says,
sitting in one chair in his office, with his arm resting on a
second chair and his feet stretched in a third, ``and with sledge
hammers beating them into gravel so we could lay the foundation.''
Evenings, his day's work done, Stith would lie on the African
earth, watch the sunset, and gaze at Mt. Kilimanjaro in neighboring
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was while I was looking at Kilimanjaro,'' he says, ``and
thinking about what life had been like for me and what life ought
to be like that I got the calling to the ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Stith brings to Africa a politics that is more
pragmatic than ideological. ``I'm much more interested in getting
something done than in making a point,'' he says. ``but sometimes
you have to make a point to create a context to get something done.
At the end of the day I want the stuff to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   On various issues that have divided Boston's black community,
Stith stood on the side of caution. He opposed as economically
unfeasible a referendum calling for minority neighborhoods to
secede from Boston. He supported an appointed school board.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Stith, the elder of two sons, rarely saw his father
after his parents divorced when he was very young, but he spent
summers with his paternal grandmother, trading the relative reserve
of the Methodist or Presbyterian churches his mother favored for
the ``knockdown, drag-out, shout, fall out, revival'' exuberance of
his grandmother's Baptist church. When Stith dressed in his Sunday
best to help integrate the Fox moviehouse, his mother admonished
him not to embarrass the race.
</P>
<P>
   Stith's mother still lives in St. Louis, and his brother, James,
died a few years ago of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Stith is in the pulpit _ he still offers guest
sermons _ the preacher in him remains. It's there in the cadence of
his speech, in the way he repeats phrases for emphasis, raising or
lowering his voice or elongating his words the second time around
for even more punch. It's there in the way he leans forward and
punctuates his points with his fingers. It's there in the way he
opens a meeting about economic literacy by saying, ``There's a lot
of stuff in the Bible on eternity, but there's only one reference
about what you need to do to get there. It's what have you done for
the least among you?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
