<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8064 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-STITH-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-11 1705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-STITH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (Attn.: Mo.; l and i coding)  
 BOSTON: ... among you.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The preacher in him is also there in the way Stith thinks of
providence, most dramatically in the way he talks _ and preaches _
about the lingering impact of his brush with death when he was shot
in the chest at age 13. A friend had beckoned him to an alley near
his home where another boy had a gun. It's unloaded, the boy
assured as he pulled the trigger. The bullet just missed Stith's
heart. That night in the hospital, Stith heard a doctor tell his
mother he would probably be dead by morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear I could have been killed,'' he says. ``That I
wasn't really speaks to this kind of sense of responsibility and
destiny to do the stuff I'm trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A subdued spender
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as Stith considers it his calling to better the economic
conditions of the inner city _ and now of Tanzania _ he also savors
the fruits of his own success. ``I've never tried to pass myself
off as a holy man committed to a monastic style of living,'' he
says, leaning back in his favorite chair at the Four Seasons, cigar
in hand, ``but I am a man of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Stith sips vermouth over lunch at the Four Seasons, where
the doormen and waiters know him by name and where the chef
prepares dishes he requests whether or not they're on the menu. He
smokes two cigars a day. His mother taught him a boy needs his gray
trousers and blue blazer and now he is so meticulously groomed that
he dons black eyeglasses when he's wearing black or gray and
tortoise shell when he wears gold. He drives a Cadillac
convertible, top down from March until December unless it rains. He
gave up basketball for golf. When his family travels each July to
their time share condo in St. Maarten they fly first class.
</P>
<P>
   Stith's spending, however, is less grand than his taste. The
Cadillac is nine years and 104,000 miles old. His favorite store is
Filene's Basement, and he used to make the sign of an ``x'' over
clothes he liked in hopes that he could buy them later at a lower
price. The courses where he regularly golfs, Franklin Park and
Newton Commonwealth, are public. Those first-class seats are
courtesy of the frequent flyer miles he and his wife accumulate
when they travel for work. The neatly trimmed hair is courtesy of
himself and $29 barber's clippers he bought (he's self-taught
because the instructional video featured only straight-haired
blonds).
</P>
<P>
   This style, combined with his ambition and an ego that his
longtime friend Rev. Joseph Washington, now a pastor in New
Rochelle, N.Y., laughs ``doesn't suffer from any malignancy or
disease,'' earns Stith his critics. He's been faulted for being out
of touch with urban youth, too connected to downtown and too
interested in his own stature. Stith shrugs at the criticism.
``Look,'' he laughs, ``if they crucified Jesus and assassinated
Martin, who's going to escape? Who's going to escape?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a fence-mending Rev. Eugene Rivers (``Is it legal for
me to say something nice about Charles or is it illegal?''), a
staunch critic who's been known to mimic Stith smoking a cigar,
says, ``Charles Stith is one of the most brilliant and accomplished
brokers on behalf of the black community that we have had over the
last 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith's day begins at 4:30 or 5 a.m. when he rises with the sun,
and a few mornings a week he and his son, Percy, are on the golf
course at 6 a.m. ``Golf,'' Stith says, ``is the closest thing to a
zen-like experience in sports. You're ultimately playing against
yourself and the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Every morning Stith reads several newspapers _ Boston Globe,
Boston Herald, New York Times, USA Today, Wall Street Journal,
Financial Times and International Herald Tribune _ and then he
reads from the Bible, a habit learned at the Interdenominational
Theological Center in Atlanta. ``A good Christian,'' he says,
``ought to read the newspaper and the Bible every day because you
get to juxtapose the temporal with the eternal.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's not traveling _ he averages 15 days a month on the
road for business _ Stith spends days in his office at the back of
ONE's six-room suite, and then ``at day's end, whenever that is,
I'll make my rounds through the house, kisses all around, then
shwoosh to the third floor'' and his cigar room.
</P>
<P>
   These rooms, office and cigar room, are comfortable, lived in,
not unkempt, but certainly not as impeccable as the clothes Stith
wears. There's a stack of papers on the table in his office, and
half-hidden by them, a Bible. Stith never found a place for the
Louisville Slugger bat he got when he gave a speech in Kentucky, so
it rests against a cabinet. A hanging papier mache parrot has a
cracked head and wears the floppy bowtie a banker gave him because
Stith prefers smaller ones. In Stith's cigar room at home, a pile
of papers on Tanzania occupy the chair beside the one where he
smokes his cigar. The books lining the closet and one wall are
sometimes stacked askew.
</P>
<P>
   If any city shaped Stith intellectually and politically and
personally, then it is Atlanta, where he came in 1973 to study at
the historically black seminary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A level playing field
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You know everybody, whether he admitted it or not, who was in
seminary when I was in seminary wanted to be the next Martin Luther
King Jr. Everybody did,'' Stith says. ``Obviously it means
something in terms of ego, but in the most positive sense it was
that everybody wanted to play that kind of role in shaping history.
I reached a point that to ultimately be acquitted before the bar of
eternal justice I don't have to carry the burden of starting a new
movement. All I have to do is be faithful in the moment. That means
simply to do what I can how I can where I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is where Stith found an intellectual freedom that eluded
him at mostly white Baker. ``When I went to seminary I needed it,
and it was a great experience. Oh, it was a great experience,'' he
says. ``It was great to get to seminary because I could say stuff
and ... it wasn't a commentary about my humanity. It wasn't a
commentary about my race.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is the city where Stith encountered a black community,
with its large middle class, that ``almost, but not quite,''
mirrored the white community. ``It really is an affirmation of
something that all black people believe and that, quite frankly,
which most white people find unbelievable, which is if you level
the playing field black people will be all right,'' he says. ``That
really is what I've been about.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is also where, after working on Maynard Jackson's first
campaign for mayor and meeting people such as Andrew Young, Stith
first sensed that some day in the future ``I could keep counsel
with a president.'' After Jimmy Carter was elected president in
1976, ``I got to the outer edge'' because so many Georgians were
part of Carter's circle. ``By '76,'' Stith says, ``I figured
there'd get to be a point when I'd be really close.'' That point
came a decade later when he met the governor of Arkansas at a Cape
Cod weekend getaway with mutual friends.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Atlanta is where Stith met a young Spelman College
senior named Deborah Prothrow in February 1975. Their courtship was
brief and intense, propelled in part by what Stith calls the
``providential'' fact that both had been admitted to Harvard, she
to the medical school and he to the divinity school. They wed in
August 1975. Asked to describe her husband, Prothrow-Stithuses
words like ``bright'' and ``humorous'' and ``hardworking,'' then
calls later to leave a message adding ``he's sexy'' to the list.
</P>
<P>
   He's the one, not she, to enjoy the thrill of jet skis. He's the
one who left his first ski lesson midstream with the words ``I get
this,'' she recalls, and bypassed the bunny hill to try a bigger
slope. The first time he ice skated he headed mid-rink to teach
himself figure eights. ``It's an intensity and drive to meet the
challenge,'' his wife says.
</P>
<P>
   Stith is also a man rooted in routine. In courtship,
Prothrow-Stith recalls, they took a bus almost daily to a
Baskin-Robbins he liked for pralines and cream ice cream. As
newlyweds they tasted Baby Watson's cheesecake in Harvard Square,
then had some every day. Now the Four Seasons is Stith's venue of
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles likes very nice things and very nice places,'' says
Prothrow-Stith. ``For a black man in America, being in a nice place
that is known for its service and knows you because you have it as
a routine lessens the chances you'll be mistreated.''
</P>
<P>
   When the White House approached Stith in 1997 about the
ambassadorship, he hesitated to upset his life and his wife
immediately looked for ways to make it happen. Now the family is
getting ready for two years in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Prothrow-Stith, for the first year at least, will travel between
Boston and Tanzania. Percy will take a leave of absence from Bates
College to serve as his father's aide-de-camp, 16-year-old Mimi
will finish high school at the international school in Dar es
Salaam, and Prothrow-Stith's mother, Mildred Prothrow, will live
with them in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the agenda for these last weeks before moving includes
a new urgency to previously scheduled security training, as well as
the job of packing his golf clubs for Tanzania, along with his
replica baseball caps from the old Negro League and a framed copy
of a South African ballot from his tenure observing elections there
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Stith has noted the irony of returning to the place where he
decided to enter the ministry, of going to the home of Mt.
Kilimanjaro. ``It's the opportunity to go to the other side of the
mountain,'' he says. ``At the least there's got to be a sermon in
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he knows what he could not foresee when he uttered those
words, that any sermon he culls from his experiences in Tanzania
will come in a city devastated by the terrorist attack. ``It really
does punctuate for me something that has been at the core of how
I've tried to live my life,'' he says. ``You have to have a sense
of urgency about the stuff you feel called to do and have an
opportunity to do because life and time are tenuous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
