<HEADER>
A8068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-11 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PAPARAZZI'S DOLCE CURRICULUM VITA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first of the paparazzi died last month, less than a year
after the crash that killed Princess Diana and set off a worldwide
debate on the hit-and-run photographers' ethics _ and the origins
of their name.
</P>
<P>
   Tazio Secchiaroli, a Roman ``street photographer,'' had been
Fellini's model for the celebrity-chasing character in 1960's ``La
Dolce Vita,'' everyone agreed. But why had Fellini named his
character Paparazzo? Was it related to razzolare, to scratch around
in trash? Influenced by pappataci, an annoying sand-fly? Was it, as
one reader of this column suggested, a Riminese dialect word for
the part of the chicken sometimes known as the pope's nose?
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of us were scratching our heads, some amazingly
well-read source tipped off The Economist that the true Paparazzo
could be found in a 1902 travel book; thus, the London weekly's
post-crash coverage included a footnote informing us that Fellini's
scriptwriter ``took the name from `By the Ionian Sea,' a book by
George Gissing. Coriolano Paparazzo was the proprietor of the hotel
in Catanzaro where the British poet had stayed.'' Gissing was in
fact a novelist, and the magazine gave the wrong date for his trip,
but the squib was still a coup _ especially the smug last line,
which noted that ``Gissing's book is still on sale in Calabria, in
an excellent Italian translation.''
</P>
<P>
   To mark Secchiaroli's departure for the great darkroom in the
sky, Michael Quinion, proprietor of the World Wide Words Web site,
revisits the history of paparazzo in his most recent newsletter.
His account differs from The Economist's in one detail _ he has
Fellini rather than the scriptwriter reading Gissing's book _ but
otherwise it looks like the last word on the word, if not on the
subject. Concludes Quinion: ``I can only wonder at what the late
Signore Paparazzo, keeper of that unnamed hotel in Catanzaro, would
make of the coincidences that led through an English writer's
recording of a brief stay, and an Italian film producer's
accidental encounter with it, to the borrowing of his name as one
of the more pejorative in the English language.'' The World Wide
Words site, including this essay as well as searchable archives, is
at www.clever.net/quinion/words.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics who'd like to meet this Signore Paparazzo can find him
via the Internet, too. Among the surprisingly numerous
Gissing-related Web sites _ even discounting those that use him
only as a limerick rhyme _ there's one with the full text of ``By
the Ionian Sea.'' In the original English, of course, not the
excellent Italian translation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Witter watch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of our British cousins, they've been wittering on for
years _ the verb, which means chattering idly, and often
annoyingly, goes back to the 1500s. But witter seems to be enjoying
a new vogue, and may at last be ready for a trans-Atlantic leap. If
anything can loft a word across the great divide, after all, it's
``Bridget Jones's Diary,'' the best-selling account of a
thirtysomething's life of comic desperation. And Bridget not only
knows wittering, she's even got a cutting-edge compound form of the
verb: She observes that her supervisor, Perpetua, ``spends the
entire time in full telephonic auto-witter to Arabella or Piggy,
discussing the half-million-pound Fulham flat she's about to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Witter's origins are somewhat obscure _ it could be related to
Scandinavian words for ``warning'' or ``sign,'' says the OED, or it
may be ``imitative'' _ simply meant to sound like the chatter or
prattle it denotes. But wherever it comes from, there's an obvious
role for witter in the American vocabulary: It can help to block
the metastasis of wax, a verb whose semantic boundaries are rapidly
melting.
</P>
<P>
   Wax is a synonym for ``increase gradually, grow'' _ the opposite
of wane _ and not simply another word for talk, as many writers now
seem to believe. No doubt misled by the cliche wax eloquent, they
have people waxing or waxing on when all they're really doing is
babbling: In a Globe story not long ago, for instance, students
``waxed street-smart philosophy over pizza and dessert.'' We can
wax our cars, but we can't wax on this way or the language gods
will wax wroth. Switch to wittering, though, and we can go on to
our heart's content.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
