<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR 2000 -- A REAL SNOOZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millennium madness is upon us, but with luck and money, you
might be able avoid the wackiness surrounding the arrival of the
year 2000. (That's a year away from the actual millennium, but
people will celebrate anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons Hotel in London will be offering one special
suite to a couple who want to escape the frantic festivities of New
Year's Eve 1999 and snooze blissfully into 2000. The ninth-floor
Park Suite will have full blackout and soundproof facilities with
all clocks and calendars removed. A special menu, inspired by
pre-1950s menus, will be offered, and black-and-white movies will
be shown in the suite. Other requests in this vein will be honored.
</P>
<P>
   The couple who place the highest bid by June 1, 1999, will
secure the peaceful room. Money offered above the published price
of the Park Suite on that date (currently the room goes for about
$1,500 US) will be donated to the British Red Cross. Good luck and
happy snoozing.
</P>
<P>
   (To bid or seek more information about this or three other
millennium packages, write after Sept. 1 to Coordinator, Four
Seasons Hotel, Hamilton Place, Park Lane, London W1A 1AZ; or
telephone 0171-499-0888; or fax 0171-493-6629.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel trivia: &LR;  Here's a math riddle from the New Zealand travel
newsletter NZ News &AMP; Features: A farmer had 17 sheep. All but nine
died. How many live sheep were left? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  In Australia and New Zealand, the movie ``Truth or
Dare'' is shown under the title ``In Bed with Madonna.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``Going to the mountains is going home.'' _ John Muir.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Fascinating fact:  &LR; The water plunging over Niagara Falls contains
the outflow from four Great Lakes _ Superior, Huron, Michigan, and
Erie, all flowing into Lake Ontario. (With thanks to Elaine E.
Comeau of West Newton, who cites as her source ``Niagara: A History
of the Falls'' by Pierre Berton.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Traveling by photo: &LR;  Maybe you can't make it to St. Petersburg,
Russia, anytime soon. But you can see the refurbished pastel colors
of St. Peter the Great's city glowing again. Just visit Norumbega
Point at Weston for ``The Empire Strikes Back: Contemporary
Photographs of St. Petersburg, Russia'' by noted photographer Susan
Wilson. For more information, call 781-899-5505.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  Athens menu describing shish
kebab: ``chopped up cow with wire through it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
