<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GIRL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENDER EVOKES LAUGHTER SUBDUED BY ABSURDITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FIONA LUIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GIRL IN THE FLAMMABLE SKIRT 
By Aimee Bender 
Doubleday, 184 pp., $21.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the opening to ``The Rememberer,'' the first story in
Aimee Bender's gut-wrenching collection of stories: ``My lover is
experiencing reverse evolution. I tell no one. I don't know how it
happened, only that one day he was my lover and the next he was
some kind of ape. It's been a month and now he's a sea turtle.''
</P>
<P>
   This bizarrely comic tale would be rib-splittingly funny save
for the simple fact that Bender breaks your heart. Her stories have
a way of tenderly dissecting the fragility of the wounded human
spirit; in the process of their telling, you ache for each lost
character and looted soul. When the narrator in ``The Rememberer''
drives her lover, by then a ``one-celled wonder,'' to the beach to
release him into the waves, Bender lulls you into a state of
mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Each story has a way of peering in on a character lost in a
labyrinth, and it is to Bender's abiding credit that each puzzle
compels rather than repels. Even with a protagonist who teeters on
the edge _ the disturbed heiress of ``Call My Name,'' who auditions
men with sexual abandon _ Bender manages to evoke sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Terse, at times twisted, embodiments of loss ensure that none of
the stories verges on the banal. ``Marzipan'' is a perfect example.
``One week after his father died,'' says the child narrator, ``my
father woke up with a hole in his stomach. It wasn't a small hole,
some kind of break in the skin, it was a hole the size of a soccer
ball and it went all the way through. You could now see behind him
like he was an enlarged peephole.''
</P>
<P>
   The child's mother then becomes pregnant, and nine months later
gives birth to her own mother. Trauma is elevated into the realm of
the absurd and fantastic, yet it transforms itself eventually into
a universe not without dignity and redemption. Through it all, a
child attempts to make sense of a world turned on its head, of a
family rent asunder. Maintaining that point of view, Bender knows,
is critical, and she renders it with justice.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Quiet Please,'' another sorrowful sojourn into the
landscape of loss, a librarian has sex with every man who comes
into her library on the day she is told her father has died. When
chaos ensues in the library and the quiet is ruptured, she is held
aloft by a muscleman; upon his shoulders she stands, comically
retouching with a pencil a mural of dancing fairies painted on the
library's ceiling. Though her grief expresses itself in the
grotesque, the heart-rending close to the story is pure Bender:
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't notice until the next day, when she comes to work
to clean up the books an hour before her father is put into the
ground, that the circle of fairies is altered now. That the
laughing ones now pull along one fairy with purple eyes, who is
clearly dancing against her will, dragged along with the circle,
her mouth wide open and screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a shared skin in all Bender's characters, an ethos of
longing fused with aloneness, that make them so appealing. In
``Legacy,'' a pregnant girl falls in love with the hunchback
step-uncle who gives her shelter, only to tumble out of love when
his deformity is unmasked as a fake hump filled with injected fat
globules. Refracting life's absurd reasonings through a prism of
the bizarre is a specialty of this young author.
</P>
<P>
   Bender's taut prose works its wise melodies throughout this
debut first collection, which despite its seeming simplicity is not
a book to breeze through. Each short story packs quite a hefty
punch, and each should be savored. From cleverly comic to starkly
surreal, Bender's audacious characters surprise and delight.
Sometimes, they even make you weep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
