<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8085 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-INSURE-ANALYSIS-BO     08-11 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-INSURE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE BATTLE IS OVER, BUT IS THE WAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A long-awaited insurance industry tax-cut bill signed
into law Monday is designed to help Massachusetts cast off its
image as one of the least competitive places in the nation for
insurance companies. But while the tax break is a boon to insurers
headquartered in the state, it is unlikely to encourage bigger
industry players, which are based outside Massachusetts, to do
business here.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci signed legislation that grants $48
million a year in tax relief to Massachusetts-based insurers in
exchange for $200 million in investment commitments to low-income
communities over five years. In the works for years, the law
effectively means that Massachusetts is no longer the only state in
the nation to tax insurers headquartered here at rates above those
levied on out-of-state competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But even as it offers insurers of any provenance a 1.5 percent
tax credit for making extra community investments, the new law may
not be enough to entice out-of-state insurers into the
Massachusetts market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt that the larger companies will seek to do more
business in Massachusetts,'' said Sean F. Mooney, an analyst at Guy
Carpenter, a reinsurance firm in New York. He cited prohibitive
regulations not repealed by the new tax cuts, including a provision
requiring new companies to cover problem customers, such as drivers
with poor records, at a proportionately greater rate than small
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   With $17 billion in all kinds of premiums, Massachusetts' entire
insurance industry accounts for 2.7 percent of the national total
of $634 billion, according to the Insurance Information Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the top-selling national firms, such as State Farm
and All-State, has a large presence in the state. Some are not here
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the new tax law, there are a host of reasons.
Massachusetts is the only state in the country where legislators,
not the market, set auto premiums. Regulations dating back to the
1970s reward small, start-up insurers and penalize larger,
out-of-state firms. Only 30 percent of all insurance sold in
Massachusetts is written directly by providers rather than sold
through agents, compared to 70 percent nationwide. Agency-sold
premiums cost more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about insurance money, you're talking
about what companies have to do to keep their commitments to
policyholders,'' said Stephen Broadie of the Alliance of American
Insurers, a trade group. ``It's important that the money be
invested in safe investments with reasonable yields.'' The new law
phases out a passel of taxes that were among the highest in the
nation, including a 14 percent net investment income tax paid by
state-based life insurers, and a 1 percent investment income tax
and premium surtaxes, both paid by state-based property and
casualty insurers.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for tax relief, life insurers and property and
casualty insurers (the latter as a group) must each collectively
invest $100 million in two funds that will finance low-income
housing and disdavantaged businesses. Under the new law, insurers
that decide the tax breaks are not worth it are not forced to
contribute to the fund. But Thomas E. Maloney, chief financial
officer at John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., said most
companies would opt for the tax breaks, which he said would improve
their bottom line even after the investment commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The tax package may not inspire large insurers but it has
encouraged community advocates, who want to see the industry invest
more in poor areas. ``Insurance companies ought to invest in the
neighborhoods in which they sell premiums,'' said Alan J. Fishbein,
general counsel at the Center for Community Change, a
Washington-based community advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Industry participants counter that insurers can ill afford to
use policyholders' money to invest in riskier projects.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of mergers among financial institutions, community
advocates have turned up the heat on insurance companies to secure
bigger investment commitments to poor regions. The strategy has
worked well with banks, which are required by law to meet the
credit needs of the communities they serve. But it has been tougher
with insurance companies, which have argued that they are
structurally different from banks. A California proposal to force
insurers to invest a percentage of premiums in poor areas failed
last April in the state's legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
