<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8088 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PEQUOT-BOS &LR;      08-11 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PEQUOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBAL TRIBUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M. R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ The largest space in North America
dedicated to the exhibition and study of American Indian culture
opens Tuesday on the grounds of the Mashantucket Reservation in the
otherwise rural Thames River valley. At over 300,000 square feet,
and at a cost that surely exceeds, and may double, the original
estimate and current announced figure of $135 million, the
Mashantucket Pequot Museum and Research Center is a monument to two
very different groups. It celebrates the ancestors of the tiny _
300-plus members _ but wealthy Pequots, and also the scattered
millions of other Indians in America north of Mexico. The visual
displays, and they are enormous, are about Pequots. The research
institution will be a study space for everyone from children in
elementary school (in their own center) to visiting scholars, who
will be given office space in the adult library. Reference
materials on all Native Americans will be collected and made
available.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, it is all a monument to the Foxwoods Casino and
Resort, buildings that rise like the Wizard of Oz's Emerald City
above the second-growth forest that dominates the hilly landscape.
The museum, with its own entrance road off Connecticut Route 2, is
just a half-mile from the dollar slot machines, but keeps its
distance. Visitors could come and go unaware of the funding source,
did not the hotel tower rise a dozen stories above the treetops,
gleaming in purple and green architectural accents setting off the
expanse of glass sliding doors that open to the guest room
balconies.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of millions of dollars for a museum seems almost unreal
in an age when just putting a new roof on the Peabody Museums at
Harvard took more than 10 years of white-knuckled fund-raising
effort. But to watch dozens of gamblers drop silver dollars and
quarters in the half-acre of slots (much more popular than the
nearby quarter-acre of card tables) at 9 on a weekday morning is to
understand that millions for research is achievable in just a few
years of dedicated effort at the one-buttoned (no longer are they
one-armed) bandits by middle-aged and senior citizens with time on
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best way to understand the museum as a public space
is to follow along on a walk through the halls. The museum, created
by committee of Pequot elders and various architectural and
information companies, does not have a single spokesperson; it
speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   The public viewing falls into two very distinct media or
concepts, both dictated by the sad fact that the Pequot culture is,
except for Colonial-era accounts by European settlers, completely
lost. The language is known only from a few word lists. The
material culture consists of no more than some durable stone tools
and a few objects, including a canoe, providentially preserved by
immersion in an anaerobic swamp. The social culture, kept alive by
story-telling, tends to stop remembering things much before the
19th century. That said, the exhibits in the museum are almost
entirely re-creations, either in three-dimenional, life-size
sculpture gardens full of Pequots, or they are pieces of culture
documented, amplified, explained on reactive, if not truly
interactive, television monitors. The electronic museum, although
overshadowed by the scale of the physical museum, sets a new
standard for user-operated media.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning, in all senses of the word, three-dimensional
exhibits are highlighted by a walk-through, half-acre, 16th-century
Pequot village. If the reader would recall either the standard
museum table-top dioramas, or the equally common
viewed-through-the-glass depictions of life-size Native Americans
doing interesting things _ frozen forever with the knife poised
above the deer's thorax or with the stone perpetually stopped in
mid-stroke as it grinds corn _ and then could imagine the dioramas
blown up to life-size (or the viewer shrunk to the size of a
beetle), but everything still as immobile, unmoving, and silent as
department store mannequins, he or she will get some idea of the
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Natural-size or monumental statues (think of the bronze Indian
forever aiming his arrow at the sky outside the Museum of Fine Arts
in Boston) constitute a genre we are all familiar with. The viewer
does not expect the archer's arms to tire, the back to itch, the
foot to cramp. Much the same is true with the miniature dioramas or
the realistic, authentically dressed, statuesque Indian figures in
a large museum exhibit. In both cases, the bodies inside the
clothing will be stylized, and the glass itself is a powerful
barrier, an insuperable threshold, between the viewer and the
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The Pequot village dispenses with the glass barrier. The visitor
walks through a community of some 20 dwellings, past more than 100
silent figures. One is, of course, not supposed to touch, but with
the glass gone, one is also terribly aware of the true nature of
the exhibit's humanoid Native Americans, that they are somehow less
realistic the more accurate they appear.
</P>
<P>
   We accept the conventions of art, whether miniature, like the
figures in Keats's ``Ode on a Grecian Urn,'' or full-size, say,
Rodin's ``Burghers of Calais.'' There is a charm and a real
poignancy in the experience of art, as in Keats describing the boy
pursuing the girl on the Grecian urn, and neither losing, nor
getting:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bold Lover, never, never canst thou kiss,
</P>
<P>
   Though winning near the goal _ yet, do not grieve;
</P>
<P>
   She cannot fade, though thou has not thy bliss,
</P>
<P>
   For ever wilt thou love, and she be fair!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pequot village, although devoid of amorous persons, does
resemble Shelley's little town on the urn, ``thy streets forever
more will silent be.'' There are sounds, an astonishingly realistic
multi-speaker stereo system brings the sounds of a summer woodland
echoing through the paths in the village _ gulls mewing, crows
squabbling, echos and responses of songbirds. It is the plastic
Pequots who are, necessarily but eerily, silent.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to predict how visitors, especially children,
will react to the major dioramas. A woodland scene, with only two
persons, is a remarkable recreation of everything from blades of
grass to a choir of birds on a verdant, unruined branch. Another
huge diorama with dozens of early Pequots (or at least, early
occupants of New England) killing caribou is somehow more realistic
than the Pequot village. There are two possible reasons: both the
caribou and the human beings are covered with pelts, natural or
sewn together. This is not trivial, for it takes the viewer's eyes
away from body parts and allows one to concentrate on the total
effect of the hunting diorama. The Pequots in the village, captured
in mid-summer weather and activities, are minimally but decently
dressed, and the sheer footage of faux skin is noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   And both the hunting scene and the woodland scene are
accompanied by really user-friendly interpretative video programs
... touching the screen allows the viewer to do everything from
look at the diorama from each side in turn to calling up a film of
a modern Native American caribou hunt, to pulling down an interview
with an archeologist on how science tries to recreate such a
powerful tableau from just a few fragments of bone and shards of
stone left scattered on the ground some 10 or 11 thousand years
ago. The televised, reactive, information mediates between the
viewer and the exhibit. It provides not just information, but
distance.
</P>
<P>
   The Pequot Village as a walk-through is powerfully close, and if
that is the intent, it works. The head, both the facial features
and skull shape of each individual Pequot mannequin, is in a
certain sense of the word, perfectly authentic. The faces are based
on life masks, plus careful measurements of the necks and skulls of
actual Native Americans. The examples come from tribes across
America. The donors, so to speak, of the faces were also measured
minutely from head to toe and down each arm, and when it came time
to put a head on a body, the sculptors hired live models whose
bodies very closely approximated the face-donors's individual
physiques.
</P>
<P>
   It will not matter to a visitor that the young woman emptying
garbage on the village dump has a head from say, the Northern
Cheyenne reservation in Montana on top of the body of a Caucasian
art student picking up some extra cash in New York City. What will
matter is that the search for perfection, for absolute realism,
only emphasises the fact that visitors are looking at a replica.
There is no artistic sense, no illusion created by technique, to
elevate the mannequins above what they are. And they are very
elegantly posed and copied bodies with a distinct and unvarying
brown covering that somehow does not resemble skin anymore than,
and perhaps less than, a patina-coated bronze mimics flesh.
</P>
<P>
   None of this may matter to children, surely the audience for
whom the Pequot Village will have the most appeal. It is a question
of suspending disbelief. To innocent eyes, the super-realism of the
Pequot village will encourage belief. The immediacy of the figures,
close enough to touch although that is strictly discouraged, will
probably overcome their patent artifice. It certainly should be
popular, it takes the successful attraction of a good wax museum to
a new level of scale and complexity. It will certainly make
visitors, of any age or background, think about the museum
experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
