u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-11 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MALDEN MILLS, A PAINFUL FIGHT BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Jan. 23, 1996, and the president of the United States was
addressing Congress and the nation in his annual State of the Union
message. The end of ``big government'' and the virtues of
traditional values were the topics of the night. Monica had not yet
entered the lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the gallery, seated strategically behind Hillary Rodham
Clinton, was Aaron Feuerstein, the owner of Malden Mills who had
just emerged as a national hero a month earlier for his pledge to
rebuild his burned out Methuen, Mass. complex against all odds.
President Clinton never mentioned Feuerstein by name that night,
but the White House invitation helped focus the nation on the mill
owner and the message of hope he represented.
</P>
<P>
   That was then, as they say. This is now.
</P>
<P>
   Running a textile mill in a world of cut-throat competition can
be a dicey business, even for a national hero. Feuerstein's Malden
Mills Industries Inc. has been losing millions of dollars, and the
company's lead lender, BankBoston Corp., put pressure on Feuerstein
to make changes, says a person familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, Malden Mills executives became
uncomfortable enough to explore moving the $120 million &UR;  &LR; credit
line to another lender, the person says. Malden Mills executives
have met with several other institutions, including Congress
Financial Corp., an asset-based lender, as late as last week.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston and Feuerstein said Monday they expect their 30-year
relationship to continue. ``The Bank of Boston is remaining with
us, and we are remaining with them,'' Feuerstein said. ``We are
treating them right, and they are treating us right.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Feuerstein said his company is ``now in the process of
restructuring our entire credit facility.'' But the effort
apparently has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   Since rebuilding the mill after a devastating December 1995
fire, Feuerstein has grown his business based on the mill's popular
Polartec products, fabrics known for their insulating qualities and
sold to companies such as Eddie Bauer and Lands' End, which use
them to make clothing.
</P>
<P>
   That unit has done well, but Malden Mills' others have not,
despite investing tens of millions of dollars in them. Last winter
the company said it would &UR;  &LR; abandon &UR;  &LR; its velvet upholstery unit, a
move that cost about 300 jobs, and it never really returned to its
low-end upholstery, or ``flock,'' business after the fire, despite
what Feuerstein called several ``false starts.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems have led to big losses. Malden Mills lost roughly
$20 million in the &UR;  &LR; fiscal year &UR;  &LR; ending last October and is
projecting a loss of roughly $17 million this year, said &UR;  &LR; the
person familiar with the figures. The company said it would be
profitable, excluding the units that were being phased out,
according to the source.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein says those numbers are wrong, but he declined to
provide his own. ``Malden Mills is a privately held company and we
have never released details on our financial information,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston has made a big bet on Malden Mills. The bank has
about $55 million of the $120 million Malden Mills loan, with
NationsBank Corp., State Street Corp., and others holding smaller
pieces, the source said. BankBoston executives were surprised at
Malden Mills' financial condition at the end of the last fiscal
year, and the loan was shifted into the bank's asset-based lending
group, which oversees higher-risk loans, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's unit worked with Malden Mills to finance the
company's seasonal Polartec business, but it also suggested some
conditions that Feuerstein found objectional, the person said.
Among them: asking Feuerstein to pledge his personal assets and his
own stock in the company to the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Over at least the last month, Malden Mills executives, including
chief financial officer Wesley Rydin and board member David
Ferrari, who works with troubled companies, have been talking to
other lenders. Among those institutions is Congress Financial,
which sometimes provides financing to struggling companies like
Grossman's and Rich's Department Stores. Edward I. Shifman Jr., who
heads Congress' Boston office, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The source says there were differences in opinion within
BankBoston on how hard to press Malden Mills. BankBoston's
chairman, Charles K. Gifford, eventually weighed in on Feuerstein's
side, and the issues that were objectionable to Feuerstein were
eventually changed.
</P>
<P>
   Said Feuerstein: ``As for me personally, there never was, is, or
will be a personal guarantee or pledge of stock.''
</P>
<P>
   A BankBoston spokeswoman said, ``We are working with Aaron and
his team, and beyond that we don't comment on our relationship with
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein is optimistic about the future of his company, which
employs more than 2,000 people. ``We are looking forward to a good,
strong, and healthy '99.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
