<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-11 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP AD MAY AID DEMOCRATIC FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republicans believe they may have a chance this year to put
a dent in the labor movement by wresting back at least one of two
Massachusetts congressional seats they are targeting.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 congressional seats in the Bay State, all held by
Democrats, the GOP has its sights on the 6th District seat held by
US Representative John F. Tierney of Salem and the 3rd District
seat held by US Representative John P. McGovern of Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney and McGovern became congressmen two years ago by
defeating two GOP incumbents, Peter Torkildsen and Peter Blute.
During their first terms, the two Democrats demonstrated a full
support for labor's agenda, according to the Massachusetts AFL-CIO,
the 400,000-member umbrella organization for unions in the Bay
State.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP apparently feels that Tierney and McGovern have strong
Republican opponents this year. The Republicans view their GOP
candidate for McGovern's seat, State Senator Matthew J. Amorello of
Grafton, as popular enough in his district to upset McGovern's bid
for a second term. They also see Torkildsen as strong enough to
unseat Tierney this year in their third matchup. Torkildsen
defeated Tierney in their first meeting and Tierney won a close
race against Torkildsen two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's race, campaign reports show that Tierney is
comfortably ahead of Torkildsen in fund-raising, and is considered
to have an edge thus far among voters. But Tierney's supporters
feel that the election is still too close for them to feel assured
of victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern supporters believe that their candidate is doing well
thus far against Amorello, but they are aware that the GOP
apparently feels McGovern is vulnerable enough for the Republicans
to spend money on behalf of Amorello's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the state GOP recently developed a campaign
advertisement, scheduled to be aired later this weekcharging that
the Massachusetts congressional delegation is doing a poor job of
bringing tax dollars to the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, state GOP chairwoman Jean Inman criticizes McGovern,
a member of the House transportation committee, when she says that
the Bay State was the only state to have its highway funds cut by
Congress. Inman stated that the funds were cut by $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The ad also charges that Tierney voted against the Highway Funds
bill. Ironically, the ad may end up helping more than hurting
McGovern's and Tierney's candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern received unexpected support from a top Republican, US
Representative Bud Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House
Transportation and Infrastructure Committee. Shuster contradicted
Inman's claim, stating that Massachusetts this year is actually
going to receive $488 million, or $105 million more in highway
funds than last year.
</P>
<P>
   As quoted in the Worcester Telegram, Shuster said the $1.1
billion ``Big Dig,'' namely the Central Artery/Third Harbor Tunnel
project, was a ``one-time deal, an understanding. There is no
question about it. Both Democrats and Republicans can agree on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's response, of course, won praise from the Democratic
candidates and outrage from the executive director of the state
GOP, Marc DeCourcey, who described Shuster's remarks as ``a lot of
Washington gobbledygook.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for the Tierney campaign said that with this ad,
the state Republican Party ``shot themselves in the foot.'' Tierney
said he voted against the bill because in it the GOP had cut
programs for the elderly and for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the GOP compared its current ad campaign to the
AFL-CIO ad campaign in 1996 that targeted Torkildsen and Blute.
Most political strategists agree that these ads helped Tierney and
McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Based on early reactions, this year's GOP ad may help Tierney
and McGovern retain their seats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
