<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNGA MAY SHED LIGHT ON BRAZIL'S DOWNFALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether Edmundo and Ronaldo are ready, the European seasons are
starting.
</P>
<P>
   A month after France '98, neither Edmundo nor Ronaldo is
prepared to join his Italian Serie A club, and questions remain
concerning the Brazilians' lackluster performance in the World Cup
final in Saint-Denis.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over who should start apparently split the
Brazilian team, according to an interview with Dunga to be
published in France Football magazine. After Ronaldo fainted the
morning of the game, many of his teammates thought he had died.
Understandably, even the most spiritually oriented of them expected
to have Edmundo in the lineup instead of a reincarnated Ronaldo
against France.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the game, Edmundo was listed to start. What
occurred after that is a mystery. But whatever led to Brazil's
collapse deserves to be better explained.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo probably should not have played, just as Robert Baggio
should not have performed for Italy in the 1994 final. But the
magnitude of Brazil's failure raised many questions. Possibly,
Dunga, who was vacationing in Miami while preparing to return to
Japan, will clarify some issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
He's not there yet
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo cut short his vacation in Cancun after a report that his
mother could be a target for kidnappers. Ronaldo is an excellent
striker and an interesting personality, but he is not the
multitalented performer that Pele was, and he should not be
presented as a savior. He is in many ways still an innocent
youngster. In Mexico, Ronaldo was pictured swimming with his
fiancee, Susana Werner, and a dolphin, still exuding
gregariousness.
</P>
<P>
   At least Inter realizes this break is healthy for Ronaldo, and
he is not expected to report to practice until later this month.
Meanwhile, Inter begins Champions Cup play tomorrow against Skonto
Riga of Latvia in Pisa.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Latvians, Danes, and Hungarians are still
allowed to participate in the tournament. Super League proponents
would shut out anyone except the most glamorous clubs, regardless
of merit.
</P>
<P>
   Silvio Berlusconi, Leo Kirch, Rupert Murdoch, and the Saudi
Arabian prince Al Waleed Bin Talal would like to finance such a
Super League, through the J.P. Morgan investment bank of New York.
They want to dominate the competition, creating a monopoly using
the American sports franchising model.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, soccer is structured in an egalitarian way and will
resist such steamroller attempts. FIFA and the continental
federations are often criticized for their Machiavellian politics,
but at least their structure is democratic. The Union des
Associations Europeennes de Football was founded on the basic
principles of fairness and meritocracy, which includes promotion
and relegation. If the Berlusconis and Murdochs are in charge, we
will have sports dictatorships, and the definition of entertainment
and sporting activity will become further skewed to the advantage
of the ultra-rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (UEFA) won't back is a hand-picked competition on the
basis on size, reputation and status,'' Alex Fynn, an advertising
executive who helped set up the European Champions League, told the
Independent on Sunday. ``That would be outlawed by UEFA and FIFA,
so players wouldn't be able to play for their national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berlusconi is a genuine fan, in his way, but he's an American
fan. Even promotion and relegation is too risky for him. The
mistake he makes is that this isn't the NFL or NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Win or else?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pressure has been relieved from Gigi Simoni, the
Inter coach. Simoni proved himself last year, when he was required
to win his opening match against Brescia or risk being fired by
Inter president Massimo Moratti, then nearly overcame Juventus in
the championship race. But there are more demanding presidents in
soccer. After defending Yugoslav champion Obilic tied newly
promoted Miliciner, 0-0, Saturday, Zeljko Raznjatovic fired the
coach, Okuka. Actually, the firing was carried out by Raznjatovic's
rock star wife, who is officially president while Raznjatovic is
being investigated for suspected war crimes in Croatia. Obilic is
expected to have a new coach by tomorrow, when it visits Bayern
Munich in a Champions League match.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
At the Copa
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where Edmundo will be tomorrow is uncertain. He is supposed to
report to Fiorentina, but there is a chance he will play for Vasco
da Gama in the Copa Libertadores final against Barcelona of
Guayaquil in Rio de Janeiro. The Copa Libertadores winner will meet
Real Madrid for the Intercontinental championship in Japan in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Like the European Champions Cup, the Copa Libertadores is on the
verge of change. The Libertadores is a fascinating competition but
it involves only 10 South American countries.
</P>
<P>
   With the emergence of the Copas MercoNorte and MercoSur, the
South American Confederation is hoping to encompass the CONCACAF
region. This could be a profitable move for both confederations.
</P>
<P>
   The structure is already in place for expansion, and the US is
projected to play a big part. The CONCACAF Champions Cup begins
tonight at RFK Stadium, with D.C. United representing the MLS.
Mexican clubs Cruz Azul, Leon, and Toluca, plus Costa Rica's
Alajeula and Saprissa are also entered. United will open against
the Trinidad and Tobago representative, Joe Public.
</P>
<P>
   United is also entered in the MercoNorte tournament, starting
Sept. 6, in a group with Alianza (Peru), Barcelona (Ecuador), and
Millionarios (Colombia).
</P>
<P>
   One CONCACAF team from these competitions and the Cup Winners
Cup will qualify for the first World Club tournament, sponsored by
FIFA, next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
French flight
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   France's season opened with fears that the league will continue
to export its most talented players. A total of 84 French players
were registered in first-division clubs outside the country. The
addition of Brazilian striker Adailton, Nigerian midfielder
Augustine Okocha, and German defender Christian Worns (Paris
Saint-Germain), plus Portuguese defender Oceano (Toulouse) is not
enough to compensate for the exodus. Olympique Marseille opened
with a 2-0 victory, but Paris Saint-Germain lost, 3-1, at Bordeaux,
and defending champion Lens lost, 3-2, at Toulouse. World Cup
champions Emmanuel Petit and Patrick Vieira led Arsenal to a 3-0
win over Manchester United, the Gunners' first victory in England's
Charity Shield since 1953 ... African football remains in a
quandary over its teams' disappointing performance at France '98.
``The plain fact is that Africa is further behind Europe and South
America than it was four, or even eight, years ago,'' noted
Emmanuel Maradas, editor of African Soccer magazine. The pattern of
corruption and incompetence must be broken for African teams to
advance. This will require individuals of great courage and
credibility. Maradas said the future must be entrusted to former
players such as Cameroonian goalkeeper Joseph Antoine-Bell and
Nigerian defender Stephen Keshi, who retired soon after USA '94.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
