<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, FOOTBALL ISN'T DRAINING CBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For what it's worth, CBS Corp. is making a bunch of money, even
though it ponied up an exorbitant amount of cash for the rights to
broadcast AFC games for the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's not clear how much CBS Sports is costing the
company, one thing is known: CBS said its second-quarter revenue
jumped 16 percent to $1.48 billion from $1.28 billion. Earnings
rose fourfold to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, CBS lost $11 million during the same period,
according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround is the result of increased earnings from CBS's
radio division, which has grown since acquiring Infinity
Broadcasting in 1996 and was aided by the purchase of American
Radio Systems during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits from television rose 5 percent to $69 million,
CBS said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's return to the NFL came with a hefty price tag: $500
million per year. At the time of the purchase, CBS officials said
they would in essence squeeze local affiliates, such as WBZ in
Boston, to help offset costs.
</P>
<P>
   That plan became clear last spring at CBS's annual spring
affiliates meeting in Los Angeles. The network sought as much as
$50 million from its affiliates, but under the agreement, the
affiliates will give up $27 million of the roughly $200 million in
compensation the network pays them to carry its programs.
</P>
<P>
   The affiliates also will give back to CBS an advertising spot
during ``Late Show with David Letterman'' and two more during
``This Morning'' to sell on a national basis.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the network will give each affiliate one spot in
prime time every night to sell on the local level, where they can
earn the highest rates. Industry analysts estimate those coveted
prime-time spots amount to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Sports president Sean McManus repeated last week that CBS
will not lose money on the NFL. ``We are ahead of schedule,''
McManus said, referring to advertising revenue secured thus far for
the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Duquette discourse
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette was a little feisty when
asked by Gene Lavanchy on ``Sports Xtra'' in Boston about the
perception that he doesn't get along with big-time talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pay the dough, they will come,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette didn't break new ground on Mo Vaughn's contract talks,
saying the team will revisit the situation when the season ends.
</P>
<P>
   Lavanchy came away with a generally positive assessment of the
much-maligned general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give the guy some credit,'' Lavanchy said. ``He
did bring a number of players here that have worked out well.
(Bret) Saberhagen comes readily to mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1349EDT &QL; 
