<HEADLINE>
ANN BEATTIE'S 36-STORY EFFORT IS TOO MUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
PARK CITY 
Ann Beattie (Alfred A. Knopf, $25) 
 
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad news about Ann Beattie.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle. That's all I have to say about ``Park City,'' a
collection of 36 of Ann Beattie's stories, including eight new
ones. I can't finish it. I just can't. I've tried and tried, but I
am going to have to give in.
</P>
<P>
   I've read maybe half of it, in fits and starts, and I couldn't
much tell you one story from another. Full disclosure compels me to
acknowledge that the day after I got the book, my wife had a baby,
so I've been a little distracted.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think it would have mattered. It's the stories.
Every single one seems just a variation on a theme:
</P>
<P>
   Tracy either lives in New York or is a graduate student at an
Eastern college, never named but clearly Yale, because the story
takes place 25 years ago in New Haven, Conn. A man named Steve has
the hots for her, but they never have slept together. Tracy has,
however, slept with most of Steve's friends, which drives him to
various forms of distraction.
</P>
<P>
   They work at jobs that are never described. Mostly they sit
around the living room of his apartment and smoke joints and drink
wine and notice tiny little details about each other _ he notes
that she has stopped painting her fingernails and started chewing
them to the quick; she senses that he no longer showers daily.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to put the moves on her, constantly plots a way to do
so but never gets around to it. She continues to disappoint him by
not making a play for him, and talks about her other boyfriends, at
least one of whom wears a leather jacket.
</P>
<P>
   It's cold outside. Occasionally Steve gets mugged. A friend has
left her husband and lives with their daughter. The story ends with
Tracy and Steve walking to a corner bar, or Tracy going off with
some other guy. And then it begins again, under a different title,
only now it's Margot and Harold.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say the stories are bad. It's just that after
however many in a row, who could possibly care?
</P>
<P>
   I've liked other things Beattie's written, and I know she has a
keen eye for detail and affairs of the heart and all that, but
please. Couldn't just every once in a while a tree fall on a house
or something?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I am too young to appreciate sitting in living rooms
talking about old flames from 25 years ago with a wine buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the second half of the book may be full of plague and
pestilence, for all I know. But I just don't think I can do the
work to find out.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still interested in reviewing books. But I just can't do
this one. At least not for a while. I've got to read something else
to get out of the '70s-relationship rut. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-11 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULLORS AWAITS HIS CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUPEN FOFARIA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems everyone wants to hear that Derrick Cullors is
frustrated about not getting the ball much this preseason. They
want stories of him fighting with coaches, having problems with
teammates, running his mouth to the media. They won't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors has been pushed to the back of the line so many times in
his football career that he hardly remembers the view from the
front. He's been criticized for his attitude and chastised for his
reputation, so the only opinion he remembers is his own.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the ink still fresh from his rags-to-riches story of
last year, when he fought from preseason bench-warmer to postseason
starter, curiosity is growing about his role this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors took the roughest path to the starting lineup and was
there for the Patriots when they needed him most; so how will he
take getting passed over for the starting running back position by
someone such as Sedrick Shaw or Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll approach this like last year,'' Cullors said. ``I was way
back in the hunt as far as running backs were concerned and then I
was starting by the end of the year. That's all. As long as I stay
positive, I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullors, who carried the ball only twice but gained 24 yards in
Sunday's 28-0 loss to the Vikings, made a big impact last year.
With injuries to Curtis Martin and Dave Meggett, the Patriots found
themselves in a situation not unlike today's _ wondering who will
step up and run the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors made light of the question late last year, earning his
first start in the season finale at Miami and rushing 22 times for
86 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the important thing today with Derrick was that we
gave him the chance to get his rhythm,'' Drew Bledsoe said after
that game. ``With the injuries we have, he's going to have to carry
the load. I think what we saw today is that he can do it and we're
going to expect him to do it from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   So why throw him to the back of the line now? Why place hope in
rookie Edwards and second-year back Shaw when you know Cullors has
come through before?
</P>
<P>
   Cullors doesn't have an answer. He never has. He's been dealing
with the question since 1994, and he still can't give a ``why,''
only a ``how'' _ how he will rise back to the top, as he has
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you get on the field, you have to make it
happen,'' Cullors says. ``You can't worry about who's going in and
who's coming out. You have to know when you're in the game, you
have to do your job, whether you get five plays or 20 plays. I'm
not going to go around saying they should start me. I'm just going
to work hard until they notice.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that work ethic that got Cullors through the injury and
insult of a tarnished tenure at Texas Christian and drove him to
complete his senior year at Murray State as the NCAA's
second-leading rusher and a first-team All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors was described as an exciting and unique runner at Texas
Christian, but an injury in the first game of the 1994 season
sidelined him for the year and put the spotlight on teammate Andre
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Cullors realized that coach Pat Sullivan was
investing in Davis _ whom he had recruited _ and would bench
Cullors _ who was wooed by the school before Sullivan's arrival. At
that point, Cullors wanted to end his football career, frustrated
by a coach who saw his talents but gave him no confidence.
</P>
<P>
   His mother persuaded him to pack his things and go to Kentucky,
where he became what some consider the best running back Murray
State ever saw. But he wasn't welcomed with open arms there,
either. Again he had to prove himself. To the school, to the team,
to head coach Houston Nutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were telling Coach Nutt that he shouldn't take Derrick
Cullors _ they said he was a bad kid and had a reputation,'' says
Steve Parker, who was sports editor of the Murray Ledger and Times
while Cullors played at Murray State. ``They said he was a problem
kid and we didn't need him. That couldn't be farther from the
truth. Only now can we look back and say he's the best the school's
ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullors gained All-America honors with the Racers and was voted
the Ohio Valley Player of the Year after leading the team to its
first conference title in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   He proved his worth. He proved it by raising his hand at one of
his first practices and firing up the team with a pep talk. He
proved it by suiting up for the biggest game Murray State had seen
in two decades _ against Eastern Kentucky, which came to town with
a 28-game league winning streak. Cullors could barely walk during
warmups after injuring his knee in the previous game, but he
managed to play and distract the defense, freeing his wide
receivers to lead the team to victory.
</P>
<P>
   But he received another shove to the back of the line when he
wasn't chosen in the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at him and they see his small size and he's not
real quick,'' says Parker. ``So they think they can do better. But
he knows this game too well. No one makes the right cut every time
and sees the field all at once. But he does.''
</P>
<P>
   That went overlooked by scouts who saw only his 5-foot-11-inch,
180-pound frame and doubted that he could withstand an NFL beating.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Cullors proved himself. He went to the Baltimore Ravens
training camp and put on a performance so impressive that it piqued
two teams' interest. Bill Parcells finally convinced Cullors he
belonged with the Patriots and picked him up as a free agent in
1996. Cullors spent the entire year on the practice squad, bulking
up to almost 200 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibiting his trademark patience and positive attitude, he
never complained. He worked hard and waited for the payoff. It came
Oct. 12, 1997, when he played his first NFL game, versus Buffalo.
He thought back to his arduous road and smiled. But that wouldn't
be the day he'd remember most. That day would come one month later,
when the Patriots traveled to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors took a kickoff at the 14-yard line and went to the
races. At about the 25, he started to slip. Without regard for his
proximity to the ground, he saw a hole and instinctively regained
his balance, going all the way to the end zone. It was the first
Patriot return for a touchdown since Jon Vaughn in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors may be undersized for the job of running back, but he
has shown time and again that his heart, talent, and instincts
compensate for that.
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots again searching for a runner, he is forced to
prove himself once more. He still isn't angry. He knows there's
none better and he'll wait until the world realizes that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a running back ever since I started playing
football,'' Cullors said. ``That just comes naturally to me. I know
how to do this job. Coach (Pete) Carroll knows what he's doing, and
I feel like if I continue to do what I'm doing _ working hard _
they may want to extend my role. So that's what I'm going to do
every time out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
