<HEADLINE>
CAPTURE THE LITTLE CHILDREN: DROPOUT MAKES FAIRY TALE A THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have children and enjoy a good scare, listen again to the
legend of the Pied Piper of Hamelin.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Browning prettied it up in his 1842 poem, but the facts
(at least part of the story is true) are dark.
</P>
<P>
   In 1284, the German town of Hamelin was overrun by rats _ its
citizens stepped on them wherever they went. One day a stranger
appeared and offered to get rid of the vermin, for a fee. Hamelin's
mayor, at his wits' end, agreed. The stranger took out a flute and
began to play, and mesmerized rats poured out of the houses and
followed him to a river, where they fell into the water and
drowned.
</P>
<P>
   The piper returned to collect his price, but the mayor was smug
and ungrateful. He refused to pay _ what, he asked himself, could
the piper do about it? But the angry stranger took out his pipe and
again began to play, and this time the creatures who came tumbling
into the streets were the town's children, who followed the piper
into the hills and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   One historical rendition said the piper was the agent of a rival
religious authority, on a mission to steal the town's little boys.
Another said he was simply a deranged vagrant who took the children
into the hills and murdered them.
</P>
<P>
   It might be literary opportunism, but Ridley Pearson prefers the
second version.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pied Piper is one of history's first recorded serial
killers,'' he says with ominous pleasure. ``Over the years it has
been turned into this lovely little fairy tale about a guy playing
his flute and running through the streets with happy children. The
fact is, he was hired to get rid of the rats and he murdered the
city's kids when he didn't get paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson found the story several years ago in an encyclopedia,
and it inspired his new suspense thriller, ``The Pied Piper''
(Hyperion, $23.95), which involves babies, kidnappers and an
illegal adoption scheme. Pearson is always looking for the kernel
of an idea, and when he finds one he extrapolates _ wildly _ until
he has something he can build into a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pied Piper'' is his 11th book, the fifth featuring
recurring characters Lou Boldt, a Seattle cop with a wife and kids,
and Daphne Matthews, a criminal psychiatrist and Boldt's one-time
lover. It is long (nearly 500 pages) and painstaking in its
re-creation of police work and of his characters' lives away from
the office. As in real life, the time line is not tidy _ there are
references not only to things that have happened in the past, but
also story lines that will jump into future books. In ``The Pied
Piper,'' Boldt's wife, Liz, undergoes treatment for cancer
(Pearson's real-life model for Boldt, a Seattle cop named Don
Cameron, lost his wife to cancer two years ago), but at the end of
the book her fate remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next novel I'll deal with Boldt's feelings about his
wife's new spiritual take on things,'' Pearson says. ``I want him
to deal with real-life issues. Too much crime fiction deals only
with the cop shop. When you go out into the field and meet these
guys, as I do, you discover that 80 percent of their day is
concerned with personal stuff, as it is with any of us. Sure, they
have to deal with criminals and dead bodies, but they also have to
worry about getting little Johnny to the dentist on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also not a big fan of a series where the characters never
get any older. My publisher would like me to hold Boldt at a
younger age, but I can't. He has to age, or he's not going to be
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson, 45, grew up in Connecticut. He was a big reader as a
kid, but did not try writing fiction until he was in prep school.
Rock and roll was his first love. He was a premed student at the
University of Kansas and later studied music theory at Brown
University, but dropped out of both. He spent years writing songs
and playing in a band before he realized that there was no future
in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is a writer, although he went the corporate route
(working in public relations at Shell Oil),'' he says. ``So one day
I was crying the blues to my mother. I said I blew it by not
getting my degree. I'm in music, which I love and could do the rest
of my life, but I only make 50 bucks a night and that's worrying
me. And our family doesn't have a shoe business I can take over. My
mother said: `Your father's a writer. Maybe you should try that.'
And a light went off in my head and I thought well, yeah, I can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time he had fallen in love with the books of John D.
MacDonald and the early fiction of Ken Follett and Robert Ludlum,
but he took a slight detour before he landed in the genre of
suspense fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed to say this, but I loved the show ``Colombo''
on television and one day I saw Peter Falk on the Johnny Carson
show and he said he was going to leave ``Colombo'' if he didn't get
better scripts. I started work on my first script the next
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote several but sold none, and began to suspect that he
would not be the one to save Falk from mediocre scripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I thought maybe the odds would be better with a novel,'' he
says. ``I heard, mistakenly I'm glad to say, that there were 5,000
novels published each year and I took that to mean 5,000 (itals)
first (end itals) novels. And I thought, hey! Great odds! Much
better odds than with the movie business! I'll try a novel.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a novel based on one of his scripts and it went
nowhere, so he wrote another and another, encouraged by an agent
who took him on. They were published, but to limited success. Then
an editor gave him Thomas Harris' ``Red Dragon'' and told him to
write a book that was as riveting as that book was. The result was
1988's ``Undercurrents'' (the first Lou Boldt novel). It wasn't
``Red Dragon,'' but it brought Pearson an audience. Two years later
he became the first American to be awarded the Raymond Chandler
Fulbright fellowship at Oxford University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I submitted my stuff and someone liked it and I was selected
to go to England,'' he says. ``There I was at Wadham College, with
the title of visiting professor. I had a corner office that
overlooked the Bodleian Library. I had dining rights at lunch to
sit with some of the finest minds in the world and talk shop. I had
High-Table privileges for dinner, which meant I sat up on a little
raised platform with people dressed in flowing black robes and
drank way too much wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a complete imposter. I (itals) was (end itals) an
imposter, because you can only wear a black robe at High Table if
you have a degree from a college. And I didn't. So for a year I ate
at High Table without a black robe. The discussions I had there I
could never have anywhere else in the world. And these illustrious
people were all thinking, who is this schmuck?''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson came home and wrote four more novels, each selling
better than the last. Today he rises early in the Idaho home he
shares with his wife and 15-month-old daughter, and puts in 12-hour
days. It takes him a little more than a year to complete a novel
(he is already talking about ``the book after next year's book'').
He plays in a band, but now it's the Rock Bottom Remainders and his
fellow musicians include Dave Barry, Stephen King and Amy Tan.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his books have been optioned for films, although none
have been made yet. He submits outlines to his publisher before he
begins writing (Hyperion rejected two of his ideas but as his books
have become bestsellers he is chafing somewhat under that
agreement. He does not lack for fans at his readings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one tonight, and I intend to read both the ``Publishers
Weekly'' review, which was very complimentary, and a review off of
Amazon that says I'm the worst hackneyed writer who ever came down
the pike,'' he says. ``You're always aware of your shortcomings.
They make sure of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson is energetic, successful and appealingly modest. And he
thinks that someday he might just have the chance to combine his
writing and his music.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big dream and ambition is to write a book and write the
screenplay of the book and write the score to the movie,'' he says.
``That's what I'd really like to do. If I can get there by the time
I'm 60, I'll be elated.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
