<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      08-11 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ZARAFA &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Allin (Walker, $22)
</P>
<P>
   In 1827, a giraffe arrived at le Jardin des Plantes in Paris,
having walked from Marseille after sailing from Egypt, a gift from
the viceroy of Egypt to King Charles X of France. The gift was a
gamble. The viceroy hoped to befriend Charles and gain France's
neutrality in Egypt's war against Greece. The ploy didn't work, but
the giraffe did _ she was the first France had seen, and the
country fell in love with her. Her walk to Paris, writes Allin, was
``a 550-mile parade'' with crowds attending her every step, coming
from vineyards and villages to marvel at ``this living mythological
combination of creatures _ a gentle and mysterious sort of horned
camel whose hump had been straightened by stretching its neck, with
legs as tall as a man and the cloven hoofs of a cow, and markings
like a leopard or a maze of lightning and that startling blue-black
snake of a twenty-inch tongue.'' This is Zarafa's story, and it's
difficult to know whether to praise it more for its
otherworldliness or for the history and people that fill its pages.
It's Allin's first book, and as odd and endearing as they come. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HELEN KELLER: A LIFE &QL; 
 &UR; Dorothy Herrmann (Knopf, $30)
</P>
<P>
   For many of us, she always will be not quite 7 years old, with
the face of Patty Duke and hands that clutch frantically at a water
pump. The scene in ``The Miracle Worker'' froze Helen Keller in
time at the moment she discovered language (after ``water,'' she
learned 29 other words that day). But her adult life was just as
intriguing as her journey from isolation to triumphant awareness.
Herrmann explores questions that were beyond the movie's reach: Was
Keller's turbulent relationship with her half-blind teacher, Annie
Sullivan, limiting or liberating? Was her beatific public persona a
front devised and managed by Sullivan to create mass appeal? How
would her life have been different if she'd had more than one
teacher, if she were less protected, if she had been permitted to
marry? It's fascinating, because so many people found transcendence
and inspiration in her triumph over disability. She was cremated
after her death, and her ashes placed next to Sullivan's in a
chapel where, to this day, schoolchildren visit her grave and learn
about her life. The place is marked by a bronze plaque, written in
Braille. So many people have touched it that it has been replaced
twice because the dots were worn away. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SIGHT-READINGS &QL; 
 &UR; Elizabeth Hardwick (Random House, $26)
</P>
<P>
   Here is Hardwick on Edith Wharton: ``(She) had her turf, that
almost forgotten sepia New York, to be turned over and over again,
like setting the plow to the family farm every spring.'' And on
Philip Roth: ``His themes are Jews in the world, especially in
Israel, Jews in the family, Jews in Newark, New Jersey; fame, vivid
enough to occasion imposters (``Operation Shylock''); literature,
since his narrators or performers are writers, actually one writer,
Philip Roth. And sex, anywhere in every manner, a penitential
workout on the page with no thought of backaches, chafings or
phallic fatigue.'' Among her other subjects: John Updike, Richard
Ford and Gertrude Stein. The essays are wonderful fun even if you
have not read half of the books she has. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE AMERICAN WAY OF DEATH REVISITED &QL; 
 &UR; Jessica Mitford (Knopf, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Published in 1963, the original edition was an unflinching and
dumbfoundingly funny look at the funeral industry and its promotion
of ornate and costly services that left survivors in financial
shock. The book wasn't an easy sell the first time (an early
response from Houghton Mifflin: ``We think that you make your book
harder to sell by going at too much length and in too gooey detail
into the process of embalming . . .''), but once it was released
the public loved it and turned toward cremation in droves as a
result of it. Mitford died in 1996, but not before she gave funeral
directors a shock of their own by embarking on this updated
edition. Now, we learn, even cremation is pricey, and mourners who
think they're dealing with independent mortuaries really might be
paying corporations that run many funeral homes. Industry insiders
called the first edition ``the Mitford war dance,'' and condemned
the fight for cheaper funerals as a ``Red plot.'' That delighted
Mitford. She ends this one with a listing of not-for-profit funeral
and memorial societies in each state. May their phones ring, and
may Mitford hear them wherever she is. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE HAND &QL; 
 &UR; Frank R. Wilson (Pantheon, $30)
</P>
<P>
   The hand, one reviewer wrote, is ``the tool of tools,'' but in
reality it is more. Wilson, a neurologist, discovered this when he
showed a video about a problem called ``musician's cramp'' to a
group of musicians. In it were hands that looked normal but had
been mysteriously debilitated _ ``formerly graceful, lithe,
dazzlingly fast hands (that) could barely limp through the notes
they sought to draw out of pianos, guitars, flutes and violins.''
Not far into the film, a guitarist in the audience fainted. The
same thing happened at other presentations, and Wilson began to
understand that ``when personal desire prompts anyone to learn to
do something well with the hands, an extremely complicated process
is initiated that endows the work with a powerful emotional
charge.'' In other words, the hand's contributions to our lives are
more profound than we ever imagined. Wilson interviews people who
use their hands in special ways (a rock climber, a magician),
explores the phenomenon of ``handedness'' and takes his book in
enough beguiling directions to balance its more laborious technical
passages. &QL;  &QL; 
(Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-TOBACCO-HNS &LR;      08-11 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO REMAINS A PLAYER TO DEFEAT IN THE MAJOR LEAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN SHEA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The minor-league pitcher, fresh out of high
school, reached into the round tin with his thumb and index finger,
pulled out a generous pinch of tobacco and inserted it between his
bottom teeth and lower lip. Minutes later, his stomach churned, and
he felt like vomiting. Two days later, he tried again, and felt
sick again.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 11 years ago. Today, San Francisco Giants reliever
John Johnstone, 29, is addicted to smokeless tobacco, also called
chewing tobacco or spit tobacco. And Johnstone has been diagnosed
with leukoplakia, a condition that, if not properly contained,
could lead to cancer of the mouth or throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stupid for doing it, no doubt about it,'' said Johnstone,
who goes through a half-can of Copenhagen-brand smokeless tobacco
each day. ``For 11 years, I've been doing it. I know the problems
that come with it, and that's what scares me. Definitely, I need to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to need help.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite baseball's ongoing campaign to reduce the use of
tobacco, an estimated 35 percent to 40 percent of big-leaguers are
users, of either the leaf variety that's packaged in bags or the
fine kind in round tins.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are a microcosm, with eight of their 25 players using
some form of smokeless tobacco _ including Robb Nen, who takes tiny
samples of leaf tobacco during batting practice, and Johnstone, who
dips constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Dusty Baker curbs his addiction by biting on toothpicks
during games, but two of his coaches are users. Baker still uses
smokeless tobacco, about a can a week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna quit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When?
</P>
<P>
   ``While I'm still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball prides itself on being aware of the problem and
assisting with a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling National Spit Tobacco Education Program (NSTEP),
which educates players and helps them curb or quit their habits,
has gained support from the owners and players' union. On Monday
night at Candlestick Park, NSTEP _ represented by ex-umpire Doug
Harvey, a cancer survivor and former spit tobacco user _ honored
the Giants organization for its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. John Greene, dean emeritus of the School of Dentistry at
the University of California at San Francisco, said there were too
few trained counselors for baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each team has an employee-assistance program, but most work
with drugs and alcohol, and few have experience in smokeless
tobacco,'' Greene said. ``We hope to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene has seen results. While examining players in spring
training as part of NSTEP, he detected a precancerous white lesion
in the mouth of pitcher Curt Schilling of the Philadelphia
Phillies. The lesion was removed in March, and Schilling gave up
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Of 141 players tested from nine teams, 83 had tissue damage
(leukoplakia), and 15 required biopsies. Greene estimated that half
of baseball's users had tobacco-related lesions, which can lead to
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen very little change in Major Leaguers dating back to
when we first started with the Giants,'' said Greene, who used the
Giants as a pilot team when he began his baseball-related research
in 1986. ``It's still running about 40 percent. But I am
encouraged. They're getting the message, which is more than what
they got in the early years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict a big decrease in the next two to three years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the Giants insist they don't officially supply tobacco
in the clubhouse, it's readily available and easy to find. Rolls of
tobacco tins are stored for any player to grab.
</P>
<P>
   Baker has tried alternatives. He used sunflower seeds, but he
quit because of the salt content and the fact that high blood
pressure runs in his family. He used bubble gum, but quit because
of its effects on teeth. He used sugarless gum, but disliked the
taste.
</P>
<P>
   The latest alternative is toothpicks. ``Toothpicks are the best
thing I could come up with,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Giants who use tobacco, two are relievers, two are
reserve outfielders, one is a backup infielder, and one is the
second-string catcher. It's a clear pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players with more idle time have a tendency to migrate to
habits,'' said Giants trainer Mark Letendre.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Barry Bonds started using smokeless tobacco as a
child and was hooked. He said he quit two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dipping when I was 13,'' Bonds said. ``I did it in high
school; I used to sleep with it. I just quit. No special reason.
Just don't need it. It wasn't hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the minor leagues, there is a ban on tobacco products. A
minor-leaguer caught with smokeless tobacco is fined $300, and his
manager also is docked $300.
</P>
<P>
   When minor-league catcher Doug Mirabelli was busted last season
in Triple-A ball, he paid his own fine plus the manager's.
Then-manager Ron Wotus, now the Giants' third-base coach, warned
his players that they'd also pay the manager's fine if they got
nabbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mirabelli was caught, he was sitting right next to me,''
Johnstone said. ``A guy with a pair of binoculars spotted him, and
that was it. You've got to make sure it's not seen at your locker,
in your pocket, anywhere. It could accidentally roll into your
locker, and you'd be to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1994 ban, studies show a decrease in use among minor
leaguers to 29 percent from nearly 40 percent, Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even that's disappointing,'' he said. ``It's banned, but
they're still using it. They use it in the back of their mouth, so
it's not seen. Or they use it away from the field. Umpires are
asked to police it, but some umpires use it, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
