<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks fall sharply. At 1:20 p.m., the Dow
industrials were down 199 points, Nasdaq down 50. Overseas, shares
declined 1.4 percent in Tokyo and 3.6 percent in Hong Kong. They
fell 3 percent in Frankfurt and 3 percent in London. At midday, the
long bond was up 26/32 point, with the yield at 5.57 percent. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   RATES-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ What the drop in rates (the yield on
the long bond is down to 5.57 percent) means for the consumer. By
Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ What next for the dollar-yen
rate? The yen has fallen further today, and that, combined with
continued worries about a Chinese devaluation, has pulled down
stocks worldwide. At midday, the dollar was quoted at 147.15 yen,
stronger than its level Monday afternoon of 146.15 yen. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   (See also JAPAN-ECON and INDONESIA-ECON, listed below.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other financial &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BP-AMACO (London) _ British Petroleum buys Amoco for about $48
billion in stock, creating the world's third-largest publicly
traded oil company. By Youssif M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   PAINE-DRESDNER (Undated) _ Folo on reports that Dresdner Bank is
in ``intensive'' talks to buy Paine Webber for as much as $10
billion. This is not the first time that speculation has developed
that Dresdner, possibly together with Allianz, which owns 22
pertent of the German bank, would make a bid for the Wall Street
firm.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD-EARNINGS (Undated) _ The outlook for Oxford Health, which
today reported a loss of $508 million in the second quarter. By
Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Perhaps the biggest threat to the yen is
the fact that ordinary Japanese in droves are starting to send
their cash abroad. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ECON (Undated) _ Indonesian debt developments. By
Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   GEOCITIES-IPO (New York) _ Geocities, the latest hot Internet
IPO, begins trading. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The judge presiding over
Microsoft suits will rule today as to whether the public may attend
normally private pre-trial questioning of Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly Business Travel column.
By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-INTERNET (Undated) _ Propelled by the soaring
popularity of the Internet, plus the shifting economics of health
care, the medical industry is rapidly going online. The Internet is
already a popular place to search for general information about
medicines and treatments, but many people are eager for more
personalized help. So a growing number of insurers and doctors are
providing personal medical information on the Internet to members
and patients. Doctors are making themselves available for questions
by e-mail. And some health plans provide interactive services that
tell a patient where the nearest plan doctor is. By Milt
Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
