<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Trading in Russian stocks was temporarily
halted today because of a sharp selloff by investors fearful that
the economy is not strong enough to withstand capital flight in
emerging markets. Investors fear that Russian markets in particular
are too feeble to withstand another onslaught of such selling. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-STONES (Moscow) _ The Rolling Stones are to have their
first concert in Moscow in 20 years. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-TALIBAN (New Delhi, India) _ The Islamic Taliban movement
captured a key northern provincial capital Tuesday in the latest of
a series of spectacular victories against opposition forces, and
Russia has accused Pakistani forces of being directly involved in
fighting there. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NUKE (Jerusalem) _ Bowing to American pressure, Israel
announced Tuesday that it would not block the next step in a U.N.
effort to draft an international treaty that would halt the
production of nuclear bomb-making material, but tempered its
announcement by making clear that it still had deep misgivings
about signing on to such a treaty itself. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Cerez, Yugoslavia) _ Refugee workers and aid
officials delivered aid for the first time here Tuesday, but they
feel they have too little of everything: food, personnel and
organization. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-U.N. (United Nations) _ Malaysia, which is expecting to
get a security council seat in the fall, is taking a cue from
Singapore and has perfected legal harrassment as a clean way to
destroy critics. The unusual case, involving the immunity of U.N.
officials, has wound up in the World Court. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
