<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-ACQUISITIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ERA OF CORPORATE MERGERS, SAN FRANCISCO FEELS THE SQUEEZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA and VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ First the phone company. Then the banks. Now,
the landmark Transamerica Pyramid. Quick, someone slap a lock on
the Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Many nationally known corporations based in San Francsico _
including BankAmerica Corp., Wells Fargo, Pacific Telesis Group,
Montgomery Securities Inc., Robertson Stephens Inc. and the Pacific
Exchange _ recently have been swallowed up in billion-dollar deals,
fueled by the merger and acquisition mania of the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Transamerica Corp. There's talk that the San Francisco
life insurer might be an acquisition target.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the corporate trysts, some San Francisco-based
companies are either packing up their headquarters, or being run by
a parent company in another city.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Antenore, a San Francisco planning commissioner, said the
long-term ramifications of these megamergers and acquisitions could
be costly to San Francisco's economy and workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the transfer of jobs and basic economic influence out
of the city. The more you remove the power to make decisions in a
place and have that power elsewhere, the more you're likely to have
bad decisions made that aren't in the interest of people living in
that place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica, which plans to merge with NationsBank Corp. in a
$64 billion deal that would create the country's largest banking
system, will move its executive suite to Charlotte, N.C., where
NationsBank is based.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how many BankAmerica jobs will be lost in San
Francisco, where the company employs 9,500 workers, but the merger
is expected to result in the loss of 5,000 to 8,000 jobs out of a
combined work force of 180,000 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Norwest of Minneapolis announced plans to acquire Wells
Fargo, the San Francisco-based bank, in a deal worth about $31
billion.
</P>
<P>
   At Pacific Telesis, the phone company's top-level executives
have been replaced by officers of SBC Communications, the San
Antonio-based telecommunications giant that acquired the San
Francisco Baby Bell for $17 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Brazer, managing partner of the San Francisco Partnership,
a privately funded economic development corporation that helps
attract businesses to the city, said a buyout of Transamerica Corp.
would be markedly less dramatic than the BankAmerica merger, mainly
because it would affect far fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   She added mergers often make good business sense for companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to mergers, companies have to pay attention to
their shareholders and what will give their shareholders better
value,'' Brazer said. ``For people in San Francisco the brand
identity lives on _ no matter who owns it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, mergers announced by corporations nationwide hit record
highs: 10,000 deals worth $845 billion, according to Securities
Data Co. in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Companies filed a record 3,702 merger notices last year with the
Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission, which must
sign off on all proposed deals over $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said the deals work out nicely for investors,
executives and financial advisers, but workers and consumers often
get slammed in the fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of employees lose their jobs as companies merge units and
slice the fat. And bigger companies can mean poorer service and
higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Federal Reserve study found that large multistate banks
charged higher service fees than smaller companies that did
business in only one state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
