<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8223 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-T     08-11 2461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-TATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALPH REED IS HIS CROSS TO BEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It's three minutes to air, and Randy Tate, head of the Christian
Coalition, is stuck in traffic on a Miami freeway, cheerfully
singing the toothbrushing song from ``Barney.'' (``While I'm
brushing my teeth and having so much fun, I never let the water
run. No, I never let the water run.'') He was to have been on a
morning radio show that reaches 15,000 Spanish-speaking
evangelicals _ folks the coalition desperately wants to enlist _
and his local organizer, who had insisted this drive would be just
a short hop, is on the cell phone begging the producer to let them
come anyway.
 &HT;    The answer is no, but Tate is perfectly pleasant about the lost
opportunity, just as he is later in the day when the same man makes
him so late for a lunch with some big-money donors that he can only
stay a few minutes before racing back to the airport.
 &HT;    The fact is, Tate is a perfectly pleasant guy. And no one would
tag him with the word critics so routinely applied to his intense
predecessor, Ralph Reed: scary. (You can't help thinking, on a day
spent hurtling nowhere, that Reed would never have put up with this
wasted motion.)
 &HT;    Back in Washington, Tate has often been seen as a little too
nice _ and not too effective. But after a year in the job, with
fall congressional elections just around the corner, he is trying
to change all that. And the centerpiece of his strategy seems to be
a lot of tough talk about homosexuals.
 &HT;    Tate was among the first to defend Trent Lott after the Senate
majority leader compared homosexuals to kleptomaniacs. He also
signed on to co-sponsor an ad campaign that says homosexuals can be
cured through religious faith. ``It wasn't a tough call,'' Tate
says.
 &HT;    While that effort has put the Christian Coalition back in the
news, it has also added to doubts about Tate, convincing his
critics that he is neither nice nor effective. Even Reed has said
that remarks like those Lott made are a big tactical mistake.
 &HT;    With that strategy, Reed has said, ``the Republican Party has
tripped over its own shoelaces and found itself on the defensive.''
In an interview in his tiny Capitol Hill office, Tate sighs and
says he doesn't really like talking about gay people.
 &HT;    ``Fifteen years ago, this wasn't an issue _ it isn't like we
decided to bring it up,'' he says, tossing an empty Coke bottle
into the air and catching it. ``Is there foam coming down the side
of my mouth?'' he cracks.
 &HT;    But he has been bringing it up plenty lately. After Lott said
homosexuality is a sin, Tate sent him an ``atta boy'' and went on
``Good Morning America'' opposite Rep. Barney Frank, the
Massachusetts Democrat who is gay, to complain that it was Lott who
had been the true target of bigotry, discriminated against for his
Christian views.
 &HT;    ``Senator Lott expressed his private religious views,'' Tate
explained on the show, ``and the White House referred to him as
extreme because he believed in the Bible. It's the religious
intolerance that really bothers me in this debate.''
 &HT;    Tate calls the ad campaign that followed ``a message of hope,
love and tolerance'' for homosexuals, but when asked, several
times, says no, he himself has not ever really known a gay person
very well: ``I've known people I've worked with that are. If you
work in Washington, D.C., you're going to run into all kinds of
people.''
 &HT;    Still, Tate insists it is the ``other side'' that forced the
issue by calling Lott's remarks ``backward.'' And there have been
other recent provocations, he says.
 &HT;    In May, President Clinton signed an executive order protecting
federal workers from job discrimination on the basis of sexual
orientation. Last October, Vice President Al Gore gave a speech
praising the now-long-gone TV show ``Ellen,'' whose star, Ellen
DeGeneres, received almost Seinfeld-level coverage when she and the
character she played announced their sexual preference for women.
 &HT;    ``We needed to speak out and the issue took off,'' Tate says.
``But when people say this is done to energize the base, I'd say
this is being pushed by Clinton to energize their base because
homosexuals are a key constituency.''
 &HT;    The head of the liberal People for the American Way, Carole
Shields, believes all this talk about the gay agenda will help Tate
raise some quick cash and turn out conservative voters _ as he
must, if he is to prove the group is still strong under the current
management. But she believes it will cost him in the long run as
the coalition tries to grow.
 &HT;    Moderates in the Republican Party agree. And even some
conservatives are skeptical. Rep. Steve Largent, a Christian
conservative from Oklahoma, says he has to wonder if the issue
hasn't been resurrected to fill a vacuum in a campaign season short
on substance.
 &HT;    ``I really oppose the homosexual agenda, but I think it's wrong
for political purposes to try to capitalize on that, and I'm not
saying the Christian Coalition is doing that,'' he says. ``But if I
were the Christian Coalition, the week after I ran those ads I
would also run an ad about how destructive adultery is to families.
I don't think there's a hierarchy of sin.''
 &HT;    Especially in recent years, Reed worked overtime to position the
coalition as squarely in the mainstream. Though Tate too insists
the coalition is in the mainstream, he was hired to reheat the old
rhetoric. And his biggest problem is Reed.
 &HT;    In his eight years with the Christian Coalition, Reed used
political instinct and media savvy to build the mailing list left
over from Pat Robertson's presidential run into the most important
lobbying group on the right. As his successor, Tate is probably
bound to feel constantly compared with the other guy and found
lacking. As Largent says, ``I'm not sure anybody could fill Ralph
Reed's shoes.''
 &HT;    In a way, nobody did. When Reed left the coalition a year ago to
start a political consulting business, Robertson split his old job
in two. First he hired Tate, now 32, a true-believing,
old-fashioned retail politician from Washington State who was
looking for work after losing his congressional seat.
 &HT;    Then Robertson paired Tate _ undercut him, some say _ with
Donald Hodel, a 63-year-old former Reagan energy and interior
secretary.
 &HT;    As Robertson says in a telephone interview: ``Randy's a
different kind of guy. Ralph is more analytical and cerebral in
terms of political strategy. They're both young and energetic and
dedicated, but Ralph is unique. He has a strategic mind that few
have.''
 &HT;    And Tate? Robertson mentions his youth, tempered by Hodel's
experience, and then says: ``He really is an extremely dedicated
person, to the Lord, his family and American and conservative
values. He's constantly up, always cheery, and it seemed he could
help mobilize the troops.''
 &HT;    Cheery? Seemed? Some conservatives wonder if Robertson didn't
also choose Tate in part because he wanted to take back some of the
power that Reed had assumed. ``I have in my own, quiet way,''
Robertson says, ``been setting the agenda for a long time.''
 &HT;    Robertson also notes that Reed left the organization with a few
challenges beyond wondering how his successors could possibly
measure up. Contributions had dropped off steeply, perhaps because
Reed had announced he was leaving. But as his old boss sees it,
``The direct mail wasn't good, the vendor was poor and Ralph was in
transition and not focusing.''
 &HT;    And though Tate never speaks other than respectfully of the act
he has had to follow, his chief spokesman, Arne Owens, says that
Tate and Hodel inherited some major problems after years of
phenomenal growth, the result in part of poor financial planning
and a comptroller who embezzled from the group.
 &HT;    Last year at this time, Owens says, the organization was $1.2
million in the red. ``Don and Randy took over and that's what they
were greeted with,'' Owens says. ``That's versus about $1 million
in the black now.''
 &HT;    (The normally ultra-accessible Reed returned the umpteenth phone
call left for him over several weeks on a Friday evening, very much
like someone who wants to leave a message rather than talk to the
person they are calling. When the call was answered, he passed on
the chance to talk on the record.)
 &HT;    Whatever the true state of the coalition's books, which have
always been closed except for the tiny peek provided by a
bare-bones annual report, Robertson's decision to give Tate only
half of Reed's old job was seen as more evidence that Tate is not a
player on Reed's level.
 &HT;    The plan was that Hodel would raise money and oversee finances
and Tate, who had found his calling to the political life as a
volunteer in Robertson's 1988 presidential bid, would serve as
chief lobbyist, spokesman and operational head.
 &HT;    And things do seem to have gone well for Tate on the local level
in the last year, with major wins in helping defeat an Oklahoma
casino expansion bill and a gay-rights referendum in Maine, where
the coalition distributed some 250,000 voter guides.
 &HT;    But the lobbying and quote-mongering aspects of the job have
clearly not been such an easy fit, in no small measure because Tate
has failed to pull off Reed's great trick of magnifying the
strength of both his grass roots and lobbying with more or less
constant media attention _ which brought in more money, which
strengthened the grass roots and lobbying, which got him more
attention and so on.
 &HT;    When Tate calls on former colleagues, there is none of the
menacing background music that seems to thrill official Washington,
no sense that if attention is not paid, he could tie up every phone
line of the Hill and go home laughing.
 &HT;    Tate has also been drowned out by other voices on the right as
more-camera-ready conservatives have scrambled to fill the
personality void left by Reed. Gary Bauer of the Family Research
Council has been so encouraged by the new windfall of attention
that he's talking about running for president. (Robertson advises
that he should ``go take a cold shower'' instead.)
 &HT;    Before his stroke in June, James Dobson, the Colorado religious
broadcaster whose radio program reaches millions, was the man to
see. He was seen as the one who brought the Republican leadership
around to the religious right's agenda this spring, when he
threatened to bolt the party if his people were not romanced with a
little more feeling. Soon, Gingrich and the rest were vowing to
make good on their old promises, swearing they would kill the
National Endowment for the Arts this time.
 &HT;    Tate is disarming in appearance, a 5-foot-8, prematurely bald
guy who has trouble keeping weight on. He says he has felt picked
on as a Christian from the day he first announced for the state
legislature at age 22. ``I had horns,'' he says.
 &HT;    He feels particularly vilified by the press, and in Chesapeake,
Va., at his group's style-free concrete headquarters, where no
visitor could conceivably accuse the coalition of wasting money on
amenities, the local paper, The Virginian-Pilot, is better known as
The Virginia Plot.
 &HT;    Tate's wife, Julie, who stays home with their two young children
and meets him enthusiastically at the door in the middle of a
workday _ ``You're staying here till dinner, right?'' _ says she
thinks stereotypes about Christians are the result of plain old
guilt. ``People don't like to think there's a right and a wrong, so
imagine how they feel about Randy. But truth is truth, whether you
believe it or not,'' she says, serving espresso and almond bread on
the patio out in back of their new home in a new subdivision.
 &HT;    Tate grew up in Puyallup, in the state he calls ``the real
Washington,'' the third of five children in a highly political and
extremely religious family. His ambition coming out of school was
maybe to start a construction business with a few friends, but his
mom talked him into continuing his education while working full
time.
 &HT;    He met his wife, who calls herself ``the helpmate,'' at age 17
on a blind date set up by another girl Randy had dated a few times.
They are alike, it is easy to see, and convinced that God wants
them right where they are. Their life together is ordered, with the
kids in bed every evening at 6:30.
 &HT;    ``It's hard sometimes,'' Julie Tate says, ``like when he went to
the White House Correspondents dinner. He's meeting Sharon Stone
and I'm scraping Cheerios off the floor in my jammies. But I have
to keep in mind that he gets to go to that dinner because I'm
taking care of his kids. It's important to be a team.'' She adds
that she never thought their team would be in and out of Congress
by the time they were in their early 30s.
 &HT;    In this job, Tate allows, ``the odds are against us. I've kind
of been an underdog my whole life.'' Still, he can't help sounding
like a really good salesman when he talks about the virtually
untapped market of religious conservatives who aren't even involved
in the political life _ yet. The coalition wants to sign up 100,000
new contacts in churches around the country by the year 2000, and
is recruiting them at a series of small coffees, with a teaching
video starring Tate.
 &HT;    This low-tech approach, ``water cooler politics,'' as he calls
it, obviously appeals to Tate, who seems happiest recalling the
mornings he spent as a candidate, standing on traffic medians in
the rain, waving at potential voters. It is possible that Tate's
tactics will prevail, that they will strengthen the coalition
around the country.
 &HT;    But in Washington, perception _ as measured in television
appearances and phone calls returned _ is power. And the perception
there is that Randy Tate, unlike his predecessor, does not quite
understand that.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Melinda Henneberger is a reporter in the Washington bureau of
The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
