<P>
   SCI-BALLOON-FOSSETT (Undated) _ Speeding along at more than 100
miles an hour, millionaire adventurer Steve Fossett on Tuesday
became the first balloonist to cross the South Atlantic Ocean. As
he passed the southern tip of Africa on his way eastward from
Argentina he passed the 5,000-mile mark _ one fifth of the distance
he will cover if he succeeds in becoming the first balloonist to
circle the world non-stop. Fossett began his journey last Friday
from Mendoza, Argentina, in his quest for ballooning glory and a
$1-million prize. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LATE-NIGHT-DINING (New York) _ New York has always had a
late-night subculture of 24-hour diners. But now, with a growing
number of affluent artists, entrepreneurs and Wall-Streeters
working long, hard hours, the city's high-end restaurateurs are
beginning to stay up late themselves, and offer serious food from
lamb shanks to caviar. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET-CORN (Undated) _ Now, at the peak of the sweet-corn
season, is when I get cranky; no matter how fresh and sweet the
corn at Greenmarkets and roadside stands, I can't find a single ear
of my grandfather's beloved Silver Queen. For 150 years, breeders
have experimented constantly with sweet corns to improve flavor,
texture, tenderness, appearance, growing time and hardiness. But
it's only in the last 20 years that corn engineers have rocketed
corn from sweet to sweeter to supersonic sweetness. Bio-engineering
has changed old-fashioned types like Silver Queen, now called
``normals,'' into sweeter types called ``sugar enhanced'' and
triply sweet types called ``supersweets.'' Bio-engineering is the
reason supersweet corn can be found in supermarkets year round _
and the reason Silver Queen can't be, even at the height of the
summer season. By Betty Fussell.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERMILK (Undated) _ There's no two ways about buttermilk:
either you love its tart creaminess, or you shudder at just a
glimpse of its cloudy film clinging to an empty glass. Buttermilk
is as thick and creamy as its name implies, but it actually has far
fewer calories and much less fat than whole or low-fat milk.
Originally this was so because it was just the thin liquid left
over when butter was made, the equivalent of the cheese maker's
whey. Today most dairies make buttermilk by culturing skim milk,
but it retains a tartness that perfectly accents the flavor of
sun-sweetened summer berries. By Richard W. Langer.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   CHARWOOD (Undated) _ Charwood, also called lump or chunk
charcoal, is made from Canadian sugar maple wood that is burned in
an oxygen-free kiln to remove the moisture and wood pollutants such
creosote and resins. The result is a clean high-dry heat that seals
in flavor very quickly. Every kind of meat and poultry I cooked had
a wonderful sweetness and was juicier than anything I had ever
tasted over briquets: chicken parts, whole chicken, steak,
tenderloin of beef, rack of lamb, pork tenderloin, salmon and
assorted vegetables. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   DRINKING-VINEGAR (Undated) _ Clustered on a silver tray in the
center of the elegant dining room at Seasons, the restaurant in the
Four Seasons Hotel in Chicago, are slender hand-blown flasks filled
with liquids in enticing tones of pale straw, amber, deep burgundy
and ruby red. Grappas? liqueurs? Guess again. The bottles are
filled with vinegars, and they are meant for sipping. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: At this time of year you
hear people say, ``Give me a good tomato and I eat it like an
apple.'' But no one actually does that, at least not more than a
couple of times a summer. Unlike peaches, whose raw glory can
barely be improved upon, tomatoes are all about potential. By Mark
Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Vegetable ragout.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   JOY-EATING-WELL Eating Well: Assessing the Institute of Food
Technology's criticisms of the new ``Joy of Cooking.'' By Marian
Burros.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ A good fino sherry or a manzanilla _ an
even more delicate-tasting sherry _ is one of life's secret joys. A
secret because most of us think the best sherries are dark and
sweet and that the pale, dry finos are inconsequential. Nothing
could be further from the truth. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A capsule review of Lambert Bridge
Merlot 1995, Sonoma County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food and dining. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ARTIST (Osnabruck, Germany) _ A German city honors one
