<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DROUGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PARCHED MEXICAN STATES, WATER BECOMES A RARE NECESSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photos available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANUEL, Mexico _ It has been more than three months since anyone
opened a faucet here with more than a passing expectation that
something wet would issue.
</P>
<P>
   Drained by nearly five years of El Nino-induced drought, the
stream-fed municipal water supply finally tapped out in early May.
</P>
<P>
   Now residents of Manuel must wait for state-supplied tanker
trucks to fill the municipal water tank every three or four days.
But they complain that one tank full lasts no more than a few hours
_ at best.
</P>
<P>
   Between tanker deliveries, they must buy expensive bottled water
or do without.
</P>
<P>
   ``That faucet is wide open, but it's been since yesterday that
anything came out of it,'' said Carmen Caraceles, pointing at the
faucet in the yard where she worked.
</P>
<P>
   Caraceles, 50, is no stranger to poverty. She moved here three
years ago from Gonzalez, a truck stop nine miles up the
black-asphalt road snaking across the coastal plain of the state of
Tamaulipas, the traditional trade route between Monterrey and the
port of Tampico on the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Her borrowed house has windows, but nothing to cover them; an
electric meter outside, but nothing electric inside; and no water
faucet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go around with the few little water bottles I have
asking people to give me water to drink,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Caraceles makes her living washing other people's clothes here
in Manuel, a task made more difficult by the water shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost days of work because there was no water to wash
with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury, households in Manuel have continued to
receive their monthly water bills from the municipal water company,
said Consuelo Garcia Torres, 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are charging us for air,'' Garcia complained.
</P>
<P>
   Weather scientists hope this is the end of the El Nino weather
phenomenon, which has hit Mexico, Central America and other areas
particularly hard this year. Even normally lush jungles dried up
and then caught fire as peasants burned fields for spring planting.
</P>
<P>
   Thick smoke from the fires blew north this spring, blanketing
portions of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But in most areas, seasonal rains finally returned, dousing the
fires and turning the countryside green.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, that is, but the northeastern states of Tamaulipas,
Nuevo Leon and Coahuila.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the last sector of the country that hasn't had normal
rains,'' Jorge Zertuche Rodriguez, Tamaulipas' secretary of
agricultural development, said in an interview in Ciudad Victoria,
the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Dams and reservoirs throughout the three states are at an
average of only 16 percent of their capacity, he said. No one is
unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   Monterrey, an urban sprawl of 3.5 million people in Nuevo Leon,
is shutting off municipal mains between 10 p.m. and 4 a.m. in an
effort to save water.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers are thinning already thin herds, while growers are
planting drought-resistant, short-seasoned crops when they are
planting at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we predicted a spring grain harvest of 1.1 million
metric tons. We actually cut 300,000 metric tons,'' Zertuche said.
</P>
<P>
   In normal years, the towering peaks of the Sierra Madre Oriental
spear the moist clouds driven inland from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The swift, clear streams and rivers flowing down from mountain
canyons irrigate thousands of acres of orange and grapefruit
orchards. But now, with some rivers dry, the citrus industry is
headed for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we cut early and got a good crop, but without water,
there won't be much this year,'' Zertuche said. ``Some growers are
telling me that their trees are starting to die.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in parts of the thirsty American Southwest, water is often an
explosive political issue.
</P>
<P>
   Tamaulipas Gov. Manuel Cavazos Lerma has clashed repeatedly with
Nuevo Leon political officials over the distribution of water from
Nuevo Leon's huge El Cuchillo Dam.
</P>
<P>
   Built in the early 1990s to ensure Monterrey's drinking water
needs, it cut off the flow from the Santa Catarina and Rio San Juan
rivers into neighboring Tamaulipas, where farmers depended on it to
irrigate corn, sorghum and cotton fields. Although scientists
predicted near-normal rains between August and November, Zertuche
said they won't help much.
</P>
<P>
   Like a dry sponge, the bone-dry soil will soak up normal
rainfall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get normal rainfall, those people who dry-farm sorghum
and corn will probably make a crop, but those who depend on
irrigation from reservoir water will not benefit because the dams
will not fill up,'' he said. ``To do that, we need a hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Water and agricultural officials in the three states are
scrambling to supplement the dwindling water supplies. Bigger,
deeper, larger are the methods used to capture and store water. But
without rain, the race is being lost.
</P>
<P>
   State workers are building tanks for cattle and drilling new
wells to fill them. But as soon as wells are drilled, the falling
water table exceeds their reach, and so thousands of wells are
being redrilled and refitted for larger capacity.
</P>
<P>
   In communities like Manuel, the water sources have either slowed
or disappeared altogether. And so the states are now trucking water
to thirsty residents.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, 40 tanker loads of water _ 100,000 gallons _ are being
sent to nine communities throughout Tamaulipas, said Jose Hernandez
Cuesta, assistant director of administrative systems for the state
water commission.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the worries and many of the ambitious projects and
plans generated by politicians and engineers is the belief that
people can resolve the region's water problems.
</P>
<P>
   Within limits, that is true, Zertuche said.
</P>
<P>
   But a report from Tamaulipas to federal water officials this
spring suggested that even the optimists know that no matter how
fine it is sliced and distributed, water is not created by people.
</P>
<P>
   After a rundown of state programs initiated to deal with the
water problems, the report concluded by first calling for the
promotion of a water-saving culture among Tamaulipas residents.
</P>
<P>
   The second simply advocated ``hoping that the normal rain cycles
return and that the dams fill up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
