<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8253 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DIRTY-TRICKS-     08-11 2754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DIRTY-TRICKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING UP DIRT ON PRESIDENT CLINTON'S ENEMIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By DAVID SAMUELS  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    In Washington, tennis is something of a ritual sport. And of all
the hardened Beltway competitors at the St. Albans Tennis Club,
from Jack Valenti to Vernon Jordan to Strobe Talbott, not one is
more famous for his flat-out desire to win than the middle-aged man
on court No. 8 serving this morning, down two games to one.
 &HT;    Facing the net, he fiddles with his glasses, then squares his
shoulders like a football lineman. He tosses the ball in the air,
grunts as he serves, rushes the net, then grimaces as the ball
whizzes by him.
 &HT;    ``Did you see him scamper?'' asks his opponent, Timothy Wirth,
the former senator from Colorado. ``It's nice to see him scamper
like that.''
 &HT;    Wirth looks like a senator, the one that Robert Redford played
in ``The Candidate,'' with aging good looks and a penumbra of
slightly fuzzy charm. He likes looking good on the court.
 &HT;    His opponent, Terry Lenzner, doesn't much care how he looks. The
object of his game is to win. When he hits his next serve long, his
eyes narrow.
 &HT;    ``Want to change the rules, Lenzner?'' Wirth asks.
 &HT;    Whether Lenzner plays by the rules is the subject of much
high-powered speculation in Washington these days. As the private
investigator hired by President Clinton's lawyers, Lenzner is a
front-line soldier in a new kind of war, in which embarrassing
information about political and legal opponents is provided for use
as ammunition in today's partisan culture of scandal.
 &HT;    Within the past year, Lenzner has testified before a Senate
committee about the president's legal-defense fund and, most
recently, before the grand jury of the independent counsel, Kenneth
Starr, about his activities on behalf of the president's lawyers.
 &HT;    It's a far cry from the young lawyer who sat at Sam Ervin's
elbow during the Senate Watergate hearings 25 years ago. In recent
months, the New York Times columnist William Safire has called
Lenzner a ``big bully'' for his aggressive style, while Safire's
colleague Frank Rich referred to him as a ``creep'' for
investigating the tobacco company whistle-blower Jeffrey Wigand.
 &HT;    ``To hire plumbers, to affect the trials of people through
adverse publicity, that's wrong,'' says Ronald Rotunda, a professor
of law at the University of Illinois who served with Lenzner on the
Senate Watergate committee and is currently a special consultant to
Starr. ``Assuming that it was all legal, and people weren't bribed
somewhere along the way, I still think it is wrong.''
 &HT;    Citing what he believes to be a deliberate tactic of digging up
dirt on the president's accusers, such as Paula Jones, and then
leaking it to the press, he adds, ``For Terry to be involved in
this is sad and appalling.''
 &HT;    Yet what Lenzner has actually done (or not done) for the
president remains a mystery. After a long series of denials,
half-denials and evasions, the president's lawyers, David E.
Kendall and Robert S. Bennett, admitted in a news release dated
Feb. 24, 1998, to having employed Lenzner and his company,
Investigative Group International (IGI), since 1994.
 &HT;    ``It is common for private counsel to retain commercial
investigative services to perform legal and appropriate tasks in
the defense of a client,'' they stated.
 &HT;    Dick Morris, the former Clinton strategist (and no stranger to
hyperbole), puts it a different way: He calls Lenzner the head of
``the White House secret police.''
 &HT;    Lenzner's activities _ at least now _ may not be quite as
extensive as many published reports have implied, according to a
prominent source close to the president's legal defense. The source
says that IGI has performed a variety of legal-defense-related
tasks, not all of them publicly reported, including digging up
information on Paula Jones' sexual history through interviews and
public-record searches, tracing the financing of the anti-Clinton
network surrounding the millionaire publisher Richard Mellon Scaife
and compiling public-record dossiers on ``likely courtroom
opponents'' _ presumably including the independent counsel.
 &HT;    This is, at first glance, strange work for a man who helped
solve the murders of three civil-rights workers in Philadelphia,
Miss., in 1964 (the ``Mississippi Burning'' case), who headed the
Office of Legal Services in 1970 and who slapped a subpoena on
Richard Nixon in 1974 as assistant chief counsel to the Senate
Watergate committee. If this sounds like the resume of a
soft-boiled idealist, however, Lenzner would be the first to set
you straight. He is not interested in ideals. He is interested in
facts.
 &HT;    Since 1984, when he founded a small investigative group with a
staff of three, Lenzner's empire _ his own private FBI _ has grown
to include nearly 100 full-time investigators working out of the
Washington headquarters of Investigative Group International, as
well as field offices in Los Angeles, New York, Boston, Chicago,
Seattle, San Francisco and London.
 &HT;    Among IGI's investigators are lawyers from some of the better
law firms in the country, as well as former police detectives and
FBI, CIA and DEA agents, reporters and news producers from ABC, NBC
and CBS. Raymond Kelly, now an under-secretary of the treasury
department, is a former IGI investigator, as is Brooke Shearer, now
at the Interior Department.
 &HT;    ``One of the real pleasures of this job, to me, is that I get to
deal with people that I've worked with for the last 25 years,''
says Larry Potts, a former deputy director of the FBI who now runs
IGI's worldwide operations. ``I get to work with people who left
the Bureau and became directors of security. I get to work with
former United States attorneys. I mean, to me, it's like being at
home. You're just working with the same folks you've always worked
with.''
 &HT;    If this morning's case meeting at IGI is not entirely
representative of the company's clientele (usually Fortune 500
corporations, high-tech firms, investment banks, law firms and
prominent politicians of both parties), it is a good example of how
the company does its work.
 &HT;    Seated around the long table in the conference room, with two
Robert Motherwell-like abstractions on the walls and a pair of
faceless Kabuki dolls on either side of the door, are two IGI
investigators and a freshly showered Lenzner. This morning's client
is Robert Nixon, who represents a Washington environmental group
and has agreed to the presence of a reporter.
 &HT;    The group wants IGI to look into a complicated real-estate deal
related to a mysterious London-based contessa, Bina Sella di
Monteluce, who has reportedly spent $11 million to persuade
Congress, the Interior Department and the District of Columbia City
Council to allow her to build an ``educational theme park'' on
national parkland in the Anacostia River.
 &HT;    In 1996, Congress passed a bill transferring the land _ now
known as Children's Island _ from the National Park Service to the
District of Columbia. Nixon explains that last December the City
Council voted to approve the contessa's lease, which included a
99-year term, plus a number of other sweetheart provisions. The
contessa's lobbyists, Nixon continues, include close associates of
Washington's mayor, Marion Barry.
 &HT;    ``We need to pull registration statements on all the lawyers,''
says Margot Critchfield, a former NBC news producer. ``There should
be an IRS Form 990 that has to be filed. That's one of the few tax
forms that's open to inspection.''
 &HT;    Lenzner is getting more excited. ``There's money moving
around,'' he says, tugging on his black-framed Nixon-era glasses
and slowly massaging the knuckle of the ring finger on his right
hand. ``There's legislation being introduced. There's Interior
Department movement.''
 &HT;    As he talks, I notice that the knuckle is swollen to two or
three times the normal size and that his ring finger is bent at a
distinct angle. It is an old football injury that never healed
right, and it gives him a slightly dangerous, back-alley look,
thoroughly in keeping with his broad shoulders and powerful hands.
With his glasses off, however, his eyes look surprisingly soft and
a little sad.
 &HT;    ``The ultimate question here,'' he says a moment later, ``is
what we can do with these facts to stop the development from
proceeding. Because getting the facts is only going to be helpful
if they meet some larger goal. There could be a PR strategy here.
There could be a legal strategy.''
 &HT;    This is the stuff of which politicians' nightmares are made. The
initial trace of the backgrounds and holdings of the people
involved in the project _ information such as their names,
addresses, dates of birth, Social Security numbers, the make and
the value of the cars they own, the value of the mortgages on their
homes, any federal political contributions they may have made, as
well as any mention of their activities in the news media _
involves little more than the press of a button.
 &HT;    ``Try the dentist,'' says Robert Walters, a former newspaper
reporter and syndicated columnist, referring to a man whose name
appears on the Children's Island corporation documents. ``I'm
fascinated by him.''
 &HT;    Connie Manwell, IGI's resident Washington information
specialist, taps a few keys on her computer and waits for the
information to download. The information services that IGI uses are
all commercially available. They include news and legal databases,
such as Dow Jones, Lexis-Nexis and Pacer, commonly used by
reporters and law firms.
 &HT;    They also include a service called Auto Track, which finds
current and previous addresses, allowing investigators to interview
neighbors, and which connects people to cars and property,
bankruptcy records and professional licenses. Another tool is CDB
Infotech, which provides financial information on individuals,
including the value and source of current mortgages and loans. And
there is more.
 &HT;    ``Some states will sell you driver's license information,''
Manwell explains, as she waits for the dentist's Auto Track file to
load, ''including your address, Social Security number, your
height, weight and the color of your eyes. Nearly anything you can
imagine is out there, including the illegal stuff, like your
medical records, credit-card bills, bank balances and the rest. We
don't touch it, but it's there.''
 &HT;    As the Children's Island investigation enters its initial phase,
Lenzner sits in his office and takes calls, his shoulders slightly
hunched, his attention tightly centered on the phone, as if he were
inhaling something vital from the receiver.
 &HT;    Scattered around his office are the big-game trophies of his
investigative career: the famous Nixon subpoena and a banner
headline, ``Alaska Wins, Oil Companies Lose,'' as well as a framed
picture of himself as the Harvard football captain, No. 60, making
a flying tackle of a quarterback from Yale.
 &HT;    On the other end of the line is Terrence Burke, a highly
decorated former CIA officer and onetime acting director of the DEA
who now runs IGI's foreign operations. Burke's active case file,
displayed on the screen on Lenzner's desk, reveals the company's
bread-and-butter casework: investigations into bid-rigging,
bribery, high-tech theft, counterfeiting and other possible crimes
in Egypt, Bangladesh, Singapore, China, Malaysia, Norway, Kuwait,
England, Chile, Macedonia, Serbia and Montenegro. Fees range from
several thousand dollars for a simple inquiry to hundreds of
thousands of dollars for a complex case.
 &HT;    IGI's ability to combine powerful computer technology with the
field experience of investigators such as Burke represents a
quantum leap over the gumshoe methods of a Philip Marlowe or Sam
Spade. It can also cause a great deal of trouble if you happen to
be the target of the investigation.
 &HT;    The Wigand investigation, conducted by IGI's New York office
under the direction of Ray Kelly, a former New York City police
commissioner, along with investigators not hired by IGI,
illustrates just how nasty this kind of work can get. Documents
portraying Wigand as a liar, shoplifter and wife-beater were leaked
to The Wall Street Journal, which published the allegations in
1996. While the documents were real, the accusations they were
intended to support were ultimately shown to be without substantial
basis in fact.
 &HT;    In Lenzner's opinion, however, the Wigand case could just as
easily have gone the other way. What if Wigand was a liar? What if
the tobacco company was right? ``I'm not quick to make moral
objections about people,'' he says. ``What drew me to Mississippi,
I'm going to be candid with you _ I had no moral compulsion to go
down there and save the world.''
 &HT;    It is this ability to see the world in dispassionate shades of
gray, without making assumptions, he says, that makes him a good
investigator. ``What you need to do is to think about what's going
on, understand it and learn more about it. And if you think about
it, that's what the civil liberties stuff was about. That's what
Watergate was about. I enjoy asking questions and getting
answers.''
 &HT;    Our conversation about his work for President Clinton takes
place during a two-hour interview, which I am not allowed to
record. It is an interesting performance, a display of toughness, a
chance to answer his critics and, most of all, to let off steam
after four years of rumors and half-truths.
 &HT;    He describes his February appearance before the grand jury with
a combativeness that echoes the most recent pronouncements by White
House sources.
 &HT;    ``I spent a lot of my time making eye contact with the grand
jury members,'' he says. ``And before I left, I told them that I
would be happy to see them again, but to please call me at my
office and not to send two FBI agents to my house with a
subpoena.''
 &HT;    When it comes to the questions asked by the special prosecutor
Jackie Bennett, Lenzner is unusually specific. ``They wanted to
know if I knew Sidney Blumenthal,'' he says. ``And I told them
that, yes, I do know Sid Blumenthal. I just met him 10 minutes ago
outside. And they wanted to know if I had ever investigated Ken
Starr, and whether I had ever conducted an investigation of the
other prosecutors. They seemed most interested in whether or not I
had investigated them. They also asked me, `When was the last time
you reported to the president?' And I told them that I've never met
the president, and I've never talked to him in my life.''
 &HT;    Asked if he is proud of the work that he did for the president,
however, Lenzner's answer is surprisingly ambivalent. ``The overall
answer is yes,'' he says. ``But I include in that the work we have
done for the DNC, as well as the Paula Jones case and other matters
in which we have been involved.''
 &HT;    What is most surprising is how normal Lenzner makes all this
sound. If Lenzner's rise tells us anything about the scandal wars
of the '90s, it may be that the power once held by J. Edgar Hoover
_ someone who worked behind the scenes, who knew all the secrets
and exerted enormous influence on public affairs _ has passed into
the hands of private men.
 &HT;    ``There's something satisfying about walking around with a
reserve bank of information that nobody else has, or few people
have,'' Lenzner says.
 &HT;    ``With an understanding of things that go on inside companies
and universities and charities and governments. But I never would
have had that chance if I hadn't become what I have become. And I
love that part. I'll be frank with you on that.''
 &HT;     c.1998 David Samuels  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (David Samuels is a contributing editor at Harper's magazine.) &LR;
</P>
