<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0812-C     08-11 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN MARKETS TUMBLE ON CONCERNS OVER GOVERNMENT CRISIS PLAN
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Shaken by losses on Asian and European markets,
Russia's battered financial markets plunged again Tuesday,
prompting trade on the Moscow exchange to be temporarily suspended.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, Russia's main stock market index had fallen 11.8
percent on panic selling driven by fresh concerns that the
government will not be able to avoid a potentially ruinous
devaluation of the nation's currency, the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Trading resumed after a 45-minute halt, and the market ended the
day down 9.1 percent to its lowest level since May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Khristiyenko
sought to reassure investors: ``Russia's default in not on the
day's agenda. It is not an issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's formerly robust market was hailed by investors
throughout 1997 on a breathtaking surge that ended late last year
at the onset of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The problems in Russia deepened in May, with steep losses in the
markets, prompting the International Monetary Fund and others to
assemble a $22.6 billion bailout package. The package was designed
to restore investor confidence and buy time for President Boris
Yeltsin's government to enact badly needed economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Russia received a $300 million loan on
Monday from the World Bank. But it was not enough to stem the
latest declines in stocks and bonds, which began late last week and
dealt a blow to government efforts to pull Russia out of its budget
mess.
</P>
<P>
   The sell-off is part of a worldwide trend as nervous investors
retreat from high-risk emerging markets like Russia's.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble has remained relatively stable throughout Russia's
financial troubles, trading at about 6.2 to the dollar, and thus
most Russians -- whose average monthly salary equals only about
$200 a month -- have been unaffected by the market turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   However, investors fear that the Russian government will be
unable to substantially increase its tax collections and reduce its
borrowing to provide enough cash for $20 billion in debt payments
to foreign banks due this year.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank has had to dip into already low foreign
currency reserves to make interest payments and bolster the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The foremost problem facing Russia is the inability of its
government to collect billions of dollars in unpaid taxes.
Yeltsin's government will ask parliament to approve seven new
measures at a special legislative session next week.
</P>
<P>
   But the lower house, the Duma, dominated by the Communist Party,
rejected a portion of the government's austerity program last month
that sought to raise taxes and will likely do the same next week,
Alexander Zhukov, chairman of the budget committee told the
ITAR-Tass new agency.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
