<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MINKS-0812-CO     08-11 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MINKS-0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THEY'RE VICIOUS! THEY'RE HORRIBLE? THEY'RE MINKS?
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A band of vicious killers is stalking English farms and
forests in a relentless search for blood.
</P>
<P>
   Minks. Thousands of them, suddenly free and hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, animal rights activists ``liberated'' as many
as 6,000 of the luxuriously coated predators from a fur farm in
Hampshire, near the English coast. Free from their cages, the
ill-tempered little carnivores have been doing what comes naturally
_ killing and maiming. Minks, which are related to weasels, will
eat smaller animals and attack larger ones. An unidentified
Chihuahua was reported by The Independent newspaper to be among the
first victims.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the situation, Hampshire authorities have set up a
24-hour hotline center to handle calls about marauding minks. They
are warning residents to protect their pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we have had a number pets _ particularly
rabbits and ducks _ that have been killed,'' Hampshire official
Anne Righton gravely told BBC television. ``A number of dogs have
been bitten or attacked by the minks. We are again urging the
public to secure their pets.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   For Bruce Berry, the director of the New Forest Owl Sanctuary,
it has been a nightmare. Sunday morning, Berry discovered the body
of a rare tawny owl with its head surgically removed, presumably by
a rampaging mink.
</P>
<P>
   Berry has taken up arms, and was shown in The Express holding
the owl's mangled body in one gloved hand and a dead mink he shot
in the other. ``I will shoot any mink on sight,'' he told the
newspaper. ``They are nothing but a pest species and there is
nothing else you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Even animal rights activists expressed alarm at the release of
so many of the animals into an alien environment, where they may
breed and permanently alter the natural balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we are not crazy about minks being kept on farms,
releasing them into the wild is totally irresponsible,'' said Rob
Dazely, the regional manager for the Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Harris, a wild animal expert from the University of
Bristol, believes the public and press are being unfair to the
minks. ``The point about minks is that they are constantly being
described as sadists who kill for pleasure,'' Harris said. ``But
they are only trying to look out for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
