<SLUG> BC-WOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDANGERED WOLF APPARENTLY KILLED BY MOUNTAIN LION 
</HEADLINE>
 KILLED-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA and STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Another endangered Mexican gray wolf, one of 11
released into the wild in eastern Arizona this spring, is dead
after an apparent battle with a mountain lion over food.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists and conservationists are lamenting the death of the
female wolf, which earlier this year gave birth to the first
Mexican gray wolf born in the American wilderness in half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   Now, only seven wolves, including the pup, are roaming free in
the Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest under the watch of U.S. Fish
and Wildlife agents who hope to repopulate the species.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a wolf was shot and killed by a retired postal worker
who said he fired at it out of fear for himself and his family when
it approached their campsite.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities decided not to prosecute Richard Humphrey of Tucson
and are standing by their conclusion that he acted in self-defense,
a Fish and Wildlife spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, investigators are confident that nature is
responsible for the latest wolf death.
</P>
<P>
   ``This incident, while unfortunate, is certainly nature at
work,'' said Tom Bauer, a spokesman with Fish and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists monitoring the wolves were alerted to the death
Friday by a citizen who saw the animal lying not far from a gravel
Forest Service road just south of Williams Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wolf had a bite-sized piece missing from its shoulder and
had bled profusely. It appears she probably had an encounter with a
mountain lion over prey,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators reached the conclusion after finding an elk calf
carcass just 5 yards from the body of the wolf. However, the wolf's
body was shipped to the National Forensics Laboratory in Ashland,
Ore., for a necropsy to determine the official cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the wolves set free under the conservation
program, the wolf killed was born and raised in captivity. The
mother wolf was born four years ago at the Binder Park Zoo in
Battle Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer noted that the program is an experiment that requires the
wolves to adapt to the wild and acquire survival skills they never
needed in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until she was released into the wild, I doubt she'd ever seen
an elk, so I doubt if she'd seen a mountain lion either,'' Bauer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, who have debated whether the wolves will be
capable of surviving in the wild, also are divided about what the
death means for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad and it's a setback and it's hugely unfortunate that
it happened to the mother of the pup, but . . . it certainly
doesn't signal the failure of the reintroduction,'' said Craig
Miller, a representative of Defenders of Wildlife, a national
conservation group.
</P>
<P>
   Other environmentalists, however, are concerned for the safety
of the remaining wolves and are pushing for a reopening into the
April wolf shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program is falling short of what it could be,'' said Shane
Jimerfield, assistant director of the Southwest Center for
Biological Diversity in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and biologists alike are united in hopes
that the pup will survive now with only one parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pup was born about May and had been weaned and was eating
solid food before this incident,'' Bauer said. After the death,
investigators saw the surviving mate return to the site and drag
the elk carcass back to the pup where both fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to increase our monitoring of our male and the
pup, but we will not attempt to capture and relocate them,'' Bauer
said. &QL; 
Graciela Sevilla can be reached at grace.sevilla(at)pni.com via
e-mail. Steve Yozwiak can be reached at steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
