<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ Prosecutors question
presidential friend and Hollywood producer Harry Thomason before a
grand jury investigating Bill Clinton's relationship with a former
White House intern. Also summoned before the grand jury were a
White House lawyer and several Secret Service officials. By JOHN C.
HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-SCAMS (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission is
advising investors to be wary of money-making opportunities that
use the glamour of movies and television. In one case, the FTC is
taking action against a company that raised $12 million by telling
investors they would profit from an informational commercial
touting Elvis Presley memorabilia. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CALIFORNIA (San Bruno, Calif.) _ President Clinton takes
a break from fund-raising duties in California to promote an
Environmental Protection Agency ruling that requires water
companies to keep consumers informed about the quality of drinking
water. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SHOOTING (Laredo, Texas) _ The family of Esequiel
Hernandez Jr., the young Texan who was killed by a Marine on an
anti-drug patrol, has accepted a $1.9 million settlement from the
Marine Corps. The family had filed a wrongful death lawsuit in
federal court after the fatal shooting, which occurred 15 months
ago. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Congress is worried that impeachment
hearings against President Clinton could backfire. So the idea of
censuring him instead is being floated: If the Monica Lewinsky
allegations appear true, he would be reprimanded for immoral
conduct but remain in office. It is not clear how this would work,
however, since only one president, Andrew Jackson more than 160
years ago, has ever come close to being censured. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
