<HEADLINE>
CONTEST: GOD'S WOES USING A PC FOR CREATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - What if God used a computer to create the universe?
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking about that since my way-cool neighbors, Rick
and Jacquie, brought over a humorous posting they found online.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know who wrote it, but it's all about how God tries to
create the universe with a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by problems at the DOS prompt, including the dreaded
``Abort-Retry-Fail'' error message, God finally goes out and buys a
Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Funny.
</P>
<P>
   It would explain a lot, though:
</P>
<P>
   - The Big Bang? No more mystery there. That was simply the first
recorded use of Pkunzip, the popular decompression software.
</P>
<P>
   - The difference between Mars and Earth? Turns out The Almighty
was testing a shareware program, Galaxy Lite, when he made Mars.
But he upgraded to Galaxy Pro before he made Earth.
</P>
<P>
   - Can't button your jeans anymore? God loaded Windows 98 and
switched to the FAT32 storage system. Now everything on Earth has
to fit into a smaller space.
</P>
<P>
   Got some examples of your own? Let's have a contest!
</P>
<P>
   Send me your best stuff. We'll collect entries for a few days,
then we'll publish the funniest and most interesting here.
</P>
<P>
   I'll award free software to the top three winners.
</P>
<P>
   Send your entries via e-mail to computing(at)azcentral.com by
Aug. 19. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
PC news to use &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a student heading to school? Then you may be in the market
for a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   Every year at this time, parents go through the same agony.
Should they buy new or used? Should they buy a PC or a Macintosh?
Should they buy retail or mail order?
</P>
<P>
   The options are even more confusing this season, as Apple
Computer prepares to market its new iMac and as the sub-$1,000 PC
market has mushroomed.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac, with its cool shape and translucent blue case, is
expected to be a hot seller at about $1,200. It's compact, fast and
genuinely interesting _ just the machine your student might need
for the dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, PCs still dominate the market. The only
problem with going the PC route is choosing the right machine.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two suggestions if you are in the market:
</P>
<P>
   - Check Arizona Central's PC Page. We have a new story online
about how to choose a computer. It's complete with tips and links
to other online resources. Find the story at www.azcentral.com/com &QL; 
puting/news/pc/index.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   - Check the Sept. 1 edition of ``PC`` magazine. It's got a great
article on PCs that cost less than $1,000. The magazine tested 37
models, and rated each for things like reliability and value.
</P>
<P>
   While sub-$1,000 machines might not offer cutting-edge
components, they are not exactly junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``PC'' magazine points out that buy ers can expect such low-end
machines to contain Pentium II processors, 3- or 4-gigabyte hard
drives, 4 megabytes of video RAM and 32-speed CD-ROM drives. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
Password: h-e-a-d-a-c-h-e &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Passwords are required everywhere these days _ the ATM, your
Internet account, logging on to your computer at work, unlocking
the keypad of your cellular telephone . . . the list goes on and
on.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual to find someone with five or more passwords.
Charlie Pabst, a summer intern at Arizona Central, claims to have
10 passwords he uses regularly.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to find advice on how to create passwords. Generally,
they should be six to eight characters long and include a random
mixture of letters (upper and lower case) and numbers. They
shouldn't be actual words, because passwords that contain words or
word combinations are easy to crack. And you should change your
passwords every three months or so.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you remember passwords? Now that's my problem. I've
got a copy of Microsoft's Front Page 98 on my computer at home. But
I can't use it because I've forgotten the darned password. (I'm
sure there's a solution, but I haven't had time to worry about it.)
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do? Do you write them down somewhere? Scratch
them into the paint under your desk? Carry them around in your
wallet? Or do you just have a great memory?
</P>
<P>
   Send in your suggestions for remembering passwords to
dhoye(at)pni.com, and I'll share the best with everybody. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
Be a part of history &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you once work on Eniac, the world's first large-scale
computer?
</P>
<P>
   Did you participate in the research and development of the first
microprocessor?
</P>
<P>
   Did you once own a TRS-80, an Amiga, an Acorn, an Apple II or a
PET?
</P>
<P>
   Have you been using computers all your life, and are you full of
interesting stories about the many makes and models you've gone
through?
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'll stop asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the gig: We're looking for computer users of all ages and
backgrounds to help us with a special online project.
</P>
<P>
   Without letting the cat out of the bag, we can say we are
interested in talking to people with stories or experiences to
share about the computers in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if you still own the machine or whether you
are working or retired or a student. If you can tell us a story or
two about a particular computer, let us know!
</P>
<P>
   Send a brief note to dhoye(at)pni.com, or call (602) 444-4462. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye is an online editor and covers computer- and
Internet-related issues for Arizona Central, the Web site of The
Arizona Republic. He can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
