<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNWARY AMERICANS JAILED IN MEXICO OVER GUNS, AMMO 
</HEADLINE>
 JAIL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Perhaps they missed the signs this side of the border,
warning travelers against carting guns and ammunition into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they thought they'd get away with it. Or perhaps they
didn't care.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, 29 Americans are jailed in Sonora, Mexico,
for violating Mexico's strict gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   The latest, a Scottsdale businessman, has been in a Nogales,
Sonora, jail for three weeks since Mexican customs officials found
ammunition and a pistol case in his vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   James Brunen, 45, went to Mexico on July 23 to buy some pots as
a gift for a relative and simply forgot he had the cartridges, his
wife, Merry Brunen, said Monday. When he realized the ammunition
was in the back of his vehicle, he alerted customs officials. But
it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   The blunder, his wife said, landed him in the middle of his
worst nightmare: a filthy holding cell with 46 other men, many
suffering from hepatitis. There are 20 cots and dozens of rats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a cage that didn't have a chair, a bed, a sink or a
toilet and it was flooded with backed-up sewage,'' Merry Brunen
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story U.S. State Department and Mexican officials call
all too familiar since Mexican authorities began enforcing a
federal law that forbids U.S. citizens from taking firearms or
ammunition into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying even a single round of ammunition into Mexico can carry
a penalty of up to five years in jail, even if it is taken in
unintentionally.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; At least 29 Americans are incarcerated in Sonora for firearms
violations committed during the first half of the year. And an
increasing number of Americans are getting nabbed along the
U.S.-Mexico border nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about these cases about visitors who
don't know the Mexican law,'' said Miguel Angel Isidro, acting
consul general of Mexico in Phoenix. ``This is a law that applies
to everybody in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department issued a warning last week to inform
travelers of the firearm restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Where little was heard about gun arrests in the 1980s, Mexico
has stepped up enforcement of its 1972 munitions law over the past
three years, amid concerns that smuggled arms have been used in
rebel uprisings, assassinations and drug wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for people to understand that we cannot bail
them out and the long arm of the American law does not reach across
sovereign borders,'' State Department spokeswoman Maria Rudensky
said.
</P>
<P>
   James Brunen is learning that the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   His wife has contacted a handful of attorneys, Arizona's
congressmen and the American Consulate in Hermosillo, but to no
avail. A judge ordered Brunen to remain in custody until he is
tried, which could take months.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Sen. John McCain and Rep. J.D. Hayworth have spoken
with authorities in Mexico, but can't do much else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in contact with the Hermosillo consulate and are doing
all that we legally can to make sure that he is being treated
fairly,'' said Hayworth's spokesman, Doug Nick. ``We can't do much
beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brunen's wife drives down nearly every day to deliver
bottled water, canned food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   She also brings cash to help pay for small perks, such as a swig
of clean water or a slightly bigger cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to buy a breath of fresh air. He had to buy protection
for his food. He had to buy the right to use a phone and the price
went up every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Merry Brunen cautioned American travelers to make sure they are
not packing weapons if they head south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very dangerous,'' she said. ``I'm living it and it is
real.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Alexa Haussler can be reached at alexa.haussler(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
