<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LATE-NIGHT-DINING-     08-11 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LATE-NIGHT-DINING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-END RESTAURANTS THAT STAY OPEN LATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All around me, a lively crowd lines the counter and
fills the booths at Florent, slurping up mussels and pate like
there's no tomorrow. Which is slightly unsettling, because there is
a tomorrow _ and it's only about four hours away.
</P>
<P>
   New York has always had a late-night subculture of 24-hour
diners. But now, with a growing number of affluent artists,
entrepreneurs and Wall Streeters working long, hard hours, the
city's high-end restaurateurs are beginning to stay up late
themselves, and offer serious food from fondue to sauteed skate,
all through the night.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Clementine expanded its late-night menu, tempting night
crawlers with dishes like grilled stuffed squid in a cumin broth as
late as 3:15 a.m. Match Downtown serves dim sum, braised short ribs
and a grilled tuna burger with green papaya slaw and miso mustard
sauce until 4 a.m. on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   At One 3 Barrow, between midnight and 3 a.m., you can have
barbecue Asian pork with summer corn and a star anise broth or a
tandoori chicken pizza with fig chutney.
</P>
<P>
   After midnight at Astor Restaurant and Lounge, a featherweight
chilled cucumber soup with anise and dill goes head to head with a
brawny braised lamb shank with pistachio couscous, root vegetables
and a pomegranate lamb juice.
</P>
<P>
   Even the new Mercer Kitchen, a restaurant run by Jean Georges
Vongerichten, a four-star chef, plans in September to serve a
condensed dinner menu until 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, of course, is interested in short ribs at 4 in the
morning. As the hours get weer, the crowds in these restaurants
don't always shrink, but they do narrow, revealing a late-night
personality distinct from the suits, students, foodies and fashion
types of the regular dinner hour.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of a few of them. Not surprisingly, most of
the restaurants with late-night menus are downtown, orbiting the
nucleus of Manhattan's clubs and bars. Uptown, the pickings are
slim. On the Upper East Side, for instance, the Lenox Room has what
it calls an ``After Rush Menu.'' It begins at 9:30 p.m., about the
time genuine late-nighters are just digesting lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper West Side is no better. A French Roast outpost keeps a
dim flicker of life going on Broadway. So does High Life, which
serves sushi to drinkers spilling out of the bars on Amsterdam
Avenue, as well as Avenue, a casual French spot on Columbus Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENTINE Clementine gets the publishing crowd for lunch and an
eclectic mix for dinner, but once they flee around 11 p.m., in
flocks a rowdy group of young Wall Streeters in suits and women in
tight-fitting clothes. There is no velvet rope but you do have to
get by a bouncer with an earpiece _ Moomba-style _ to get into the
dimly lit bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the destination before the destination,'' said John
Schenk, the chef and co-owner of the restaurant. People drop in,
drink cocktails at the long 34-seat bar while waiting for their
friends to arrive. A disk jockey keeps the mood bouyant with a mix
of retro jazz, hip-hop and drum and bass.
</P>
<P>
   Around midnight, the oval booths go quickly and food starts
appearing. You see a burger here and there, but this is a sharing
crowd. And the kitchen, which is open until 3:15 a.m., has found
just the right food: quick hits of clean, sharp flavors, tender
bites of salty sausage or cheese, salads for slim figures and good
bread to soak up the cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, diners seem to spend most of their time on cell
phones, deciding where to go next. Personally, I'd rather stay and
eat. The salmon toasts are phenomenal. Small round toasts are
rubbed with just enough wasabi to make your nose tingle, the salmon
is rich and smoky and a little grated cucumber slakes the palate.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a fried soft shell crab BLT, veal paillard with
fava beans, chopped salad, caviar with toast points and creme
fraiche, and even Jiffy Pop popcorn. And the Clementini, made with
vodka and clementine juice isn't a bad drink, sweet but slick
enough to slide down with ease. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLUE RIBBON
</P>
<P>
   Blue Ribbon Sushi has long been a standard for downtowners, but
its late-night relative, Blue Ribbon, is the place that chefs and
people in the food industry flock to after work. And like everyone
who goes there, they, too, wait in line to get in. Even after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Flay, chef at Bolo and Mesa Grill, still goes there now
and then. ``I used to go with Mario Batali and Matthew Kenney and
my partner Lawrence, Alan Harding or Joe Bastianich and we'd be
there until 4 in the morning,'' he said. ``Mario would just keep
ordering wine.'' But then, he said, everybody got really busy with
more restaurants, cooking shows and the rest of it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a younger group of up and coming chefs is picking up the
slack. And they are no less zealous. After midnight on a recent
evening, Erica Miller, chef at Blue Star, met Chris Santos, the
chef at Time Cafe North, and Colleen Grapes, the pastry chef at
Time Cafe North, for ``dinner''.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my favorite booth,'' said Ms. Miller, as she slid into
the tall, round, red velvet booth. ``I am soo hungry,'' she said.
``When you cook you don't eat, you know.'' An order of foie gras
terrine was delivered on cue.
</P>
<P>
   They studied the menu intensely and gossiped about the food
world. ``All day long you cook for people,'' Ms. Grapes said. ``So
it's nice to have people cook for you.''
</P>
<P>
   They kept the kitchen busy, ordering raw oysters, more foie gras
terrine, cheese fondue and beef marrow with marmalade, hallah and
sea salt.
</P>
<P>
   Around the room, oysters from the raw bar abounded, stacked on
top of the small square tables. Diners were well dressed, some in
silk, some in Polo. Meanwhile, others sat on benches outside and
stood sandwiched by the bar waiting for tables. It could have
easily passed for early evening.
</P>
<P>
   But it was indeed 2 a.m., and as Ms. Miller lamented, spreading
more foie gras on a piece of toasted brioche, ``I have to be back
at work by 8.'' The Sunday brunch crowd, now well into dreamland,
would soon be up and hungry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   IL BUCO
</P>
<P>
   It began as an antique store. Then it was an antique store that
served wine and cheese. Then it was an antique store during the day
and a restaurant serving lusty Mediterranean food at night. And
now? Well, it's just a restaurant with a lot of antiques. The food
is still lusty, and the hours have only gotten later.
</P>
<P>
   Il Buco doesn't really warm up until 10 p.m. And once it does,
people linger for hours, lulled by the Spanish wines, the flamenco
music, and the candle lighting, which casts seductive shadows
through the rustic room.
</P>
<P>
   The menu changes daily, and house rules are contingent on
pleasure. Smoking, a regular customer said, is permitted after
11:30 p.m. as long as no one complains. At the copper bar, they
have only top shelf liquor, no soda and all juices are freshly
squeezed. ``Because the owner doesn't believe in serving any
junk,'' said Mark Henegan, the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Henegan slinks through the room like a cat, making sure everyone
is content and entertained. He points to a man at the bar having a
heart-to-heart with someone on his cell phone while hovering over
risotto with shrimp, ``He's French.''
</P>
<P>
   Then to a foursome at one of the long wood farm tables in the
corner, ``They're, I don't know, not American.'' And two more, ``Ah
yes, there's two Spaniards.'' The crowd is European, but not
Eurotrash.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come for a little drink, a little conversation, a
little I don't know,'' he says, then smiles.
</P>
<P>
   I do _ great food like warm roasted asparagus slathered with
goat cheese, grilled chicken livers wrapped in pancetta, a tangle
of grilled prawns sprinkled with sea salt and striped bass with
roasted clams and fresh corn. With the bread, comes a plate of
unfiltered Umbrian olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is currently open until 1 a.m. ``This isn't even
late though,'' Donna Lennard, an owner, said without an ounce of
irony in her voice. ``We're going to start opening late in the
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORENT
</P>
<P>
   Any self-respecting, late-night diner has been to Florent at
least once. The diner style restaurant is open all night, open to
anyone who will make the journey to the meat-packing district to
get there.
</P>
<P>
   Around 3 a.m. on a recent morning, an Asian woman in a long,
straight dress, sitting with two friends, polished off a bowl of
steamed mussels, had a dessert of cigarettes, then laid down on the
long banquette to take a nap. The server came buy and picked up the
empty bowl without batting an eye.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Flotilla DeBarge, a cabaret performer, grooved to the
disco music on the sound system as she made her way through the
mussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hyped after doing a show,'' she said. ``I come for a cup
of coffee, the lentil salad and mussels and frites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know who or what you're going to see in here,'' she
said, paused, then smiled, ``Like me.'' Though she has spotted
celebrities like Matt Dillon and Marilyn Manson, she was quick to
add, ``I don't want you to think it's some celebrity-gawking
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeBarge brings her own music for the restaurant to play,
too. ``Yeah, that's what drag queens do,'' said Jose Pita, the
manager, as he passed by with a plate of fried eggs. ``They bring
their own music. They don't tolerate anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   A tone of tolerance is the beauty of this place. Worlds that
might normally collide in daylight, seem to harmonize under
Florent's hazy pink light. While Ms. DeBarge continued to sway to
the rhythm at the counter, a man from Nashville in the fashion
industry with a starched plaid shirt and dress watch picked at a
plate of eggs and toast at a nearby table.
</P>
<P>
   He and two friends, one an investment banker, the other also in
the fashion business, had started the evening with dinner at
Gramercy Tavern, then went to Tramps and Automatic Slims. Their
evening nearly over, he added, ``You know, one thing you can say
about this place. It's the best music we've heard all night.''
</P>
<P>
   CAFETERIA
</P>
<P>
   By the looks of the crowd at Cafeteria, a new restaurant in
Chelsea, you might think that when you call for a reservation, they
ask you to wear either black or white (and bare shoulders, please,
if you are a woman), so that you blend into the cool, white,
minimal dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Until 11 p.m. the dining room is loud and crowded, the wait at
least an hour. But then it trims down. The noise level lowers to a
buzz, people hang on each other a little more, the people streaming
in wear less clothing and drinks get dealt out like cards.
</P>
<P>
   But the food _ which is part California, part diner and nowhere
in between _ keeps pumping out of the kitchen. There is a delicious
macaroni and cheese, a spicy fried oyster po boy that looks like
it's on steroids, as well as tuna tartare and a large, leafy salad
weighed down with sliced avocado. The men eat, the women pick.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Newton, a co-owner of the restaurant, said he got the idea
for Cafeteria while in Los Angeles. ``Because there's nothing to
eat after midnight in L.A.,'' he said. He seems to have hit a
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a scene,'' said Jared Kurtz, a bartender at
Bowery Bar, who was there celebrating a friend's birthday. ``Going
to these places reminds me why I left L.A.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLUE RIBBON 97 Sullivan Street (Spring Street); (212) 274-0404.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: until 4 a.m., Tuesday through Sunday. Reservations for
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: appetizers, $8-$39.50(caviar); entrees, $9.50-$78;
desserts $7-$9.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd: a Banana Republic crowd, mostly chefs and Soho residents.
</P>
<P>
   CAFETERIA 119 Seventh Avenue South (17th Street); (212)
414-1717.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: until 1 a.m. daily. Reservations preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: appetizers, $4.95 to $9.95; entrees, $7.50 to $18.95;
desserts, $5.95
</P>
<P>
   Crowd: as stylishly minimalist as the decor.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENTINE 1 Fifth Avenue (Eighth Street); (212) 253-0003.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: for the late-night menu, Sunday to Thursday, 11:30 p.m.
to 3:15 a.m.; Friday and Saturday, 12:30 to 3:15 a.m. No
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: appetizers, $6 to $10; entrees, $8 to $15; desserts, $5
to $7.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd: rich bohemian, and a few suits.
</P>
<P>
   FLORENT 69 Gansevoort Street (Washington Street); (212)
989-5779.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: 24 hours on weekends; closed 5 to 9 a.m. weekdays.
Reservations accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: appetizers, $1.50 to $8.25; entrees, $5.95 to $13.95;
desserts, $3.50 to $4.95.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd: from drag queens to lawyers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IL BUCO 47 Bond Street (Bowery); (212) 533-1932.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: until 1 a.m., Friday and Saturday, and until midnight
Sunday to Thursday. Reservations accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: appetizers, $4 to $14; entrees, $14 to $25; desserts, $7
to $18.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd: bare skin and studied rumpledness.
</P>
