<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S VISIT LUCRATIVE FOR CALIFORNIA CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California Lt. Gov. Gray Davis doesn't care that
President Clinton will testify next week about whether he had a
sexual relationship with a White House intern. And aides say Davis
doesn't pay much attention to talk of impeachment of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic nominee for governor is less interested in the
president's sex life than in his ability to attract money _ big
money _ for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was in California Tuesday for three fund-raising events
to help the Davis campaign, which expects to rake in upwards of $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little bit helps,'' said Michael Bustamante, Davis'
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   California Democratic Party officials say Clinton remains their
``No. 1 asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party strategists question why Davis and his campaign
would seek the president's help now, just days before the president
testifies before a federal grand jury about his relationship with
former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking a huge gamble,'' said Mike Madrid, political
director for the California Republican Party. ``They're saying
let's get him here and raise a million dollars, and it doesn't
matter what may happen in a month. Here is a man (Davis) who will
have taken in a million dollars from someone involved in perhaps
the greatest sex scandal in American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Clinton remains popular, even though many Americans
believe he lied when he denied having an affair with Lewinsky. A
CBS News poll last week found that 76 percent of those surveyed
said they believed the president had an affair. Yet 63 percent said
the matter should never have been investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's support has remained strong in California. Analysts
and allies of the president say people here see the investigation
as a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people want to see a resolution to this,'' said Rep.
Ellen O. Tauscher, D-Calif., who said she believed the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see the president doing the job he was elected to
do,'' said Tauscher, a first-term House member running for
re-election this fall. ``They want more attention paid to the
things that impact them every day. They want a good public
education system, they want to be able to get good jobs, and they
want to make sure we are able to save the Social Security system.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations have done little to diminish Clinton's
popularity among Democratic candidates. He has traveled the country
helping them to raise money, raising a total of $1.4 million on
Monday alone for candidates in Kentucky and Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARDBOARD-CANS-(NEW-S     08-11 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDBOARD-CANS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE WAY FOR CARDBOARD CANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By MARK WARD  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardboard cans capable of holding carbonated drinks have been
created by British researchers. It's the first time anyone has
designed a cardboard container strong enough to hold a pressurized
beverage. If used widely, the cans should eventually be cheaper to
make and recycle than aluminium ones.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Freeman and his colleagues at Scientific Generics in
Cambridge make their can with four layers of thin cardboard. The
layers are staggered so that the seams of each sheet meet at
90-degree intervals around the can. The seams are usually the point
of failure in a tube, Freeman says, but with this design each seam
gains strength from the sheets above or below it.
</P>
<P>
   A thin aluminium membrane is sprayed onto the inside of the cans
to make them airtight, and the ends are plugged with shallow cones
that point outward. Opening the can involves removing one of the
cones, turning the sealed tube into a beaker. Freeman says that
prototypes have been able to withstand pressures of up to 480
kilopascals (about 5 atmospheres), higher than the 275 kilopascals
fizzy drinks are usually pressurized to.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific Generics is looking for a partner to develop the
idea. Freeman fears that large soft drink companies will be wary,
because they have so much invested in aluminium cans. He says:
``The challenge is finding someone with the will to make it
happen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0188 </DOCNO>
