<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRONIC-TOOTH-WIGG     08-11 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-TOOTH-WIGGLER-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE VIBRATION KEEPS YOU SMILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By PETER HADFIELD  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dentists who check a tooth's health by wobbling it with their
fingers may soon have a more scientific method at their fingertips.
A Japanese firm has developed an electronic wiggler that detects
loose teeth before it's too late to repair them. If a tooth is
loose enough to be jiggled by hand, it may already be too sick to
save.
</P>
<P>
   Being loose is a common symptom of gum diseases such as
gingivitis, in which the membrane and even the bone to which the
tooth is attached become infected. The British Dental Association
estimates that 10 percent of adults will lose teeth because of gum
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The new instrument fits on the end of a probe. When touched
horizontally against the center of a tooth it vibrates at 5
kilohertz for one second. Data on the tooth's movement are analyzed
by a computer, revealing how well the tooth is anchored in the jaw
and the strength of the membrane supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probe is just a prototype, so it's still undergoing
tests,'' says Tetsuo Kakuno of Dental Edison, an instrument
developer near Hiroshima. ``We're not sure when it will be on the
market.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
