A8522 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2KPROBLEM-SURVIVALIS     08-11 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KPROBLEM-SURVIVALISTS-960(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR 2000 COMPUTER PROBLEM SPAWNS NEW BREED OF SURVIVALISTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by Y2K PROBLEM-WEB SITES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is Dennis Elenburg's worst nightmare: It's Saturday
morning, Jan. 1, 2000, and Elenburg's alarm clock doesn't go off.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't go off because the power is out.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the power out, but the phones don't work.
</P>
<P>
   Since midnight, the temperature in the house has dropped 10
degrees, and his kids are cold.
</P>
<P>
   But Elenburg has planned for this. He already lives far enough
from Dallas to avoid urban rioting. He has been storing food and
water for nearly two years. His generator powers a radio, and
through a rudimentary network of amateur broadcasters, Elenburg
finds out he's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Regional brownouts plague the country. Groceries and drugstores
can't open. Hospital equipment has failed. Even if Elenburg could
call the police, the department's emergency vehicles may not
operate.
</P>
<P>
   And the banks? Completely inoperative.
</P>
<P>
   All because our computers don't know what day it is.
</P>
<P>
   Elenburg hopes this is an exaggerated scenario, but no one, he
says, can be sure. Like a growing minority, Elenburg believes a
computer glitch known as the millennium bug, or Y2k (short for Year
2000), could throw the world into chaos. They're storing food and
water, converting their assets from paper to gold, even moving to
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   The doomsayers, in most cases, aren't your traditional
survivalists or religious radicals. Many, Elenburg included, work
in the computer industry and understand the technology behind the
bug. When the clock rolls over to the next century, they say, it's
possible that everything from electric power grids to cameras could
quit functioning, with terrifying results.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone who sees Y2k as a significant problem is convinced
that anarchy will ensue. In fact, the voices of moderation far
outweigh the alarmists. The world still has 17 months to rectify
the most significant problems, stresses Leon Kappelman, an
associate professor of business computer information systems at the
University of North Texas in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of it is, it's bad. It's real bad,'' Kappelman
says. ``But that doesn't mean you leave. It means you redouble your
efforts. You focus where you can do the most damage, and you fight
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, computer experts point out that about one-third of
companies have yet to confront the Y2k issue and, as of May, only
40 percent of the most crucial government computers were compliant.
</P>
<P>
   What's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   To save money and space, early computer programmers decided to
drop the first two digits of the century date. That means most
computers read 1998 as ``98.'' When the year rolls over to 2000,
date fields will read ``00.'' Some computers will simply spit out
bad data when they encounter ``00''; others will crash or shut
themselves down.
</P>
<P>
   The glitch has already wreaked sporadic havoc. The computer
system that schedules patient appointments for three hospitals and
75 clinics in Pennsylvania went down in April after someone tried
to type in an appointment for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1996, Visa was forced to recall 12 million credit
cards with expiration dates of 2000 after credit card authorization
systems around the country refused to accept them, according to
computer expert Ed Yourdon.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street tested its mettle against Y2k in July, turning its
clocks ahead to the week of Dec. 29, 1999. Preliminary results
showed no Year 2000-related problems, but experts stress this
doesn't mean the stock exchanges will be free of bugs.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the problem is mind-boggling: Programmers
worldwide will need to examine 250 billion to 300 billion lines of
software, and companies must hunt down several billion microdevices
(self-contained computers) embedded in products as unimportant as
coffee makers and VCRs and machinery as crucial as coolant systems
on nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   A typical oil rig, for example, has 10,000 embedded chips
throughout its circuitry. An electric company's power grid may have
10 times that, notes Yourdon, a software engineering consultant and
leading Y2k activist.
</P>
<P>
   Estimated costs to correct the problem run between $300 billion
and $600 billion. The federal government alone will spend $4
billion. In the private sector, Chase Manhattan bank will dole out
$250 million, The Prudential Insurance Co. $110 million and Federal
Express Corp. $75 million. There's enough Y2k business to keep the
3 million U.S. computer programmers working overtime for years to
come. Problem is, they've only got 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
