A8534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      08-11 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUMMER VEGETABLE STEW WITH DEPTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the last of eight columns by Deborah Madison, the former
chef at Greens in San Francisco and the author of ``Vegetarian
Cooking for Everyone.'' Her collaborator is Mark Bittman. Next
week: the first of eight columns by Charlie Palmer, the chef and
owner of Aureole in Manhattan.)  
 (HLW)  
 By DEBORAH MADISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twice a week during the summer, I come home from the
farmers' market with a huge assortment of vegetables. The
possibilities abound, but I often feel an overwhelming urge to use
this bounty to put together a colorful, fresh-tasting vegetable
stew. Others might choose to stir-fry, but I prefer these little
braises because I like to get the vegetables tender, drawing out
all of their delicious juices and allowing them to mingle.
</P>
<P>
   Because mid- and late-summer vegetables are typically quite
sweet, there is a balancing act to a dish like this. First of all,
you need to add some complexity, as well as a unifying element. I
provide that at the last minute with a drizzle of a quickly made
basil oil, a kind of stripped-down pesto that smacks of basil and
little else. Then you need acidity, in the form of vinegar; not so
much that you actually taste it, but enough to offset the sugar in
the peppers, corn and tomatoes and to tie their flavors together.
Handled correctly, this stew provides the same kind of depth of
flavor you would get from one containing meat.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the pieces large so that the stew retains some form on the
plate, and add the vegetables sequentially so that each one cooks
the right amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware that the freshness and wonderful color of vegetable
stews do not last long. Although the dish will be delicious the
next day, its best flavor is really fleeting, and the colors begin
to fade as soon as the cooking is complete. So I like to serve it
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a starchy element provides a foil for all of the colors
and flavors of the vegetables. Sometimes I slip a few simmered
ravioli into the stew at the end, or serve it with biscuits or
popovers. But I really love it spooned over some freshly mashed
potatoes, which also take well to the basil oil. The result is
comfort food to the nth degree.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE RAGOUT WITH MASHED POTATOES AND BASIL OIL
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, longer with dried beans
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh or dried shell beans, like cranberry or navy
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, smashed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   Several sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 red, orange or yellow bell peppers, or a combination
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup plus 1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup packed basil leaves, washed and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 medium new potatoes, about 2 pounds, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   3{ tablespoons butter (or use more oil)
</P>
<P>
   4 shallots, peeled and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   About 1 pound zucchini, cut into quarters the long way with
3-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   2 cups green beans, trimmed and cut into 1{-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   2 large tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cups corn kernels (about 5 ears)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon wine or other vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Cook beans, onion, garlic, and thyme in water to cover until
tender; fresh beans will take 30 minutes or so, dried beans
considerably longer. Salt to taste, and drain the beans, reserving
their liquid. (While beans are cooking, proceed with the recipe.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut peppers in half, scoop out cores, trim white membranes,
make a couple of small slits on each end, and press down to flatten
them. Place them skin side up on a baking sheet, and brush with 1
tablespoon olive oil. Broil about 6 inches from heat source,
rotating so they are exposed evenly to heat (but always with skin
up), just until skin puffs up and separates, 5 to 10 minutes. Stack
halves on top of one another, skin to skin. Allow them to cool for
a few minutes, and then peel and cut into strips.
</P>
<P>
   3. To make basil oil, place basil in a blender with the 1/3 cup
oil, and turn machine on. While it is running, add 1 or 2
tablespoons water, just enough to loosen mixture; it should have a
creamy consistency. Add salt to taste, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Boil potatoes in salted water until quite tender. Place 1{
tablespoons butter in large, deep skillet or casserole, and turn
heat to medium-high. When it melts, add shallots, and turn heat to
medium. Cook, stirring occasionally, until they are translucent and
soft, at least 10 minutes. Add zucchini and green beans; when
zucchini begins to brown, add about { cup of bean-cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   5. As soon as zucchini begins to soften, add peppers, tomatoes
and cooked beans. Add bean-cooking liquid as necessary to keep
mixture stewy but not soupy, as much as 2 cups. When everything is
tender _ in about 10 minutes _ add corn and vinegar. Turn heat to
low, and keep warm while you mash the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Mash the potatoes with remaining butter, about { cup of
remaining bean cooking liquid, and salt and pepper to taste. Place
potatoes in center of large bowl, and spoon stew around it. Drizzle
everything with a bit of basil oil, and sprinkle with pepper.
Serve, passing remaining basil oil at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
