<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2KPROBLEM-SURVIVALIS     08-11 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KPROBLEM-SURVIVALISTS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: got 17 months. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOBAL `STRESS TEST': A dozen people fill a row of tables in the
back room of the Denny's at Midway Road and Interstate 635 in
Dallas. Financial adviser Randy Flink has passed around eight-page
outlines titled ``Constructing Your Y2k Personal Insurance Plan,''
and the group peruses them silently between bites of burgers and
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Elenburg heads the Dallas Area Y2k Community Preparedness Group,
or DAYCPG, which gathers here weekly. Flink, president of
Championship Financial Advisors and today's featured speaker, met
Elenburg on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The lone woman at the table divides her attention between
Flink's handout and a packet from Storm Chasers Shelters Inc., a
Fort Worth company selling a ``full line of subterrain utility
shelters.'' Her three kids wait in a nearby booth.
</P>
<P>
   After the presentation, a former Merrill Lynch financial
consultant approaches Flink. The man says that after he heard about
Y2k, he wrote his clients a letter and quit his job. ``I told them
I thought it was time to get out of the market,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Elenburg, an independent computer consultant, experienced his
Y2k awakening six weeks after starting as Year 2000 project manager
for ``a major telecommunications company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw all the complexity and the depth (of the problem) and
how it really affected a company that was high-tech,'' explains
Elenburg, a young, articulate and perfectly normal-looking husband
and dad. ``All at once, we're going to get a massive stress test of
the global computer systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Elenburg, who co-operates the Web site Y2k Watch and dubs
himself the Y2k Weatherman, says ``the likeliest scenario will be a
serious financial crash.'' Still, he has purchased more than $1,000
in dehydrated and bulk food and converted most of his assets to
precious metals or cash. ``I like to call myself the most pragmatic
optimist you'll ever meet.''
</P>
<P>
   BUGGING OUT: The Internet nurtures a burgeoning Y2k subculture,
with Web sites hosted by computer programmers, professors,
survivalist groups, financial experts, religious organizations and
concerned citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Gary North, perhaps the best-known of the so-called
``safe-haven'' advocates, calls Y2k ``the biggest problem that the
modern world has ever faced'' on his Web site. North, a historian
who believes Y2k is God's way of punishing man for his reliance on
technology, has already taken refuge in rural Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   At www.yardeni.com, respected Wall Street economist Ed Yardeni
predicts a 70 percent chance of a worldwide recession. Captain
Dave's Survival Center warns of shortages of batteries, candles and
toilet paper, even the possibility of martial law. ``Sales of
survival-related food are really reaching record levels,'' Dave
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Dave himself will be ``in an isolated mountain region'5 on New
Year's Eve 1999, sharing a house with another family, he says in a
phone interview. ``We will have at least six months' worth of food
... water-purification systems ready and two wood-burning stoves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking the Year 2000 (bug) would be an annoyance,'' he
adds. ``You wouldn't be able to make a phone call for a few days.
And now I'm looking at it as having potentially longer-term
effects. Is this something that's going to be gone in two weeks?
Not necessarily. So why not take the vacation time and bug out, so
to speak?''
</P>
<P>
   The Cassandra Project, an independent Web site, contains reams
of information on ``areas of concern'' such as banking, nuclear
power, and gas and oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra's Research Director Paloma O'Riley came across Y2k
while serving as a computing security specialist in the Navy during
Desert Shield and Desert Storm. She left a job as Year 2000 project
manager for the British maker of Land Rover vehicles to return to
the United States and begin cajoling her state government into
action.
</P>
<P>
   O'Riley now works with the Colorado governor's office on Y2k
awareness, and the Cassandra Project's Web site last month drew
600,000 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling people not to move,'' O'Riley says. ``We stand a
much better chance of getting through it if we stick together, so
running off to the hills isn't going to accomplish anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Anderson created her site, Y2k Women, this past spring. A
month ago, she added a weekly e-mail magazine called Dear Karen and
captured 600 subscribers as of the third issue.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
