<HEADER>
A8542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTTERMILK-2TAKES-NYT     08-11 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTTERMILK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANGY BUTTERMILK, SWEET MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. LANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no two ways about buttermilk: either you love its tart
creaminess, or you shudder at just a glimpse of its cloudy film
clinging to an empty glass. Having grown up in the Swedish
countryside, where fermented milks were more common than fresh, I'm
definitely in the first category, though I admit I never saw
buttermilk drunk from a glass until I arrived in America.
</P>
<P>
   Buttermilk is as thick and creamy as its name implies, but it
actually has far fewer calories and much less fat than whole or
low-fat milk. Originally this was so because it was just the thin
liquid left over when butter was made, the equivalent of the cheese
maker's whey.
</P>
<P>
   Today most dairies make buttermilk by culturing skim milk, but
it retains a tartness that perfectly accents the flavor of
sun-sweetened summer berries.
</P>
<P>
   One of the simplest ways to enjoy buttermilk is as a cold soup.
In Sweden, it is served up in a deep plate and sprinkled with sugar
and ground ginger. I prefer to eat it country style, adding
crumbled thick Swedish rye crisp, like Ryvita. In Sweden,
cornflakes now seem to have surpassed rye crisp as the ``bread'' of
choice for this dish.
</P>
<P>
   This year, I had the idea of using buttermilk to concoct a panna
cotta, an Italian-style eggless custard. Now although Italy and
Sweden are at opposite extremes in so many ways, I have always
found a certain similarity in the creamy smoothness of panna cotta
and filbunke, a thick milk dish of summer that my mother used to
set out on the windowsill to harden. (It used to be called
clabbered milk.)
</P>
<P>
   In my mind's eye I can still see those clear 50s Pyrex dishes in
which the cream would slowly rise to the top. The ``good
bacteria,'' I was told, would settle in as the milk solidified,
resulting in a cool, rich, creamy layer on top and a custardy panna
cottalike pudding on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned filbunke is so smooth it makes yogurt seem almost
gritty by comparison. Or I should say, it (italics)was:(end
italics) you can make filbunke only from unhomogenized milk, and I
haven't had any since Ginger, our Jersey cow, stopped giving milk a
dozen years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that panna cotta uses gelatin to help the milk set,
while in Sweden the liquid firms up naturally with whatever yeasts
and bacteria are in the cooler air. But for me, the likeness
outweighed the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The buttermilk panna cotta came out tart and flavorful. It
shines as a summer dessert served with macerated fresh berries or
preserved lingonberries, the smaller wild Scandinavian version of
American cranberries, stirred with sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Another unusual dish that uses buttermilk almost as a custard is
buttermilk pie. I first saw it in a local diner in Ohio during my
college days. I have since made a similar version using ground
ginger, the traditional topping for filbunke, as flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   And I came across buttermilk again recently at a stop at the
We-Li-Kit Farm ice cream stand in Abington, Conn. Tucked away in
the rolling farm country of northeastern Connecticut on Route 97
just south of Route 44, this small family-run operation draws
customers from miles around, especially for its ice cream. One day
recently there was a new item, strawberry buttermilk ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   I was used to making buttermilk shakes as summer coolers, adding
vanilla ice cream and fresh fruit from the garden. But using the
buttermilk as a base for the ice cream itself was something I had
never thought of.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor was spectacular, the tartness of the buttermilk
accenting the flavor of the strawberries and bringing back memories
of those northern summers where the dark of night was only dusk. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERMILK PANNA COTTA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus about 3 hours' refrigeration &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 envelopes unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Macerated blackberries (see recipe). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan, combine 1{ cups of the buttermilk with
the sugar. Sprinkle the gelatin over the mixture, and allow it to
sit 2 to 3 minutes. Place the saucepan over medium heat, and stir
constantly until the gelatin is dissolved; do not allow to boil.
Remove the pan from the heat, and add the remaining 1{ cups
buttermilk and the lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer the buttermilk mixture to a covered container, and
refrigerate until thickened but not firm, 1 to 2 hours. Stir three
or four times during this period, to achieve uniform consistency.
When ready, the mixture will mound slightly on the surface when
dropped from a spoon; use it in the next step before it thickens
beyond this stage.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large mixing bowl, combine the cream and vanilla, and
whip until soft peaks form. Add about { cup of the whipped cream to
the buttermilk mixture, and stir in to smooth it. Then add the
buttermilk mixture to the bowl of whipped cream, folding in until
just combined.
</P>
<P>
   4. Spray the inside of a 6-cup mold with vegetable oil spray, or
wipe with a flavorless oil. Transfer the buttermilk mixture to the
mold, cover with foil or plastic wrap, and refrigerate until set,
about 2 hours. To serve, unmold onto a serving platter, and top
with macerated blackberries.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 12 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MACERATED BLACKBERRIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes, plus 1 hour resting time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh blackberries
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kirsch liqueur, if desired. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a small mixing bowl, combine the blackberries, sugar and
kirsch. Stir gently to mix. Set aside in a warm spot, like a sunny
windowsill, and allow to macerate for 1 to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 cups. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RASPBERRY BUTTERMILK SHAKE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raspberries
</P>
<P>
   1 large scoop premium vanilla ice cream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a blender, combine buttermilk, raspberries and ice cream.
Blend at medium speed until smooth. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 serving (about 2{ cups). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GINGER BUTTERMILK PIE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1} cups plus 3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   { cup light vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground ginger. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare the pie crust, preheat oven to 425 degrees. In a
medium mixing bowl, sift together 1} cups of the flour, and the
salt. In a small bowl, combine the oil and milk, and blend with a
fork. Make a well in the center of the flour, and add the oil
mixture. Stir with a fork to mix lightly; then add 1 teaspoon cold
water. Continue to blend the dough, handling as little as possible
to produce a flaky, finished crust.
</P>
<P>
   2. Shape the dough into two balls of equal size. On a lightly
floured surface, roll out the remaining ball into a 9{-inch disk.
(Refrigerate or freeze the other one, and use for another purpose.)
Fit the dough into a 9-inch pie pan, folding under and fluting the
edge. Prick the dough with a fork, and lightly cover with foil,
pressing gently to conform with the shape of the dough. Bake 10
minutes, and remove from the oven.
</P>
<P>
   3. While the crust is baking, prepare the filling: in a medium
mixing bowl, combine the sugar and remaining 3 tablespoons of
flour. Add the eggs, melted butter, buttermilk, lemon juice and
ginger. Transfer to the container of a blender, and mix briefly at
the lowest speed; do not allow the mixture to become foamy.
</P>
<P>
   4. Pour the filling into the pie shell, and bake 10 minutes. If
necessary, cover the crust edge with strips of foil to prevent
further browning. Reduce the oven heat to 350 degrees, and bake
until a knife or toothpick inserted into the center comes out
clean, about 20 minutes. Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 to 10 servings (one 9-inch pie).
</P>
</TEXT>
