<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK: MERLOT'S SECRET  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Lambert Bridge Merlot 1995, Sonoma County, Calif. About $20. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A deep, intense wine, this Lambert Bridge merlot benefits
considerably from the addition of 22 percent cabernet, both
sauvignon and franc.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics in the trade say that the only reason so much cabernet
was used in so many merlots was that there was so little merlot to
go around. They call it stretching.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but a lot of merlot turns out to be soft and
characterless: a nice, forgettable red wine. Cabernet sauvignon and
cabernet franc, on the other hand, add hard tannins, which we wine
writers variously describe as ``structure'' or ``backbone.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. The fact is that the merlot-cabernet blends have more
life, more interesting flavors, more complexity. Could that be why
the Bordeaux people have been blending these grapes for a couple of
centuries?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
