<HEADER>
A8554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRINKING-VINEGAR-NYT &LR;      08-11 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRINKING-VINEGAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINEGAR'S SECRET LIFE, AS AN APERITIF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clustered on a silver tray in the center of the elegant dining
room at Seasons, the restaurant in the Four Seasons Hotel in
Chicago, are slender hand-blown flasks filled with liquids in
enticing tones of pale straw, amber, deep burgundy and ruby red.
</P>
<P>
   Grappas? liqueurs? Guess again.
</P>
<P>
   The bottles are filled with vinegars, and not for some
table-side salad toss. These were made to be sipped, and are served
as aperitifs or as palate-refreshers between courses, for $4 a
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big eye-catcher,'' said Andreas Kappenhagen, the
director of the restaurant and bar. ``People see others order it
and want to know about it and try it. Most are pleasantly
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The handmade vinegars are from Weinessiggut Doktorenhof,
Germany's first estate to produce wine just for vinegar. Grapes
like gewuerztraminer, riesling, sylvaner and pinot noir, some
allowed to mature to make beerenauslese and eiswein, are grown for
the vinegars. Some are mellowed with honey and others are made with
berries or seasoned with herbs like lavender and sage. One is
flecked with bits of gold leaf. They are aromatic and very smooth,
with tart acidity but no real throat-grabbing bite.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, they are even served in special, narrow,
long-stemmed glasses designed for tasting vinegar by Georg
Wiedemann, the owner of the estate. Of the nearly 30 vinegars the
estate makes, Seasons restaurant carries nine.
</P>
<P>
   Wine buffs need not fear that a few sips of vinegar will spoil
the taste buds for that bottle of fine Bordeaux with dinner. After
all, when it comes to vinegar, these are Chateau d'Yquem.
</P>
<P>
   Weinessiggut Doktorenhof sipping vinegars are not served in any
New York restaurants, but are available at Fairway, 2127 Broadway
(74th Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132nd Street), where a
17.7-ounce bottle is $22. In a hand-blown flask, the vinegars are
$85 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2KPROBLEM-SURVIVALIS     08-11 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KPROBLEM-SURVIVALISTS-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: the third issue. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anderson, who lives in the Fort Worth suburb of Colleyville with
her Y2k consultant husband and their children, leans toward North's
version of Year 2000 repercussions. ``I really believe there are
going to be severe problems,'' she says. ``But regardless of
whether you buy into it hook, line and sinker, you should be
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is storing buckets of whole wheat and filling liter pop
bottles with water. She recently discovered a Los Angeles company
that sells a ``hospital in a box'' _ sort of an advanced first-aid
kit that Anderson may help to market.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Susan Powter interviewed Anderson on her syndicated
radio talk show. The former family therapist is in the midst of
writing her first book, tentatively titled ``Mars and Venus Look at
Y2k,'' a millennial take on John Gray's bestseller about men and
women's communication styles.
</P>
<P>
   Religion informs Anderson's Y2k beliefs, but only to a certain
extent. ``There are a whole boatload of Christians who believe this
is related to Armageddon,'' she says. ``I don't fall into that
camp. Gary (North) is saying that man's idolatry to technology is
kind of catching up to him, and that I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   `ONE GIANT HEADACHE': Ed Yourdon, co-author with his daughter
Jennifer of ``Time Bomb 2000,'' a personal preparation guide for
the millennium, has spent 35 years in the computer field, the past
20 as a consultant to Fortune 500 companies and government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   He recently moved to Taos, N.M., from New York City, a change of
address partly based on his Y2k concerns. ``There's enough of a
chance that the disruptions might make major cities like New York
totally unlivable for a year that I would plan accordingly,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Computer professionals have known for decades that the problem
was looming. Yourdon was warning programmers of the glitch in the
1970s. But it wasn't until 1995, when companies began having
trouble computing five-year financial forecasts, that Yourdon
started focusing on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the ramifications of 10 percent of the banks going
down? If 10 percent of the utility companies go down, is that
enough to take down the (power) grid?'' Yourdon asks. ``That's the
area where we're all totally in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most Y2k activists, Yourdon believes the world will witness
the effects of the upcoming crisis months before Jan. 1, 2000. ``By
the summer or fall of next year, it will be abundantly obvious
whether this thing has been exaggerated,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The great moral debate in the computer industry these days is
whether programmers should stick around past the stroke of midnight
to help troubled businesses, or get out of Dodge before their
neighbors start looking for scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really knows what's going to happen,'' says William
Ulrich, author of ``The Year 2000 Software Crisis'' and president
of Tactical Strategy Group Inc. in Soquel, Calif. ``I believe there
are going to be a lot of little problems spread across a lot of
companies and government agencies. It's going to cause one giant
headache for almost all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich places himself ``on the optimistic side of the curve.''
Still, he advises folks to do some ``personal contingency
planning.'' Be judicious about investments. Have some extra cash on
hand. Prepare for some telecommunications and power problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay off airplanes at midnight,'' he cautions. ``If you're
traveling, make sure you have alternative ways home.''
</P>
<P>
   The most proactive step citizens can take is to organize a
community-based program to work with local businesses. Hold a
series of public meetings and include local government in
contingency planning. ``Awareness and communication will reduce a
lot of the fear,'' adds Ulrich, who suspects that the doomsayers'
warnings will do nothing more than incite panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end of the world,'' adds O'Riley of the Cassandra
Project. ``The worst that could happen is we'll go back to living
in 1900, and what was so bad about that?''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
