<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      08-11 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALE, DRY SHERRIES: THE FRESHER THE BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (JT)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bordeaux region of France runs on Champagne. Whether it is
an anniversary dinner at a back-country chateau or a business lunch
in town, the table wine will be red Bordeaux, but the aperitif will
always be Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it was in Margaux when my old friend Alexis
Lichine, the wine writer, shipper and chateau owner, was alive.
Anything from a late breakfast to a midnight supper with his guests
and family at his winery there, Chateau Prieure-Lichine, was reason
for a bottle of Champagne. Except for Alexis. Once he had seen to
everyone else's glass of Krug or Pol Roger, he opened a bottle of
fino sherry for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Driving through Spain, which isn't too far from Bordeaux, he'd
stop the car suddenly and dash into a shop. Minutes later, he'd
emerge holding a bottle of La Ina or Tio Pepe. ``It's good and
fresh,'' he'd say. ``We'll have it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   After a lifetime in the wine trade, he knew that a good fino
sherry or a manzanilla _ an even more delicate-tasting sherry _ was
one of life's secret joys. A secret because most of us think the
best sherries are dark and sweet and that the pale, dry finos are
inconsequential. Nothing could be further from the truth. In
Andalusia, where sherry is made, the finos and manzanillas are the
most prized. In the great sherry houses like Domecq and Gonzalez
Byass, they are thought of as the most complex of all sherries and
equal to any aperitif wines in the world.
</P>
<P>
   And not just to aperitifs. On my own visits to the Spanish towns
where sherry is made I've been served a fino or a manzanilla with
every meal. ``What do I have to do to get some red wine around
here?'' I once asked one of the sherry makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly up to Rioja,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   That was before I came to understand what Lichine had known for
a long time: that fino and manzanilla are extraordinary wines.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, it's nearly impossible to discover how good these two
wines can be unless you can be close to the source. ``Delicate'' is
not just an idle descriptive: these wines probably should never be
bottled. But bottled they must be, so the trick is to drink them as
soon after bottling as possible, ideally within seven or eight
months. Which is why Lichine would jump from the car in San
Sebastian or Bilbao, Spain, when he saw a place he knew would keep
only fresh fino.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, that usually means a good Spanish restaurant,
like Solera in New York, where the staff knows how to handle and
serve these wines. The wines should be served chilled but not
freezing, and they should be consumed once the bottle is opened.
Half bottles make a lot of sense.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it's difficult to get Americans to try drinking sherry
with meals, it's even harder to find restaurants that will serve
finos in half bottles. To most restaurateurs, sherry of any kind is
an aperitif, to be sold more profitably by the glass.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that most finos come to this country with too
much alcohol _17.5, even 18 percent _ to make them easy to
preserve. In Spain, they are often sold at 15.5 percent or, in the
case of manzanillas, 14.5, which isn't much more than some of the
macho zinfandels California turns out as table wines.
</P>
<P>
   Most sherries come from the blazing white-chalk vineyards around
the inland city of Jerez, in Andalusia, the southernmost province
of Spain. Manzanilla comes from Sanlucar de Barrameda, just a few
miles away from Jerez on the coast, where the weather is cooler and
the breath of the sea is always in the air. It is said that the
salt of the sea also flavors manzanillas.
</P>
<P>
   Both wines are made from the palomino grape, probably a native
Andalusian variety. As it ages in the barrel, sherry develops a
flor _ a white film that is a kind of yeast, which consumes
whatever sugar is left in the wine after fermentation. The flor
lasts for a few years, then dies and sinks to the bottom of the
barrel. The flor is left behind when the sherry is bottled, but it
contributes directly to the unique taste of the sherry,
particularly the light finos.
</P>
<P>
   I've already mentioned the two best-known finos, La Ina and Tio
Pepe. I'd be remiss in not also highlighting the wines of Emilio
Lustau. This house specializes in single-cask, or unblended,
sherries, some of them 30 years old. Most of these sherries have
been produced for investors, who keep them strictly as commodities:
they sell them to the big sherry firms when those firms need
something very special for a certain blend. They are called
almacenista sherries.
</P>
<P>
   At any particular time, Lustau may also have five or six
separate manzanillas and finos on the market. It only remains to
find a retailer who appreciates their quality and knows how to
stock them. These are not wines that should remain in a back
storage room until space is made for them on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that with these exceptionally delicate wines there
are no regulations requiring the bottles to be dated. Which is why
Alexis Lichine dashed into shops in Spain, where he knew he'd find
the youngest, freshest wines.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps its just another good reason for visiting Spain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
