<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WOOD-BURNING OVEN? CRANK UP THE GRILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Sonoma County, Calif., this spring, a friend and I were
treated to a wonderful home-cooked meal of rack of lamb grilled
over a wood fire. The chops were so succulent and so delicately
flavored that we immediately started thinking about building a wood
oven in the backyard of the house in rural Vermont where we spend a
lot of time in the summer. Then we thought better of it, because
the remnants of meals might be just one more attraction for the
wildlife that frequents the place _ deer, porcupines, bear.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine my excitement when I learned that you don't
need a wood-burning oven to cook over wood _ all you need is an
ordinary barbecue grill. The man who told me this, Don Hysko, is
the president of Peoples Woods/Nature's Own, a company in
Cumberland, R.I., that sells not only chunks of wood cut for
grilling but also an alternative to briquets called Chunk Charwood
that he said would produce much more succulent grilled food than
traditional briquets.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one way to find out for myself. After five days
of cooking over Charwood, and also over Hysko's aged chunks of wood
in oak, ash, cherry, apple and pecan, I'm a convert.
</P>
<P>
   Chunk Charwood looks like pieces of charred wood, because that
is what it is. It is also called lump or chunk charcoal. Canadian
sugar maple wood is burned in an oxygen-free kiln to remove the
moisture and wood pollutants. The result is a clean, dry heat that
seals in flavor. Everything I cooked _ chicken parts, whole
chicken, steak, tenderloin of beef, rack of lamb, pork tenderloin,
salmon and assorted vegetables _ had a wonderful sweetness and was
juicier than anything I had tasted over briquets.
</P>
<P>
   The high heat the Charwood produces caramelizes the natural
sugars in the food. No wonder the wood-grilled pizzas at Al Forno
in Providence are so good. They use the same product.
</P>
<P>
   Even for me _ someone not that skillful around the barbie _ the
Charwood was easy to work with. Using a charcoal chimney starter
and two sheets of newspaper balled up in the lower part of the
chimney, I simply poured the chunks of Charwood into the top
chamber, lit the paper in two or three places and went back inside
to do other chores while I waited for the Charwood to obtain a
glowing red color. This took about 15 minutes. Then I added it to
the grill the way briquets usually are. The Charwood seems to burn
more quickly than briquets, so be prepared to grill when it's
ready.
</P>
<P>
   Then I turned to cooking over wood chunks. If you want a smoky
flavor, this is the way to get it. The pork tenderloin, chicken and
vegetables that were cooked over wood were superb. Whether the
grill was covered or open, the smoky flavor of the wood came
through. It was particularly appealing in the vegetables _
eggplant, red peppers and zucchini.
</P>
<P>
   And the wood chunks were almost as easy to light as the
Charwood, using the same technique; the chunks are small enough to
fit into a large chimney. As soon as they are blazing _ 15 to 20
minutes _ add them to the grill and spread them evenly over the
bottom. When they are glowing red, in another 5 to 10 minutes, they
are ready. Wood burns hotter than Charwood, so you might not need
as much. But keep in mind that not all wood that you buy is aged
and may not be so easy to light.
</P>
<P>
   The company also sells wood chips that can be placed over the
hot Charwood to impart the flavor of the wood. (They come in the
same flavors as the wood chunks.) But for the life of me, I could
not taste the difference between one wood and another, except for
the mesquite, which has a distinctive flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples Woods/Nature's Own Chunk Charwood, wood chunks and wood
chips are available in many markets around the country, by mail
order from (800) 729-5800 and on the Web at www.peopleswoods.com. A
17.6-pound bag of Charwood is $8.90 plus shipping; a 20-pound bag
of wood chunks, $11.95 plus shipping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
