A8583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-ARTIST-2TAKES     08-11 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ARTIST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GERMAN MUSEUM HONORS AN ARTIST, LOST TO THE HOLOCAUST  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1995 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSNABRUECK, Germany _ Gustel Moses-Nussbaum knew that her
cousin, Felix Nussbaum, had been a painter. She also knew that,
along with his parents and most of her family, he had died at
Auschwitz. But it was only in 1960 that she learned that many of
his oils were stored in a Brussels basement. Nussbaum had once
said: ``If I perish, do not let my paintings die. Show them to the
people.'' Mrs. Moses-Nussbaum felt duty-bound to make this happen.
</P>
<P>
   On July 16, this northwestern German city where he was born in
1904 opened the new Felix Nussbaum Museum to house some 160 of his
paintings. As a measure of the importance that Osnabrueck gives to
the initiative, the museum was designed by the Polish-American
architect Daniel Libeskind and inaugurated by Gerhard Schroeder,
the president of Lower Saxony and the front-runner to become
Germany's next chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   That all this has come about is, of course, a tribute to the
efforts of Mrs. Moses-Nussbaum and her sister, Shulamith
Jaari-Nussbaum. But it also tells the story of a German city's
determination to turn its back on its own all too vivid Nazi past
and reinvent itself as a symbol of peace. When Mrs. Moses-Nussbaum
first brought the paintings here in 1970 in the hope that someone
would be willing to restore the works of a local though largely
unknown artist, she needed Osnabrueck. Today, the city needs Felix
Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Nussbaum left Osnabrueck in 1922 at the age of 18 to study art
in Hamburg. He returned to visit his parents, but he never again
lived here. In 1925, he moved to Berlin and continued to study
while setting up a studio and sharing an apartment with his
girlfriend, an artist from Poland named Felka Platek. He was a
prolific painter, his figurative oils evocative of van Gogh and his
landscapes influenced by de Chirico, but he sold little. Indeed,
his main client and fan was his father, Philipp, a prosperous iron
merchant who donated several of his works to friends in Osnabrueck.
</P>
<P>
   Nussbaum and Platek moved to Rome in October 1932 after he won a
scholarship as a guest student at the Prussian Academy in the Villa
Massimo. That December, a fire in his Berlin studio destroyed 150
of his paintings. According to some accounts, it was set by Nazi
youths. In May 1933, with Hitler now firmly in power, Nussbaum was
ejected from the Prussian Academy and began wandering through
Italy, Switzerland and France, eventually reaching Oostende,
Belgium, in January 1935.
</P>
<P>
   By then, at least half of Osnabrueck's 500 Jews had fled the
city, including Nussbaum's parents, who successively lived in
Switzerland, Cologne and Amsterdam. Osnabrueck was a hotbed of
Nazism and anti-Semitism: it had a flourishing Nazi party as early
as 1926, and its Roman Catholic archbishop, Wilhelm Berning, was
known as the Nazi prelate. Osnabrueck's large synagogue, like those
of many German cities, was burned on the night of Nov. 2, 1938. And
during the war, says Peter Junk, a local historian, ``no one here
hid a single Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oostende, where he was befriended by the painter James Ensor,
Nussbaum's life was unsettled by the refusal of the Belgian
authorities to grant him and Platek, who was also Jewish, identity
papers. In 1937, they married and moved to Brussels, where
Nussbaum's work was still mainly portraits, still-lifes and
landscapes, although the gathering darkness of Europe was evoked in
a handful of oils. In May 1940, after Germany occupied Belgium,
Nussbaum was arrested and interned in a camp at St. Cyprien in
southwestern France. Six months later, he escaped and somehow made
his way back to Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The years that followed became increasingly difficult. In the
spring of 1942, Nussbaum hid his paintings with two acquaintances,
including a Belgian dentist whose name is remembered only as Dr.
Grosfils. Nussbaum and his wife also went into hiding, first in an
attic and then in a basement. Remarkably, he continued painting.
Indeed, as if his greatest talent were unlocked by terror, it is
the work done during this period that has earned him a place as a
rare artistic witness to the persecution of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   His best-known painting is perhaps ``Self-Portrait With Jewish
Identity Card'' from August 1943, which shows Nussbaum wearing an
overcoat, the collar turned up to reveal a yellow star, and his
right hand holding up an identity card stamped ``Juif-Joud.'' Other
works, like ``Organ Grinder,'' show scenes of desolation. Several,
like ``Couple Grieving,'' ``Jew by the Window'' and ``Jaqui in the
Street,'' capture the fear and solitude of defenseless Jews
awaiting their fate at the hands of the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   On June 20, 1944, Nussbaum and Platek were arrested, and, five
weeks later, they were deported to Auschwitz. Nussbaum's parents
and brother were arrested in Amsterdam and sent to the death camp.
Mrs. Moses-Nussbaum and her sister were in hiding in the southern
Netherlands, but their parents, a brother and a sister also died in
Auschwitz. After the war, the surviving sisters made their way to
Israel, where they live today.
</P>
<P>
   What they call their life's work to rescue Nussbaum's paintings
began in 1960 when they heard that Grosfils had a collection of
their cousin's work. Because the Belgian dentist refused to hand
them over, demanding proof that the cousins were legitimate heirs,
it was nine years before a Belgian court ruled in their favor. The
177 paintings they recovered were in dismal condition, damaged by
dirt and moisture and in some cases ripped.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
