<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOY-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW `JOY' IS CAUGHT IN A CLASH OF FOOD PHILOSOPHIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Joy of Cooking'' is the most famous American cookbook. That is
both an advantage and a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Early editions of ``Joy,'' first published in 1931 by Irma S.
Rombauer, are commonly described as the family bible. The recipes
are simple; the directions are clear. A revised edition published
last year by Scribner has sold about 900,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   But because of its fame, the book also gets its share of
potshots. Writing in the April issue of Food Technology, a
publication of the Institute of Food Technologists, Dr. Christine
Bruhn, the director of the Center for Consumer Research at the
University of California at Davis, criticized the book's food
safety and nutrition information, saying that the new version is
full of ``contemporary counterculture myths.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruhn, whose doctorate is in consumer behavior, claims that
the book is rife with scientific inaccuracies. But what Dr. Bruhn
is really criticizing is the book's philosophy, which runs counter
to hers and that of the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Its 28,000 members work in food science and technology and
related professions. The organization's belief that every
technological advance in food production _ irradiation and the
creation of fake ingredients like the fat substitute olestra _ is
good runs contrary to the book's philosophy that natural and
organic foods are more healthful and that factory farming is bad
for the animals and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruhn said that she felt ``betrayed'' by the new edition and
that ``the work was not carefully researched.'' ``I don't mind a
different philosophical approach,'' she said in an interview, ``but
if they are embracing an alternative culture, they should say so.''
</P>
<P>
   But the book's philosophy nothing new. It was even more clearly
stated in the 1975 edition, which adamantly called for taking care
of the environment and eating more legumes, grains and vegetables
and less meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joy'' is not entirely blameless in Dr. Bruhn's attack. Like
many cookbooks, it has a few errors, some having to do with food
safety advice. But Dr. Bruhn and the institute weaken their case
against the few mistakes by taking statements out of context, by
ascribing statements to the book that it does not contain and by
oversimplifying.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Guarnaschelli, the editor of the revision, acknowledged
that the book contains mistakes but said that Dr. Bruhn and the
institute ``made so many false claims it was hard to take the rest
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Joy of Cooking' was never a health book,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the institute's press release on Dr. Bruhn's
article, the book says that ``food additives lower the nutritive
value of food.'' The book contains no such statement. In fact, it
says that some additives, like vitamins, are good.
</P>
<P>
   A charge that the list of food allergens in the book does not
include peanuts and eggs, two common sources of food allergies, is
half right. Eggs were omitted and will be added in the next
printing, Ms. Guarnaschelli said.
</P>
<P>
   On food safety, the press release accuses ``Joy'' of saying that
``it is OK to use raw eggs in no-cook recipes.'' Such a statement
cannot be found in the book, which in fact has an extensive section
about the safety problems with uncooked eggs.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest philosophical differences between the institute
and the authors of the book relate to farming practices. Dr. Bruhn
and the the institute believe that factory farming and conventional
agriculture, both of which rely heavily on synthetic chemicals, are
safe and that organic farming is just one of those ``counterculture
myths.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Guarnaschelli makes no apologies. ``If anything the book has
a bias toward organic food and local agriculture,'' she said. Still
it does not make either of the following statements attributed to
it in the press release: ``Pesticide residues on fruit are at
unacceptable and hazardous levels,'' and ``Organic produce does not
need to be washed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruhn also said she did not appreciate the book's statement
that ``as poultry production moved from the barnyard to the
processing plant, both the quality and the safety of our poultry
were compromised.'' That is blaming ``animal agriculture for a
variety of sins without regard to scientific support,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But few scientists _ or people in the industry _ dispute the
fact that high levels of the harmful bacteria salmonella and
campylobacter in chickens are attributed to the conditions under
which they are raised and processed.
</P>
<P>
   There is one serious error in ``Joy of Cooking,'' the
recommendation to cook ground beef to 155 degrees: the Agriculture
Department recommends 160 degrees. And the book gives confusing
advice about washing fruits and vegetables. Ms. Guarnaschelli vowed
that these would be fixed in the next printing, expected within the
next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marion Nestle, professor and chairwoman of the nutrition and
food studies department at New York University and a consultant on
``Joy,'' said that if Dr. Bruhn and the institute were really
interested in fixing the errors, all they had to do was write a
letter to the editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a more insidious purpose,'' she said. ``To blame
problems of food safety on the `Joy of Cooking' and home cooks,
rather than on the food producers who are truly responsible.'' Dr.
Bruhn's column, she said, ``is not really about the book; it is
about the politics of food safety.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
