<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: A STAR RETURNS; GLIMMERGLASS STAGES `LILITH';
PROTESTERS ALARM CONCERTGOERS; THE KING REMEMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faith Prince is returning to Broadway, this time
opposite Martin Short in the revival of ``Little Me.'' Ms. Prince,
who won a Tony in 1992 for her portrayal of the feisty Miss
Adelaide in ``Guys and Dolls,'' will play Belle Poitrine, a poor
girl who stumbles her way through a series of madcap adventures and
unfortunate men, all of whom will be played by Short.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, with a book by Neil Simon, lyrics by Carolyn Leigh
and music by Cy Coleman, is scheduled to begin previews at the
Roundabout Theater Company in late September. The casting,
announced Tuesday by the Roundabout's artistic director, Todd
Haimes, brings Ms. Prince back to Broadway for the first time since
she left the revival of ``The King and I'' in December.
</P>
<P>
   Opera Emerges
</P>
<P>
   It has been a while coming, but it looks as if Deborah
Drattell's first opera, ``Lilith,'' will finally receive its
premiere. It was scheduled to be unveiled in June by the Dicapo
Opera Theater in Manhattan but was canceled because of a
contractual dispute involving the theater, the American Federation
of Musicians and the 92nd Street Y, the opera's co-producer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``Lilith'' is being staged by the Glimmerglass Opera in
Cooperstown, N.Y., which will present the work on Sunday. The opera
follows the story of Lilith, known in Jewish myth as the demonic
first wife of Adam, and her encounters with Eve. Ms. Drattell, 42,
was named the first composer in residence at the New York City
Opera last year.
</P>
<P>
   Movement Interrupted
</P>
<P>
   Whoever knew classical music fans _ nay, English classical music
fans _ could be so rowdy? At a concert on Monday night at Albert
Hall in London, a group of ``anti-modern music activists''
disrupted a performance of Oliver Knussen's ``Coursing'' by the
Birmingham Contemporary Music Group. The Evening Standard reported
that the protesters took over a balcony box, set off an alarm and
proceeded to dump leaflets on the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets called the concert, part of this month's Proms
series sponsored by the BBC, a ``banal grab bag of other people's
musical effects.'' The protesters then fled. No arrests were
reported and the concert continued after a brief delay, the
newspaper said, ``to tumultuous applause.''
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Redux
</P>
<P>
   The King is gone, but he's not forgotten. Sunday will be the
21st anniversary of Elvis Presley's death, but in Memphis, Tenn.,
the annual Elvis Week celebration has begun. Panel discussions
Tuesday featured people who had known Presley, including several
actresses who starred in his films.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tribute concerts each night, other attractions
include a seminar at the University of Memphis on Elvis' place in
musical history, and a five-kilometer ``Fun Run.'' Festivities end
this weekend with an all-night candlelight vigil followed by a
gospel brunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
