<HEADLINE>
A TASTE FOR THE OPERA  
 CEDAR-WRAP CHEESE 
MANHATTAN CHILI DELIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Operas preserved on tapes, disks and videos have long been the
stock in trade of the Metropolitan Opera's gift shops at Lincoln
Center. Now, to benefit the Metropolitan Opera Guild, an
educational and fund-raising division of the opera, the shops are
selling fruit preserves with operatic themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love for Three Oranges'' marmalade, an obvious choice, is
a dense, sufficiently tart spread. There is a ``Hansel and Gretel''
strawberry preserve, because the children were sent into the woods
to gather strawberries; it is rich and high quality, with plenty of
lush berries.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes a real opera buff to know that there is a ``Cherry
Duet'' in ``L'Amico Fritz'' by Pietro Mascagni, and the jam it
inspired is delicious, full of cherry flavor and thick with fruit.
</P>
<P>
   You're more likely to eat the jam than to see this rather
obscure work. The preserves, made for the Opera Guild by Clearbrook
Farms, are $13.95 for a 24-ounce jar. A set of three is $39.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American cheese makers continue to create products that dazzle
the palate. Trade Lake Cedar sheep's cheese, named best cheese on
Sunday at the American Cheese Society conference in Madison, Wis.,
is one such newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   It is made by Mary Falk near the town of Trade Lake in northwest
Wisconsin. The five-pound wheels are more than a foot in diameter,
nearly four inches thick and wrapped in cedar fronds. It's an ivory
cheese, firm but silky, and has a fruity, slightly tangy flavor
with a whiff of evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   It is $19.98 a pound at Fairway Market, 2127 Broadway (74th
Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132nd Street). At Murray's Cheese,
257 Bleecker Street (Cornelia Street), it is $15.99 a pound. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan Chili, 1500 Broadway, is unfortunate enough to have
its entrance on 43rd Street, directly across from the Conde Nast
construction site near Seventh Avenue. While workers dismantle
unstable scaffolding, the restaurant is closed, as is 43rd Street
between the Avenue of the Americas and Seventh Avenue. But its
kitchen, which has an entrance on Broadway, is open.
</P>
<P>
   So Manhattan Chili will deliver its chili and other Mexican
specialties Monday through Friday from 11:30 a.m. to 10 p.m. To
order: (212) 730-8666.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
