A8628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-2TAKES     08-11 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR QUICK WAYS TO BOOST A TOMATO'S POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this time of year you hear people say, ``Give me a good
tomato and I eat it like an apple.'' But no one actually does that,
at least not more than a couple of times a summer. Unlike peaches,
whose raw glory can barely be improved upon, tomatoes are all about
potential. The difference between consuming a tomato out of hand
and slicing it, then sprinkling it with a pinch of salt and a few
drops of olive oil, is the difference between a snack and a dish.
And the great thing about tomatoes is that it takes so little to
convert them from one to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Here are four recipes, none of which takes more than 20 minutes
to make, and all of which can contribute mightily to summer eating.
Cold tomato soup with rosemary is an almost instant starter,
requiring no cooking at all. It benefits from a period of chilling
after being put together, but if you use ice cubes in place of
chicken stock you can skip even that.
</P>
<P>
   Cumin-tomato relish and pan-grilled tomato salsa are both
multipurpose. The relish is uncooked _ simply chopped tomatoes
combined with seasonings. I add onion, red pepper and some cumin
seed for crunch, and serve it with grilled meats; it's also good on
hamburgers and sandwiches. Pan-grilled tomato salsa has a charred
flavor, combined with just enough oil and vinegar to make the whole
thing juicy; it's great on top of grilled fish or chicken, or as a
side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta with fresh tomato sauce is the dish I produce when good
plum tomatoes make their first appearance. It has a thick
creaminess that you can never duplicate with canned tomatoes, no
matter where they're from.
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes should always be cored before using: use a paring knife
to cut a cone-shaped wedge out of the stem end and remove it. But
peeling and seeding, a cumbersome process called for in many
cookbook recipes, are almost always optional. Sometimes I think it
even detracts from the final dish by reducing the amount of juice
in the tomato _ juice that contains the essence of tomato flavor.
(If you doubt this, slice some tomatoes and place them on a board
propped up at an angle. Salt them lightly and collect the juices
that flow off the board, then drink them _ no tomato juice ever
tasted so good.)
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to peel and seed tomatoes, here's the drill: Bring
a pot of water to a boil. Meanwhile, cut a small X on the smooth
(flower) end of each tomato. Place them into the boiling water. In
about 30 seconds, you'll see the skin begin to loosen. Immediately
remove them from the boiling water and plunge them into a bowl of
ice water. When they're cool, peel, then cut them in half through
their equators. Squeeze, and shake out the seeds. (You might
consider doing this over a strainer and recombining the reserved
juices with the pulp.)
</P>
<P>
   I'd perform this process _ which would nearly double the time it
takes to prepare the recipes here _ only in something like the cold
tomato soup with rosemary, where seeds and bits of skin might
interfere with the smooth texture of the soup. I also peel if I
have tomatoes that were coated with wax, an increasingly common
process that prolongs shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   COLD TOMATO SOUP WITH ROSEMARY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus time to chill  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 slices stale French or Italian white bread, crusts removed
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds ripe tomatoes, peeled, seeded and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh rosemary leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken stock or ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   The juice of 1 lemon, or more to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Soak bread in cold water briefly; squeeze dry, and combine in
a blender with tomatoes, rosemary and garlic (you may have to do
this in two batches). If using stock, turn on machine and drizzle
in the stock; blend until smooth. If using ice cubes, place them in
the blender and blend until mixture is smooth. Pour the mixture
into a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Season with salt and pepper, then add lemon juice to taste.
Chill and serve.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CUMIN-TOMATO RELISH  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cumin seeds, or 1{ teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds plum or other tomatoes, cored and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   { red bell pepper, seeded, stemmed and minced (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced onion
</P>
<P>
   Salt and cayenne pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one lime
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. If you're using cumin seeds, place them in a small skillet
and toast over medium heat, shaking the pan occasionally, just a
minute or two, until they are fragrant. Finely grind all but {
teaspoon.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine the ground cumin, the tomatoes, the optional pepper,
the onion, the salt, the cayenne and the lime juice; taste and
adjust seasoning if necessary. Just before serving, toss with the
cilantro and reserved cumin seeds.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 2 cups. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAN-GRILLED TOMATO SALSA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 large meaty tomatoes, cored and cut into thick slices
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sherry or balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat a large skillet, preferably cast iron or nonstick, over
medium-high heat for about 5 minutes. Add the tomatoes, raise the
heat to high and cook until lightly charred on one side, 3 to 5
minutes. Turn, and cook the other side very lightly, about 1
minute. If necessary, work in batches to avoid crowding the
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine the olive oil and vinegar in a large, shallow dish
and, as the tomatoes are done, turn them in the mixture. Season,
and serve as a side dish, or as a sauce for grilled or roasted fish
or chicken. (The salsa can be refrigerated for up to a day or two.
Bring to room temperature before serving.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PASTA WITH FRESH TOMATO SAUCE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ to 2 pounds tomatoes, cored and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound linguine, spaghetti or other long pasta
</P>
<P>
   { cup freshly grated Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of water to a boil, and salt it. Place the
butter or oil in an 8- or 10-inch skillet, and turn heat to medium.
When butter melts or oil is hot, add tomatoes and turn heat to
high.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cook, stirring occasionally, until tomatoes begin to juice
up, then turn the heat to low and keep warm, stirring occasionally,
while you cook pasta.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook pasta until it is tender but firm. Drain, and toss with
tomatoes and cheese. Season with salt and pepper, toss again and
serve immediately.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
