<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-GINGRICH-0812     08-11 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-GINGRICH-0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GINGRICH LAUDS IRISH FOR 'TAKING RISK FOR PEACE,' IGNORING
'EXTREME FACTIONS'
 &HT;    EDs: With optional add.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Midway through a bipartisan swing
across Ireland, House Speaker Newt Gingrich on Tuesday expressed
``cautious optimism'' for the sometimes fragile peace process here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that we have seen more movement in the last 12
months than one might have thought possible,'' Gingrich said after
meeting with representatives of both sides of the conflict that
ravaged this land for decades. ``The groups we met with today
consistently from every background wanted to see the process move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich made the remarks standing on the concrete foundation of
a Habitat for Humanity house he and other members of Congress and
their spouses helped get underway in a poor neighborhood here. The
spare cinderblock house is being built in Glencairn Estate, not far
from some of the city's toughest neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Seven members of the U.S. House of Representatives, their
spouses and a number of staff people and security personnel are
with the Georgia Republican on the seven-day tour through both
Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic to the south.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation met earlier in the day with representatives of
Sinn Fein, the political arm of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), as
well as Unionist leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message again and again is very simple: The agreement is
there, it's clear, it needs to be implemented,'' Gingrich said,
wearing jeans and a blue denim workshirt. ``This is a tremendous
opportunity to move forward for everybody and we hope that we can
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he had spoken about the trip to President Clinton,
who expressed support. Leaders across Ireland hope that a planned
trip by Clinton next month will boost the delicate peace process.
Most political parties here support the process, but the ``Good
Friday'' accord rests on the strength of an alliance between
opposing pro-Irish republican and pro-British unionist politicians.
Violence over the summer has tested this alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to admire the courage of those who have taken the
risk for peace,'' the speaker said. ``(The future of the accord)
probably depends on leaders having courage, and leaders deciding to
place their children's futures and the opportunity for peace and
for prosperity ahead of posturing and appealing to most of the
extreme factions. I think it's very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Option add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring a dozen or so shouting protesters who assailed Gingrich
as unsympathetic to gays and poor people, the speaker offered a
cagey response to a reporter who asked if he didn't harbor hopes of
returning to Belfast someday as president.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed and responded: ``I hope to come back here someday
under any circumstances, as either the speaker, retired speaker a
college professor -- or in some other job.''
</P>
<P>
   One side issue of the trip is Gingrich's desire to trace his
heritage in Donegal. On Thursday he will meet with an expert on the
genealogy of the O'Doherty family, the ancestors of his mother,
Kathleen Daugherty.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he knew little about his family's Irish roots.
``We think they came over in the 1840s, but beyond that I don't
really know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
