<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-11 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN CRIES WOLF WHISTLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stalked and harassed, made to feel unsafe in public places, the
victims of street abuse in Maggie Hadleigh-West's ``War Zone''
often generate their share of sympathy. Too bad, because in a film
that means to decry the treatment of women, a lot of the victims
are men.
</P>
<P>
   And these tragically benighted wolf-whistlers are turned into
prey by the filmmaker who hounds them. Dressed to stop traffic (or
at least slow it down marginally), Ms. Hadleigh-West roams city
streets with her Super-8 camera, cornering any fool who dares to
look her over.
</P>
<P>
   By her own calculations, she was annoyed by 1,050 insensitive
men during the five-week period when the film was shot.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ms. Hadleigh-West's confrontational tactics are meant to
turn the tables on male aggressors, they backfire spectacularly.
Out on the prowl, the filmmaker becomes her own worst enemy as she
refuses to make the slightest distinction between the smiling guy
who calls out ``Hello, beautiful'' and the vicious rapist who
prompts a 911 call.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of making what she has called ``a film that can
ultimately participate in the liberation of men,'' she dishes out
mocking sarcasm (``Oh, is that how you say hi, by whistling at a
woman on the street'') that discredits her arguments and even her
motives.
</P>
<P>
   Turning potentially serious material into a stunt that has made
her the toast of various talk shows, she appears to be having much
too good a time demanding attention and making men squirm.
</P>
<P>
   The pity of it is that within ``War Zone'' there are several
other women whose concerns about unwanted male attention sound more
serious and authentic and who describe them in much less
self-serving ways.
</P>
<P>
   But in those interviews with women of varied ethnic backgrounds,
the filmmaker typically treats racist slurs and lecherous
wisecracks as if they were interchangeable, showing no sense of
proportion about the abuses that are described.
</P>
<P>
   And in any case, the other women aren't given much screen time.
The bulk of the film is devoted to watching Ms. Hadleigh-West
create ambushes and get into shrill disputes, daytime television
style.
</P>
<P>
   The men's responses _ not the antique feminism of a woman who
takes offense even at ``Have a nice day'' and finds it outrageous
that strangers size each other up on the street for any reason _
give this documentary more verve than the filmmaker's one-note
attacks do.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no, no, 'cause as a matter of fact I'm gay,'' protests
a man accused of staring. ``May I just be alone right now and smoke
my pot?'' asks another. Then there's the guy who insists that
``Give it up, freak!'' has worked well for him as a come-on line,
or the worker in the crowd at lunchtime who makes a smooching
noise. (``Who did that?'' the filmmaker asks indignantly. ``Did you
do that?'')
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man accused of noticing Ms. Hadleigh-West's breasts
insists, quite plausibly, that he was only looking at the black
band around her arm because he thought it was a bandage and had a
similar injury of his own.
</P>
<P>
   While ``War Zone'' may be enough of a conversation piece to draw
the attention that other, better documentaries deserve, its
counterproductive effects are truly regrettable.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hadleigh-West is a filmmaker who asks questions like ``Sir,
are you ashamed of yourself?'' and describes how she laughed over
Lorena Bobbitt's attack on her husband. She reduces men to
insulting stereotypes while complaining that they do the same to
women, and she makes snide remarks like ``You're not aware of the
fact that women are assaulted and raped, sir?'' None of this does
feminism any favors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
