<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      08-11 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(HLW) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Slow improvement is expected across New England as low pressure
migrates into Nova Scotia. A large disturbance in the jet stream
will linger over the Northeast and this will trigger a few showers
into the Catskills and Poconos. Cooler air will combine with clouds
from Massachusetts northward to keep readings well below seasonal
levels. Drier winds from the North will promote intervals of
sunshine from the central Appalachians to the Middle Atlantic
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary between seasonal conditions over the Middle West
and a sultry air mass occupying the South will become stalled from
the Carolinas to Oklahoma. Clusters of showers and strong
thunderstorms will attend the front. The focus of heavy rain will
likely be in southern Georgia and northern Louisiana. South Texas
will be rather hot and sunny.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure crested over the central Great Lakes will produce
fine weather from the Mississippi Valley to the western
Appalachians. Sunshine will be abundant and winds will be light
along with comfortable humidity. Nighttime readings will drop into
the 40s in parts of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The return flow of humid air into the Rockies will invigorate
the monsoon. Afternoon thunderstorms will be widespread from New
Mexico to the Grand Canyon and northeast into Wyoming. Flash floods
are possible in a few spots. A surge of warm, humid air into the
upper Plains will cause a few thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   The interior West will be bright and a bit hotter. Offshore
winds from the Columbia River to near San Francisco will keep ocean
clouds away from the shore, but fog will return to the Northwest
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Sky Lights
</P>
<P>
   A red sunrise was observed over Illinois on Tuesday as smoke
drifted south from fires in Canada. Colors in the heavens are often
determined by the make-up and size of particles. For example, air,
which consists primarily of oxygen and nitrogen molecules, causes a
blue sky. Violet, blue, green, yellow, orange, and red, which
comprise sunlight, are scattered helter-skelter by air molecules.
But violet, blue, and green are scattered more than yellow, orange,
and red. Upon reaching the eye, the brain processes and integrates
the skewed assortment of colors so that we ``see'' the sky as blue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-LABOR-0812-COX     08-11 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LABOR-0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. CRITICIZES MEXICO FOR HEALTH AND SAFETY VIOLATIONS AT
TIJUANA FACTORY
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico has received another critical report from
the U.S. Labor Department, charging failure to enforce health and
safety laws at a Tijuana auto-parts factory.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Monday, is the first investigation under
the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) that could lead to
economic sanctions against a member country if Mexico fails to
address the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's report is the second part of a probe into allegations
of unchecked poor working conditions and unfair treatment of
independent union supporters at the Han Young ``maquiladora''
factory in Tijuana, a border city south of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Using a labor side accord established by NAFTA, Mexican and U.S.
labor activists filed complaints last year that Mexican officials
were not enforcing their own labor laws at the factory. The first
part of the report, issued in April, found that Mexico had failed
to protect the rights of Han Young employees to organize an
independent union.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to guarantee the right to unionize is not grounds for
sanctions against a NAFTA country. But failure to enforce health
and safety, child-labor and minimum-wage laws can lead to millions
of dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a financial incentive there, and the fact that there
could be substantial fines, brings pressure to bear in this case,''
said Mary Tong of the San Diego-based Maquiladora Support Group.
</P>
<P>
   Tong's group filed the complaints last year against the Mexican
government, along with the United Steelworkers of America, the
National Association of Democratic Lawyers of Mexico and other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The latest report on Han Young recommends that Mexican Labor
Secretary Jose Antonio Gonzalez and U.S. Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman hold ``ministerial consultations'' on allegations of health
and safety violations as well as union discrimination in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the safety and health of workers in the workplace
to be a high priority, and I'm certain the government of Mexico
shares this position,'' said Irasema Garza, secretary of the
National Administrative Office (NAO), a branch of the U.S. Labor
Department and issuer of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``By consulting on the safety and health issues raised in this
submission,'' Garza said, ``we hope to learn more about Mexican
efforts to improve in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Labor Department spokesman Fernando Irala said the
Mexican government had no comment because it had not yet received
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Under NAFTA, complaints about labor law violations can be
submitted to officials in Mexico, Canada, or the United States.
Mexican officials, for example, are investigating allegations that
U.S. labor officials have failed to protect the rights of migrant
apple pickers in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   But the Han Young complaint has become a primary test case for
promises that NAFTA would improve rather than degrade working
conditions in the member countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Han Young factory assembles truck chassis for Hyundai
Precision America, which sells vehicles to American consumers. Last
year, welders at the plant tried to organize a union to address
economic grievances and complaints that workers had suffered broken
bones, burns and possible respiratory illnesses and hearing loss
because safety standards were not followed.
</P>
<P>
   The workers were told they already had a union _ which was
linked to the Mexican government _ that would represent them. A
battle over union representation ensued that is still not resolved
today.
</P>
<P>
   On a diplomatic note, the latest U.S. report on Han Young says
that Mexico, by enacting new federal regulations in April 1997,
``has undertaken a serious effort'' to improve the enforcement of
its safety laws.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that Mexican officials had inspected the Han
Young plant and assessed fines of about $9,400. But U.S.
investigators also said they were unable to obtain proof that these
fines were ever collected, or increased as a result of subsequent
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious deficiencies continue at the workplace,'' U.S.
investigators add. ``The deterrent effect of inspections and
financial penalties is lost if they are not enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for a bilateral meeting to discuss these
allegations, but under NAFTA Mexico must respond to the U.S.
request for consultations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
