<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV18-     08-11 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEXIBLE ART OF PLAYING THE PONIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday Aug. 18)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dignified man seated next to me won on Constantly Classy and
I was impressed because I was holding a bet on another horse who
might have come in had she not decided to say ``whatever''
somewhere in the fourth furlong.
</P>
<P>
   Actually I had heard mention of Constantly Classy from the guys
who run a prerace seminar at the Sonoma County Fair - between the
pita sandwiches and the barbecued ribs stand - but was turned off
when they said this might be the day that Constantly Classy
``breaks her maiden.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed too gynecological for public discussion, even if it is
acceptable horse lingo and, I have learned, can refer to both a
male and a female horse.
</P>
<P>
   (For further edification, a maiden is a horse that has yet to
win a race. To break one's maiden is to win one's first race.)
</P>
<P>
   I've been learning something about horse racing, but alas not in
a moneymaking sort of way, since being asked by the sports editor
to be a guest handicapper. I told him that I take the common
people's approach to betting (clever names and jockey colors) and
mostly go to the fair for the sausage and pepper and onion
sandwiches but he said I would provide a good balance to the
horse-savvy handicappers.
</P>
<P>
   The guy next to me at the races didn't look like a long shot
sort of gambler. I had assessed him in the sidelong way you do
strangers with whom you share a close seat and narrow aisle and are
always apologizing for squeezing past.
</P>
<P>
   But I had decided from the way he stayed seated while all around
him people were yelling and doing victory wiggles over a $2 show
ticket that he was a more serious pony player.
</P>
<P>
   I was with my friend who knows more about horses than I do. For
example, she studies up on the jockeys and trainers and she can
explain the difference between a trifecta and a quinella wager and
so I begged her to be my phantom adviser.
</P>
<P>
   I continue to lose with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I invited her to actually go with me to the track so we
could play the horses up close. Some people had wrongfully assumed
I had been hanging out at the track every day, when what I've been
doing is studying the small print in the Daily Racing Form the
afternoon before the next day's race.
</P>
<P>
   I was in the grocery store on a recent 100 degree day and buying
a box of Eskimo Pies when a clerk said, ``Aren't you supposed to be
at the races?'' And I said, ``Like you really think I go there?''
</P>
<P>
   Going to the track was a lot more fun - nice afternoon breeze,
lovely view of the western hills - than looking at the racing
magazine and I took every opportunity to get inside real gambling
minds.
</P>
<P>
   When the man next to me announced that he had won big on
Constantly Classy, I asked about his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was ``dumb luck'' and I protested he was just being
modest but it turns out it was both. Dumb and luck.
</P>
<P>
   I have studied many approaches and believe that winning at
horses has something to do with horse sense and a little to do with
sixth sense (a psychic connection to names that remind you of
former boyfriends) and very much to do with dumb luck.
</P>
<P>
   The women in front of us at the races bet on horses with Irish
names and they didn't do that well. The women at my book club to
whom I passed out pages of the racing form tried to find names with
literary meaning. And we lost.
</P>
<P>
   I used to think that the reason I don't win big at the races is
because I don't bet big. Had I a chunk of money to throw around, I
would probably score wildly, I maintained. But since becoming a
temporary handicapper I have discovered that is not true because I
have been given more than $1,200 (of hypothetical money to
hypothetically bet) and I still do about as well as when I'm
nervously considering whether I can bet $2 of my own real money.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my male friends accused me of picking only female names
and I told them I would never be that transparent and that in fact
I had even tried using gender balance to score. Some days I would
bet on female owners of male-sounding horses. And vice versa. I
tried exotic names. I tried sexy names. I thought Undulating
Treasure would be irresistible, but hers were not the moves that
won.
</P>
<P>
   A betting pair who were studying the horses in the viewing area
before the race said they looked for horses with ``a good butt and
an attitude,'' which made me think of a friend's description of her
dream man.
</P>
<P>
   So, back to the stranger and Constantly Classy.
</P>
<P>
   She was the No. 5 horse in the seventh race, but when the man
went to bet he looked at the wrong page in the racing program. He
bet on the favored horse in the ninth race, which was No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   So he bet on the right horse in the wrong race and won.
</P>
<P>
   And that's my hot tip for the day.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
