<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-GINGRICH _ BELFAST, Ireland _ House Speaker Newt
Gingrich continues his week-long trip to Ireland today meeting with
leaders of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican
Army (IRA) and Catholic and Protestant leaders. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   BELARUS-INTERNET _ MINSK, Belarus _ In a dingy office not far
from the intersection of Lenin Avenue and Karl Marx Street, some
serious capitalism is being committed in the most Soviet of the
former Soviet republics. Belarus, a country of 10 million
sandwiched between Poland and Russia, has been noted for its
repression and lack of free enterprise in the seven years since the
Soviet Union disintegrated. Yet huddled around a computer terminal,
Olga Zauyalova, 20, and her partner Pavel Bintsarovski, 18, perform
an uncanny exercise in this country with little in the way of a
market economy: They create, produce, advertise and sell products,
competing via the World Wide Web. Unfortunately, their company --
appropriately called ``Alien'' -- is mere fiction, and their
profits are all on paper. But the whiz kids have excelled as part
of an international competition of young entrepreneurs. They are
among eight teams from six nations scheduled to compete in Atlanta
on Thursday (Aug. 13) in the Global Business Challenge, sponsored
by Junior Achievement International and the computer-equipment
maker Hewlett-Packard. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MOSCOW _ Trading in Russian stocks was
temporarily halted Tuesday because of a sharp selloff by investors
fearful that the economy is not strong enough to withstand capital
flight in emerging markets. Russian stocks and bonds have plummeted
in the past two sessions, amid widespread flight from emerging
markets. Investors fear that Russian markets in particular are too
feeble to withstand another onslaught of such selling. Traders said
the ruble was also slightly lower today, despite the heavy
intervention of the Russian Central Bank. Investors also worry the
loan won't be enough to allow Russia to prop up its currency.
Before the suspension of trading was announced, Deputy Prime
Minister Viktor Khristiyenko tried to calm the jittery markets:
``Default is not an issue here,'' he said. (Holmes, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 3 p.m. EDT. in both the (i) International and
(f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-LABOR _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexico has received another
critical report from the U.S. Labor Department, which cites health
and safety violations at a Tijuana maquiladora. The department is
urging ``ministerial'' level consulations between Mexico's
Secretary of Labor and Welfare and U.S. Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman. Under a special side agreement to NAFTA, this is the second
report issued on complaints about working conditions at the the Han
Young auto-parts factory in Tijuana. A previous report on Han Young
that attracted international attention found that Mexico had failed
to enforce laws guaranteeing the right to freely organize unions.
If health and safety laws are not enforced by a NAFTA member, that
country can face economic sanctions. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MINKS _ LONDON _ We're not making this up. In southern
England, some perturbed animal rights activists apparently have
freed thousands of minks to roam free. However, it appears that
these are hungry, nasty little creatures are eating local dogs,
chickens and small pigs. Believe it or not, it is causing a great
deal of alarm here. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ISRAEL _ JERUSALEM _ The waitress could see that my
parents and I were novices. Huddled with a few Israelis in the
bathroom corridor of a downtown sandwich shop, we waited for word
that the suspicious object down the street had been deemed
harmless. ``Is this your first time?'' said our server with a big,
friendly smile. Such friendly smiles might be a rarity in this
tense city, but bomb scares are not. Minutes later, we were allowed
back to our table. Israeli bomb specialists were putting their
armor vests back into their van. After a year as Cox Newspapers'
Middle East correspondent, I realized, during this visit from my
parents, that I'm getting used to conditions that most Americans
would find unnerving and most Israelis barely notice. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story is for use on Thursday, Aug. 13. and is being
resent for those who have not used it and to kick off a weekly
installment of journals for Cox Newspapers' foreign correspondents.
It originally moved Tuesday, Aug. 11, in both the (i) International
and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
