</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADISE-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PARADISE' FOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; If you like the way Vince Vaughn, Anne Heche and
Joaquin Phoenix act together in the dramatic film ``Return to
Paradise,'' opening Friday, you're in luck. Vaughn and Phoenix will
come back in October in the darkly comic thriller ``Clay Pigeons,''
and by the end of the year we should see Vaughn and Heche check
into the Bates Motel for Gus Van Sant's controversial remake of
Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   Though partially just an accident of casting, the three actors
couldn't be happier about the way their burgeoning careers are
dovetailing with one anothers' (``Pigeons'' was filmed before
``Paradise''; ``Psycho'' is wrapping up production now). ``I really
respect Vince as an actor,'' says Phoenix, whose work ranges from
Ron Howard's cuddly ``Parenthood'' to Van Sant's sardonic ``To Die
For.'' ``He's very talented and we both are really passionate about
making films. We just really hit it off on `Clay Pigeons,' which we
both really believed in, then in this second one together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole thing is just to try to be real, try to be truthful
with all of it, with acting,'' says Vaughn, who made his first big
splash as the sublimely superficial party animal in ``Swingers,'' a
film made by another set of friends. ``I think that you're
perceived as something of a weirdo if you work that way, but Anne
and Joaquin have that approach, too. That really feels good for me
as an actor; it gives you a chance to honestly explore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very intriguing when you get a script like this, that
could really make people think,'' Heche (``Six Days, Seven
Nights'') says of ``Paradise,'' which was written by Wesley Strick
(``Cape Fear,'' ``Wolf'') and Bruce Robinson (``The Killing
Fields,'' ``Withnail &AMP; I''). ``And it's not just what's on the
page. When actors like Vince and Joaquin are attached, you start
going wow, there's even more potential here.''
</P>
<P>
   A kind of ethical suspense story, ``Paradise'' plots the
relationship of three carefree young American guys _ Vaughn's
Sheriff, Phoenix's Lewis and David Conrad's Tony _ who meet during
an extended vacation in Southeast Asia. Sheriff and Tony head home
to New York while Lewis, who wants to help endangered orangutans,
stays on in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, limo driver Sheriff is confronted by Beth
(Heche), a lawyer representing Lewis. He's been in prison since
they left, for drug dealing _ seems he was caught with the hashish
Sheriff and Tony didn't pack _ and will be executed within a week
unless one or both of his holiday friends returns to Malaysia and
admits some of the contraband was theirs. This would mean stiff
prison sentences for the confessors, but it's the only way Lewis'
life will be spared.
</P>
<P>
   Between Beth trying to persuade the reluctant Sheriff to do the
right thing and Sheriff's own nagging sense of responsibility for
Lewis' predicament, ``Paradise'' offers ample opportunity for
exploring complex motivations and ever-changing, emotion-charged
relationships. And that's just what the ensemble delivered,
according to director Joseph Ruben (``Sleeping With the Enemy,''
``True Believer'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince and Anne met on this movie, and from the very first
rehearsal it was clear that they just connected as people and as
actors,'' says Ruben. ``They both work in a way that directors just
love to have actors work. They really respond to what's going on in
a scene. A lot of actors, good actors, come in knowing exactly what
they're going to do. It can be strong, but they give you the same
thing take after take, regardless of what the other actors are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Vince and Anne, if one of them changed the other would
change; they would play off and react to each other. What you get,
if the actors really work that way, is really strong, in-the-moment
acting. You get a different level of reality and it gets very alive
and unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's previously established, professional friendship with
Phoenix informed their ``Paradise'' work in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I cast Joaq, I didn't know they had worked together,''
Ruben recalls. ``But it added a level of emotion to the movie.
There are scenes where Vince is legitimately moved by Joaquin, and
when he imagined his friend in this situation, it just brought up
so much genuine feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think acting is acting. But the best acting, obviously,
is you're so in the circumstances of what you're doing that what
happens is real. Having somebody that you actually care about
sitting in that cell changed everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming ``Clay Pigeons,'' Vaughn and Phoenix also
portray a beautiful friendship. From hell.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is Clay, a gas station attendant in a small Montana town
who innocently (more or less) finds himself implicated in a string
of violent deaths. Vaughn is Lester, a big-hearted, cowboyish
trucker who befriends the troubled young man _ and who just may be
the devil in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really an internal exploration, so I wanted to play Clay
very subtly,'' Phoenix explains. ``Vince's character is the
animated one in the film, and his doing that allowed me to play
somebody who's discovering himself and trying to come to terms with
the good and bad that's inherent in all of us. Vince's character is
almost a figment of my imagination, the devil on my shoulder who
takes advantage of the time when I'm most vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Lester as not even literal,'' Vaughn adds. ``He's more
of a demon. Because Clay made mistakes in his life, this force came
into it and he couldn't get him out by fighting him or telling
anyone about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester was perhaps good training for Norman Bates, the most
infamous embodiment of mad evil in the annals of cinema. Still
Vaughn, as well as Heche, know that they're risking the wrath of
cineastes everywhere who simply don't want to accept anyone except
Anthony Perkins and Janet Leigh in the classic horror story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you don't get a fair shot out of the gate with it and
I understand why, because people like the first one,'' Vaughn says.
``But I just think people should be open to the fact that
everything _ music, plays _ is meant to be exploited and
reinterpreted. It's almost 40 years later and it's time. And so
far, it's been fun and, I think, really worthwhile. As actors,
we've been having a ball with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince and I were able to encourage each other much quicker
than we would have been able to with somebody else who we didn't
know or work similarly with,'' Heche adds. ``Especially since Vince
is really going into such strange depths, I'm glad to have been
there for him to get into that. We both trusted each other on these
new characters.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so, in fact, that tabloids have speculated that the
``Psycho'' stars are having an affair _ which is about as absurd as
recent tab reports that Phoenix's girlfriend, Liv Tyler, was
responsible for the breakup of her ``Armageddon'' co-star Bruce
Willis' marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's insane,'' notes Heche, whose relationship with comedian
Ellen DeGeneres has been an ongoing media obsession for more than a
year. ``How many times do I have to say I tell the truth? It's
gross. What's behind it is that some people don't want Ellen and me
to be in love as we are, and that's kind of sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I would like people to understand that
actors can just have joyous working relationships and let that
stand for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sometimes they do become more than that. Vaughn, for
example, is currently dating Joey Lauren Adams (``Chasing Amy''),
with whom he co-stars in another upcoming movie, the family drama
``A Cool, Dry Place.''
</P>
<P>
   But romance is one thing. Finding colleagues with whom you can
really enjoy creating different, daring movies is an almost equally
special _ and about as rare _ pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne and Joaq are both great actors, in my opinion, and
they're easy to get along with,'' Vaughn observes. ``You can go out
on a limb and they're there for you, and vice versa. And they're
also both bright, fun and easygoing. You don't have to call them by
their character names on the set and that junk. They jump in,
they're totally committed and you can trust them. But then they can
jump out and be regular, kid around and that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Vaughn, Phoenix and Heche deny that they're actively
looking for more work to do together. To at least one informed
observer, though, it seems inevitable that the team will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all three of these actors will work together again in
different combinations,'' director Ruben says. ``To me, they're
about as good as any three young actors working in this country
right now. In different ways, they're all exceptional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
