r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPPER-SPRAY-HNS &LR;      08-11 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPPER-SPRAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA DEPUTIES DEFEND USE OF PEPPER SPRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sheriff's deputies were ``courteous'' and
``compassionate'' when they daubed pepper spray on the eyes of
several already immobile environmental protesters, their lawyer
told a jury.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for the demonstrators, however, described the
police action as the needless infliction of pain on defenseless
people, a ``new and unorthodox use of pepper spray that has not
been sanctioned by law enforcement anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as trial opened Monday on whether the use of
pepper spray by deputies in Humboldt County violated the
protesters' civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker of San Francisco is presiding
over the case brought by nine demonstrators against the Humboldt
County Sheriff's Department, Sheriff Dennis Lewis, Chief Deputy
Gary Philp and the Eureka Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dispute that the protesters illegally trespassed and
refused to disperse, or that the deputies had the right to arrest
them. Rather, the suit stems from three separate pepper spray
episodes during the protests last fall against logging of ancient
redwoods along California's North Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Macon Cowles, the lead lawyer for the plaintiffs, began by
telling the jury of two men and six women that his clients were
nonviolent participants in what have become perennial ``symbolic
protests'' against harvesting of rare trees that ``date to the time
of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 25, 1997, four protesters locked themselves to 25-pound
pieces of pipe at the Scotia office of the Pacific Lumber Co. When
they refused to unlock themselves, deputies used cottons swabs to
dab the noxious substance in the corners of the protesters' eyes.
Two protesters unlocked themselves, but deputies still had to cut
loose the other two.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 3, 1997, two demonstrators locked themselves between the
tracks of a bulldozer on the lumber company's property. This time
the deputies daubed their eyes with the caustic chemical and gave
each a ``full face shot'' from less than three feet away, Cowles
said. Even then, the men did not unlock themselves and deputies had
to cut the pipe, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 16, 1997, protesters deposited a tree stump and sawdust
in the Eureka office of Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., and four women
locked their hands and legs to it.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists targeted Riggs because they saw him as a
promoter for the logging industry, Cowles said. The deputies held
back the women's eyelids and swiped cotton swabs on their eyes, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowles contended the incidents violated the county's written
rules on using the spray, an ``off the books'' use of what is a
``good tool'' when used properly.
</P>
<P>
   The spray incapacitates its subjects with severe pain, coughing,
twitching eyes, temporary loss of upper body control,
disorientation and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Delaney, the deputies' attorney, said they acted properly.
The deputies applied the spray safely to counter what they saw as
dangers posed by cutting through heavy locks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she said, the demonstrators used standard bicycle
locks that deputies could sever with bolt-cutters. Then they used
heavier locks that required grinders. In these incidents, they used
pieces of pipe weighing some 25 pounds, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies feared using the grinders to remove the locks would
spark a fire or cut the protesters, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She described the spray _ made of cayenne pepper and known
scientifically as oleoresin capsicum _ as ``a natural, organic
food-grade product.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the incidents, Philp researched the issue and consulted
with the Humboldt County district attorney's office and the county
risk assessment officer, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies intensified the applications only when initial
efforts did not achieve the desired effect, she said, adding that
they were ``courteous, compassionate'' and washed the spray off
with water as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, who do not claim they were permanently injured,
seek unspecified payments for pain and suffering and a finding that
the applications violated the Fourth Amendment's ban on
unreasonable seizures of their bodies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
