<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE FACES TOUGH CHOICES IN SENTENCING CONVICTED KILLER, 11 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An 11-year-old California boy convicted of
involuntary manslaughter for shooting his 13-year-old neighbor
could become the youngest of the 8,200 inmates in the California
Youth Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Or he could go back to his parents and be placed on probation
and in an outpatient counseling program.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal justice system has a complex mission when dealing
with the youngest of violent offenders. For an adult, the gravity
of such crimes may merit lengthy terms behind bars. But judges and
criminal justice professionals have much more leeway with minors,
where the primary goal remains rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Juvenile Court Judge Lois Haight found the Antioch boy
guilty of involuntary manslaughter in the slaying of Larry Kiepert,
who was shot through the head with a 30.06-caliber rifle bullet
while he and family members were playing basketball in their back
yard.
</P>
<P>
   Because she could discern no malice in the June 6 shooting,
Haight said, she was unable to find the boy guilty of murder. But,
she said, the defendant had known the weapon was loaded and
intentionally fired the gun.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the boy had shown ``deceptive behavior'' after the
shooting by lying about the incident and trying to hide evidence by
flushing the bullet casing down a toilet. But she found that he had
acted without malice, citing ``his age, his average intelligence
and his lack of serious misbehavior before this terrible
incident.''
</P>
<P>
   In cases involving very young offenders, judges, prosecutors and
probation officers must make tough decisions as to whether the
offenders were aware enough of the gravity of their actions to be
held criminally responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at the element of when they did what they did,
and did they know what they were doing is wrong,'' said Contra
Costa County Deputy District Attorney Harold Jewett.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial of the Antioch boy, prosecutors contended that
the boy had fired in revenge because Kiepert had shot him in the
leg with a BB gun two days earlier. But defense attorneys argued
the shooting had been an accident. They argued that the youngster
couldn't even have seen Kiepert when the gun went off.
</P>
<P>
   Haight is scheduled to sentence the youth Sept. 8. Depending on
what she decides, the boy could go to the Youth Authority, where he
could spend the next 10 years, or be sentenced to probation and
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney William Gagen expressed hope his client would
be rehabilitated instead of punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Counseling is absolutely essential,'' he said, adding his
belief that there was no crime because his client, who was home
alone on the day of the shooting, didn't have the capacity to know
the consequences of his actions while playing with his father's
hunting rifle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
