<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROLLOPE'S STAR RISING AGAIN, WITH REASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My formal introduction to Victorian literature was in high
school. Charles Dickens was its centerpiece, and we read works by
William Makepeace Thackeray, George Eliot, the sisters Bronte,
Wilkie Collins, a few others ... but the name of Anthony Trollope
was not mentioned in the course, nor were any of his books on the
reading list.
</P>
<P>
   My first acquaintance with the Trollope byline occurred back
when hardbound Modern Library editions cost 95 cents. I bought
``The Eustace Diamonds'' but only read it sometime later when
Trollope was an obligation in college study, although still ranked
beneath those aforementioned others.
</P>
<P>
   An anecdote rendered professorially was that Anthony Trollope
would complete a novel in the morning, knock off for lunch, and
begin a new novel in the afternoon. From his first novel, published
in 1847, to the last one issued posthumously in 1883, the Trollope
writing machine ground out 47 large novels and a smattering of
nonfiction, including what may be the best autobiography by a
19th-century author.
</P>
<P>
   More amazing still, Anthony Trollope (1815-1882) was, over more
than half of his authorial tenure, a full-time employee of the
General Post Office in London. His strong work ethic was prodded by
happiness in his work; and as an author, he was enamored of a world
of his own invention.
</P>
<P>
   That world was and is Barset, an imaginary county in the west of
England. Barchester is its principal town; and of Barset, Trollope
in his autobiography reported that ``I had it all in my mind, its
roads and railroads, its towns and parishes ... throughout these
stories, there has been no name given to a fictitious site which
does not represent to me a spot of which I know all the
accessories, as though I had lived and wandered there.''
</P>
<P>
   The six Barset novels, appearing from 1855 to 1867, are ``The
Warden,'' ``Barchester Towers,'' ``Doctor Thorne,'' ``Framley
Parsonage,'' ``The Small House at Allington'' and ``The Last
Chronicle of Barset.'' With these books, Trollope effectively
established the novel sequence in English fiction. Thus he emulated
Balzac's ``La Comedie Humaine'' with the device of background
characters reappearing in the various novels.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Trollope fictions is a second six-novel sequence,
popularly known as the Palliser novels, after the family of
Plantaganet Palliser that populates every tale. These, issued from
1864 to 1880, are ``Can You Forgive Her?,'' ``Phineas Finn,'' ``The
Eustace Diamonds,'' ``Phineas Redux,'' ``The Prime Minister'' and
``The Duke's Children.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the Palliser sequence was served honorably by
BBC's Masterpiece Theater. To what extent this raised Trollope's
stature internationally is difficult to determine; but for whatever
reasons, the Trollope star has risen, is rising still, and on both
sides of the Atlantic he now outstrips Thackeray and almost every
Victorian Brit except Dickens, whom he reasonably threatens.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, I knew little about Trollope's mother, who gets
short shrift in his autobiography. She was Frances Trollope
(1780-1863), who made an unfortunate marriage that produced many
offspring. To earn a living for her brood, she made several
business ventures and failed in all of them until, past age 50, she
took up a writing career.
</P>
<P>
   She then attained fame writing more than 40 books, mostly novels
that were quite popular in their time and are now forgotten and
probably worthless. But she was a woman of extraordinary energy, a
fitting subject for a biography, and now there is one _ ``Fanny
Trollope,'' on Viking's fall list. Perhaps the most provocative
aspect of Pamela Neville-Sington's study is the abrasive
relationship between Fanny and son Anthony, fueled by mutual
jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   The Trollopes, then, are a dynasty; and direct descendant Joanna
Trollope writes popular novels today. The recognition gap is
effectively closed, and we expect to hear more and more about
Anthony and other Trollopes.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8719 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-MODEL-KANSAS-     08-11 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MODEL-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEL OF PERSEVERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marc Levitz knows a little about how hitting bottom feels.
</P>
<P>
   For a few weeks last fall in Milan, Italy, he felt painfully
close. Some days he was cold, hungry, low on money and living in
low-grade Italian hotels, all for the sake of modeling jobs that
did not come.
</P>
<P>
   When he told his mother, Meryl Levitz of Overland Park, how much
he weighed she was so alarmed that she shipped him vitamins. ``I
kept saying, `Why don't you just come home?' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Levitz, 27, is a graduate of the University of Kansas and Blue
Valley North High School. These days his head is shaved as smooth
as marble tile. He has a formidable, complex tattoo occupying much
of his upper right arm, clear, piercing blue-green eyes, a thrift
shop wardrobe and a youthful sense of confidence that some might
call attitude.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a gripping tenacity that kept him pushing until late
last year, when his modeling career suddenly went into orbit. In
January he was booked in eight of the prestigious Milan menswear
runway shows, including well-known names such as Krizia and Giorgio
Armani. He also appeared in the Giorgio Armani campaign, which will
be part of the print ads in U.S. magazines this fall.
</P>
<P>
   He worked even more of the fall menswear shows earlier this
summer. And to his own surprise, he was recently voted No. 10 among
the top 10 male models by a European fashion magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want something bad enough, you get it,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Home for a brief visit recently, Levitz recalled how as a kid he
began to think modeling was ``kind of cool'' after watching models
on television and seeing photographs of his mother, who modeled
early in her life.
</P>
<P>
   He had a couple of jobs in high school and then nothing. He went
on to study advertising and marketing in college. ``I was a
terrible student,'' he said, remembering how he barely squeaked
through to graduation. A job in advertising lasted six months. ``I
just can't see myself sitting at a desk, holding a real job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago Levitz packed up his belongings and left
home for Los Angeles, where he made the rounds of agencies, waited
tables and picked up an occasional modeling job. His mother wasn't
surprised. ``When he was about 14, he started saying, `I'm going to
move to California.' I said, `No you're not.' And he said, `Yes I
am.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One late night after a long shift, the manager of a restaurant
where he worked _ ``my very beautiful manager,'' as he puts it with
a smile _ suddenly suggested that he shave off his collar-length
curly hair. He obliged without a second thought. The hair was
beginning to thin out up front anyway, and he found the idea of
transplants and other hair-growth treatments disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   His mother saw his new look for the first time when she spotted
him on a country music video, but she took it in stride. He was
always trying to be different, she said, even as a young teen-ager
when he insisted on dyeing his dark hair blond. He turned it orange
at one point.
</P>
<P>
   But in an industry where image is everything and quirky is
rewarded, it often pays off to set yourself apart. Modeling work
began to pick up, he said, and he started to think about Milan.
Last summer after his truck was totaled in an accident, Levitz used
the insurance payment to buy a plane ticket. Life would never be
quite the same.
</P>
<P>
   Levitz's adventures started when he arrived in Brussels,
Belgium, prepared to sleep in the airport during a long layover. He
spotted a friend from Los Angeles, who invited him to come with her
and stay with her friends. They welcomed him into their home, and
when he left his thank-you gift was American toilet tissue he had
packed in his bag.
</P>
<P>
   When he first arrived in Italy, he stayed in youth hostels, but
because he had to leave with all his things every morning and
return that night, he kept moving around as one without a home.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, he was having no luck with modeling agencies.
``Sometimes the guy wouldn't even look at my book. He'd just be
thumbing through it and talking to someone,'' Levitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally he signed with the Major agency. He ultimately moved
into a cold-water residence hotel with other models. He began to
make friends and found a certain camaraderie among other young men
with similar aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   He learned how to make his way around Milan and quickly mastered
the art of tricking the Milanese transit system by reusing his
paper metro ticket. ``Why not? You're poor. And you get bored. It's
something to do,'' he said as he explained how he and his friends
had a way of slipping through the turnstile when the transit
security wasn't watching or, on occasion, backing one another up to
intimidate the officers when they tried to apprehend them.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Levitz found a supportive friend in his agency
booker, Mossimo Tacchini. ``He gave me money out of his pocket,''
Levitz said. ``I would go to his house and we'd talk for hours.''
</P>
<P>
   And toward the end of the year he started to get bookings for
print ads. He had used a credit card to buy a ticket for a quick
Christmas trip back to the United States, and he even postponed his
trip because of work possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   After he returned on New Year's Day from a Christmas with his
cousin in New Jersey, groggy from his own New Year's celebration
overnight, he was sent off on a round of go-see appointments to the
design houses.
</P>
<P>
   A few days into the week, as he tried to find his way from place
to place, Levitz stopped to call his booker, who told him what
turned out to be very good news. He was on reserve for the Emporio
Armani, a collection by Giorgio Armani, a youthful, less expensive
version of Armani's signature line. It was a turning point. When he
did the show he was so impressed with Armani the man, whom he found
to be so professional and polite, that he considered it the best
moment of his career.
</P>
<P>
   After he worked for Armani the first season, he was
automatically booked for the next one. And then he was hired for
the Armani fall book, from which the ads were chosen.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a challenging year indeed. He credits his parents
with giving him encouragement and support. ``My dad took care of my
financial affairs. I mean, he made sure I paid my bills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still a little incredulous about his life, Levitz is not sure
what happens next. ``I don't know if it was just luck or what,'' he
said of the past few months. When he left Kansas City recently, he
was to try out for a charity runway show in San Francisco and then
return to Milan. He hopes to hit the modeling scene in Paris soon
and then New York, certainly more competitive than European cities.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first to admit his life is not perfect. ``I don't have
a real apartment. I don't have a dog. I don't have a car,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he knows it's not bad. He has enough free time to read books
_ in recent months 30 something, including Jack Kerouac and some on
Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   He is enjoying a certain visibility. His grandparents were
sitting in a doctor's office in New Jersey not long ago when they
were surprised to spot him in a magazine. Relatives in Florida had
similar experiences. His mother is busy collecting the books she
can find.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ideal? He sees himself working about five years,
saving some money and settling with a family somewhere in
California.
</P>
<P>
   With his focus, it could happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
