<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good leather ahead
</P>
<P>
   OK. Not everyone is up to sashaying about in a leather cat suit
and it's certainly not a sight we want to see. But when Uma Thurman
crawls into Emma Peel's skin (literally in leather) in the new film
remake of the television series ``The Avengers,'' her cool wardrobe
could provide some hot fashion do's and don'ts for the stylishly
inclined.
</P>
<P>
   Peel's image is rooted, of course, in the '60s, and the familiar
leather cat suit was a must, says costume designer Anthony Powell.
But she couldn't wear that every day, so his challenge was to go
beyond it with a wardrobe suited to Thurman's style, reminiscent of
the '60s and representative of the '90s. To make them fit in the
same image as the cat suit, everything else she wears is form
fitting or made of suede and leather, including the eye-catching
pink leather suit.
</P>
<P>
   Consistency is a ploy to consider if you think your clothes are
disjointed and project no particular fashion style.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ralph Fiennes wardrobe as John Steed could indeed be
inspiration for every man. His suits were made by Savile Row
tailoring shops, including the bowler hat, from a company in
service to the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   Man, you're looking good
</P>
<P>
   For men who are not sure whether to vent with suits, or are
slightly challenged when it comes to combing hair over the balding
spots, Men's Health magazine offers the quintessential Guide to
Style in the back of the September book. There is even a fold-out
``Cheat Sheet'' poster to prep you for shopping trips.
</P>
<P>
   Some tips:
</P>
<P>
   - If you wear a single vent jacket, don't put your hands in your
trouser pockets. The spread will expose your rear end. Bad form.
</P>
<P>
   - The correct length for trousers: With pants waist precisely at
your waist, the front of your trouser leg should rest on the top of
your shoe with a slight fold.
</P>
<P>
   - You'll know your comb-over ploy _ the practice of using hair
from thick spots to cover thin _ is too obvious and you need to see
your barber if your bangs begin at the back of your head and you
are not George Clooney or a cast member of ``Friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
