<HEADER>
A8725 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACTERIA-FOOD-2NDTAKE     08-11 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACTERIA-FOOD-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES TEST VACCINES TO KEEP HARMFUL BACTERIA OUT OF FOOD
CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) ... Traditionally these companies have made treatments
aimed at keeping herd and flock animals healthy. In recent years,
however, each has developed or is researching products that would
protect animals against salmonella or E. coli, which often don't
make animals sick but can be deadly to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccines stimulate the body's natural defenses against an
infection. Similar treatments using what's called competitive
exclusion, stimulate good bacteria in animals' guts to keep bad
bacteria from getting started.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense suggests that immunizing the animals we eat against
these bacteria is a good idea. To understand why this approach is
new requires understanding the anatomy of the meat and egg
industries and of animals themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Chu, vice president of biological research development and
regulatory affairs for Fort Dodge, said animal producers saw no
reason to invest in drugs to treat against microbes that didn't
affect their animals. These bacteria generally live in the animals'
gut, instead of muscles, and are simply passed out in their
excrement.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, Chu said, the companies that raised animals had no
faith that operators of meat-packing plants were doing enough to
guard against these microbes getting into meat. Without safeguards
in food-processing plants, the investment by the hog grower or
cattle producer would be for naught.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was fecal or environmental contamination,'' Chu
said, ``it might come at the packing plants or processing plant,
what used to be called slaughterhouses.''
</P>
<P>
   That is an issue that still needs to be addressed, said John
Phillip, a vice president for research with Bayer Animal Health in
Merriam, Kan. ``The big issue is who pays and who gets the benefit?
A company can vaccinate but not get the premium payment from the
person who buys the meat.''
</P>
<P>
   This is changing, Chu said. Since January large meat and poultry
companies have been forced by new federal regulations to reduce the
level of pathogens in the animals they raise and process. They must
establish processes to guard against bacteria getting into their
products.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was resistance to the new regulations, companies
now are making investments to reduce bacteria, said Bill Roenigk,
vice president of the National Broiler Council, a trade association
representing most of the food chicken producers in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Many poultry producers, he said, now see the value of treating
chickens with vaccines or competitive exclusion products. These are
one of many ways producers are using to reduce pathogens in their
flocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irradiation can do the same thing but it is not something
consumers see as natural,'' Roenigk said. ``Consumers understand
vaccines and good bacteria and are more accepting of that.''
</P>
<P>
   These advances are what has prompted many animal-health
companies to begin investing in research on vaccines, thinking
there now may be a market. Research spending on biologicals has
increased 155 percent to $101.8 million since 1987, according to a
trade association for animal-health companies.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers and restaurant workers make up the final piece of the
foodborne illness equation. The general belief is that if they cook
food to about 160 degrees Fahrenheit, then pathogens would be
killed and people wouldn't get sick. But it is isn't that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be avoided but probably that is asking too much of
mankind,'' said Joan Leonard, a partner in Biomune and creator of
its key vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers are ignorant of how to prevent food contamination
in their own kitchens. It might not occur to consumers that taking
cooked hamburgers off the grill and putting them on the same plate
that held the raw patties could contaminate the cooked food.
</P>
<P>
   There are many new programs by the meat industry and others to
inform consumers about how to prevent food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we expect consumers to take responsibility, you have to
educate them,'' said Scott of the National Food Processors
Association.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
