<HEADER>
A8727 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORISM-NEW-FORM-KA     08-11 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-NEW-FORM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S TERRORISM IS FRIGHTENING IN BOTH ITS COMPOSITION AND
RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ The terrorists who murdered Missourian Kenneth R.
Hobson II last week when they blew up the American Embassy in Kenya
almost certainly didn't know his name or face.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the rest of the more than 200 people they
killed or the 5,000 people they injured in the two almost
simultaneous embassy bombings. The casualties of Friday's terrorist
attacks were employees and pedestrians in the wrong places at the
wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   But the terrorists were part of a new breed of extremists that
both puzzle and worry experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, we thought we understood something about
terrorism,'' said University of Kansas political scientist Philip
Schrodt. ``The classic example was some dramatic event that
attracted attention for a cause, a kidnapping or a hijacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was more like the Lockerbie airplane bombing or
Oklahoma City. There was no message attached to the action. No one
claimed responsibility. They don't seem even to have been out to
impress anyone. The only point seems to have been to kill people,
and maybe just to kill Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies a problem for this country: How does a nation
deal with an invisible enemy?
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Monday announced a $2
million reward for information leading to the arrests of the
bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although terror can turn buildings to rubble and laughter to
tears, it can never, will never, deter America from its purpose or
presence around the globe,'' she told State Department employees.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the United States is sending several hundred investigators
to the bomb scenes to help determine who's responsible.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is much deeper than that. What experts see
emerging from the embassy rubble is just one more puzzle piece from
the new world of international terrorism, which creates a picture
that is almost wholly random.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Kisangani Emizet, a professor and expert in
African politics at Kansas State University, said that by logic,
the bombings should have happened elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no strong anti-American feelings in Kenya and
Tanzania,'' he said. ``That is why this is such a puzzle. Perhaps
those who did this came from elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years after terrorism began replacing guerrilla warfare
as a violent outlet for those seeing themselves as oppressed, the
rules are changing.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer Nudell, a counter-terrorism expert from Virginia, noted
that terrorists used to try to avoid mass death, especially among
those not involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think back 20 or 30 years to the attacks by the Red Brigade,
where extreme actions including kidnapping,'' he said. ``The
Weathermen did plant bombs. But they were attempting to publicize
their agendas. And killing people on this scale would have been
seen as counterproductive to the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims today are discounted as unimportant, at best. In many
cases, they are dehumanized. In the United States, this is seen
inside white supremacist camps, where minorities and Jews are
literally classified as subhuman. Among Islamic extremists, America
is classified as ``The Great Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   And in many cases, killing these targets is seen as the reason
behind the terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
   This is unlike decades past, when the largest terrorist groups
had either nationalist agendas (a free Northern Ireland, a
Palestinian homeland, a free Albania) or ideological agendas
(pro-communism, anti-capitalism).
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd hijack a passenger plane and _ with cameras rolling _
blow it up in the desert,'' Schrodt said. ``But first they let off
the passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   But such public actions may have led to this more secretive
brand of terrorists. Brent Smithy, a University of
Alabama-Birmingham terrorism expert, said that, over time,
counter-terrorism efforts thinned the ranks of those making public
demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shift away from the public action is so that terrorists
can survive to attack again,'' he said. ``In the past, terrorists
were looking to make a point. Today, they're looking to avoid
detection, detention and prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   They accomplish that in two diametrically opposed ways.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said many of the terrorists operating worldwide today are
actually professionals. The most successful among them build grand
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that on the other side of the spectrum there is a
growing threat from so-called ``uncoordinated violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new, leaderless, structureless tactic,'' he said.
``A communique saying simply `Kill Americans' is issued. That's all
there is to the order. It's not sent to anyone in particular, and
no potential sites are mentioned. But individuals of similar
viewpoints eventually see the communique and decide on their own
how to follow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the bomb finally goes off, there are no ties to an
organized group or a leader. It's a very frightening development in
terrorism and almost impossible to defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the number of terrorist attacks may decline, future
death tolls are expected to grow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8731 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACTERIA-FOOD-2TAKES-     08-11 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACTERIA-FOOD-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES TEST VACCINES TO KEEP HARMFUL BACTERIA OUT OF FOOD
CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Just beyond a parking area at a Lenexa, Kan.,
industrial complex sits a line of 10 wooden storage sheds, like one
would find in someone's back yard, only larger.
</P>
<P>
   From their open doors comes the crowing of roosters, back and
forth, up and down the line. A squawking cacophony of roosters,
hens and chicks. These birds, however, are not destined for the
dinner plate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are being used to test a vaccine to keep
salmonella out of chickens and their eggs and to reduce the amount
of bacteria that makes it into consumers' lasagna, hamburgers or
turkey sandwiches. One vaccine immunizes against a strain of
salmonella responsible for an estimated 2 million cases of food
poisoning a year, double from 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The chickens belong to Biomune Inc., one of several
animal-health companies in Kansas' Johnson County and the area that
have or are developing so-called ``biologicals'' to immunize
animals against various bacteria. Although not a magic bullet,
vaccines are believed to offer a tremendous opportunity to cut the
number of food poisoning cases in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Plylar, a founder of Biomune, said some countries are far
ahead of the United States in using vaccines to fight foodborne
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary use of our vaccine is to protect humans,'' Plylar
said about the vaccines Biomune sells to the egg industry. ``It is
required in Germany to keep salmonella out of the human food
chain.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that what people eat might make them sick, or kill
them, has become a greater concern in the last two decades. Because
of better reporting, more cases of foodborne illness are being
identified.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, a California juice manufacturer agreed to pay a
$1.5 million fine following an outbreak of E. coli bacteria that
killed a 6-year-old and made 66 other persons sick. Potato salad
from a Chicago caterer was implicated in an E. coli outbreak that
made at least 4,500 people sick.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has made food safety an issue and
included $71 million in its proposed budget this year to improve
food safety.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a finger on the magnitude of foodborne illnesses is
tricky. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimate
between 6 million and 80 million cases of foodborne illnesses occur
in the United States each year, resulting in an estimated 9,000
deaths. Cancer will kill an estimated 564,000 people this year in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Because reporting of foodborne illnesses is so poor, it can't be
proved that the situation is worse than it used to be. However, the
potential for problems is growing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Centers for Disease Control, these are the
reasons foodborne pathogens have become major public health
problems:
</P>
<P>
   Older people and people with impaired immune systems are more
susceptible, and those groups are growing.
</P>
<P>
   New pathogens are emerging. Some are impervious to antibiotics,
making them harder to treat. Some, such as E. coli 0157:H7, are
proving particularly deadly, especially to children.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of megafarms and huge meat processing plants
increases the chances of making more people sick. National shippers
can deliver contaminated foods far and wide. Meat is a common cause
of foodborne illness.
</P>
<P>
   In their milder forms, foodborne illnesses cause cramps,
vomiting and diarrhea. Some pathogens can cause miscarriages,
meningitis or lead to kidney failure in children.
</P>
<P>
   Although the breadth of the problem is unknown, infected food
breaks the unwritten contract with American consumers that they can
expect their food to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers expect their food to be safe and have a right to
expect that in general. But they have to realize there is no zero
risk,'' said Jenny Scott, senior director of food safety programs
with a trade association of food processors in Washington D.C. ``At
this point in time, eating rare ground beef is a greater risk than
in the past and one most people should be unwilling to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County is a hotbed of animal-health research and
development. Besides Biomune, a niche player in the industry, Bayer
Animal Health and Fort Dodge Animal Health, large players in the
multibillion dollar animal-health industry, have headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   - MORE -
</P>
</TEXT>
