<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEROUX-NAIPAUL-ART-2     08-11 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEROUX-NAIPAUL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN FACT AND FICTION ARE BONDED BY BITTERNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until it suddenly ended, the friendship between V.S.
Naipaul and Paul Theroux, as mentor and protege, was mutually
rewarding over a period of more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the forthcoming publication of Theroux's book ``Sir
Vidia's Shadow: A Friendship Across Five Continents,'' and the
controversy surrounding it, there is only bitterness. As often
happens in a divorce, their friends are forced to choose sides.
</P>
<P>
   To someone who knows them both and has assiduously followed
their careers, the result can only be a subject of great regret.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, I wrote a profile of Naipaul for The New York Times
Magazine. Since then, we have been friends and in the intervening
years I have written other articles about him. At the time of that
original piece, I also met Theroux, and he was a thoughtful guide
to his mentor's life and work.
</P>
<P>
   Often when we talked, Naipaul would express curiosity about his
American friend, about his book sales as well as his literary
stature.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone conversation, Theroux said that it was ``a
forbidden thought to write about a friend, a wife, a child.'' He
added that when a friendship ends, as his did, ``in a surgical
way,'' then the rules are broken, and a writer is able to speak his
mind about matters that earlier would have been considered not for
publication.
</P>
<P>
   For a book that falls far short of revelation, a price has been
paid. Casual comments to a friend now become a matter of public
record. ``Sir Vidia's Shadow,'' part of which appeared in a recent
issue of The New Yorker, has aspects of revisionism.
</P>
<P>
   Although Theroux may believe that he has simply uncensored his
thoughts, it seems more likely that he has altered previously held
judgments.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if he has gone through his diaries and colorized
events. Quirks of character that once may have struck him as
amusing he now condemns.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, his physical descriptions of Naipaul are etched
in malice. In its detailed re-creation of scenes and dialogue from
the past, the book almost reads like a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Theroux said that he wrote the book because, to his knowledge,
there had never been a full-length portrait of his literary mentor
by a younger artist _ at least not since Boswell followed Johnson.
Beckett had not written about Joyce, nor had Gorky written
extensively about Tolstoy.
</P>
<P>
   If Theroux had written the book that he seemingly intended to
write, it would have had interest beyond that of the clash of
personalities. But this is not a mentor memoir. It is the story of
a friendship turned feud. An appropriate comparison might be the
published correspondence between Edmund Wilson and Vladimir
Nabokov, who had a falling out over their differences about
translating Pushkin.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Theroux feels that he had the provocation, but somewhere
along the line a trust has been broken, and by focusing on
idiosyncracies the book avoids the full complexity of its subject.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the perspective, Naipaul is either a man without a
constituency or a citizen of the world. Born in Trinidad of Indian
parentage, he was educated at Oxford and has lived in England most
of his life. He is very English, with the manners and the interests
of a country squire who is equally at home in the city.
</P>
<P>
   When he writes about the Third World, it is as a visitor, a
traveler. As well as being a brilliant writer, he is one of the
most articulate and outspoken artists. A man of wide learning and
firmly held convictions, he is unafraid to speak his mind, even, or
especially, when he is taking an unpopular position.
</P>
<P>
   The candor of his opinions is offset by his acerbic sense of
humor, which is often directed against himself (one of many aspects
shortchanged in Theroux's book). At the same time his belief in his
talent is matched by a kind of creative suffering during a writing
process in which he undergoes ``despair, desperation, panic.'' He
is an extraordinarily complicated person, not easily captured in
print, even by a formerly close friend.
</P>
<P>
   The two first met in Africa in 1966 when Naipaul was already a
highly regarded novelist and Theroux was at the beginning of his
career. More than anyone else, Naipaul encouraged the younger man
to be a writer and to keep revising. He was specific in his
suggestions, acting as adviser as well as editor.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Theroux was an unflagging acolyte, but also one of the
few people who could offer Naipaul critical suggestions about his
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Theroux is an American who has lived most of his life in alien
cultures, and his novels assume an international cast. He is a kind
of collector _ of places, adventures and other writers, whom he has
often written about.
</P>
<P>
   Although Theroux has never had the stature of Naipaul, whose
distinguished novels have made him a perennial candidate for a
Nobel Prize for literature, he has won a wide public following for
his books of travel as well as his novels.
</P>
<P>
   For both men, a deep intellectual curiosity is combined with a
devotion to their art. In recent years, each has moved away from,
or rather, has reinterpreted the form of the novel, though that is
what brought them their first recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sir Vidia's Shadow,'' Theroux says that nonfiction, as well
as fiction, is ``a version of the truth,'' an idea that is endemic
to his own work. When Naipaul crosses the fictional line, the
bridge is more stylistic than contextual, as in ``The Enigma of
Arrival'' and ``A Way in the World,'' in which he applies
novelistic principles to a retelling of moments in his life.
</P>
<P>
   His current book, ``Beyond Belief,'' is another Naipaul return,
in this case to the world of Islam for a work that is part
journalism, part contemporary political history.
</P>
<P>
   As for Theroux, his novels ``My Secret History'' and ``My Other
Life'' are a more overt merging of fact and fiction, with even, in
the second book, the use of a character named Paul Theroux as
narrator. His last novel, ``Kowloon Tong,'' deals with the
quick-changing life in Hong Kong. With Theroux, it is sometimes
difficult to determine what the author has seen and what he has
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Theroux has frequently written about Naipaul, in an adulatory
book of criticism, ``V.S. Naipaul: An Introduction to His Work,''
in 1972, and in articles published over three decades.
Paradoxically, the book of criticism has become one of Theroux's
most valuable works, selling for more than $1,000 at antiquarian
book fairs.
</P>
<P>
   The split between the two men was precipitated by what Theroux
called an ``abusive note'' that he received from Naipaul's wife and
her disparagement of a eulogistic obituary that he wrote about
Naipaul's first wife. Sometime later, the two authors accidentally
met on a London street and Naipaul reportedly told him to ``take it
on the chin and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Theroux moved on by writing his book. In one of the stranger
sections, he claims that, as a judge for the Booker Prize, he was
instrumental in the prestigious award not being given to Naipaul's
novel ``A Bend in the River,'' a shortlisted finalist.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Naipaul's ``A House for Biswas'' and ``A Bend in the
River'' were both on the Modern Library list of the 100 greatest
English-language novels of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir Vidia's Shadow'' is Theroux's version of the truth. Others
who know Naipaul will necessarily have their own portraits. To take
one example of the differing perspectives, Theroux repeatedly
writes about what he considers to be Naipaul's cheapness: the two
of them would go to elegant restaurants in London, and the younger
writer would always be forced to pay the bill. If this so disturbed
Theroux, he should have suggested that they go to less expensive
places.
</P>
<P>
   In my experience, after many luncheons and dinners, Naipaul has
always readily shared the cost (unless the meeting was in the
nature of an interview, and then the expense was paid by my
employer). We have also been guests in each other's homes.
</P>
<P>
   Theroux criticizes Naipaul for accepting a knighthood after
years of scoffing at the idea of titles and suggesting that they
should be sold at the post office. Naipaul accepted the knighthood,
but, in contrast to actors and others, he does not use the title.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, The New Yorker published a selection of letters
from Naipaul to Theroux revealing the older writer's artistic
generosity. In one letter, Naipaul asked his friend to be discreet
in personal matters. He said: ``I opened myself to you at various
times without reserve, and sometimes with flippancy, which may not
always be understood.'' Theroux's book confirms that
misunderstanding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
