A8740 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-DRUGS-ATHLETES-A     08-11 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DRUGS-ATHLETES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES AND DRUGS: JUST SAY NO  
 (THIS EDITORIAL WILL APPEAR IN WEDNESDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The punishment should fit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Most reasonable people could probably agree with that homily.
But what if the transgression is not a crime?
</P>
<P>
   What if the transgression is, for example, an athlete ingesting
a substance that has been banned by the official organization
regulating the sport?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the answers to that question are easy, sometimes they
are not so easy.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an easy one: Two years ago, Irish swimming sensation
Michelle Smith gathered more than three gold medals at the Olympics
in Atlanta. She also garnered troubling suspicion that she used
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Though she denied the charges and passed every drug test she was
required to take, the suspicion was understandable: Her husband,
Erik de Bruin, a Dutch track star, was serving a four-year
suspension for illegal testosterone use; and few world-class
swimmers have such precipitous drops in time, as did Smith,
especially at the age of 26.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago the international swimming federation (FINA),
banned Smith for four years after it was determined she manipulated
an out-of-competition drug test by adulterating her urine sample
with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Smith could have been banned for life, but a four-year
suspension will mean she misses the 2000 Sydney Olympics and the
2001 world championships in Fukuoka, Japan. Her career might be at
an end.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a not-so-easy one: Gary Hall Jr. of Phoenix is battling a
suspension over a positive marijuana test that prevented him from
entering competitions which are essentially preliminaries to the
2000 Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Though FINA officials say Hall tested positive for marijuana at
the 1996 Olympics, the rule prohibiting the drug - though passed
before the Games - did not take effect until a month after the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   There are no easy answers to these difficult questions over
``crime'' and punishment, for elite athletes, save one: Don't do
drugs. Period. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-YOUTH-CRIME     08-11 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-YOUTH-CRIME </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAJORITY OF TEENAGERS SAY SCHOOL CRIME AND VIOLENCE IS THEIR TOP
CONCERN
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six out of 10 teenagers say their top concern is
crime and violence in school, according to a nationwide survey
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey paints a picture of high school students who are
concerned with scholastic achievement, get along well with their
parents and are optimistic about the future.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of nearly 1,200 students found that four out of 10
said they make homework a priority, with one-fourth receiving
mostly A's on their last report card. Half of the students said
they try to take the most difficult and challenging courses they
can, although girls were more likely than boys _ by a ratio of
three-to-two _ to sign up for tougher courses.
</P>
<P>
   Some boys said they try to hide their intelligence from peers
for fear of being called a ``nerd'' or ``geek.'' Girls indicated
they feel pride about their intelligence and don't try to hide it.
</P>
<P>
   Among other survey findings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Girls feel optimistic about achieving their career goals and
anticipate earning the same or more than men.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most teenagers said cheating exists in schools and they
believe more than half of all students cheat at one point in their
high school careers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Four out of 10 cite a family member as their role model; six
out of 10 said parents spend the ``right amount'' of time with
their children and that they like and respect their parents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nine out of 10 feel that mathematics is the most important
course to take for future success.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The top career choices, in order, were: teacher, computer
hardware/software developer, medical doctor, business person and an
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by The Horatio Alger Association of
Distinguished Americans, Inc., a non-profit educational
organization, who sent self-administered mail questionnaires to
high school students between the ages of 14 and 18 nationwide in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
