</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT SAYS FBI KNEW OF MOB INFORMANT'S WHEREABOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ More than two years after mobster-informant Angelo
``Sonny'' Mercurio skipped town to avoid a racketeering indictment,
the FBI learned that he was at a Fourth of July barbeque with
drug-dealing partners who were setting up a big marijuana delivery
from the West Coast, an agent testfied Tuesday in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The agent, Joseph Hobbs, said Mercurio was not arrested that day
in 1991, or three days later, when agents were told he'd be
cruising Boston Harbor in a rented boat. Rather, Hobbs said, the
prized informant who had tipped the FBI off to one of its greatest
investigative coups _ the 1989 bugging of a Mafia induction
ceremony _ remained free for three more years until he was arrested
in 1994 in Georgia with 150 pounds of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Hobbs testified, he was puzzled by his fellow
agents' lack of aggression towards Mercurio, even though Hobbs
believed the information he gave them was taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs, who was assigned to a squad that investigated drug cases,
was not part of the organized crime team that had cultivated
Mercurio as an informant. He testified that he did not know
Mercurio was providing information to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs was the latest witness to testify before US District Judge
Mark L. Wolf, who is considering whether to drop extortion and
racketeering charges against the region's leading Irish and Italian
gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for New England Mafia boss Francis P. Salemme,
Winter Hill Gang leader Stephen Flemmi, Mafia soldier Robert DeLuca
and Winter Hill gangster John Martorano argue that the alleged
conspiracy between the rival gangs is invalid because Flemmi had
been promised immunity from prosecution as an informant.
</P>
<P>
   Through his questions Tuesday, Salemme's lawyer, Anthony M.
Cardinale, suggested that another valuable FBI informant _ Mercurio
_ received favorable treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Assistant US Attorney Fred M. Wyshak Jr.,
Hobbs said Mercurio was not arrested at the barbeque because agents
did not want to jeopardize their drug investigation or the safety
of their cooperating witness. Hobbs insisted that the FBI did not
know that Mercurio was at the Independence Day barbeque at the home
of his brother, Michael Mercurio, until a cooperating witness who
attended the party reported to agents afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   The agent also testified that Sonny Mercurio was never part of
the drug investigation he worked on with agents from the US Drug
Enforcement Administration and state drug agents from Maine.
</P>
<P>
   But DEA agent Michael Cunniff, who followed Hobbs to the witness
stand, said Sonny Mercurio was a target of the investigation, which
allegedly involved large shipments of marijuana from Los Angeles to
Boston _ and that Hobbs knew that.
</P>
<P>
   Cunniff claimed that Mercurio became a target after he was
spotted at the barbeque in Woburn, but Cardinale showed him a
document which indicated that the DEA named him a target of the
investigation on July 3, the day before the Woburn gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs said he told organized crime supervisor Edward Quinn and
agent Rick Carter that Mercurio was at the barbeque and also told
them that Mercurio was expected to join a party aboard a boat
docked behind the Marriott Long Wharf in Boston the following
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs said Carter later told him that agents staked out the boat
but Mercurio never showed up. But there is no report in FBI files
of the failed surveillance, according to testimony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
