<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HARRISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNA J. HARRISON, WAS PROFESSOR OF CHEMISTRY AT MT. HOLYOKE; 85 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Mo.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anna J. Harrison, a former teacher in a one-room schoolhouse in
Missouri who became a professor at Mount Holyoke College and the
first woman president of the American Chemical Society, died of a
stroke Saturday in Holyoke (Mass.) Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harrison taught chemistry at Mount Holyoke from 1945 to
1979. During her tenure, the college produced more women who went
on to earn doctorates in science than any other institution in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, she was elected the first woman president of the
American Chemical Society. In 1984, she became the fourth woman to
serve a two-year term as president of the American Society for the
Advancement of Science.
</P>
<P>
   She was born and raised on a farm near Benton City, Mo., and
attended a one-room rural school.
</P>
<P>
   When she graduated from the University of Missouri during the
height of the Great Depression, there were no jobs for young
chemists. She went back home to live and taught at the one-room
school she had attended. Her students ranged in age from 5 to 21.
``It was excellent training in independence,'' she said in a story
published in the Globe on Jan. 23, 1977. ``If you got yourself in
trouble, you damned well got yourself out.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years teaching at the school, she received a graduate
assistantship at the University of Missouri, where she earned a
doctorate in chemistry. But she was still unable to find a job in
the chemical industry. ``I got letters saying there weren't any
jobs and, even if there were, they wouldn't hire a woman,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She then got a job teaching at Sophie Newcomb College in New
Orleans before joining the faculty at Mount Holyoke in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harrison was the author of ``Chemistry: A Search to
Understand.'' In the introduction to the textbook, she discussed
her philosophy of teaching. ``It's not so much a question of
capturing their attention,'' she wrote. ``It's a question of not
turning it off. Most people are naturally curious about science if
they're not turned off.''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves a niece and nephew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
