<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPLIFE-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      08-11 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POP LIFE: HE'S BACK BACK, BABY: A NEW (IMPROVED?) ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Swiftly and with little fanfare, one of pop's
strangest comebacks has been under way in a small studio in a wood
cabin in the hills of Malibu. At the mixing board there, Ross
Robinson, a hard-rock producer known for his work with heavy,
rap-influenced acts like Korn and Limp Bizkit, played some new
music, which hasn't yet been heard publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The guitars ground out brittle, clipped metal riffs, the bass
lines were thick and dark, and electronic effects evoked the
atmosphere of a horror film. But the voice screaming on top
belonged not to a young punk but to Rob Van Winkle, 29, better
known as Vanilla Ice, the white rapper whose hit ``Ice Ice Baby''
topped the charts in 1990 but whose reputation quickly faded from
hit maker to has-been and paradigm of inauthenticity in a rap world
that trades on credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice playing music for slam-dancing, skateboard-wielding
punks seems as unlikely as Hanson turning to gangsta rap, but just
such an album, ``Hard to Swallow,'' will be coming out on
Republic/Universal Records on Oct. 20, complete with a hard-rock
remake of ``Ice Ice Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People kept saying to me, `It might hurt your name, it might
hurt your reputation,''' Robinson said of his decision to produce
Vanilla Ice. ``I said, `Then I'm doing it.' It's the most punk-rock
thing you could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting nearby in the studio, sporting a blond goatee and black
shorts exposing tattoo-covered legs, Vanilla Ice interrupted, ``No
one's going to expect the Iceman to come up with something like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   When a photographer approached, he insisted, ``I don't pose
anymore,'' then proceeded to strike poses as she snapped. It is a
scene emblematic of Vanilla Ice's identity confusion. He insists
that he has abandoned all attempts at creating an image and is only
interested in music. Yet in some ways, he is just playing another
character.
</P>
<P>
   The real Vanilla Ice is probably somewhere between the boastful
faux rapper of ``To the Extreme'' and the troubled faux punk of
``Hard to Swallow.'' On the outside, he seems like a fraternity
jock; on the inside, he is a self-described hypochondriac with
attention-deficit disorder, anxiety and intimacy problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd come to California again,'' he said,
referring to his fear of Suge Knight, the chief executive of the
Los Angeles gangsta rap label Death Row Records, currently in
prison for parole violation. Vanilla Ice and others have accused
the enormous Knight of dangling him off a hotel balcony as an
inducement to share royalties on ``Ice Ice Baby,'' which a relative
of Knight's helped write. (Knight got his royalties but has denied
that he used intimidation.)
</P>
<P>
   Since his last album, ``Mind Blowin','' in 1994, Vanilla Ice has
been at work reinventing his sound and his life. ``I've had a big
comedown since selling 15 million records,'' he said, referring to
worldwide sales estimates of his 1990 debut, ``To the Extreme.''
``I turned to drugs and released a record called `Mind Blowin''
because that's what I had been doing. Now I've got a boy and a
beautiful wife, and I've promised them I won't go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice says he quit drugs, turned to religion and started a
grunge band in Miami called Picking Scabs three years ago and got
married last year. He has also spent recent years motocross racing
and competing professionally in jet-skiing. Earlier this year,
Monte Lipman, a Republic/Universal executive who worked with
Vanilla Ice on his first album, introduced him to Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper compared his experience in the studio with Robinson,
known as an emotionally demanding producer, to psychotherapy.
Though many of Vanilla Ice's lyrics rail against the music
industry, releasing a ``fire'' that he says has been building
inside after being used by the business and then left to suffer
humiliation alone, he also deals with issues from his deeper past
on a song called ``Family.'' ``Where did I get this anger? Where
did I get this hate?'' sings the man who once claimed to be a
wholesome alternative to negative-theme rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes twisted people to make good music,'' he said. ``A lot
of people didn't know that I was an abused child. My mother was
almost killed by whoever it was that made her pregnant with me.
Ross has a way of getting things like that out of you. And now I
feel like I am free, because I put it on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he seems to be telling the truth these days, Vanilla Ice
has a reputation for fudging his background to achieve musical
credibility. His biography in the early 90s falsely claimed that he
was raised in the ghettos of Miami, where he went to high school
with Luther Campbell of 2 Live Crew and was stabbed by gang
members. He was really raised in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Vanilla Ice blames his former manager for creating this
apocryphal biography and circulating it without his approval. ``He
didn't want people knowing I was selling drugs to pay for studio
time,'' he said. Vanilla Ice blames other people for most of his
career missteps. ``I was like a puppet to these people,'' he said
of his former label, SBK. ``I never thought I'd play for a white
crowd or cross over. It just wasn't me. Then they asked me, `Would
you do a song like M.C. Hammer for a million bucks?' I said, `Hell,
yeah.' Anybody would do that. And it worked in everyone's eyes but
mine. I knew it was going to backlash on me.''
</P>
<P>
   So would he do it for money again? ``You could have a number,
and maybe I'd do something now,'' he said. ``But it's got to be a
lot higher than a million.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Vying for Catatonia
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes record labels can be shortsighted. Two years ago,
Warner Brothers Records began gearing up to release ``Lost Cat.''
The album was by Catatonia, a four-year-old Welsh band led by a
charismatic tomboy named Cerys Matthews. The label brought the band
to America for three concerts and pressed advance CD's for the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many new Welsh bands _ Super Furry Animals, Gorky's
Zygotic Mynci, 60 Ft. Dolls, Dub War _ Catatonia, with fuzzy,
melodic music topped by Ms. Matthews' winsome rasp, seemed most
likely to find an audience among college-radio fans. But the record
was never released. Executive changes and layoffs were occurring at
Warner Brothers, and Catatonia was caught in the middle, with the
label refusing to tell the band whether it was going to release the
album and remaining executives doubting the band's prospects for
success in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredibly frustrating,'' remembered the band's
co-manager, Martin Patton, ``especially when you know you have a
band this great. If someone said `no' or `go away,' I would have
been happier.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Warner Brothers declined to discuss the matter,
but no doubt the label felt silly this year, when Catatonia's
single, ``Mulder and Scully,'' hit No. 1 on the British pop charts,
followed by its second album, ``International Velvet,'' which also
went to No. 1. Suddenly, the band was in the midst of a bidding war
in the United States, and because Warner Brothers hadn't committed
earlier, Catatonia was up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone from Sony Music to Warner Brothers subsidiary labels
wanted to sign the group. In the end, a small Warner Brothers label
won out: Vapor, run by Neil Young and his manager, Elliot Roberts.
The label plans to release only two albums this year; one is by the
lovesick singer Jonathan Richman, and the other is ``International
Velvet,'' which entered record stores two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he first heard the group's music on a recent trip
to England. When he called Warner Brothers in the United States to
find out about the status of the band, he said, no one was even
aware of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can anybody see this band and doubt what a great singer
and performer Cerys Matthews is?'' Roberts asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``International Velvet'' is a beguiling pop album, alternately
wispy and muscular, like a more rock-and-roll Bjork or the Cocteau
Twins with venom. Lyrically quirky, the album includes songs about
``The X-Files'' (``Mulder and Scully''), the Mafia (``I Am the
Mob''), momentary lust (``Why I Can't Stand One Night Stands'') and
Wales (``International Velvet,'' sung half in Welsh).
</P>
<P>
   ``My accent is such a mixture _ North, South, West Wales,'' Ms.
Matthews said in an interview last year. ``It's a bit embarrassing,
my voice. We moved around a lot and my parents are from different
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had an open mind to everything music-wise,'' she
continued. ``My main motivation for making music was loving singing
and loving getting lost in songs.''
</P>
<P>
   The band is to perform on Aug. 13 at the Mercury Lounge in
Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
