<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: NEWS FROM AROUND THE TV DIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what is intended to be one of the first big television
projects of the new century, ABC is to present an eight-hour
mini-series based on the civil rights-era books by Taylor Branch to
be broadcast in January and February of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lyne, the executive vice president for movies at ABC, said
Tuesday that she had closed a deal with Columbia Tri-Star Pictures
to bring to network television ``Parting the Waters,'' which won a
1988 Pulitzer Prize for history, and ``Pillar of Fire,'' the second
volume in Branch's planned trilogy on the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia had been trying to develop ``Parting the Waters'' as a
movie for nearly a decade, Branch said Tuesday, and he had
``absolutely despaired'' of the project's ever coming to fruition
because of trouble condensing the enormous amount of material to
fit a film format.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have been out promoting the second book I detected there
was less resonance of the 1960s,'' Branch said in a telephone
interview. ``I saw this history as perishable.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the deal was shifted to ABC, he was ``extremely
gratified,'' even though, he said: ``There are things about a
feature film that can be special. The movie `Gandhi' was always our
model.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Verno, the executive vice president for movies at
Columbia, aware of the problems of adapting the book to film, took
the project to Ms. Lyne and ABC. ``Telling this as a feature meant
cutting it into small pieces,'' Ms. Lyne said. ``Now we can tell so
many of the dramatic stories that Taylor includes in his books.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, that will mean capturing many of the stories of
lesser-known figures in the civil rights movement that Branch
included, though Ms. Lyne acknowledged that ABC would cast actors
to play familiar historical figures. ``John F. Kennedy, Robert
Kennedy, J. Edgar Hoover, and of course, Martin Luther King, we're
looking for actors to play all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch said: ``I have ideas about the casting. I'm going to try
to put my shoulder to the wheel on that without getting in the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch and Harry Belafonte, who had been developing the material
for the movie, will work on the miniseries as producers, Branch
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy this is going to get on in January of 2000,''
Branch said. ``You can make an awfully good case that this is the
freedom story of the 20th century. It's great to be able to tell it
at the start of the new century. I think it's a peculiarly American
freedom story when you can say the oppressors and the victims are
both liberated.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedic Musical Chairs
</P>
<P>
   Craig Kilborn might get to keep his ``Five Questions'' comedy
bit when he moves from Comedy Central to CBS, but he shouldn't
expect to get on the air anytime soon, certainly not before Jon
Stewart slides into the chair Kilborn is vacating as star of ``The
Daily Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the messages that Comedy Central executives sent to
CBS and Kilborn at a news conference Tuesday to introduce Stewart,
the comedian and onetime syndicated talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   The changeover will probably come in January, said Doug Herzog,
the president of Comedy Central. As for when Kilborn will be
allowed out of his contract _ which runs until August 1999 _ to
join CBS, Herzog said, ``We're working that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central made no secret of its displeasure with CBS for
hiring Kilborn away to succeed Tom Snyder as host of ``The Late
Late Show,'' and initially signaled its intention to tie the star
up as long as possible. On Tuesday, Herzog sounded a little more
accommodating. ``We're talking with CBS about it,'' he said. ``One
thing we want to be sure of is that Jon gets on the air for us
first.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what material Kilborn might be bringing to CBS, Herzog
used the dreaded term ``intellectual property,'' a legal reference
that harked back to the days when David Letterman left NBC and that
network claimed virtually everything he had done as its
intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   The incoming host, Conan O'Brien, completely disavowed any
interest in repeating Letterman's comedy bits, and Stewart did the
same Tuesday regarding Kilborn's routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into a show you want to establish your own
identity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Madeleine Smithberg, the executive producer of ``The Daily
Show,'' said the ``Five Questions'' bit, in which Kilborn asks a
guest five rather bizarrely related questions, sprang from
something Kilborn told her he often does on dates. Ms. Smithberg
suggested incorporating the idea into the show, which, she said,
gave them both a hand in its creation as intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who signed a four-year contract to take over ``The
Daily Show,'' acknowledged a paradox in his replacing Kilborn, who
is going to CBS to take the job Stewart had been thought to be in
line for: the host of the show following Letterman's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's musical chairs,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog treated Stewart's arrival as a coup, and some reports
have the host earning $1.5 million to $2 million a year, among the
highest salaries ever for a cable star. As for the real reason he
chose to sign up for a show on cable, Stewart said, ``I value my
anonymity.''
</P>
<P>
   Exploring the Titanic
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Titanic, be they history buffs or romantics swayed
by the Oscar-winning movie, will have a rare chance on Sunday to
follow along live as explorers, both human and robotic, roam the
ruins of the sunken ocean liner.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel will transmit the images as a manned
submersible unit with two small robotic-operated vehicles attached
ventures into unexplored areas, including the captain's quarters,
said Bob Reid, the executive producer of the two-hour program (8
p.m., Eastern time).
</P>
<P>
   And while ``live via satellite'' is a familiar concept, the idea
of images coming live via satellite from two and a half miles below
the ocean's surface is something else again.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a signal via a cable connected to the robotic vehicles
``is relatively easy,'' Reid said. ``What's difficult and has never
been done before is getting a live signal from the manned
submersible to the ship and to the satellite.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be dangerous to connect a cable, or any tether, to such a
unit because the ocean's currents could entangle it in the wreck,
he said. So a robotic vehicle will be stationed on the ocean's
floor and the three-man sub will ``plug in'' to it ``as a sort of a
way station,'' he said. The men may have to disconnect if their
safety is jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   A special satellite is required, too. ``It has to be
gyrostabilized so it can rock and roll with the ship and stay in a
constant position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientific expedition is being conducted by RMS Titanic
Inc., legal guardian of the wreckage site, with dozens of
scientists and historians aboard four companion ships.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to examine why ``the bow is relatively intact but the
stern is a mangled mess,'' Reid said, and hope to find and bring to
the surface the ship's Marconi radio.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel and NBC's ``Dateline'' are collaborating
on the production.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's edition of ``Dateline'' will include a report
on RMS Titanic's efforts to raise a chunk of the ship's hull out of
the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Change for Gumbel
</P>
<P>
   CBS News will shut down production of ``Public Eye with Bryant
Gumbel'' at the end of this month, a decision that may mean the end
of that news magazine but not the end of efforts to put Gumbel at
the center of a prime-time news magazine on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   CBS News executives said that Andrew Heyward, the president of
CBS News, told the show's staff Tuesday afternoon that ``Public
Eye,'' which was dropped from the CBS fall schedule, would not
continue to produce stories in anticipation of returning as a
midseason replacement for the network.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel said this week that he hoped a recent surge in ratings
might cause CBS executives to rethink the decision to keep it off
the fall schedule. At the least, he said, he expected the show to
return by January.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision makes that less likely, though it is still
possible that CBS will revive the show. It is more likely, CBS News
executives said, that CBS will create a different news magazine for
Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   As news magazines often do, ``Public Eye'' has shown signs of
ratings life in summer, finishing among the top 20 shows for the
first time last week. And there are high hopes for Wednesday
night's edition, a special about Tom Whittaker, a disabled climber,
and his assault on Mt. Everest. (Gumbel interviewed him in a hotel
in Nepal, 16,000 feet up.)
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel said he has had ``excellent conversations'' with Leslie
Moonves, the president of CBS Television, about his future at the
network.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves has committed to another CBS news magazine for January,
``60 Minutes II.'' That led to widely circulated suggestions that
Gumbel would drop his show to join that one.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed those suggestions. ``I'm preoccupied with this
show,'' he said. He and Moonves have ``talked a little bit'' about
``60 Minutes II,'' he said, but added, ``I'm committed to making my
own show work.''
</P>
<P>
   As for why it didn't work this past season, Gumbel said: ``We
made some mistakes. I think what I've really learned is these
things do take some time. Would I prefer to be on the fall
schedule? Of course I would. But I recognize the realities of the
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
