<HEADER>
A8765 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-HILL-COX     08-11 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-HILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author: `Never be satisfied with nothin' '
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As one of nine black children in rural Louisiana in the 1960s,
Ernest Hill grew up in a tiny house on a dirt road with no running
water. There was no indoor plumbing but there were books. Lots of
books. And a mother and father who had a vision that went far
beyond the impoverished environment.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the nine children grew up to graduate from college _
three earned degrees from Yale(Conn.) _ and all succeeded in their
chosen fields. (Hill's older brother, Kenny, not only graduated
from Yale, but he also went on to win three Super Bowl rings with
the Oakland Raiders and New York Giants.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing thing,'' says Hill, 37, who recently
published his second novel, ``A Life for a Life,'' after earning a
bachelor's degree from the University of California at Berkeley and
a master's degree from Cornell(N.Y.). ``They worked with us from a
very early age. Our mom would read to us and our dad always taught
us to do our best. He told us, `A man is a man from his shoulders
up.' They set these standards that were very, very high and they
shielded us from things we shouldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in life, while his brothers and sisters fell in line and
made A's, Ernest Hill resisted. He read only what was necessary and
slid through high school on his athletic ability. He won a football
scholarship to Northeast Louisiana University, and then transferred
to Berkeley after suffering a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first week there, a group of students had congregated
outside and were having a discussion about the South,'' Hill
recalls. ``I was soon pulled into it and a girl from Norway asked
me what I thought about Richard Wright. I said, `Who?' and she
couldn't believe I hadn't read `Native Son.' The next day she
brought me a copy and I read the book out of spite. It was the
first book I truly enjoyed. I knew then that I wanted to write like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he postponed writing until he finished his master's
degree at Cornell. When a student from Lebanon asked him what he
was going to do next, Hill replied that he was going to UCLA to
work on his doctorate. After that, he said, he would write novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked me if I knew any Ph.D.'s who had written a novel,''
Hill says, ``and I didn't. That night I started writing `Satisfied
With Nothin'.' That was my first attempt at creative writing. I had
taken no courses. It was all from my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The title for the novel came from a conversation Hill had with
his father when he was in the fourth grade. As they were driving
past a juke joint, Hill's father pointed to a group of men sitting
out front playing dominoes and drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Tell me what you see.' I said I saw men having a
good time. He said, `What you see is something I don't ever want
you to be. Never be satisfied with nothin'. You have to believe you
can achieve anything you want.'''
</P>
<P>
   The novel painted a grim picture of a young black Louisiana man
who rises to fame as a star football player. His attempts to
succeed in a racist world, however, are thwarted and he ends up
being ``satisfied with nothin'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Life for a Life'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23) has a happier
ending. The novel is a powerful tale of a young African-American
man who is saved from violence and poverty by a humble hero. When
15-year-old D'Ray Reid unintentionally kills a college bound honor
student during a convenience store robbery, it appears that he is
fated to join his daddy, who is serving a life sentence in prison.
Instead of condemning Reid, Henry Earl, the victim's father, visits
the youth in prison and prods him to rehabilitate himself.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson here, as in his own life, Hill says, is that a proper
role model can work miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Earl, who enters Reid's life, teaches him how to live
his life the right way. We had a father who knew how to succeed.
For me, that was the key.''
</P>
<P>
   But how did a family from the poorish parish with the highest
illiteracy rate in the state succeed when others failed, ended up
on drugs or in the penitentiary? Hill's father says there was no
secret to the family's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked day and night to support them and give them a
chance,'' says Charley Hill, 74, who taught high school, coached
and worked as a cannery supervisor. ``I never kept them out of
school to work. I allowed their mother to stay home with them. And
I talked with them a lot. I never drank or swore and I told them
quotations and tried to inspire them, things like `A job worth
doing is worth doing right,' and `Never be satisfied with
nothing.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Hills also made sure their children were kept away from
places where they might get in trouble. Other children were
encouraged to come to the Hills' house to play so the mother,
Katie, 67, a former teacher, could supervise them.
</P>
<P>
   Education was always a priority, says Ernest Hill, now a writer
in residence at Southern University in Baton Rouge. There were
encyclopedias and other books, but there was no dining table. ``We
would eat out of aluminum pans, like a buffet. We'd sit on the
floor or on the bed and eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill's father never made more than $10,000 a year in his life,
but he still managed to educate nine children and eventually built
a five-bedroom house with three bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set unbelievably high standards for us,'' Hill says. ``I
remember when he sent my oldest brother off to Yale, the whole
community said he was smart, but he was not prepared to leave Oak
Grove, La., and compete with the smartest students in the country.
A white lady came by and told my father this. He listened politely
and called my brother into the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `It's going to be tough. Do your best. If things
don't work out, pack your bags, get on the plane, and when you come
to Monroe to deplane, pause at the top of the steps and wave your
transcript. If you're going to get an F, get the best one.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between reality and a pipe dream is to have
someone who can convince you it's true. And, just like Mr. Henry in
my novel, that's what my father did.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
