A8766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN12-COX     08-11 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Old pals recall Fort Benning, the Vineyard
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She is a friend of legend, my daughter's old pal Elsie Gilman.
</P>
<P>
   They were young Army wives at Fort Benning(Ga.) when their
husbands, newly graduated from Georgia Tech, were in the Army
engineers corps. They made friends immediately, an Atlanta girl and
a brisk, efficient young New Englander, who grew up on a farm on
Martha's Vineyard. They had their first babies at roughly the same
time, saw one another infrequently through the post-Army years, but
have stayed in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Elsie happened to be in Atlanta when my daughter arrived from
Omaha for her son's wedding, and we had a gala time reminiscing. I
hadn't much to contribute except that my husband and I spent a fine
week on what Elsie called ``the Vineyard'' in her grandmother's
cottage, enjoyed visiting her father's farm, her own weekend
cottage set in the middle of 10 family acres, and all the points of
interest around that island, including a visit to Edgartown.
</P>
<P>
   But after they had caught up on family news, and reports on the
three children each of them has, the old friends started recalling
the long ago days at Fort Benning and later at the Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Elsie had strong ideas about being a thrifty wife and feeding
her family fresh home-grown vegetables. So she planted a garden and
gave my daughter canning lessons. The story my daughter is fondest
of is the meticulous, loving care Elsie took in planting and
harvesting spinach to feed her firstborn, a hefty boy called Sam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam was too good to eat canned baby food,'' my daughter said.
``He had to have the freshest spinach from the garden, picked at
just the right moment when it was dew-cooled in the early morning.
It was carefully washed and tenderly cooked, only the best for Sam.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then,'' she took a deep breath, ``after she had two more
babies, we were visiting with our children on the Vineyard, and
Elsie would take a bag of sugar doughnuts to the window and call,
`Boys! Breakfast!' and tossed it out to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsie made a face. It was as my new Jewish friend would say,
``Enough, already!''
</P>
<P>
   Elsie, a nurse, once became concerned that her grandmother and
two ancient great aunts weren't getting the care they needed at a
nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   She brought them home to the Vineyard and spent the summer there
with them, treating them more like girl campers than nursing home
patients. I always liked the stories of how she oiled their old
bodies and gave them sponge baths, how she took them shopping for a
new van and was guided by their preference, how she bought them
pretty shifts to wear in the afternoon and invited their friends
into tea.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of their old friends had died, Elsie was hard-pressed
to find enough guests for some afternoon teas. She asked the
postman and the grocer and sundry acquaintances from village
stores. It was all very merry, and the old ladies flourished.
</P>
<P>
   One piece of Elsie's wisdom, which I have tried to incorporate
into life on our island, is that boy young 'uns don't need clothes
at the beach. A pair of cutoff jeans will do for all occasions, she
decreed. Sleep in them, swim in them, don't bother about laundry,
they'll dry clean on young bodies after an ocean bath.
</P>
<P>
   Having Elsie in town for a little while was a bonanza for her
old Fort Benning neighbor, and for me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
