<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAGWEED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Say Gesundheit! to start of ragweed season
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   'Snot a joke: The new season of sneezin' is nigh.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike spring pollen, which warns you with a thick powdering of
yellow on the car, the dog and anything else outside for more than
five minutes, fall's allergy season sneaks up without so much as a
dusty windshield.
</P>
<P>
   So this is your warning: The ragweed is coming! The ragweed is
coming!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things you can predict,'' said Dr. Kathleen
Sheerin of the Atlanta Allergy and Asthma Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Ragweed, a common and tenacious plant that likes moist areas
such as riverbanks, gets its cue to pollinate when the days shorten
and the nights lengthen to a certain point, sometime after Aug. 15,
Sheerin said. The clinic probably will resume its daily pollen
count next week, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And forewarned is forearmed, as they say, especially since
certain allergy medicines, such as the prescription drug Vancenase
and the over-the-counter nasal spray Nasalcrom, must be taken for
at least a week before they start to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best to be on your medicine before the season starts,''
Sheerin said. ``Get your prescriptions in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also recommend the usual: keep the windows shut, change
the furnace filter, bathe the pets. Ragweed usually pollinates in
the morning, so if you're allergic, avoid that time of day for
outdoor activities.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few good things about the fall pollen season is that
it is shorter and less intense than the spring pollen season. In
colder climates, the season ends with the first frost, but here in
the South, the pollen just dissipates after about a month.
</P>
<P>
   But mold, another major allergen, also is expected to start
tickling noses in late summer or early fall. So keep the Kleenex
handy.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Allergy and Asthma Clinic's pollen line for daily
pollen counts is 770-662-6100, or you can view the clinic's
Internet site at http://www.atlallergy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
