A8769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-JEKYLLISLAND-C     08-11 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JEKYLLISLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three groups to rock at annual Jekyll Island concert
 &HT;    By Alan Patureau
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEKYLL ISLAND, Ga. -- The Rockefellers, Vanderbilts and their
super-wealthy cronies used to vacation at Jekyll Island, but now
the state of Georgia owns it, and anyone can enjoy a rich
experience on this Golden Isle.
</P>
<P>
   It gets even better on Aug. 22 at one of the Southeast's biggest
beach parties. Jekyll's 15th annual Beach Music Festival will
feature three golden oldies rock 'n' roll groups: Paul Revere and
the Raiders, the Tams and the Swingin' Medallions.
</P>
<P>
   About 14,000 people are expected to gather at noon for the
five-hour frolic at the Beach Deck, a large stage erected in the
sand just south of the causeway road (Ga. 520) from Brunswick.
Tickets are $7 in advance or $10 day of show; call the Jekyll
Island Welcome Center, 1-800-841-6586.
</P>
<P>
   Festival gates will be located just north and south of the
Jekyll Island Convention Center. No food, beverages, coolers or
pets allowed inside _ but food, soda and beer will be sold. And
don't forget the suntan lotion.
</P>
<P>
   Singer-keyboardist Revere and the Raiders, known for hits
including ``Indian Reservation,'' have sold 50 million albums and
been awarded eight gold records. The Tams are best known for their
1968 gold record, ``Be Young, Be Foolish, Be Happy.'' The Swingin'
Medallions are still helping people party to hits such as ``Double
Shot of My Baby's Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at the festival will be the Coastline Band from Charlotte,
named ``1996 Group of the Year'' by the Carolina Beach Music
Industry.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Beach Music Festival Golf Tournament precedes the
seaside bash at 10:30 a.m. Aug. 21 at Jekyll's Pine Lakes Golf
Course. Entry is $70, including greens fees, cart, snacks, prizes
and two festival tickets. Registration deadline is Friday, call
912-635-2368.
</P>
<P>
   -- Also playing: A must-see attraction is the Jekyll Island Club
Historic District, a Victorian complex with its handsome turreted
hotel and ``cottages'' (actually mansions) where the wealthy
vacationed from the 1880s to World War II. Tram tours depart on the
hour from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m., adults $10, students $6, children
under 6 free.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lodging and meals: Alas, the charming Jekyll Island Club
Hotel is booked solid for the weekend, but you can enjoy Sunday
brunch in the Grand Dining Room, $16. Among the island's 1,500
hotel rooms, best bets are the Jekyll Inn, Comfort Inn Island
Suites and the Beachview Club, with doubles from $99 to $159.
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: By boat, Jekyll is only 2 miles south of St.
Simons Island (vs. 20 miles by road and causeway). So if you're
staying on the larger isle, you can avoid traffic by taking the new
Water Taxi Service, a 35-minute ride from the Golden Isles Marina
on St. Simons to the Jekyll Wharf Marina; $12.50 round trip, call
912-638-5678. The 330-mile drive south from Georgia's capital city,
Atlanta, to Jekyll is fastest via I-75 to Macon, I-16 to Savannah,
I-95 to Brunswick, then a quick dogleg on U.S. 17 and Ga. 520 to
Jekyll.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
