A8770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MUSICOLDIES-CO     08-11 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MUSICOLDIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama prepares musical blast from the past
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Stars fall on Alabama: ``Saturday Night at the Oldies Live,''
at the Alabama Music Hall of Fame in Tuscumbia on Aug. 22, is the
first in an ongoing concert series. Percy Sledge (``When a Man
Loves a Woman''), Martha Reeves and the Vandellas (``Dancin' in the
Street'') and Billy Joe Royal (``Down in the Boondocks'') will
headline the show. Also performing: 1970s Muscle Shoals recording
artists FCC, Jackson Highway, Travis Wammack and Ribbon of Blue.
</P>
<P>
   -- The 'Bama connection: Both the Eufaula-born Reeves and
Leighton native Sledge are in the Alabama Music Hall of Fame. While
Royal is not an Alabamian, he is a supporter of the museum and has
recorded at Muscle Shoals.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tickets, etc.: Gates open 4 p.m.; music begins 5 p.m. $15;
under age 6 free. The first 100 people at the Hall of Fame between
1 and 4 p.m. Aug. 22 may purchase the numbered, limited-edition CD
``Percy Sledge's Greatest Hits'' at $20. Sledge will be on hand to
autograph them.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-239-2643.
</P>
<P>
   -- About the hall: Impetus for the Alabama Music Hall of Fame,
which opened in July 1990, came from the Muscle Shoals Music
Association, an organization of recording studio owners, producers,
musicians, songwriters and other music professionals. The
12,500-square-foot hall houses hundreds of exhibits showcasing
Alabama's rich musical heritage, exemplified by such people as W.C.
Handy, Dinah Washington, Jimmie Rodgers, Sam Phillips, Tammy
Wynette and the Temptations. An exhibit on the Muscle Shoals
recording industry _ which claims to be ``the hit-recording capital
of the world'' _ offers background on the area's contribution to
music.
</P>
<P>
   -- A peek inside: Visitors can climb aboard the group Alabama's
touring bus, the Southern Star; warble a tune to take home in the
recording studio; and see a life-size wax figure of Nat ``King''
Cole sitting at his piano. Elvis Presley's recording contract with
Sun Studios is displayed. And among the costumes are outfits worn
by Lionel Richie and the Commodores. Children are awed by the
15-foot-tall jukebox and a 17-foot guitar.
</P>
<P>
   -- Details: The Hall of Fame is open 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
Monday-Saturday, 1-5 p.m. Sunday. $6 adults; $5 seniors 55 and
older; $5 ages 13-18; $3 ages 6-12; children under 6 free.
1-800-239-2643.
</P>
<P>
   -- About Tuscumbia: Named for a Chickasaw chief, the city _
northwest Alabama's oldest _ is built around a large natural
spring. Some of the original homes and buildings from the early
1800s have been preserved in a historic district. Ivy Green, the
birthplace and childhood home of Helen Keller, is open year round
for tours. For more information, call the Shoals Chamber of
Commerce at 205-764-4661.
</P>
<P>
   -- Creature comforts: Holiday Inn, Ramada Inn and Days Inn are
in Tuscumbia; Hampton Inn and Jameson Inn are in Florence. Locals
flock to two popular steakhouses, George's in Tuscumbia and Dale's
in Florence. (You may have seen the famous steak sauce from Dale's
at your local grocery store.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
