A8772 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      08-11 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Wednesday, Aug. 12. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286. 
 
BULLETS-MEXICO (Undated) - Mexican diplomatic officials say that
Scottsdale, Ariz., businessman Jim Brunen really had some lousy
luck when it came to assignment of a Mexican judge after he crossed
the border with ammo in his vehicle. Turns out that the judge
earlier had been roundly chastized by a higher court for quickly
releasing another U.S. citizen with ammo. Meanwhile, an off-duty
Nogales, Ariz., police officer was released within three days last
month after customs people found 2 boxes of ammo in his car. He had
a different judge. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A``
category. 
 
BILBY-OBIT (Phoenix) - U.S. District Judge Richard Bilby has died
of a heart attack. We take a look at him and his record. By JERRY
KAMMER and MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. 
 
JAZZDANCE (Phoenix) - A look at the weekend's events at the 1998
International Jazz Dance Conference in downtown Phoenix: the
performances, the seminars, the people. By KENNETH LAFAVE. Story
will move in the ``E'` category. 
 
SAMESEX (Undated) - The United Methodist Church's judicial council
ruling on blessing same-sex union is released Tuesday. DEVELOPING.
By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH. Story will move in the ``A`` category. 
 
ALLIED WASTE (Scottsdale, Ariz.) - Allied Waste buys yet another
company, this one a biggie. The $1 billion-plus deal makes Allied
Waste the third-largest garbage company in the country and cements
its position as one of the largest public companies in Arizona. By
DAWN GILBERTSON. Story will move in the ``F`` category. 
 
WOLF KILLED (Undated) - Another endangered Mexican gray wolf, one
of 11 released into the wild in eastern Arizona this spring, is
dead after an apparent battle with a mountain lion over food.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biologists and conservationists are lamenting the death of the
female wolf, which earlier this year gave birth to the first
Mexican gray wolf born in the American wilderness in half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   Now, only seven wolves, including the pup, are roaming free in
the Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest under the watch of U.S. Fish
and Wildlife agents who hope to repopulate the species. By GRACIELA
SEVILLA and STEVE YOZWIAK. Story moved in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LAWDOG (Undated) - She's a barrister for the birds, a legal eagle
for greyhounds. And she'd go to the wall for a lowly lab rat if it
was being maimed or mutilated through product testing. Stephanie
Nichols-Young doesn't know why she feels so strongly about
defending and protecting the rights of animals, animals who are
more likely to cough up fur balls than her hourly fee. ``I just
do,'' said the Phoenix attorney who refused to eat meat as a child
after seeing a slaughtered calf hanging in a barn. Nichols-Young is
not alone in her interest, however. ``It's growing because we have
at least a dozen law schools now teaching classes on animal law,''
she said. PHOTO. By LINDA HELSER. Story moved in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOYE-COLUMN (Undated) - What if God used a computer to create the
universe? I've been thinking about that since my way-cool
neighbors, Rick and Jacquie, brought over a humorous posting they
found online. I don't know who wrote it, but it's all about how God
tries to create the universe with a PC. Frustrated by problems at
the DOS prompt, including the dreaded ``Abort-Retry-Fail'' error
message, God finally goes out and buys a Macintosh. Funny. It would
explain a lot, though. By DAVID HOYE. Story moved in the ``F''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ Offended by nudity on the cover of
``Rolling Stone''? The usual suspects are, but I'm not. By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
ANNE STEPHENSON. Story moved in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BOOK-AUTHOR (Undated) _ ``The Pied Piper is one of history's first
recorded serial killers,'' Ridley Pearson says with ominous
pleasure. The story inspired his new suspense thriller, ``The Pied
Piper'' (Hyperion, $23.95), which involves babies, kidnappers and
an illegal adoption scheme. By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOK-PARKCITY (Undated) _ Bad news about Ann Beattie. Uncle. That's
all I have to say about ``Park City,'' a collection of 36 of Ann
Beattie's stories, including eight new ones. I can't finish it. I
just can't. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDITORIAL: Drugs and athletes: Just say no. Story moved in the
``K'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
