<HEADER>
A8774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CDC-TEENS-life-COX     08-11 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDC-TEENS-life-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some eyes are opened as teen health risk conference gets
underway
 &HT;    By J. Matthew Aldag
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Would you know a condom if you saw one?
</P>
<P>
   Sarita Rodriguez was surprised when one woman didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their faces were turning red when I was showing them condoms.
One woman had never seen a condom,'' said Rodriquez, a recent
graduate of Central High School in Erie, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled a class of women, some of them in their 40s, she
was teaching about the basic of HIV/AIDS prevention. When she asked
the group for an example of how HIV can be transmitted, she kept
getting the same answer: ``Saliva.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrong answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is promoting
education as a means to prevent HIV/AIDS transmission, looking at
that and other teen health risks at a national conference here this
week. HIV/AIDS has become more common in young populations; 50
percent of people who contract HIV are teens and young adults. The
opening speech of the conference Tuesday stressed what CDC experts
think is a effective way to teach teens: Let the teens do it.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriquez is a lead peer educator of the Family Health Council
of Pennsylvania. She is concerned that some adults have ``no idea
how you get HIV,'' because they won't be able to teach their kids
the facts about the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parenting classes should be given before they become
parents,'' said Rodriquez. She said teens want to get involved with
HIV/AIDS education, but few states have peer health education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want us to get youth involved, why don't you start
here. I don't see any youth here,'' said 25 year old Gary Artman to
the hundreds of health experts attending the opening panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easy to talk about us. But while it may be more
difficult, it is more advantageous to talk to us,'' he said. In
Pennsylvania, Artman participates in roundtable discussions
intended to educate youth about dangerous sexual activity. He is
amazed how often he runs into teens who think they don't need
condoms or that they are ``above the virus.''
</P>
<P>
   Artman, who is gay, had no HIV/AIDS sexual education in high
school, only an insensitive gym teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time it would come up, he would make a gay joke about
it,'' he said. Students were no better informed. During basketball
games in gym class, one student complained that Gary was going to
sweat on him and give him AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Pasquarelli and Scott Nelson of Brookwood High School in
Gwinnett County also grew up with little formal HIV/AIDS education.
They found a way to learn, and then to teach. With AIDGwinnett, a
community-based peer education program, the seniors run role
playing demonstrations at schools, churches and youth detention
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said that having kids teach sex education is better than
learning from a teacher who turns red when reading from a sex
education textbook. ``I can talk about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Pasquarelli don't get paid a cent for their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an idea out there saying a lot of youth are slackers
and don't care about anything. We are living proof that is not
true,'' said Artman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
