<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHLAMYDIA-GIRLS-COX     08-11 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHLAMYDIA-GIRLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Study reveals that chlamydia affects one in three sexually
active teen girls
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chlamydia, already considered a severe, silent sexually
transmitted disease among adult women, is striking earlier and more
frequently, a new study of teenage girls shows.
</P>
<P>
   Almost one in three sexually active adolescent girls between
ages 12 and 19 in the Baltimore area tested positive for the
infection during a 33-month study conducted by John Hopkins
University. Findings, released today in The Journal of the American
Medical Association, showed 14-year-old girls had the highest
proportion of infection, 27.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study is significant because chlamydia is considered the
Stealth bomber of sexually-transmitted infections, the one that
most often leads to infertility, chronic pain, and in some cases,
death during pregnancy. Chlamydia, a bacterial infection spread
through sexual contact, can easily be treated with antibiotics. But
women often don't have symptoms and the infection goes undiagnosed
until complications arise.
</P>
<P>
   Previous estimates had put the overall adolescent chlamydia rate
at one in 10 teens, but higher in urban areas and among poorer
women.
</P>
<P>
   Because some 75 percent of infected women are unaware they have
chlamydia, health experts have stressed the need to screen
annually. Now, the John Hopkins study recommends sexually-active
teenagers be screened every six months.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the time span between the initial negative test
and the first positive test was on average, seven months, among the
3,202 girls tested. Also, individual high-risk behaviors, such as
multiple sex partners and inconsistent condom use, failed at
predicting who would get the infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chlamydia control programs have succeeded by screening all
sexually active adolescent females, regardless of sexual practices
or demographics,'' study author Dr. Gale R. Burstein concludes.
``Public health researchers should concentrate future efforts on
prevention and partner notification.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which has historically had one of the worst STD rates
in the nation, just started a program to detect chlamydia sooner.
Under legislation that took effect July 1, health insurance plans
must pay for annual screening of all women age 29 and under. The
legislation does not apply to large companies that self insure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
