<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHLAMYDIA-QandA-COX     08-11 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHLAMYDIA-QandA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The facts about chlamydia
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Kathleen E. Toomey, director of the Georgia Division of
Public Health, and Dr. Helene Gayle, director of the National
Center for HIV, STD and TB Prevention, a branch of the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, talk about chlamydia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is chlamydia?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is a sexually-transmitted disease caused by the bacterium
chlamydia trachomatis. It can be spread by an infected man or
woman, whether or not that person has any noticeable symptoms. It
must be spread through direct person-to-person sexual contact. Two
uninfected people with no other sex partners besides each other
cannot contract chlamydia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are its symptoms?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oftentimes, none. Up to 80 percent of women and 50 percent of
men have no symptoms, so they do not seek health care and
unknowingly spread it. Men sometimes experience swelling of the
testicles, or discharge from the penis. Women could have discharge
or burning upon urination.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How widespread is the infection nationally?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is the most frequently reported infectious disease in the
United States. There are an estimated 4 million new cases of it
every year, split evenly among men and women. Most of the cases
involving women occur in the under-24 age group.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   A: Georgia ranks eighth worst in number of reported cases. An
estimated 100,000 Georgia women are infected with chlamydia every
year, with the highest prevalence rate among 15 to 19-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are its consequences?
</P>
<P>
   A: Left untreated, chlamydia infections in women lead to
long-term and potentially life-threatening consequences such as
infertility, constant pain, tubal pregnancy and HIV exposure. Some
40 percent of women will develop pelvic inflammatory disease (PID),
which can be debilitating in pain and require repeated
hospitalization or repeated outpatient visits. Just one PID episode
of pelvic infection can leave a woman infertile because of
fallopian tube scarring. Of those contacting PID from chlamydia, 20
percent will become infertile. Another 9 percent will suffer a
tubal pregnancy, which is the leading cause of first-trimester
pregnancy-related deaths among American women. And 18 percent of
the women will suffer constant pelvic pain, which can lead some to
undergo hysterectomies. In addition, women infected with chlamydia
have a 3-to-5 fold increased risk of acquiring HIV, if exposed to
the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the consequences for men?
</P>
<P>
   A: Men exposed to chlamydia may develop urethritis _ pain while
urinating. If the infection reaches the testicles, it can produce
scar tissue that blocks sperm ducts, causing sterility.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If pregnant women are infected with chlamydia, can it affect
the fetus?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Between 35 percent to 50 percent of infants born to
infected mothers develop a relatively minor eye inflammation, while
25 percent may develop pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the estimated costs of chlamydia?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nationally, the annual cost of the infection and its
complications is more than $2.4 billion. In Georgia, it costs $51
million. Every dollar spent on screening and treatment of this
disease saves about $12 in complications.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It sounds so widespread , so dire and so costly. What can be
done?
</P>
<P>
   A: The consequences of chlamydia are completely preventable. The
key lies in widespread screening, early detection and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Just the past few years have seen improvements in easier and
less-expensive testing, and in quick-acting antibiotics. Growing
culture for 48 hours is no longer required. Instead, a swab taken
from a woman's cervix is run through a test that looks for the DNA
fragments of the bacterium. Urine tests are in the final stages of
research. Treatment no longer requires a one-week dose of
antibiotics; one single dose is now available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What progress has been made in curtailing chlamydia?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the past decade, many more clinics and doctors' offices
are screening for chlamydia. Significant decline in infection rates
have been made in regions of the country that have implemented
federally funded screening (a 65 percent decrease in the Northwest
from 1988 to 1995 was noted). And a randomized trial at a health
maintenance organization found a 56 percent decrease in pelvic
infections in the group of women screened for chlamydia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
