<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER12-COX     08-11 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    British animated series is just a filler before the new season
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is retching. Is that what NBC thought would get the ``South
Park'' crowd?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say what NBC was thinking when it picked up ``Stressed
Eric,'' a six-episode animated series imported from England (9:30
EDT tonight on NBC ). Was it even thinking? It sure wasn't thinking
about attracting viewers. ``Stressed Eric'' has the short-timer
look of programming filler _ a cheap, mildly amusing stop gap
before the real stuff begins this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Feeble is a single father of two living in London. His wife
split to find herself (``I'm going for a swim in the lake of me''),
leaving frazzled accountant Eric to keep the household together.
It's not easy. His daughter is allergic to practically everything;
his son barely talks, but eats practically anything.
</P>
<P>
   His au pair is useless _ even when she's awake. ``When I ask you
to stay in and look after the kids,'' Eric says one morning while
trying to wake her, ``I don't expect you to go out and have 37
vodka slammers and come home at 4 a.m. with a rock band called the
Puss Doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   There's the decadent air of ``Absolutely Fabulous'' wafting
through here, but it loses its pungence when displayed as a
cartoon. So we're left with the perfect network compromise: neither
risky enough, nor smart enough, to look like anything original.
</P>
<P>
   Or like anything you'd want to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
