<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-11 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WILL CONGRESS REACT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that President Clinton's ordeal in the Monica
Lewinsky saga is about to shift from the courts to Congress, the
prospect of launching an impeachment process looks far less
politically palatable than it did when it was merely distant
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy of bringing down a president over moral impropriety
and perjury is one thing; the reality of probable voter anger at
those hypocrites who would levy such a disproportionate punishment,
quite another.
</P>
<P>
   If Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr sends a report to Congress
accusing the president of lying about a sexual dalliance and
encouraging others to lie as well, Congress cannot ignore it.
Partisan zealots and moral purists will demand some action, no
matter how inconclusive and circumstantial the evidence may be.
</P>
<P>
   But a rush to impeach the president for conduct that was
reckless and disingenuous but posed no constitutional crisis or
serious abuse of power is unlikely to be a popular move. A majority
of Americans already believe that the president misbehaved but
think he's doing a good professional job and ought to stay in
office anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, kicking Clinton out would leave the Republicans with an
incumbent Al Gore to face in the year 2000 presidential contest,
not a pleasing prospect from their point of view.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do? There is another way for Congress to kick Clinton
in the teeth without actually pounding him to smithereens. And that
is to consider censuring him instead.
</P>
<P>
   Since Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott recently suggested the
idea as a possible alternative, it has attracted increasing
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that Congress has the constitutional authority
to formally rebuke a president, short of the somber ritual of
impeachment for ``high crimes and misdemeanors.'' Such a move would
be plowing virtually untested ground.
</P>
<P>
   But it would have the momentary political charm of putting a
legislative and legal end to this tawdry tale more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Only one president, Andrew Johnson, has been impeached by the
House. It happened in 1868, during the post-Civil War turmoil, but
the Senate, sitting as a trial court, acquitted him _ by only one
vote short of the two-thirds majority needed for conviction. In
1974, the House Judiciary Committee recommended the impeachment of
Richard Nixon, who then resigned to avoid that fate.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred sixty-four years ago Andrew Jackson became the only
president to be censured, setting an ominous example that
politicians have thus far not cared to repeat. Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W. Va., recounts the dramatic episode in his authoritative
two-volume history of the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for the censure, approved by the Senate on March
28, 1834, on a 23-18 vote, was that Jackson was acting like a
despot. The real issue, however, was strictly a power struggle
among the era's political giants.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had refused to recharter the elite United States Bank
and withdrew its government deposits, effectively ending the bank's
self-serving dominance over American monetary policy. This angered
the bank's powerful allies, who formed the Whig Party and demanded
Jackson's censure.
</P>
<P>
   After their victory, Sen. Thomas Hart Benton, a Jackson backer,
dismissed the censure as ``nothing but an empty fulmination.'' And
so it proved to be.
</P>
<P>
   The House refused to go along with it. In the congressional
elections later that fall, Jackson's supporters increased their
majority in the House and took control of the Senate. Two years
later, the pro-Jackson Martin Van Buren was elected to the White
House and the Democrats tightened their grip on Congress. The
political climate became favorable to clearing Jackson's name.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1837, his Senate allies drew black lines around the
original recorded censure with the words ``expunged by order of the
Senate.'' The move was approved 24-19.
</P>
<P>
   The Whig Party, defeated on the bank issue and in the
congressional and presidential elections, lasted only another 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has been more effective in censuring its own members,
although it has applied the penalty only nine times, under great
provocation. Censure does not remove a member's right to vote or
speak or serve on committees, although it tends to isolate the
guilty person socially and politically.
</P>
<P>
   It is less harsh than the punishment of expulsion, a rarely used
remedy last recommended by the Senate Select Committee on Ethics in
1995 against Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore. He was cited for sexual
misconduct, influence peddling and obstruction of the committee's
investigation. Packwood resigned rather than let the recommendation
go to a full Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious case was that of Sen. Joseph McCarthy,
R-Wis., whose witch hunt for supposed communists in government
trampled civil liberties and produced no substantial evidence of
subversion. He was censured in 1954 for conduct ``contrary to
senatorial traditions.'' He remained in the Senate but died in 1957
a shunned and broken man.
</P>
<P>
   In any Clinton case, the House Judiciary Committee would be the
first congressional entity to tackle the issue of impeachment,
censure, reprimand or no action. In past decades the House has
censured several members, mostly for criminal offenses, but it
tends toward lighter reprimands for ethical violations. Speaker
Newt Gingrich, for instance, received a fine and a reprimand in
1997 for improper use of tax-exempt dollars for political purposes,
and he was allowed to keep his post as House leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8781 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GTECH-FOOTBALL-CO     08-11 0281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GTECH-FOOTBALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players suspended for one year
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech football coach George O'Leary suspended
tight ends Mike Lillie and reserve Chris Myers for one year Tuesday
for unspecified violation of team rules.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary would not divulge what the players had done or when the
infractions occurred, saying only that they had violated team rules
and that it ``took a while'' to make the decision. The move came
two days before varsity players were scheduled to report to campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like to start off with this note, but we needed to
do it,'' O'Leary said. ``It was a hard decision, but that was the
decision that was made. I wanted to make sure I made the right
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillie, a redshirt sophomore from River Ridge, La., and Myers, a
redshirt senior from Panama City, Fla., were listed as co-starters
at tight end on Tech's preseason depth chart. Myers plans to
complete the academic year at Tech, while Lillie plans to transfer
to another school, although he's not sure where, Tech spokesman
Mike Finn said.
</P>
<P>
   Tech returns three other tight ends _ senior Matt Gubba, junior
Conrad Andrzejewski and redshirt freshman Russell Matvay.
</P>
<P>
   A freshman at the position is Brian Lee, a 6-5, 243-pounder from
Florence, Ala. Sophomore fullback Ed Wilder also could be used at
tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a position we have some flexibility with,'' O'Leary said.
``But no question they'll be missed. . . . It has to hurt you down
the road because you've worked so hard to build depth. That's my
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
