A8782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KENTUCKY-COX     08-11 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KENTUCKY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kentucky aims for a bowl year
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hal Mumme's comfort level is demonstrated by his steadfast
refusal to wear neckties in a button-down league that last fall was
forced to take notice of the Kentucky coach's swashbuckling
play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Couch's comfort level depends a lot on the fact that Mumme
fully turned him loose to steer a BYU-style offense that delighted
the citizenry of a basketball-crazed commonwealth and made football
more than a sporting diversion. But the Heisman quarterback
candidate acknowledges the honeymoon will be over if the Wildcats
can do nothing more this year than provide breathtaking
entertainment without the results required in the bottom-line SEC.
</P>
<P>
   A year after Mumme arrived from Valdosta State to give Kentucky
a badly needed football makeover, the Wildcats are still snarling
about a 5-6 finish in his first campaign. They're convinced that
two games, including a 23-13 loss at Georgia, shouldn't have
slipped away, taking some of the shine off the school's first win
over Alabama in 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   For just the second time in school history, a full complement of
40,000 season tickets is expected to be sold. The athletic
department already has begun its ambitious Heisman campaign for
Couch, a junior who finished ninth in last year's balloting and
could be playing his last season of college football. And while the
schedule isn't especially kind, with road games at Florida, LSU and
Tennessee, there are enough soft spots for Kentucky to earn its
first bowl bid in six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to expect us to win those games we lost last
year, but that's a good feeling for us to have,'' Couch said.''
People believe in us now, and we believe in ourselves as well.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Kentucky understandably places its full faith and
trust in Couch, who led the country with 3,884 passing yards and 37
touchdowns and was second in total offense with 341.7 yards a game.
Returning to the no-huddle, shotgun formation are All-American
receiver candidate Craig Yeast, who had 73 receptions for 873 yards
and 10 touchdowns, all school records, and three others who caught
at least 31 passes each. One of them is a running back, Derek
Homer, who managed 502 yards on the ground to complement the
aerials. Couch's line also has four of five 1997 starters
returning.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the defensive side of the ball that still causes
shudders, despite Mumme's protestations that there was considerable
progess during the spring. The Cats were last in the SEC in total
defense (392 yards), scoring defense (33 points) and first downs
surrendered (20 a game). While there are some solid returnees in
linebacker Jeff Snedegar and free safety Willie Gary, Kentucky
simply cannot afford to give up points as easily as the offense
produces them. One possible solution for a shaky defensive line is
true freshman Dennis Johnson, the Atlanta Touchdown Club's national
prep player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we went with 14 guys (on defense) who had never
walked onto an SEC playing field before,`` Mumme said. ``We need
more numbers, and we need more speed. At the other places I've
been, we've won championships because of great defense. That's what
we're trying to do at Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch worked in the off-season and spring on greater precision
throwing longer passes, and he gained 18 pounds, to 230, and thinks
that it has helped his arm strength. Spicing up an already
flavorful attack with deeper patterns also figures to help him
prepare better for the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in the NFL has always been a dream of mine, but I'm
not thinking about it now,'' he said. ``I'm having too much fun
playing college football. We're going to put points on the board no
matter who we're playing, but the bottom line is we're going to
have to stop some people.''
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY FACT BOX
</P>
<P>
   Location: Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 24,000.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Hal Mumme (5-6 in one season at Kentucky, 70-33-1
overall).
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Commonwealth Stadium (55,453).
</P>
<P>
   All-time record: 504-477-44.
</P>
<P>
   SEC championships: 2 (1950, 1976).
</P>
<P>
   1997 record: 5-6; 2-6 SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: Sept. 5 at Louisville; Sept. 12 vs. Eastern Kentucky;
Sept. 19 vs. Indiana; Sept. 26 at Florida; Oct. 3 at Arkansas; Oct.
10 vs. South Carolina; Oct. 17 at LSU; Oct. 24 vs. Georgia; Nov. 7
vs. Mississippi State; Nov. 14 vs. Vanderbilt; Nov. 21 at
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Coming Thursday: Arkansas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
