<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS12-COX     08-11 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie Fisk risking his health, some doctors believe
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like many NFL rookies, Atlanta Falcons fullback Darren
Fisk has a vision of making it in pro football. Sometimes, though,
that vision gets a little blurry.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk, an undrafted free agent from Colorado, has been in three
head-to-head collisions in camp that produced blurred vision and
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   At least one doctor thinks that Fisk, 24, has suffered from
post-concussion symptoms. At least one other physician thinks a
defective artery leading to Fisk's brain gets pinched easily when
his head is jarred to the left. A neuro-opthamologist believes the
problem could be migraines triggered by collisions.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk has no history of such problems and isn't sure what to
think. Doctors have told him that playing poses a very slight risk
of vision loss and left the decision on playing to him.
</P>
<P>
   After missing practice Monday, Fisk was back out on the practice
field Tuesday, lowering the boom on linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to church Sunday, and the whole sermon was about how I
have to do what (God) wants me to do and not what I want to do,''
said Fisk, a 6-foot-1, 230-pound back from Los Gatos, Calif.
``(Team officials) said (Sunday night), 'We really don't think
there is a big risk; it's up to you.' I went to meetings (Monday)
night and thought about it, and something was just telling me to
keep going. Something's not right, but I honestly don't think I'm
going to lose my vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk, who said he previously had a concussion or two, said his
problem started on July 25, the third day of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a goal-line scrimmage, I had a hard head-to-head collision
with a linebacker, and about 10 seconds later I started having
blurred vision, kind of a headache, and I thought, 'Oh, no, I've
got a concussion,''' said Fisk, who was honored as the ``Tough
Buff'' at Colorado for his intensity and physical nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practice was over, and I was like, 'Should I tell anybody?
Because it's the NFL and it might hurt my chances.' (Starting
fullback) Bobby Christian told me I should tell them. So I told
them, and it was no big deal. That next Wednesday, I got another
one, and it was like, 'Whoa! I better watch what I'm doing. At
Colorado, I was taught to lead with my head, more than my
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, in Jacksonville (Aug. 1), and I (hit) a linebacker, head
to head. I couldn't see for 45 minutes or so, and I got a
headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk didn't miss a practice the next week, and a CAT scan
revealed no abnormalities. But team doctor Andrew Bishop expressed
enough concern that Fisk was told there could be some risk if he
played Friday in the preseason opener against Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk decided to play and had no problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, team officials had him undergo a magnetic
resonance imaging test (MRI), and it was revealed that Fisk has a
congenital defect _ an artery leading to the left side of his brain
is smaller than normal. But there was no conclusion that it was
causing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   An eye doctor found nothing wrong, so Fisk was sent to
neuro-opthamologist Robert Spector, who concluded that the problems
are migraine-related. Although a small percentage of migraines
include vision-related problems, there are cases of it happening.
</P>
<P>
   Spector declined comment, and questions were referred to head
trainer Ron Medlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not really suffered a concussion, per se, but he did
see a white flash across the eyes which can be construed as a
symptom of a concussion,'' Medlin said. ``(Dr. Spector's)
conclusion was that it was migraine-related, brought on by the
blows he received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say 110 percent, 'Darren, you're at no risk,' because
that is an unknown.' There have been a couple cases in literature
of partial vision loss (in cases like this). (But) the risk is
greater of breaking an ankle or tearing up a knee.''
</P>
<P>
   So Fisk, who is fighting long odds to make the team, continues
to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called my parents, and they said, 'What are you going to do
if you lose your vision?''' he said. ``So they didn't think I
should do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it, and something was just telling me to keep
going. I don't know if they think I'm a problem now, but I love
this, and something is telling me to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
