<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-WHOWHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS PURCHASE AIMED AT INTERNET GATEWAY STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc., long regarded as a laggard in the race to become a
gateway to the Internet, &UR;  &LR;  hopes to leap to the head of the pack
with a $133 million purchase of WhoWhere Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lycos chief executive &UR;  &LR;  Robert Davis said the deal,
announced Tuesday, will help his firm become not only a doorway to
the Internet, but a major destination in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, of Waltham, Mass., will pay about 2 million shares
of &UR;  &LR; its stock for WhoWhere, a closely-held Mountain View, Calif.,
firm that owns the popular WhoWhere Internet white pages service as
well as MailCity, a free electronic mail system and Angelfire, a
free Web page hosting service.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos is one of several firms building Internet ``portals'', or
Web sites that attract millions of visitors. While visitors aren't
charged for using the portal, advertisers and Internet retailers
pay millions of dollars to have their ads and electronic
storefronts on portal sites. The leading portals are run by the
America Online computer network and by the Internet search service
Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts us in a credible position to say we're challenging for
the No. 1 &UR;  &LR; spot in this space,'' said Davis, of the WhoWhere
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Portals generally offer popular services like Web page searches,
news headlines and free e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Lycos' &UR;  &LR; expansion plan is Angelfire, where
visitors can build their own Web site at no charge. Angelfire
presently has 1.3 million users, many of whom are adolescents or
adults over 40. That makes the company a good fit with Tripod, a
free Web site service that Lycos purchased earlier this year.
Tripod's 1.8 million members are mainly teens and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   Both Angelfire and Tripod attract users who spend hours on-line
designing their Web sites and visiting other sites created by
members with similar interests. Lycos will thus be able to deliver
an audience of millions to Internet advertisers, in much the same
way television delivers millions of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The other parts of the WhoWhere acquisition are also supposed to
feed into this strategy. WhoWhere itself attracts thousands of
users trying to look up people's e-mail addresses and phone
numbers. MailCity has 9.3 million registered users.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Delhagen, an Internet analyst for Forrester Research in
Cambridge, said that Lycos is doing a good job of establishing
itself as a major presence on the Internet. ``They've grabbed yet
another big community,'' said Delhagen. ``This gives them yet one
more opportunity to generate revenue for all those commerce
partners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
