<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-YOUTHCRIME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAJORITY OF TEENAGERS SAY SCHOOL CRIME AND VIOLENCE IS THEIR TOP
CONCERN
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six out of 10 teenagers say their top concern is
crime and violence in school, according to a nationwide survey
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey paints a picture of high school students who are
concerned with scholastic achievement, get along well with their
parents and are optimistic about the future.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of nearly 1,200 students found that four out of 10
said they make homework a priority, with one-fourth receiving
mostly A's on their last report card. Half of the students said
they try to take the most difficult and challenging courses they
can, although girls were more likely than boys _ by a ratio of
three-to-two _ to sign up for tougher courses.
</P>
<P>
   Some boys said they try to hide their intelligence from peers
for fear of being called a ``nerd'' or ``geek.'' Girls indicated
they feel pride about their intelligence and don't try to hide it.
</P>
<P>
   Among other survey findings:
</P>
<P>
   Girls feel optimistic about achieving their career goals and
</P>
<P>
   anticipate earning the same or more than men.
</P>
<P>
   Most teenagers said cheating exists in schools and they
</P>
<P>
   believe more than half of all students cheat at one point in
their high school careers.
</P>
<P>
   Four out of 10 cite a family member as their role model; six
</P>
<P>
   out of 10 said parents spend the ``right amount'' of time with
their children and that they like and respect their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Nine out of 10 feel that mathematics is the most important
</P>
<P>
   course to take for future success.
</P>
<P>
   The top career choices, in order, were: teacher, computer
</P>
<P>
   hardware/software developer, medical doctor, business person and
an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by The Horatio Alger Association of
Distinguished Americans, Inc., a nonprofit educational
organization, who sent self-administered mail questionnaires to
high school students between the ages of 14 and 18 nationwide in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
