<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: LOWER FARES TO NORTH DAKOTA; SPECIAL DEAL TO HONG
KONG; LAPTOP UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bowing to pressure from North Dakota politicians and local
airport managers, Northwest Airlines said Tuesday that it would cut
business fares to and from the state as part of a six-month trial
to stimulate passenger traffic. The fares, discounted as much as 60
percent on connecting flights and 42 percent on nonstop flights,
are available immediately for travel from Sept. 14 through March
31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The new discounts come against the backdrop of mounting
political pressures in state legislatures and in Congress to rein
in rising business fares. Just this Monday, a Democratic candidate
for attorney general of Minnesota said that if elected, he would
summon a task force to recommend ways of increasing airline
competition in the state and would also investigate whether
Northwest had violated antitrust laws _ a suggestion the carrier
denies.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Tuesday's decision, Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., said:
``Community representatives and our airport managers have been in
ongoing discussions with Northwest on the issue of reducing fares
since last October. Northwest is responding to our analysis and
concerns that the current business fares are inhibiting some North
Dakota travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Last May, in what it said was an effort to spur economic
development in the nine-county greater Des Moines, Iowa, area,
UAL's United Airlines cut fares between Des Moines and other
Midwest cities by 34 percent, to $249 each way. It also cut 50
percent off 14-day advance fares that do not require a Saturday
night stay. And by deploying bigger planes between Des Moines and
Chicago, it added 812 seats each week during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mitchell, chairman of the Business Travel Coalition, said
that both the United and Northwest decisions were directly related
to the increasing business, government and news media pressure on
the airlines. Tuesday's cuts, he said, ``underscore the usefulness
of federal government leadership on the competition issue in
providing local communities with impartial data and analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Northwest does not seem prepared to lose revenue
indefinitely on its North Dakota experiment. ``A substantial
increase in the unrestricted business fare traffic will be required
to maintain these fares after the test period,'' the carrier said
in a statement. ``For example on many routes, passengers in the
business fare category will have to double their current level just
to maintain present revenue levels for Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   During the test period, one-way fares between Bismarck, N.D.,
and Chicago, for example, will fall to $195 from $460, between
Bismarck and Washington to $325 from $680 and between Minot, N.D.,
and Chicago to $195 from $484. Reductions on flights from both
Bismarck and Minot to Minneapolis-St. Paul will range between 36
and 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said it would support its lower business fares with
increased marketing, advertising and by including the rates on its
World Wide Web site. Test results will be reported by early January
1999, and a final evaluation will be released about mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap Seats to Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
   From now through the end of the month, Cathay Pacific is
offering round-trip flights to Hong Kong from New York and Los
Angeles for $399 plus taxes and fees. Seats are limited and tickets
_ nonrefundable even in the event of illness _ are valid for travel
between Sept. 1 and Nov. 30, among other restrictions. Moreover,
the fare is available only via the Internet, although there is no
charge for registration (www.cathay-usa.com/hop) and it takes only
a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling With Laptops
</P>
<P>
   An American Express survey of business travelers has found that
65 percent of respondents always or almost always use a laptop
computer on overnight trips. Those travelers will probably be
pleased to learn that the new security gates at United Airlines'
Terminal 7 at Los Angeles International airport, scheduled to open
in early September, will allow passengers to go through without
switching on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Security-minded laptop owners may be glad to know that Port
Inc., which already offers a motion-sensitive system for
notebook-computer carrying cases, has developed a remote control
security system. When motion is detected, an electronic sensor
triggers an alarm that activates a siren, which sounds for up to 30
seconds. A key chain remote control, usable up to 40 feet, has a
panic button that signals an immediate alarm to find a lost
carrying case or to signal an alert if a thief grabs the case.
</P>
<P>
   The August issue of Mobile Computing &AMP; Communications magazine
reports on the results of a drop test of seven leading computer
bags, each one dropped from 29 inches (desk height) and 40 inches
(shoulder height). The winners, which tied for first place, were
Brenthaven's Computer Topload ($275) and Tumi's Safecase Basic
Computer Brief ($250).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
