<HEADLINE>
FOREIGNERS DETAINED FOR QUESTIONING IN BOMBING PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police in Tanzania have arrested 14 foreigners and
detained 16 others for questioning as authorities cast a wide net
for anyone who has information about last week's US embassy
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Six Sudanese, six Iraqis, one Somali and one Turk were arrested,
according to police there. They did not provide a satisfactory
explanation for their presence in the country and could not produce
their passports, a spokesman said. He declined to name the 14
people, who were arrested in Dar es Salaam at different times. None
has been charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Foley said US investigators on
the ground in Kenya and Tanzania have ``access to the information
they require.'' But he refused to say whether the suspects have
been questioned by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Sudanese suspects said that he worked for the Saudi
Arabian embassy in Dar es Salaam, and five claimed to be visitors.
The Iraqis included a civil servant, an engineer, a teacher, a
telecommunications technician and an agricultural engineer. The
Somali said he was working for the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees. No details were available about the Turk.
</P>
<P>
   A Tanzanian police spokesman called them ``dubious characters''
who might have been involved in the bombing that killed 10 people
near the American embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania's former
capital.
</P>
<P>
   As details emerge from last Friday morning's events in Nairobi
and Dar es Salaam, intelligence officials have a better idea of the
size of the bombs and the type of explosives used. Experts now
believe the device in Nairobi weighed at least 500 pounds. Israel
army radio reported that investigators think the bombers used
Semtex, a sophisticated plastic explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Both those factors point to Osama bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi
exile thought be living in Afghanistan, according to Ariel Merari,
an expert on international terrorism at Israel's Tel Aviv
University. In February, Bin Laden and leaders of the Islamic Jihad
group issued a fatwa, or Islamic religious ruling, calling for the
killing of Americans, civilian and military. Just a few weeks ago,
Bin Laden warned reporters of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department cautioned against drawing conclusions from
the nationalities of those arrested. The investigtion ``is going to
take a long time, given the nature of the crime,'' said spokesman
James Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intelligence organizations of this country are now very
busy exchanging notes with the Americans,'' said Mirari. ``But they
don't know any more than the Americans at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Merari, who keeps extensive computerized files on terrorists,
said the authorities first try to assess what motivated an attack
and then analyze how it was carried out.
</P>
<P>
   A day after announcing a $2 million reward for the capture and
conviction of the bombers, State Department officials said that US
agencies had received numerous tips, although it is too early to
evaluate how useful they will be.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also refused to confirm a report that a security
camera atop the American embassy in Tanzania, which was pointed at
the site of the bombing, did not have film.
</P>
<P>
   As the rescue effort entered its fifth day, the death toll in
Kenya reached 218, including 12 Americans. Another 10 died in
Tanzania, where the US embassy was in a less crowded residential
neighborhood by the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern African country of Swaziland, a bomb threat
Tuesday triggered fears of another attack. Two buildings housing
U.S. embassy offices were evacuated, but police found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Another six American embassies and consulates elsewhere abroad
have been closed temporarily because of threats, according to
Patrick Kennedy, an assistant secretary of state in charge of
administation. ``We are not shutting the embassies down. We are not
leaving,'' Kennedy said. ``We are taking, in effect, a timeout.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few world leaders to speculate publically on the
identity of the bombers was Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, who said the initial evidence points to ``international
terrorism centered on Islamic fundamentalism.''
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with African ambassadors in Washington, Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright alluded to the speculation. ``Terror is
not a form of political expression, it is certainly not a
manifestation of religious faith,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she will visit the sites of the destruction soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Bonnie Rochman contributed to this report
from Jerusalem; wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
