<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Aug. 12 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact William Toren at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   BLOWER-BAN (Los Angeles) _ Opening a loophole that effectively
neuters the Los Angeles leaf blower ban, the City Attorney's Office
said it will not prosecute gardeners who say their machines are
fueled by methanol, not gasoline. Officials will rely on gardeners'
word and not check the fuel. By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the
``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PROP227 (Los Angeles) _ Since voting to disregard voters and
joining efforts to overturn Proposition 227, members of the Los
Angeles City Council have been receiving dozens of complaints from
angry constituents. Councilman Richard Alatorre, who launched the
fight to retain traditional bilingual education, says he will use
is political officeholder account to pay the legal expenses. By
Patrick McGreevy. (Will move in the ``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NAGGING (Los Angeles) _ A new survey shows what millions of
children already know: nagging pays. Up to 40 percent of consumer
purchases and dining choices are determined by kids who nag their
parents to buy. By Melissa Schmitt. (Will move in the ``a''
national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FARRAH-FAWCETT (Los Angeles) _ Farrah Fawcett took the stand in
the domestic abuse trial of her boyfriend, director-producer James
Orr. Fawcett had told police that Orr had struck her, but later
declined to press charges. The Los Angeles City Attorney's Office,
however, proceeded with the case. By Alex Roth. (Will move in the
``a'' national news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
