A8845 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-BOMBINGS-HNS &LR;      08-11 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-BOMBINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS U.S. WILL NOT BACK AWAY FROM GLOBAL RESPONSIBILITIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
and STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton called on Americans Tuesday to
``send a clear signal to the world'' that the United States would
not back away from its global responsibilities in wake of the
deadly bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is terribly frightening to people when something
like this happens, but ... I think it is important that we all, as
Americans, send a clear signal to the world that we are not going
to back away from our involvement with other people, and we are not
going to back away from our opposition to terrorism,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes us more vulnerable as targets because we have taken
the toughest stand around the world against terrorism. Now is the
time to bear down, not back up, on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the Bay Area for fund-raising events, will return to
Washington at dawn Wednesday to hold meetings with his national
security staff and to attend memorial services Thursday for 10 of
the 12 slain Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One American, married to a Kenyan, will be buried in Africa and
another will be flown to Dover, Del., where her remains will be
released directly to the victim's family.
</P>
<P>
   The president told Californians that the United States was
working with the governments of Kenya and Tanzania on rescue and
treatment efforts for victims in both countries. And, he said the
African governments were working closely with the United States to
find the terrorists responsible.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. allies are also providing help.
</P>
<P>
   Australia, Britain, France, Germany, Greece, Israel, Norway,
Japan and South Africa have joined the United States in sending law
enforcement experts, soldiers, planes, blood or trauma teams to the
destroyed embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
said State Department spokesman James Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Friday morning bombings, the U.S. military has
completed more than 17 airlift missions to and from Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also notified Congress that he ordered 50 to 100
combat-ready troops to provide security around the damaged
embassies in Africa and to protect U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The notification was required by the War Powers Act, but Clinton
emphasized the troops were deployed for medical and security
assistance only and will return to their bases.
</P>
<P>
   Six other U.S. embassies around the world were briefly closed
after receiving terrorist threats in the wake of the attacks in
East Africa, Patrick Kennedy, assistant secretary of state for
administration, told reporters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy refused to disclose which embassies had been threatened,
citing security concerns. He called the temporary shutdowns a
``brief timeout'' to assess security and said the safety measures
did not significantly interfere with the work of embassy employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not shutting embassies down in a permanent sense,''
Kennedy said. ``We are not leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright hopes to visit the
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania soon, Foley said. However, Albright
will not make the trip until she is sure the visit would not
interfere with the ongoing investigation, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to symbolize the fact that we will not be intimidated,
that we will rebuild our embassies,'' Foley said. ``Our foreign
policy is not going to be changed ... as the result of any
terrorist attacks.''.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
