<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVEN-SEEKING INVESTORS PUSH TREASURIES UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities made modest price gains Tuesday
as investors sought a haven from the stock market and from overseas
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for Treasuries pushed down the long bond's yield,
which falls as prices rise, close to its all-time low. One reason
for the demand was that the dollar surged to an eight-year high
against the Japanese yen, and investors grew concerned that Russia
might default on debt repayments. A strong dollar makes
dollar-denominated investments like Treasury securities more
attractive to foreign investors, not only for the return but also
for the potential gains from currency translations.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day the 30-year benchmark issue was up 11/32, to
a price of 107 17/32, and its yield fell to 5.60 percent, from 5.62
percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the Treasury's $16 billion, five-year-note auction Tuesday,
part of its quarterly sale of notes and bonds, the yield came in at
5.327 percent, a little worse than expected, although not
surprising considering bonds were rallying at the time. Usually
dealers will raise yield levels ahead of an auction to attract
investors, but the rally may have cut into that pre-auction
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the government will auction $11 billion of 10-year
notes by reopening the 5.625 percent issue due May 15, 2008, and on
Thursday it will sell $10 billion of a new 30-year bond. In
when-issued trading, the 10-year note was being offered at a price
to yield 5.36 percent and the 30-year bond at a price to yield 5.52
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Whelan, vice president and portfolio manager at Aeltus
Investment Management, said the bond market's strength came from
two sources Tuesday, primarily from the so-called flight to quality
from other assets like emerging markets and stocks. The second
source of strength, he said, was ``from people beginning to wonder
if Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan would entertain the idea
of an ease in interest rates to offset some of the global weakness
that seems to be deteriorating further.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the close of the New York market, bond yields came off
their best levels of the day, in response, Whelan said, ``to a
stabilizing stock market and a mediocre five-year note auction,
which I thought was affected by the rally in Treasuries.'' He
added, ``Some investors will set up short positions ahead of an
auction, but the rally in the market caused those investors to
cover their positions prematurely.''
</P>
<P>
   Even strong economic data Tuesday were overwhelmed by events in
overseas markets and in domestic stock markets. Second-quarter
nonfarm business productivity edged down at a two-tenths of 1
percent annual rate, which was in line with expectations given
Asia's economic crisis and the General Motors strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Donne, vice president and senior portfolio manager at
Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus, Ohio, said: ``Clearly the
stock market decline is an indication of an asset reallocation play
going on. There is a question now being asked: What is the most
desirable asset? People are rethinking their positions, but it does
not reflect any change in fundamentals in the market. The economy
has not changed except to slow slightly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
