<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AGREES TO $1.9M SETTLEMENT IN SHOOTING OF YOUNG TEXAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The federal government will pay $1.9 million to
the parents of a young Texan who was shot and killed last year by a
Marine assigned to an anti-drug patrol near the Rio Grande, the
family's lawyer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Esequiel Hernandez Jr., 18, was killed May 20, 1997, by Cpl.
Clemente Banuelos, who was leading a four-man patrol on the edge of
Redford, a remote West Texas village of mostly adobe and
cinderblock shacks.
</P>
<P>
   Rosendo Ibaro, a friend of the Hernandez family, said the
out-of-court deal was tantamount to an admission of guilt by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they are offering money, that means they were
automatically liable. That's the way I see it,'' said Ibaro, who
drove the school bus that Hernandez rode to daily.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Watney, a spokeswoman for the Justice Department, said
the government didn't admit any wrongdoing in the settlement and
that privacy laws prevented her from discussing details of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can confirm is that there was a settlement,''
Watney said from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that would adequately compensate the family
for the loss they have suffered,'' said Bill Weinacht, a Pecos
lawyer who represented the Hernandez family in its pursuit of a
wrongful death lawsuit against the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Weinacht said the settlement involves structured payments from
the Justice Department and the Navy Department, which includes the
Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Marine officials from the start said the Marines acted properly.
Banuelos, who was honorably discharged from the Marines in June,
shot Hernandez once in the ribcage with an M-16 rifle after
Hernandez fired twice at the Marines with a .22-caliber rifle and
aimed the weapon a third time.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines were working in conjunction with the U.S. Border
Patrol on a mission to gather intelligence on drug traffickers
operating in the vicinity of Redford at a crossing area known as El
Polvo, or the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Hernandez family have said the young man likely
thought the camouflaged soldiers were wild animals or may have been
shooting at rocks as he tended the family goats. He carried the
rifle to protect the goats.
</P>
<P>
   The incident sparked a national debate about the use of the
military to patrol the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question problems occurred,'' Weinacht said of the
incident. ``They (the Marines) certainly need to alter their
procedures to better protect the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, grand jurors who deliberated Tuesday in nearby Marfa
declined to indict Banuelos after considering charges of murder,
manslaughter and deadly conduct, said Albert Valadez, the district
attorney in Presidio County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them (jurors) to consider murder because of the
statement by Banuelos that he shot to kill,'' Valadez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the grand jury would reach a different decision, but
I was wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Presidio County grand jury that met last year also did not
charge any of the Marines in the case, but the matter was again
presented at the urging of federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Zimmermann, a retired Marine colonel who is representing
Banuelos, said that although his client committed no crime, the
Hernandez family deserved a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a humanitarian point of view, I thought there should be
some kind of compensation,'' Zimmermann said from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point we need to let Clemente Banuelos know what he
did was what he was supposed to do and let it go,'' Zimmermann
said. ``Corporal Banuelos' actions were entirely justified under
the law and consistent with what he was trained to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has yet to decide whether to resume
anti-drug patrols along the border, and U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas, who is head of the House subcommittee on immigration, is
investigating the shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
