u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BALLOON-FOSSETT-A     08-11 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BALLOON-FOSSETT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLOON SOARS OVER ATLANTIC, SETTING RECORD IN SOLO FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867. 
(nk) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speeding along at more than 100 mph, the millionaire adventurer
Steve Fossett on Tuesday became the first balloonist to cross the
South Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   As he passed the southern tip of Africa on his way eastward from
Argentina, Fossett clocked 5,000 miles _ one-fifth of the distance
he hopes to cover in the next two weeks to become the first
balloonist to circle the world nonstop. By coincidence, he
completed the South Atlantic leg of his flight on the 20th
anniversary of the first balloon crossing of the North Atlantic _ a
record achieved by the Double Eagle II, which was a larger balloon
flown by a crew of three.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett emulates the piloting style of Charles Lindbergh by
always flying alone and by carrying a bare minimum of equipment and
comforts.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday the 54-year-old commodities broker and sportsman,
who lives with his wife, Peggy, in Beaver Creek, Colo., began his
quest for ballooning glory and the $1 million Budweiser prize from
a stadium in Mendoza, Argentina. This is his fourth attempt at
circling the world; he already holds the world's ballooning
distance record of 10,360.61 miles for his flight in January 1997
from St. Louis to Nonkhar, India.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade at least a dozen attempts have been made by
balloonists from four countries to circle the earth _ all of them
in the Northern Hemisphere _ but all have fallen far short of the
goal. Besides the daunting technical and weather problems they
faced, the balloonists had to contend with the withholding of
overflight permission by various countries. China, Libya and Iraq,
among others, have thwarted balloon flights.
</P>
<P>
   By making his latest transglobal attempt in the Southern
Hemisphere, Fossett hopes to avoid political problems. The only
major land masses he expects to cover are South America, South
Africa and Australia. But the disadvantage of the southern route,
he said in an interview before starting his current flight, is that
a forced landing in the vast southern oceans, far from any shipping
route, ``would present serious problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossett's Solo Spirit balloon, built by Cameron Balloons Ltd. in
Britain, has roughly twice the volume of helium lifting gas
(450,000 cubic feet) as did his previous balloons. This allows him
to carry much more propane fuel for burners that heat air and
provide supplementary lift at night, when the balloon loses
buoyancy.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Fossett lifted off on Friday, a fire broke out
involving two of the craft's four burners, and his face was burned.
But he extinguished the flames and repaired one of the damaged
burners, so that three will be available for the rest of the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett's spokesmen at Washington University in St. Louis report
that although he is flying at 24,000 feet in an unpressurized
capsule, he is reasonably comfortable. The cabin temperature, which
on previous flights was below freezing, is about 60 degrees.
Fossett conditioned himself for the thin air of his trip by
sleeping each night during the past month in a low-pressure chamber
simulating high altitude.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW12-COX     08-11 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors sift for clues amid market's rubble
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An agonizing waiting game is under way on Wall Street as
investors look for clues to how long the latest stock market
correction will last, and how bad it will get before it turns.
</P>
<P>
   In a report circulated by Prudential Securities to its offices
Tuesday, recently bearish technician Ralph Acampora said the bottom
``will be made in the October time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts prefer not to be pinned down to a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if this is a bear market or a normal bull market
correction,'' said Ricky T. Harrington of Interstate/Johnson Lane.
``A serious correction is certainly overdue. Or, the market could
go into another trading range.''
</P>
<P>
   If the market's longer-range future is fundamentally good, as
analysts generally contend, its near-term technical signals are
scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standout negative signal is the biggest divergence
(between big and small stocks) in years,'' said Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   He said stock market averages are being propped up by the
purchase of mostly blue chip stocks by mutual fund managers and
foreigners seeking a safe haven _ and that the indexes are
deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underneath a seemingly strong market you have a weak market,''
said Harrington, citing recent reports that as many as half of all
Nasdaq stocks and 30 percent of all New York Stock Exchange stocks
are down 30 percent or more from their 52-week highs.
</P>
<P>
   As for fundamentals, he said the market is finally waking up to
the fact that Asia's economic crisis really is putting a dent in
U.S. corporate earnings, and that this will continue.
</P>
<P>
   This has produced the weakest market since 1994, when stocks
fell during a yearlong series of interest rate hikes by the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's market looked for a while as though it would be a
repeat of a week ago, when the Dow lost 299.43 points, its third
worst one-day point loss.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Dow was down nearly 258 points, or 3 percent,
before a late rally trimmed the loss to 1.3 percent. Broader and
secondary market averages fell even more: the technology-loaded
Nasdaq composite by 2.5 percent and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller-capitalized stocks by 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blame shrinking profit growth for the latest
correction, as double-digit earnings increases drop to low
single-digit gains.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based First Call, which tracks earnings trends, said 89
percent of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies have released their most
recent quarterly earnings, and the average year-over-year gain is
2.3 percent. That's down from 3.8 percent in the first quarter and
11 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the excessive valuation of most stocks and you have
the seriousness of the latest correction, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't justify stocks selling at 28 times earnings,''
Georgia Tech's Fred C. Allvine said of the price-to-earnings ratio
of the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a market of hot air that could drop 20 to 30
percent,'' said Allvine, director of Georgia Tech's Stock Market
Project. ``People need to protect their gains.''
</P>
<P>
   The best protection, according to some investment advisers, is
to adopt a longer-range strategy and stick to it even in a down
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming a strategy is in place, we think there are
opportunities here,'' said D. Ray Peebles, a portfolio manager at
Atlanta-based CornerCap Investment Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, ``there is a lot of hand-holding in this business,''
said Peebles. ``And we have done some hand-holding recently.''
</P>
<P>
   He said an investment strategy should be tailored to the
individual's goals and objectives, and change when those objectives
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not suggested an increase in cash holdings,'' said
Peebles of the portfolios under his firm's management. ``We stay
fully invested.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
