<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8880 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-NUKE-ART-500&AMP;A     08-11 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NUKE-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL REMOVES ROADBLOCK TO TREATY ON NUCLEAR MATERIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Bowing to American pressure, Israel announced
Tuesday that it would not block the next step in a U.N. effort to
draft an international treaty that would halt the production of the
fissile materials used to make nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The move followed similar reversals by India and Pakistan, and
it opened the way to international negotiations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel, thought to be the world's last remaining undeclared
nuclear power, tempered its announcement by making clear that it
still has deep misgivings about signing such a treaty.
</P>
<P>
   A government statement said that prime minister Benjamin
Netanyahu had told the United States that Israel still had
``fundamental problems'' with the very idea of halting production
of plutonium and highly enriched uranium, the fissile materials, as
the United States first proposed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, India and Pakistan had been major obstacles to
the American plan, which is seen by proponents as an important step
toward halting the spread of nuclear weapons. But both countries
shifted course in an effort to win back good favor after their
nuclear weapons tests this spring and the worldwide condemnation
that followed.
</P>
<P>
   That had left Israel as the lone holdout within the 61-member
U.N. Conference on Disarmament. President Clinton, in a letter on
Aug. 9, urged Netanyahu to support at least the formation of a
committee that would begin to formulate a treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has maintained a policy of nuclear ambiguity for years,
refusing to confirm or deny reports that it has up to 300 nuclear
weapons. It has never signed the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty
and has never permitted international inspectors to visit its
top-secret nuclear reactor in Diomona, which was built with French
assistance in the 1950s and is believed to be an atomic bomb
factory.
</P>
<P>
   The rules of the disarmament conference, a permanent committee
of the United Nations that is based in Geneva, require unanimous
approval. And so Israeli opposition could have proved fatal to the
American plan. The qualified OK that Netanyahu issued Tuesday may
well insulate his government from what could have been a torrent of
international criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The careful language of the Israeli announcement seemed to
suggest that Netanyahu had made his decision grudgingly and that
the government was in no way eager to embrace any treaty that could
limit Israel's suspected nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The statement quoted Netanyahu as telling his Cabinet at a
meeting Tuesday morning that Israel had ``made it clear that our
support for the establishment of the committee does not indicate
that we are taking a position on the treaty and its contents.'' It
also quoted him as saying that Israel had told the United States
that Israel ``has its own considerations, which are unique to its
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli envoy, Yosef Lamdan, conveyed Israel's decision to
the headquarters of the disarmament conference in Geneva Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, following Israel's action, the conference agreed to
form the special committee, Agence France-Presse reported.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until now, the United States has for the most part gone along
with Israel's artifice about its nuclear program, choosing not to
confront it over the issue of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But that stance has prompted increasing complaints from Arab
countries, who see it as evidence of an American double standard,
particularly when compared with the hard line that Washington has
drawn against suspected efforts by Iraq and Libya to acquire
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official who described Clinton's Aug. 9 letter to
Netanyahu would not characterize its tone. But the official, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity, said it was merely the latest
in a series of American messages _ including a telephone call from
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to Netanyahu last week _
urging Israel not to stand in the way of the next step toward the
proposed treaty.
</P>
<P>
   A treaty halting the production of fissile materials is not
likely to affect nuclear stockpiles already in place, meaning that
Israel might sign such an accord without relinquishing its option
to use nuclear weapons. But such a treaty would also require
countries to open weapons facilities to inspection, something that
Israel is plainly not eager to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
