<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-430&AMP;ADD-N     08-11 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ECONOMIC WOES GROW AS STOCKS AND BONDS REACH RECORD LOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's markets were swept along in a global economic
downdraft on Tuesday. By the end of the day's trading, stocks and
government bonds were selling at near-historic lows _ that is, even
lower than on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts questioned whether the Russians, already embarked
on an all-out effort to avert bankruptcy, would be able to rebuild
the confidence of world financial markets, which seem to have
written them off.
</P>
<P>
   The main index of Russian stocks fell 9.11 percent, nearly as
great a decline as Monday, to its lowest level since May 1996.
Bonds fared even worse, with the bond issues created when old
Soviet-era debt was repackaged after the fall of communism falling
to their lowest prices ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian ruble, continuing its rise, edged close to an
exchange rate of 6.3 a dollar, above the informal trading range the
government has said it wants to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates on the Russian equivalent of U.S. Treasury bills
approached 80 percent for three-month maturities and 140 percent
for nine-month maturities.
</P>
<P>
   Those levels have not been seen since early July, before the
International Monetary Fund assembled a $22.6-billion loan package
that was supposed to calm investors' fears about Russian financial
stability.
</P>
<P>
   The loan package clearly bought the government several months to
improve its fiscal condition, but it has not brought calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a collapse in confidence about the Russian government's
ability to fund itself,'' said Charles Blitzer, a former World Bank
official and director of emerging markets research in London for
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc. ``Russian debt is priced at
default levels, though I frankly think that the prospect that the
government would default is minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many analysts say that the problems in the Russian
market stem as much from the global economic situation as from any
domestic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The price of oil, one of Russia's principal commodities and a
major source of tax revenue, has been hovering around 10-year lows,
and the government said the value of oil exports in the first half
of 1998 had decreased 46 percent from 1997. Most emerging markets
in Asia and Europe absorbed major blows from the decline of the
Japanese yen, which has raised fears of currency devaluations in
China and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But if that is comforting, it does not make the Russians'
situation any better. As investors lose confidence for whatever
reason, the price of borrowing goes up and foreign investment in
the economy goes down _ developments the nation's financial leaders
can ill afford.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blitzer said the government appeared to be doing a credible job
of carrying out the terms of the IMF loan package of early July _
terms that included a thorough overhaul of the government's
convoluted tax policies and an increase in tax collections. But he
added that the government has has not been clear and unwavering in
carrying out some of its plans.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he said, the government has wavered in its plans
for selling new debt issues, changing both the amount and
scheduling of debt packages at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   The government also has not said how it intends to prevent a
devaluation of the ruble. Defending the ruble takes money, and even
sanguine analysts say the government needs all the money it has _
and more _ just to meet domestic expenses and interest payments on
its ever-growing debt.
</P>
<P>
   The government said on Tuesday that it had spent 10.9 percent of
its consolidated revenue in the first three months of 1998 for
interest payments on foreign debt, up from 7.9 percent in the same
period last year. The treasury needs to issue more debt to meet
those payments and other expenses, but the government decided last
week to call off any more debt sales this month. Demand was so low
_ and therefore, interest rates would have been so high _ that
further auctions did not make sense, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials issued a flurry of statements on Tuesday in an
attempt to persuade investors that the nose dives in the markets
did not merit a panic.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Finance Minister Oleg Vyugin said Russia's finances would
be stable this month because ``all commitments are financed from
sources that are absolutely clear.'' Nor would it make any sense to
try new fiscal tacks to rally the markets, he said, ``because most
investors are vacationing and so new tools would not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, experts said on Tuesday night that the United
States had dispatched its senior expert on the Russian fiscal
crisis, Deputy Undersecretary of the Treasury David Lipton, to
Moscow to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings, scheduled before the latest break in investor
confidence, are part of a series of bilateral consultations to
determine the progress of reforms that the Yeltsin government
promised in mid-July in return for the bail-out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
