<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8885 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS &LR;      08-11 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HELP FOR LEARNING DISABLED ON WELFARE, SUIT CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hilda Ramos of New Bedford wanted to do well in the GED
program, but she usually got everything wrong and left the class in
tears. Now she frequently plays computer games in class instead.
</P>
<P>
   Ateefeewawa Pereira of Boston also has had difficulty earning a
general equivalency diploma, bouncing through three programs in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The issue facing the two women, both single mothers on welfare,
is not that they are unable to learn, but that they have
substantial learning disabilities that state welfare officials are
failing to accommodate, according to the women's attorney, Ruth
Bourquin of the Massachusetts Law Reform Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, 30, is mildly retarded and has dysgraphia, a writing and
spelling &UR;  &LR; disorder, while Pereira, 20, has dyslexia. The
class-action lawsuit they have filed is being closely watched by
welfare officials in other states and in the disability community.
In it, they charge that Transitional Assistance Commissioner Claire
McIntire has effectively deprived welfare recipients with learning
disabilities of equal access to job training and education programs
that could help them get off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Powers, Department of Transitional Assistance spokesman,
countered that welfare officials have only $25 million for
employment training and education programs and that priority should
be given to recipients who are subject to work requirements and
time limits.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, who also suffers depression, received a disability
exemption from those rules. And if recent studies in other states
are any indication, the number of welfare recipients with
disabilities are considerable.
</P>
<P>
   Soon-to-be-released results of a three-year pilot study found
that 44 percent of nearly 700 welfare recipients in Washington who
were tested had learning disabilities, said Melinda Giovengo, a
coauthor of the study. In a smaller study in Kansas, 30 percent of
89 welfare recipients tested were found to have learning
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Young of the National Institute for Literacy said the
findings show that many women went through public school systems
without being diagnosed and have ended up on welfare because the
early misconception had been that boys, who tended to act out and
been more verbal, were more apt to have learning disabilities than
girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls tend to be more hypershy and quiet,'' said Young. ``So
girls tend to get socially passed along to the point where they
can't hide it anymore, and they tend to drop out and blame
themselves because they are told they are lazy, stupid, and
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   That, essentially, is what happened to Ramos. Apparently never
diagnosed as learning disabled while attending New York public
schools, she recalled dropping out of the 10th grade after the high
school principal told her the school couldn't do anything for her.
</P>
<P>
   But states' response to the growing evidence of the link between
learning disabilities and welfare dependency, Giovengo said, should
not be to grant more recipients exemptions from welfare-to-work
rules. Instead, states should find ways to help them learn and
succeed in spite of their disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been exempted all their lives,'' she said. ``We have
tossed them to the bottom of the food chain because they can't do
what we expect them. But these people have abilities. Why waste
human potential?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
