u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNTREATED-STDS-BOS &LR;      08-11 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNTREATED-STDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS URGE TWICE-A-YEAR STD SCREENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A Baltimore study showing almost one-third of sexually active
teenaged girls to be infected with chlamydia has prompted the
researchers to call for screening every six months instead of once
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Chlamydia has no symptoms in up to 70 percent of cases, but is
the leading preventable cause of female infertility and painful
pelvic inflammatory disease.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the current Journal of the American
Medical Association, found the highest rate of chlamydia infections
_ 33.5 percent _ in 14-year-olds. Overall, of the more than 3,000
teenaged girls aged 12 to 19 in the study 29.1 percent tested
positive at least once.
</P>
<P>
   Many girls were tested more than once over the 33 months ending
September 1996. About 20 percent of all tests were positive.
</P>
<P>
   The study found no correlation between chlamydia infections
among the teens and known risk factors such as multiple sex
partners or prior history of a sexually transmitted disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to screen everyone under age 20,'' said lead author
Dr. Gale Burstein of the department of molecular microbiology and
immunology at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore. ``We could not
use any of the (risk-factor) variables to decide who to screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Screening every six months would allow for the detection and
treatment of new infections before they inflame and scar the
uterus, causing infertility, said Burstein.
</P>
<P>
   An accompanying editorial said the screening suggestion made
sense, but questioned whether parents, doctors, teens and insurers
would accept that.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention currently
recommends testing all sexually active teens for chlamydia whenever
they undergo a pelvic examination. Current guidelines recommend an
annual chlamydia screening for those at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Study author Dr. Thomas Quinn of the division of infectious
diseases at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore said new urine
tests make more frequent screening easy to do in schools and
communities. He cited studies that show it is cost-effective
whenever chlamydia incidence rises above 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts public health officials reported that chlamydia
cases rose 8 percent last year over the year before. In 1997, 7,330
cases were reported, far below the peak level in 1989 of 10,131.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eight percent increase we're seeing is a result of better
tests,'' Dr. Paul Etkind, director of STD prevention for the
Department of Public Health, said. ``There's more intensive
screening going on in family planning and STD clinics and more
education.``
</P>
<P>
   New tests can now detect infections with as few as 10 bacteria
in a vaginal or urine sample instead of the 10,000 that were needed
before, he said. Some areas, he added, are showing rates of 5
percent to 9 percent, double their previous levels.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Baltimore study was conducted among inner city
youths, the researchers said the disease is common among all
population groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chlamydia is the most common STD,'' Quinn said. ``If you've
got activity, you're going to find chlamydia. It's not going to go
away until you do this screening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
