<SLUG> BC-INVESTMENT-SCAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT AGENCIES CRACK DOWN ON ENTERTAINMENT INVESTMENT SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: ADDS graf at the end noting unsuccessful effort to reach a
company official.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal and state agencies announced Tuesday that
they are targeting companies that use the glamour of movies and
television to entice people into investing in fake money-making
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission, the Securities and Exchange
Commission and the North American Securities Administrators
Association, which consists of state regulators, said they have
filed 60 lawsuits against allegedly phony entertainment and
media-related investment companies in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Bernstein, FTC consumer protection director, said false
promotions by the companies being sued have led to losses of about
$100 million for investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Showbiz schemes have enormous appeal,'' she said at a news
conference. ``They play on the glitz and glamour of Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies targeted in the suits filed in U.S. District
Courts around the country include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Automated Systems &AMP; Concepts International Inc. of Los
Angeles. The FTC accused the company on Aug. 5 of selling $10,000
investments in the production of ``infomercials'' that would offer
packages such as an Elvis Presley coffee-table book, an Elvis CD
and Elvis postage stamps for sale. The scheme raised about $12
million, the agency charged. It said the company falsely claimed
that parts of the package were being considered for official
sanction by Graceland, which controls Presley products, and that
the infomercial would air on the QVC shopping network.
</P>
<P>
   _ World Interactive Gaming Corp. of Bohemia, N.Y. The FTC said
that the firm told people their $10,000 investment in an Internet
gambling casino would earn them $150,000 in one year. The FTC said
in a lawsuit filed Monday that the company had raised $2 million
from about 200 investors.
</P>
<P>
   _ My Pet TV of Los Angeles. According to the FTC, promoters
allegedly told investors they could make large profits from a cable
TV network for children. But the network never got off the ground.
According to an FTC suit filed last Friday, the company transferred
funds from the children's network without telling the investors and
used the money to start a cable network devoted to pet programming
that never aired.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the companies could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Charles Hammond, 43, a shipyard manager
from Greene, Maine, said he invested $20,000 in the children's
network in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The promotional material ``was so professionally done and so
well laid out with the list of people that were going to produce
and direct,'' he said. ``It seemed so legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said, the company told him he owned part of a new
cable network that was called ``My Pet TV.'' By the end of last
year, Hammond said, he realized he had lost his money.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Cooke, 58, a retired aerospace engineer from Vienna, Va.,
said he was caught in a movie production scheme two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Desert Gold Partners Company, based in several
California cities, told him he could buy shares in a nonviolent
action movie to be called ``Operation: Desert Gold.'' He said he
checked with Better Business Bureaus in San Diego, San Francisco
and Los Angeles, Calif., to ensure that the firm was legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I'd done as much homework as I normally do on an
investment,'' he said, adding that he thought the movie was being
made even though production was slow. But a year later, Cooke said,
he was shocked to learn that the firm had shut down and its assets
had been frozen. He said he doesn't expect to get his $20,000
investment back.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Walker, SEC director of enforcement, said Desert Gold
raised $8 million from about 600 investors. The agency sued
officials of the firm Tuesday morning just hours before the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   To date, he said, there is no movie and all of the money has
been spent.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach a Desert Gold official in San Francisco were
unsuccessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELARUS-ECON-ART-800&AMP;     08-11 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-ECON-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGN OF THE TIMES IN BELARUS: OWN CURRENCY NO GOOD FOR EXPORTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867. 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It's not easy to get fiscal respect when your national
currency is nicknamed the bunny, as in ``That will be 500,000
bunnies, madam. Cash or check?'' But in Russia's westerly neighbor
Belarus, where the bunny is king, appellation is the least of the
economic worries.
</P>
<P>
   The Belarussian ruble _ called the zaichik, or little hare,
after the engraving that is its main feature _ has lost half its
worth in five months, and more than 10 percent in the last week
alone. International lending agencies all but wrote off the economy
last spring. Foreign investors have been packing up and leaving for
months.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the government has announced a new and perhaps
unintentionally revealing plan to shore up the ruble's value:
starting next week, the country will no longer accept its own
currency as payment for exports.
</P>
<P>
   That will keep outsiders from pumping more rubles into an
economy already flooded with so many that the currency is
essentially worthless. But outside experts say it will not solve
the real problem: the Belarus government, which controls most of
the country's industry and the prices of most goods, insists on
printing more and more rubles whenever it runs short of cash.
</P>
<P>
   The latest plunge in the ruble's value occurred after the
nation's autocratic and eccentric president, Alexander Lukashenko,
said the government would issue more bunnies to pay for the fall
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Its currency aside, Belarus is not the sort of place these days
that brings to mind fields of cuddly cottontails. Lukashenko is
that rare leader who openly longs for a return to the Soviet
Union's glory days, and he brooks little dissent. Personal and
press freedoms are sharply limited, and the country's human rights
record has come under growing attack.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials are not spared. This summer, Lukashenko
evicted many foreign diplomats from their residences, and even one
Belarus public servant who criticized the country's fiscal policy
quickly found herself jobless and in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another blip in what's become a long, slippery
slope,'' said an official of one international lending agency in
the Belarus capital of Minsk. ``They control prices while they push
up the money supply,'' said the official, who asked not to be
identified. ``The two actions are incompatible, and the result is
inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, inflation is no problem in Belarus. The official
exchange rate is about 41,000 rubles to the dollar. But there are
at least three other less official exchange rates, up to and
including the black-market rate, which now hovers around 85,000
rubles per dollar, and climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, prices in Belarus are officially stable, a result of
government decrees capping them. But unofficially, prices are
edging up by 3 or 4 percent a month. Some sellers evade the decrees
by reissuing their price-controlled goods under new names. Others
sell goods on the black market or in open-air markets that are hard
to patrol.
</P>
<P>
   One result is hardship. Inflation gnaws at the average worker's
take-home pay of $50 to $100 a month; pensions are even smaller.
Another is isolation. Foreign companies, especially Western ones,
have slashed their investments in Belarus. Motorola abandoned a
semiconductor-manufacturing venture in May, and a Western maker of
television picture tubes pulled out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of Belarus' foreign trade is now conducted with
Russia, and even there, much of the trade takes the form of barter
rather than using hard-to-get cash. Only last week, according to
news reports, Belarus agreed to pay Russia's natural-gas monopoly,
Gazprom, $300 million in refrigerators, tractors and other hard
goods to settle a longstanding debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Belarus government can give away tractors because it
dominates some 90 percent of the nation's industrial base.
Conveniently lodged between western Russia and Poland, Belarus was
something of an industrial powerhouse in the old Soviet era,
shipping television sets, farm implements, cars, textiles and
machinery both westward to Moscow and to the old Warsaw Pact
nations of eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko's policy has been to keep state control of industries
while allowing them to react somewhat to the forces of capitalism _
``market socialism,'' as his government calls it. According to
government statistics, it has worked: The nation's gross domestic
product leaped 11 percent last year, and exports swelled by 27
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, so did inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To boost production, they have to pay salaries,'' said Mikhail
Seleznev, a Belarus native and an investment analyst for United
Financial Group, in Moscow. ``And to pay salaries, they simply
print money. The local currency is being printed whenever they need
it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the exception of the construction of a gas pipeline
traversing the country, foreign investment has dwindled. And
because the government requires companies to convert much of their
foreign-trade receipts into zaichiks _ at the government's
artificially low rate _ exporters have become money-losers as well,
too poor to modernize or innovate.
</P>
<P>
   The government has periodically tried to stabilize the ruble,
withdrawing from currency trading in Moscow and plugging a loophole
that had allowed currency traders to exchange bunnies for Ukrainian
gryvnias. On July 8, it outlawed the private purchase of foreign
currency from nonresidents.
</P>
<P>
   The latest demand, that all exports be sold for hard currency,
clamps another control on the wobbly zaichik. And Lukashenko's
government brags, with some justification, that a strong hand has
avoided the wild swings from fiscal crisis to crisis that have
marked Russia's blind leap into capitalism. To which Western
experts reply: At least Russia swings upward once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belarus is just using up whatever capacity they have as a
result of the Soviet breakup,'' said the international lending
officer. ``There's no new equipment; no new production; no new
capacity. As long as they can keep effective controls on the
markets and banks, they'll just slowly run downhill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
