<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT AGENCIES CRACK DOWN ON ENTERTAINMENT INVESTMENT SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: ADDS graf at the end noting unsuccessful effort to reach a
company official.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal and state agencies announced Tuesday that
they are targeting companies that use the glamour of movies and
television to entice people into investing in fake money-making
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission, the Securities and Exchange
Commission and the North American Securities Administrators
Association, which consists of state regulators, said they have
filed 60 lawsuits against allegedly phony entertainment and
media-related investment companies in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Bernstein, FTC consumer protection director, said false
promotions by the companies being sued have led to losses of about
$100 million for investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Showbiz schemes have enormous appeal,'' she said at a news
conference. ``They play on the glitz and glamour of Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies targeted in the suits filed in U.S. District
Courts around the country include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Automated Systems &AMP; Concepts International Inc. of Los
Angeles. The FTC accused the company on Aug. 5 of selling $10,000
investments in the production of ``infomercials'' that would offer
packages such as an Elvis Presley coffee-table book, an Elvis CD
and Elvis postage stamps for sale. The scheme raised about $12
million, the agency charged. It said the company falsely claimed
that parts of the package were being considered for official
sanction by Graceland, which controls Presley products, and that
the infomercial would air on the QVC shopping network.
</P>
<P>
   _ World Interactive Gaming Corp. of Bohemia, N.Y. The FTC said
that the firm told people their $10,000 investment in an Internet
gambling casino would earn them $150,000 in one year. The FTC said
in a lawsuit filed Monday that the company had raised $2 million
from about 200 investors.
</P>
<P>
   _ My Pet TV of Los Angeles. According to the FTC, promoters
allegedly told investors they could make large profits from a cable
TV network for children. But the network never got off the ground.
According to an FTC suit filed last Friday, the company transferred
funds from the children's network without telling the investors and
used the money to start a cable network devoted to pet programming
that never aired.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the companies could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Charles Hammond, 43, a shipyard manager
from Greene, Maine, said he invested $20,000 in the children's
network in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The promotional material ``was so professionally done and so
well laid out with the list of people that were going to produce
and direct,'' he said. ``It seemed so legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said, the company told him he owned part of a new
cable network that was called ``My Pet TV.'' By the end of last
year, Hammond said, he realized he had lost his money.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Cooke, 58, a retired aerospace engineer from Vienna, Va.,
said he was caught in a movie production scheme two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Desert Gold Partners Company, based in several
California cities, told him he could buy shares in a nonviolent
action movie to be called ``Operation: Desert Gold.'' He said he
checked with Better Business Bureaus in San Diego, San Francisco
and Los Angeles, Calif., to ensure that the firm was legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I'd done as much homework as I normally do on an
investment,'' he said, adding that he thought the movie was being
made even though production was slow. But a year later, Cooke said,
he was shocked to learn that the firm had shut down and its assets
had been frozen. He said he doesn't expect to get his $20,000
investment back.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Walker, SEC director of enforcement, said Desert Gold
raised $8 million from about 600 investors. The agency sued
officials of the firm Tuesday morning just hours before the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   To date, he said, there is no movie and all of the money has
been spent.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach a Desert Gold official in San Francisco were
unsuccessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
