<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VALENTIN-CANDY-BO     08-11 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VALENTIN-CANDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTIN MAKES SWEET MOVE FOR CANCER CHARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Valentin's Sweet Hits Candy may not sell like Baby
Ruth or Reggie! candy bars, but that hardly matters.
</P>
<P>
   What matters is that the Red Sox third baseman is lending his
name and portrait to the New England Confectionery Company for a
new candy that could raise as much as $50,000 for the Jimmy Fund,
the charity that raises money for the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as being a baseball player and being involved with the
Jimmy Fund for a while now, I really didn't think it would affect
me the way it has,'' Valentin said. ``When you meet these kids _
and having two of my own _ it's amazing how much life these kids
have even when they are so sick. It's just been an amazing
experience, and I am happy to do everything that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin is marching in the footsteps of players such as Ted
Williams and Carl Yastrzemski who have been the Red Sox' main
spokesmen for the Jimmy Fund. Earlier this year, he reached an
agreement with NECCO, the country's oldest candy maker, to put his
portrait, a picture of him swinging the bat, and a copy of his
autograph on the box of a new product, NECCO Sweet Hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination, somewhere between the NECCO Wafers and our
Sweet Hearts product that sell so well around Valentine's Day,''
said Walter Marshall, NECCO's vice president for logistics and
planning. The candies also bear the printed words of baseball
jargon, including two that are particularly appropriate for
Valentin: ``third base'' and ``double.''
</P>
<P>
   NECCO will make no profit from the sale of the candy, and
Valentin will make no fee. Both will donate their proceeds to the
Jimmy Fund, according to spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said NECCO has purchased 1 million boxes for Sweet Hits
and plans to bring all of them to market. He expects that the
eventual contribution could be about $50,000 in NECCO's first
involvement with the Jimmy Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Hits should begin appearing this weekend at Stop &AMP; Shop,
Star Market, Demoulas, Shaws, Trucci's, Brooks, Bradlees, Osco,
Ro-jacks, Cost Plus, and Candy World &AMP; More _ and many of the
stores will mark the product with special displays.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin said he became especially interested in the
fund-raising device after one of the many children he has visited
at the Jimmy Fund Clinic at Dana-Farber died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucas Bartlett was just an amazing kid,'' Valentin said
Tuesday, the emotion welling in his voice. ``You know, he's gone
now, but he's always going to be with me. He was a friend of
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Red Sox second baseman Mike Andrews, the chairman and
executive director of the Jimmy Fund, praised Valentin for his
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that it is sometimes tough when they are playing
and they are so into their sport,'' Andrews said. ``But it's too
bad all ballplayers don't do what John has done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
