A8898 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-$ADV16-NYT     08-11 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAIRY TALE THAT GETS REAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVER AFTER: A Cinderella Story &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore, Anjelica Huston, Dougray Scott, Jeanne Moreau,
Richard O'Brien &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Andy Tennant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 119 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forget the fairy godmother, the singing mice and the magic
pumpkin: Cinderella was a (italics)real person,(end italics) and
the grande dame (Ms. Moreau) who opens the story wastes no time in
scolding the Brothers Grimm for getting the tale all wrong. But the
main features of the story are actually intact.
</P>
<P>
   A freethinker long before her time, Danielle (Ms. Barrymore)
subtly and sweetly defies her stepmother (Ms. Huston) and
not-so-sweetly challenges the prince (Scott). Like her traditional
counterpart, she impersonates nobility as she sleeps among the
cinders; but only after she and the prince recognize themselves as
soul mates is the way cleared for the happy-ever-after ending. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None, though Danielle can be a swashbuckler with the
best of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 The film will be a bit long for restless children, but
the story may well entertain many of them because it's a familiar
one. Some may find a villainous landlord played by O'Brien very
scary, however. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-12 Children this age will take to the notion of
Cinderella as a real person, but the romantic theme may be too
yucky for many boys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP The notion of revisiting a fairy tale may put
them off at first, but many teen-agers will like the idea of
romance in the South of France. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne O'Connor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIR BUD: Golden Receiver &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Zegers, Cynthia Stevenson, Gregory Harrison, Robert
Costanzo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Richard Martin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 91 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Air Bud'' (1997) it was established that Buddy the golden
retriever can play basketball. Now, it turns out, the animal also
has a feel for the football field. To avoid contact with his
mother's new boyfriend and generally deny the fact that life goes
on after his father's death, young Josh (Kevin Zegers) joins his
junior high school football team as a backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with a rifle for a throwing arm, Josh needs a receiver
who can go deep and hang on to the ball. That would be his dog,
Buddy, who carries the team to the state finals only to get
snatched by animal trainers with Russian accents. Between the
sensitive situation at home, the big game and the missing dog,
there's a lot to straighten out before the final gun. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The two dog snatchers get some slapstick comeuppance in
the form of nasty spills and blows, but they are such buffoons that
even small children won't take their mishaps seriously. In a
similar vein, the dog's imprisonment with the other animals is more
of a lark than an ordeal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 This is such a soft, sweet little movie, so thoroughly
cleansed of any seriously untoward occurrences, that it is hard to
see how anything in it would upset small children. And, of course,
they will love Buddy and the other animals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-10 This is the ideal age group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP By this age, most children will find the
goings-on silly and overly sanitized.
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Nichols &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BASEKETBALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trey Parker, Matt Stone, Robert Vaughn, Ernest Borgnine, Trevor
Einhorn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Zucker &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 105 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a playing field bereft of golden retrievers, Coop (Parker)
and Remer (Stone) invent a mongrel of a game that combines
basketball and baseball. Shoot a hoop and run around the bases. In
Zucker's often riotous spoof of the professional sports scene,
``baseketball'' instantly becomes a hot commodity, complete with
rapaciously greedy owners, idiotic play-by-play, nine-month-long
playoff seasons, squads of cheerleaders in S&AMP;M outfits and teams
like the Los Angeles Riots.
</P>
<P>
   Only Coop, who invented the game, is determined to keep
baseketball clean and pure. But the clock is running out on his
team, the Milwaukee Beers, and their fans, the foamheads. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE A lot of body slams and board-in-the-face roughhouse
typical of a rowdy farce. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX With boys relentlessly being boys, there are lots of exposed
body parts and continual crude humor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY All the usual and then some. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE Hollywood's obsession with vomiting is again on
display. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 12 Obviously this isn't a film for the very young.
Older children, attracted partly by the fact that the film features
Parker and Stone, the creators of television's ``South Park,'' will
be on the floor with laughter, but parents should be aware of the
sexual content and profanity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Again, be aware of the R rating, but many
teen-agers will be up for some good, stupid and ultimately harmless
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Nichols
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
