<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CALIFORNIA-HN     08-11 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CALIFORNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES GOP-LED CONGRESS TO PASS HIS ENVIRONMENTAL AGENDA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton pressed Republicans in
Congress on Tuesday to pass his environmental agenda and announced
new rules requiring water utilities to inform consumers about the
quality of their drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The White House stepped up its confrontation with Congress as
senior officials also took aim at a Republican's comments that the
GOP could ``win'' a public relations battle over a government
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and Congress remain at odds over a series of
funding bills pending in the House or Senate. Congress has yet to
enact any of the 13 measures that keep government operating after
Sept. 31, and Clinton has threaten to veto seven of them.
</P>
<P>
   The president, in California to raise $3 million for Democrat
Gray Davis' campaign for governor, trekked to a water filtration
plant to highlight his environmental agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is in Congress today a disturbing trend to break up what
historically, at least for the last 30 years, has been a bipartisan
consensus on the environment,'' Clinton told the small crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton unveiled new regulations that will require the 5,600
water utilities nationwide to provide a ``consumer confidence''
report to their 240 million customers beginning in October next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The reports must inform consumers of the source of their water
and whether it meets federal standards. It must identify potential
sources of contaminants and provide health advisories for people
with medical conditions, such as HIV, that make them vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that five years ago in Milwaukee a microbe
outbreak sickened 400,000 people and killed dozens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is ever an area where we need progress, not
partisanship, it is to ensure the purity and safety of our
environment. But there is a question about that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized Congress for refusing to fund his clean water
action plan that would restore 40 percent of the nation's waters
currently too polluted for fishing or swimming. He also complained
that Congress refused to release funding for his plan to add 100
national and historic sites for federal protection.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the month of July was the hottest on record, Clinton
also criticized Congress for cutting his initiatives to reduce
greenhouse gas emissions, a primary contributor to global warming.
And, he blasted members for attaching what he called
anti-environmental language to measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawmakers have attached language to unrelated bills to cripple
wildlife protection and cut through an Alaskan wildlife refuge with
a $30 million road. These back-door assaults must also stop,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the administration jumped on comments made by
Rep. David McIntosh, R-Ind., chairman of the Conservative Action
Team, that Republicans could ``win'' a battle over a government
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Erskine Bowles, Clinton's chief of staff, sent a letter to House
Speaker Newt Gingrich,R-Ga., calling McIntosh's comments
disturbing. ``We continue to believe that shutting down the
government is not any way to sort through our different views of
budget priorities,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the White House nor Congress has shown signs of
willingness to compromise as the clock ticks down toward a
shutdown. A series of government shutdowns in 1995 resurrected
Clinton's approval ratings and proved a disaster for Congress,
which was blamed by the public.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles called on Gingrich to repudiate McIntosh's comments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
