<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, Aug. 12. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S.-EMBASSIES (Washington) _ Several U.S. diplomatic
posts have been temporarily closed in response to threats made
after the terrorist attacks on the embassies in Kenya and Tanzania,
State Department officials say. By Philip Shenon. (We plan to move
the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars inside: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-U.S.,
AFRICA-TANZANIA.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST-DROUGHT (Plymouth Flat, Texas) _ Just two years after
a drought wasted large swaths of the region's richest agricultural
land, Texas and Oklahoma are in the midst of a new drought that
officials in both states say shows signs of developing into the
costliest and most devastating the region has seen since the Dust
Bowl years. By Rick Lyman. (The story has moved in ``a'' news
file.) With map and photo. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   JONESBORO-TRIAL (Jonesboro, Ark.) _ A boy pleads guilty and a
12-year-old friend is convicted on charges they gunned down four
schoolmates and a teacher in an ambush outside their school. By
Rick Bragg. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   BP-AMACO (London) _ British Petroleum PLC announces it will
acquire the U.S. oil giant Amoco for $48.2 billion in stock in the
largest oil industry merger ever. By Youssef M. Ibrahim. (Scheduled
to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer: MARKET (New York) _ Stocks buckle as investors grow
increasingly fearful that sickly Asian economies will drive down
corporate earnings at U.S. companies in the second half of the
year. By Gretchen Morgenson. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``f'' news file.) With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-STRIKE (New York) _ Ending a two-day strike, Bell Atlantic
employees return to work after reaching a tentative agreement with
management. By Terry Pristin. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BELARUS-ECON (Moscow) _ Sign of the times in Belarus: own
currency no good for exports. By Michael Wines. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.) With map.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HILLARY (Washington) _ As her husband prepares to face a
grand jury Monday about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, Mrs.
Clinton's approval ratings across the country are higher than ever.
Instead of laying low at the White House, away from the kllieg
lights and the inevitable questions, Mrs. Clinton has jammed her
schedule with things to do and people to see. By Lizette Alvarez.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) With graphic
and photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-COLUMNIST (Boston) _ The Boston Globe gives its
columnist, Mike Barnicle, a reprieve: Matthew Storin, The Globe's
editor, announces at a crowded noon staff meeting that he will no
longer demand Barnicle's resignation but has imposed a two-month
suspension instead. By Felicity Barringer. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
