<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS JAPAN SIGHS, WALL STREET BUCKLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DOLLAR-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks buckled Tuesday as investors grew increasingly
fearful that sickly Asian economies would drive down corporate
earnings at U.S. companies in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average lost 1.3 percent on the day,
closing at 8462.85. That puts the average 9.3 percent below its
July 17 high of 9337.97 and within shouting distance of a 10
percent correction.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last Tuesday's 300-point decline, which came on a day
with little in the way of news, Tuesday's drop came amid a raft of
fresh and frightening world developments. First was an indication
that the Asian typhoon appeared to be gathering speed. Japan's
Economic Planning Agency said in a monthly report that the
country's worst slump since World War II was deepening; this sent
the Japanese yen plunging to 147.27 versus the dollar, setting an
eight-year low.
</P>
<P>
   The yen is crucial to world markets because the further it
falls, the greater the fear that China will devalue its currency,
causing another round of devaluations across the Pacific Rim.
Japan's Nikkei 225 index fell 219.43 points, or 1.4 percent
Tuesday, and in Hong Kong, the Hang Seng index lost 3.6 percent.
Malaysia's stock index fell to its lowest level in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Russia worsened as well Tuesday as investors,
concerned that the Russian government would not be able to meet its
debt payments this year, fled the country's stocks and bonds. The
Russian Trading System suspended trading for 45 minutes during the
day after the benchmark RTS index lost more than 7.5 percent of its
value. That market has fallen almost 73 percent since 1998 began.
Latin American stocks reeled as well.
</P>
<P>
   By the time all this news had registered with U.S. investors _
around 10:30 a.m. _ the Dow was down 220 points. At its low point,
the Dow had lost 254 points, or almost 3 percent. By the end of the
day, a buying spree in oil stocks brought the average back a bit to
close down 112 points.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, smaller stocks took bigger hits Tuesday than their
large-capitalization brethren. The Nasdaq composite lost 46.51
points, or 2.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, investors seemed to watch the day's events
warily but without panicking. Several mutual fund companies
reported that the heaviest selling took place in the morning.
According to John Woerth, a spokesman for the Vanguard Group,
buyers began returning to equity funds shortly after noon.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody was willing to buy on this particular market
dip. One stock broker in St. Louis reported a distinct mood change
among his clients. Last Tuesday, when the Dow dipped nearly 300
points, the bargain hunters came out in force, but the sidelines
was the preferred place to be Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the consensus du jour among Wall Street analysts _
that a bear market cannot begin unless interest rates rise or a
recession looms _ lost much of its credibility Tuesday. ``The
earnings side of the stock market is really starting to deteriorate
rapidly,'' said Richard Bernstein, chief quantitative strategist at
Merrill Lynch in New York. ``We are in a profit recession where we
will have zero or minus 10 percent earnings growth this year.
That's what we think the market is seeing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, three elements began to sink into the investor psyche
Tuesday. One was that the continuing deterioration in Asia means
corporate earnings among American companies in the second half will
not bounce back as Wall Street's Pollyanna analysts continue to
claim. Although hard data to support this belief will not be
available for quite some time, anecdotes about declining sales at a
variety of American companies are spreading. The stock market is
picking up this buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's developments in Russia also seemed to show that
investors are increasingly skeptical about governments' ability to
stem currency devaluations. Back in June, when the U.S. Treasury
joined the Japanese government in defending the yen, it was an
attempt to stop the Asian contagion dead in its tracks. So much for
that idea: the yen is 0.7 percent below where it was when the two
governments intervened.
</P>
<P>
   The $22.6 billion bailout of Russia by the International
Monetary Fund in mid-July was another line in the sand drawn by
Robert Rubin, secretary of the Treasury, and the International
Monetary Fund. The bailout was given an initial chance of success
by investors hoping to see fiscal reforms across Russia. But
Charles Peabody, an analyst at Mitchell Securities, said: ``The
markets are starting to wonder why Secretary Rubin and the IMF have
not been successful. The markets fear that they are failing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the most troubling view that crept onto investors' radar
screens Tuesday is that for all the Federal Reserve's concerns
about inflation, it could be deflation that ultimately undoes the
U.S. stock market. As investors absorb the possibility of another
round of Asian devaluations, so too do they begin to comprehend
what a deflationary spiral could bring.
</P>
<P>
   Deflation is disastrous for an economy, as Japan is discovering,
because as the prices of goods fall, consumer spending grinds to a
halt. People simply wait to buy goods until they feel that the
prices will fall no further. What this kind of behavior does to
corporate earnings is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   E. Han Kim is professor of finance and international business
and director of the Mitsui Financial Research Center at the
University of Michigan Business school. Kim also acted as a
financial adviser during the debt negotiations with the Korean
government earlier this year and is a specialist in Asian finance
and economies. While last year's devaluations actually benefitted
the U.S. economy by keeping prices of foreign goods down and
inflation low, he said, U.S. companies would find another
devaluation less pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have virtually zero inflation,'' he said. ``So
the next thing could be deflation. The chance of a deflationary
spiral is greater now. It was really slim before, but is a real
danger now.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason why even the whiff of deflation scares the daylights
out of the stock market is that it is a virtual unknown. The U.S.
economy has not experienced deflation since the 1930s, so few
investors know what to expect or how to measure it. ``What scares
people the most is the unknown,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists do know that deflation plays out slowly and
insidiously and that the Federal Reserve Board chairman has little
in his arsenal to counteract it. While Greenspan can curb inflation
by slamming on the monetary brakes and raising interest rates, in a
deflationary environment the Fed has few levers to pull. The only
way to get out of a deflationary period is to contract the supply
of goods. This means shutting plants, laying off workers, anything
that will remove excess supply from the economy and restore
companies' ability to raise prices of their goods.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the chances that China will devalue its currency?
Better and better with each fall of the yen, say market watchers.
Richard Babson, chairman and president of Babson United Inc., an
investment advisory firm with $2 billion under management, said:
``We expect the Chinese to devalue and unpeg the Hong Kong dollar
in the first quarter of next year. If it's a choice between
maintaining an international system by not devaluing and having
riots in the streets of Beijing, they'll devalue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
