<SLUG> BC-MICROCHIP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Humane Society wants microchips implanted in animals
 &HT;    By Kelly Simmons
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A microchip identification program at the Cobb County,
Ga. animal shelter has proved so successful that the Humane Society
is asking county commissioners to institute a policy requiring the
chips for all animals that pass through the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Several counties have voluntary microchip programs at animal
shelters. Cobb would be the first county in metro Atlanta to
require people who adopt or retrieve pets to have the
identification chips implanted in the animals, said Joy Evilsizor,
general manager of the Cobb Humane Society.
</P>
<P>
   Since launching its pilot microchip program in February,
Evilsizor said the shelter staff already had identified 10 to 15
animals a month using a universal scanner that reads the chips.
Instead of being held in shelter cages, the animals were quickly
returned to their owners, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really works,'' Evilsizor said. ``It's a long-term
potential solution.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how it works: Tiny chips, each coded with a number, are
implanted in the back of an animal's neck. A handheld scanner
deciphers the code, which is fed into a computer. The computer
reveals the animal's owner and contact information. Of the three
companies that manufacture the microchips, the Humane Society is
recommending Cobb use AVID, which has a universal scanner that
identifies all three brands of chips.
</P>
<P>
   The chips would cost pet owners $15, which would be added to pet
adoption fees. Owners retrieving lost or stray pets also would be
charged for the chip. Evilsizor said the program would pay for
itself, and perhaps even generate revenue for the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners agreed to consider the policy. ``It's a good
concept,'' commissioner Joe Thompson said. ``Part of the new
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
