<HEADLINE>
SECURITY CAMERA AT EMBASSY IN TANZANIA HAD NO VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related: AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-U.S.-EMBASSIES,
AFRICA-BOMBINGS)  
 (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania _ A security camera that was pointing
directly at the U.S. Embassy gate here where a terrorist bomb
exploded did not contain videotape but was merely used for
monitoring by Marine Corps guards, a State Department security
official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The camera, which was attached to the roof of the embassy
building and survived the blast intact, was one of six or seven
cameras on the embassy site, he said. None of them had tape.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that the cameras were never intended to have
tape but that a ``lesson learned'' from the explosion here was the
need for videotape to be installed in embassy security cameras
around the world. U.S. officials said soon after the blast last
Friday that the security camera might provide vital evidence for
the investigation now under way by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   After it was discovered that there was no videotaped record of
Friday's blast, all embassies were ordered by the State Department
to start installing cameras with videotape, said the security
official, a senior official with the State Department's Diplomatic
Service Security Office. He is heading a team of 40 security and
counterterrorism experts flown in from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures from the cameras at the embassy here _ as in most
embassies _show up on monitoring screens in the booth inside the
embassy door, where Marine Corps guards are on duty, he said. It
was impossible, the official said, for a Marine to watch all
monitors all the time, but what the guard had seen on his monitors
last Friday would be ``part of the ongoing investigation'' by the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Tanzanian police said on Tuesday that they had arrested 14
foreigners in connection with the bombing of the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The officials gave only nationalities and some job descriptions
but no names of those being held for questioning. Six of the men
are Iraqis, six are Sudanese, one is Turkish and one a Somali,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for the arrests are their dubious characters and
intelligence information suggesting that they may be involved with
the explosion,'' said police spokesman Aden Mwamunyange at a news
conference. It was not clear Tuesday night whether the FBI
investigators here have interviewed those being held.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department officials cautioned that the
arrests, which were apparently made over the last several days,
appeared to be part of a general roundup that is a common part of
crime investigation in some African countries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most striking aspect of the arrests was that all of those
being held were not Tanzanian and that they came from predominantly
Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanzanian leaders have repeatedly stressed that they did not
believe that a Tanzanian was involved in the bombing, which killed
10 people and wounded more than 70.
</P>
<P>
   No Americans died in the explosion here. The official death toll
has risen to 10. Tanzanian mortuary officials Tuesday identified
the body of a Tanzanian security guard who was at the embassy gate
inspecting a water tanker when the bomb went off.
</P>
<P>
   At the morgue at the main hospital, the chief pathologist, who
would give his name only as Dr. Makata, said that the bodies of the
two people who were closest to the water tanker at the time of the
explosion were the most severely mangled.
</P>
<P>
   This appeared to lend credence to what U.S. officials have
called the most plausible scenario of what happened here _ that the
bomb was attached to the water tanker that made daily water
deliveries to the embassy building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water truck is clearly a key aspect,'' the State
Department security official said.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Paul Elisha, 32, the security guard who was
apparently looking at the underside of the truck with a mirror
attached to a long stick, was the most difficult to identify,
Makata said. The other severely damaged body was that of the
driver, Yusuf Shamte Ndange.
</P>
<P>
   Although the extent of death and destruction was significantly
less here than in Kenya, the attack has shaken a nation proud of
its stability.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanzanian leaders have sought to place responsibility for
the attack outside its own borders. President Benjamin Mkapa said
after touring the damaged embassy building that it was ``very
unlikely'' that the bombing was carried out by a Tanzanian.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many Tanzanians acknowledge that if foreign Islamic
militants were responsible for the attack, they would have found it
relatively easy to send in or recruit helpers here. The border
controls of Tanzania are lax and the country is within relatively
easy access of the Sudan, to the north. The Sudan has provided
shelter of Osama bin Laden, who is known to have financed many
terrorist actions.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of the people along the Tanzanian coast are
Muslims, and in the last several years, pockets of a more
fundamentalist Islam have emerged here. In February, there were
violent clashes between the police and more militant Islamic
fundamentalists outside a mosque in the Mwembe Chai area of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   For the FBI and other U.S. law-enforcement personnel here, the
arrests by the Tanzanians of the 14 foreigners show the difficult
balancing act of working on a vastly complicated criminal case in a
country with limited crime-investigation resources.
</P>
<P>
   One U.S. official said the arrests by the Tanzanians should not
be taken ``too seriously.'' On the other hand, the FBI was anxious
to get the full cooperation of the Tanzanians and not repeat the
rocky relationship with law-enforcement officials in Saudi Arabia,
where the attacks in 1995 and 1996 on U.S. military installations
remain unsolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
