<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV PRODUCER TESTIFIES IN STARR INVESTIGATION AS CLINTON ATTORNEY
REVIEWS EVIDENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Hollywood television producer and a White House
lawyer testified Tuesday before a federal grand jury investigating
whether President Clinton tried to cover-up a relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors questioned image-maker Harry Thomason and deputy
White House counsel Cheryl Mills about the president's
damage-control efforts during the early days of the Lewinsky
controversy, Clinton's private lawyer was reviewing evidence at the
heart of the sex-and-perjury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney David Kendall, who represents the president in the
Whitewater investigation, spent almost five hours at the federal
courthouse viewing the president's videotaped Jan. 17 deposition in
a sexual harassment lawsuit filed against him by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In that testimony, Clinton denied engaging in sex with Lewinsky,
a statement the former White House intern contradicted, a legal
source said, when she appeared last week before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall was allowed to view the tape under the supervision of
Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson as preparation for
Clinton's impending grand jury appearance. Permission was granted
by U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright, a federal judge in
Arkansas who four months ago dismissed the Jones lawsuit but
ordered all evidence to remain under seal.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, who left the courthouse Tuesday without comment, is to
meet with the president Wednesday to prepare for his grand jury
appearance. Clinton is to testify via closed-circuit television
Monday from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Thomason spent more than an hour with the grand jury
responding to questions about his five-week stay at the executive
mansion and private conversations he had with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grand jurors seemed like great people,'' Thomason told
reporters, adding, ``I've always believed that the president is
telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomason is credited with advising the president during the
early days of the scandal to avoid legalistic responses and to
firmly deny the alleged affair. A few days later, the president
issued a finger-wagging statement saying he ``did not have sexual
relations'' with Lewinsky and never asked anyone to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason has produced several successful television comedies,
including ``Designing Women'' and ``Evening Shade.'' He teamed up
with his wife, Linda Bloodworth-Thomason, to produce a short film
about Clinton for his first presidential campaign in 1992 and
created a 12-minute film about Clinton for the 1996 Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky matter is not the first investigation of the
Clinton White House involving Thomason. A congressional inquiry
found that he played a key role in what is known as the travel
office firings, the dismissal of seven longtime White House workers
four months after Clinton took office.
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying before the grand jury Tuesday was Mills, a
deputy to White House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff and a key
participant in court debates aimed at fending off independent
counsel Kenneth Starr. Mills left the courthouse without comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mills was subpoenaed after the White House lost a court fight
over the use of attorney-client privilege to keep government
lawyers from having to testify.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, several more Secret Service officers appeared at the
courthouse to testify in Starr's probe. So far, at least 14 Secret
Service employees, including the head of the president's personal
security detail, have been called before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
