<HEADER>
A8923 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BP-AMOCO-ART-1     08-11 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BP-AMOCO-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP TO ACQUIRE AMOCO IN BIGGEST OIL-INDUSTRY MERGER EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ohio, Texas)  (ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Petroleum PLC announced Tuesday that it would
acquire the American oil giant Amoco for $48.2 billion in stock in
the largest oil-industry merger ever.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would be the largest of an American company with a
foreign entity.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by regulators and shareholders from both companies,
BP Amoco, as the company is to be known, would be the world's
third-largest multinational oil company in terms of its net income,
after Exxon Corp. and Royal Dutch/Shell Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers in the United States are unlikely to feel any
immediate effects from the deal. Prices at gas pumps are mostly
dependent on world oil supplies, which are currently plentiful. And
while the consolidation of gasoline outlets may slightly decrease
retail competition, the exploration prowess of the combined
companies could eventually result in larger supplies of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   Oil executives at other companies said the deal benefited both
BP and Amoco. The main strength of British Petroleum, they said, is
the business of looking for and finding oil reserves. But the
company is weak in the business of refining the oil into products
and chemicals and distributing it to consumers, at which Amoco
excels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of Amoco is in areas that are lacking at BP such
as the natural gas reserves, which it possesses, and
petrochemicals,'' Andrew Avramides, an oil consultant in London,
said. ``The merger brings these assets into a larger, far more
comprehensive structure, making BP Amoco a true giant with enhanced
structures.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and dealmakers alike said the announcement could set
off a wave of consolidation in oil companies not unlike that seen
in the financial services and telecommunications industries.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that might consider moves now are Mobil Corp., Chevron
Corp. and Texaco Inc., all of which saw their stocks rise despite a
downdraft in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks said BP chief executive Sir John
Browne approached Amoco chairman Larry Fuller in late spring about
a possible merger. Sir John believed that consolidation was
inevitable and, said an executive close to the deal, ``Both of
these guys said if we don't pick a partner, we are going to be
last.''
</P>
<P>
   It is expected that the merger will take months to be approved
by regulators, although there are no obvious impediments to the
deal's structure.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesperson said: ``A merger of this
magnitude has to come under review. We will be looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The two companies employ a total of 99,450 workers around the
world. Amoco, with 43,450 total employees, expects to cut 5,000 to
6,000 jobs, but none in its Chicago headquarters, Dan Dietsch, the
company's media relations adviser, said. A spokesman for BP said
the company planned to cut about 1,000 jobs in Cleveland when
refining and marketing operations there are moved to Chicago. Other
cuts are expected at Amoco's research offices in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco and BP said Chicago would remain the headquarters for the
new company's North American business of refining, marketing and
transportation, ``and, in due course, the worldwide chemicals
business.'' Amoco is the fourth-largest company in the Chicago
area.
</P>
<P>
   The merger announcement coincides with another significant drop
in oil prices on world markets, which are flooded with supplies.
Producers have been hurt by the economic slowdown in Asian
economies, a mild winter and overproduction by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   As the deal was announced in London Tuesday afternoon, the
average oil price around the world hit a 10-year low. Average oil
prices around the world stood at about $10 a barrel, which in
today's dollar is lower than the price of oil 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Senior oil executives and analysts alike stressed that the move
by British Petroleum must be looked at as a strategic decision
transcending the fluctuations in the prices of what remains one of
the world's most essential commodities and a vital element of
economic growth worldwide. Avramides said that today's low oil
prices are ``not a permanent condition.''
</P>
<P>
   David Mayhew of Cazenove &AMP; Co., a London brokerage firm, said
that no company can ignore current oil prices, but added that
``this move provides considerable economic and financial benefits
on the long run; it makes a great deal of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir John, who will head the new company as its chief executive,
said the merger was forced by the need for economies of scale and
by increasing competition in a global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``International competition in the industry is already fierce
and will grow more acute as new players emerge,'' Sir John said
Tuesday in a press conference. ``In such a climate the best
investment opportunities will go increasingly to companies that
have the size and financial strength to take on those large-scale
projects that offer a truly distinctive return.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview later, he added: ``People always ask me if such
mergers are good for consumers. Competition always is good for
consumers. It is also exciting and challenging. This deal moves us
into the super-league and provides the prospect of real competition
for those already in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir John said that the merger would bring some $2 billion in
savings as the two companies eliminate redundancies and consolidate
their divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The merger ranks as the world's largest industrial company
corporate combination, surpassing the $36 billion acquisition of
Chrysler Corp. by Germany's Daimler Benz AG announced in May, and
it is the sixth-largest merger of any type. It brings together one
of Britain's top industrial companies, founded in 1909, and a major
U.S. company that came out of the Standard Oil of New Jersey
monopoly when it was split up in the early part of this century.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A senior Kuwaiti oil executive whose country holds about 7
percent of BP shares hailed the deal as a major breakthrough.
``Over the past decade they have gone through a major
rationalization process cutting costs, staffing, increasing their
reserves of oil worldwide and their efficiency,'' the Kuwait
official, who insisted on anonymity, said in an interview in
London.
</P>
<P>
   BP will exchange American depository receipts equivalent to 3.97
of its shares for each Amoco share. BP closed Monday at 7.73
pounds, making the value of the deal worth $48.2 billion based on
964,406 million Amoco shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of trading Tuesday, BP shares had increased 22
pence in London, to 7.95 pounds, raising the value of the takeover
to $49.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   British Petroleum will also assume $4.86 billion in long-term
Amoco debt.
</P>
<P>
   The board of the new company, which will be based in London,
will contain 13 BP directors and nine from Amoco. Amoco must pay
$950 million if it breaks the agreement. BP will have to pay $1
billion if it backs out. Although both companies strove Tuesday to
represent the deal as a merger, analysts tended to look at it as an
acquisition by BP which will control 60 percent of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will have 9.2 billion barrels of crude oil
in reserves. Amoco has been struggling recently to refocus its
growth overseas in an effort to move away from the saturated
American market. The company sold about one-third of its domestic
oil and natural gas properties last year. With Amoco, BP also
acquires 9,300 retail gasoline outlets. The new company will also
become the largest natural gas producer in North America. If
completed, the merger would make BP the largest company in Britain,
supplanting the pharmaceutical manufacturer Glaxo Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of the year, Amoco's net income fell to
$673 million from $1.3 billion a year ago. Revenues fell to $15.4
billion from $17.6 billion. U.S. oil company stocks have been
battered this year because of overproduction by world oil producers
and falling demand from Southeast Asian countries. Amoco's stock,
which was split earlier this year, is down 12 percent over a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   British Petroleum was advised by J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and the law
firm of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell. Amoco Corp. was advised by Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter and lawyers Wachtell Lipton Rosen &AMP; Katz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
