<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLLAR-MARKETPLACE-AR     08-11 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: U.S. HAS FEW OPTIONS AS YEN DRIFTS LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET, JAPAN-ECON) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on recent market volatility is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the Japanese yen falling to yet new lows and
pulling down financial markets around the world, the United States
finds itself with few options.
</P>
<P>
   It can intervene in the currency markets to support the yen, as
it did in June, or jawbone the Japanese government to stimulate its
economy. But neither maneuver is likely to be very effective in the
absence of drastic measures by the Japanese, a point made
repeatedly by Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Back in June, the United States had the element of surprise when
it worked in concert with Japan to prop up the yen, which had
traded as low at 146.78 to the dollar. (As the Japanese currency
weakens, it takes more yen to buy a dollar.)
</P>
<P>
   The move was intended to give the Japanese some breathing room
to implement bold policy changes, changes that have not yet
materialized. Timed just before President Clinton's trip to China,
the intervention was also intended to placate the Chinese, who had
been sending signals that a further decline in the yen would force
them to devalue their currency, the yuan. A Chinese devaluation
would deepen the financial crisis in Asia and reverberate through
world financial markets, perhaps setting off other devaluations.
</P>
<P>
   After the intervention, the yen rallied, rising to 136.75 to the
dollar where it held its ground temporarily. The Chinese reassured
the president that they would not devalue.
</P>
<P>
   The move also helped calm worried financial markets. After the
June 17 intervention, the Dow Jones industrial average took a 7.8
percent runup to its record high of 9,337.97 about a month later.
And foreign stock markets got a lift, albeit a smaller one. Hong
Kong rose and Mexico rallied. Even Canadian stocks got a boost,
although they are now down 19 percent from their 1998 high.
</P>
<P>
   But currency traders view that intervention as a one-time
success. What the United States can only hope is that the yen does
not fall precipitously, but grinds down slowly, said Richard
Medley, the president of Medley Global Advisors, which provides
advice to institutions and hedge funds. To achieve this, he said,
the United States and Japan may be forced to intervene again.
</P>
<P>
   However, a second intervention, he cautions, will be less
effective. For one, traders are expecting it now and have
positioned themselves accordingly. In addition, the new Japanese
government has not convinced investors that it will take the
necessary steps, like tax cuts and banking reform, to revive its
stalled economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are telling investors to buy the dollar,'' Medley said.
``You may get some smoothing intervention, but don't expect it to
be an effort to reverse the trend.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the falling yen has become a sell signal on the world
equity markets. How much far can it fall? It won't be difficult for
the yen to hit 150 to the dollar, analysts said Tuesday. In New
York trading, it dropped 0.8 percent to 147.35, its lowest close in
eight years. Some year-end forecasts have the yen down to 180 to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no fundamentals supporting the yen,'' said Carl
Weinberg, chief economist at High Frequency Economics in Valhalla,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   This could spell a stormy end of summer for the financial
markets as investors grapple with a still uncertain outlook for
Asia and its impact.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday and Monday, the weakening yen _ and the specter of a
Chinese currency devaluation it has conjured up for investors _ was
blamed for sharp declines in stock markets and currency markets
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   A devaluation by the Chinese would make its exports cheaper,
taking sales away from other Asian nations that are fighting back
from economic collapse. And it would cut into American corporate
earnings in two ways: American sales would drop even further as the
Chinese and other Asian countries lose purchasing power, and goods
brought into this country would be cheaper, putting downward
pressure on products of American competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks slumped Tuesday in the United States after a bigger rout
overnight in Asia. In Latin America, where a Chinese devaluation is
particularly feared as triggering currency declines, the Brazilian
Bovespa stock index dropped 5.6 percent in two days and the Mexican
Bolsa fell 6.8 percent. The Mexican peso dropped to a record low
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the French CAC 40 was off 2.4 percent, while the
British FTSE 100 fell 2.8 percent, and the German DAX index
declined 3.2 percent. In Asia, Hong Kong's Hang Seng index plunged
3.6 percent, while the Nikkei 225 index in Japan dropped 1.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Commodity prices also are following the yen's lead. Oil and
copper prices fell Tuesday on concern that Asian consumption will
slow.
</P>
<P>
   What is complicating the situation for American policy makers is
that investors fear a further decline in the yen will trigger a
Chinese devaluation. Not too long ago, a level of 150 yen to the
dollar appeared to be the line in the sand to hold off the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists, however, argue that there is little direct
correlation between the two currencies. The Japanese and the
Chinese do not compete very much in terms of exports. In addition,
the benefit to China of making its exports cheaper is not enough to
offset the political and social costs of a devaluation on the giant
domestic economy, Weinberg argued.
</P>
<P>
   Medley considers the Chinese trade surplus a more important
gauge than the yen. He said that if the surplus fell to zero _ it
was $20 billion for the first half of the year _ the Chinese would
have to devalue to because it would give China a trade deficit that
would threaten its huge foreign currency reserves. ``We recommend
keeping your eyes on this number for the next few months, rather
than newswire headlines,'' he told clients.
</P>
<P>
   But the yen-yuan devaluation link has taken hold, in part
because the June intervention was seen as a response to complaints
from China.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are portfolio managers we speak to who have set sell
orders on their emerging market portfolios that are linked to the
level of the yen,'' said Jeremy Fand, senior foreign exchange
strategist at BankBoston. While he does not think the link is
appropriate, he said a lot of these orders are bunched at 150 yen
to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg of High Frequency Economics concludes, ``The perception
is more important than the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   This means that a weakening yen could become more disruptive to
financial markets, even if China is not compelled to devalue its
currency, because even if there is no yen-yuan link, the markets
see it that way for now. ``China, Japan and the United States are
connected in every trader's mind,'' Fand said.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Treasury and the Federal Reserve, which would
conduct any future intervention, cannot afford to become ``the
policemen of world financial markets,'' he said. Alan Greenspan,
the chairman of the Fed, he said, ``doesn't even want to be
responsible for the fate of the Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
