<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8930 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-TUMBLE-BOS &LR;      08-11 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-TUMBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURMOIL IN JAPAN UNDERCUTS US MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ US stocks fell abruptly Tuesday after turmoil in
Japan's markets set off a round-the-world rout. The Dow Jones
industrial average tumbled 258 points by early afternoon, but
recovered partially to end the day off 112.
</P>
<P>
   The decline continued a sharp ``correction'' that has sliced
nearly 10 percent of US stock prices since mid-July, though many
individual issues have suffered losses of 20 percent or more. While
many investors remain bullish, there is growing concern on Wall
Street that a bear market could be in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blamed a new report on Japan's economic troubles as the
spark for Tuesday's selloff, but said other factors were at work
too. They include more general fears about Asia, including worries
about a destabilizing devaluation of the Chinese yuan; mounting
evidence that corporate America cannot keep churning out
ever-larger profits; and concerns the US economy may be slipping
from its near-perfect alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amid all the talk about Japan and Asia, we may be taking our
eyes off the ball,'' said William Cheney, chief economist for John
Hancock Financial Services in Boston. ``The apparent momentum of
job growth, income growth, and consumer spending in the US may be
more fragile than it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   American investors rushed to dump bank and technology stocks
thought to be especially dependent on Asian business, pushing the
Dow down 1.3 percent to 8462.85 and other market measures down a
similar fraction.
</P>
<P>
   That still means that the 30-stock average is up for the year,
but only 7 percent, a paltry amount compared to the 30 percent-plus
gains investors have come to expect in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Economic and financial fragility were certainly apparent
elsewhere in the world Tuesday as markets from Budapest to Buenos
Aires plunged.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian stock exchange suspended trading for 45 minutes
after its RTS stock index fell 9.1 percent to a two-year low.
Mexican shares fell 2.8 percent while Brazil's bourse lost 4.1
percent. Bellweather indexes in Britain, France, Italy, Spain, and
Sweden lost 2 percent or more. In Asia, Japan's Nikkei 225 index
drop 1.4 percent and Hong Kong's Hang Seng index dropped 3.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in areas where we haven't seen serious trouble, we're
seeing it now,'' said Joyce Change, emerging markets director for
Merrill Lynch in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the few bright spots in overseas news Tuesday, British
Petroleum said it would buy Chicago-based Amoco Corp. in a
stock-and-debt deal valued at about $53 billion. It would be the
largest-ever foreign acquisition of a US company, eclipsing
Daimler-Benz A.G.'s $44.3 billion purchase of Chrysler Corp.
announced in May, and create
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the takeover was part of the firms' efforts
to cope with some of the lowest crude oil prices in 12 years, and
predicted that other large energy company combinations are in the
offing.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, Tuesday's news out of Japan seemed minor. The
country's Economic Planning Agency, an organization that's roughly
equivalent to the White House Council of Economic Advisers, simply
changed the term it uses to describe Japan's economic condition
from ``stagnation'' to ``slump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was simply a recognition of what everybody else knows. It
was just a little less rosy than usual,'' said Arthur Alexander,
president of the Japan Economic Institute, a Washington-based think
tank partially funded by the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
   But the change together with fears that the new government of
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi may not win approval of financial
reform legislation was enought to sent virtually every stock market
in the world spiraling downward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has turned into a policymakers' nightmare, and that's
making people realize that Asia is a lot worse off than the markets
have thought until now,'' said David M. Jones, chief economist for
Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the Asian crisis, analysts have been sharply
trimming their forecasts of US corporate profits, and many now
predict that profits will grow only about 4 percent this year, a
dramatic change from the double-digit growth during most of the
1990s. As profit growth has slowed, stock prices have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Tuesday's market tumble together with other
recent declines, like last week's nearly 300-point drop in the Dow,
have finally begun to catch up with a handful of big-company stocks
whose recent rise helped prop up major market indexes and mask the
fact that most stocks have been sliding for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chosen few are finally being affected,'' said Robert J.
Barbera, chief economist for Hoenig &AMP; Co., a New York regional
brokerage. ``The amazing thing is not that the market has held up
so well in the face of Asia. The amazing thing is that a short list
of stocks held up so well and gave the appearance of a market that
had not been tarnished by Asia,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
