<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8931 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TROCKS-DANCE-$ADV16-2     08-11 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROCKS-DANCE-$ADV16-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TROCKS, VETERANS NOW, TAKE THEIR FUN SERIOUSLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Les Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo began life on
an evening in late fall 1974, in a small meeting room at the West
Side Discussion Group, a gay social center far west on 14th Street
in Manhattan. That first season was short, though eagerly attended.
</P>
<P>
   The way had been paved three years earlier by the pioneering
Original Trocadero Gloxinia Ballet. The stage was essentially a
space cleared for dancing. The scenery trembled. What props there
were tended to be cleverly functional.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Tuesday, the all-male Trocks, as the group is
affectionately known, perform at the Joyce Theater for a one-week
season. Fresh from a highly successful engagement in Japan, where
they have a large and loyal audience and even a fan club, the
dancers will take off right after their appearance at the Joyce for
performances in South Africa and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   They have risen up on their loaf-sized points everywhere from
Billings, Mont., to St. Petersburg, Russia, once the world capital
of classical ballet, and have performed in television specials
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a Trocks audience is likely to include dance aficionados
and novices of all ages. Children tend to laugh the loudest and
longest at the high jinks of such noted ballerina characters as
Colette Adaie, Ida Nevassayneva and Fifi Barkova, who are partnered
by a male contingent that includes the Legupski brothers Dimitri
and Vladmire, Velour Pilleaux and Kilroy Wazir.
</P>
<P>
   But the ladies can knock off 32 fouettes with the best of them.
And the repertory has widened and deepened, with a return to
lovingly performed classics after a too-close brush with broad
Keystone Kops-style comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Trocks once specialized in romps with names like ``A Ball on
Night Mountain.'' At the Joyce, they will perform the ``Pas
d'Odalisques,'' a choreographic jewel from ``Le Corsaire'' also
seen this summer in a new production by American Ballet Theater at
the Metropolitan Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   The Joyce repertory also includes the New York premiere of
``Stars and Stripes Forever,'' choreographed by Robert La Fosse, a
principal dancer with the New York City Ballet, and set, like
George Balanchine's ``Stars and Stripes,'' to march music by John
Philip Sousa.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers will also get their first chance to see the Trock
production of a famous excerpt from the 1844 ballet ``La
Vivandiere,'' staged for the company, like the Odalisques trio, by
Elena Kunikova, a former principal dancer with the Russian Maly
Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. The genteel notices about ``homophile''
events that were pinned to the bulletin board of the 14th Street
center have been replaced by broadsheet calls to gay action that
plaster lightposts throughout the Joyce's Chelsea neighborhood. Men
taking ballet class in toe shoes are no longer quite the anomaly
they were in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   And dancers, once loath to admit that they were performing with
the Trocks, now receive leaves of absence from their jobs with
mainstream dance companies to appear with the troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I can't do (italics)that,''(end italics) Brian Norris, who
plays the hulking ballerina Vanya Verikosa and her brother Andrei,
told himself a decade ago when he saw an audition notice for the
Trocks. Norris had come to New York from Grants Pass, Ore., intent
on becoming a Broadway gypsy.
</P>
<P>
   At home he had performed with the State Ballet of Oregon. A
stint in the East followed with the Rochester City Ballet. But jobs
were otherwise few. Dancing with the Trocks, whom he joined in
1994, eventually seemed like a bearable alternative to waiting
tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a small town,'' Norris said by telephone from
Tokyo. ``I had a lot of `What will the neighbors think?' in me. But
I grew up. I grew out. My parents have been to the show four times
and loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief ingredient in the ``growing up'' of the Trocks has
been the artistic direction of Tory Dobrin, who joined the company
in 1980. Like all company members, Dobrin plays both a male and a
female dancer. As Adam Baum, he occasionally hoists his Swan Queens
with a grunt modeled after that of tennis player Steffi Graf, an
idol. But Dobrin has come to feel that the Trocks have a serious
role to play in ballet.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Trockadero performances of the Russian classics are now one of
the few places one can still see undiluted ``tutu ballets,'' danced
with old-style Soviet commitment and panache.
</P>
<P>
   For all the jokes, the Trocks' affection and erudition shine
through in the heightened technical skills that are also to be
found in dance in general today, and in details like exquisite
costuming and the hiring of Ms. Kunikova as a guest coach.
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin is returning to the Russian ballet of the 1960s that he
came to love on videos broadcast by the television station of the
City University of New York in the 1980s. ``At first it seemed so
mannered,'' Dobrin recalled. ``Then it seemed so complete. We just
take it three steps further.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Trocks who asked La Fosse to create ``Stars and
Stripes Forever,'' danced by Balanchine-style regiments with the
corps playing stripes. They are adding Merce Cunningham's 1964
``Cross Currents'' to their repertory, to be staged by Meg Harper
and danced straightforwardly, with no jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin's approach to performing is a key to the company's
philosophy. In an era in which drag acts are now an accepted part
of the American cultural fabric, it is possible to move beyond the
idea of impersonation and have audiences follow.
</P>
<P>
   The Trockadero, Dobrin says emphatically, is not about drag
queens. There is more Margaret Thatcher than Margot Fonteyn in his
female character, Margaret Lowin-Octeyn, D.B.E.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put on the makeup, you're putting on a personality
you've created in your own mind,'' Dobrin said. ``First you develop
the character you play, then you approach the ballet with that in
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris does not think of himself as female when he plays Madame
Verikosa. ``I'm me,'' he said. ``I'm Brian doing Odette. I'm
trying, in `Swan Lake,' to be true to the choreography and
technique and make the emotion and character big. I'm playing it
straight, with a twist.''
</P>
<P>
   He lets the audience know he is ``just a dancer playing a
part,'' he said, however many images that role may have in the hall
of mirrors that is the Trockadero.
</P>
<P>
   Why has the company lasted a good deal longer than many other
dance troupes, with an enviable 40 weeks of work, at a living wage,
most years? Dobrin was able to fine-tune the company repertory and
style when he worked several years ago for the impresario who
produced the Trocks. Not knowing that Dobrin danced with the
company, tour presenters were unguarded in their comments.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial factor in the company's longevity, however, has
likely been the simplicity of its operations, presided over since
1974 by Eugene McDougle, the general director.
</P>
<P>
   Business is conducted from McDougle's Upper West Side apartment.
The Trocks' carefully maintained records are stored in a closet at
the home of the company archivist, Anne Dore Davids. The Trocks
rehearse in rented studios. Costumes and sets were moved out of
McDougle's basement into storage at an insurance company's
insistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never been given any National Endowment for the Arts
or state funding, which meant that we didn't have to build a
superstructure with as many or more administrators as dancers,''
McDougle said. ``We had to live by our wits and what we made, which
allowed us to scale back to zero if necessary. We have lived or
died not by the decisions of some committee someplace but by what
happens on the stage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
