<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: San Diego Padres
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: 10:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Qualcomm Stadium, San Diego, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: Fox Sports South.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: RHP Greg Maddux (15-5, 1.53;
18-10, 2.62 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. RHP Andy Ashby (15-6, 2.55;
3-2, 4.63 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Notes: With the run support he has been getting lately, it's a
wonder Maddux is winning at all. After scoring an average of 4.9
runs for him in the first half, the Braves have fallen quiet on the
days Maddux has pitched, averaging 2.7 runs in his six starts since
the All-Star break. Maddux has gone 3-3 in those games, only
because he allowed no earned runs in two starts and allowed a
single earned run in a third. It hasn't hurt that Maddux continues
to lead the majors in ERA (1.53) and shutouts (five). Pitching in
San Diego has provided a challenge for him during the years. His
ERA in 16 starts at Qualcomm is 2.72 (just .01 above his career
ERA), yet he has just an 8-7 record at the park. His next victory
will be his 200th. Ashby, who began the season as the Padres' third
starter, is keeping pace with ace Kevin Brown, losing just once in
his last eight starts and only twice in almost 11 weeks. He has
limited opponents to two runs or fewer in six of his last nine
starts and has made hitters work to get on base. Ashby has
permitted only three walks in his last 50 innings.
</P>
