<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: King of spin a hype heavyweight
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If hype is the true art of the age, then Don King is
the greatest artist of our time, greater than Updike, greater than
Springsteen. The surpassing contradiction is that Don King has
become a multimillionaire by peddling lesser performers when it is
he who is the, ahem, Real Deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he emceed a press conference at the Georgia Dome,
his intent to publicize a prizefight. Three heavyweight champs and
one mayor were on the dais, but it was clear who was the star. In
the span of 90 minutes, the former felon was poet and historian,
missionary and visionary, huckster without peer or shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I've had the opportunity to address Atlanta as
a free man,'' Don King called it, having only recently thrown off
``the shackles and fetters of investigation and indictment.'' He
mentioned Powerball, then said: ``Numbers is my game. Of course,
when I was doing it, they wanted to put you in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   He introduced a woman in the audience, prompting a riff about
the role women played in abolition. A question about a possible TV
blackout sent him across the Pond _ ``In England, everything is
televised live and everything is sold out'' _ and then back to the
Revolution: ``Thirteen colonies beat England.''
</P>
<P>
   He gestured to Vaughn Bean, the nominal challenger who arrived
beneath a red hat almost as tall as King's own famed mane. ``He's
wearing a turban, but he didn't come here to tell your fortune.''
Noting Bean's faith, he said: ``Muslims should pay (to see the
fight). They've got all the oil.''
</P>
<P>
   He referred to a war as, in essence, Ted Turner's big break.
``CNN is No. 1 worldwide, and it never would have happened if he
didn't have Desert Storm.'' He called a kickboxer to the podium,
referring to him as ``the Frenchman from France.'' Of this same
intrepid individual, Don King also said: ``He's white, but he can
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much money Evander Holyfield was actually ``risking''
by fighting in his hometown, Don King shrugged. ``Numbers would
only depreciate what he's doing.'' No media person seized upon this
world-class deflection and dared to follow up. We were all in the
master's thrall.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Don King lauded Holyfield as ``a heavyweight
champion human being.'' On the night Holyfield's ear was bitten,
Don King was handling Mike Tyson. ``We're moving on,'' he said, no
irony in his tone. ``Now I am preaching Holyfield.'' Should the
champ somehow be toppled six weeks hence, doubtless his handler
will move on yet again, this time to Bean, whom Don King said
Tuesday reminded him of a coffee commercial: ``Juan Valdez, the
Colombian.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton White House has been credited with perfecting spin.
That ignores history. Don King was spinning like a Maytag when Bill
Clinton was off at Oxford not inhaling. On Tuesday, he was at it
still, hyping a pedestrian fight by injecting life into old lines:
``It's the irresistible force against the immovable object!
Something's got to give!'' Here Don King smiled hugely, a singer
reworking his greatest hit. ``And give it will! On Sept. 19! Here
in the Georgia Dome!''
</P>
<P>
   Me, I felt like applauding.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: markb(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
