<SLUG> BC-GLF-FEATURE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Piney canyons await players at Sahalee
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ We've gone from Winged Foot to a place where
you might spot Big Foot. When the PGA Championship hits the tube
Thursday, don't be surprised if you see some lumberjack shirts in
place of the usual squadron of Ashworths and Izods. Sahalee Country
Club, which hosts this week's PGA Championship, is a course that
might promote drivers to be removed from bags and replaced by chain
saws.
</P>
<P>
   Towering Douglas firs, cedars and hemlocks line every fairway
with such claustrophobic proximity that accuracy off the tee is
even more necessary than usual at a major championship. They say
Sahalee means ``high heavenly ground.'' It ought to be: ``Is there
no ground here off the fairway without a tree on it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best way to prepare for this course would have
been to go to a big city like New York and maybe play down Fifth
Avenue,'' said Lee Janzen, whose game was precise enough to prevail
at the abnormally narrow Olympic Club two months ago. ``I've played
courses this tight maybe somewhere, but I don't think the trees
were this tall. Here, you have no opportunity to work the ball out
over any trees. They're just too tall.''
</P>
<P>
   The weapons of choice for longer hitters are going to be 3-woods
and 2-irons. Tiger Woods said Tuesday he plans to hit no drivers.
Of course, it helps when your 3-wood goes 280 yards and your 2-iron
260. Considering the flailing John Daly has been doing lately, he
might want to stick with 7-irons. The frustration level for missing
the fairway has the potential for a new PGA record.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could be a fly on the guys' golf bags,'' Janzen said,
``you might hear some words you've never heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Fred Couples, who grew up in the Seattle area and shaped
his game on such piney tunnels, respects the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the golf course can be had if you just keep the ball
in play,'' said Couples, who had not seen Sahalee since 1978.
``Normally, if you're in the rough, there's not too many trees in
the way. Here if you try to do too much and you try to go a little
bit around a tree, it's hard to maneuver the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a week requiring extreme patience, which could
rule out tirade-and-tantrum-prone players such as Woods and Colin
Montgomerie. The player who can force himself to take less club,
hit it straight and rely on his shaping skills on iron approaches
to the greens is more liable to find the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   While the rough was advertised as being in the four-inch range,
it is much longer in some areas. In some cases, that could work to
the players' advantage. Although deeper rough will require a
loftier escape club, it might keep misguided tee shots from running
farther into the forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a low, straight shot off the tee and a high, soft
shot into the greens,'' Bob Estes said. ``That's a complete game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
