<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anyone remember Pebble Beach?
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the stranger bits of scheduling in PGA Tour history,
the rain-shortened AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach Invitational will be completed
Monday, seven months after it started and then was interrputed by
El Nino. In case you've forgotten, with 18 holes remaining there
are a pair of co-leaders _ Tom Watson and Tim Herron at 10-under
par. Sea Island's Davis Love III is two shots back. To help ease
the logistical problems of the situation, the PGA Tour arranged a
chartered jet from Seattle Sunday night to get the players to
Carmel, Calif. Herron joked months ago, ``I wonder if anyone has
ever led a tournament for this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobilo really needs an eye patch
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand's Frank Nobilo took 30 stitches above his left eye
recently at the Lake Nona Golf Club in Florida, where he's a
member, when, while driving in a cart, he was felled by a ball hit
from the range. Doctors told him that being struck just a hair in
either direction could have caused blindness or even death. ...
Callaway Golf will debut a new line of metal woods today, the
Steelhead driver and fairway woods. Priced in the $175 range, they
are Callaway's market combatant to the Adams Tight Lies and Orlimar
TriMetal fairway woods. ... Tiger Woods is still using buddy Mark
O'Meara's backup putter, a Ping Anser2. The transition was not
difficult. He used a similar model as an amateur. With a slightly
longer shaft than his former Scotty Cameron model, the putter
allows Woods to stand over the ball a little taller. ``I'm able to
see the line better,'' Woods said. ``I'm not as hunched over.''
When Woods finished a shot behind O'Meara at the British Open,
O'Meara said,chuckling, ``That's why it's my backup putter.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples and Lynx a question mark
</P>
<P>
   Fred Couples was surprised by a question Tuesday that forced a
comment on the struggling Lynx Golf Co., in which he's both a
representative and has a co-ownership position. Couples was asked
about the Maxfli irons he is using, replacing the Lynx irons that
used to occupy his bag. He remains with the Lynx driver, which he
is still ``killing.'' Said Couples a bit awkwardly, ``A lot of my
other clubs, they're six and seven years old ... but Lynx is
struggling and I really couldn't get a new set. A lot of the
grooves that I had are worn out.'' He grew fond of Maxfli's irons
in Britain while testing some balls at the company's trailer.
``Right now they're really debating what to do at Lynx,'' Couples
said. ``I've tried to stay out of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
