</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTONA-BLACKCOLLEGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Angry Floridians at odds over Black College Reunion
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Atlanta has struggled with Freaknik, and
now this beach resort is grappling with widespread unhappiness over
Black College Reunion, an annual event that was marred in April
when four police officers were shot and a black youth killed in a
gunfight.
</P>
<P>
   Angry residents _ most of them white _ want the city to actively
discourage the 10-year-old event, which this year was officially
recognized by Daytona Beach for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But other residents _ most of them black _ say the city isn't
treating black visitors the same as it does others who come to
special events such as Bike Week and Race Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're talking strict enforcement of the law, let's have it
for all the events, not just Black College Reunion,'' said Richard
Moore, a black resident. ``I'm tired of the traffic gridlock during
(Daytona 500) Race Week.''
</P>
<P>
   At a contentious meeting Tuesday, city commissioners discussed
recommendations by a citizens committee that reviewed the 1998
reunion, which despite city recognition drew widespread complaints
about gridlock, drunkenness, sex in public, loud stereos and
littering.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners were not scheduled to vote on whether to withdraw
their recognition of the event, but instead were to consider only
suggestions for improving next year's reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Debate over the issue has threatened to divide the city along
racial lines. Daytona Beach has hosted other, mostly white public
festivals for decades, including Spring Break and Bike Week, the
annual invasion of thousands of motorcycle enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, both those events have also drawn public criticism,
and city officials made efforts to tame rowdy crowds by increasing
police presence, tightly controlling traffic flow, strictly
enforcing public drinking prohibitions and offering more organized
events to entertain revelers.
</P>
<P>
   That was the strategy for the 1998 Black College Reunion.
Previously an unofficial gathering of college students and others
who came to town for a weekend in April, the event this year had a
promoter recognized by the city who planned an array of concerts,
contests and other events that were supposed to help tame the
rowdiness.
</P>
<P>
   But the concerts drew only tiny audiences, as did most of the
other organized activities. The estimated 110,000 visitors seemed
mostly interested in cruising, and their cars jammed streets on the
beach, leading to gridlock that outraged many residents.
</P>
<P>
   Revelers hung from trunks and out of car windows, some tossing
litter freely, while others drank alcohol in public, and many of
the young men chased and accosed women, some of whom were
scantily-clad.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions boiled over when the gunfight occurred in which an
Orlando youth was killed and police officers were taunted by
hostile crowds. The gun battle renewed the debate over the issue,
with many residents saying it was the last straw.
</P>
<P>
   City officials quickly appointed the 15-member biracial
committee to study the affair. But even the panel couldn't agree,
with a majority recommending the city continue recognizing the
event, while four members submitted a separate report calling on
the city to severe its ties to the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Among the suggestions of the majority report:
</P>
<P>
   _ Include in advertising and mailings to black colleges and
universities information about the city's code of conduct
discouraging lewd and rowdy behavior.
</P>
<P>
   _ Focus marketing efforts on the schools, and try to get
endorsements from school presidents and student leaders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get the word out through the media and at the schools that
laws will be strictly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give notice of traffic checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give police authority to close bridges to the beach if
necessary to control traffic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop a better traffic plan and cut down on cruising.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish a Human Relations Commission.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work with the African-American community to get its support
for stricter law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage hotels to work with the universities to develop
pre-registration procedures that will include providing
identification to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Debate over the suggestions was heated at times, on the
commission and from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Burke, who served on the panel, said he feared the city
could not afford to provide enough police to keep the event safe.
He suggested having the National Guard on standby, saying, ``We
came within a hair's breadth of riots and destruction this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, however, said commissioners were threatening to violate
the rights of the black attendees. ``These kids are going to come
back whether you like it or not,'' he said. ``As citizens of this
country, they have the right to go anywhere they please.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the commission's final actions, debate over the event
seems likely to simmer for months to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters in my zone have told me they don't want Black
College Reunion_ever,'' said Commissioner Christina Travis, who
lives on the beach. ``It is not a reunion. It's a street party that
has overflowed into the neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
