<HEADER>
A8954 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-COLUMNIST-NYT &LR;      08-11 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-COLUMNIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELEAGUERED BOSTON COLUMNIST ALLOWED TO KEEP HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also these stories from The Boston Globe:
GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS and GLOBE-BARNICLE-REACT-BOS) 
(mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston Globe gave Mike Barnicle a reprieve Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After five days of lobbying by supporters of the popular
columnist and after 30 hours of meetings and telephone conferences
among the newspaper's top executives, Matthew Storin, The Globe's
editor, announced at a crowded staff meeting that he would no
longer demand Barnicle's resignation but had imposed a two-month
suspension instead.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday afternoon, Storin said he had been
``persuaded by the argument that the punishment doesn't fit the
crime.'' Barnicle's offense _ using jokes in an Aug. 2 column that
paralleled the writings of the comedian George Carlin _ originally
brought him a one-month suspension, after he told editors he had
not read Carlin's book.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, a local television station, WCVB-TV, broadcast a
videotape of a June 22 program showing Barnicle recommending the
book as summer reading. The editors in Boston called Storin, who
was on vacation in Italy, he said. The decision to ask for
Barnicle's resignation, Storin said, ``was urged on me and I urged
it on the publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barnicle refused to resign. After he pleaded his case to the
listeners of Don Imus' radio program and to the audience of NBC's
``Today'' show last week, the newspaper was deluged with calls,
e-mail and letters, heavily in Barnicle's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ultimately we tried to be fair to everybody,'' said
the newspaper's publisher, Benjamin Taylor. ``To Matt, to the
editors, to Mike and most importantly to the newspaper and the
staff. He added that a well-publicized letter the chief executive
of Staples sent him on Friday questioning whether it was worth
advertising in a newspaper that didn't carry Barnicle's work ``was
not a factor in our decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, in turn, offered more in the way of public apologies
than he has since the furor erupted last Wednesday, changing his
earlier defiant tone to one of contrition. ``I apologized to Matt,
I apologized to the publisher for putting the newspaper in this
terribly awkward position due to my own personal sloppiness,'' he
said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time to be sloppy in the summer of media
introspection,'' Barnicle added. ``I caused great distress for a
great many good people who work hard every single day to put this
paper out.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision left The Globe's newsroom deeply divided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a happy boy today because I think the management did the
right thing,'' said David Nyhan, like Barnicle an associate editor
at the paper and a longtime member of the paper's staff. ``I am
vastly relieved. I am proud of the publisher and the editor for
reversing a stand that was taken in too much haste.''
</P>
<P>
   But others complained, sometimes bitterly, of a double standard.
Though no one argued that Barnicle's offense was comparable to the
repeated fabrications that led to the forced resignation of the
columnist Patricia Smith earlier this summer, several people argued
passionately that Barnicle got special treatment. Ms. Smith is
black and Barnicle is white.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not solely a racial issue. It is a credibility
issue,'' said Howard Manly, the sports media critic for The Globe.
``The Boston Globe suffered a significant hit as a result of
management's indecisiveness. The paper will require years to
overcome the perception that it is in fact an institution where the
old-boy network flourishes,'' added Manly, who described himself as
``black first, a journalist second.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Barnicle and the paper's editors, Manly said: ``I totally
feel for them. Here was a guy who fought for his job and was
afforded every reasonable doubt. But would that happen to me or any
of the other 300 or 400 or so reporters in the building? No.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added: ``What Pat Smith did was disgusting. But how this
particular case was handled suggests, to me at least, that there
are some people who are larger than one of the oldest newspapers in
the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
