<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELPHI12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Merger might cost Ohioans jobs
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Delphi Automotive Systems will partially merge
two of its seven major automotive parts divisions in a move that
could eliminate some white-collar jobs in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for Delphi, the huge automotive parts unit of the
General Motors Corp., said Tuesday the company will combine parts
of its Kettering-based Delphi Chassis Systems with its Delphi
Energy &AMP; Engine Management Systems division in Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the move, company officials said Delphi Chassis will
keep its world headquarters and 360 jobs in Kettering, and no
immediate layoffs are planned.
</P>
<P>
   But further consolidation of the divisions could shrink Delphi's
local corporate work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time we expect that some of our support functions would
be consolidated to eliminate redundancies (in the two divisions),''
said Jim Hagedon, Delphi Chassis spokesman. ``We expect any
reductions in manpower would occur through attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial integration of the two divisions is expected to
affect personnel, finance and other supporting departments, company
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, Alan S. Dawes, the highest ranking
Dayton-area executive for the General Motors Corp., has been named
Delphi's chief financial officer. Dawes, 43, has been the general
manager of the Delphi Chassis division since 1994 and will relocate
from Kettering to Delphi's world headquarters in Troy, Mich. He
will also maintain his status as a GM vice president and will
report directly to J.T. Battenberg III, president of Delphi
Automotive.
</P>
<P>
   Dawes will be replaced as Delphi Chassis general manager by Guy
C. Hachey, who recently served as director of manufacturing for the
Delphi Interior and Lighting division in Warren, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   However, under the new operating structure, Hachey will report
directly to Donald L. Runkle, general manager of Delphi's energy
division.
</P>
<P>
   Runkle will be the top executive in both Delphi Chassis and
Delphi Energy, but company officials said the move doesn't reduce
the power of its locally-based Chassis division.
</P>
<P>
   Battenberg said the partial consolidation of Delphi Chassis and
Delphi Energy is designed to reduce infrastructure costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The integration) will sharpen both division's focus on sales,
marketing and engineering, while maintaining each division's
individual product lines and customer relationships,'' Battenberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   GM said last week it will turn its parts unit into an
independent company by next year.
</P>
<P>
   When the spin-off is completed, only Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base will employ more people locally than Delphi. The world's
largest maker of auto parts employs 15,000 workers in seven area
plants, making the Dayton metropolitan area Delphi's No. 1 U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say communities with a large Delphi presence can expect
more consolidation and cost-cutting as the spin-off approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of cost cutting and consolidation is happening all
over GM and Delphi. It's what Wall Street has been begging the
company to do for years,'' said David Cole, director of the Office
for the Study of Automotive Transportation at the University of
Michigan. ``There are cost overlaps in Delphi's divisions and I'm
sure they'll continue to eliminate those,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
