<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio plants to be expanded by GM
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ General Motors Corp. is planning a third major
investment at it's Moraine facilities in about a year, a $65
million expansion of the Delphi Harrison Thermal Systems, company
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The project would retain 375 jobs, making the next generation of
car air-conditioning compressors in a renovated,
300,000-square-foot building, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said employment could reach 700 at the expanded
site. The company wants to begin production of the compressors by
next May.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first phase in a number of phases to bring a brand
new family of compressors into reality,'' said Jerry Jackson,
manager of the Thermal Systems plant.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials presented the plan to the Montgomery County
Commission on Tuesday, seeking support for a 75 percent, 10-year
tax abatement for the project, equipment and inventory. The
commission will not vote on the matter until later this month, but
two commissioners _ Don Lucas and Charles Curran _ indicated
support on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moraine City Council is expected to vote on the abatement
Thursday. Because it is a 75 percent abatement, the
Kettering-Moraine City School District does not have to give its
approval. However, a tax incentive review committee, made up of
officials from the school district and the cities of Kettering and
Moraine, approved the abatement last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the school district) do informally support the
abatement,'' said Jerold Steck, treasurer for the school district
and a member of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   GM is considering putting the new operation in a vacant building
recently used as an Autoworks Warehouse, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   GM employs 3,600 workers at the Delphi Harrison Thermal Systems
operations. Workers not shifted to the new plant will continue to
produce the air conditioning units they do now, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said agreements with the International Union of Electrical
Workers Local 801, which represents the plant's work force, allows
the company to use teams of workers in the new plant and teach team
work concepts. Having a more flexible work force was necessary to
help convince the company to invest in the plant, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have the competitive agreement that was recently
negotiated we probably wouldn't be here,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   IUE Local 801 Shop Chairman Donnie G. Owens said the plant,
which is expected to be spun off from GM when Delphi Automotive
Systems becomes a separate company next year, will be able to sell
auto air conditioners to any car maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we're spun off we can sell to anybody,'' Owens said.
``We can put them on anything, anyone who wants them.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the last year, GM has initiated two other major
investments at its Moraine works: a $355 million expansion of the
truck assembly plant, and a $320 million joint investment with
Isuzu Motors Ltd. on a 400-employee diesel engine plant.
</P>
<P>
   The company received tax abatements on both projects.
</P>
<P>
   Moraine Mayor Roger Matheny supported using tax abatements to
retain jobs. He said the city has kept its auto-industry employment
high by being willing to offer tax incentives to encourage GM to
stay and grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to retain in order to gain,'' Matheny said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
