<HEADER>
A8968 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-U.S.-EMBASSIES     08-11 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-U.S.-EMBASSIES-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAKE OF BOMBINGS, SEVERAL U.S. EMBASSIES SUSPEND OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related: AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-TANZANIA, AFRICA-BOMBINGS) 
(HLW) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several American embassies have suspended routine
operations in response to threats made after the terrorist attacks
on the embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, State Department officials
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, speaking on condition that they not be named,
said that the affected embassies included those in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia and Kampala, Uganda. The embassy in Mbabane, the capital
of the southern African nation of Swaziland, was evacuated for
several hours on Tuesday after a bomb threat. In West Africa, the
American Embassy in the Ivory Coast said it had cut back its
business hours while security was reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo office of the Agency for International Development was
also shuttered and its employees moved into the well-fortified
American Embassy in the Egyptian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they could not recall a similar instance in
recent years in which several American diplomatic installations,
which often get threats of violence, had suspended operations
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has announced a worldwide alert for embassies
and other diplomatic installations after the terrorist attacks last
week. The State Department and Congress have faced criticism since
the attacks that they failed to provide sufficient security for
embassies abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the American diplomatic missions were not given the
upgraded security recommended by a independent commission after the
bombing of the American Embassy and Marine barracks in Bierut in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick F. Kennedy, the assistant secretary of state for
administration, said that the United States was ``not shutting down
embassies in a permanent sense.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that since the bombings last week, the Department and
its overseas posts had received between one dozen and two dozen
threats, including some considered ``copy cat'' threats of
terrorist attacks mimicking those in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not leaving,'' he said. ``We are taking, in effect, a
brief time-out in order to make the security adjustments that are
necessary to be responsive to a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another State Department official, speaking on condition that he
not be identified, said that, ``where prudent, we're reducing
staff, we're moving from one building to another, we're reducing
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that Americans living or traveling abroad would
be able to obtain emergency services from all American embassies,
regardless of terrorist threats. ``You will always be able to get
an operator at the embassy and be connected to an a duty officer _
24 hours a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The department refused to provide a formal list of the shuttered
embassies out of concern that it might be used by terrorist groups
to identify future targets for attack.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer not to go into identifying specific embassies,''
Kennedy said at a news conference. ``I think that just probably
leads to more copycat calls.'' The closings, he said, had occurred
in ``several regions'' of the world.
</P>
<P>
   He said the embassies had been closed at the request of
ambassadors or, in their absence, the highest-ranking local
American diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always said to our chiefs of mission that they are
responsible to protect the lives and safety of personnel
overseas,'' Kennedy said. ``If the chief of mission feels that
there is information available to him or her that says, `I must
take a particular step, including potentially briefly suspending
operations until adjustments to the security posture can be made,'
then we feel that is absolutely the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not describe the threats that had prompted the decision
to close some embassies, but he said all were being taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a call comes in or whatever it is,'' he said, ``each call
is analyzed and measured and then the post, the ambassador, the
regional security officer, the emergency action committee at the
post does what is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   An American official at the U.S. Embassy in Kuala Lumpur,
speaking on condition that he not be identified, said that the
embassy closed its iron gates on Tuesday for all but emergency
services for American citizens. The official said it would remain
closed on Wednesday in order for the embassy compound to be
``hardened'' against a possible terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thinks of Kuala Lumpur as a terrorist target, but we
want to take every precaution to keep our people safe,'' the
official said. ``I think you'll see additional barricades outside
the embassy later this week, some more barbed wire.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said that the American embassy in
Uganda, which borders both Kenya and Tanzania, was closed on
Tuesday but was expected to reopen on Wednesday with tightened
security measures in force.
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, the offices of the Agency for International
Development were closed and its employees moved into the sprawling
compound of the U.S. Embassy, which is considered one of the
best-protected and most security-conscious in the Middle East,
State Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, has hindered the
conduct of American diplomacy not just in Kenya but across much of
East Africa. The embassy there effectively functioned as a regional
headquarters for the State Department and other American government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   After the U.S. Embassy in neighboring Sudan was shut down in
February 1996 in response to evidence that the Sudanese government
was harboring anti-American terrorist groups, the embassy staff was
moved to Nairobi, where they worked out of the now-shattered
embassy building. State Department officials said it was unclear
how diplomatic relations with Sudan would be conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
