<SLUG> BC-TEN-WTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAILOR-MADE WIN FOR RAYMOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ They were the kind of shots that Lisa Raymond
prefers, right down the heart of the court, where she can attack
them. Raymond, ranked 17th in the country and seeded No. 3 in the
Boston Cup took advantage of those shots that her opponent, Amy
Frazier, was hitting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball very solid, with Amy hitting the type of ball
that I like,'' said Raymond, who won, 6-4, 6-2, in the first-round
match of this Corel WTA Tour event. ``She hits very flat and hard.
It's a nice ball. She doesn't hit with a lot of topspin. She hits
it in my strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond looked confident and played aggressively in this match,
which years ago might have been played deeper in a tournament. But
Frazier is now ranked 79th after being as high as 16th in the
country in 1994 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond looked strong on her backhand, which she can hit with
topspin as well as belting it with a slice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely effective against any of the girls because
most girls have two-handers so I can mix my backhand a lot more,''
Raymond said. ``But you can't be complacent against Amy. You have
to be aggressive. She's very aggressive, so if you don't take it to
her, she's going to take it to you and put you on the defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond won the first set by serving out in the 10th game,
taking it at 15 when Frazier hit a forehand long up the line. In
the second, Raymond broke Frazier's serve in the fourth game and
again in the eighth, when she took the match at love.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier nevertheless was pleased with her play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to play my game, getting a lot of first serves
in, and I wanted to try to move her first, but I wasn't able to do
that very much,'' said Frazier. ``She doesn't have any weakness.
She can stay back or come to the net, as well as hit slices or go
with the topper. She was forcing the play and I was making too many
unforced errors.''
</P>
<P>
   In another afternoon singles match, Barbara Schett won for the
first time in a while on a hardcourt. Not since the middle of
March, at the Lipton Invitational in Key Biscayne, Fla., had she
played on the surface, so Schett spent the first set getting used
to the surface. Then she went to town, routing Kristina Brandi of
Tampa, 6-4, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing on clay a while and everything out here was
so quick,'' said Schett, ranked 29th. ``In the first set, I didn't
know my opponent, but I was moving really well. And then in the
second set, I was confident, playing much more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her groundstrokes were penetrating and she caught me off the
court with her angles,'' said Brandi, who was a qualifier. ``She
hits a lot of angles and that tended to get me off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players had problems with the amount of foot traffic
passing by Court 5. Spectators were constantly roaming past to get
to other courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the qualifier they stopped people from walking
around,'' Brandi said. ``We expected them to have some boards up to
force people from not walking through that area. That made it
difficult to play on that court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
