<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF THE ICE CREAM TRUCK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The  &UR; Earl of Snowdon &LR; , who used to be married to  &UR; Princess &LR; 
 &UR; Margaret &LR;  and has a lot of opinions, said in London recently that
an ice cream van parked near the Albert Memorial Hall in London was
an eyesore. Whereupon artist  &UR; Edna Weiss &LR;  put tongue in cheek and
pen in hand, writing to the Tate Gallery to suggest that the van,
if parked outside that institution, could be considered a piece of
conceptual art.
</P>
<P>
   Much to her surprise, reports the Times of London (in a story
clipped and forwarded by  &UR; Gladys &LR;   &UR; Perint Palmer &LR; ), curator  &UR; Simon &LR; 
 &UR; Wilson  &LR; of the Tate took her suggestion seriously. Citing the work
of  &UR; Marcel Duchamp &LR; , who found art in a urinal, and  &UR; J.M.W. &LR; 
 &UR; Turner &LR; , who ``also looked at landscape and saw art in it,'' he
said there was precedent for considering the van an aesthetic
creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an artist were to designate the ice- &LR;  cream van a work of
art and exhibit it as such,'' he said, ``and if someone were then
to nominate it for the Turner Prize'' (a prestigious art award),
``it might indeed be considered by the jury for short-listing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's point of view _ ``Anything and everything is art,
because an artist says it is'' _ has given rise to vigorous debate
in the British arts community. ``Mr. Wilson has conceptual second
sight,'' wrote  &UR; Simon Jenkins &LR;  in a Times essay. ``He can spot a
Carracci in a Cornetto'' (a British ice cream confection), ``a
Hockney in a Haagen-Dazs, &LR;  and a Watteau in a Mr. Whippy'' (a soft
ice cream).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the truck's still parked near the Albert Hall, and
the ice cream is selling like hotcakes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARE DEAD ANIMALS ART? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Endowment for the Arts is not _ repeat, not _
being called upon to sponsor the ``Hermann Nitsch 6-Day Orgy
Mystery Theater,'' but that didn't stop Rep.  &UR; James Traficant &LR; ,
D-Ohio, from railing against it in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Theater'' is a piece of performance art, sponsored by
 &UR; David Bowie &LR;  and  &UR; Yoko Ono &LR; , that includes the butchering of live
animals on stage. ``Beam me up. What is next, folks?'' said
Traficant, whose remarks were reported in Roll Call. ``The  &UR; Lorena &LR; 
 &UR; Bobbitt &LR;  do-it-yourself art expo?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Meanwhile, on the Senate side, Senator  &UR; Patrick Leahy &LR; , D-Vt.,
is the sponsor of ``Re-Membering the Primates,'' a photo show on
display in the Capitol Rotunda this week that features dead
animals. The animals, photographed by  &UR; Sally Linder &LR; , were killed
in a 1995 fire in the Philadelphia Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RULES IN JAPAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a vacation in Japan,  &UR; Anne Clerk  &LR; forwards the
very specific set of rules from the Castle Hotel in Kumamoto. Among
them is the request to ``Refrain From the Following'':
</P>
<P>
   ``To carry the following into the room, lobby or the hall:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Animals, birds, etc.;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Things unclean or with a loathsome smell;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Items of great quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests are also forbidden from using ``the furnitures and
fixtures in the room, lobby or the hall for the purpose other than
the original intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, it is taboo ``to fix other items to the room or the
furnitures, or work up to alter those existing situations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Johns Hopkins University has sent word that one of its faculty
members, constitutional law expert and political scientist  &UR; Joel
Grossman &LR; , is of the professional opinion that a sitting president
can pardon himself. Grossman has prepared a scholarly treatise on
this subject for publication in the Presidential Studies Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marisa Tomei &LR;  and  &UR; Glenn Close &LR;  were in Sarajevo last
weekend, performing alongside Bosnian actors in a play about female
victims of war. First lady  &UR; Hillary Rodham Clinton &LR;  sent a letter
to be read aloud for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tiggy-Legge Bourke &LR; , former nanny to  &UR; William &LR;  and  &UR; Harry &LR; ,
the little princes of Britain, is in trouble over a recent
excursion during which she allowed Harry to go rappelling without a
helmet or safety line. The British Press Association says
 &UR; Prince Charles  &LR; has asked aides for a full investigation of the
incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
