<HEADER>
A8976 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHONE-STRIKE-375&AMP;ADD-     08-11 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-STRIKE-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC STRIKE ENDS AFTER TENTATIVE PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   (bl)  
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bringing a swift conclusion to a two-day-old strike that had
begun to inconvenience telephone customers from Maine to Virginia,
Bell Atlantic employees returned to work Tuesday after reaching a
tentative agreement with management that insures that jobs in the
company's high-technology growth areas will go to union employees.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed two-year contract agreed to Tuesday, the
company guaranteed that all installation, maintenance and repair
work involving advanced data communications for residential and
corporate customers, including access to the Internet, would be
performed by members of the Communications Workers of America. The
company also agreed to phase out hundreds of mostly customer
service jobs now being outsourced to nonunion workers in Hampton,
Va., and put them back into the union's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major victory,'' said Larry Mancino, a vice
president of District One of the Communications Workers of America.
``There is no contract in this industry that has those kinds of
protections.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic executives described the accord, which is subject
to ratification by the union membership, in more measured terms.
``This is a balanced agreement,'' said Steven Marcus, a company
spokesman. ``It meets the union's needs and it also meets our
customers' needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Sacco, executive vice president for human resources, pointed
out that the company retained some leeway in hiring nonunion
workers. ``The contract gives Bell Atlantic the flexibility to
manage its business in an increasingly competitive market,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Characterizing the agreement as a major victory for labor, Paul
Osterman, a professor of management at the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology, said the union had scored in two ways _ by
preventing further erosion of jobs and persuading management that
its members are qualified to do high-technology jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be able to show that they can do those jobs or can
be trained to do those jobs,'' Osterman said. ``I think it's a big
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the recent General Motors strike, wage increases played a
relatively minor role in the Bell Atlantic dispute. The proposed
contract calls for an increase of 3.8 percent in the first year and
4 percent in the second.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``On the pay front, what the union is achieving is holding their
own,'' Osterman said, ``but they are preventing terrific
degradation.''
</P>
<P>
   The walkout, which began at 12:01 Sunday, did not interrupt
basic telephone service for the company's 27 million customers, but
many people were unable to reach directory assistance, place
operator-assisted calls or get their telephone lines repaired or
installed. About 23,500 managers were assigned to perform work
normally done by 73,000 union employees.
</P>
<P>
   The latest walkout and its speedy settlement was a far cry from
1989, when workers at Nynex, which merged with Bell Atlantic last
year, went on strike for four months. This time, negotiators, eager
to avoid a long walkout, worked nonstop even after the contract
expired Sunday, and came to an agreement at 5 a.m. The company was
under pressure to reach a speedy resolution because of competition
that did not exist nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996, which reduced regulations in
many communications markets, has unleashed a host of hungry new
companies eager to win business away from established phone giants
including Bell Atlantic. Before the act's passage, Bell Atlantic,
along with the rest of the Baby Bell local phone companies, enjoyed
virtual monopolies in many of their markets.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge posed by the new competitors is especially
daunting for older companies like Bell Atlantic because most of the
upstarts have nonunion work forces. Each day that the strike
continued would have afforded Bell Atlantic's competitors another
opportunity to convince Bell Atlantic's customers that they would
be better off with a different phone company.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, stock prices of many competitive local phone providers,
including RCN Corp., dropped Tuesday on news of the settlement, but
Bell Atlantic's shares rose slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilant over the settlement, union officials said they
prevailed on almost every point. Resolving one especially
contentious issue, Bell Atlantic agreed to extend a lucrative early
retirement program that expired when the contract ended. To
discourage eligible workers from taking advantage of the program
immediately, the company agreed to sweeten their pensions if they
defer their departure.
</P>
<P>
   The company also agreed to extend a provision negotiated under
the last contract that prevents it from laying off workers,
downgrading their jobs, or forcing them to transfer from one
location to another during the life of the contract. In addition,
the agreement makes it easier for the union to organize workers at
all Bell Atlantic subsidiaries except Bell Atlantic Mobile, the
cell phone unit, which employs 7,100 people.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic will not have to abandon entirely the use of
contract workers. James Dowdall, vice president for labor
relations, said the company would still be able to hire a limited
amount of nonunion labor under certain emergency or peak demand
situations or when it lacked qualified union personnel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Bell Atlantic employees returned to their jobs Tuesday, a
tentative agreement between Southern New England Telecommunications
Inc. and its workers appeared to have run into some problems.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which serves virtually all 3 million residents of
Connecticut, had announced Friday that it had reached a deal with
the Connecticut Union of Telephone Workers, but the proposed
contract met resistance from rank-and-file union members.
</P>
<P>
   A threatened walk-out, scheduled for noon Tuesday, was averted
when SNET agreed to reopen negotiations with the 6,200-member union
and talks began under the direction of a federal mediator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FB-DOAKWALKER-HNS &LR;      08-11 3288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FB-DOAK </SLUG>
 WALKER-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Doak Walker always a hero
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo. _ Dick Davis tried to think of something
to say. He never had wondered about such things before. The words
had always come easily, quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But now his friend and hero, a generation's hero, was in a
hospital bed trying to teach himself how to chew his food, and
Davis knew the words had to be right. What could he say? How should
he act? Would he cry? How could he not? Davis practiced lines,
rejecting each. He imagined his friend pinned by paralysis to that
hospital bed and worried about the news his face would surely tell
the moment he walked into the room.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they were 6 years old, Doak Walker and Dick Davis
were already old friends. They had been next-door neighbors in East
Dallas. And by the time their families moved to Highland Park, they
had become the sort of friends you keep for life, and they joined
the other neighborhood kids in a local swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   They were fearless, diving deep into the water, until suddenly
Davis was missing. A peg under the water had grabbed Davis by the
shorts and wouldn't let go. Water began filling his lungs. The more
he struggled, the more securely he became trapped beneath the
water's surface. Panic replaced daring.
</P>
<P>
   But his old friend, the sort of friend you can count on, found
Davis beneath the water, pulled him free and saved his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doak Walker,'' Davis said six decades later, ``was always a
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Davis was on his way to Denver to see his hero unable to
move. For the first time, Davis didn't know what to say. Walker had
been an ideal, a legend and a friend for life, the best athlete and
teammate Davis had ever known or imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had always loved him. Strangers loved him. He had been the
last American hero before television and cynicism changed the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   In January, this most graceful of legends was on the last of the
downhill runs' long, swooping arcs he so loved when he crashed on
an intermediate ski slope named ``Rainbow'' he had cruised a
thousand times before. Walker severely bruised his brain stem. He
was left paralyzed from the neck down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up together. We were inseparable. He is like my
brother,'' Davis said. ``But when I walked into the room to see
Doak, I didn't know what to say. I'm never lost for words, but I
was really worried about it. And then I walked in, and he had a
great, big smile on his face. He immediately put me at ease.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, a therapist asked Walker if he would like to try to
say a few words. Walker was still trying to teach himself how to
talk then, but he had the ``cup'' at the end of the long ventilator
tube that runs down his throat into his chest removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him,'' Davis said, ```Is there anything I could do for
you? Is there anything you need, anything you want.'''
</P>
<P>
   Walker thought about the question a moment, smiled again, and
forced out a few raspy words: ``How about a cheeseburger and a
beer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens to everybody,'' Hank Edwards, one of
Walker's enormous ``family'' of friends in Steamboat Springs, said.
``When we went to see him the first time, we were really
apprehensive about it. It's really hard to explain, but when we
left, I felt good. His eyes were brilliant and bright. It was just
typical Doak. You don't leave feeling sorry for him. I left
thinking, `this guy's going to make it.' We went to see him, and he
ends up making us feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   America was never more optimistic, more proud than when Doak
Walker was its hero.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, America was prosperous, hopeful, growing,
victorious. When Doak Walker won the Heisman 50 years ago this
season, America cherished its heroes as perfect magazine-cover
reflections of a nation never more sure of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was the first post-war hero, the last before television
brought its power to show everything, including the warts. Heroes
were not created then to sell shoes. They were selected based on
their ability to fit the nation's ideals, the values that had
inspired real heroism in real battles. America was filled with true
believers. It believed in Doak Walker.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Walker did everything for SMU. He was the Mustangs'
top rusher, passer, defender, kick returner, punter and place
kicker. He was their quiet leader and called all the plays.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-10, 175, he was unimpressive at a glance, but that only
served his legend. He was so swift, so agile, he would seem to use
the entire field in a maze of cuts and moves. Walker seemed to
touch every moment that unbeaten 1948 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was gifted,'' Davis said. ``He could do anything. He
had grace, balance, strength, speed. He could do anything, and he
excelled in everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Raleigh Blakely, an SMU teammate, ``They talk today about
guys going both ways. When Doak came out of SMU, he was working
both ways all the time. A lot of people don't realize how great he
was on defense. I guess we could all tell you how great he was, but
the thing that stands out to me was there was something about him
in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``His greatness showed up game time on Saturday. Monday through
Friday, I could throw the ball further. There were guys who could
kick the ball further, run faster in a foot race. On Saturday,
there was no peer. When it was game day, he had a gear none of us
ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the previous season, when Walker's legend had just started
to grow after his return from the service, the Dallas News
typically wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulging with manpower and versatile skill, the visitors from
Houston (Southwest Conference favorite Rice) will have every
advantage except for the brains and ability wrapped up in the
person of the 175-pound sophomore tailback who grew up in the
shadow of (SMU's) Ownby Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rice is said to be three- and four-deep in all positions and
has speed, strength, spirit and savvy. SMU has Walker and the idea
that he alone will make the contest even.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 14-0 SMU win, Walker carried 12 times for 87 yards,
completed four of five passes for 33 yards, intercepted two passes
and recovered a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   And Dallas football fans were so entranced, the Cotton Bowl,
SMU's part-time home, was expanded by more than 26,000 seats after
that season, and by another 8,000 the next to watch one player for
just two more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played (five games as a freshman) in 1945 when a lot of us
weren't back from the service,'' Davis said. ``Then he was drafted,
and went into the service in 1946. In 1946, our team had a lot of
veterans, battle-hardened guys. A lot were great All-Americans.
They started hearing stories about Doak, and after what they'd been
through, a lot of these guys didn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when they saw him _ he was sort of small _ they really
didn't believe it. But once he put a football uniform on, you knew
it. He had that respect. You could just tell. Everybody knew he was
the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly as many stories of his intelligence during
games. In the 19-19 tie with TCU in 1947, while returning the
kickoff that helped SMU's last-minute comeback, he veered past SMU
coach Matty Bell on a 57-yard return to shout instructions that
Bell put Gilbert Johnson in for the next play. Johnson's ensuing
touchdown pass tied the game with 15 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if he was, as a player, peerless, his legend survives a
half-century later for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Other players could be respected; Walker was beloved.
</P>
<P>
   Before Michael or Dr. J, before Ali or Namath, or even Mantle
and Mays, Walker was a hero from the pages of newspapers and
biographies, smiling from the covers of Life and Look, Sport and
Collier's.
</P>
<P>
   He was the sort of athlete that could inspire dreams _ fast,
graceful, handsome and humble. He had thick hair Vitalis would
later use to move merchandise and blue eyes that virtually every
hospital visitor still speaks of as they leave the room.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was so large a figure, one wire service moved an obituary
when his cat died. He was so popular a teammate, when Life magazine
released an issue in 1948 with a cover of Walker in position to
pass, and 40 people lined up outside a drug store near SMU waiting
for the doors to open, 30 were SMU teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He married the homecoming queen, with whom he posed on a famous
Collier's cover. He starred for the university around the corner
from his parents' home. For 50 years, he answered every piece of
fan mail. In 1948, he wrote the Associated Press a thank-you note
for naming him All-American. In 1949, he wrote asking he not be
selected, arguing an injury kept him from playing enough to deserve
the honor for a third time.
</P>
<P>
   America did not know every detail then and didn't need to. It
could look at the 47 magazine covers and fill in the rest.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Doak Walker 3-time All American was published and the
legend picked up speed. Esquire wrote, ``Doak Walker was everything
a football hero should be; handsome, shy, reticent and unassuming
off the field, a cool, swashbuckling, brigand on the field. He was
every father's shining son, every mother's darling boy, every
athlete's sturdy leader, every sorority girl's golden dream. There
was no one in the world who could match him. No mortal could live
up to that much adulation. But Doak Walker did.''
</P>
<P>
   So loyal were those he touched, when Davis and Blakely put
together a reunion last spring, 40 SMU players said they could
attend, and all 40, stretched from Florida to California, showed.
And 50 years after the unbeaten, Heisman season, Blakely believes
they came back to trade stories about the teammate who could not be
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there were other reasons they wanted to get back
together,'' Blakely said. ``It wasn't a tribute to Doak. But Doak
Walker and his injury made it happen. They wanted to be together to
talk about Doak.''
</P>
<P>
   To teammates, Walker was not a face on a magazine cover. Those
were not tales of a god from Greek mythology. It was real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy that got his picture on every damned magazine in
the country,'' Blakely said. ``Why did nobody mind that? They
wanted to be the first to have a copy. When I go places now, when
they introduce me they say, `He played with Doak Walker.' That's
awesome. I can grow about four inches hearing that. It's pride.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all real, they still insist. Even time, even emotions
rekindled by his current circumstances, do not exaggerate the
stories. And even those trained to doubt, to question, don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had so many characteristics that were quite uncommon,''
said Felix McKnight, the former editor of both major Dallas
dailies, and a writer in Fort Worth at the time who could not get
sportswriting out of his system with Walker playing at SMU.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 60 consecutive years of newspapering, from staff writing to
correspondent, to the editor-publisher level, I've have had the
opportunity to meet and write about many, many men and women, from
Dizzy Dean to Ike Eisenhower. But I sincerely don't think I ever
met a man who occupied his corner with the style and dignity that
Doak Walker as an athlete gave us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Werner name is gold in Steamboat Springs, local royalty
except that you always could walk up and say hello, or if you were
sick, Hazie Werner would stop in with fresh bread and tonics.
</P>
<P>
   Skeeter Werner was a legend when she met Doak Walker in 1968.
She had twice been an Olympic skier, once an alternate. Her
brothers Bud and Loris had also been Olympians. They still talk
about the way Bud attacked a slope before he was killed in a St.
Moritz avalanche in 1964. Storm Mountain was renamed Werner
Mountain. Skeeter had stopped competing to model and design ski
clothes, eventually running the ski school and later the ``Storm
Hut'' ski store.
</P>
<P>
   Walker had already ended his six-year NFL career, had dabbled in
business and coaching, when Skeeter was asked to teach a celebrity
to ski for ``Stars and Stripes'' and an instant romance that has
lasted three decades began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked me up at six o'clock in the morning and we went to
the very top of Storm Peak, and it was the most gorgeous corn snow
(spring, crusty snow) I ever skied in my life,'' she said. ``It was
so great we climbed all the way back up again because the lift had
broken down. Then we played 18 holes of golf. Then we played
tennis. We went to a cocktail party that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He carried my skis for me. I never had anyone carry my skis,
so I thought I better pay attention to this guy. We went to the
party and out to dinner and decided to get our sleeping bags and
sleep on the mountain. The next day we got up and skied, came back
down and played golf. I was going to visit friends in Scottsdale
the next week and knew Doak was in a golf tournament in Palm
Springs. Why I called him I don't know because I never did that in
my life, but I asked him to meet me in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out to dinner and the next day played 36 holes of
golf, and then stayed up all night on a diving board talking. The
next day we went out to dinner and I asked him to marry me. The
couple with us said maybe we should wait a little longer, but I
said `No, I want to get married now.' So Doak chartered a plane to
Las Vegas and we got married.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, Walker, the hero and legend, had moved into
the Werner home in which Skeeter was raised and happily called
himself ``Mr. Werner'' around Steamboat Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Friends could drop in at any time in the house just off
Steamboat Springs' main road for coffee in the morning, drinks in
the evening, football every weekend. His Heisman Trophy, once found
on the circular rack of ski jackets in the Storm Hut, sits on the
mantle. His NFL Hall of Fame bust, earned in just six seasons with
the Lions, is off in a corner. There are trophy cases stuffed with
almost 300 shiny reminders of the athletic excellence of Skeeter
and Doak Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Walker skied roughly 75 days a year. He rode his horse
(``Herschel Walker''; Skeeter's is ``Bo Jackson'') on long pack
trips and played golf in paradise. He hunted for elk and went fly
fishing for rainbow trout. And he cherished his friends nearly as
much as they treasure him.
</P>
<P>
   But now, friends trade stories of Walker instead of beers with
him. They laugh out loud, but stop and look away before their
emotions become too great to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite saying of his is, `I don't know, I'm pretty
busy,''' Chris Gotchy said. ``He'd always say it with that silly
smile on his face. He has the cutest little silly grin. I'd ask if
he wanted to play golf, or if he could come over and help us move
some rocks or something off our property. He'd say, `I don't know,
I'm pretty busy.' It was his way of saying `of course.' He said to
me the other day in the hospital. `I don't know. I'm pretty busy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to ride his horse over to wax my daughter's skis or
just drink iced tea.'' With that, Gotchy could talk no more. She
looked away to fight tears. ``He'll ride again up to my house
again,'' she finally said, softly. ``I know he will.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, a collection of letters and faxes Walker
received in the hospital reaches almost three feet from the desk.
Skeeter read every letter to Walker. Some brought jokes, others
memories, but most offered thanks and prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get through maximum five without breaking down,'' Jack
Beattie said. ``I can't remember ever going more than five before I
just had to stop. There's some from kids. Some from people 60 years
old he wrote back to 50 years ago. It's a real study, something
very special, the way he touched people. It's what he's about.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tugboat, a Werner Mountain bar, Walker's friends trade
stories and laughs. There could be a thousand groups of friends
doing the same thing, Edwards said. The annual Steamboat Springs
Walker-(Verne) Lundquist golf event raised roughly $215,000 to help
refurbish the 93-year-old Werner-Walker home. And virtual strangers
who knew Walker only through smiles in the supermarket or on the
slopes asked Edwards to provide a fund raiser for Walker that they
could afford. In one evening they raised $2,500 a few dollars as a
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of his close friends,'' Jack Doyle, the Tugboat
manager said. ``But he is just a super nice guy to everyone. You
would never know he was a star. He would never talk about it. The
stars go down to Aspen for everybody to notice them. They come here
just to be people. Doak was just people. He just had that big grin
all the time. You'd see him in the grocery store and he'd give you
a big smile and a pat on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tugboat co-owner Larry Lamb, ``Besides being an extremely
important athletic person, he's just a warm, loving, giving,
exceptional, kind, affectionate guy. And if he could, he'd come
right in here and sit down and have a beer beside you and shoot the
fat about what went on that day. He'd say how great it is to see
you. And if somebody tapped him on the shoulder and asked for his
autograph, he'd love to give it.''
</P>
<P>
   So they trade stories. There was the time after a pack trip Lamb
convinced Walker to ride his horse through the bar. ``They came
back and said they were parched,'' Lamb said. ``I don't know how
they could be parched. They brought 15 bottles of whiskey and 14
cases of beer.'' There was the day Werner and Walker were married.
``The guy said, `Do you Ewell take Gladys ,''' Edwards said. ``Doak
looked at Skeeter. Skeeter looked at Doak. `Ewell?' `Gladys?' They
had never heard each other's real first names.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards talked of the time his wife mentioned that Walker's No.
37 had always been her favorite number. Twenty years later, when
Hank and D.J. Edwards were married, Walker sent the red SMU jersey
of his Heisman Trophy season as a gift they cherish. There were
Thanksgiving and Christmas dinners. Songs he would sing. ``And he
has a horrible voice,'' Lamb said. The crowd laughed at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   They even told of visits to the hospital. When D.J. visited, he
told her, ``Skeeter's coming tomorrow. Can you help me? I need
practice kissing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Walker was managing his first words and Skeeter asked, just
to hear the answer again, ``Do you love me, Doak?'' he waited, and
waited, before he finally smiled and forced out the words, ``Don't
rush me.''
</P>
<P>
   And as they tell the stories, Walker and Werner, in Hawaiian
shirts in a Hula Bowl photo, among the walls of celebrities that
had stopped by for a pint, seem to smile at the retelling.
</P>
<P>
   And in a sense, the magic that could be seen from the Cotton
Bowl's upper decks half a century ago still works. Even motionless,
there's something heroic, something that makes every friend believe
he will walk again, every visitor feel somehow better.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask, should I visit him in this condition?'' Gotchy
said. ``Should I kiss him? Should I hug him? But you see his face,
those eyes so expressive. It's Doak. He hasn't lost a beat through
this whole thing. There is a charm about him. You see these big
guys come in to see him, and they don't know how to act. Pretty
soon, they lean over and give him a hug or give him a kiss. He just
has a way that touches people.''
</P>
<P>
   It was real, that feeling that somehow came off those magazine
covers. Perhaps it wasn't the time or the long runs or good looks,
but something was there. It still is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing progress, and he will improve,'' Beattie said.
``We all hope for the day he can walk again. It's somewhat
doubtful. But we go beyond that. Nothing is too much for this guy.
You never know what to expect of this guy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
