<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONESBORO-TRIAL-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARKANSAS TEEN-AGER OFFERS EXCUSE IN SCHOOL SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ark. _ Just before a judge remanded 14-year-old
Mitchell Johnson and 12-year-old Andrew Golden into juvenile
detention for a school shooting spree that killed a teacher and
four little girls, the older boy offered a courtroom filled with
their relatives a childlike excuse.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not mean to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to shoot over their heads,'' said the
quavering, trembling Mitchell, who pleaded guilty in an
abjudication hearing _ the juvenile court equivalent of a trial _
in the Craighead County Courthouse Tuesday. ``We didn't think
anybody was going to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Golden, who was 11 years old on March 24, the day he and
Mitchell used a false fire alarm at Westside Middle School to lure
their schoolmates outside and then fired repeatedly into the
terrified mass of students and teachers with high-powered rifles,
pleaded not guilty. His lawyer said his client was insane at the
time and was not mentally competent to stand trial, although the
judge did not allow him to plead so.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Ralph Wilson, after a two-hour trial in which
prosecutors quickly laid out an open-and-shut case, convicted
Andrew and found him, along with Mitchell, to be ``delinquent,''
the juvenile court equivalent of a guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, his hands tied by strict laws that prevent anyone who
commits a serious crime before their 14th birthday from being
punished as an adult, remanded the boys to the Division of Youth
Services, where they will probably be held in a juvenile detention
center until their 18th birthdays, then released.
</P>
<P>
   ``The punishment will not fit the crime,'' said Wilson, as the
kin of the five victims clutched each other's arms and pressed
tissues to crying eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, the two boys could be held until they turn 21,
but the state has no facility for adult offenders sentenced under
juvenile court laws, and cannot, by law, put the boys in a state
prison.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Mitchell, barring any crimes committed in
juvenile detention that could extend his sentence, will be out in
four years. Andrew, who sat stone-faced throughout the hearing,
will be out in six.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the victims _ another nine students and a teacher
were wounded in the attack _ had hoped the hearing would finally
answer why this thing was done, would reveal what was going on in
the minds of the two boys.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew, an award-winning marksman who stole guns from his
grandfather to use in the shooting, refused to say anything, and
Mitchell offered more of an apology than an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Although police and balliistics experts have said the boys
methodically fired into the crowd _ Shannon Wright, an English
teacher, was hit twice by a 30.06 hunting rifle fired by Mitchell _
the boy said he did not mean to shoot anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry,'' said Mitchell, who turned 14 Tuesday. ``I
understand that it may be impossible for some of you to forgive me.
If I could go back and change what happened on March 24, 1998, I
would in a minute. I have caused pain. I have asked God for
forgiveness and that he will heal the lives of the people I have
hurt by my actions.''
</P>
<P>
   For the relatives of the boys' victims, the justice they
received was not nearly enough. They saw only two boys who, even
now, refused to take responsibility for their actions that day.
</P>
<P>
   In a withering testimony in which he spoke directly to the two
boys, Mitchell Wright, the husband of the slain teacher, said there
was no way the killings were unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   The older boy, Mitchell, was firing a rifle with a telescopic
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell me it was random, son, not with the scope on
that gun,'' Wright said, his face red, his eyes beginning to tear.
</P>
<P>
   The bullets that left a sidewalk wet with blood took his best
friend, and the mother from his 3-year-old son, Zane.
</P>
<P>
   The boy has been told his mother is in heaven, but he wonders
why, when he wants to be rocked to sleep, she cannot come down and
do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zane looks for his mother to come back,'' said Wright. ``You
have robbed a 3-year-old boy of his innocence. He told me, `Don't
worry about those two bad boys. If they break out of jail, I'll
take care of you.'''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about how his wife, who taught Andrew, gave him extra
time on one project, because he was nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Four other relatives took the stand during the sentencing phase,
including Lloyd Brooks, whose 11-year-old niece, Natalie Brooks,
was killed in the ambush.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, he pointed out, had turned 14 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrated Natalie's birthday on May 26,'' said Brooks, his
voice shaking. ``We brought flowers to her grave.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile hearings are typically closed to the public and press
here in Arkansas, but the judge allowed a more open hearing because
of the intense interest in the case. About 100 family and friends
came to the courtroom, passing through a medical detector to get to
the heavily guarded courtroom _ state officials had said the boys
had received several death threats.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, there were few spectators who came only for the
spectacle, inside or outside. Most people here say they are sick of
it, sick of the pain of it.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew seemed not to even be interested in the proceedings, as
prosecutors built their case against him.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Val Price, said the boy should have been allowed to
claim insanity as a defense _ the judge would not allow such a plea
_ and did not even know what was happening to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client today does not understand the nature of the
proceedings,'' said Price to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   But teachers at the school, and people who knew the boy, said he
did not seem to have any mental problems beyond a mild problem with
his attention span.
</P>
<P>
   The case prosecutors built was really more of a synopsis, short,
curt and businesslike. The only real drama came when they showed
the court two of the guns.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the guns was cocked, loudly, some people in the
courtroom caught their breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence put on by the state was overwhelming evidence,''
said Price.
</P>
<P>
   The boys had apparently planned it for some time. Students at
Westside said it was to get even with a girl who had said she did
not want to be Mitchell's girlfriend anymore _ she was slightly
wounded in the attack _ and in revenge of teasings the boys had
received. But what made the boys respond so violently is still a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, like others here, asked the boys to someday ``tell us
why.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jonesboro crime, the deadliest in a series of school
shootings that left people dead in Pearl, Miss., West Paducah, Ky.,
and Springfield, Ore., also killed middle school students Paige Ann
Herring, Britthney Varner and Stephanie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, without any objections from either of the public
defenders assigned to represent the two boys, showed in the
courtroom how the boys, both of them dressed in camouflage, stole a
van from Mitchell's house, loaded it with guns from Andrew's
grandfather's house, and drove to a copse of trees that offered a
clear field of fire into the schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew rang the bell, drawing the students outside, then went to
join his friend in the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fired numerous times into the gathering of students and
teachers,'' said Mike Walden, the deputy prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The boys then fled for their van, which they had loaded with
camping gear, ammunition and junk food. But before they could reach
the van police officers intercepted them and ordered them to throw
down their guns and lie down. Mitchell did so at once, and then
Andrew complied. At no time did they point their guns at the
arresting officers.
</P>
<P>
   Although several people here talked about finding some peace
after the verdict, the case is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's lawyers said they would appeal the judge's ruling, as
did a lawyer for Mitchell's father, Scott Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said his son was mistreated while in the Craighead
County juvenile facility.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was not fed well or treated properly by doctors or
counselors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to allow my son to stay in Arkansas,'' he said,
but did not explain how he planned to accomplish that. ``This isn't
the place for a rabid animal, to say nothing of a 14-year-old
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who said his son was sexually abused as a little boy,
said his son never told him why he did what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have an answer for why,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
