<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8984 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      08-11 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI IN EAST AFRICA: FAMILIAR METHODS AND UNRESTRICTED ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related: AFRICA-U.S.-EMBASSIES, AFRICA-TANZANIA,
AFRICA-BOMBINGS) 
(HLW) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With what it describes as the largest team ever
assembled to investigate terrorism against Americans overseas, the
FBI is following a familiar investigative method in East Africa,
aimed at rapidly amassing enormous amounts of data that authorities
hope will yield evidence to unravel the bombing plot against the
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries have granted the agents nearly unrestricted
access to evidence, witnesses and possible suspects in the case,
and officials at the Federal Bureau of Investigation privately
expressed confidence on Tuesday that, in time, they can crack these
cases.
</P>
<P>
   The case is being managed in Nairobi by Sheila Horan, a career
counterintelligence agent, who heads an FBI counterterrorism unit
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Horan's agents are working behind the teams of search and
rescue personnel focused on their main task, the tedious but
crucial effort to identify, collect, evaluate and preserve evidence
in an effort to identify the perpetrators and, if the case can be
made, use it against them in an American court.
</P>
<P>
   In Tanzania, the agents are working in cooperation with local
authorities who have detained more than two dozen people, among
them Sudanese, Iraqis, a Somali and a Turk. Dar es Salaam's
ambassador to the United States, Mustafa Salim Nyang'anyi, said
some of those arrested ``may have had a hand'' in the attack. He
said all were turned over to the FBI for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a prime suspect, the agents are following
three primary trails, officials said on Tuesday. The first involves
interviews with witnesses, suspects and others who may have
relevant information like residents in the vicinity of the
bombings, car rental agents, and airline representatives who might
have observed unusual movements in the hours before or after the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The second track involves tapping into intelligence information
collected by the Central Intelligence Agency and the espionage
services of friendly countries that will be asked to seek out any
relevant information about the bombing to pass on to American
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The third and most visible line of inquiry centers on the
collection of physical evidence. It will be analyzed to determine
the explosive used in the attack. Agents did not arrive at the
scene until 36 hours after the blast, but officials said the
inquiry would have been delayed in any case, because search
operations must be completed before investigators can cordon off
areas to search for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The forensic search focuses on an effort to assemble parts of
vehicles that may have been used in the bombing to determine, if
possible, the manufacturer and ownership. In addition, vehicle
parts often provide clues to the nature of the blast and the
explosive power of the bomb; traces of chemical residues can be
analyzed on portable lab equipment flown to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, FBI officials said that they could not confirm
reports that the bombers in both cities used Semtex, a Czech-made
military high explosive, a sophisticated explosive that would
heighten suspicions of a carefully orchestrated or possibly
state-sponsored terrorist plot.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI's explosives lab has a reputation for being slow to
definitively identify explosives in bomb cases. As a result, other
officials said that the FBI might ultimately conclude that the
bombers in both countries used Semtex.
</P>
<P>
   The early upbeat mood represents a stark contrast to the
bitterness and frustration that followed recent FBI attempts to
extend its reach overseas. In the case of the 1996 bombing at Al
Khobar Towers in Saudi Arabia, in which 19 airmen were killed, the
FBI sent more than 60 agents after Saudi officials told the
Americans they would receive full cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   But Saudi authorities kept FBI agents in the dark from the start
and even after two years of complaints by American authorities, the
Saudis have not allowed agents to interview any of the several
dozen suspects who have been detained. The perpetrators have yet to
be identified and none has been punished.
</P>
<P>
   In East Africa, the FBI has moved quickly to capitalize on local
cooperation. As a result, the size and composition of the
investigative force bears a close resemblance to the agent force
that conducted domestic investigations of the World Trade Center
bombing in 1993 and the Oklahoma City federal building blast in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   And in a small but telling gesture, American agents have even
been permitted to carry their firearms and wear bullet proof vests
_ a meaningful concession within law enforcement circles that
suggests that FBI agents are operating in Africa much as they would
in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
