<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXFORD-REACT-NYT &LR;      08-11 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXFORD-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGE EMPLOYERS KEEPING OXFORD DESPITE PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)  (Eds: See also OXFORD-EARNINGS) 
(mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the relentless bad news concerning Oxford Health Plans
Inc. _ and another heavy dose of it Tuesday _ many of the region's
large employers are continuing to do business with Oxford, at least
for now.
</P>
<P>
   The company's unusually comprehensive list of doctors and
generous benefits appeal to employees, and that outweighs concern
about the insurer's financial instability, hammered stock price and
increased rates, they say. Also, there are few great alternatives
available currently.
</P>
<P>
   Several employers and benefits experts said that Oxford, even in
its embattled state, is preferable to more outwardly stable firms
that offer significantly fewer doctors and benefits and entail
administrative headaches for patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``All managed care companies have made changes in recent years,
and not any of them have treated our employees particularly well,''
said John Carroll, a benefits manager at Time Warner Inc., which is
leaning toward keeping Oxford. ``Our primary concern at Time Warner
is keeping employees happy, and so far with Oxford, there haven't
been problems on the service side.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Oxford said it lost $507.6 million in the second
quarter, and that it would raise rates about 9 percent for
employers and cut some reimbursement to doctors, many of whom are
already angry about Oxford's recent cuts and lags in payment. The
stock price, which had plunged 90 percent since last October when
the company's problems became known, rose 68.75 cents Tuesday to
$7.25. State regulators have told Oxford to provide better
financial information and to take larger reserves to meet its
capital requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But these problems do not directly affect the individuals
insured, so many companies are loath to tell their employees that
the plan is being snatched from them and that they may have to
change one or more of their doctors. Other companies want to avoid
the tremendous administrative work involved in changing carriers,
especially if a new insurer is perceived to be inferior by its
users.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. is continuing to negotiate with Oxford, as
is Columbia University. A spokeswoman at Gannett Inc. said the
company planned to offer Oxford again in 1999. American Express,
Bell Atlantic and Citibank all said they were holding on to the
plan for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of inertia in the system because change has its
own costs,'' said Rich Ostuw, a global health-care practice
director for Watson Wyatt, an insurance broker in Stamford, Conn.
``There is going through the process, communicating with employees
and doing the paper work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our clients are not delighted with any service they
are getting from any of their health care providers,'' Ostuw added.
``So they shouldn't say they will jump from one because things are
less-than-perfect only to find they've gone to someone else not
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some employers, especially those with few employees,
have decided not to renew Oxford contracts for 1999. Most brokers
said they have seen pockets of defection, and at least two Oxford
competitors, Aetna US Health Care and Anthem Health &AMP; Life
Insurance of New York, said that they had gotten small chunks of
business from Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of new clients, 25 percent are coming from Oxford plans,''
said Carmine Morano, president of Anthem, adding that they were
mostly small employers. An Aetna spokeswoman said that since
January, the company had picked up 40,000 new members from Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Between the first and second quarters of this year, Oxford's
total membership dropped 4.3 percent, and although company
executives said that most of that was because Oxford dropped
Medicaid patients in Connecticut, they expect to lose some
commercial business in 1999 as a result of rate increases, although
they declined to say how much.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, brokers find many new clients are reluctant
to sign on with Oxford. ``Although Oxford was competitively priced,
new prospects were reluctant to take it,'' said Steven Spiro,
president of Sprio Risk Management, a broker in Valley Stream, N.Y.
``So in that sense I would say their problems are affecting new
sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts noted that a reduction in Oxford's highly regarded
services could send client companies elsewhere. ``Better clients
are more mobile and less rate sensitive,'' said Bradley Hamburger,
vice president of Halland Cos. LLC, an insurance broker in Jericho,
N.Y. ``If Oxford's service is not as good, that is going to affect
happiness and morale of employees,'' he added, so then clients
might change carriers, ``especially businessmen of closely held
companies that read about the financial problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
