<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-REACT-     08-11 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT DECISION ON BARNICLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe's decision Tuesday to rescind its demand for
Mike Barnicle's resignation stirred emotions like a tough column on
a raw topic: Some hated it. Some cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, peppered at a noontime staff meeting like a defendant
under cross-examination, was alternately contrite and pugnacious as
he apologized for sloppiness and laziness.
</P>
<P>
   And the reaction to the Globe's unusual decision not to follow
its demand for his resignation with his dismissal, also drew
sharply contrasting reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the newspaper, many staffers complained about what they
called the leniency of Barnicle's punishment. Outside, some
journalism experts credited Globe editors for what they called the
courage to absorb criticism in reaching a sanction that more
properly fits the swashbuckling columnist's crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire the Globe for reaching an extraordinarily tough
decision but it was the right decision,'' said Marvin Kalb,
director of the Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and
Public Policy at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barnicle did nothing evil, though he did do something quite
foolish and rushed. I think he's learned a lesson. I think he'll be
a better columnist for this experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalb predicted _ correctly _ that the paper would be criticized
for ``playing favorites'' in keeping Barnicle while asking for, and
getting, the resignation of his former colleague on the Globe's
Metro page, Patricia Smith, who in June admitted she wove
fabrications into her column.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very disappointing and embarrassing for the Boston Globe
and the city that the Globe choked and buckled beneath the pressure
to extend their perverse understanding of affirmative action to a
white male reporter who plagiarized and lied by any other name,''
said the Rev. Eugene F. Rivers III, the co-founder of the Boston
Ten Point Coalition. ``The Globe's decision to give him a two-month
slap on the wrist might as well have put Mike Barnicle in as
publisher and editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Barnicle's credit, he effectively mobilized his white
resistance forces to intimidate very well-meaning white liberals
who choked and caved in. The leadership at the Globe really needs
to engage in some serious soul-searching with regards to what is
clearly a lack of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   While Globe editors urged the staff to put the embarrassing
episode behind it, Barnicle's escape from the brink of dismissal _
in what one reporter labeled the journalistic Houdini act _
dominated newsroom discussion all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a feeling in the newsroom that the punishment
is too light,'' said Judith Gaines, who joined the newspaper staff
in 1988. ``Some reporters still think Barnicle should have been
fired. Others think something in the range of three-to-six months'
suspension would have been more appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Alisa Valdes-Rodriguez, a feature writer and a member of the
staff for four years, said the decision means that a newspaper in
the business of telling the truth has learned the fine art of
evasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will beat around the bush here, but the fact, to me,
are obvious. I think Barnicle was not fired because it would have
been too expensive in terms of advertising. He was not fired
because it would have cost us subscriptions. As much as people
believed Pat Smith was given a job because of the color of her
skin, I believe that Mike Barnicle was allowed to keep his job
because of the color of his skin. A lot of us believe this. Not
many of us are stupid enough to say it in print. I am one of the
few who puts my integrity above my paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes-Rodriguez flatly called the Globe a racist institution
that pays ``lip service to diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cost to all of this that the paper seems to have
not considered,'' she said. ``There are many of us here who take
this very personally. There are many of us here who know that if it
had been us causing lawsuits ... or just generally screwing up in
the paper, we would not have made it. We are generally darker than
Mike, or we have Spanish surnames, or our families come from Haiti
or Vietnam, or we are female. Not only would we not have made it,
we would have been held up as fine examples of why affirmative
action is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the National Association of Black Journalists
criticized the Globe's decision, saying: ``The Globe was correct in
quickly and firmly insisting on Patricia Smith's resignation, but
by making excuses to accommodate Mike Barnicle, their action gives
rise to accusations of a double standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the right choice _ I'm delighted with the
decision,'' said Paul Szep, editorial page cartoonist at the Globe
for 31 years and a friend of Barnicle's. ``Everyone came out a
winner. It was handled with dignity and aplomb. It would have been
just so bad to lose Barnicle. The paper would have been the worse
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Barnicle for 25 years. He he has put his heart and
soul into the newspaper, part of the fiber of it. An institution.
You just don't throw that over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Steele, director of the ethics program at the Poynter
Institute in St. Petersburg, Fla., said if the newspaper concluded
that Barnicle's offense was a one-time foul-up due to laziness, it
should be credited for rethinking a tough decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it became the classic between a rock and a hard place
scenario,'' said Steele. ``You have a highly popular columnist who
is fighting the penalty. You have an editor who is standing by what
he thinks is a principled decision. I think it is true that the
decision to ask for Barnicle's resignation was made more quickly
than it needed to be. With the value of hindsight, this was a case
that would have benefitted from further conversations between all
parties involved before a decision was made on the nature of the
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Smith at her home were not successsful. Asked
her reaction to the Globe's decision Tuesday, she told WCVB-TV,
Channel 5 in Boston, ``Very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Diego Ribadeneira, a 12-year veteran at the Globe, said the
details of Smith and Barnicle's problems are different. ``But I
also believe Barnicle was treated uniquely,'' he said. ``I'm not
sure the outcome would have been the same if anyone else here
behaved in the same way. I also believe the Globe needs to
vigorously investigate and disseminate any past allegations
involving Barnicle's work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeffrey Brown, chairman of the Boston Ten Point
Coalition, said Barnicle's two-month suspension ``forces people
reconsider the reality of a double standard, and I can't help but
think, what if it was (Globe columnist) Robert Jordan who did this
thing with the jokes? What would have happened to him? How would
this have been spun? You just can't help but wonder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
