<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-NYT     08-11 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMASON TELLS GRAND JURY ABOUT HIS HELP TO CLINTON AFTER SCANDAL
BROKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-HILLARY) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For 90 minutes Tuesday, Harry Thomason, a
television producer and friend of the Clintons, testified here
before the grand jury about how he helped the president navigate
the first chaotic days of the Monica Lewinsky crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the courthouse, Thomason told reporters that
prosecutors for Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr had asked him to
describe the advice he had given to the president in January, after
moving into the White House to help with damage control. At that
time, Thomason had urged Clinton to issue a forceful denial that he
had had a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, the 25-year-old
former White House intern. She testified last week that she had had
a sexual relationship with the president, said a lawyer familiar
with her account.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason is back in town this week to help the president prepare
for his grand jury testimony Monday, which is to be transmitted by
closed-circuit television from the White House to the federal
courthouse. Prosecutors might have been trying to send Thomason an
ominous message _ that they might summon him to the courthouse
again, to describe any new advice he dispenses to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Thomason was as ebullient as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed the president was telling the truth,''
Thomason said with a smile. ``I thought the grand jurors were nice,
the prosecutors were courteous. It was actually a good morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article last month in The New Yorker, Thomason was
portrayed as the stage manager of Clinton's defiant denial Jan. 26,
in the Roosevelt Room of the White House. ``I did not have sexual
relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky,'' the president said
then. ``I never told anybody to lie _ not a single time, never.
These allegations are false. And I need to go back to work for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement remains Clinton's most complete remarks on the
subject that has consumed Washington for nearly seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason's own words in The New Yorker may have led to the
subpoena that summoned him to appear before Starr's grand jury.
Thomason told The New Yorker that he encouraged Clinton to offer an
emphatic denial, remarking that the president added the phrase,
``that woman,'' because he had momentarily forgotten Ms. Lewinsky's
name.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomason may prove to have limited usefulness to
prosecutors. He told the Associated Press that the president had
told him ``nothing'' about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason also said that the prosecutors asked him to describe
his activities after he had moved into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them in general I was reading articles and watching all
the news shows so we would know what people were talking about,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason has produced and directed several successful television
series, including ``Designing Women'' and ``Evening Shade,'' both
of which were set in the South. Thomason and his wife, Linda
Bloodworth-Thomason, co-produced the short campaign film ``The Man
from Hope,'' which depicted Clinton's life for his first
presidential campaign in 1992. They also produced a 12-minute film
about Clinton's first term which was shown at the 1996 Democratic
national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors appear to be searching for a clearer sense of the
advice given to Clinton in the days after Starr's inquiry of the
Lewinsky matter first became public. They are also hunting for what
Clinton may have confided to his closest legal and political
advisers. A federal appeals court last week rejected the
president's bid to block the testimony of White House lawyers on
the grounds of attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy White House counsel Cheryl Mills testified for several
hours this afternoon. Asked if she would return for further
testimony, Ms. Mills told reporters, ``Not if I can help it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several unidentified Secret Service personnel also testified
Tuesday. At least 14 uniformed officers and agents have testified
before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Just one day after the appeals court ruling, the grand jury
heard from Lanny Breuer, a White House lawyer who refused to answer
some questions on executive-privilege grounds. Harold Ickes, a
former deputy chief of staff and frequent political adviser to
Clinton this year, also testified late last week.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known Tuesday whether Starr's prosecutors had also
subpoenaed White House counsel Charles Ruff. In the next several
weeks, deputy White House counsel Bruce Lindsey, a close friend of
the president, is also expected to testify. Lindsey is now
recovering from back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, David Kendall, the president's personal lawyer, spent
nearly five hours at the courthouse Tuesday, presumably to view
Clinton's Jan. 17 deposition in the sexual misconduct lawsuit by
Paula Jones. Under oath, Clinton denied that he had had a sexual
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, U.S. District Court Judge Susan Webber Wright gave
Kendall permission to view the videotape, saying that Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson, who presides over the grand jury proceedings,
would control Kendall's viewing of the videotape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
