<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HILLARY-ART-N     08-11 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HILLARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY SCANDAL DRIVES UP MRS. CLINTON'S POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., N.Y., N.M.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic on Mrs.
Clinton's rising popularity is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton's bus slowly chugged
along the roads in upstate New York recently on a preservation
tour, she glanced out the window at a woman holding aloft a
cardboard sign. It said: ``You Go Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Mrs. Clinton has been trying to do just that,
and in some respects, is succeeding, even as her husband prepares
to face a grand jury Monday about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's approval ratings across the country are higher
than ever. Instead of sequestering herself at the White House, away
from the klieg lights and the inevitable questions about Ms.
Lewinsky, Mrs. Clinton has crowded her schedule with things to do
and people to see.
</P>
<P>
   Two weekends ago, in the Hamptons on New York's Long Island,
Mrs. Clinton dropped in on the glitterati, firing up a crowd of
1,000 people who whooped and hollered as she introduced her
husband. And she has helped several Democratic candidates in
fund-raising stops, raising $150,000 in Philadelphia for one
candidate two weeks ago. Soon, she will be traveling to Russia,
Ireland, Chile and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, Mrs. Clinton has chosen to stir things up by
dishing out a few select words about the Lewinsky matter, in which
a grand jury is investigating whether Clinton lied when he denied a
sexual relationship with the former intern and tried to cover it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in an interview published in the Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette, Mrs. Clinton said ``prejudice'' against the state
of Arkansas is what is driving the attacks on her husband.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Mrs. Clinton blamed a ``right-wing conspiracy,''
spearheaded by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and his allies,
for trying to ruin her husband's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of this is prejudice against our state,'' Mrs.
Clinton told the newspaper. ``They wouldn't do this if we were from
some other state.''
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks puzzled and angered some in Arkansas. ``I know she
must be going through a lot of stress, but I don't think anyone in
Arkansas believes this is occurring because of prejudice towards
the state,'' said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark. ``It's
inexplicable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark., was less charitable. ``It is sad and
unfortunate that Arkansas is depicted by the first lady as a
backward state, worthy of ridicule and prejudice,'' he said. ``It
would be much better if the first lady would make a mature and
responsible assessment of the situation and not blame us Arkansans
for their troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   And Republican pollster Ed Goeas couldn't resist quipping,
``First it was the right-wing conspiracy, now it's the chicken-wing
conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one disputes that Mrs. Clinton has swayed a number of
Americans, especially women, over to her side in the past eight
months. According to a CBS News poll conducted July 19 through July
21, 50 percent of those surveyed said they held a favorable opinion
of Mrs. Clinton and 26 percent say they did not. Historically, only
35 percent or so of Americans have expressed support for the first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   Some consultants say that after six years, people are finally
starting to take a shine to Mrs. Clinton and her reconfigured role
as first lady. Others point directly at Ms. Lewinsky, and say that
the public sympathizes with Mrs. Clinton and that has softened her
in a way that speeches and press releases never could.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the best person they can put out there,'' said Goeas.
``She's kind of standing by her man, and has been determined to do
exactly that. Some people feel sorry for her. Some respect her.
It's probably a combination of both.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Democratic pollster Mark Mellman, ``I think that the first
lady has handled this whole set of attacks with grace and
intelligence and wit, and people admire that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Mrs. Clinton's legal background, and her
own experience as a subpoenaed witness before Starr's Whitewater
grand jury, make her one of the president's most valuable
strategists.
</P>
<P>
   But the private Mrs. Clinton has remained steadfastly elusive.
How does she broach the subject of Ms. Lewinswky with her husband?
Do they talk about the infamous dress? Does she advise him on what
to say?
</P>
<P>
   The answers are all subject to speculation, but little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at best this is an extremely difficult time and I
think the president and Mrs. Clinton are probably communicating, in
many ways through their lawyer, David Kendall,'' said former White
House aide DeeDee Myers on the news program, ``This Week With Sam
and Cokie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these issues are just too difficult for them to
discuss with each other in many respects.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``These are the kind of issues that I think husbands
and wives don't often sit down and sort of have frank conversations
about.''
</P>
<P>
   During a fund-raiser at the home of Alec Baldwin and Kim
Basinger in the Hamptons in early August, an ebullient Mrs. Clinton
got the crowd riled up for her husband, then gave him a hug before
he took the microphone and delivered five minutes of subdued
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's staff said she thrives on her public appearances,
especially when she is talking about children's issues, health care
and the encroaching millennium. ``She believes that if you spend
one day pacing around the White House, that's one day you are not
doing something to advance the agenda of the president,'' said Neel
Lattimore, Mrs. Clinton's former press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, she approached the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee and offered to attend a number of fund-raisers
for House and Senate candidates, many of them challengers facing
uphill climbs. She has attended six fund-raisers since June and is
expected to attend several more over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Sallick, the communications director for the committee, said
that after the president, she is the party's biggest draw. Just
before a special election in Albuquerque, N.M. Mrs. Clinton drew
2,000 at a college gym on 48 hours notice, Sallick said. He also
said she has helped spur women who do not typically turn out to
show up and write checks. Recently, Mrs. Clinton has raised
$100,000 in a Cincinnati race and $150,000 at an Indiana
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides the president, who tends to do more fundraising for
the national party committee, she is in the most demand of any
other Democratic official,'' Sallick said.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Spottswood, a candidate for a House race in Wisconsin,
said Mrs. Clinton visited her in Milwaukee, attending a small
reception that netted her $60,000. Ms. Spottswood said Mrs.
Clinton's wifely travails have certainly played a hand in her
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There but for the grace of God,'' Ms. Spottswood said. ``Any
woman could find herself with unwelcomed rumors. She has dealt with
it with so much dignity and grace, it has resonated with people.``
</P>
</TEXT>
