<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE BACKTRACKS, SUSPENDS COLUMNIST FOR TWO MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six days after Boston Globe editor Matthew V. Storin
asked for Mike Barnicle's resignation, he acknowledged acting too
``hastily'' and instead suspended the columnist for two months
without pay.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning turnaround Tuesday, including an apology by
Barnicle at a packed noontime meeting of the Globe staff, capped a
week of controversy over the fate of the popular 25-year Metro
columnist. It followed three meetings between Barnicle and top
Globe officials in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Given the June 18 resignation of black columnist Patricia Smith
after admitting fabricating some characters and quotes in four 1998
columns, the Barnicle suspension may prove divisive inside and
outside the Globe. Storin said Tuesday that ``these two offenses
were much different'' but noted that some staffers &UR;  &LR; are ``still
uncomfortable with whether there are double standards for ... Mike
Barnicle and Patricia Smith.'' Concerned minority Globe staffers
reportedly slated a meeting Tuesday night to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnicle controversy began when his Aug. 2 column was found
to contain eight jokes similar to those in comedian George Carlin's
1997 book, ``BrainDroppings.'' Initially last Wednesday, Storin _
accepting Barnicle's explanation that he had never read the book
and got the jokes from friends _ suspended him for a month without
pay. But later that day, WCVB-Ch.5 in Boston ran a clip of Barnicle
endorsing the book on the June 22 edition of ``Chronicle.'' At that
point, Storin, on vacation in Italy, asked for Barnicle's
resignation. Barnicle responded that he would not resign.
</P>
<P>
   At the emotional and sometimes contentious staff meeting
attended by Barnicle, Storin explained his change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though there were clear offenses here and violations of
professional standards in my opinion,'' he said, ``I did not feel
that if it came to a question of termination for Mike Barnicle that
the punishment fit the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon press conference Tuesday, Storin noted that
``perhaps too hastily I called for Mike's resignation,'' adding
that Barnicle ``convinced me he didn't remember having done that
tape for Channel 5.''
</P>
<P>
   While admitting errors Tuesday, Barnicle, 54, said, ``I did not
plagiarize anything. Nor did I lie to the publisher or the
editor.'' He added that ``I did not remember doing the TV tape''
about ``BrainDroppings'' since it was filmed several months ago and
was part of a segment on 17 books that lasted less than three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I think the decision that's been reached is the right
decision,'' Globe publisher Benjamin B. Taylor said Tuesday. ``It
was made by the editor of the paper. I fully support it and him.''
The Globe's owner, The New York Times Company, issued a statement
saying it ``has a policy that all of its media properties have
editorial independence and autonomy. In keeping with our policy, we
support the Globe's right to make its own decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Globe staff Tuesday, Barnicle confessed to
having created the current furor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here today because of my sloppiness,'' he said. ``We're
here today because I have caused embarrassment to the institution,
to the paper. ... I think what's happened is terrible for a lot of
things, for a lot of people, but none more so than the institution
where we all work _ The Boston Globe. ... I apologize to each and
every one of you collectively. And if I could, I would apologize to
each and every one of you individually for having put the place
where you work ... into such a tough light.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the conditions of the suspension agreement,
Barnicle will face closer supervision of his columns and will
reduce the amount of his outside work because, in Storin's words,
``we need a better bang for the buck.'' Barnicle, who also works
for Channel 5, PBS's ``NewsHour with Jim Lehrer,'' and MSNBC,
declined to say Tuesday what outside work he would curtail. He did
say that he would continue at ``Chronicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin also cited Barnicle's distant relationship with many of
his Globe colleagues as a problem that needed to be tackled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became clear to me ... how faulty, how unsatisfactory
Mike's relationship was with his editors, including myself,'' he
said. ``And there was no way that I thought we could go forward
unless that could be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the problems in that relationship were evident at
Tuesday's staff meeting when Barnicle faced a barrage of tough
questions on everything from his estrangement from his colleagues
to the number of times his work has been subject of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's Globe career came under the public microscope after
the Patricia Smith case unraveled in late June. In explaining why
he had given Smith a second chance despite evidence she had
fabricated some 1995 columns, Storin said at the time that he was
concerned that the paper had not ``addressed ... head on''
lingering doubts about Barnicle's work.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Smith resigned, Harvard Law professor Alan
Dershowitz accused the Globe of following a double standard for not
similarly disciplining Barnicle for a 1990 column that Dershowitz
said contained a fabricated quote attributed to him.
</P>
<P>
   (Last week, The New York Times reported that the Globe had paid
Dershowitz a $75,000 settlement in that case, an assertion the
Globe and Dershowitz have declined to confirm. Tuesday, in response
to questions about other Barnicle-related litigation, assistant to
the publisher Alfred S. Larkin Jr. confirmed that the paper paid
$40,000 after losing a suit in which a gas station proprietor said
he'd never made a racist statement Barnicle attributed to him in a
1973 column. Larkin also said there was some type of settlement,
perhaps an apology, after a 1990 column in which a tenant made
unrefuted charges against a Lynn, Mass. landlord.)
</P>
<P>
   Several days after Smith's resignation, the Globe reported that
it had reviewed 364 Barnicle columns dating back to January 1996
and gave them a clean bill of health. But that did not put the
issue to rest. In its August issue, Boston magazine resurrected
charges initially made in 1991 against Barnicle about two columns
that the magazine said featured characters who could not be tracked
down. It also brought up two old columns that reportedly elicited
complaints from the late Chicago columnist Mike Royko that Barnicle
had borrowed from his work.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's staff meeting, Barnicle angrily dismissed these
allegations as ``a classic case of where the media takes things and
perception becomes reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On each occasion, whenever any questions arose at the
particular time it arose, I was confronted by an editor at this
paper and gave that specific editor answers to any questions the
editor may have had about the columns in question,'' he said. ``I
do not put lies in the paper, I do not make things up.''
</P>
<P>
   He also characterized his accuser Dershowitz as ``a very smart,
very important, very influential, very obnoxious human being.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his case to Globe staffers Tuesday, Barnicle explained
that ``this is the only place I have ever really worked as an
adult. This is the only place I have ever wanted to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But given the tenor of some questions at both the staff meeting
and press conference, it is clear the the specter of a double
standard in the treatment of Smith and Barnicle looms as a
significant issue. Taylor and Storin both tried to address that
concern Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we tried to look ... at the two cases as
separate and distinct cases,'' said Taylor at the press conference.
``The two cases were different.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin also said that ``these two offenses were much
different,'' explaining that Smith was caught fabricating after she
had been warned. ``First of all, I gave Patricia a second chance
... Clearly Mike now has had his second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And whatever the fallout from Tuesday's events, the principals
in the Barnicle episode acknowledged just how difficult an ordeal
this has been.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was upbeat about the Globe's credibility with its
readers, Storin told the staff that ``This is a period of great
vulnerability for this paper. You can imagine ... that it was like
a nightmare to have this thing happen at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I find this at one level to be deeply painful,'' added
Barnicle. ``I don't think I'll write about this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8996 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZEMLINSKY-MUSIC-$ADV6     08-11 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEMLINSKY-MUSIC-$ADV6-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE CASE FOR AN ODD AND ANXIOUS ROMANTIC  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His time will come,'' Arnold Schoenberg confidently asserted in
a memorial tribute to his mentor, colleague and brother-in-law,
Alexander von Zemlinsky.
</P>
<P>
   As that statement implied, by the time of Zemlinsky's death, in
Larchmont, N.Y., in 1942, his music had been almost totally
forgotten, a victim of the derailing of Austro-German musical
culture under the Nazis, of changes in taste that had made his
luscious, lustrous hyper-Romanticism seem old-fashioned, and
probably also of his self-doubts, which kept him from doing much on
his own behalf, even though he held important posts as a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   But Schoenberg's prophecy has been borne out during the last
three decades, and not just once but at least three times. The
centenary of Zemlinsky's birth, in 1971, prompted the first flurry
of revivals.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s his operas were brought back to life, and there
were several important recordings. Now James Conlon is pressing the
case again, with five Zemlinsky albums recorded under his baton for
EMI Classics in Cologne, Germany, and more to come. Two of the
operas are represented in this first batch, ``Eine Florentinische
Tragodie'' and ``Der Zwerg'' (``The Dwarf''), together with
collections of orchestral pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced,'' Conlon writes of Zemlinsky, ``that in
several years a wide and enthusiastic public will know and love his
works.'' That conviction leaps out of these performances, which are
strong, sumptuous and finely detailed. Conlon also allows one to
make a good guess as to why this music still needs zealous
advocacy: though all of it is beautifully made, only rarely did
Zemlinsky push himself above the giants he admired _ Brahms,
Wagner, Mahler, Strauss _ and produce something that while
belonging in the same Romantic sunset as the rest of his output, is
utterly his own.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, Zemlinsky is a head above other late Romantics
whose claims have recently been advanced, like Franz Schreker and
Hans Pfitzner. And at its best, his music can stand comparison with
anything Richard Strauss wrote between the wars.
</P>
<P>
   But that best is restricted to just a few works, which certainly
include ``Der Zwerg,'' along with the Second String Quartet and
some of the songs: all works composed during the period from 1914
to a few years after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser pieces have their pleasures, which Conlon's
recordings duly notice. Of the two symphonies (EMI 5 56473 2; CD),
both dating from the 1890s, the Second has a scherzo with an
unforgettable theme, robust and savage. Zemlinsky was in thrall to
Brahms at this time, but he upped the Gypsy side of Brahms, and his
music began to hint at his family origins among the Jews of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In another work of the same decade, the cantata ``Spring's
Burial'' (5 56474 2; CD), echoes of Brahms' Requiem are combined
with Wagnerism. This disk also includes ``Dance Poem,'' drawn from
a ballet score on which Zemlinsky worked in the first four years of
the new century, and a suite of incidental music for Shakespeare's
``Cymbeline.''
</P>
<P>
   It was characteristic of Zemlinsky's luckless career as a
composer that the ballet, ``The Triumph of Time,'' was never
produced and that the ``Cymbeline'' production, scheduled for the
1915-16 season, was canceled because of the war. Not until 1996 was
the ``Cymbeline'' music performed.
</P>
<P>
   Another discouragement came in 1905, when the symphonic poem
``Die Seejungfrau'' (``The Mermaid'') was first performed and
poorly received. Zemlinsky withdrew the score, which was not heard
again until 1984, when Riccardo Chailly performed and recorded it
for Decca/London.
</P>
<P>
   Conlon's version (5 55515 2; CD) is fine, but at almost 45
minutes, the piece is long for its material. Nor is its interest
sufficiently enhanced by its juicy autobiographical subtext,
according to which the mermaid of Hans Christian Andersen's story
represents both Alma Schindler, who had recently abandoned
Zemlinsky for Mahler, and the composer, who in human society felt
like a fish out of water. The piece is coupled with the Sinfonietta
of 1934, which is fluent and even vigorous yet impersonal.
</P>
<P>
   The period of Zemlinsky's greatness had come earlier and was
defined partly by cultural shifts happening around the time of
World War I, partly by his discovering subjects that allowed him to
give voice to his keenest anxieties. Those anxieties had to do with
his body.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Schindler recorded in her diary before the beginning of
their affair that he ``cuts the most comical figure imaginable _ a
caricature, chinless and short, with bulging eyes.'' This
assessment may have been ungenerous, but it was evidently shared by
Zemlinsky, who found opportunities for poignant self-identification
in the story of ``Der Zwerg.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for the wider cultural context, there, too, he found himself
an oddity, a dodo among the modernist swallows. He conducted the
first performance of Schoenberg's atonal opera ``Erwartung'' and
admired the work of Berg and Webern. But he could not go that way
himself. If, in the light of what his Viennese friends were doing,
tonality had to be seen as only a part of musical reality, it was a
partial reality he needed. If atonality was now in some sense the
truth, he preferred illusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Der Zwerg,'' again, acknowledges this fact; the necessity of
illusion is its subject. The Dwarf believes himself to be handsome
and a fit swain for the Spanish princess to whom he has been given
as a birthday present. When he rips a curtain, looks into a mirror
and discovers the truth about himself, he dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eine Florentinische Tragodie,'' too, unfolds largely in an
atmosphere of pretense. A merchant returns home to find his wife in
the arms of her princely lover, and instead of protesting at once,
he plays out a sadistic scene in which he offers his wares to the
intruder, expressing his jealousy only by implication until the
moment finally comes to take his vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Both operas were based on writings by Oscar Wilde _ the tale
``The Birthday of the Infanta'' and the incomplete play ``A
Florentine Tragedy'' _ and they owe something, in points of musical
style and dramatic cruelty, to an earlier Wilde opera, Strauss's
``Salome.''
</P>
<P>
   But their unsettling malaise is Zemlinsky's own. In ``Eine
Florentinische Tragodie'' everyone in the theater knows that the
ostensible action is a charade. In ``Der Zwerg'' everyone knows
this except the Dwarf, and his innocent ignorance seems to have
stirred the composer as much as it must stir anyone who listens to
the piece.
</P>
<P>
   The score of ``Der Zwerg,'' completed in 1921, is rich, colorful
and fascinating. It seems to combine Strauss' gift for musical
illustration with Ravel's love of the strange and fantastical, and
it makes all of Zemlinsky's other orchestral works sound like rough
drafts. Its central character, too, is a brilliant and moving
creation.
</P>
<P>
   At first the Dwarf is seen largely from outside, as the
orchestra portrays his awkward movements. But soon the opera
accepts him at his own valuation. The crooked slips and
syncopations give way, and he opens out into a heroic vocal style:
having been introduced as a Nibelung gnome, he becomes a Siegfried.
</P>
<P>
   In the new recording (5 56208 2; two CDs), David Kuebler
achieves this dual personality magnificently. He has a character
tenor's pathos and keen sense of the text, yet he can also move
decisively into a radiant high register.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite him, Soile Isokoski has the porcelain brittleness and
artificiality needed for the Infanta. The two of them work
frighteningly well together in the disturbing scene where the
Infanta plays with the Dwarf's emotions, encouraging his love for
her. There are also excellent contributions from Iride Martinez as
the Infanta's warmhearted maid and from Andrew Collis as the
chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Kuebler is to be heard again as the prince in the recording of
``Eine Florentinische Tragodie'' (5 56472 2; CD), with Deborah
Voigt and Donnie Ray Albert completing the triangle. But as good as
this performance is, ``Der Zwerg'' is something else.
</P>
<P>
   A Hamburg production toured widely in the 1980s and was
recorded, but it somehow failed to give the work the boost it
needed. The new recording, which makes good the cuts and
alterations of the Hamburg version, should do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, the opera is being staged in Paris, with Conlon
conducting and Kuebler again in the title role; an American
production cannot be far behind. Then Zemlinsky's time will have
come for good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
