<SLUG> BC-AMGEN-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT CLAIMS AMGEN FALSIFIED EARNINGS PREDICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. -- A San Diego law firm has filed a
class-action suit against Amgen Inc., claiming the biotech giant
mislead investors last year about the company's earnings prospects.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego-based Milberg Weiss said in its filing that between
January and August 1997 Amgen officials issued false statements
about future sales potential for the company's two lead drugs and
about the impact a settlement with competitor Johnson &AMP; Johnson
would have on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the suit said top Amgen executives benefited by selling
shares in the company at a time when the stock was trading at
artificially inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen officials declined to comment on the case, and attorney
Jan Adler at Milberg Weiss could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   While Amgen shares did fall $2.125 Tuesday, or nearly 2.9
percent, to close at $69.6875, analysts attributed the drop to the
stock market's overall decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't pay these things (lawsuits) that much
attention because they're usually a lot of hot air,'' said analyst
Caroline Copithorne at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The suit specifically says unjustifiably positive statements
issued by Amgen boosted the company's share price from $52.50 in
mid-January 1997 to $69.375 in May 1997 and kept it trading at more
than $58 per share through August. During the same period, Milberg
Weiss claims, top Amgen officials sold $32.4 million worth of their
own personal holdings in the company.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also claims that by keeping the stock price above $58 a
share, Amgen avoided paying $158 million on speculative option
contracts on Amgen stock. The options would have been triggered if
the share price stood below $58 when the contracts expired in
August 1997, the suits states.
</P>
<P>
   When eventual sales did not match what the suit claimed Amgen
officials implied, the stock price fell to the $40 range.
</P>
<P>
   Copithorne said that proving Amgen fraudulently promoted the
company will be difficult and speculated that Milberg Weiss will
seek an out-of-court settlement with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything blatantly fraudulent, or the intentional manipulating
of results, those are cases where you can get an enormous
windfall,'' she said. ``This case is all about nuances and
technicalities involved with the stock. While (the price) went
down, for biotech companies the drop wasn't all that extreme. When
you see stock prices drop 75 percent because of failed products,
those are cases where there's more of a splash and more potential
for some huge payoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
