<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-POET-LAUREATE-ART-     08-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-POET-LAUREATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWRENCE FERLINGHETTI: CITY'S MOST FAMOUS POET GETS IT IN WRITING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a voice of the Beat Generation, poet,
publisher and book seller, Lawrence Ferlinghetti has always held a
prominent place in San Francisco's cultural community. Tuesday, he
was elevated to a loftier status.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown, recognizing the need for ``great cities of
the world'' to ``place great stock in their great artists,'' named
Ferlinghetti the city's first poet laureate, a post that requires
him only to give a speech now and then in his yearlong term and
promote poetry around the city.
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly much of a challenge for a poet of international
renown. But the role is an unusual one for Ferlinghetti, 79, whose
devout suspicion of government remains a theme in much of his work.
He has always believed strongly that artists should resist
government grants because the money ties them to bodies of power
that cannot be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the new job, which pays him $5,000, was hardly lost
on Ferlinghetti as he thanked Brown, a Democrat he apparently
trusts: Ferlinghetti said he voted for Brown for mayor in 1995 even
though he is registered to vote with California's Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Plato's republic, poets were considered subversive, a
danger to the republic,'' Ferlinghetti said, standing beside the
mayor. ``I kind of relish that role. So I see my present role as a
gadfly, to use as a soapbox to promote my various ideas and
obsessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has a poet laureate _ Robert Pinsky _ and so
do most states. But not many cities have them, in part because
poetry is an acquired taste and the more accomplished poets are
grabbed by states. New York City does not have a poet laureate but
two of its boroughs do, Brooklyn (Dennis Nurkse) and Queens
(Stephen Stepanchev).
</P>
<P>
   Brown offered no explanation for why it took San Francisco so
long to anoint one, other than to say it was high time.
</P>
<P>
   For Ferlinghetti, the appointment comes at a time when his most
influential work is probably behind him. A native of Yonkers who
moved to San Francisco after serving in World War II, he joined
other emerging writers, like Kenneth Rexroth, Allen Ginsberg and
Jack Kerouac, to give shape to youthful feelings of distrust and
disenfranchisement.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, they became the voices of the Beat Generation, its
adherents, Beatniks, and in 1953, when Ferlinghetti opened City
Lights, a book store in San Francisco's North Beach neighborhood,
they had a place to gather. They do still.
</P>
<P>
   Selling only paperback books at first to satisfy Ferlinghetti's
enduring notion that art should be affordable to all, the store has
expanded over the years to include hardbacks and mainstream books
that are sold in national chain stores. But it retains its original
charm, with an entire room of poetry books, another of hard-to-find
authors and open areas for poetry readings.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Peters, a onetime librarian at the Library of Congress who
is co-owner of City Lights, said many customers still came just to
buy poetry.
</P>
<P>
   The passing years have done little to blunt Ferlinghetti's
energy. He continues to work in the book store, publish and write
poems. His latest poems are collected in a book issued last year.
He regards the book, ``A Far Rockaway of the Heart,'' as a
companion to an earlier collection, ``A Coney Island of the Mind,''
which was published in 1958 and became one of the most popular
collections of poems of the time.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed not entirely sure how to gauge the overall health
of poetry in modern America. What he hears most, he said, are
voices of the street, rap artists whose words he finds ``much more
violent, much more alienated than the Beats ever were.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beats shared similar feelings of isolation, he said, adding,
``These are most materialistic, militaristic, avaricious times
today. There is more of a need for Beat ideas, non-materialism,
spiritual values, being free as an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   As poet laureate, Ferlinghetti does not begin any official
duties until October. But he has a few ideas he would like to sell.
One is having the federal government designate North Beach a
historic district before the tourists and upscale shops obliterate
any reminders of the past.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to establish a poet-in-residence program.
</P>
<P>
   But he offered no details about how those goals might come
about. Nor did Brown. For now, though, Ferlinghetti did not seem
all that concerned about it. ``I was hoping this was just an
honorary position,'' he said, cracking a smile. ``I have so much
else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
