<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MACHINISTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING BEGINS SERIES OF COST-CUTTING MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the first of a series of cost-cutting measures, The
Boeing Co. has frozen all hiring in its commercial aircraft
division and ordered managers to get special permission before
granting travel requests or other ``non-essential'' items,
according to an internal company bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   The notice sent by Boeing Commercial Airplane Group President
Ron Woodard and obtained by the Post-Intelligencer Tuesday also
instructed managers to curtail spending on the ``low-hanging
fruit'': off-site meetings, non-essential office supplies,
periodical subscriptions, trips to seminars and non-crucial
computer hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given our profit margins, we simply cannot afford the `nice to
do' things,'' Woodard said in the bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   His cost-cutting program is a direct response to Boeing Chairman
Phil Condit's goal of obtaining a 7 percent net return on sales by
the year 2000 _ meaning Boeing would earn 7 cents on every dollar
of revenue, after taxes and other expenses are paid.
</P>
<P>
   Companywide, Boeing expects to earn about $1 billion this year,
less than 2 percent of projected sales.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve the overall 7 percent profit margin goal, earnings
from Boeing's commercial aircraft division and its defense and
space operations must be at least 11 percent, Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's commercial division is far from that now with earnings
from operations expected to be less than 1 percent this year. Next
year, the commercial division _ which accounts for about 60 percent
of the company's total revenues _ is predicting only a slight
improvement with a 2 to 4 percent profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us should find that an acceptable operating profit
margin and we must dedicate ourselves to doing better _ much
better,'' Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company is gaining ground on getting its airplane
production back to normal and now ``where we need to focus renewed
attention is on costs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that we've had a very difficult year,'' Woodard
said. ``Our production problems, combined with pricing pressures in
the marketplace, have led to poor financial performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also plans to reduce costs by cutting employment between
18,000 to 28,000 jobs by the end of next year through attrition and
layoffs. The company employs 238,000 people in 27 states.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have not yet said exactly how many job cuts
will occur or where and Woodard did not address employment in his
recent memo, but the reductions are expected to be spread
throughout the company.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the overall number are 12,000 previously announced
reductions from Boeing's commercial aircraft division, which has
headquarters in Renton and employs about 110,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, job cuts could come from further consolidation of
Boeing operations throughout the country, which the company expects
to announce tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, Boeing plans to announce whether it has decided to
establish a new 737 assembly line at its commercial aircraft
factory in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   While executives officially are saying no decision has yet been
made, people familiar with the announcement said the California 737
assembly plan already has been approved.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless Boeing officials will continue last-minute
negotiations Wednesday with the company's largest union, which
opposes sending assembly work to California.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for going along with Boeing's plan, the Machinists
union is seeking concessions from the company, according to people
familiar with the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
