<SLUG> BC-OXFORD-EARNINGS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OXFORD HEALTH POSTS BIG LOSS FOR 2ND QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla., N.Y.)  (Eds: See also OXFORD-REACT) 
(mk) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oxford Health Plans Inc., the popular health plan that has been
struggling for nearly a year to return to profitability, reported
Tuesday a loss of $507.6 million in the second quarter, reflecting
several large charges and continued operating losses.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, which was much greater than expected, was seen by
health-industry analysts as an attempt by the managed care company
to write off much of its problem businesses and past practices.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the company's actions as ``a line in the sand
separating Oxford's past and its future,'' Oxford's new chief
executive, Dr. Norman Payson, said that the company was already
raising premiums and cutting costs sharply to achieve its goal of
making money by the middle of next year.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Payson outline his strategy for turning around
Oxford, analysts and consultants said that the company seemed to be
clear about what steps it needed to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company knows exactly what it has to do,'' said Kenneth
Abramowitz, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein. ``There is no
rocket science here.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting there may prove a serious challenge, especially
since Oxford's goal of returning to profitability can only be
achieved if its membership does not fall sharply and reduce
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers may face steeper rate increases, based on their
individual costs, and decide to switch plans to save money.
Doctors, many of whom have stayed in Oxford's network despite their
difficulty in getting paid, could decide to abandon the plan if
their fees are cut too sharply. At the same time the company must
stem its sizable losses and it needs to be careful about making any
dramatic changes that could drive away its doctors or its members,
said Bob Braddick, a consultant with William Mercer in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Once the darling of consumers and investors alike, Oxford has
fallen badly out of favor. The stock, which sold for as much as $89
last summer, was brutally punished in October, when the company
first said that it had underestimated the cost of delivering care
after it fell months behind in paying its doctors and hospitals.
Oxford had become such a favorite with consumers because it
promised an affordable health plan that allowed them tremendous
freedom in picking a doctor. Shares of Oxford closed Tuesday at
$7.25, up 68.75 cents, but down 53 percent for the year so far.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Tuesday's reported loss was a result of nearly $300
million in unusual or one-time charges. Those charges included the
cost of consolidating some of its operations as well as its
decision to drop much of its Medicaid and Medicare business, the
government programs that it has said caused much of its losses.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would essentially drop all Medicare business
outside of New York and all of its Medicaid business, except where
it could shift some of the risk onto the hospitals providing the
care.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford will also drop much of its commercial business outside of
the New York area, leaving such markets as Illinois and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The charges also include the cost of adding $152 million to its
reserves at the request of the New York State Insurance Department.
The department requested the additions after a lengthy review of
Oxford's finances in which it determined that the company had
underestimated the medical claims it needed to pay over the next
year. ``We believe we are well reserved at this point,'' Payson
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Payson emphasized that the size of the loss did not
reflect the true state of its business, the company is still losing
money. By its own estimate, the company's cash flow losses are
roughly $85 million this quarter, and it said that it expected to
have another $100 million in losses over the next six months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even ignoring the special charges, Oxford's medical costs were
very high, eating up 95 cents of every dollar of premium Oxford
took in during the second quarter. ``They are still not a healthy
organization,'' said Braddick, the Mercer consultant. ``They have a
ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxford's goal is to bring its medical costs down to about 85
cents or so by increasing premiums by about 9 percent, cutting fees
to doctors and hospitals and pushing more people to stay within its
network.
</P>
<P>
   It also hoped to sharply reduce its hefty administrative costs
by some $200 million next year by using fewer consultants, having
fewer employees and undertaking other cost-saving measures.
</P>
<P>
   But keeping employers remains a serious challenge. While Oxford
says that most employers are deciding to stay with the company,
many are making that critical decision right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to have a difficult time retaining a lot of
their business,'' predicted Henry Moyer, a benefits consultant in
New York, who advises companies that frequently offer only one
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Membership is already down slightly from the first three months
of the year, even in the company's flagship Freedom plan product.
Overall, the company said that its membership had dropped from
about 2.1 million members at the end of March to 2 million at the
end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Oxford has managed to hold on to the vast majority of its
customers, most of whom still believe the company is a better
alternative than the competition. ``We continue to be the health
plan of choice,'' Payson argued.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Oxford can come up with a plan that still pleases
consumers and makes its shareholders money, it does not have the
luxury to try forever. If the company does not reduce its losses
quickly, it could run into the same kind of capital crunch that
caused it to seek a $710 million cash infusion from private
investors earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Payson said that the company had plenty of ``cushion'' and
should not need more capital before becoming profitable sometime
next year. ``We have sufficient firepower and time to complete our
turnaround plans,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT &LR;      08-11 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE YEN FALLS, MARKETS FEAR JAPANESE SAVERS WILL LOOK
ELSEWHERE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As the yen falls to new lows against the dollar,
ordinary investors are fleeing to other currencies, heightening
concern that a fundamental shift in sentiment is under way against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Among the factors mentioned by currency traders as immediate
causes of the yen's fall are the faltering stock market, doubts
about the new government's commitment to dealing with problems in
the banking sector and the possibility that China might devalue its
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns pushed the yen down to a rate of 147.63 to the
dollar in London trading early Tuesday, an eight-year low, and to
147.35 in New York later. The benchmark Nikkei index of 225 stocks
fell for a seventh consecutive trading day, closing down 219.40
points, or 1.4 percent, at 15,406.99. In Hong Kong, the main stock
index fell 3.6 percent, to 6,779.95. Most other Asian markets were
also lower.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest worry among currency traders is that the yen is
reaching a level where Japanese housewives, who control the family
purse strings and thus a vast pool of savings, are swapping their
yen for dollars, German marks and pounds sterling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the main worry for me,'' said Steven Barrow, a currency
strategist at Bear Stearns International in London. ``The key here
is what's happening to Japanese savings and the fear that ordinary
Japanese are looking to send their cash abroad in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   The yen's slow erosion over the last few months has contributed
to a surge in the government's already large surplus in the current
account, which measures the difference between income from foreign
sources and foreign obligations payable, excluding net capital
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Few have been paying attention, however, to the even larger
outflows from capital and investment accounts since last spring, a
strong indication that Japanese households are beginning to seek
higher returns and less volatility in other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow noted that while the current account surplus has been
running at one trillion to 1.5 trillion yen a month, according to
government figures issued in July, Japan's capital and investment
accounts are running deficits of 2 to 2.5 trillion yen a month,
reflecting a net outflow of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they're earning more foreign currency from trade, it
seems they're only too willing to see even greater sums flowing
back out to take advantage of higher yields elsewhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest factors in the decision last month by Moody's
Investors Service, the credit-rating agency, to put Japan's
triple-A rating on review for a possible downgrading was concern
that the household sector had joined the flight to other
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of particular concern is the potential for volatile portfolio
shifts into foreign currency assets by Japanese residents in the
post-Big Bang environment,'' Moody's said in its news release,
referring to sweeping financial reform measures that went into
effect on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   And traders worry that the government statistics fail to fully
capture the flight from yen to dollars or other currencies. A shift
of individual savings out of yen and into other currencies may not
show up in the government numbers because the money may never leave
the country. Instead, it may sit in a foreign currency account at
the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, Citibank, Sumitomo Bank and other
banks that offer such accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to get a read on how big that shift is, however,
since most banks refuse to disclose breakdowns of foreign-currency
deposit accounts and yen deposit accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese bank officials contend that April's financial reform
measures did not really enhance the ability of Japanese depositors
to shift their savings into dollars and other currencies, but they
do concede a marked uptick in demand for foreign-currency accounts
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Until this spring, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi was almost the
only Japanese bank to promote foreign-currency accounts
aggressively. Katsumi Tsuiji, a Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi spokesman,
said the demand for those accounts had accelerated since April,
although the increase was somewhat modest because the bank already
had a significant part of the foreign-currency deposit market.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuiji declined, however, to disclose the amount in
foreign-currency deposits, as did a spokesman for Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo Bank began offering foreign-currency deposit accounts
in five different currencies last year, in advance of the financial
reforms. A spokesman said that from March until the end of July,
the amount of deposits held in foreign-currency accounts had
increased 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Few believe the government is prepared to step in and try to
stem that tide. In the past, intervention has taken place only in
advance of a significant policy development, and there is no new
policy in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, various senior officials of the ruling party have
expressed dissatisfaction with the yen's direction in recent days,
but to no avail. Tuesday, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa hinted
obliquely that the government might move to prop up the yen, and
Eisuke Sakakibara, vice minister of finance for international
affairs, suggested that the Group of Seven industrial nations would
join in support of the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa, noting the negative impact that the slide in the yen
is having on other Asian currencies, said, ``I couldn't speak of
specific levels, but it is necessary to intervene if the market is
not moving in an orderly fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The markets assume that as the yen weakens, Japanese exports
become more competitive with those of other Asian countries, and
concern is mounting that the Chinese will be forced to devalue
their currency, the yuan, in spite of pledges not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   A report Tuesday in The Financial Times said the Chinese
government was selling yen, in a major shift in its
foreign-currency portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next key point is 150'' yen to the dollar, said Hiroshi
Sakuma, a foreign-exchange trader at Barclays Bank in Tokyo.
``That's the target point for a lot of investors and speculators
because that's the point that many think the Chinese will have to
devalue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some economists and strategists suggest that allowing the yen to
weaken is, in fact, the government's newest plan to reinvigorate
the deteriorating Japanese economy, in spite of the stern tone of
disapproval emanating from the ministry of finance.
</P>
<P>
   Economists like Paul Krugman have argued that Japan should
deliberately unleash inflation, which would encourage consumers and
companies to spend rather than save in fear that their purchasing
power would be diluted in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Chudler, chief strategist at Salomon Smith Barney in
Tokyo. said: ``This could be the economic policy they're after. If
they allow the currency to depreciate, it should be inflationary by
making imports more expensive, and many economists believe Japan
desperately needs inflation to get the economy going again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
