<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9009 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-REVIVALS-ART     08-11 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-REVIVALS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV6-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CROWD OF OLD MUSICALS SQUEEZES THE NEW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Rebecca Luker is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Audiences flocking to the Martin Beck Theater for the
revival of ``The Sound of Music'' couldn't care less that many
critics find the musical irredeemably saccharine. With its famously
tuneful score, this 1959 show, the last Rodgers and Hammerstein
collaboration, is comfortingly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   People watch dazed with happiness, bobbing their heads, along
with the Von Trapp children as they learn their do, re, mi's,
smiling with recognition as Maria lists her favorite things.
</P>
<P>
   There is no glitz, no benumbing spectacle, no blaring rock-ified
orchestra, just good old-fashioned musical value and an uplifting
story. The dance numbers are human-scaled and cute; the child
actors are impish and cute; Rebecca Luker's Maria is sweet-voiced
and cute.
</P>
<P>
   So, don't try to tell contented ``Sound of Music'' audiences
that there is a downside to Broadway's obsession with looking back,
manifested by the prevalence of commercially safe revivals like
this one.
</P>
<P>
   An entirely different kind of audience can be found three times
a season at City Center's Encores series, thoroughly enjoying more
modest trips back to Broadway's past, often its distant past.
Encores resurrects neglected old American musicals in exuberant,
choreographed, costumed, concert performances with winning casts
and restored orchestrations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the major commercial revivals on Broadway, which are
geared toward turning big profits over long runs, the Encores
series is a nonprofit operation that presents only six performances
of each show. Where else can you hear a stylish performance of the
original 1927 version of George and Ira Gershwin's zany and
musically dazzling ``Strike Up the Band,'' which Encores presented
last season?
</P>
<P>
   The rich American musical tradition stretches back at least to
the 1920s. That is about 80 years' worth of repertory. So it is
natural, even essential, that some energy and care be put into
maintaining this heritage.
</P>
<P>
   But the balance between old and new has long been tilting to the
old, and the problem is getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revivals encourage more revivals,'' Stephen Sondheim said
recently. ``Like kudzu, they are choking out new shows.''
</P>
<P>
   However much the public enjoys a chance to revisit musicals like
``The Sound of Music'' or the Roundabout Theater Company's gritty,
decadent revival of ``Cabaret,'' it stands to reason that the
effort, talent and, especially, money that go into revivals
decreases the potential resources for new material.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true now, with production costs for new works
so prohibitively high. If audiences will turn up for a familiar old
show, why should investors take a risk on something new? The more
successful the revival movement becomes, the more this supposed
celebration of the American musical's past will wind up stifling
its future.
</P>
<P>
   This trend is all the more dismaying because it has happened
before, with grim consequences in classical music during this
century. A growing preoccupation with past repertory, an
ever-increasing marginalization of modern works, the shifting of
financial support to institutions that curate the old rather than
cultivate the new _ it is all eerily familiar to those who have
tried to champion contemporary classical music in our time.
</P>
<P>
   The history of opera presents the closest parallel to the
predicament facing the American musical. In the 19th century, going
to the opera was almost like going to the movies today. The new
Verdi opera was awaited like the new Scorsese film.
</P>
<P>
   The repertory in most houses was primarily new or recent,
meaning works written within, say, the previous 15 years.
Occasionally, something like ``Don Giovanni'' was presented in the
nature of a special revival.
</P>
<P>
   This infusion of new works lessened after the turn of the
century, though there was still a significant public demand for
fresh repertory. It is often forgotten that, in the beginning of
his career, Arturo Toscanini was virtually a new-music specialist,
a champion of operas by his Italian-composer colleagues, though
later in his life he was vilified by living composers as a
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Caruso sang many roles written expressly for him,
like Dick Johnson, the bandit-hero of Puccini's ``Girl of the
Golden West,'' and Count Loris in Giordano's ``Fedora.'' Compare
his record with today's opera superstars. Among the Three Tenors,
only one, Placido Domingo, has sung in the premiere of an opera
written for him, Gian-Carlo Menotti's ``Goya.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1920s, radical new approaches to harmony, the
breakdown of tonality and the increasing availability of music
through new mass technologies, like the phonograph and radio,
created a climate in which worried impresarios started placating
rather than challenging the public, until today, when introducing a
new concert piece or opera is considered an act of courageous
programming.
</P>
<P>
   The same trend can be traced in American musicals, though the
time it took was much compressed. Popular arts in the 20th century
have developed at a 20th-century pace. In the years between, say,
Louis Armstrong and Ornette Coleman, jazz progressed as much as
classical music did from Bach to Boulez.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 20 years, major revivals have increasingly claimed
Broadway theaters and lured audiences away from new scores. In this
case, the challenge came from the growing separation between
theater music and pop styles.
</P>
<P>
   The theater music of Gershwin and Porter was also the popular
music of their time. But the music of, say, Jule Styne was far
removed from the pop and rock of the 1950s and 60s that excited
young people. Shows like ``Hair,'' the Who's ``Tommy'' and, most
recently, Jonathan Larson's ``Rent'' represent attempts to bridge
that gap.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But even when young creators today reach out to new audiences,
the climate for doing so is perilous. ``Producers are unwilling to
take a chance on new work, because so much of it doesn't become
successful,'' said Sondheim, whose musical modernism has earned him
impassioned admirers but intimidated Broadway audiences. ``They
would rather put their money into pre-sold products, like musicals
adapted from Disney movies, or revivals of shows familiar to the
public, who know what they are getting when they see something
called `The King and I.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, young creative talent is also being crowded out of
theaters by mega-musical British imports from the 1980s like
``Cats'' and ``Les Miserables'' that have settled in for good, it
seems, the Broadway equivalents of Grant's Tomb and other tourist
monuments.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, reflects the situation in opera, where crowd-pleasers
like ``Carmen'' and ``La Boheme'' are fixtures in the repertory of
houses large and small. That these operas were the daring, fresh
new works of their day is hard to convey any longer.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the American musical's focus on the past has
come to resemble the early-music movement in classical music, which
advocates using restored (or newly built) period-specific
instruments and adheres to the carefully researched performance
practices of earlier centuries. The aim is not just to recover
neglected early repertory but to present familiar works in
performances deemed historically ``authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Compare the talk of early-music movement proponents to some
revealing comments from Rob Fisher, the dynamic, 46-year-old
musical theater conductor who serves as musical director of
Encores.
</P>
<P>
   The task of reconstructing old shows from original, often
incomplete, sources requires the kind of scholarship that
musicologists typically employ in the classical field. For his
yeoman efforts, Fisher has rightly become a hero to devotees of the
American musical. But the attitude of historicism that creeps into
his work is worrisome, when viewed in the context of this overall
backward trend.
</P>
<P>
   In Fisher's interesting program notes for ``Strike Up the
Band,'' he explains that the script to the original version of the
show, which closed in 1927 during a pre-Broadway tryout in New
Jersey, is intact. But not the musical score and orchestrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus began our search for any original artifacts that could
help us restore this piece,'' Fisher writes. By assembling parts
from various sources, he learned ``the instrumentation and sound of
the orchestra'' as Gershwin originally intended it. The style of
the choral writing was ascertained from a later 1930 version of the
show that finally reached Broadway. So the musical, as presented by
Encores, he concludes, contained ``every bit of original material
we could find.''
</P>
<P>
   His archival attitude is strikingly similar to that of the
early-instrument movement leaders in classical music. Here is
William Christie, the musical director of the respected Paris-based
early-music ensemble Les Arts Florissants, writing in the program
notes for his recording of Mozart's ``Magic Flute'':
</P>
<P>
   ``For our part, we use the instruments that Mozart knew, the
voices that he admired and a vocal technique close to the one that
he himself practiced.'' He adds, ``It would be dishonest of me not
to admit that we wanted our own version to be a riposte to other
versions.''
</P>
<P>
   This is fairly presumptuous talk. Still, what's so wrong with
looking back? After all, it's great to get a chance to hear a
neglected Gershwin score. And, although ``The Magic Flute'' is a
repertory staple, it's at least interesting to have Christie's take
on how it might have sounded in Mozart's day.
</P>
<P>
   But the archeological aspect to these exhumations seems a sure
sign that both traditions are stuck, especially in comparison with
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the appeal of the Encores productions, particularly the
shows from the decades before World War II, is the way they zap us
back to a vibrant time when American musicals were just sassy
excuses for some snazzy songs and lively dance routines, pinned
like clothing on a mere string of a plot.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kern, Porter and Rodgers and Hart, Gershwin churned out his
shows, often one or two a year. In 1924 alone, he wrote four. He
was like some Broadway descendant of Rossini, who produced 39
operas in 20 working years before he basically quit the opera
business at only 37 and at the height of his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that Gershwin's shows, like Rossini's operas,
aren't filled with craft and elegance. But Gershwin was a pragmatic
man of the theater who wrote for specific performers and
situations, and he was quite willing to change songs, arrangements
or whatever was necessary when the show went on tour, or when
another production came along.
</P>
<P>
   Surely he would have been puzzled by the painstakingly complete
recordings that the musical-theater conductor and historian John
McGlinn has done of shows like ``Of Thee I Sing'' and Kern's ``Show
Boat,'' which scrupulously include every jettisoned scrap of music
from every existing version.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher essentially agrees. ``Back then, these shows were a more
disposable product,'' he said recently, ``like the entertainment of
the week. The creator was not expecting us to come along at the end
of the century and put this mosaic back together.'' But Fisher's
audiences understandably love these trips back to the unjaded days
when everybody was making it up as they went along.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim also has a wistful fondness for the early decades of
the musical, before Rodgers and Hammerstein's innovations made it
requisite that a show have a strong narrative book from which all
the songs convincingly emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the time of the Gershwins, the vitality was fabulous,''
Sondheim said. ``Everything didn't depend on money. No art forms
today have that kind of vitality, where people are having fun just
trying things. Maybe the Internet, with its cyberbooks and web
sites. It's a mess, but it's vital.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Looked at this way, there is a specific parallel between the
pre-book days of the musical and 18th-century opera and oratorio.
Performance practices back then were just as fluid and vital as
Broadway in the 1920s. Handel and Mozart were theater pros who
tailored their operas to star performers and specific companies.
</P>
<P>
   This is something many period-instrument proselytizers seem to
forget. A lot of scholarship and polemical arguments have gone into
attempts to perform, say, the ``Messiah'' the way Handel would have
performed it. But there were, by some counts, at least 10
presentations of the work in Handel's lifetime involving different
complements of performers and different versions of the score.
Which one is authentic?
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, when Mozart was asked to supervise the Vienna
premiere of Handel's ``Messiah'' in 1789, nearly 50 years after its
composition, his first step was to update this old piece, which
meant re-orchestrating it for the latest instruments and in the
latest style.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway today, the shows that most benefit from revival are
those that had mixed receptions when new and deserve a second look,
or a new approach.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim's challenging musicals have particularly benefited from
re-considered revivals, especially those that puzzled people when
new, like ``Pacific Overtures'' and, especially, the remarkable,
much-maligned ``Merrily We Roll Along.''
</P>
<P>
   The best recent example was the acclaimed revival of Sondheim's
``Follies'' at the Paper Mill Playhouse in New Jersey. The
production of this 1971 show, directed by Robert Johanson, was a
revelation. The complicated book was pared down and cleared up. The
performances were triumphant, particularly from a roster of
veterans who portrayed the former follies girls of the title.
</P>
<P>
   And Sondheim's score, a veritable compendium of older-show song
styles evoked with affection but not without humor, seemed more
brilliant than ever. It reminded me of a comment by Vladimir
Nabokov, who, when asked what his novel ``Lolita'' was about,
replied, ``My love affair with the English language.'' On one
level, ``Follies'' is about Stephen Sondheim's love affair with the
songs from the early days of the American musical.
</P>
<P>
   So revivals deserve a place on the Great White Way. And Fisher's
Encores celebrations are valuable contributions. But the danger of
old works pushing out new ones remains, and young creators are
languishing. Some are no doubt struggling for attention, as
Jonathan Larson did for most of his brief life. Larson had been
turning out scores for musicals for 15 years before New York
Theater Workshop took a chance on him and booked ``Rent'' for a
limited run.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, it took Larson's sudden death to focus attention on
his work, which now looms as a major and innovative contribution to
the musical tradition and which has also been (timid potential
producers take note) hugely profitable.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Rent'' opened, in 1995-96, two other shows by emerging
composers appeared: ``Floyd Collins,'' in 1996, based on true
events surrounding a cave accident in Kentucky in 1925, featured an
accomplished and intriguing score by Adam Guettel; and, in 1997,
``Violet,'' about a scarred woman in rural North Carolina who
travels to Tulsa in hopes that a television evangelist can cure
her, has a revivalist-tinged score by Jeanine Tesori. (She also has
provided the hauntingly beautiful incidental music for the current
production of Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night'' at Lincoln Center.)
</P>
<P>
   Each show had aimed for a Broadway run. Neither got further than
a stint at Playwrights Horizons, which had developed them and where
they received somewhat mixed reviews. Still, these are promising
creators who need more opportunities to attempt things, to make
mistakes, to learn by doing, just the way Gershwin did.
</P>
<P>
   How might Gershwin have fared today, when each new project has
to have almost provable appeal before producers will consider it,
and where so much energy is put into milking the past for sure
profits?
</P>
<P>
   hoices must be made between reviving the old and fostering the
new. But the risk of bringing back shows like ``The Sound of
Music'' in expensive Broadway productions is that the Jeanine
Tesoris of our day may never get a crack at Broadway at all, and
another Jonathan Larson may be languishing, undiscovered.
</P>
<P>
   A Rodgers and Hammerstein revival can be as enjoyable as an
original-instrument performance of Mozart's ``Jupiter'' Symphony.
But they are hardly necessary, the way new creators and new works
are. At least if the American musical is to have a future as well
as a past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
