<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NLRB TO MOVE ON PLAYERS' COMPLAINTS  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next step in the labor dispute between the National
Basketball Association and its players will come Thursday. The two
sides will not meet at the bargaining table, and they will not go
before an arbitrator. Thursday it is the National Labor Relations
Board's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is the day the New York office of the NLRB plans to
forward to the general counsel in Washington a recommendation on
the players' unfair labor practice charge. ``We're still receiving
information from the NBA,'' Daniel Silverman, director of the New
York office, said Tuesday. ``We don't have a full case investigated
yet. But we hope we'll have a submission to Washington with a
recommendation within a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Silverman does not plan to be in his office Friday, the
first day of a planned vacation, he is expected to make his
recommendation to the board Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman, who was instrumental in settling Major League
Baseball's 1994-95 strike, could take one of three steps: dismiss
the union's charge, issue a complaint against the league based on
the union's charge, or recommend that the board seek an injunction
in federal district court that, if granted, would shatter the
league's labor strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The players' preference is an injunction that would declare the
NBA's lockout illegal. In filing the unfair labor practice charge
last month, the union contended that the lockout was illegal
because the owners had not bargained in good faith and had
unilaterally changed working conditions, such as placing a freeze
on signings.
</P>
<P>
   Because seeking an injunction would be the most severe step the
NLRB could take, it would need approval first by the acting general
counsel, Fred Feinstein, and then by a majority of the five-member
board in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If Silverman recommends seeking an injunction, the timing could
be critical. William Gould, the board chairman, ends his term Aug.
27, which means if the matter is not addressed promptly, the board
may be reduced to four members when the recommendation comes up for
a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I know is the New York regional office will
conclude its involvement on Thursday,'' Gould said Tuesday in a
telephone interview. ``The matter will go to the general counsel on
Thursday. I don't know how quickly, if at all, the general counsel,
will take action. By tradition, we wait for the general counsel to
make a recommendation to us, if in fact there is a
recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
