</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AYCKBOURN-THEATER-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING HIS BAG OF TRICKS, AYCKBORN PLAYS WITH TIME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It is no secret after 53 plays that Alan Ayckbourn
relishes a challenge. And in play No. 49, ``Communicating Doors,''
the task he has posed for himself is this: how to mold a comic
thriller _ or even a scary farce _ while at the same time shuttling
his characters back and forth in time with an abandon many a
filmmaker might envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of a plot, I think of an idea, and then I wonder, `How
can I get that onto the stage?' '' Ayckbourn was saying one recent
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old playwright was speaking by telephone from his
office at the Stephen Joseph Theater in Scarborough, Yorkshire,
which has been his creative home for most of his prolific
professional life. A member of the theater company since 1957, he
became its artistic director in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Like all but three of Ayckbourn's plays, ``Communicating Doors''
had its premiere in Scarborough, in 1994. It opened 18 months later
on the West End, where it ran almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the American premiere of the play opens Off
Broadway at the Variety Arts Theater, directed by Christopher
Ashley.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Hodges plays Ruella, Julia McKenzie's star role in the
West End version. Ruella is the second wife of an aging client of a
young, latex-clad dominatrix named Poopay (``It's French for
doll''), portrayed by Mary-Louise Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Ruella is destined to suffer the same fate at the hands of her
murderous husband as his first wife, and it is the conceit of this
play to whiz its characters between 1978, 1998 and 2018 in an
effort to rewrite history _ with a communicating door between hotel
suites as the specific onstage mechanism that allows for the travel
in time.
</P>
<P>
   Not, Ayckbourn said, that the play ought to seem a mere trick.
``Whatever devices you use should always be there to serve the
theme,'' he said. ``If the theme has been overtaken by the device,
then something's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, he said, his interest lay in ``the question that
all of us ask: What would have happened if I had taken a different
course, if I had done this or done that?''
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Ayckbourn said, ``that we can alter things at the
time if we just think about them a little harder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I once called the play a `Back to the Future' for the stage,''
he continued, ``but it seemed to me very important that in the
middle of that was a human story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Communicating Doors,'' he added, was about ``turning points in
lives, people you meet who can change your life, as Ruella does for
Poopay and vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley is known for his work with the American dramatist Paul
Rudnick on plays like ``Jeffrey.'' He called Rudnick and Ayckbourn
both very funny writers, though Ayckbourn has a much slower burn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's comedy is explosive and building,'' Ashley said.
``Ayckbourn is sneakier in terms of what is comic about the moment.
I keep thinking about puzzles with him _ if A, then B; if B, then
C.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Ayckbourn plays, too, toy with time. ``Henceforward ...''
(1988) occupies the same vaguely ominous future intermittently
envisioned in ``Communicating Doors,'' while ``Time of My Life''
(1993) begins at a matriarch's 54th birthday and then shifts both
ahead and back to reveal a family in psychic disarray.
</P>
<P>
   New York, Ayckbourn is aware, has a distinctly edited view of
his career, insofar as many of his plays have yet to be seen there
and those that have been _ ``A Small Family Business,'' for
example, had a short Broadway run in 1992 _ did not always succeed.
</P>
<P>
   This play, he said, ``is about self-determination and survival
and pulling yourself up by your bootstraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are much more concepts that an American audience will
understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
