<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9029 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-SHOOT-DEAL-HNS     08-11 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SHOOT-DEAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AGREES TO $1.9 MILLION DEAL IN SHOOTING DEATH OF TEXAS TEEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The U.S. government has agreed to a $1.9 million
wrongful-death settlement with the family of a border youth shot
last year by Marines, but a Presidio County grand jury refused
again Tuesday to indict the man who pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Weinacht, lawyer for the family of Esequiel Hernandez Jr.,
said Tuesday that the Navy and the Department of Justice agreed to
pay the hefty sum rather than face a civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Weinacht's announcement came on the same day a grand jury for
the second time in a year declined to charge 23-year-old Marine
Cpl. Clemente Banuelos with murder in the death of Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied I've done what I could,'' said Presidio County
District Attorney Albert Valadez. ``There are no loose ends.
Everything has been tied up and presented to the grand jury in a
nice big package.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, news of the settlement revived allegations of wrongdoing
in the case of the high school sophomore, who was shot to death
last year by a team of four Marines on an anti-drug patrol along a
remote stretch of the Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   But with the second grand jury decision made public Tuesday,
hope of laying blame on the government in the Hernandez case rests
largely with U.S. Rep. Lamar Alexander, R-Texas, whose House
Judiciary subcommittee is investigating the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning we've believed there are problems with
the facts of this case,'' said Weinacht, a Pecos attorney who spoke
for the Hernandez family. ``Certainly there's enough evidence to
call into question the conduct of the Marines.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Watney, a Justice Department spokeswoman, said the
government acknowledged no fault in its agreement with the
Hernandez family. She declined to acknowledge the amount of the
settlement, which Weinacht said came in the form of a $1 million
annuity that over its life is expected to grow to $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends of Esequiel Hernandez said the settlement
proves the government is to blame in the youth's death. Weinacht
quoted Margarito Hernandez, one of Esequiel's seven brothers and
sisters, as saying that if the federal government ``accepted the
deal, they accepted it was a wrong thing that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement further suggested to some that the state and
federal inquiries into the matter, all of which have exonerated the
Marines, are suspect. Additional investigations by the Marine
Corps, which falls under the Navy, and Joint Task Force 6, the
anti-drug umbrella group under which the Marines were training at
the time of the shooting, also found no wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proves to me wrongdoing at the very highest level,'' said
Mel LaFollette, an activist and Hernandez family friend who has
fought the government since the young Hernandez was shot. ``It
proves beyond a reasonable doubt that there was an unlawful
cover-up of this incident.''
</P>
<P>
   While the investigations into the matter have suggested
otherwise, the House Immigration and Claims Subcommittee is
nevertheless delving into the matter. Angered that no one has been
reprimanded in the shooting, Smith has subpoened the Justice and
Defense departments for documents related to the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred May 20, 1997, on a bluff east of Redford,
a tiny town west of Big Bend National Park on the banks of the Rio
Grande. Hernandez, who had just turned 18 and had no criminal
record, was herding his goats at dusk when he encountered the
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hernandez shot twice with his vintage .22-caliber rifle,
it is unclear whether he knew what he was firing at. The Marines,
camouflaged from head to toe for their undercover operation in the
desert scrub, trailed Hernandez for 20 minutes before Banuelos shot
him once with an M-16 from about 150 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a member of the military had fired on a
U.S. citizen since troops were deployed on border operations in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The incident sparked a vigorous debate about the role of the
armed forces on the border and led to the end of armed military
anti-drug patrols. But neither Presidio County grand jury probes
nor one convened by the Justice Department last winter yielded any
indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The investigations, including those of the Marine Corps and
Joint Task Force 6, found the Marines were acting within the rules
of engagement, which allows soldiers to fire if fired upon, even in
domestic law-enforcement situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position from the beginning is that Cpl. Banuelos was
completely justified,'' said Jack Zimmermann, a Houston lawyer
representing Banuelos. ``But under the circumstances, the
humanitarian award seems appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The second grand jury convened this month and last, meeting four
times and even taking a walking tour of the site where Hernandez
was killed. Though no live witnesses were presented, Valadez made
use of stacks of evidence from the recently concluded federal
probe.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the El Paso-based Border Rights Coalition, said the
sizeable settlement proved the investigations wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way the government ever acknowledges fault is through
a quick and easy settlement like this one,'' said Laura Valdez, a
spokeswoman for the group. ``The government has never been in the
business of giving away money.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of modest means living in an adobe home a short walk
from river bank, Esequiel Hernandez Sr. and his wife are to receive
the money in installments. Weinacht said they are happy to have the
matter behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really ready to be left alone,'' he said. ``They just
want to go on with their life, and this will help relieve their
economic strain.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinacht said the elder Hernandez intends to make few changes in
his life, no longer picking onions and alfalfa as a day laborer in
the nearby fields but still herding his goats and farming hay on
the flood plain of the river that divides the United States from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Hernandezes may want to distance themselves from
the death of their son and the national attention it won,
LaFollette said the incident still haunts Redford.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day it's a raw and open wound on everybody's psyche,
especially the children's,'' he said. ``There's an unpleasant
feeling toward the government.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
