<HEADER>
A9030 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADAM-COHEN-MUSIC-$ADV     08-11 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAM-COHEN-MUSIC-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAM COHEN, SINGER, SONGWRITER AND SON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16.) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're an aspiring singer-songwriter itching to pour your
oh-so-sensitive and special feelings into personal anthems of pain
and redemption, it must be intimidating to labor in the shadows of
Bob Dylan, Joni Mitchell, Leonard Cohen and all the others who
hijacked confessional poetry in the 1960s and '70s and grafted it
onto folk music.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, how do you begin to match achievements
that radically personalized pop music's voice and opened up its
subject matter to embrace the minutely autobiographical? And in
today's dumbed-down pop culture, in which emotional vulnerability
is viewed with suspicion and everyone pretends to know everything
about life anyway, who's going to want to listen?
</P>
<P>
   Adam Cohen, 26, the son of Leonard Cohen, deserves points for
jumping in over his head and infusing some passion into a moribund
folk-pop tradition. In the best songs from his debut album ``Adam
Cohen'' (Columbia) _ the nasty, tormented ones _ this talented but
still partly unformed songwriter forces you to feel his anger,
jealousy and frustration over various erotic entanglements.
</P>
<P>
   It is when he steps back and begins philosophizing about how
everybody is lost and alone that Cohen's songs deteriorate into
platitudinous reflections.
</P>
<P>
   The singer, who worked with several collaborators on this
surprisingly melodic album, is a highly expressive vocalist whose
voice blends hints of his father's sepulchral drone with the racked
expansiveness of Bono (a sometimes too-obvious influence) and the
eager, crybaby emotiveness of the Canadian pop singer Dan Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But what's best about Cohen's singing is the way he delivers a
lyric as if he were living the song right then and there. At the
same time, the album's most original songs have jagged melodic
lines and shifting atmospheres that perfectly mirror the lyrics'
volatility.
</P>
<P>
   The most explosive performance can be found on the album's
opening cut, ``Tell Me Everything,'' whose narrator demands to know
_ pleading tremulously at first, then escalating to a tone of
raging desperation _ if his best friend is sleeping with the woman
the narrator loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spare me the lies, and all your tact,'' he says grimly, then
bursts into a howl. ``Tell me everything!'' he screams. ``Leave
nothing out/Tell me all about it/I'm right here listening.'' The
vocal equivalent of Method acting, it's quite chilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell Me Everything'' is not the only song about a twisted,
deceitful triangle. In ``Sister,'' which Cohen hisses in a tone of
bitter contempt, the narrator sneers at an obsequious friend, who
may be homosexually inclined, for saying he wants to date the
narrator's sister ``because she's so much like you.''
</P>
<P>
   In this creepy blanket put-down, Cohen describes the object of
his scorn as ``the kind of guy who looks you a little too deep in
the eye'' and recalls having once observed him sneaking into his
room and trying on his cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Adding an extra-musical resonance to these songs of embattled
friendship involving a shadowy female figure is their relation to
one of Leonard Cohen's greatest songs, ``Famous Blue Raincoat.'' As
this long, pained epistle offering forgiveness to the man who slept
with the letter-writer's wife unfolds, it becomes ever clearer that
the narrator himself is half in love with the friend who betrayed
him.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer cruelty, ``Sister'' can't touch ``Don't Mean
Anything,'' one of the nastiest songs ever written about falling
out of love. In speech-song verses that have been electronically
filtered to make them sound even more sinister, the singer icily
describes acting out a charade of affection with a lover for whom
he has lost all sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   In the chorus, he croons, with a quiet boastfulness, lines that
are devastating in their bluntness: ``It's hard to feel when you
don't/It's hard to say you will when you won't/And if you do/It
don't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell Me Everything,'' ``Sister,'' and ``Don't Mean Anything''
are the three clear winners on an album whose other songs are
marred to varying degrees by sentimental cliches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Pain,'' a strong, insightful ballad about how emotional
masochism can enhance intimacy in a relationship, is bogged down by
a mundane refrain in which poor Vincent Van Gogh, one of pop
music's favorite points of pretentious comparison, is trotted out
as a too-easy reference.
</P>
<P>
   Other songs on the album find Cohen overly enthralled with his
influences. ``Beautiful as You'' is the prettiest of several songs
that strain to make grand statements about love and life in a style
reminiscent of U2. ``How the Mighty Have Fallen,'' a laboriously
elongated slogan, and ``Down She Goes,'' an impersonal observation
of a drug addict's decline, have the flatness of songwriting
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   But the album's best songs still mark ``Adam Cohen'' as an
unusually impressive debut and one that also bears out that old
expression about the apple not falling far from the tree. If the
late Jeff Buckley (the son of Tim Buckley), Rufus Wainwright (the
son of Loudon Wainwright III) and now Cohen all bring strong echoes
of their fathers into their work, they have also staked out their
own territory in terms of subject matter and attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Although we'll never know how Buckley might have developed, at
the time of his death last year he was moving toward a fusion of
hyper-romantic folk-jazz with his own quirky style of alternative
rock. Wainwright brings his father's whimsy to gay subjects and
writes ornate folk-pop music that skews toward the operatic.
Cohen's music is also stylistically more expansive than his
father's in its inclusion of light funk grooves.
</P>
<P>
   Like their famous fathers, they all chose to take the high road
artistically at a time when that road has never seemed lonelier and
more fraught with commercial pitfalls. As their albums show, it is
still a road well worth taking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEOCITIES-IPO-NYT &LR;      08-11 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEOCITIES-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID DOWNTURN, ANOTHER INTERNET COMPANY'S IPO CATCHES FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never have so many pictures of puppies been worth so much.
</P>
<P>
   Investors clamored to buy the stock of Geocities on Tuesday,
despite a falling market and the fact that the company has yet to
prove it can make money by giving its 2 million members free pages
on the Internet's World Wide Web to show off their kids, their pets
and their bottle-top collections.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Geocities shares closed at $37.3125, more than double
the offering price of $17. That values the company, which had a
loss on revenues of less than $5 million last year, at $1.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Geocities is among a sector of Internet businesses known as
virtual communities, because they offer free real estate in
cyberspace and often organize chat areas of shared interests as
virtual neighborhoods, villages, etc. Virtual communities hope to
sell advertising based on the number of visitors these home-grown
Web pages attract.
</P>
<P>
   Their primary competition for visitors and advertising dollars
is the Internet contrivances known as portals that combine free Web
pages with e-mail, search facilities and other services and
products to attract users.
</P>
<P>
   The portal business won another endorsement Tuesday _ and
Geocities got a formidable new competitor _ when Lycos, a search
and directory service, said that it had agreed to buy WhoWhere for
$133 million in stock. WhoWhere operates the Anglefire service,
which offers home pages, electronic mail service and a telephone
directory that lets Internet users look up phone numbers online.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Lycos bought Tripod, another service that offers
home pages, for $57 million.
</P>
<P>
   The two deals will give Lycos 3.1 million home pages, more than
Geocities' 2.1 million. Measured by numbers of visitors to its
sites each month, Lycos will now be No. 4 on the Internet, behind
America Online, Yahoo and Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Media Metrix, a company that measures audience
size on the Internet, found that Anglefire was the fastest-growing
site in the first half of this year. The other fast-growing sites
were also mainly those that offered home pages, chat and other
``community building'' services.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in the stock of Geocities was all the more spectacular
because of the sharp decline in the overall stock market and of
Internet companies in particular. Shares of America Online fell
$5.625, to $107.125, and Yahoo dropped $2.625, to $91.375. Lycos'
shares fell a greater percentage, closing at $63.5625, down $4.375.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors continued to show insatiable appetite for the
initial offerings of Internet companies. Last month, the stock of
Broadcast.com, which offers audio programs on the Internet, jumped
245 percent on its first day of trading, the biggest debut increase
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Geocities offering was oversubscribed by 20 times, said one
person involved in the underwriting. Indeed, that was after the
opening price was increased from an initial target of $12, to a
proposed range of $14 to $16, and was ultimately set at $17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geocities is a meaningful franchise with fantastic growth and
good management,'' said Keith Benjamin, an analyst with BancAmerica
Robertson Stephens, a brokerage firm that was not involved in the
underwriting. ``It's not obvious how profitable that franchise will
become.''
</P>
<P>
   Geocities, and its competitors, hopes to make money by placing
ads on people's home pages as well as on the other pages that
people see as they navigate around the service. But advertisers
have been skeptical of gambling on home-grown content that at best
is random and extraneous and at worst offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lycos chief executive Robert Davis said that since buying
Tripod the company had been able to add nearly 200 advertisers and
direct marketers to the service. He said that Lycos expected
similar results with sales of ads on WhoWhere's services.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the analysts who follow Lycos' stock said they were
impressed with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take my hat off to Bob Davis,'' said Paul Noglows, an
analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``He has a knack for taking traffic
and squeezing revenue out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that Lycos would keep its two services separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tripod is geared almost entirely to the Generation X audience,
which is highly desirable to advertisers,'' he said. ``Anglefire
includes a lot of other demographic groups.''
</P>
<P>
   WhoWhere chief executive Dale Fuller said the company had
several other suitors, whom he declined to name, and had many
investment bankers interested in taking the company public.
Ultimately, he said, the company's investors, which included
venture capital funds backed by the Rockefeller and the Bass
families, preferred Lycos shares to any of the alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Williams, an analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan, said the
price Lycos paid seemed reasonable, relative to other Internet
acquisitions. Microsoft, for example, paid $400 million, or about
$40 a member, for the Hotmail electronic mail service. Ms. Williams
said Lycos was paying $13 for each WhoWhere member.
</P>
<P>
   The market value of Geocities, on the other hand, comes out to
$523 a member. That makes for some pretty pricey puppies, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2143EDT &QL; 
