<HEADER>
A9032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-WILLIAMS-NYT     08-11 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' WILLIAMS IS ON FAST TRACK  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD CLIFFS, N.J. _ Jayson Williams is not someone who is
comfortable with idle time. With the National Basketball
Association players locked out, the All-Star center for the Nets is
spending his off season running from one appearance to another
trying to fill the gaps in his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Last week it was a trip to the Cayman Islands to film a
commercial. Presumably footage of a seasick Williams hanging over
the side of a boat will be cut, along with the footage of his
lawyer, Oscar Holt, rushing to the aid of the 6-foot-11-inch player
a bit too quickly and being flipped overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Safely back on shore, Williams delivered a brief lecture Tuesday
at the Jayson Williams All-Star Basketball Camp, then patiently
signed autographs for the children in attendance. When the line
finally wound down, he hopped in his car and headed to one of his
twice-a-day workouts, and then it was on to the next round of
charity appearances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing Williams will not do is sit and wait for the league
and the players union to settle their differences. Williams
reiterated his desire to find a game, and if it isn't in the NBA,
he said, he will go wherever he has to go to get paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls from Billy Hunter telling me to come down,'' he
said, referring to the executive director of the NBA players
association. ``He says that I'm intelligent and can help them with
this stuff. But I don't have the patience for it. I don't have the
patience for somebody getting up and walking out on a situation
like the owners did. I think it was immature.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has maintained that if the lockout is not settled, he
will play in Italy. He said he received an offer from the Italian
team Kinder Bologna on a per-game basis.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' agent, Sal DiFazio, was not available for comment, but
another agent said that it would be possible to structure such a
deal and that an Italian League team might be willing to do it if
it believed that the NBA lockout would be resolved quickly. This
would enable the European league to reap the benefits of the
publicity Williams would bring without the cost being prohibitive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is a free agent, has no contract that restricts
him from playing elsewhere. But the NBA honors European deals, so
to return, he would have to have an escape clause in any deal he
signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a basketball player,'' Williams said. ``If you think I'm
going to sit back here all year and not go to Italy and play
basketball, you're crazy. That's what I do. I've got to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy is out if there is an NBA. But they told me they'll pay
me by the game. I'm going to go out there and do some camps. I'm
real big in Europe. The day that the NBA gets it back, that's the
day I'll come back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
