<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/11/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- BELARUS-ECON, 8-11 --
Belarus' ruble, called the zaichik, or little hare, has lost half
of its worth in five months and more than 10 percent in the last
week alone. Now, the government has announced a new and perhaps
unintentionally revealing plan to shore up the ruble's value:
starting next week, the country will no longer accept its own
currency as payment for exports. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WEST MILFORD, N.J. -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- NY-CAMP-EDUC,
8-11 -- Mamasa Njie, left, and a partner, Joseph Natal, working on
an analysis of pond water at Camp Vacamas during their three-week
session combining camp with school work. ``I thought we were just
coming here and we'd pick what we wanted to do, like in other
camps,'' Mamasa says. (Richard Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) OGDENSBURG, N.Y. -- Aug. 11, 1998 --
CANADA-BORDER-SHOPPING-2, 8-11 -- The empty Park Plaza in
Ogdensburg, a town in the North Country where Canadians shoppers
were plentiful before the currency woes. Lou Williams, the owner of
two Ogdensburg motels, says the Canadians used to arrive on Friday,
``party hearty all night and spend all day Saturday shopping.''
Then ``they'd shop a little more on Sunday and go home.'' (Michael
J. Okoniewski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) OGDENSBURG, N.Y. -- Aug. 11, 1998 --
CANADA-BORDER-SHOPPING-1, 8-11 -- Michael Mills clearing weeds at
the empty Park Plaza in Ogdensburg, a town in the North Country
where retailers have seen their fortunes fall with the declining
Canadian dollar. Shoppers used to pour over the border, but not
anymore. (Michael J. Okoniewski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) JONESBORO, Ark. -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- JONESBORO-TRIAL,
8-11 -- Scott Johnson, the father of 14-year-old Mitchell Johnson,
after his son pleaded guilty Tuesday in the Jonesboro school
shootings, in which a teacher and four students were killed. After
a two-hour trial, Circuit Judge Ralph Wilson on Tuesday convicted
12-year-old Andrew Golden and found him, along with Mitchell, to be
``delinquent'' - the juvenile court equivalent of a guilty verdict.
(Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HOUSTON -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SOUTHWEST-DROUGHT-2, 8-11 --
Lynn Bartlett, a farmer in Texas, has sprinklers for his cotton
that reach only so far. In the areas that get little relief from
the drought, the cotton bolls are stunted. While many parts of the
country, including the Northeast, are suffering through dry months
verging on drought, the situation is particularly severe in Texas
and Oklahoma. (David Bowser/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) HOUSTON -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SOUTHWEST-DROUGHT-1, 8-11 --
Lynn Bartlett, a farmer in Texas, has sprinklers for his cotton
that reach only so far. His irrigated, tall cotton is behind him.
``This is basically burnt-up cotton,'' he says. ``We had a good
planting rain back in May, then a week or so later the tap just
shut off and it's been off ever since.'' (David Bowser/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR, 8-11 --
Harry Thomason, center, a television producer and President
Clinton's friend, testified Tuesday about his advice on the Monica
Lewinsky matter. Thomason is back in town this week to help Clinton
prepare for his grand jury testimony Monday, which is to be
transmitted by closed-circuit television from the White House to
the federal courthouse. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SF-POET-LAUREATE, 8-11
-- As a voice of the Beat Generation, poet, publisher and book
seller, Lawrence Ferlinghetti has always held a prominent place in
San Francisco's cultural community. On Tuesday, he was elevated to
a loftier status. Mayor Willie Brown, recognizing the need for
``great cities of the world'' to ``place great stock in their great
artists,'' named Ferlinghetti the city's first poet laureate.
(Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CIREZ, Serbia -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- YUGO-KOSOVO, 8-11 --
The Makolli family relaxing under a tree near the village of Cirez
in Kosovo province Tuesday. Mother, daughter and baby are among
15,000 refugees who have fled from fighting to the area around
Pristina. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LONDON -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- THEROUX-NAIPAUL-2, 8-11 --
V.S. Naipaul at home in London in 1994. A former protege, Paul
Theroux, has turned against him in a new memoir, ``Sir Vidia's
Shadow: A Friendship Across Five Continents.'' As often happens in
a divorce, friends of the two men, who had mainained a relationship
for more than 30 years, are forced to choose sides. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) EAST SANDWICH, Mass. -- Aug. 11, 1998 --
THEROUX-NAIPAUL-1, 8-11 -- Paul Theroux at his desk in East
Sandwich. Until it suddenly ended, the friendship between V.S.
Naipaul and Theroux, as mentor and protege, was mutually rewarding
over a period of more than 30 years. Now, with the forthcoming
publication of Theroux's book ``Sir Vidia's Shadow: A Friendship
Across Five Continents,'' and the controversy surrounding it, there
is only bitterness. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CHICAGO -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- DRINKING-VINEGAR, 8-11 --
Lustered on a silver tray in the center of Seasons, the restaurant
in the Four Seasons Hotel in Chicago, are slender hand-blown flasks
of liquids in tones of pale straw, amber and burgundy. Grappas?
Liqueurs? Guess again. The bottles are filled with vinegars, served
as aperitifs or as palate-refreshers between courses, for $4 a
glass. ``It's a big eye-catcher,'' says Andreas Kappenhagen, the
director of the restaurant. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- CHARWOOD, 8-11 -- A blend of
Chunk Charwood (charred Canadian sugar maple) and chunks of wood
cut for grilling. They are sold separately by Peoples
Woods/Nature's Own. The result is a clean, dry heat that seals in
flavor. (David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SIMPLE-COOKING, 8-11 --
Unlike peaches, whose raw glory can barely be improved upon,
tomatoes are all about potential. The difference between consuming
a tomato out of hand and slicing it, then sprinkling it with a
pinch of salt and a few drops of olive oil, is the difference
between a snack and a dish. And the great thing about tomatoes is
that it takes so little to convert them from one to the other.
(David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- NY-LATE-NIGHT-DINING-2, 8-11
-- At Clementine, young Wall Street types spend some time at the
34-seat bar and then share plates of food with friends. For many,
it's the first stop of the night. In July, Clementine expanded its
late-night menu, tempting night crawlers with dishes like grilled
stuffed squid in a cumin broth as late as 3:15 a.m. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- NY-LATE-NIGHT-DINING-1, 8-11
-- Florent in the meat-packing district attracts bankers, fashion
industry types and performers like Flotilla DeBarge and Jeffrey
Breaux. New York has always had a late-night subculture of 24-hour
diners. But now, with a growing number of affluent artists,
entrepreneurs and Wall Streeters working long, hard hours, the
city's high-end restaurateurs are beginning to stay up late
themselves, and offer serious food all through the night. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 8-11 --
Manhattan's Solera restaurant serves fino sherries like Tio Pepe
from Gonzalez Byass, La Ina from Dome and Alvear's Fino Montilla.
Most sherries come from the white-chalk vineyards around the city
of Jerez, in Andalusia, the southernmost province of Spain.
(Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ULSTER COUNTY, N.Y. -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SWEET-CORN-2,
8-11 -- Silver Queen corn, an older variety known for its big white
ear and full corn flavor, in early development at Caradonna Farms
in Ulster County. This type of corn was grown widely earlier in the
century and must be rushed to market soon after picking, as it
starts to lose its sweetness. In the last 20 years, it has been
supplanted by hardier varieties that stay sweet longer. (Chris
Ramirez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MIDDLETOWN, N.Y. -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SWEET-CORN-1, 8-11
-- At Sycamore Farms in Middletown, Henry Smith picks an ear of
white Incredible sweet corn, a sugar-enhanced variety that is
quicker and easier to grow than varieties grown in years past. For
150 years, breeders have experimented with sweet corns to improve
flavor, texture, tenderness, appearance, growing time and
hardiness. But only in the last 20 years have any real strides been
made. (Chris Ramirez/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- PROFILE-STITH-BOS, 8-11 -- The
Rev. Charles Stith, longtime activist and recently named ambassador
to Tanzania, sits in his office in the Back Bay area of Boston.
Stith is just back from Washington, from a hurried trip to the
State Department crisis center monitoring the aftermath of the
bombings of U.S. embassies in Dar es Salaam and Nairobi. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
