<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9037 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERBAN-CYMBELINE-THEA     08-11 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBAN-CYMBELINE-THEATER-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW `CYMBELINE' OF MOON, GRASS AND TREES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Stephanie Roth Haberle and Liev Schreiber is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds.: 1st 3 graphs are in italics) 
(af) 
 By ANDREA STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just before Shakespeare's ``Cymbeline'' opened in June at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music, the directors Adrian Noble and Andrei
Serban talked in these pages about staging this rarely seen
adventure-comedy-romance in nearly back-to-back versions.
</P>
<P>
   Noble's, by the Royal Shakespeare Company, was his first attempt
at directing the play. So, too, with Serban, whose ``Cymbeline''
opens Sunday night at the Delacorte Theater, part of the New York
Shakespeare Festival's 43rd season in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, with Noble warning about the play's five-act length
_ ``It's absolutely massive'' _ Serban said that he had not decided
on any concept and that he was ``just starting.'' At a recent
preview he seemed to have made up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few nights ago, as a nearly round-faced moon smiled
whimsically overhead, the large cast of Andrei Serban's
``Cymbeline'' ended the first act by appearing to walk into Central
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the park had grown over the set, which consists of a
large grass-covered oval, a grove of trees and a stream along one
side. At the center of the stage is a white circle of sand on which
much of the action takes place. Elaborate it isn't, but there is
more than a hint of concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way, my imagination has to work,'' Serban said. ``Realism
in a situation like this would be killing.''
</P>
<P>
   The director, 55, who from 1990 to 1993 ran the National Theater
in Romania, where he was born, is the head of the graduate acting
program at Columbia University. Perched high up at the Delacorte,
where he could see everything going on, he talked about the play
during intermission.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed pleased and concerned about his leading lady,
Stephanie Roth Haberle, who is 7{ months' pregnant. She portrays
Imogen, daughter of Cymbeline, king of ancient Britain. In a story
full of concealments, her pregnancy is undisguised.
</P>
<P>
   Other cast members include Herb Foster, Hazelle Goodman, Randall
Duk Kim, George Morfogen, Liev Schreiber and Robert Stanton. Among
the more than 20 plot complications are scenes involving
cross-dressing, lost brothers, mistaken identities, a wicked
stepmother and war. Eventually, the god Jupiter arrives to sort
things out.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking quickly in his Romanian accent and gesturing
frequently, Serban said about Ms. Haberle: ``Stephanie carries life
inside her. It is very touching. It's not a metaphor; it's real.
From night to night, you don't know. She could give birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did he choose the actress, who spends half the play dressed
as a man?
</P>
<P>
   ``In auditions, she touched me the most,'' he said. ``She makes
the language part of her experience. When I see Shakespeare, I am
often bored because the actors don't understand what they are
saying. Stephanie is very much like what I feel Imogen is in the
play _ like Dante's Beatrice, the symbol of the soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Serban said there is more symbolism in his decision to have
Schreiber play both the evil Iachimo and the god Jupiter. Iachimo
bets Imogen's exiled husband Posthumus (Michael Hall) that he can
seduce her. Though he fails, he boasts of his success, and the
furious Posthumus orders his wife's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, Iachimo is portrayed as a conniver and manipulator,
an Iago, a villain,'' Serban said. ``But I think he is Jupiter, who
takes a human form in order to challenge Posthumus to see himself,
to see his limitations, to see his own vanity, so that he can
suffer and mature. From the very beginning, Imogen is ready for
Posthumus, but he is not ready for her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So Iachimo is a very positive devil, a holy devil _ we need
that in life,'' the director said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   He went on: ``I am convinced that nothing that happens to us is
accidental. Everything in our life is a test. We are always
tested.''
</P>
<P>
   By whom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think by G-O-D,'' he replied, laughing again and
spelling but not saying the word. ``I'm very old-fashioned that
way. I'm not a post-modernist.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars date ``Cymbeline'' to about 1610, six years before
Shakespeare's death. ``Compared to `Cymbeline,' '' Serban said, ``
`King Lear' is like the `Ninth Symphony.' `Cymbeline,' being a late
work, is more like Beethoven's late quartets. It is much more
subtle, more delicate, more like a man at the end of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   A documentary entitled ``Crossroads,'' made earlier this year
about the acting program at Columbia and Serban's work there, shows
the director speaking about reactions over the years to his
productions: ``I got incredibly bad reviews all my life,'' he says
in the movie. ``I have friends who ask me, `How do you get your
next job when you get such bad reviews?' ''
</P>
<P>
   This might be a bit of an exaggeration. For example, Serban's
most recent production in New York _ ``The Caucasian Chalk Circle''
at La Mama in May, with his graduating students as cast members _
won critical praise. He has worked with many leading actors, and
since 1980 has directed operas around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a theory about this,'' he explained the other day,
referring to the reviews. ``What I try to do in the theater is
always to change. I don't have, like Robert Wilson, Richard Foreman
or Peter Sellars, a style of my own. I try to do theater that
escapes definition. When critics come, they say, `What is his
style?' But I don't have a style. And perhaps that is confusing to
people.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Delacorte, as people began returning to their seats,
Serban looked around, interested to see how they were reacting.
</P>
<P>
   Later he said: ``I hope the audience goes home with a vast range
of impressions about human life. An audience that sees this play
might then be able to see life on a cosmic as well as a social
level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People fall asleep easily in the theater,'' he said. ``The
seats are comfortable. It's very warm. In Central Park, we are in
the fresh, open air. We can see the moon. We can feel we are part
of something greater. It is an opportunity not to fall asleep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
