<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRITISH PETROLEUM TO BUY AMOCO IN $48.2 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   British Petroleum announced that it would acquire Amoco, the big
oil company, for $48.2 billion in stock. The deal is the largest
oil industry merger ever, as well as the largest foreign takeover
of an American company. If approved by regulators and shareholders
of both companies, BP Amoco, as the company is to be known, will be
the world's third-largest multinational oil company in terms of net
income after Exxon and the Royal Dutch/Shell Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN MARKETS PLUNGE
</P>
<P>
   Russian stocks fell 9.11 percent, nearly as great a decline as
on Monday. Government bonds tumbled to their lowest prices ever, as
rates on the Russian equivalent of United States Treasury bills
approached 80 percent for three-month maturities and 140 percent
for nine-month maturities. ``It's a collapse in confidence about
the Russian Government's ability to fund itself,'' a former World
Bank official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Belarussian ruble _ called the zaichik, or bunny, after the
engraving that is its main feature _ has lost half its worth in
five months, and the Belarus Government will no longer accept it as
payment for exports.
</P>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC WORKERS END STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Ending a two-day-old strike against Bell Atlantic, members of
the Communications Workers of America declared victory and returned
to work. They reached a tentative agreement with management that
insures that jobs in the company's high-technology growth areas
will go to union employees.
</P>
<P>
   THE YEN'S FALL FROM FAVOR
</P>
<P>
   With the yen trading at eight-year lows _ 147.35 yen to the
dollar in New York _ currency traders fear a fundamental shift in
sentiment is under way against the yen. Housewives, who control
vast savings, are moving into dollars, pounds and marks.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND-QUARTER PRODUCTIVITY OFF
</P>
<P>
   Workers' productivity fell at an annual rate of two-tenths of 1
percent in the second quarter, the first such drop in three years,
as Asia's economic crisis and strikes at General Motors plants took
a toll.
</P>
<P>
   LONG BOND'S YIELD NEAR LOW
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.62 percent,
near its all-time low, as investors seeking a haven from stocks and
overseas markets pushed up bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART PROFIT EXCEEDS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores said that its quarterly earnings rose 30
percent, to $1.03 billion, or 46 cents a diluted share, 3 cents
above analysts' forecasts. Profit surged almost fivefold at its
international stores.
</P>
<P>
   GEOCITIES' SUCCESSFUL IPO
</P>
<P>
   Investors clamored to buy the stock of Geocities, which gives
its 2 million members pages on the World Wide Web to display
pictures of their kids, their pets and their bottle-top collections
_ a business on which it has not proved it can make money. Shares
closed at $37.31, more than double the offering price of $17, in a
day the market tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ADOBE ISSUES WARNING ON REVENUE
</P>
<P>
   Adobe Systems warned that revenue would fall below analysts'
expectations, possibly resulting in a third-quarter loss, and that
three senior executives would leave. Adobe is cutting 240 to 300
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ASSOCIATES FIRST TO BUY AVCO
</P>
<P>
   Associates First Capital, the finance company spun off by Ford
Motor, agreed to buy Avco Financial Services for $3.9 billion in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   BAD SHOWS FOR INVESTORS
</P>
<P>
   Announcing enforcement actions, Federal regulators said that
fraudulent entertainment-industry investment schemes had cost
investors $100 million in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM SELLS ITS MUSIC STORES
</P>
<P>
   Viacom Inc. sold its disappointing chain of Blockbuster Music
stores to Wherehouse Entertainment for $115 million in cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
