<SLUG> BC-HKN-LAFONTAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELUCTANTLY, LAFONTAINE RETIRES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having suffered a series of debilitating and
increasingly dangerous concussions, the most recent of which
occurred last March 16 when a freakish collision with a Rangers
linemate ended his season, Pat LaFontaine announced his reluctant
but unequivocal retirement from hockey Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my choice, you bet I'd be suiting up for the New York
Rangers this season,'' the 33-year-old center said during a news
conference at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine suited up as Mark Messier's replacement last season
despite five previously diagnosed concussions and a history of
post-concussion syndrome. It was a testament to LaFontaine's desire
to close his career on his own terms and to the Rangers'
desperation to back Wayne Gretzky with a proven center.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine finished the season _ albeit prematurely _ second on
the team in scoring with 62 points and tied for first in goals with
23. But the injury from his head-on crash with Mike Keane, which
was not diagnosed as a concussion at first, all but assured that
LaFontaine would not return to hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``His was a career almost second to none, certainly in American
hockey history,'' said the Rangers' president, Neil Smith.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine is a five-time All-Star and two-time Olympian whose
148-point season with the Buffalo Sabres in 1992-93 set a record
for American-born players. In January, he became only the third
American player to score 1,000 NHL points.
</P>
<P>
   The solid but far from strapping 5-foot-10-inch sniper
accumulated 468 goals and 545 assists in 1,056 games. His
consistency put him in eighth place on the career goals-per-game
list behind such notables as Mario Lemieux, Wayne Gretzky and Mike
Bossy.
</P>
<P>
   The collision with Keane resulted in LaFontaine's sixth
diagnosed concussion, a Grade II level injury that followed on the
heels of a more severe Grade III blow that knocked him unconscious
and cost him the 1996-97 season at Buffalo. LaFontaine's concussion
as a Ranger was the 56th sustained by an NHL player in 1997-98, a
season in which notables like Eric Lindros, Dennis Vaske and Paul
Kariya were also sidelined by concussions. Lindros, acutely aware
that his younger brother, Brett, was forced into retirement in 1995
after sustaining two concussions within eight days, was out for a
month with his second career concussion.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' Vaske saw his season end on Nov. 14, and Kariya,
the Mighty Ducks' captain, never returned after sustaining his
fourth concussion on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the past few years has the NHL dropped its historically
cavalier attitude toward concussions, a little-researched injury
that presents difficulties in rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL still has no formal policy for preventing the hits that
provoke concussions, nor has it adopted the recovery timetable (a
minimum of one week off the ice for first-time concussion victims)
suggested by researchers into sports-related brain injuries.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine sustained his fifth concussion on Oct. 17. 1996, from
a vicious blow by Pittsburgh's 6-foot-6-inch Francois Leroux that
sent him crashing to the ice helmetless and left him unconscious
for several minutes. But he was back in uniform within days, and
played seven games before leaving the lineup with post-concussive
symptoms that plagued him the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The collision with Keane, a crash that affected LaFontaine as if
he had ``run into a brick wall,'' caused the last in a series of
concussions that began when James Patrick knocked him senseless
during a Ranger-Islander playoff game in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine, who spent his whole career as a target of brawnier
opponents intent on muscling him into submission before he could
outskate or outsmart them, said he probably has received four or
five ``unofficial'' concussions in addition to the half-dozen that
have been diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest one ended his career because doctors could no longer
guarantee that his next concussion, whenever it came, would not
carry dire and long-lasting consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Rangers left the decision solely to him, LaFontaine
said it would be irresponsible for him to play next season. He said
the decision to leave hockey was ``made for him'' two weeks ago by
Dr. James Kelly, the Chicago neurologist who gave him the green
light to join the Rangers last season after the Buffalo Sabres,
citing his history of concussions, declined to put him back on
their roster for an eighth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you sustain a head injury, the risks go up further
and further, and I always said that if it ever got to the point
where there was more than minimal risk, I would stop playing
hockey, and it's at that point now,'' said LaFontaine, whose
concussion symptoms have included migraine headaches, depression,
fatigue, nausea and mood swings so crippling that there were days
when he could not convince himself there was a reason to get up in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   LaFontaine, whose career spanned 15 seasons with the Islanders,
Sabres and Rangers, said he had no immediate plans for retirement
besides spending time with his wife, Marybeth, and their three
children, as well as continuing his charitable work, particularly
his affiliation with the American Academy of Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very, very fortunate to have played 15 years, but
what I've gone through in the last couple years isn't something
anyone wants to go through,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
