u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-asthecowboysturn-HNS &LR;      08-11 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-as </SLUG>
 the cowboys turn-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Scissorgate no help in cutting to the chase
<TEXT>
<P>
   McIver-Irvin talk lingers around Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
He found a coach who was a polar opposite of the gun-toting,
loud-mouthed leader to whom the Cowboys had gotten accustomed. He
searched for a first-round draft pick whose reputation had never
been tarnished. He even hired help to meet with his players and
conduct a sort of ``sensitivity training.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite Cowboys owner Jerry Jones' efforts, Dallas once
again finds itself in the harsh spotlight because of players who
can't stay away from trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Michael Westbrook was seen pummeling Redskins teammate
Stephen Davis on the sidelines during last year's training camp has
an in-house incident captured such attention.
</P>
<P>
   And in the case of the Cowboys, as has become the norm, most of
the details are clouded in mystery.
</P>
<P>
   This much is known: Receiver Michael Irvin was in some way
involved in the incident that caused offensive lineman Everett
McIver to suffer a deep gash on his neck. Beyond that, the rest has
just been rumors and speculation.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to be true that the wound was inflicted with a pair
of scissors during an argument over a haircut, though none of the
principals is talking.
</P>
<P>
   Jones admits to sitting down with both players to ensure no
problems linger. He adamantly denies, however, any knowledge of a
purported payoff between the two designed to stifle public
discussion. It was reported that Irvin, with or without the help of
Jones, paid McIver an amount in the high six figures to buy his
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not given anyone any money,'' Irvin said, breaking more
than a weeklong silence on the subject. ``I didn't pay anybody
anything. There has been no deal.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to believe McIver's silence would be worth a
significant sum to both Irvin and Jones. The Wichita Falls
authorities are helpless to make an arrest without McIver's filing
a complaint. Because no witnesses have come forward _ on the
insistence of head coach Chan Gailey _ they have no evidence a
crime was committed.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, in his original news conference after the incident
occurred, characterized it as ``horseplay'' that somehow resulted
in injury, stressing McIver was not to blame. Unless another
witness comes forward with a different version, both the campus and
city police have to characterize it as an accident.
</P>
<P>
   That is crucial for Irvin, who is already serving a probationary
period after pleading no contest to cocaine-possession charges in
1996. Assault with a deadly weapon would certainly be a probation
violation, which could send him to jail for up to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive to keep Irvin out of jail is obvious. The
perennial Pro Bowler caught 75 passes for 1,180 yards and nine
touchdowns last year. No other Cowboys receiver had more than 47
catches or four touchdowns. And when Irvin missed the first five
games of the 1996 season after a league suspension connected to the
drug-possession charge, the Cowboys went 2-3. They won eight of
their final 11 games once he returned, and he again led the team in
receptions and receiving yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jones denies any role in a payoff or any knowledge of
such.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not aware of any deal,'' he insisted. ``I know of no
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And though the police are not investigating the incident, the
NFL may be. In July 1997, the league instituted its new
violent-crime policy, which serves up possible fines and/or
suspensions for players involved in such conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The policy states that league employees cannot ``engage in or
aid, abet or conspire to engage in or incite violent criminal
activity.'' The policy goes on to give examples of violent crimes,
including ``any crime involving the use or threat of physical
violence to a person or persons.''
</P>
<P>
   While the policy does not set out specific punishments, it does
require clinical evaluation and counseling for any employee found
to have engaged in such activity. Further punishment is left up to
the commissioner, though the policy clearly states that players can
be suspended from participation in preseason, regular-season and
postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials have refused comment as to whether they are
looking into the situation, though Jones has said he expects they
probably will.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, McIver returned to practice Monday for the
first time since suffering the injury July 29. He has been assured
he will keep his starting job at right guard, though he said he has
some catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you miss time, going through the season, it's a
setback,'' McIver said. ``I've got a lot to make up, but I'm
willing to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   McIver should see significant playing time when the Cowboys face
the New England Patriots in Mexico City on Monday. He did not play
in the first two exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be better off if he had gotten the work in,'' Jones
said. ``But considering that he's a veteran with some skills, it's
not as much of a concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger concern is the distraction the incident caused and
the unwanted spotlight the Cowboys once again find shining on them.
McIver and Irvin insist the air has been cleared between them, and
the other players say they've gotten better at dealing with such
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been a concern of mine,'' quarterback Troy Aikman
said. ``The media has said a lot about this, and maybe in the past
this would have taken away from what we do on the field. But I
don't think this has at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an initiation, however, for rookie coach Gailey, who
says he never expected everything to go perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you think things are going to go completely smooth
all the time, you're living a little bit in a dream world,'' Gailey
said. ``There are going to be problems. There are going to be ups
and downs. How you deal with it is the key. You deal with it. You
go on to the next one. You work together as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've handled it. I've talked about it. It's done. You can't
get caught up in that, or you don't go forward where you are
supposed to go forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
