<P>
   (NYT9) CHICAGO -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- DRINKING-VINEGAR, 8-11 --
Lustered on a silver tray in the center of Seasons, the restaurant
in the Four Seasons Hotel in Chicago, are slender hand-blown flasks
of liquids in tones of pale straw, amber and burgundy. Grappas?
Liqueurs? Guess again. The bottles are filled with vinegars, served
as aperitifs or as palate-refreshers between courses, for $4 a
glass. ``It's a big eye-catcher,'' says Andreas Kappenhagen, the
director of the restaurant. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- CHARWOOD, 8-11 -- A blend of
Chunk Charwood (charred Canadian sugar maple) and chunks of wood
cut for grilling. They are sold separately by Peoples
Woods/Nature's Own. The result is a clean, dry heat that seals in
flavor. (David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SIMPLE-COOKING, 8-11 --
Unlike peaches, whose raw glory can barely be improved upon,
tomatoes are all about potential. The difference between consuming
a tomato out of hand and slicing it, then sprinkling it with a
pinch of salt and a few drops of olive oil, is the difference
between a snack and a dish. And the great thing about tomatoes is
that it takes so little to convert them from one to the other.
(David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- NY-LATE-NIGHT-DINING-2, 8-11
-- At Clementine, young Wall Street types spend some time at the
34-seat bar and then share plates of food with friends. For many,
it's the first stop of the night. In July, Clementine expanded its
late-night menu, tempting night crawlers with dishes like grilled
stuffed squid in a cumin broth as late as 3:15 a.m. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- NY-LATE-NIGHT-DINING-1, 8-11
-- Florent in the meat-packing district attracts bankers, fashion
industry types and performers like Flotilla DeBarge and Jeffrey
Breaux. New York has always had a late-night subculture of 24-hour
diners. But now, with a growing number of affluent artists,
entrepreneurs and Wall Streeters working long, hard hours, the
city's high-end restaurateurs are beginning to stay up late
themselves, and offer serious food all through the night. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 8-11 --
Manhattan's Solera restaurant serves fino sherries like Tio Pepe
from Gonzalez Byass, La Ina from Dome and Alvear's Fino Montilla.
Most sherries come from the white-chalk vineyards around the city
of Jerez, in Andalusia, the southernmost province of Spain.
(Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ULSTER COUNTY, N.Y. -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SWEET-CORN-2,
8-11 -- Silver Queen corn, an older variety known for its big white
ear and full corn flavor, in early development at Caradonna Farms
in Ulster County. This type of corn was grown widely earlier in the
century and must be rushed to market soon after picking, as it
starts to lose its sweetness. In the last 20 years, it has been
supplanted by hardier varieties that stay sweet longer. (Chris
Ramirez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MIDDLETOWN, N.Y. -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- SWEET-CORN-1, 8-11
-- At Sycamore Farms in Middletown, Henry Smith picks an ear of
white Incredible sweet corn, a sugar-enhanced variety that is
quicker and easier to grow than varieties grown in years past. For
150 years, breeders have experimented with sweet corns to improve
flavor, texture, tenderness, appearance, growing time and
hardiness. But only in the last 20 years have any real strides been
made. (Chris Ramirez/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Aug. 11, 1998 -- PROFILE-STITH-BOS, 8-11 -- The
Rev. Charles Stith, longtime activist and recently named ambassador
to Tanzania, sits in his office in the Back Bay area of Boston.
Stith is just back from Washington, from a hurried trip to the
State Department crisis center monitoring the aftermath of the
bombings of U.S. embassies in Dar es Salaam and Nairobi. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
