<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PUBLIC PRESIDENT SHOWS NO SIGN HE'S LEWINSKY-LEERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As his rendezvous with a grand jury draws near,
the face that President Clinton shows in public could not seem more
relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   In a whirlwind coast-to-coast political fund-raising tour this
week, the president has appeared upbeat, energetic and, above all,
engaged in his official duties, keeping an eye on the plunging
stock market and vowing revenge against terrorists who bombed two
embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever steps he is taking behind the scenes to prepare for his
grand jury testimony next Monday about Monica Lewinsky, his public
face is calm and confident.
</P>
<P>
   With an actor's skill, his hands in fluid gesture, he conducts
fact-laden tutorials with Democratic Party donors on issues like
Social Security and the environment, muses about his advancing age
and brags on what terrific shape the country is in.
</P>
<P>
   In a move unusual of late, he visited reporters on his airplane
during a late-night flight Monday, casting himself in the role of
movie reviewer. They were watching ``Deep Impact.'' Clinton,
roaming by in his bluejeans like a college student pacing the dorm
during finals, said ``Armageddon'' was better. But really, he said,
``Zorro'' was ``the best movie of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters reached for their notebooks, the president
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax,'' he instructed on his way out of range. ``The workday
is over.''
</P>
<P>
   For perhaps everyone but Clinton. The combination of
circumstances _ his pending testimony, the rampant speculation in
Washington over whether he will or should make a public statement
about Ms. Lewinsky, whether his presidency has been irreparably
weakened _ gives an added layer of meaning to his often ruminative
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   One theme that has emerged is a sense that he can never let down
his guard _ and that the political is quite personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have you done in the times in your life when you thought
everything was hunky-dory?'' he said in a fund-raising speech in
Chicago. ``The natural thing to do is to sort of say: `Man, I have
been working like crazy. This is great. Leave me alone. Give me a
break.'''
</P>
<P>
   But relaxing, he said, would be a mistake. ``Instead,'' he
continued, ``we ought to say: `Hey, we may not get a time this good
again for a while. Let's take this time to think about the big,
long-term challenges this country faced, and let's go on and face
them and deal with them now.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is his message, whether referring to terrorists in Africa
or Republicans in Congress. ``Now is the time to bear down,'' he
said defiantly, ``not back up.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, much of the impression of a president not
preoccupied by matters Lewinsky is by careful design. A pristine
water-treatment plant high in the hills above San Francisco _ as
far as possible from Washington _ provided Tuesday's backdrop for
Clinton to talk about clean water.
</P>
<P>
   While his old Arkansas buddy and image adviser Harry Thomason
was testifying to the grand jury back in Washington, Clinton was
telling a low-key handpicked audience of about 100 officials and
plant employees, ``Today is a happy day.'' He added later, ``Safe
water is something all Americans agree on.''
</P>
<P>
   Another stop was at a hotel ballroom here where 700 people paid
more than $1,000 each and rose to their feet as he entered. ``We
love you!'' one of them shouted. The event was one of three Tuesday
where Clinton helped bring in more than $3 million for the
Democratic nominee for governor of California, Lt. Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   At each chance, those who introduce the president refer to the
breadth of his knowledge and the high-mindedness of his purpose. At
the water-treatment plant, Rep. Tom Lantos described him as ``the
environmental president'' but quickly added That he could also be
called ``the education president and the public-safety president
and the good-economy president.''
</P>
<P>
   People along the way seem to appreciate Clinton's public
determination to avoid the topic that has consumed Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nonissue,'' Marguerite Young, the California director
of Clean Action, said as she bobbed her infant on her chest and
listened to Clinton talk about protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's concerned about the things he's in charge of,'' she said.
``He's not in charge of having a perfect private life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
