<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLEBY TRIES TO HIDE THE SORROW  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It is difficult to imagine the grief Stuart
Appleby will feel as he competes in the PGA Championship this week.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's wife, Renay, was killed on July 23 in an accident
outside a train station in London. As Stuart and Renay were
unloading luggage from a taxi, Renay was crushed between the taxi
and another car when the driver mistakenly thought he was in
reverse instead of drive.
</P>
<P>
   What could be worse than watching your 25-year-old wife die? Why
did this happen? How do you go on?
</P>
<P>
   Almost three weeks later, Appleby is still trying to sort out
those questions, and so many others. He will tee off in a
tournament Thursday for the first time since the accident, not
knowing what to expect, but knowing Renay would want him to
continue playing the game he loves.
</P>
<P>
   However, the greatest love in Appleby's life has been taken
away. And as Appelby courageously answered questions at a news
conference Tuesday afternoon at Sahalee Country Club, he broke down
in tears several times, unable to hide his sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest times are when you do a lot of thinking, when you
just wish things were different,'' said Appleby, a 27-year-old
native of Australia, who met Renay in 1992 and married her in
December of 1996. ``It's tough getting through nights. When you
really love someone, you miss the simple things. Everyone has been
fantastic, but no one can replace that person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of good times. I feel very lucky that I knew her.
The time we spent together was real quality. I feel like she was
first prize of a raffle, so to speak. I was lucky enough to win
her. She was obviously only here for a short time, but she had a
huge impact on a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy has saddened the atmosphere of the year's final
major championship, with Appleby's peers determined to help him
through his ordeal. Renay was an outstanding golfer and she made
many friends among the players when she spent several months as
Stuart's caddie during the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Until the accident, Appleby was having the most successful year
of his career, with $678,562 in winnings, four top-10 finishes, and
a victory at the Kemper Open in June. Appleby's friends are glad to
see him back on tour.
</P>
<P>
   `` He said he would rather be busy than sitting at home thinking
about it,'' said Robert Allenby, a fellow Australian golfer, who
has known Appleby since they were teenagers competing in junior
tournaments. ``I'm sure Renee would have told him to get off his
butt and play. That's the type of person she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Allenby recalled Renay's first impression of Stuart, when they
met as members of an Australian golf team that traveled to the
United States to compete against college teams. It was hardly love
at first sight.
</P>
<P>
   `` They had a fight, and she thought he was a stuck-up pig,''
said Allenby .``That was Renay. She said what she thought. But it
was from that trip that they really got together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't surprise me that they ended up together. She had
such a personality and a funny sense of humor. She'd joke about
anything and everything. It's so tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   So tragic that many people don't know what to say, or what to
do. But Appelby is trying his best to cope. Tuesday, he played a
practice round with Allenby, Tiger Woods, and Mark O'Meara. Appleby
owns a home in Orlando, Fla., where he is neighbors of both Woods
and O'Meara. Woods still found it hard to believe what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday I saw him for the first time, and it was tough to
even talk to him,'' said Woods. ``I almost teared up on the spot. I
get a little choked up talking about it. My heart goes out to him
and his entire family. I knew Renay just a little bit as a friend,
and she was a genuine person, just the greatest. From a player's
standpoint, if he ever needs us at any time, he can find us, pick
up the phone, we're always there We'll drop whatever we're doing,
because to lose a loved one like that so quickly and tragically is
just a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby has not been to his Orlando home since the accident. The
house was one of Renay's joys, and the memories of their times
there are still overwhelming. For now, Appleby is taking each day,
step by step. He plans to play in the Sprint International next
week, as well as the NEC World Series of Golf in two weeks, trying
to establish some kind of normal routine. However, nothing for
Appleby will be quite the same again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not an hour that goes by that I don't think of her,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would she want me to do? She would want me to get back.
I've just got to imagine that she's here and she's helping me, and
everything will be okay.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
