<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BORDER-SHOPPING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN BUCK STOPS AT THE BORDER; WEAK CURRENCY HURTING U.S.
BUSINESSES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OGDENSBURG, N.Y. _ It is high summer in the North Country, with
the back-to-school shopping season fast approaching. Time for local
business people to reminisce about the days not so long ago when
the Canadians flocked across the border as dependably as the
swallows to Capistrano.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would show up with empty suitcases and literally no spare
clothes, and they would do all their clothes shopping in one
afternoon,'' said Norman V. Garrelts, the president of Hacketts, a
local department store here, recalling another North Country store
he once managed. ``At the end of the day, the parking lot would be
covered with empty shopping bags.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Canadians are staying away. The Canadian dollar has
fallen to its lowest level in modern times, and the commercial
fortunes of dozens of towns along the border have fallen with it.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if half the people around here had suddenly moved away.
Along almost all of the U.S.-Canada border, the Canadian side is
much more populous, and shopping by Canadians, who were drawn
across the border by lower sales taxes, longer shopping hours and
often more choices, has formed an important part of local markets
on the American side.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Canadian dollar began to plummet, however, trips by
Canadians to New York state, by far the biggest destination for
Canadians, declined by 9.3 percent, to 2.4 million trips in 1997
from 2.6 million in 1996, according to Statistics Canada, a
government agency. Canadian spending in the United States has
declined for each of the three consecutive quarters ending in
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three shopping centers, and one is derelict, one is
struggling and the third is half-full,'' Garrelts said. ``We were
just over-stored, and it was all based on getting the Canadian
dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects of the Canadian dollar's drop have been felt all
along the snaking border. At the Bellisfair Mall in Bellingham,
Wash., business is down 5 percent to 10 percent, said John
Bucksbaum, the executive vice president at General Growth
Properties, which owns the mall. And Blaine, Wash., which sits
right on the border, seems to be hurting even more.
</P>
<P>
   Mickie Blazicevic, a supervisor at Cost Cutters in Blaine, said
that even with the discount outlet's lower prices there were fewer
Canadians going across the border regularly to buy groceries. And
several gas stations in the area have closed.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, towns that had refashioned themselves as French
Canadian tourist destinations, complete with signs in French, are
also feeling the pinch, said Vaughn Stinson, the executive director
of the Maine Publicity Bureau. ``It's really been very, very
soft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For most Americans, the decline in Canadian spending in the
United States may mean little more than a drop in the number of
Canadian quarters, pennies and dimes that show up in their pocket
change. But people in the North Country, as the four New York
counties that border the St. Lawrence River are known, have close
ties to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are oriented toward Canada, absolutely,'' said Ram L. Chugh
(pronounced choodge), a professor of economics and director of the
Rural Services Institute at the State University College at
Potsdam. ``Our commercial relations are not only with Canada, but
our major cultural, sophisticated and important urban areas are
Ottawa and Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, people here follow the value of the Canadian
dollar the way farmers watch the weather. Driven down by the low
worldwide demand for Canadian commodities, which is partly a
function of the Asian economic crisis, the value of the Canadian
dollar has fallen from a high of 89.3 cents in American money in
1990 to 66 cents, a loss of 26 percent of the Canadian dollar's
purchasing power in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on the Ogdensburg Bridge to Canada reflects the widening
disparity between the two dollars. Bridge crossings hit a peak of
866,000 in 1991-92, when the Canadian dollar could still hold its
own, but has declined without interruption each year since, to
517,000 crossings both ways in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, as the Canadian dollar slid, American businesses
tried to keep their Canadian customers by giving them, in effect, a
discount. Signs saying: ``Canadian at par,'' offered equal value
for both currencies at many stores. Informal discounts are still
common _ one local motel gives Canadian customers 75 cents for
their dollar, instead of the market's 66 cents _ but the advantage
has clearly moved across the river: ``$1.00 U.S. (EQ) $1.50
Canadian,'' says an advertisement for Young's clothing store in
Prescott, Ontario, that ran recently in local American papers.
</P>
<P>
   Do not blame Bobbie White, an 18-year old from Wallpole,
Ontario, who was on the American side the other day not to shop,
but to hunt for a job that pays in American dollars. ``To me, the
way the dollar has gone means `Stay on the Canadian side,' '' Ms.
White said. ``Everybody used to come over here to shop all the time
_ there were these long lines at the border going back _ but not
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White's first stop in job-hunting was at a sparkling,
500,000-square-foot mall built in Massena, 35 miles east of here,
to capture Canadian business. The St. Lawrence Centre _ even the
spelling is Canadian _ opened in 1990, when the Canadian dollar
stood at nearly 90 cents in American money and as the Canadian
government was about to impose the widely detested 7 percent
national sales tax, the Goods and Services Tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all of those factors, the Canadians were basically
flocking to the U.S.,'' said Ron Patnode, director of marketing for
the mall. ``Our license plate count showed that 40 percent to 50
percent of our shoppers were Canadian, but then it began to
decline.''
</P>
<P>
   The mall's license plate census hit 10 percent Canadians in
1995, Patnode said, but it has come back some to about 20 percent
to 22 percent. ``They're still coming, but it's not like it was
before,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
