<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW PROFILE HELPS PETER DEVELOP AS A GIANT  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nineteen months after he signed with the Giants
as a free agent in what was a highly controversial episode for the
team, Christian Peter will start his first professional game Friday
against the Jacksonville Jaguars. Peter, a defensive tackle, will
replace the injured Robert Harris.
</P>
<P>
   It is only an exhibition start, but Giants coaches have said
that Peter should also play quite a bit in the regular season in a
rotation with Harris and Keith Hamilton at the two tackle spots.
</P>
<P>
   For Peter, who has a history of sexual and other assaults, this
promotion has been accepted without any conspicuous delight.
</P>
<P>
   Peter, who played sparingly last season, has insisted on
maintaining a low profile with the Giants. It comes with the
acknowledgment that his reputation precedes him. He has decided
that his best course is to be quiet off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``All anyone knows is what they've read about me in the
papers,'' Peter said as he stood on the Giants' practice field
after this afternoon's session. ``I understand that. I'm not a
saint and I made poor judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giants got me the help I needed, and now all I can do is
act the way I have, and maybe in time, people will change their
opinions of me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is evident that Peter's teammates have welcomed him more
warmly this season.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, he often was alone on the practice fields and in the
catacombs of Giants Stadium. At training camp last year, it was not
uncommon to see Peter eating by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was true or not, everybody had heard the stories,''
said linebacker Corey Widmer, who plays directly behind Peter in
most defensive formations. ``But I've gotten to know him; I think
several guys have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hung out a few times. I've seen him outside football and
I've seen no problems. I haven't seen him wanting to fight anybody.
He's level-headed. Contrary to what people may have read, I think
he's a good person.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys with crystal-clear images who I've gone out to
bars with and when I see them I go: `Holy cow, do they have
everybody fooled.'''
</P>
<P>
   Peter's new position as the third tackle on the depth chart _
this week, or after the return of Harris, who had fluid drained
from his knee _ is one of the surprising stories of a relatively
predictable Giants training camp.
</P>
<P>
   It is a big jump in one year for a player who some thought would
never play a down in a National Football League game.
</P>
<P>
   Peter was drafted in 1996 by the New England Patriots, but
reaction in Boston was so harsh that the Patriots released him
three days after picking him.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, the Giants signed Peter. He began training camp
strong, but faded as the weeks wore on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I burnt out,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' defensive coordinator, John Fox, said: ``Christian
had sat out a year without any football, and that is going to hurt
anybody. Plus he's a rookie. He's learning new defenses every day
and the game is quicker than he's ever played it. But we saw enough
to know he might make that leap that a lot of second-year players
do.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 1998 training camp opened, Peter was in better shape. He
seemed quicker and immediately impressed the coaches and the
Giants' offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the same traits as a tackle that Erik Howard had,''
Widmer said, referring to the Giants' former All-Pro tackle. ``He's
a fighter inside, and that's what those guys have to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter, 25, linked his improvement to his growth on a variety of
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little wiser and more mature,'' he said. ``I feel
quicker, but it's because I've taken the time to learn and get
stronger in a lot of ways. I'm proud of what I've done. Hopefully
it's just a beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants Coach Jim Fassel had a similar perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christian Peter has gone through a lot to get to this point,''
Fassel said. ``We've watched him pretty closely and he knew that.
He's come through that and right now he's got every chance to be a
very important part of our football team. I don't think he wants to
go back to where he was.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
