<HEADER>
A9057 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXASLOTTERY-GTECH-HN     08-11 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASLOTTERY-GTECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER HEAD OF TEXAS LOTTERY SETTLES LAWSUIT WITH GTECH CORP. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nora Linares, former director of the Texas
Lottery, has reached a settlement in her lawsuit against the
company that runs the state games, her lawyer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Linares had accused Gtech Corp. in a lawsuit filed in April 1997
of making a ``systematic effort'' to get her fired to take
attention away from the company's own wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney Buck Wood said Linares and Gtech agreed to a
settlement Tuesday, but he declined to discuss the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you my client is very pleased with the
settlement,'' Wood said. ``There was a financial aspect to the
settlement. It was not done for a feel-good statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gtech spokesman Marc Palazzo confirmed that a settlement had
been reached on ``mutually agreeable terms'' that he, too, declined
to discuss. Linares could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Linares sued Gtech after the Lottery Commission fired her in
January amid revelations that the company had briefly hired her
boyfriend for $30,000 in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   Linares, who said she did not know about the secret consulting
contract, accused Gtech of hiring her boyfriend ``in an effort to
have some potential future leverage'' over her.
</P>
<P>
   Gtech officials at the time called Linares' allegations ``false
and misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Gtech was facing its own troubles at the time the story about
Linares' boyfriend came out. State officials had begun questioning
the fact that the company was paying its chief Texas lobbyist $3
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Linares became a liability to Gtech and her continuing to
serve as lottery executive director served only to draw further
attention to Gtech's illegal corporate practices and questionable
relationships,'' her lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Linares' suit claimed Gtech launched a public relations campaign
against her that led to her firing.
</P>
<P>
   She originally sued the lottery commissioners who fired her, but
then dropped that effort in favor of suing Gtech.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the controversy, state lottery commissioners
decided to rebid Gtech's $160-million-a-year state contract. Gtech
refused to take part in the bidding process, and ultimately the
commission decided the least expensive way to run the lottery was
to stay with Gtech.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery director hired to replace Linares, Lawrence Littwin,
was fired after just four months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Littwin claimed his firing was politically motivated, saying the
lottery commissioners did not want to take on Gtech when Gov.
George W. Bush was facing re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Gtech, in its lawsuit to stop the rebidding process, claimed
Littwin had been prejudiced against the company and had made
derogatory comments about the company at a lottery convention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
