<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GABRIELE-MUNTER-ART-2     08-11 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GABRIELE-MUNTER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST IN THE GLOW OF THE MAN AT HER SIDE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The history of 20th-century art has had more than its share of
female artists whose achievements have been overshadowed by the art
of their better-known male companions.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes Sonia Delaunay, Lee Krasner, Frida Kahlo,
Helen Torr, Marguerite Zorach and Anni Albers. Georgia O'Keeffe is
one of the few exempted from this category, largely because her
husband, the photographer Alfred Steiglitz, worked tirelessly on
her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the importance of the male halves in the
relationships varies a lot, as demonstrated simply by reciting, in
parallel order, the names of the men attached to the women listed
above: Robert Delaunay, Jackson Pollock, Diego Rivera, Arthur Dove,
William Zorach and Josef Albers. But in comparison, the work of
their female companions has received proportionately far less
attention.
</P>
<P>
   One almost suspects some unwritten (or should we say
unconscious?) agreement that a closer look at the women's art would
be too threatening to the significance of their significant others.
</P>
<P>
   But what is threatened is not so much an individual artist's
stature as our understanding of artistic invention, and our
tendency to view it as the province of a single artist rather than
something shared and by definition collaborative. Lee Krasner, for
example, is not equal in stature or importance to Jackson Pollock,
and no amount of historical research will make her so.
</P>
<P>
   But her work deserves examination, and its quality, especially
early on, strongly suggests that she had a role in Pollock's
development _ that it would not have been the same without her.
</P>
<P>
   It may be fine for Picasso to have identified Braque as ``ma
femme'' during the early years of Cubism; it is less so for
artists, or the art historians who tend their flames, to identify
the women who really were their wives as artistic partners. But no
artist is an island _ be he, or she, a movie director, composer or
painter.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to ``Gabriele Munter: The Expressionist Years,
1903-1920,'' an exhibition of 70 paintings, drawings and prints at
the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts in Richmond through Sept. 20. Even
for students and knowledgeable admirers of 20th-century art, Munter
(1877-1962) is little more than an elusive presence in the annals
of German Expressionism.
</P>
<P>
   For decades she has been mentioned in these histories, when
mentioned at all, as pupil and companion of the Russian painter
Wassily Kandinsky. Such citings can't be avoided: with Kandinsky,
Munter was one of the founding members of the Blaue Reiter group in
1911. But she did much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   This show was organized by Reinhold Heller, a professor of art
history at the University of Chicago, for the Milwaukee Art Museum,
which has the largest group of works by Munter, 11 in all, outside
Germany. Showing roughly a third of Munter's output during the
period under scrutiny and none of her later paintings, the
exhibition cannot be considered definitive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it presents enough work _ much of it being seen in this
country for the first time _ to verify that Munter and her art
deserve far more attention than they have received. Backing this
conclusion is Heller's catalogue text, which draws on Munter's
letters and journals as well as on interviews from the late 1940s
and '50s. It gives the first detailed account in English of her
life, artistic development and relationship with Kandinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship seems to have been fairly tumultuous,
punctuated by passionate times together, by separations
crisscrossed with letters that often involved lengthy discussions
of art, and finally by recriminations and betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Munter and Kandinsky, 11 years her senior and married, met and
fell in love in 1902, when Munter, determined to be an artist and
dissatisfied with her training, enrolled in Kandinsky's drawing
class at the experimental, short-lived Phalanx School in Munich. It
was just about the only place in Germany where women could study
art alongside men, the alternative being a dilettantish ``ladies'
art academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 11 years they often worked side by side and openly
lived together. Kandinsky taught her, already a skilled draftsman,
to draw in a quick, loose shorthand style _ as the prints and
drawings in this exhibition strikingly attest _ and to translate
this approach into painting.
</P>
<P>
   He praised her natural talent and innate vision and encouraged
her to try this or that method or medium. But he was not above
pettiness, reacting jealously if she wrote of interest in another
artist's work (Picasso's, for example); complaining that their
stressful situation, which made Munter something of a social
outcast, was just as hard on him; and condescendingly patting her
on the head, as when he suggested in a letter from 1903 that
woodcuts might be ``much too much for the small, poor (lazy)
Ella.''
</P>
<P>
   They spent 14 crucial months (May 1907 to June 1908) together in
and around Paris, working on prints and absorbing the ideas of the
Parisian avant-garde, especially the work of van Gogh, Gauguin, the
Fauves and Matisse. But when World War I forced Kandinsky back to
Russia and he finally obtained a divorce, he married another woman.
</P>
<P>
   Munter spent most of the war waiting for him in Scandinavia. She
did not learn of the marriage until after 1921, when Kandinsky sent
a lawyer to collect paintings of his in her possession. Of such a
saga, one can only say: screenwriters, start your laptops.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to report that the show in Richmond will knock
your socks off. It won't, but it will peel them off gradually and
surreptitiously. Munter was, quietly and forcefully, a terrific
artist _ a superb draftsman, inventive colorist and daring
manipulator of paint and pictorial space, thanks to an innately
casual, confident touch.
</P>
<P>
   Her tendency to simplify reality into economical, nearly
abstract components is in step with her artistically momentous
times, and sometimes a little ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   Especially riveting here are a series of small, radiant
landscapes made in Murnau during the summer of 1908, in which she
builds upon the tenets of Fauvism by concocting more unusual,
discordant colors and broadening the often stippled brushwork that
the Fauves carried over from Impressionism. The resulting bold
shapes, which are really little autonomous slabs of paint, grant
her extraordinary colors full voice.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Murnau Moors'' of 1908, for example, the landscape
progresses through fields of light yellow-green, turquoise and
peach to mountains of electric blue and then violet, finishing with
a sky of more, but softer, light green and yellow. These hues are
dramatized by small, framing intervals of darker, more traditional
colors, greens and browns in quick, fat strokes that indicate trees
and low-lying hills.
</P>
<P>
   In her paintings of the village of Murnau, Munter's colors
become even more electric, in part because the actual facades were
painted different colors, but also because their contiguous planes,
windows and shutters gave her more options for contrasts within a
more restricted space.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, beyond her sex, that Munter is only now beginning to
receive her due may be that she doesn't entirely fit the German
Expressionist profile. The people in her portraits rarely seem
troubled or anxious; only occasionally does a landscape seem at all
threatening, as in the uncharacteristically drab, barren terrain
that isolates the single dwelling in ``The Green House, Murnau'' of
1911.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Munter's natural artistic inclinations _ her emphasis
on color, direct paint handling and distortions of reality _ may
have contributed to the style's development. Without reproducing
any visual evidence, Heller argues as much, asserting that in
August 1908, Kandinsky and Munter, along with the Russian painter
Alexei Jawlensky, worked together closely in Murnau developing a
new way of painting.
</P>
<P>
   He claims that no one artist was dominant and that their works
were sometimes indistinguishable. In other words, a three-person
version of Picasso and Braque.
</P>
<P>
   But Munter's work fits in at several other locations on the map
of early 20th-century modernism. She remained far more within the
orbit of the French styles, especially Fauvism, that influenced all
the German Expressionists.
</P>
<P>
   For her, Fauvism was not simply a jumping-off point for a more
rhetorical mode, be it Kirchner's bitter social satire or
Kandinsky's dynamic rumblings. Instead she built directly upon it,
extending it as other French artists, most notably Matisse, were
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Like Matisse, Munter painted for the sake of painting, for the
pleasure of recording her perceptions of the visible world in such
a way that the colors and forms on the canvas took precedence, but
without obliterating that world. And like Matisse, she envisioned
art as an extremely intelligent armchair that soothed but also
stimulated.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Munter's ``Still Life, Yellow'' and ``Still Life,
Red'' of 1909, with their blunt compositions, bright dominant
colors and black outlines, are startlingly close to Matisse's work
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   She seems not so much to be borrowing from Matisse as to be
paralleling his exploration while using other inspirations,
especially the children's art that she began to collect around
1908.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the French affinities, Munter's ability to imbue her
images with a singular personality, through color and paint
handling, also relates to certain American painters of the same
period, especially Marsden Hartley, who visited her in Munich in
1913, Arthur Dove and to some extent O'Keeffe.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, Heller cites a journey to Texas to visit
American relatives in 1898-99 as a formative influence on Munter,
who photographed the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Munter was one of several European and American painters who
continued to narrow the gap between method and meaning that the
Impressionists had begun to close. Her paintings told the story of
their own making with directness and honesty in a way that
Kandinsky's large early abstractions, for all their influential
all-overness, never mustered. Subsequent painting has made
extensive use of both approaches.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition and its catalogue may raise more questions than
they answer, but the questions are fascinating and raise equally
fascinating larger ones about the nature of originality and the
collaborative nature of all creativity.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, show and text also open a very specific field
of inquiry for other art historians and curators concerning
Gabriele Munter's art, her role in the development of Kandinsky's
art and her contribution to the modernist enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Munter could be the last artist's helpmate of the 20th century
to be recognized in her own right; and she may be one of the most
significant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
