<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLBOARDS-AD-COLUMN-     08-11 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLBOARDS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BILLBOARDS STILL MAKE SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As a young man, L. Lowry Mays bet his future on
oil, becoming a petroleum engineer. A few years later, thinking the
stock market, which was then booming, would be more fun, he went to
Harvard University, earned an MBA and became an investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   Mays turned to another career 10 years later _ this time as a
radio entrepreneur. Teaming up with a flamboyant San Antonio car
salesman, Red McCombs, now the owner of the Minnesota Vikings, he
paid $130,000 for a local FM station.
</P>
<P>
   That venture grew into Clear Channel Communications Inc., a
company that owns 230 radio stations in the United States and has
full or partial ownership in an additional 163 stations outside the
country. It also owns or operates 18 television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mays, while continuing to amass radio stations,
expanded into yet another field: billboards. Today Clear Channel,
where Mays is chief executive, is the largest outdoor advertising
concern in the world.
</P>
<P>
   All this might sound a bit as though Mays, now 63, is an
acquisitive gambler. Acquisitive? Definitely. A gambler? If so, a
very deliberate one. His company relies less on debt than is common
in the industry, often buying with stock or cash. And Mays has a
reputation for shrewdly assessing the profit potential of each
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Investing in billboards, he said, simply made sense; indeed,
Mays expects billboards to dominate company revenues by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor advertising grew 8.8 percent last year, the largest jump
in the last 13 years, according to the Outdoor Advertising
Association of America, a trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Fletcher, the association's president and chief executive,
predicts that billboards will continue to flourish because of media
fragmentation, technological improvements and an increase in the
time Americans spend driving. ``All three factors are growing,''
she said. ``I've been in this business 22 years and I have to pinch
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays, in a recent interview at his compact company headquarters
near the San Antonio airport, said, ``The reason that people want
to reach people out of home is because the mobility of our society
escalates every year,'' whether it involves two adults driving to
work each morning or so-called stay-at-home spouses hurtling
between soccer matches.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Transportation, Americans drove
2.4 trillion miles in 1995, more than double the number of miles
driven in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Also, improvements in billboards have attracted more
advertisers. Rather than painters slowly rendering an ad on
sections of wood or metal, now computers print sharp images on
vinyl, which can be hung quickly and moved as needed.
</P>
<P>
   That new technology, said Gordon Hodge, an analyst with
Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities, has made billboards and bus
shelters more attractive to fashion advertisers like Calvin Klein
and consumer products companies like Procter &AMP; Gamble, which has
used billboards to advertise Pantene shampoo. ``It was very
important for the sheen of the hair to come through,'' Hodge said.
``I think before the vinyl it was not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason national advertisers have been attracted to what
had been largely a local-plus-tobacco medium, is that the outdoor
advertising business has consolidated rapidly in the two years
since Outdoor Systems Inc. of Phoenix bought Gannett Co.'s outdoor
division. Larger companies can offer more billboards in more
markets, Hodge said, making the buying easier for these
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel entered the outdoor market in February 1997 with
an agreement to buy Eller Media Corp. and its 50,000 billboards for
$1.15 billion in cash and stock. Eight months later, the company
announced it would add 34,000 billboards through the $1.7 billion
purchase of Universal Outdoor Holdings Inc.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Clear Channel reached across the Atlantic to buy the
London-based More Group PLC for $760 million, giving it an
additional 90,000 billboards and bus shelter display surfaces in 22
countries and pushing Clear Channel to No. 1 in the international
outdoor advertising market.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hodge, Outdoor Systems Inc. still has a small edge
in the United States, where Clear Channel has 90,000 displays.
</P>
<P>
   Mays said he would continue to hunt for billboard companies that
are likely to provide a healthy return on investment _ 20 percent
after taxes and interest on the money invested is the company's
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards mesh well with the company's other media holdings,
Mays said, allowing Clear Channel to offer advertisers a third
outlet and allowing the company's radio and TV programs to
advertise on their own billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel received almost half its $697.1 million in 1997
revenues from radio, but Randall Mays, Mays' 33-year-old son and
the company's chief financial officer, predicts that 50 percent of
1998 revenues will come from outdoor advertising, with 40 percent
from radio and perhaps 10 percent from TV.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is publicly traded, is not worried about what
the recent spate of tobacco industry settlements and proposed
settlements will mean for billboards. Clear Channel is already
moving away from tobacco, the elder Mays said. Cigarette companies
buy a lot of billboards, and they want lower rates, he said. ``We
can replace those at higher prices,'' he continued, and at the same
time avoid being vulnerable to a settlement that could pull all
tobacco ads at once.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco has already fallen to No. 3 in billboard spending, after
entertainment and business and consumer services, according to
Competitive Media Reporting, a data research company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
