<SLUG> BC-FBN-TURNOVERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE DETERMINES FIELD POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defense wins championships _ that is an overused axiom in pro
football. But it happens to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Once a team kicks its running game into gear, dispenses a
passing attack that averages plenty in yards per pass attempt while
avoiding sacks, and offers high-rolling special teams, then its
defense can complement everything by continually feeding its
offense the ball.
</P>
<P>
   A stout defense, which can be the foundation for a team, has
several ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing turnovers is a gigantic plus.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Giants' defense led the National Football
Conference with 44 turnovers forced, and Kansas City and Pittsburgh
led the American Football Conference with 34 apiece. Each of those
teams won 10 or more games. Each was a divisional champion.
</P>
<P>
   Preventing first downs, of course, is also critical.
</P>
<P>
   A defense that forces several three-plays-and-a-punt series
sparkles. It provides more chances for its own offense and more
chances to tire the opposing defense.
</P>
<P>
   Two key areas, however, help to separate monster defenses from
kitten ones in today's National Football League _ yardage gained
via sacks and via interceptions. These elements create havoc for
offenses. Both create excellent field position for your team and
terrible field position for the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Peek at the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, they won the NFC East with an offense that
struggled mightily; in total offensive yards gained, it ranked 27th
of the 30 NFL teams.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants' defense kept giving the offense field position
and chances. It had 27 interceptions (most in the league) and
gained 503 return yards on those thefts. No other NFL team topped
500 yards, and only one other team topped 400 (Kansas City with
432). The Giants also added another 341 yards worth of field
position in their 54 sacks. Add the interception yardage gained
with sack yardage gained and the Giants' total was 844 yards. No
other NFL team cracked 800 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Giants' defense of '97 soared in creating
opportunity and being the club's spine.
</P>
<P>
   The top seven NFL defensive teams in yardage gained via sacks
and interceptions each won nine or more games. Four won 12 or more.
Each made the playoffs with the exception of the Jets, who finished
fifth in this category with 621 yards. The Jets' success in this
area was a huge factor in their fighting for a playoff spot until
the last day of the regular season and in turning a 1-15 team in
1996 into a 9-7 squad last year.
</P>
<P>
   So, want a top-caliber NFL defense? Sack 'em for big losses.
Intercept and run rampant on the return.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the teams that were in the Super Bowl last
year, they had the two best quarterbacks,'' Ted Cottrell, the
Buffalo Bills' new defensive coordinator, said of Denver's John
Elway and Green Bay's Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age, the quarterback can be the show, and if
you can sack him or intercept him, your defense wins. We tell our
defensive backs to break on the ball. Knocking down a pass is fine;
we'd rather have the ball. Then, once we get it on the
interception, our guys are taught that they are no longer on
defense. They are on offense. And if the other offense is lazy, we
are going to get a big return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys on the opposing offense are not used to tackling or
used to getting blocked. We look at these two things on a per-game
basis. We don't want five interceptions in one game and then not
another for two weeks. Per game, each game, how are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams in training camp now ask themselves, how are we doing
here? The answers for a few follow, with each team's defensive
sacks and interceptions in parentheses:
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (59/16) Good news: the Saints led the league in
sacks. Bad news: Saints quarterbacks were sacked 50 times. The
Saints gained 408 yards in sacks; they lost 317 yards when their
quarterback was sacked. They were intercepted 17 times more than
they intercepted others and lost 148 more yards on interceptions
than they gained. They spun their wheels. Their camp points
strictly to offensive discipline.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINA (36/11) The Panthers gained only 72 return yards on
their defensive interceptions. Compare that with San Francisco's
366 yards in toppling the Panthers for the NFC West title and it is
easy to see why Carolina seeks improvement.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO (46/15) No Bill gained more than two interceptions last
season; 23 NFL teams featured a player with at least four thefts.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (38/25) In yards gained via defensive sacks and
interceptions, the Rams ranked 10th in the league, but they won
only five games. Their offense did too little and did not protect
the ball (44 sacks for 326 yards lost and 30 turnovers).
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND (45/19) Pittsburgh earned one more interception than
the Patriots' 19 but gained 133 fewer yards than the Patriots did
on interception-return yardage. That means that the Patriots played
teams whose offenses could not tackle after the interception or
that the Patriots' interceptors were more swift and fancy on
returns.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (43/14) The Eagles' offense, once intercepted,
allowed 425 return yards and 4 touchdowns on those thefts. It was
the only team to allow 400-plus yards in such a manner.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (31/10) This team ranked 28th in yards gained via
defensive sacks and interceptions but compensated with quarterback
Dan Marino and special teams _ and made the playoffs. The Dolphins
need improvement in defensive aggressiveness to push further.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
