</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-SCAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
70 COMPANIES ACCUSED OF USING TINSELTOWN GLAMOUR TO FLEECE
INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Demonstrating that Tinseltown's glitter isn't
always gold, federal officials on Tuesday announced a nationwide
crackdown against 70 businesses and individuals accused of
operating bogus entertainment scams that bilked thousands of
investors out of at least $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Con artists promise Titanic profits, but too often investors
end up going down with the ship,'' said Denise Voigt Crawford,
president of the North American Securities Administrators
Association Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Risky Business, a sweeping action by a three-agency
task force, focused on schemes covering a wide range of
entertainment projects, including television programming, movies,
an infomercial for Elvis Presley memorabilia and a proposed
Internet casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``These investment opportunities are peddled as bright, new
initiatives. But they're actually the same old story,'' said Jodie
Bernstein, director of the Federal Trade Commission's Bureau of
Consumer Protection. ``They are touted with fabulous earnings
claims, promoted with deceptions and virtually all the investors
end up losing their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that in some cases the ventures being pushed by
telemarketers didn't exist or if they did, had little chance of
succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, telemarketers would encourage investors to pour
money from individual retirement accounts into the schemes by
saying that the deals had been approved by the Internal Revenue
Service, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all false,'' Heather Hippsley, an assistant director in
the consumer protection bureau. ``Most of the money (invested) goes
to overhead and sales commissions. There is very little money for
the actual investment.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, 60 complaints were brought by the FTC, the Securities
and Exchange Commission and state securities regulators against
operators of the businesses that tried to cash in on the public's
fascination with Hollywood's glamour.
</P>
<P>
   One of the companies targeted, Los Angeles-based My Pet TV, was
accused of victimizing 1,200 investors who poured $16 million into
what was billed as the ``Children's Cable Network,'' which would
broadcast nonviolent, educational children's programs. Most of the
money was used to pay the company's principals and telemarketers,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is accused of then illegally diverting $650,000 that
remained from the initial investment into a cable television
network devoted to programming geared toward pet owners.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints were also filed against two affiliated companies,
Cable Marketing and Management Inc. and The Pet Channel, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals named in the complaints were Michael Marcovsky,
president, chairman and chief executive officer of My Pet TV, and
Sheldon Altfeld, president and chief executive of Cable Marketing
and Management and vice president of network operations for My Pet
TV.
</P>
<P>
   FTC officials said the two company executives have not responded
to the federal complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Automated Systems &AMP; Concepts International Inc. of Los Angeles
was accused of selling $10,000 investments in the production of
infomercials for such products as an Elvis Presley coffee-table
book, stamps and a collection of previously unreleased songs.
Federal officials estimate investors sunk $12 million into the
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Also named in the complaint were John R. Munoz, the company's
president; Timothy Munoz, president of Premier Entertainment, a
related business; and Frank Gale, vice president of Automated
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials could not provide any other information about
the three businessmen and their attorney could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
