<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9066 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-11 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TRUTH OR DARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., items in boldface should be set in italics)  
 (HLW)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It makes perfect sense that Geraldo could be the
``NBC Nightly News'' anchor for the millennium. It makes perfect
sense that ``60 Minutes'' could hire Murphy Brown as a
correspondent. It makes perfect sense that Bill Clinton could go
onto the board of Dreamworks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a harmonic convergence. We may be awash in nostalgia about
``Private Ryan'' and a time when America had values more important
than celebrity. But we're stuck with a quarrelsome, raunchy, blurry
period where we constantly scramble to figure out what the rules
are.
</P>
<P>
   The artifact of our age will be a Gap dress that may bear what
one tabloid called ``the presidential seal of approval.'' We are
way through the looking glass here.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr plays Captains Ahab and Queeg, spending $40
million to report the obvious: Our president skirts the truth and
likes skirts. As Wilde might dub this federal fox hunt, the
unspeakable in full pursuit of the unedifying.
</P>
<P>
   With Harry Thomason here to explain his ``Wag the Dog'' role to
the grand jury and to help produce the president's rebuttal to
designing women, it's a good time to debunk the biggest myth about
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He is not, as Bob Kerrey told Esquire, ``an unusually good
liar.''  &UR; (I didn't inhale. It was a fluke that I didn't get
drafted. I did not have sexual relations with that woman. &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   He is like a little boy standing in the middle of a room with a
paper bag on his head, thinking he is invisible. Americans know he
lies, but they like him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He stammers. He loses his temper. His eyes get clouded. He looks
down. He answers slowly. He has trouble with his prodigious memory.
He leaves semantic and syntactical clues. Watch his tenses, his
adverbs, his articles.  &UR; (That allegation is false.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When he looked scared and tried to duck behind the present tense
when Jim Lehrer asked him last January, ``You had no sexual
relationship with this young woman?'' _ ``There is not a sexual
relationship,'' Clinton replied _ wasn't it obvious that something
inappropriate had occurred between the president and the intern?
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is such a skilled manipulator, such a consummate
charmer with words, then why did he need a coach to rebut the
Monica story? His denials in that first round of interviews were so
lame that Thomason rushed here to script a more forceful denial.
</P>
<P>
   When Clarence Thomas fought off Anita Hill's charges, he did so
``unequivocally,'' with such force that the senators leaned back
from the blast of the words.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has never mastered the categorical denial, the big
intimidating blast that forces the listener to either accept or
reject your version. He prefers fibs that wink, or hem and haw,
buying him some time.
</P>
<P>
   Where Thomas denied ``each and every single allegation,''
Clinton is always sticking in wiggle words like ``solely.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Clinton will turn a denial into an admission. Or he
will excuse himself inside the admission, asking for exoneration
even as he claims he did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In the famous 1992 ``60 Minutes'` interview with Steve Kroft,
Clinton denied Gennifer Flowers' story but admitted causing pain in
his marriage. Most viewers came away understanding that he had been
involved with Ms. Flowers, but that he was denying some details of
her version. Rashomon rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can't even admit to a prevarication without tacking on
another. Is there anyone who believes his latest account, that he
did dally with Ms. Flowers, but only one time?
</P>
<P>
   His preposterous six-month refusal to explain his relationship
with the young White House intern says it all. If Clinton could say
Monica Lewinsky made everything up, or that it was inconceivable
that he was anywhere near that infamous navy blue dress, wouldn't
he scream it at the top of his lungs? Instead, the president stays
silent, as his fretful aides call reporters to ask if they've heard
anything about the lab results.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is in a pickle. If he lied, he now has to figure out
some way to avoid committing perjury in the grand jury without
admitting perjury in the civil case. How can something be true and
not true at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   It is the moment when this luckiest of presidents might finally
learn that you cannot have everything you want without any
consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-APPLEBY-COX     08-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-APPLEBY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `There's a long road to go' for Appleby
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Stuart Appleby had to stop several times, his
voice so choked words could no longer come out. Clearly, he isn't
done weeping for his wife, Renay, who died July 23 in a freak car
accident in London. Maybe he never will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like she was the first prize in a raffle of sorts, in
life and picking partners, and I was lucky enough to win her,'' the
27-year-old Australian said Tuesday, weeping between words. ``She's
changed a lot of people's lives. She obviously was only here for a
short time, and she had a very big impact on a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Renay Appleby and golf were Stuart's life. She caddied for him
in 1996 when they were trying to save money. More recently, with
her husband becoming a two-time winner on the PGA Tour, she walked
in the gallery, supporting his every move. At night after a round _
she always traveled with him _ they shared ideas and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Now all that's left is Appleby's golf. By deciding to play this
week in the PGA Championship at Sahalee Country Club, he's sinking
himself into his work, trying to cope with the void caused by her
horrific death. Renay was crushed between two cars when a cab
driver mistakenly thought he was in reverse and instead lunged
backwards into her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there with another gentleman,'' Stuart said. ``We were
doing CPR, heart massage, trying to find a pulse.''
</P>
<P>
   They never did.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby looks extremely tired. His eyes are sunken, his eyes
reddened. He is growing a beard, but not hiding behind it. He
requested a press conference in the PGA media center, choosing that
over a weeklong, daily barrage. He didn't realize how every thought
and mention of Renay would bring the nightmare into reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a part of the process of trying to move on,'' he
said. ``Not in a rushing sense, but to take one step at a time. I
had a loss of a person very close to me. Maybe other people don't
know what to say. Maybe I've got to reassure everyone that I'm OK.
We're all in this big group of people together in the world.
There's no preferences dealt out when someone disappears from us
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly, it's just one day at a time and just trying to get a
rhythm,'' he said. ``I suppose the worst of it's over in an impact
sense, but there's a long road to go. ... At my best, I feel good,
very normal. At my worst I feel terrible. It's a feeling I would
never want to wish on anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby is taking ``little baby steps'' in the recovery. The
funeral in Australia is behind him. He has returned to the PGA
Tour, planning three straight events. Returning to their house in
Orlando will take some time. Too many memories still live there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough getting through nights,'' he said. ``When you
really love someone, you miss the simple things. It's a whole
package of experiences that you've shared with someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow players such as close friend and fellow Australian Robert
Allenby, are his safety net. They all want to help. Stuart wants to
chat with Davis Love III, whose father died in a 1988 plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   For Couples, who has lost both parents over the last two years,
there's something of an identification to Appleby's pain. But Renay
was 25. The couple was just entering the good life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You drive into the trees and make a triple bogey and go to the
next hole,'' Couples said. ``And if you're worried about it for a
while, you just relate to things that happen to other people. ... I
give him a lot of credit for being able to get on a plane, leave
the house and come and play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples said he was ``in shock'' not only to see the story on TV
but because ``I was just in London and witnessed a little old lady
actually dive back to the curb to get out of the way of a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a really strong guy,'' said U.S. Open champion Lee
Janzen, a neighbor at Isleworth Country Club in Orlando. ``I know
it's not going to be easy for him for a long time. He knows he
needed to get back on tour. The biggest thing we can do is let him
know that's he's got a lot of friends who care about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said close friend Jesper Parnevik, already sensing Appleby's
resilience, ``He still has a positive outlook on life. It's not
like it's over. He just has to live it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
