<SLUG> BC-BULLETS-MEXICO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMMO JAILS AMERICANS IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a matter of great confusion in the Mexican legal system,
said Roberto Rodriguez, Mexico's consul in Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   On July 23, Scottsdale, Ariz., businessman James Brunen was
arrested entering Nogales, Sonora, with 149 rounds of ammunition he
said he mistakenly left in his vehicle. Brunen has been in jail
since.
</P>
<P>
   A week after, former Nogales, Ariz., police officer Jaime
Morales was arrested with two boxes of bullets at the same crossing
site. Three days later, Morales was released.
</P>
<P>
   Brunen and Morales had different federal judges assigned to
their cases, one with a strict interpretation of Mexico's ban on
all firearms and ammunition, the other who showed some compassion
for an unwitting violator.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats like Rodriguez say they wish there was some
consistency because ``there's just a lot of confusion now.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rodriguez said, the same judge handling Brunen's
case had ordered the prompt release of another U.S. citizen
bringing ammo into Nogales, Sonora, last year when it was
determined that it was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   But a higher court in Sonora's capitol, Hermosillo, chastised
the judge's decision, and ``that same judge is trying to act in
accordance with the ruling of the superior tribunal,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing remains clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have firearms or ammo on you when you cross that line,
you are in violation of Mexican law,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Brunen can attest to that.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke with reporters Tuesday about his rat- and
cockroach-infested prison cell and about life in a jail designed
for 350 people but home to about 1,500 inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Brunen said he already has spent $15,000 in legal fees and
expects to spend double that before he gets the case resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't come here. Don't bring your money here. They hate us
here,'' Brunen said.
</P>
<P>
   Brunen reiterated that he had taken a weapon from the vehicle
before leaving Scottsdale on a trip to Nogales to buy decorative
pots for friends. He said he simply forgot about the ammunition
until he had crossed the border.
</P>
<P>
   When stopped by Mexican customs officials, Brunen said he told
them in broken Spanish that he was declaring the ammunition, using
the words ``declare-o, declare-o.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a report of the incident filed by Mexican customs officer
Gilberto Chontal Maldonado, Brunen told authorities that he
couldn't remember whether he brought any ammunition with him.
Chontal said Brunen denied bringing weapons with him.
</P>
<P>
   Chontal said customs officers found a holster behind the
driver's seat of Brunen's Jeep Cherokee and started asking
questions. They then searched the vehicle and found 100 9mm rounds,
20 .38-caliber rounds and 29 .380-caliber rounds in the area of the
spare tire.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said it was clear, at least to his mind, that Brunen
had made no effort to conceal the ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't hidden in a bag or anything like that. It was out in
the open,'' Rodriguez said. ``Maybe some judges consider it hidden
simply because it was in the trunk area.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said that Brunen can expect to come to trial within 40
days of his arrest. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or mark.shaffer(at)pni.com
via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
