<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marichal sends a message
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ People are still sending Dennis Martinez stuff, like
the bottle of 1988 Dom Perignon he found in his locker with a note
from San Diego reliever Randy Myers when he hit the clubhouse
Tuesday. But perhaps the most important item he received was a
two-sentence fax from the Dominican Republic, signed by Juan
Marichal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't his voice, which would have been something different
than a fax but he signed it,'' said Martinez, who surpassed
Marichal's record for victories by a Latin American pitcher with
his 244th Saturday. ``It was saying congratulations for overcoming
the record, that he was really pleased by it. It was quick. It was
a two-line thing. But that was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The record now his, Martinez has no idea if this will be his
last season. He has been periodically effective this year and,
perhaps more important, has had no recurrence of the elbow trouble
that drove him to retirement last August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what will happen after the year,'' he said.
``I'm only thinking about this year. It's not as easy as it used to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt's quad, episode 826
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss arrived at Qualcomm Stadium with an improved left
quadriceps after three days off. After huddling with trainers,
manager Bobby Cox determined his shortstop was not as improved as
he thought he was, shelving Weiss for Ozzie Guillen for the third
straight game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got pretty sore (Friday), but it's the same old thing,''
Weiss said. ``I thought before the San Francisco series I was done
with the thing. I felt great. I didn't expect it to pop up again.''
</P>
<P>
   But after seven straight starts, Weiss felt the muscle twinge in
his first at-bat last Friday against the Giants' Kirk Rueter, when
he ran out a hopper over the mound. Two days later, it was no
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing that it's getting closer to the end of the season,
we're going to be a lot more cautionary than we might have been if
this was May,'' he said. ``That's the bottom line right now, trying
to be healthy for the last few weeks.'' Hair today, gone tomorrow
</P>
<P>
   The great Andruw Jones hair saga has reached a conclusion. For
now. He has no hair at the moment, having shaved his head and his
platinum tint job on Monday. His smooth pate required plenty of
explaining to the steady stream of teammates who came to his locker
for hair updates. For those scoring at home, in the last week he
went from bronze to blond to none.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
