<SLUG> BC-INVESTMENT-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT-FRAUD CRACKDOWN SET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fraudulent investment schemes centered on companies
that say they are raising money for entertainment ventures have
cost American investors $100 million in recent years, federal
regulators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing a joint crackdown on entertainment-industry
investment fraud, officials from the Federal Trade Commission, the
Securities and Exchange Commission and a group of state securities
regulators said that a growing number of consumers had complained
recently about losing money in entertainment investments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, H. Dean Cooke, a 58-year-old retired aerospace
engineer from Vienna, Va., said at a news conference Tuesday that
he had invested $20,000 last year in Desert Gold Partners, which
said it was producing a film about the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the SEC charged four California-based companies and
three individuals with securities fraud in the sale of $8 million
of Desert Gold partnership units to 600 investors nationwide. The
commission said that the defendants transferred most of the money
raised to themselves and their affiliates, but no movie was
produced.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC also announced the filing of three other enforcement
actions in entertainment-related ventures and filed three cases in
federal court in Los Angeles and one in federal court in Salt Lake
City.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC announced the filing of four regulatory actions,
including one charging a California company with deceptive
practices in raising $16.5 million from investors to operate a
cable television channel with nonviolent programming for children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
