<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-LOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOBE WARNS OF POSSIBLE LOSS IN 3RD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Adobe Systems Inc. warned Tuesday that its
third-quarter revenue would fall below analysts' expectations,
resulting in a potential loss. Adobe also announced the departure
of three senior executives and a reduction of 240 to 300 jobs, or
13 percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Adobe fell $1.375, to $30.8125, on Nasdaq before
trading was halted for the company's announcement late in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, based in San Jose, Calif., is a leading maker of software
programs used in publishing, including Photoshop, Illustrator,
Pagemaker and the Postscript language used in printers. Although
Adobe has modified many of its programs to take advantage of the
Internet, and many are used to create Web sites, analysts said the
company had run into difficulty exploiting the transition to
electronic publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adobe is a tremendously successful company in the print world,
but they haven't really figured out the right products and strategy
for making money and being successful on the Web,'' said
Christopher Galvin, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe also said in its announcement Tuesday that business
continued to be hurt by Japan's recession. The company said that
cost-cutting efforts, including the reduction of jobs, would lower
expenses by as much as $60 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The company said revenue for the quarter that will end Aug. 28
was likely to be $220 million to $225 million, compared with $230
million in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After a one-time reorganization charge and other nonrecurring
expenses, Adobe said, net income may break even or be a loss,
compared with net income of $53.4 million in the quarter a year
earlier. Analysts had expected Adobe to earn 52 cents a diluted
share, according to First Call, which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe also said Tuesday that three top executives, P. Jackson
Bell, executive vice president and chief administrative officer;
Robert Roblin, executive vice president for marketing, and Ross
Bott, executive vice president for product divisions, had resigned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9078 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILBY-OBIT-AZR &LR;      08-11 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILBY-OBIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUCSON FEDERAL JUDGE RICHARD S. BILBY DIES SUDDENLY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER AND MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Richard S. Bilby, a Tucson federal judge known for
incisive intelligence, blunt-spoken manner and high-profile clashes
with Arizona officials, died suddenly Tuesday near his summer home
in Flagstaff. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
   Bilby collapsed while taking a walk with his dog, friends said,
and paramedics were unable to revive him.
</P>
<P>
   Bilby, who presided over the 1992 civil trial of financier
Charles H Keating Jr. was the son of a pioneering Arizona family
and an outspoken critic of those he thought had abused their
professional or political power.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the death of the Tucson native, who played golf
frequently and carefully watched his diet, stunned his colleagues
on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would live forever,'' said Judge Robert
Broomfield, who presides over the U.S. District Court in Phoenix.
``He was the model of health.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Irving, a retired U.S. District Judge in San Diego,
said, ``It was a real shock to me. His father lived until he was
about 95, and I used to joke with him that he was in such
tremendous shape that he'd be around forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving called Bilby ``a very talented judge with an uncanny
ability to cut right to the heart of a case'' and move it
efficiently toward resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very decisive,'' Irving said. ``A totally honest and
ethical person who called things as he saw them.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hawkins, who argued cases in Bilby's court before
himself becoming a judge in the 9th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals,
hailed Bilby's pragmatism and willingness to bring computer
technology into the courtroom and involve jurors in the questioning
of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, when he became a senior judge, I described
him in a speech as `the trial lawyer's trial judge,' '' Hawkins
said. ``He was probably one of the most innovative trial judges
this state or any state has seen.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 interview, Bilby said he had ``the best job in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I most like about being a judge is that I get to solve
problems,'' he said. ``Being a judge is much better than being a
trial lawyer. Here, I give the ulcers rather than get them. Plus, I
just enjoy watching attorneys work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilby was a man of vivid contrasts. He once served as Pima
County Republican Party chairman, but his views often sounded like
those of a populist Democrat from the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   He was a respected figure in a profession dominated by somber
men of grave self-importance, but he sported a Mickey Mouse watch
and preferred not to wear a judicial robe in his courtroom, unless
a jury was present.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. Dennis DeConcini, a Democrat, made Bilby his
first judicial nomination, a move that wasn't popular with some of
DeConcini's Democratic colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But DeConcini, who grew up with Bilby in Tucson, said he picked
his friend for the job because ``he was an excellent lawyer who
just had a sterling reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he was a senior judge, Bilby's death does not create a
vacancy on the federal bench that can be filled by presidential
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Bilby made plenty of headlines in his career. He tangled with
former Gov. Fife Symington over juvenile corrections and criticized
state prison officials for failing to protect inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bilby openly attacked suggestions by Gov. Symington and
others regarding the automatic transfer of repeat and violent
youthful offenders to adult court.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we take the position that every child who commits an
assaultive crime should be considered an adult, that puts us back
in the Dark Ages,'' he said. ``My God, I thought we were smarter
than that!''
</P>
<P>
   Bilby subsequently ordered the state juvenile corrections agency
to limit its bed space - and then determined that the Arizona
Department of Juvenile Corrections was not in compliance with his
order.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Bilby struck down as unconstitutionally vague Arizona's
ban on ``partial birth abortions;'' he permanently blocked the law
from taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   He said the law, passed by the Legislature, unconstitutionally
burdens a woman's right to terminate a non-viable fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Bilby also presided over a massive 1992 civil trial in which
investors successfully sued Keating as well as accountants,
business associates and lawyers who were accused of having helped
the Phoenix financier sell junk bonds in his ill-fated American
Continental Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking bluntly from the bench, Bilby said that if one of
Keating's law firms saw a pattern of fraud, it should have walked
away. ``You can take your big fees and leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bilby later said he had no tolerance for professionals who
``abuse their status.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a lawyer or a CPA (certified public accountant) or a
doctor, you have special privileges that allow you to make a lot of
money'' and hold a preferred position in society, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems to me that when you have those perks, you have
special obligations that go along with them. I expect lawyers and
all professional people to be honest and hard-working and candid.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Bilby said his background explained his scorn
for self-importance and his demand for candor. ``It's just the way
I was brought up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bilby's parents were Mormon pioneer stock who met at the Gila
Academy in Thatcher, eloped and, in 1912, struck out for Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their first home was a wooden-floored tent on the banks of the
Rillito River,'' said Bilby, whose mother taught school while his
father attended the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Bilby credited his mother with doing most of the work of raising
four children, while his father built a law practice and became a
leader in state Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an exceptional woman who, I think, gave me my ideas
about fairness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I grew up, the three luckiest things that could
happen to you were to be born in the United States, to be White and
to be healthy. My mother made me realize that you don't have a lick
to do with any of those things, so when you look at other people,
you've got to realize that not everybody has the same breaks in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilby earned a bacelor's degree from the University of Arizona
in 1955, and, after service in the Army, earned a law degree from
the University of Michigan Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Hawkins said Bilby's relatively privileged background and
Republican Party activism made some Tucson observers of his early
career on the bench misjudge him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought that he might not be sympathetic to claims of the
poor and minority groups and those who thought the government had
run roughshod over them,'' Hawkins said. ``But he was very much an
advocate, in the appropriate circumstances, for the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, ``The Republic'' reported Bilby's sharp
criticisms of state prison officials over the death of inmate Steve
Benitez, who was murdered by gang members in his Tucson prison cell
after officials had allowed him to rejoin the general inmate
population, even though they knew his life had been threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you that Benitez really bothers me, because I
think it evidences an attitude,'' Bilby told Department of
Corrections Director Terry Stewart in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the attitude that scares me more than anything else, that
`What we (DOC) are doing is right.' But if what you are doing is
right,'' Bilby said, ``Benitez should be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Paul Rosenblatt remembered Bilby on Tuesday
as a ``man of very strong convictions and beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt said that with the abbreviated caseload of a senior
judge, Bilby had ``wanted to focus on playing golf and enjoying
life . . . ``It just seemed like everything was just the way he
wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilby is survived by his wife, Elizabeth, and two grown
daughters. Funeral arrangements are pending. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
