<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS' LINE FINDS RIGHT COMBINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ The offensive line might be USC's biggest
question mark, but it appears that at least the right side has been
settled. Junior Travis Claridge and sophomore Brent McCaffrey would
start at right guard and right tackle, if the season began today.
</P>
<P>
   The other three positions might be up for grabs, but getting the
right side decided has to be viewed as progress for a largely
inexperienced group. It doesn't help matters that the offensive
line has been the most maligned position for the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've been beaten down a bit,'' offensive line coach
Steve Greatwood said. ``It seems like the offensive line is where
the buck stops. Whether it was warranted or not, and it probably
was, that's where it has stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Greatwood has been working at restoring morale as well as
teaching techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to prop them up,'' he said. ``There's not
a lot of household names in the group, which has not been the norm
at USC. We're young. We're just a bunch of no-names right now, but
I think I'll have an excellent group.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other positions, Ken Bowen and Rome Douglas are battling
for the left tackle spot, while junior-college transfer Donta
Kendrick and Jason Grain are splitting time at left guard. Matt
McShane, Eric Denmon and Grain are all practicing at center,
although McShane was considered the leader following spring
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said the team will have to practice in pads before any
other decisions are made on the line.
</P>
<P>
   __ Haslip making strides: Defensive back Ken Haslip has emerged
during the first two days, impressing Hackett with his play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Haslip is in better shape than he's ever been,'' Hackett
said. ``I'm very happy with our secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Antuan Simmons, who is battling Haslip for a starting
spot, was cleared to practice Tuesday and also drew Hackett's
attention. ``He's around the ball a lot,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Thomas nurses ankle: The role of highly touted quarterback
Jason Thomas has been slowed the first two days by a sore ankle.
It's the same ankle that Thomas fractured last season at Dominguez
High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I aggravated it through the dropbacks we did Saturday,''
Thomas said. ``It's a lot different than in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is being limited to one practice per day, and doctors
have told him scar tissue around the ankle is causing the
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   __ Jersey switch: Offensive lineman Trevor Roberts is wearing
No.76 in training camp because there are no available jerseys with
his No. 77. What happened to the No. 77's? They were shipped to
Ohio for the NFL Hall of Fame ceremony induction involving former
Trojans lineman Anthony Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   __ Not in camp: Wide receiver Kevin McLaughlin of Hart, who
underwent reconstructive surgery last spring, is not in camp but
will return once school begins. McLaughlin is redshirting this
season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Taking it slow: Hackett is having several players, including
wide receiver Larry Parker and linebacker Mike Pollard, sit out
every third or fourth practice session so they can simply observe
and absorb what's happening on the field. Hackett referred to it as
a ``mental practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be pulling guys not necessarily with an injury,''
Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
