A9093 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-11 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lopez
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys pay visit &QL; 
to Spin City again
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MOST of us can think back to our high school days and probably
remember engaging in antics that can only be described as
``horseplay.''
</P>
<P>
   As I remember it, horseplay usually involved either delivering
or receiving a series of ``frog'' punches to the biceps. Sometimes,
it might have been hiding a teammate's uniform, or when the locker
room really was hopping, perhaps rubbing some Ben Gay inside an
unsuspecting teammate's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   It was horseplay. It was boys being boys. It was what we did
when we were sowing oats, sprouting wings and doing all those
things we did when we thought we were men but in truth were not.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, wherever there was horseplay, there also was a
burly coach who appeared from his office, either blowing a whistle
or wielding an inch-thick paddle. And that was that. Horseplay
over. Situation under control.
</P>
<P>
   It was all part of learning to grow up and being accountable _
how we left horseplay behind and replaced it with real-world games
like mortgages, carting kids to T-ball and building love-hate
relationships with Stairmaster machines.
</P>
<P>
   But then, there are the 'Boys. The Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Talk proves cheap ...
</P>
<P>
   They told us they would be men this year. They told us the
antics and charades were done. They brought in familiar faces and
personalities we could love _ the professorial Calvin Hill, the
respected head coach Chan Gailey. Quarterback Troy Aikman and
Emmitt Smith _ respected players and people _ talked of renewed
enthusiasm and no longer having to worry about distractions. A
trimmer offensive line came to camp and, more important, brought
healthy knee cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Boys told us they finally would grow up and worry as much
about image and integrity as their 10-13 record over the past 23
games.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently they were, are and forever will be just 'Boys in
men's bodies, so long as receiver Michael Irvin has a friend in
Jerry Jones and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a coach in desperate need of a scary-looking
paddle in his top desk drawer, or at least a whistle he doesn't
have to swallow whenever Jones shows up, it is Gailey, a good coach
in an undeniably, inevitably bad place.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent episode among these 'Boys was the July 29
training-camp fight involving Irvin, offensive lineman Everett
McIver and a pair of sharp scissors Irvin apparently thrust into
McIver's neck.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the fight, Jones not only ignored the promised
integrity and accountability but also put a gag order on all those
involved and started spin-doctoring. He switched on his made-for-TV
smile and called it all ``horseplay.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ask me, horseplay certainly isn't what it used to be. I
don't remember locker-room stabbings, ever.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Irvin went to the innovative ``blame the media''
card, telling reporters, ``You guys are working harder to put me in
jail than the police.''
</P>
<P>
   But in actuality, the police didn't have to work very hard to
find Irvin in felony possession of cocaine in 1996. Judge Manny
Alvarez also didn't have to work hard deciding that even if that
was a nice mink coat Irvin wore to court, he still would give Irvin
four years' probation and a warning that one violation of parole
could result in up to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ... but silence can cost
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we are in the midst of a 'Boyish cover-up that obviously
involves deceit, or at least the kind of truth-bending Dallas has
not seen since J.R. told Sue Ellen he would be faithful.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: We know the two-inch gash in McIver's neck came
dangerously close to his carotid artery. What we do not know is how
McIver's serious wound was surgically repaired.
</P>
<P>
   There were 15 stitches sewn into McIver's neck. But there is no
record of his being admitted to any Dallas-area hospitals, which
are required to report to police all violent incidents (stabbings,
etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Could Jones be so conniving and deceptive that he turned to a
team trainer or perhaps his tailor and said, ``Come on! We gotta
make this scissors thing look like a big ol' misunderstanding! Sew
that kid up!'' After all, Jones knows Irvin's pass-catching skills
might deteriorate slightly by 2018.
</P>
<P>
   One recent report said Jones himself negotiated a
high-six-figure settlement between Irvin and McIver in exchange for
McIver's not filing charges _ charges that surely would have
interested all those officers, attorneys and Judge Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is investigating. Campus police and district attorneys
are waiting for substantial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the particulars of the stabbing remain hazy, from
the bits of information that have squeezed through the cracks of
the locker-room walls, I'm picturing an uncensored Jerry Springer
episode about home makeovers gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   Globs of hair in players' hands. Chairs flying through the air.
Profanities. Punches flying. Sharp objects. Situation out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   'Boys will be boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
