A9094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIV-DIVING12-COX     08-11 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIV-DIVING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pesek-Bonner takes 3-meter synchronized
 &HT;    By Tracey Thomson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Tuesday night, the Georgia Tech Aquatic Center
opened the 1998 U.S. National Diving Championships, showcasing the
talent of 65 athletes competing for spots on the U.S. National and
World Cup teams. The divers, ranging in age from 13 to 39,
completed the preliminary round in the men's and women's 3-meter
and 10-meter platform synchronized competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Synchronized diving, a relatively new event in the sport, was
developed by Tom Gompf in 1995. Gompf, a U.S. Diving and FINA
official, introduced the event as a way to increase the number of
specators at diving meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spectators like synchro because more things can happen,'' said
Tracy Bonner, the first-place finisher with partner Kathy Pesek in
the 3-meter competition. ``There is more difficulty, and that makes
it more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Synchronized diving involves a pair of athletes executing a
number of moves simultaneously. Divers are scored by a panel of
five judges based on individual and team performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is definitely difficult in synchro. But the hardest
part is concentrating on your own dive, and trusting your
partner,'' Pesek said.
</P>
<P>
   For Pesek and Bonner, timing and trust have developed over time.
While the two have only been competing as a pair for a year and a
half, both have trained with Tennessee Diving and competed for the
University of Tennessee under the instruction of coach Dave
Parrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definately have an advantage over other divers because we
have trained with the same coach and have developed the same
technique,'' said Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   With the sport still in its infancy, many divers have not had
the luxury of training together for any amount of time. Jessica
Johnstone and Olivia York of Marietta formed their synchro team
four days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we are both from here and we train here, we just decided
to try and see how we would do,'' said Johnstone whose team placed
16th in the 3-meter competition.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 10-meter platform, 1996 individual platform
Olympians David Pilcher and Patrick Jeffrey placed first, advancing
to Sunday's final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to come back and have some fun,'' said Jeffrey,
who finished ninth in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 3-meter synchro competition, Kevin McMahon and
Justin Dumais finished first, earning the pair a spot in Saturday's
finals. The women's 10-meter platform competition concluded the
synchro portion of the National Diving Championships. Placing first
were Laura Wilkinson and Patty Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Championships give divers an opportunity to earn points
toward January's World Cup in New Zealand. Many divers who competed
in the synchro portion will continue in individual competition
through Sunday's conclusion of the Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
