<SLUG> BC-SWM-USNATIONALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Younger freestyler overtakes Bennett in Nationals
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLOVIS, Calif. _ Olympic champion Brooke Bennett got a little
taste Tuesday of how Janet Evans felt losing to a younger swimmer _
namely Bennett _ at a major meet. Now can Diana Munz hold onto her
newfound supremacy?
</P>
<P>
   Munz, 16, of Chagrin Falls, Ohio, defeated Bennett in the
800-meter freestyle at the U.S. Swimming National Championships as
the temperature surpassed 100 degrees and their rivalry reached
into the hot zone.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can remember back when Janet was swimming and I wanted to
beat her,'' said Bennett, 18, of Plant City, Fla., who held off
Munz in January for the world title at Perth, Australia. ''It's
just the determination inside of you to make you get to that wall
first. But I think I still have a lot left in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett took the early lead, but didn't get out far enough and
Munz was able to draft off her. Munz passed Bennett with 590 meters
to go and kicked, touching the wall with pale blue fingernails. Her
time of 8 minutes, 31.74 seconds was more than two seconds off her
best. Bennett's time, 8:35.81, was about eight seconds slower than
her top mark.
</P>
<P>
   Munz had already defeated Bennett in three races earlier this
year at spring nationals _ the 400, 800, and 1,500 _ but recognized
that Bennett hadn't shaved and tapered to prepare for that meet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the first time that we've both been ready to go and I was
able to bring it in as a win,'' Munz said.
</P>
<P>
   At this same pool in 1987, Evans set world records in the 800
and 1,500. ''Wow, I didn't know that,'' Munz said. ''You know,
Janet Evans is seriously my idol _ even if she's not swimming.
Brooke now is the No. 1 swimmer, and it's just amazing that now
it's coming to me!''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Munz will meet again here in the 200, 400 and
1,500-meter freestyles. Bennett believes that theirs will be a
rivalry for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that she's right there, and I think for the rest of our
careers we're going to be neck and neck with each other,'' Bennett
said, ''which is good for me because I went through a couple of
times where I had really no competition.''
</P>
<P>
   While she acknowledged, ''It always hurts (to lose),'' Bennett
said it was ''good for me to come here, and find my weaknesses and
work on those for the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Both qualify for the 1999 Pan Pacific meet in the Olympic pool
in Sydney. Bennett has a reminder of Australia at home in the form
of her pet wallaby, Tilly-May. A wallaby is like a baby kangaroo.
</P>
<P>
   While Bennett is known for her animal menagerie, Munz was almost
embarrassed to admit that she has no peculiar hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have two dogs, labrador retrievers,'' she offered. ''Their
names are Splash and Backstroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Thompson won the men's 800, which is not an Olympic event,
while Tom Dolan suffered another of his asthma attacks and was
14th. He should be fine by Thursday, when he swims his gold-medal
event, the 400 individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
