<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOEL BARR, 82, DEFECTOR WHO BECAME PIONEER IN SOVIET MICROCHIP
INDUSTRY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Joel Barr, an American Communist and friend of
Julius and Ethel Rosenberg who barely eluded the FBI before he
could be charged with espionage in 1950, died on Aug. 1 in a
hospital in Moscow. He was 82 and had lived in St. Petersburg for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   An old friend, Morton Sobell, who served 18 years in prison on a
charge of conspiracy to commit espionage, said Tuesday from his
home in San Francisco that Barr had died of a heart ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Rosenbergs, who were tried with Sobell, were executed
in 1953 for their role in providing nuclear secrets to the Soviets,
Barr went on to become a founder of the Soviet Union's microchip
industry. He never played a major espionage role and no arrest
warrant or indictment was ever issued against him. He applied for,
and received, Social Security benefits and held both American and
Russian citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a cog in the wheel,'' said Edward Wierzbowski, a
documentary filmmaker who helped Barr in his old age. ``He was just
one of hundreds of Americans supplying information to the Soviet
Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Wierzbowski said on Tuesday that a KGB official had told him
that Barr had provided Soviet agents with radar and electronics
information. ``This was important to the Russians, who were not
getting any technological assistance from the Americans and the
British,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Barr defected to the Soviet Union with Alfred Sarant, an
engineer from Ithaca, N.Y., and established the Soviet equivalent
of Silicon Valley at a time when the Russians were far behind the
West in microchip technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KGB had people everywhere and knew that he was going to be
arrested'' in the United States, Wierzbowski said. Barr then went
to Paris for a supposed holiday and slipped behind the Iron
Curtain, first to Czechoslovakia and then to the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Sarant was interrogated for three days by the FBI and fled,
ultimately to the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Barr was born in Brooklyn of parents who had emigrated from
Russia and, although he was regarded as an excellent pianist, he
studied engineering at the City College of New York. Among his
classmates were Rosenberg and Sobell.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Los Angeles Times in 1992, Barr said
that Rosenberg signed him up as a party member and they became
friends.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Barr said: ``I am ready to confess, or
whatever the word is, to say that really I made a tremendous
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that his actions were never meant to ``put the
United States in peril,'' but rather to help communism to thrive in
the Soviet Union so it might spread to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted he helped the Soviets build their first radar-guided
anti-aircraft guns but contended: ``Nothing I did in America was
used directly in my work in the Soviet Union, but, indirectly, my
general education, which I got in America, has helped me a lot in
my work here.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Barr applied for and received an American passport,
which he used to travel to the United States and to apply for a
Social Security pension, which he got.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his life, Barr gave up on communism. ``I
believe that now history will show that the Russian Revolution was
a tremendous mistake,'' he told The Los Angeles Times. ``It was a
step backward. The real revolution for mankind that will go down
for many, many years was the American Revolution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
