<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-CONSORTIUMS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES AGREE TO SHARE CHORES, BUT WITHOUT UTTERING THE M-WORD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, LeBron Fairbanks, the president of a small,
distinctively Christian liberal arts college in Mount Vernon, Ohio,
had an inspiration. Budget cuts were threatening his institution,
but, he figured, he could save ``bushels of money'' by combining
resources with neighboring colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was daring for an institution like Mount Vernon
Nazarene College, which is committed to its religious traditions
and wary of blurring its identity.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Fairbanks came up with a proposal in which Mount
Vernon and five other Ohio colleges would seek ways to combine
administrative tasks. He found a receptive ear for his experiment
at the Teagle Foundation, a midsize private philanthropy that was
just then shopping for a way to make a significant contribution to
higher education. Teagle so liked the idea (and trusted Fairbanks,
as an earlier grant recipient) that it set up the Collaborative
Ventures Program and has issued more than $4 million in grants to
help colleges set up money-saving collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   While only a handful of such consortiums existed in 1995, today
there are at least 21 representing more than 125 colleges and
universities. They range from the elite Five Colleges Inc.
(Amherst, Hampshire, Mount Holyoke, Smith and the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst) to the Montana Consortium of American
Indian tribal colleges (Rocky Mountain, Salish Kootenai, Little Big
Horn and Fort Peck Community College).
</P>
<P>
   The appeal for Five Colleges was not just to save money but also
to enrich academic programs. Specialized courses like Arabic, early
music and astronomy rotate among the Five Colleges campuses, which
individually might not be able to afford such unusual offerings.
Students are encouraged to register for the shared courses at
member institutions for no additional fees, and free intercollege
bus service is provided.
</P>
<P>
   Five Colleges is now trying to consolidate programs in American
ethnic studies. A $135,000 Teagle grant will help pay for a new
ethnic studies teacher who will shuttle from campus to campus this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the colleges in the Montana Consortium are too far
apart for shuttle buses, so they are creating an online university
using distance-learning techniques, with a shared curriculum and
faculty exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great many of these small institutions are being caught in a
squeeze,'' said Richard W. Kimball, president of Teagle. ``On the
one hand, their costs are going up because education is
labor-intensive, and on the other they can no longer continue to
raise tuition faster than the rate of inflation because the public
won't stand for it. They've got no alternative but to reduce
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was approached by Fairbanks, Kimball said he was aware
that some collaborative efforts in the past had failed. But he
recalled thinking, ``If a very conservative school like Mount
Vernon Nazarene College is interested in this, maybe the time is
right nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of consortiums is not entirely new. The Associated
Colleges of the Twin Cities, an organization of five colleges in
the Minneapolis-St. Paul area, has shared academic programs for
about two decades. It is expanding its collaborations and is now
working on a plan to share security services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future will require higher-education leadership to reach
out to others where there are administrative overlaps and academic
programs which can be combined,'' said Larry Osnes, president of
Hamline University in St. Paul, a Twin Cities institution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some of the most striking efforts involve institutions that have
strong religious ties. A consortium of seminaries around Columbus,
Ohio, is linking libraries and requiring students of each
institution to take at least one course at another consortium
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fairly avant-garde in this,'' said Norman E. Dewire,
president of the Methodist Theological School in Ohio, part of the
consortium. ``But we realize we can't live in a world apart.''
</P>
<P>
   College administrators are not unmindful of the risks. ``Of
course we have to be careful,'' said Fairbanks of Mount Vernon
Nazarene College, which is now in league with five diverse
institutions, including Ohio Dominican College, a Roman Catholic
institution, and Wilmington College, which is affiliated with the
Religious Society of Friends, the Quakers. Teagle awarded $560,000
to the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a fierce loyalty to these institutions,''
Fairbanks said. ``If you talk to the alumni about mergers, changing
the name or losing your identity you're looking for another job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
