<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS'S STYLE HAS BEEN TO GET RESULTS, NOT ACCLAIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The man has his quirks. No one questions that. His Red
Sox cap looks as if it is three sizes too big, pulled low enough to
hide his eyes and highlight his ears. Sometimes he thumps his desk
in the manager's office when he speaks. You close your eyes and
swear it is comedian Dana Carvey imitating George Bush on those old
``Saturday Night Live'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams returned to Fenway Park Tuesday, the first time he
and his team have been at home since July 26 (although his office
calendar was still flipped to June). That's why, by 3:30 p.m.,
there was already a crowd of Sox fans outside the players' parking
lot. They came with cameras and caps, hoping for glimpses and
autographs. Most of them weren't looking for the manager. They
should have been.
</P>
<P>
   We all talk about the Eccentricities of Jimy. Not many have
discussed his dugout brilliance. If Jim Leyland _ the first choice
for the Boston managerial job after Kevin Kennedy was fired in 1996
_ were sitting in his seat, maybe there would be loud Manager of
the Year debates about him. But many dismiss Williams as a guy who
could just as easily be wearing overalls and holding a pitchfork, a
great candidate for a 1990s portrait of American Gothic. He is as
homey as anyone you've met. But you've got to give him his props:
He knows baseball. Question is, would you make him Manager of the
Year?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. Manager of the Year,'' Mo Vaughn said before last night's
Sox-Royals game.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is pinstriped opposition to that statement.
Only 200 miles from here, a man named Joe Torre has led the Yankees
to nearly three wins in every four games. Everyone has known since
late May that the Yankees will easily win the American League East.
Now they're talking about winning 117 games, which would break the
record of the 1906 Cubs. There are many who argue that you have to
give the Most Valuable Player Award to the slugger who breaks Roger
Maris's home run record. In most cases, I would think that you'd
have to do the same thing with a manager who leads his team to the
most wins in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Torre could be Manager of the Year, too,'' Vaughn said.
``But with the low expectations people had for this ball club, Jimy
deserves it more. Everyone knew the Yankees were going to be good.
But they didn't know about us. And Jimy has kept us rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   If I lived in another city, Torre would have my vote, based on
the Yankees winning 75 percent of their games during a year in
which 16-game winner David Cone didn't even make the All-Star team.
But those who have a front-row view of what Williams has had to go
through here understand that the race for the award should be
close. He lost his leadoff man and second baseman in spring
training. He began the season with outfielders who many predicted
would not have a 20-homer man among them. He has had to shuffle the
lineup a few times this season because of the absence of Vaughn or
Nomar Garciaparra. He stood aside when his general manager snubbed
his first baseman and as his first baseman ripped his general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   He's a genuinely nice man. But you know there have been times
when he has looked at the now-dormant civil war between Vaughn and
Dan Duquette and said to himself, ``Why can't these guys chill out
until the end of the season?'' He's probably thought it; he's never
said it. People have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is as good a man as he is a manager,'' pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan said. ``That's just as important as anything else in
the big leagues because of the amount of time you spend around
these guys. His top assets are his integrity and his honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan paused and smiled before he added, ``With all the
distractions we've had with injuries and all the other stuff that
normally happens over the course of a summer in Boston, he's been a
rock. He's our foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   That should have been obvious in Texas Saturday night. Williams
decided to give Darren Lewis the night off and put Darren Bragg in
the leadoff spot. Bragg finished the night with four hits,
including a home run, off former teammate Aaron Sele. The next
night, Bragg was batting seventh. Williams was asked Tuesday if he
would consider putting Bragg back in the leadoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's our leadoff hitter?'' he asked, thumping on the wooden
desk again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren Lewis,'' he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that was it. Before that, he had been asked about the
surging Baltimore Orioles. You know what he said, right? He talked
about the Royals, how they were last night's opponent, the Sox had
to focus on them and basically made other unremarkable statements
not many people want to hear. But these are Jimy's gospels. On the
left side of his desk is a picture of his family. It is framed in a
case inscribed, ``Father.'' On the right side of that desk? A thick
booklet that reads, ``Advanced Scouting Report: Kansas City
Royals.''
</P>
<P>
   Your team will beat his because your team is better. Your team
will not beat his because his team did not master the basics.
Before games, he drills Kerrigan about the state of the bullpen. He
insists that his players be on time and play hard. He loves hustle
plays such as Bragg's artful slide home in the seventh inning last
night. He likes one-on-one talks, too.
</P>
<P>
   Said Vaughn, ``When I threw that ball away in Texas (the
decisive run in a 4-3 loss), he came to me the next day and said,
`Listen, this is how you have to think about it. Think about it;
just hear me out.' He keeps things in house. He'll pull you in his
office and sit you down rather than rip you in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will never rip his guys. He'll thump on his desk and
sometimes speak in evasive terms that some would call presidential.
They'd be wrong. Jimy Williams's style is, well, managerial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
