<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY CASE MAKES PHONE RING FOR SIMPSON DNA EXPERT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(budgeted as NY-SCHECK-PROFILE)  (mk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are three things that Barry Scheck, the DNA
expert on O.J. Simpson's defense team, would like you to know about
Monica Lewinsky's dress.
</P>
<P>
   First, that Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, surely has
the results already. ``It should be clear to everybody,'' Scheck
said. ``They can analyze the dress very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, if there is evidence on the dress of a physical
encounter with President Clinton, then Starr has an ethical _ but
not legal _ obligation to disclose it now, before the president
testifies to the grand jury. ``Otherwise he's setting up a perjury
trap,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   And third, if there isn't evidence, then Starr should disclose
that, too. ``If there's no sperm on the dress,'' Scheck said,
``then the incendiary publicity that has resulted from this dress
is very unfair. This is not a game of `Gotcha!'''
</P>
<P>
   Scheck, 48, is one of the nation's most visible defense lawyers,
and still laboring to get out from under the bloody gloves of O.J.
Simpson. ``The problem with the Simpson case is that you become
like a 'toon,'' he said. In fact Scheck has been at plenty of
soap-opera trials with notorious clients. His cases could fill up a
season of ``The Practice,'' the ABC series about lawyers in Boston
that he watches all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck not only represented Simpson in his acquittal on murder
charges, but also helped defend Hedda Nussbaum from criminal
prosecution when her lover, Joel Steinberg, killed the 6-year-old
girl they reared together. His biggest failure, or Pyrrhic defeat,
was his defense of Louise Woodward, the British au pair who was
convicted of murdering her 8-month-old charge, but then freed after
a judge reduced her sentence to involuntary manslaughter. Now
Scheck is part of the team representing Abner Louima, the Haitian
immigrant who prosecutors say was tortured in a Brooklyn police
station.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when news of Ms. Lewinsky's dress was back on the
front pages, Scheck's phone began ringing again. So far the White
House hasn't called _ ``That would be a big story,'' Scheck said _
but the press, needing comment on DNA, is hungry.
</P>
<P>
   How many calls in all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten zillion,'' said Scheck, over breakfast on Monday of a
double espresso (he has two or three a day) at a 12th Street cafe
around the corner from Fifth Avenue and the Benjamin N. Cardozo
School of Law at Yeshiva University, where Scheck is a professor.
Absolutely no one would call Scheck press shy, but he did restrain
himself to the ``Today'' program, an appearance on CNN and comments
to two newspapers. ``See, I'm afraid of the yuck factor,'' he said.
``It upsets me to be discussing semen on a dress in the
continuation of a presidency that held great promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheck is a rumpled, distracted and tenacious old lefty _ he was
gassed at the 1968 Democratic convention and still remembers the
order of the acts at Woodstock _ who looks as if he has just hacked
off his long hair and found a suit in the back of his closet.
</P>
<P>
   He said he became a lawyer because he wanted to change society,
but seems to have had doubts along the way. He is proudest of his
work on the Innocence Project, a shoestring program he runs at
Cardozo with another New York lawyer, Peter Neufeld, that uses DNA
evidence to reopen old cases. So far, the project has helped
exonerate 32 people wrongly convicted. Twelve were on Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any justification for being a lawyer, this is
it,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   Over his coffee, Scheck looked as if he needed to wake up, but
then talked steadily for two and a half hours. He lives in Brooklyn
Heights, is married to a psychiatric social worker, has two
children and often stays up until 1:30 a.m. reading and watching
television. ``I'm a glutton for mass culture,'' he said. He plays
golf at the Dyker Beach public course in Brooklyn. ``The 14th hole
used to have an abandoned car on it,'' he said. Friends describe
him as a regular guy but a pit bull in court.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck still defends his work on the Simpson team: ``I never
called anybody names,'' he said. He says he was not challenging the
legitimacy of DNA evidence in that case, but attacking the Los
Angeles Police Department's methods.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck's father managed Connie Francis and moved his family from
Forest Hills to the Upper East Side. Scheck first became interested
in the law while watching ``The Defenders,'' the 1960s television
series, and later interviewed the lawyer F. Lee Bailey for his
student newspaper at Horace Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the interview with Lee because Lee was dating Connie
Francis,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck was a war protester at Yale, where he was chosen to meet
with W. Averell Harriman, the chief envoy to the Paris peace talks.
``He took one look at me and turned off his hearing aid,'' Scheck
said. Scheck went to law school at the University of California at
Berkeley, then spent two years as a public defender in the South
Bronx. He has been at Cardozo since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Scheck wrote a movie script with two colleagues
about a public defender, a woman, in the South Bronx, which is
still kicking around Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think I should have gotten out of the law
entirely,'' he said seriously, ``and dedicated myself to writing
screenplays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
