<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WILL PATIENCE HELP HUNDLEY FIND GROOVE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Todd Hundley deserves praise for merely being in
left field for the Mets on Tuesday night, as he has been for most
of the last four weeks. Hundley is still not himself, but he
returned with a surgically-repaired right elbow because the Mets
have a chance for the post-season and he is supposed to make them
more imposing. It was an unselfish move.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hundley hammered his first homer of the season in
Monday's 4-2 victory over the Cardinals and is gradually showing
more continuity from the left side of the plate, he conceded that
the search continues for the right rhythm, the right stroke and the
right results. Unfortunately for the Mets, Hundley's search is
colliding with their tense pursuit of a wild-card berth. That is
not the smoothest of marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley went 10 months without swinging a bat against a major
league pitcher after undergoing reconstructive elbow surgery, which
is why his body feels like it is March. Still, Hundley has not made
excuses for his scant production and has worked diligently to make
the awkward shift from catcher to left while Mike Piazza leases
shin guards in New York for a few months. But Hundley stares at the
mirror often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's tough not to be who I know I can be,'' Hundley
said. ``That's why you have to be patient. I just got to learn to
be patient with this change and this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   That is also what the Mets feel they must do. Be patient and
wait for their best power hitter and most popular player to go
deep. Be patient and let the old Hundley emerge, as he did with one
ferocious swing Monday. But how long should their patience last?
</P>
<P>
   Despite his massive homer off Matt Morris' juicy fastball, there
have been and will continue to be frustrating times for the player
who has struck out 12 times in his last 17 plate appearances and 35
times in 83 at-bats after whiffing three times and slapping a
run-scoring single Tuesday night. Bobby Valentine, the Mets'
manager, insists that Hundley is barely missing pitches and will
not judge him on a sliver of the season. There are many reasons for
the Mets to be patient, such as Hundley's record-setting 41 homers
in 1996, his 30 bombs last year, his $21 million contract, the
potential protection he could provide Piazza in the batting order
and the absence of a superior alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll eventually come and I'll get into a groove and I'll take
off from there,'' Hundley vowed Monday night. ``Go look at every
year, and I start off slow. I've come back so it's not much of a
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not a concern today. What about in two weeks? How about a
month? The Mets do not want to be faced with the delicate questions
about a valuable player who has made a sacrifice, but they could
emerge. Hundley's memory is cloudy since he actually has more
career homers and a higher batting average in April than in any
other month. If he continues to labor, when does a .205 hitter
without consistent power behind Piazza become detrimental to a
post-season push?
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand what he's going through, and I'm with him every
step of the way,'' said Valentine, which is exactly what a manager
is supposed to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed to winning,'' said Steve Phillips, the Mets'
general manager. ``We think Todd is part of that equation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine will have to review Hundley's status sometime.
With the leadoff man Tony Phillips as a new and important catalyst,
Jermaine Allensworth added for his speed and Butch Huskey (strained
left hamstring) eligible to be activated next Tuesday, Valentine
will have a crowded outfield that also includes Hundley, Brian
McRae and Lenny Harris. McRae and Phillips will likely play every
day. Hundley could merit similar status if he did more than whiff
11 times in 12 at-bats as a right-handed hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't think this was working out, I'd tell them,'' said
Hundley, who admitted he has struggled to adapt to what he called
the ``boring world'' of the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   When Valentine was asked whether Hundley would be part of an
outfield rotation once Huskey returned, he said: ``Probably. Let's
hope he keeps playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Hundley can make sure the Mets never have to address
these delicate questions. If Hundley bashes a few homers and drives
in a batch of runs in the next week and then remains consistent,
the Mets could avoid answers they do not want to ponder. So could
Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doubts can happen,'' Hundley said. ``That's what I'm
trying not to let happen. I'm not going to let it happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
