<SLUG> BC-NYC-COLUMN-BROTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BROTHERS LAND ON THEIR SIDE OF THE DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 (mk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shrieks and squeals filled the yellow school bus as
it bounced and bumped over the potholes along the factory-lined
streets of the East Williamsburg Industrial Park. They subsided,
only to be replaced by the bouncy beats of a hip-hop song on the
radio. Bear Mountain was still an hour away, but the children from
St. Barbara's Day Camp were getting psyched for the summer's final
outing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have bus music,'' one child shouted. ``She'll be
coming 'round the mountain when she comes. Yee-haw! She'll be
coming 'round the mountain when she comes. Yee-haw!''
</P>
<P>
   Brother Rick Dixon, the camp's director, savored the exuberant
scene, speaking up only a few times to quiet the group when the
yee-haws reached rodeo riot levels. He did so reluctantly, at that,
since he knew this was a big day for youngsters who feel cooped up
in their Bushwick neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a group like this, the more ordered and controlled it is,
the easier it is for us,'' Dixon said. ``At the same time, it's not
good for human relations. I'm continually struggling with that
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus trip was a breeze compared with the demands of his own
spiritual journey as a member of the Little Brothers of the Gospel,
a tiny Roman Catholic order that practices prayer and contemplation
in neighborhoods that are poor, violent and sometimes raucous.
Odder yet to some of their neighbors, their mission is not to build
schools or hospitals, but to offer simple acts of constant
companionship. With the income gap between the rich and poor
widening, Dixon said the hardest part of his mission was to
convince others that money may help, but it doesn't heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our consumer-oriented culture, there is so much pressure,''
he said. ``The only things kids see is this drive for money,
exploitative love and sex. It's almost like we've forgotten that
profound friendship is love, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon and his confreres didn't need any studies to tell them how
rich and poor were diverging more and more. Good economic times
forced them to move to Bushwick two years ago from their longtime
home on the Lower East Side. Four of them had lived in an apartment
just steps off the Bowery on East Fourth Street until skid row gave
way to sidewalk cafes, pricey apartments and clubs of the moment.
Most of the poor families they had known over the years had
gradually been scattered to other parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lower East Side is a better community because it attracts
tourists,'' Brother Giorgio Gonella said. ``But in recent years we
felt like guests and the neighborhood belonged to the people who
went to restaurants and theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   What had once been a struggling community, he said, began to
feel more and more like a no man's land of urban individualism.
What Bushwick lacked in material wealth, they discovered soon after
their arrival two years ago this month, was offset by what it had
in human bonds. And while their neighbors first thought they were
undercover policemen, little by little they became friends with the
people they saw each day sitting outside on stoops, chatting in
bodegas or worshiping at church.
</P>
<P>
   A previous generation once measured success by the mile,
equating it with how far they could move from the neighborhood.
Jackie Gracie, a day camp counselor, credits people like Dixon for
reminding others how they can work to improve the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's willing to listen,'' Gracie said. ``He may be a brother,
but he's really like a brother from a different mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The Little Brothers call the neighborhood a little village, even
if the curses that filter into the small chapel in their apartment
would make it appear that this was hardly a place for
contemplation. Quite the opposite, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When survival is a daily challenge, somehow there is something
beautifully naked,'' Gonella said. ``The dialogue always comes down
to the basic questions. Why life? Why death? Why poverty? The more
middle-class you are, the more expert you are in the art of hiding
from the real questions. Living in a poor neighborhood, your
contemplative life is enriched by the tragedies which oblige you to
be truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to a richness of life that Gonella didn't see
being replaced any time soon by cafe society.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't come here unless you belong here,'' he said. ``So
far, we don't have any yuppies moving here. They're all going to
Williamsburg.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980811.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-BROTHEL-NYT &LR;      08-11 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BROTHEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY HAMLET JOLTED BY CHARGES THAT WOMAN RAN BROTHEL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ On Old Glen Road in this lush and
lolling hamlet, things have never been quite the same since Judith
Kelly Dempsey moved into the 20-room Georgian Colonial estate known
as Sunnymede in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   First, there were complaints about her decision to sell off some
of the property for new houses. Now, neighbors have a more
startling concern: police say Mrs. Dempsey had turned her mansion
into an all-hours bordello called An Afternoon Delight.
</P>
<P>
   At first, residents said they did not know what to think of the
car traffic and other activities at Sunnymede. Some thought Mrs.
Dempsey might have held frequent dinner parties. Others thought the
cars constantly entering and exiting her driveway were construction
workers doing renovations to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Weinlein, 71, who lives on Beechwood Drive, around the
corner from Sunnymede, said there had been rumors in the
neighborhood for months that Mrs. Dempsey was operating a brothel.
</P>
<P>
   She voiced her suspicious to a neighbor across the street.
``When I told her I thought it was a house of ill-repute,'' Ms.
Weinlein recalled, ``she said: `I think they are renting rooms. I
think its a boardinghouse.'''
</P>
<P>
   After a seven-month investigation that was initiated because of
neighbors' complaints _ including reports that men demanding
massages were knocking on their doors _ a law enforcement team led
by the Morris County prosecutor's office raided the stately home
last Wednesday. They arrested and charged four women with
prostitution and three men with soliciting prostitution. Detectives
then set up a sting operation in the mansion, and arrested and
charged another 12 men with soliciting prostitution, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dempsey, a 46-year-old former Playboy bunny who had worked
as a real estate agent, owns the home in Morris Township with her
estranged husband, Robert. Neighbors said that Mrs. Dempsey did not
have children. And they said that although Mrs. Dempsey had
organized house tours in the township for charity, she was not
particularly friendly with other residents on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dempsey was on vacation in Las Vegas at the time of the
raid. When she returned to New Jersey on Monday, she turned herself
in to the Morris Township Police, and was arrested and charged with
promoting prostitution. She was released on her own recognizance,
as were the other 19 people arrested. She faces 3 to 5 years in
prison and a fine of up to $7,500 if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dempsey's lawyer, Michael R. Ascher, said on Tuesday that
his client was innocent. ``We are going to be entering a plea of
not guilty at the appropriate time,'' Ascher said. ``And I am sure
my client is going to be vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Morris County prosecutor John B. Dangle said
Mrs. Dempsey had been charging customers $225 an hour, and that the
escort service advertised in the Daily Record, Morris County's main
newspaper, and had a phone number listed in the local Yellow Pages.
Prosecutors estimated that the brothel had been operating since
last November and that it had weekly revenues of about $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Tuesday, stunned residents of the area walked
or drove by to gawk at the mansion, which is located in a
neighborhood called Convent Station. Television camera crews and
reporters also spent much of the day on Old Glen Road. There was no
sign of Mrs. Dempsey's silver Jaguar, and a woman who responded to
knocks on the door referred all inquiries to Ascher.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Morristown area seemed abuzz Tuesday with the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an atrocity,'' said one neighbor, who declined to give
her name. ``Everybody else is working hard and trying to raise
their children and to teach them good standards, and there is this
sleazy operation going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   And this was not the first time that Mrs. Dempsey had angered
neighbors. They said Mrs. Dempsey had submitted a bid for the house
before it even went on the market, promising that she and her
husband would live there and would not parcel off pieces of the
property to developers. But they said that in recent years, several
acres of the property had been sub-divided into four lots, where
new houses were built.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-bedroom mansion is surrounded by sprawling lawns and
shrubbery. There is a wide second-floor balcony and a covered
veranda on the first floor overlooking an English garden. A
driveway leads to a three-bedroom carriage house that neighbors
said had been occupied by renters.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, Suzanne Hamlin, said that Mrs. Dempsey would often
walk to a branch of First Morris Bank, just a block away from her
house, to make large deposits in cash. Officials at the bank
declined to comment on that report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
