A9225 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  FARRAH-FAWCETT-LADN     08-11 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
FAWCETT TESTIFIES TO DOMESTIC VIOLENCE
</HEADLINE>
 FARRAH-FAWCETT-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ALEX ROTH 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Weeping on the witness stand, actress Farrah
Fawcett testified that an argument with her producer-boyfriend
about another woman led to angry words, threats, shattered windows
and a bloody cut to her head.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old former ``Charlie's Angels'' star was the first
witness against James Orr, 45, in the Santa Monica Superior Court
trial Tuesday. He faces misdemeanor battery charges in the January
scuffle outside his Bel-Air home Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught me and we struggled, and I ended up on the ground,''
the actress said, adding that she begged Orr to stop, telling him,
``I think I'm really hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said in opening statements that Orr, a
writer-producer whose movie credits include ``Mr. Destiny'' and
``Three Men and a Baby,'' is guilty of domestic abuse for banging
the actress's head against the ground. Orr's attorney said the
fight was a case of mutual combat instigated by Fawcett -- and that
prosecutors charged Orr simply because he was the man.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett's testimony came after the City Attorney's Office gave
her immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The actress acknowledged Tuesday that she was the first to get
physical. As they drove home from a restaurant, she kicked him and
grabbed his face. Shortly before the scuffle, she kicked in a
window in the door of his house. A day after the scuffle, she
returned to the house with a baseball bat and broke some more
windows, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   Orr's attorney, Donald R. Wager, accused prosecutors of taking a
``men bad, women good'' approach to domestic-violence prosecution.
He accused Fawcett of acting ``like a petulant child.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Del San Juan said prosecutors charged Orr
because he committed battery, while Fawcett's acts were simply
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision was to prosecute the more serious offenses,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Orr faces a second battery charge against Fawcett for a scuffle
in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett testified Tuesday that the January incident started with
an argument after she discovered a letter from another woman in a
garbage can outside Orr's house.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at dinner at the Belgian restaurant Mon Grenier in
suburban Encino, they argued when Orr said she took too long to
sign an autograph, Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Orr's house, Fawcett refused to get out of the car.
Later, carrying a baseball bat she'd found in the back seat, she
went into the house to pack some belongings. She said she took the
bat ``as a statement to say, Leave me alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The arguing continued inside the house, with Fawcett picking up
a fire poker and later threatening Orr with a drum-set stand, she
testified. Orr responded by jabbing her with a bar stool, bruising
her arm, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she left his house, he called her a vulgar name and walked
back inside. She responded by kicking in a window pane in the door
and running away, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Orr stormed out of the house and wrestled her to the ground,
banging her head against the pavement at least twice, she
testified, opening a wound on her head.
</P>
<P>
   She said she refused to go to the hospital for fear he'd be
arrested. But a day later, she and her personal assistant returned
to his house, she said. She also brought a bat. The two argued
again, and she began smashing his den windows. Orr's attorney said
she caused $5,000 worth of damage.
</P>
<P>
   The two continued dating after the fight and Fawcett threw Orr a
birthday party in March, but the couple broke up recently, Wager
said. Fawcett referred to him as ``Mr. Orr'' during her testimony
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
