<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD TAKING A CUT EVEN BEFORE THE FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of months ago at a charity golf tournament in New
Jersey, Evander Holyfield joked that he would probably have to pay
out of his own pocket to make a bout against Vaughn Bean, the
International Boxing Federation's No. 1 contender.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Holyfield is taking a cut in his normal purse ($8
million to $10 million) and is tying his purse to a percentage of
the gate at the Georgia Dome for his title defense against Bean on
Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's lawyer, would not estimate the
champion's purse, but said it would be less than $3 million, even
if ticket sales were strong.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield isn't the only one to get an early start on the season
of giving. Showtime will broadcast the bout during a free preview
weekend, which means that more than 60 million homes in America
that have cable will have access to the fight at no cost. Could
this largess have been prompted by the unwillingness of casinos in
Las Vegas and Atlantic City, N.J., as well as pay-per-view outlets,
to pay big fees for an unappealing fight?
</P>
<P>
   ``We could sell this fight to Atlantic City or Vegas today and
make more money, because the ticket prices would be higher,'' said
Jay Larkin, head of programming at Showtime, speaking by telephone
from a news conference in Atlanta on Tuesday to officially announce
the Holyfield-Bean bout. ``But Evander wanted this fight in Atlanta
and everyone, Showtime, Don King and Evander, stepped up to make it
happen. Evander agreed to tie his purse to the performance of the
gate. He's taking a huge financial risk, which flies in the face of
all the critics who say he's only out to make as much money as he
can for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time that Holyfield fought in Atlanta was in 1991. Not
many people turned out at the Omni to see him defeat Bert Cooper.
But since then Holyfield has cemented his claim on the heavyweight
championship by beating Mike Tyson twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Dome, which seats 76,000 for football, will
accommodate 40,000 seats for the fight. Many of the seats will be
priced between $35 and $25. The top price is $500.
</P>
<P>
   The parties involved will have to hustle to sell the bout in
Atlanta, which isn't noted as a boxing town.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Thomas said that King has come up with several
novel promotional ideas to push the fight in his hometown.
Holyfield will train for two weeks in Houston and spend the final
four weeks leading up to the fight training at two different gyms
in Atlanta. ``It's a much different task getting 40,000 people to
come out in Atlanta than it is to get 12,000 gamblers to come to a
fight in Las Vegas,'' Thomas said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
