<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-TICKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD SERIES' FIRST DOUBLE: BOX SEAT PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deciding that World Series tickets were vastly undervalued,
Major League Baseball has doubled the price of box seats for its
premier event, from $75 to $150.
</P>
<P>
   The executive council took that step at a meeting last June,
commissioner Bud Selig said Tuesday, but the development was never
announced and came to light only this week when teams sent letters
to season-ticket holders telling them of post-season prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the sensitivity of it and I share those
concerns,'' Selig said by telephone from Milwaukee. ``But I think
this is the right thing to do. Frankly, our own people have been
critical that we were undervaluing the tickets for our premier
event. The discussion was spirited though in the end unanimous.''
</P>
<P>
   The top price of $150 for a World Series game is still
considerably less than the top prices for other championship
events.
</P>
<P>
   The top ticket price for last January's Super Bowl was $350,
with the rest at $275. The price has not been set for the next
Super Bowl. For the Stanley Cup finals, the Washington Capitals
charged $250 for their best seats; the Detroit Red Wings, $200. The
Chicago Bulls had 100 courtside seats available for $475 each for
the National Basketball Association finals, but the top price for
other seats was $90. The Utah Jazz had a top regular price of $113
and had five rows of seats at courtside available at $180 to $300
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of discussion comparing our price with the prices
of the best seats at other championship events,'' Selig said. ``My
father always used to say nothing is good or bad except by
comparison. So when you look at $150 for a World Series box seat,
it's still a lot less than the top ticket for the other events.''
</P>
<P>
   Clubs can charge even more than $150 for premium World Series
seats. The Yankees, for example, will have club box seats with
waitress service for $300 each. Those seats will cost $150 for the
league championship series and $100 for the division series.
</P>
<P>
   In parks where clubs have two levels of box seats, lower and
upper, they may charge $120 instead of $150 for the upper boxes.
The price of reserved seats was raised from $50 to $100, although
upper reserved can be $85. General admission tickets will cost $40,
up from $30 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Price increases are more moderate for the series leading to the
World Series. For the league championship series, box seats are
going from $50 to $60, reserved seats from $35 to $45 and general
admission from $25 to $30. For the division series, clubs can set
prices within a range of $17.50 to $30, up from a range of $17.50
to $25 last year.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Milwaukee Brewers, Selig said: ``I would
always agonize over ticket increases, even $1. But in the end, you
can make a very compelling case for the World Series, considering
the undervaluing and comparison with other events.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
