<HEADER>
A9234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-RUNOFFVOTE-COX     08-11 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-RUNOFFVOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats pick Taylor; Day leads GOP bid for lieutenant
 &HT;    By Charmagne Helton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ State Sen. Mary Margaret Oliver wanted to be Georgia's
first female lieutenant governor. But that dream seems not to be
coming true this year.
</P>
<P>
   With 74 percent of precincts reporting statewide Tuesday, Oliver
trailed fellow state Sen. Mark Taylor of Albany by about 50,000
votes for the Democratic nomination. His lead appeared too great to
overcome even with DeKalb and Fulton county precincts _ both
considered Oliver strongholds _ still out.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press called the race for Taylor around 9:15
p.m., but Oliver's supporters were still hoping for a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not ready to concede,'' campaign consultant Angelo
Fuster said around 9:30 p.m. ``We're waiting on the metro
counties.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican race for lieutenant governor, Clint Day was
leading Mitch Skandalakis, 54 percent to 46 percent, with
three-fourths of precincts reporting statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press also gave early victories in two other
statewide races. Michael Thurmond beat Steve Henson in the race for
the Democratic nomination for labor commissioner, and David Ralston
defeated Kip Klein for the Republican nomination for attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   In a runoff election in the middle of August with few
high-profile contested races, only the most loyal voters were
expected to return to the polls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, that often means Christian conservatives. For
the Democrats, that normally means traditional liberals. Knowing
this, the candidates for lieutenant governor tried to appeal to
those voter bases.
</P>
<P>
   Day and Skandalakis each called himself the ``true
conservative'' candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race has been entirely about trust and truth,'' said Day.
``We have a conservative record.''
</P>
<P>
   Day, a 39-year-old former state senator, sought to tarnish any
appeal to conservatives Skandalakis might have by running TV
commercials that reminded voters the Fulton County Commission
chairman created a gay and lesbian task force.
</P>
<P>
   Day also accused Skandalakis of waffling on abortion, trying to
bring casino gambling to Georgia and paying for phone calls to
strippers during a 1994 trip to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Skandalakis, 40, appeared to be the GOP front-runner before
Tuesday's runoff. He accused Day, a millionaire, of failing to pay
his taxes and of desecrating Native American burial grounds. Citing
an endorsement by a gay-oriented newspaper, Skandalakis said Day,
not he, was the gay community's favored candidate. In the
Democratic runoff, Taylor called Oliver soft on crime, but he
admitted early on in the campaign to past cocaine use. He
apologized, calling it a ``youthful indiscretion,'' and insisted he
hadn't used the illegal drug since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver ran TV commercials and distributed mailings to remind
voters of her opponent's drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
