<SLUG> BC-BLOWER-BAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION LETS AIR OUT OF LOS ANGELES' BAN ON GAS-POWERED LEAF
BLOWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Rendering Los Angeles' leaf-blower ban
essentially useless, the City Attorney's Office said that it won't
prosecute gardeners who say they fuel their machines with methanol,
rather than gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and police said they will rely upon sworn
declarations from gardeners that they are using methanol and will
not check the fuel or machines.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski said Tuesday she will ask her
colleagues as soon as next week to close the methanol loophole,
which was used successfully to beat defeat tickets in three court
cases recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts' rulings are pretty solid, so we need to look at
the law _ and change the law,'' said Miscikowski, who pushed for
the ban that won final approval on a 9-6 vote in January.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the council amends the law, a bill now
pending in the California Legislature could remove Los Angeles'
ability to impose such a ban unless approved by a citywide vote.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 14, authored by Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles,
also would regulate blowers in terms of noise, not fuel type.
Polanco's chief aide, Bill Mabie, predicts that the bill will win
Assembly approval within three weeks and then will garner the
Senate's backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans support it because they look at these ordinances
as government intrusion on essentially small-business people,''
Mabie said. ``The Democrats tend to support it because of the issue
of workers' (rights) to use their tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners hailed Tuesday's concession by the City Attorney's
Office as a key victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very optimistic and excited that we triumphed in the
courts,'' said Alvaro Huerta, secretary general of the Association
of Latin American Gardeners of Los Angeles, which has a membership
of more than 1,000 people citywide.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the City Attorney's Office said it would dismiss a
ticket against a gardener after three defeats in court in which
tickets were overturned on the basis of the fuel used.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said a gardener who is cited from now on for using a
leaf blower can avoid prosecution by providing a sworn declaration
as to the type of fuel used and a declaration from the person who
modified the machine to run on methanol.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Thomas, chief of the City Attorney's Criminal Division,
said that the courts have made it impossible for his office to
prosecute the leaf-blower ban when gardeners claim to use methanol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts us in a pretty tough position given the courts'
rulings on the ordinance,'' Thomas said. ``We can't just ignore
that.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 27, Municipal Court Judge Elizabeth Allen White threw
out $270 tickets against two gardeners because they had used
methanol, which is not covered by the city law.
</P>
<P>
   City officials and police said they have no intention of
verifying whether the gardeners' leaf blower actually was using
methanol. But to guard against fraud, Thomas said his office plans
to review each contested ticket when the methanol exemption is
claimed.
</P>
<P>
   But most claims will be accepted on face value as a show of good
faith to the Los Angeles law firm, Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro, that
has been representing the gardeners for free in leaf-blower cases,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury attorney Kimberly Buffington said her office had four
remaining leaf-blower tickets that will be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge victory,'' Buffington said.
</P>
<P>
   The council could begin debating Miscikowski's amendment as soon
as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Until the law changes, Miscikowski said the ban on
gasoline-powered leaf blowers will be difficult for police and
inspectors to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to discern by smell or look between gas and
methanol so a person on the street wouldn't know it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Hernandez, who opposed the ban, said he has not
decided whether to support the amendment because he believes the
law specifically was written to outlaw gasoline-powered blowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep referring to this as a loophole when the reality
is we were outlawing gasoline leaf blowers,'' Hernandez said. ``We
never discussed the type of fuel, only the pollutants.''
</P>
<P>
   A supporter of the ban, West Los Angeles attorney Jack Allen of
the Coalition to Ban Leafblowers, said the City Attorney's Office
should not have conceded the methanol exemption so easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should fight it in court,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners association President Adrian Alvarez said his group
will work to find other loopholes. ``We're not going back to brooms
and rakes, so we're going to continue to protest and find legal
challenges to the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city should simply ban blowers that use internal-combustion
engines, lest the gardeners find another way around the law, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The association believes Polanco's bill may be the best
compromise and members went to Sacramento last week to lobby
lawmakers for support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2333EDT &QL; 
