<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONTECH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TECHNOLOGY/DAVID EINSTEIN  
 APPLE'S IMAC _ THE NEW VW BEETLE OF COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - ON TECHNOLOGY   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Most tech stocks took a tumble yesterday, but not Apple Computer.
The Cupertino company blithely ignored the market's sell-off,
gaining $1.06 to close at a 52-week high of $39.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clearly, Steve Jobs, Apple's interim CEO for life, is onto
something with the $1,299 iMac, which ships this Saturday. He's hit
a chord just as he did in 1984, when the first Macintosh captured
the public's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The curious thing is that he's doing it without a technological
breakthrough like the graphical interface that the original Mac
introduced to the world. In fact, the iMac is basically just a Mac
honed by improvements you'd expect after 18 years, with a built-in
monitor and a seductive translucent case that would look right at
home in Tomorrowland.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac appeals to the average person, who is basically
befuddled by technology and just wants a computer that's easy to
use. Forget the megahertzes and the gigabytes, just get me on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the market right now is ripe for a machine like the
iMac. With entry-level PC prices well below $1,000, computers have
entered the realm of commodity appliances such as televisions and
stereos.
</P>
<P>
   Does anybody care how many watts a stereo amplifier has? Or how
many lines of resolution there are on a TV? No. You just plug the
things in and enjoy them.
</P>
<P>
   Apple is lucky in a way. It can't compete on price/performance
with the Compaqs and Dells of the world. But it doesn't have to.
Nobody needs a 400 MHz Pentium II or an 8 gig hard drive. The
technology inside the iMac is more than adequate for almost
anything a normal person would do with a computer, including word
processing, desktop publishing or, most importantly, getting
online.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Internet seems to have become the driving motivation
for purchases of new computers. And if what you really want is to
surf the Web and do e-mail, the iMac is a match for any PC, no
matter how powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The new Apple is a little ahead of its time, equipped as it is
only with USB ports for connecting printers, scanners and such. It
probably won't be until late this year that USB-compatible devices
start hitting the market en masse. Meanwhile, a few scanners, mice,
keyboards and modems are available with USB connectors.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, however, all PC-makers will convert to USB, phasing
out serial and parallel ports that have confused consumers for a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs' decision not to put a floppy disk drive in the iMac also
shows his predisposition toward future-tech. As recordable CD-ROM
drives and DVDs catch on, floppies probably will go the way of the
dinosaur. Still, it would have cost Apple just a few bucks to put a
floppy drive in the iMac and give users a convenient way to back up
and exchange data.
</P>
<P>
   From the advance rumblings, it seems certain that iMacs will be
gobbled up by Apple users who can't afford the faster, more
expensive G3 Macs. The big question is, will the new computer also
appeal to first-time PC buyers who might otherwise go for a cheap
Compaq or HP machine?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it might. One gets the feeling that other PC-makers
consider entry-level systems as step-children that cower in the
shadow of the high-end, $2,500 screamers. Apple, on other hand, has
imbued the iMac with a hip personality all its own.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it hurt that the iMac comes along at a time when
Americans are happily embracing post-modernistic designs. If
Volkswagen can sell a truckload of the revivified Beetle, Apple
should find a wide market for the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-98 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
