r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREETSMARTS-SFCHRON-     08-11 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREETSMARTS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK VEVERKA/STREET SMARTS  
 BEHIND THE HIGH-LEVEL DEPARTURES AT HAMBRECHT &AMP; QUIST 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Time to batten down the hatches at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist?
<TEXT>
<P>
   After unsuccessfully trying to sell the niche investment bank to
a larger suitor _ in contrast to its Bay Area brethren Robertson
Stephens and Montgomery Securities _ H&AMP;Q is suffering from some
defections and dismissals among its research ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The highest profile departure is that of Bruce Lupatkin,
director of the bank's research department. Sources close to the
company say that Lupatkin was shown the door after a number of
highly regarded analysts jumped ship. The reason: He failed to
provide adequate leadership and direction to the department, and
the quality of the research sometimes suffered, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;Q chief executive Dan Case confirmed that Lupatkin had left
the company, but he would not expound on the terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an exceptional professional and we wish him well,''
Case says.
</P>
<P>
   At least three researchers have bailed from H&AMP;Q, including
Shelly Hale Young and Jean-Michele Valet _ who were both
well-respected consumer product analysts, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the revolving door suggests that H&AMP;Q might be
back in play. Because if it were bought by a larger brokerage or
major financial institution, the research department would likely
be the first to go.
</P>
<P>
   But sources close to the company say buyout talks haven't
rekindled. If anything, the opposite is true. The window for a
takeover of H&AMP;Q may have shut, and management is trying to preserve
its franchise as a nimble underwriter of technology companies,
sources say.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;Q's stock is trading below $30, down substantially from the
low $40s when takeover talk ran rampant late last year. Case would
not comment on speculation regarding future ownership of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   But sources say Case is telling the troops that the boutique
investment bank is prepared to stand alone now that Robby Stephens
and Montgomery Securities have been swallowed by BankBoston and
NationsBanc respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were in his position, I would say the same thing,'' says
one hedge fund manager, who watches the company closely.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR; Net Madness
</P>
<P>
   The latest installment of Internet madness opened with a bang,
but it wasn't without its moments of high drama.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday was not the ideal day for GeoCities of Santa Monica to
go public as the stock market took on water like an ocean liner
pierced by an iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet portal company kept a stiff upper lip during
its first day of trading, despite the Dow Jones industrial average
sinking more than 250 points at one point. (The Dow made a
late-inning rally to close only 112 points down at the bell).
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, GeoCities more than doubled its initial offering
price of $17 to end the day at $37.31. The company, which generates
Net traffic by letting users set up free Web sites, sold 4.75
million shares, or a 15 percent stake. Its market cap is now a
whopping $1.1 billion. The initial filing with the Securities and
Exchange commission pegged the initial price range at $12 to $14.
Goldman Sachs was the lead underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market was going to hell in a hand basket, and that's a
very difficult market (in which) to float a new offering,'' says
Ryan Jacob, portfolio manager for the Internet Fund, a $3.5 million
no-load fund based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, doubling the price in your first day isn't too
shabby.''
</P>
<P>
   Shabby or not, it wasn't the kind of off-the-charts performance
that many portal-stock fans expected. Jacob surmises that if the
IPO had been priced on a less-tumultuous day, its opening price
(which was around $20) would have been significantly higher.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with that thinking based on the unearthly
performances of other Internet offerings launched earlier this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the fact that GeoCities saw support for its shares
build throughout the day was testimony to how strongly (rightly or
wrongly) Internet stock zealots felt about the company _ despite
the weird and wacky vacillations of the current market, says Jacob,
also research director for the IPO Value Monitor, an institutional
service owned by Horizon Management in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Despite GeoCities's noble showing in the face of
market-adversity, there were some unhappy campers out there.
</P>
<P>
   One way to play the GeoCities IPO was to buy shares in one of
its largest shareholders, CMG Information Services (CMGI) of
Andover, Md.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI owns 9.8 million shares of GeoCities, or a 31 percent
stake. Its shares soared last week in anticipation of yesterday's
GeoCities IPO, but those same shares plunged $5 to $74.25 in the
wake of yesterday's offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit of a letdown for CMGI shareholders,'' says
Jacob.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF 94103,
by phone at 415-777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He
also appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak on Tuesdays and Thursdays.  &LR;
</P>
