<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS ADDS WHOWHERE WEB DIRECTORY  
 BY JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - LYCOS   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Upping the ante in an increasingly crowded Internet portal market,
Lycos Inc. yesterday said it will snap up Mountain View-based
online directory WhoWhere Inc. for $133 million in stock.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not to be outmaneuvered, rival Infoseek laid out $17 million in
company shares for Quando Inc., a maker of ``virtual databases''
allowing Net surfers to comparison shop.
</P>
<P>
   The buyouts are the latest machinations among online and
mainstream media companies vying to create so-called portal sites.
</P>
<P>
   They believe the all-in-one sites _ which are crammed with
e-mail, chat rooms, e-commerce features, breaking news and search
engines _ are the most efficient way to hook Web users and generate
advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any serious Web site needs to offer services that make
people's lives easier for basic activities like communications and
shopping,'' Infoseek CEO Harry Motro said. ``If you don't, you
won't be around long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a land grab,'' said Jan Horsfall, Lycos vice president of
marketing. ``You have to add as much distinct content as you
possibly can to differentiate your (portal).''
</P>
<P>
   Internet insiders said the more significant deal is Lycos'
acquisition of WhoWhere, a provider of e-mail and home-age
technology, yellow-page and white-page listings, classified ads and
other information on the Web. The company's MailCity e-mail service
has 9.3 million registered users.
</P>
<P>
   Observers consider the acquisition significant to the fortunes
of 3-year-old Lycos in the portal wars because it is trailing
Infoseek, Yahoo, Excite, AOL and Netscape in both viewership and ad
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are comparing the portal market to the television
industry, where only five or seven major networks will survive,''
said Abhishek Gami of William Blair &AMP; Co. LLC in Chicago, who
recommends Lycos stock. ``In the process, every independent company
will be bought out by one of the big boys. This is an extremely
rough space to compete in.''
</P>
<P>
   Gami noted that of the 15 most popular Internet sites listed by
online pollster Media Metrix, Lycos is among the smallest.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, like Amazon.com and other Internet companies, has been
using its stock to buy companies since its shares more than tripled
in the past year. Lycos closed at $63.56 yesterday, down $4.38.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Earlier this year, the Waltham, Mass., company purchased
Tripod Inc., a free home-page service, and WiseWire Corp., whose
software allows Internet users to make customized searches.
</P>
<P>
   WhoWhere, which is backed by the Rockefeller family's venture
capital arm VenRock, will operate as the West Coast division of
Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
