<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOBE CLEANS HOUSE, PLANS SHUFFLE, LAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - ADOBE   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Warning of an expected earnings drop, Adobe Systems yesterday
announced a management shakeup and plans to lay off up to 10
percent of its worldwide workforce.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's second-largest maker of PC software, known for
graphics and desktop publishing programs such as Adobe Photoshop,
Illustrator and PageMaker, said it will save $50 million to $60
million per year in part by laying off 240 to 300 full-time
employees and contractors. Adobe also plans to streamline
operations and eliminate three senior vice president positions.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the San Jose-based company said net income for the
third quarter, which ends August 28, ``may approach break-even or a
loss'' after a one-time restructuring charge, compared with net
income of $53.4 million in the third quarter of 1997. Previously,
analysts surveyed by First Call had forecast a third-quarter profit
of 52 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe said third-quarter revenues are expected to be between
$220 million and $225 million, down from $230 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe's earnings projections ``are disappointing,'' company
President Charles Geschke said in an interview. ``It was altogether
clear we had to do some restructuring on the spending side to get
our current numbers under control and so we had headroom to invest
in new product opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   All but 25 of the layoffs will be full-time employees and will
include an undetermined number of vice president and other
management positions.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe has about 3,000 employees and contractors worldwide, with
about 1,500 in the Bay Area, said spokeswoman Wink Grelis. The
layoffs are expected to be completed by the end of the third
quarter, but Adobe has not disclosed which jobs will be cut, Grelis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they were encouraged that the restructuring puts
Geschke and CEO John Warnock, two former Xerox PARC researchers who
founded Adobe, in more-direct control of the firm's future product
development and marketing plans. However, Adobe still has to prove
that it can deliver new products and generate more revenue,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a great franchise, but unfortunately, they haven't
been able to show revenue growth,'' said Christopher Galvin, an
analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, which has rated Adobe stock a hold
for the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of execution,'' Galvin said. ``Adobe has this
great opportunity to turn their leadership position in the print
marketplace into the Web world, but they're still working on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst John Rossi of BancAmerica Robertson Stephens said Adobe
still seems to be moving too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking about fast-moving markets like the Internet
and enterprise applications for document management,'' Rossi said.
``The idea is to get the products out there and start marketing. I
want to hear more urgency in the voices of the people in this
company. It's almost a do-or-die period for Adobe.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the restructuring, three senior executives
resigned: P. Jackson Bell, chief administrative officer and
executive vice president; Robert Roblin, executive vice president
for marketing; and Ross Bott, executive vice president in charge of
the products division. Their positions were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   In their places, Bruce Chizen, head of Adobe's Graphics Products
division and a former Claris Corp. executive, was promoted to
executive vice president for worldwide products and marketing.
Chizen will report directly to Warnock.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Covert was promoted from vice president of finance and
operations to chief financial officer and senior vice president.
Covert held CFO positions with Philips Electronics, ISC Systems
Corporation and Northern Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Geschke said the three departing executives were not forced to
resign, but chose to do so after Adobe decided to have its product
engineering and marketing divisions report to one boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found ourselves having difficulty making decisions
efficiently,'' Geschke said.
</P>
<P>
   Chizen said marketing and products ``were two distinct
organizations, and communicating between them took a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring announcement came after the market closed.
Adobe was down $1.38 to $30.81 per share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
