<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA FIRMS GRAB BIGGEST SHARE OF VENTURE CAPITAL IN
2ND  QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - VENTURE   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Despite a volatile stock market, institutional investors continued
to pour money into high-tech and other startups during the past
quarter.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Venture capital firms invested $1.1 billion in 168 Bay Area
companies in the three months ending June 30. That was up from $773
million invested in 119 local companies in the first quarter,
according to VentureOne, a San Francisco research firm. The total
also was higher than the $1 billion poured into 161 companies
during the second quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Three quarters of the companies that received venture capital
commitments in the past quarter were information technology firms.
But the one that received the most is in health care. Vascular
Systems, founded four years ago in Mountain View to develop
intravenous drugs to prevent and treat life-threatening blood
clots, raised $21.55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that won financing in the past quarter include:
</P>
<P>
   _Whisper Communications. The Sunnyvale maker of automated
meter-reading systems quietly raised $20 million to expand
production of its pager-sized radio device that fits in an
electric, gas or water meter.
</P>
<P>
   The device can transmit meter readings every 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The technology not only spares utilities the cost of sending out
workers to read meters, but it can take readings every 15 minutes.
This would allow utilities to price energy for peak and nonpeak
periods just as telephone and cellular phone companies now price
their services.
</P>
<P>
   Whisper CEO Mick Mullagh says his company's system allows
two-way communication, unlike competing products from public
companies CellNet and Itron.
</P>
<P>
   If radio transmission doesn't go through the first time,
Whisper's technology could tell the meter to store the information
and resend it later. Whisper has several contracts, including one
to supply meter-reading components for 1.1 million customers served
by Illinois Power.
</P>
<P>
   As part of pricing strategies to reduce peak demand and
utilities' investments in new power plants, Mullagh says electric
utilities could adjust home thermostats (with the owner's
permission) to cut energy use and consumer bills during peak hours.
</P>
<P>
   _Quokka Sports. The San Francisco company, which covers
international sporting events online, raised more than $14 million.
Started two years ago and named for an Australian marsupial, the
company covered the nine-month, round-the-world Whitbread yacht
race, providing a stream of digital photos, instrument readings,
e-mails and other information.
</P>
<P>
   The company specializes in what CEO Alan Ramadan calls ``total
sports immersion coverage.'' By wiring racers, climbers and other
athletes in the same way NASA tracks astronauts, Quokka intends to
``transform spectators into participants.''
</P>
<P>
   _allapartments.com. This year-old San Francisco company provides
more than 5 million online listings of rental units in over 4,000
U.S. cities. It provides photos and floor plans as well as other
information about schools, insurance, crime rates and career
resources.
</P>
<P>
   The company was started by Marcus &AMP; Millichap Real Estate
Investment Brokerage and raised $10 million in second-round
financing from three venture capital firms and Netscape CEO Jim
Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more companies are integrating electronic commerce
strategies in their business plans,'' said VentureOne research
director Jean Yaremchuk.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, venture firms invested $3.2 billion in 467 companies
during the past quarter. As usual, Bay Area companies were the main
magnet, attracting 34 percent of all the dollars. Venture capital
firms are flush with cash from pension funds and other
institutional investors. In the first half of this year, VC funds
raised $7 billion, or 34 percent more than the $5.2 billion raised
in the same period last year, according to Venture Economics.
Meanwhile, the average fund size nearly doubled to $112.2 million
from $65.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   A record number of companies are receiving venture capital. But
worries about Asia's economies and the outlook for U.S. stocks has
kept quite a few private companies from selling stakes to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of the year, only 48 companies backed by
venture capital had initial public offerings, compared with 60 in
the first half of 1997. The leading venture investors were Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers of Menlo Park, which backed 6 IPOs, and
BancAmerica Robertson Stephens of San Francisco, which backed five.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that technology continues to create
unparalleled opportunities,'' said Jay Hoag, general partner of
Technology Crossover Ventures in Palo Alto. His firm invested in
allapartments as well as Autoweb, a Santa Clara startup that helps
consumers research, buy and sell new and used cars online.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news for venture capitalists is that so much money is
chasing the hottest deals that venture firms are having to pay more
for their early investment stakes. As a result, Hoag suspects, ``we
won't enjoy the 40 percent to 60 percent annual returns of the past
couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology Crossover Partners is unusual in that it invests in
both private and public companies. Because many fast-growing
high-tech companies have lost 25 to 50 percent of their value in
recent weeks, Hoag figures that some are better bargains than
startups.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what's happening in the public markets today,'' Hoag
said, ``it makes sense to selectively invest in companies that are
growing 40 to 50 percent a year and selling at 25 times estimated
earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
