<SLUG> BC-GLF-APPLEBY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLEBY DISCUSSES WIFE'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
 PGA FEATURE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Stuart Appleby's professional golfing life
turned around when he won the Honda Classic in Coral Springs, Fla.,
last year, but his entire life was devastated last month. After
competing in the British Open, he watched in disbelief on a London
street as his wife, Renay, was pinned between two cars while the
couple were exiting a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Her death sent a shock wave through the world of golf, but
Appleby has managed to interrupt his mourning to prepare for the
80th PGA Championship that begins Thursday at Sahalee Country Club.
Appleby broke down twice Tuesday as he answered questions about
what life has been like, about returning to his native Australia
for the funeral, and about returning to golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's baby steps,'' he said on a few occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here on normal terms. It's quite obvious what
happened. If you've got questions, fire away. I'm quite comfortable
being here talking about whatever you need to ask me about this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that when I came back, I had to do this. It's probably
one of the easiest things. It's nothing. It's something I could not
avoid. Maybe that's part of the process, trying to move on, take
one step at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a loss of a person very close to me. It's just a very
unusual circumstance, so I've got to reassure everyone that I'm OK.
There's no preferences dealt out when someone disappears from life
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby is a native of the farming village of Cohuma in the
southeast state of Victoria, and Renay caddied for him when he came
to the United States to play on the Nike Tour in 1995. He was moved
to tears when her name came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to feel, what to say,'' said Appleby. I wish
I could correct myself a little easier, have a plan of where I want
to go. It's just one day at a time, and I'm just trying to find
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good at best. I feel terrible at worst. It's a feeling
I would never want to wish upon anyone _ the feeling you have so
many qusetions but can't find answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a little bit of time. I'll be OK. I'd say the toughest
time is when you do a lot of thinking, when you just wish things
were different. I've had a lot of support, which makes a lot of
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's been fantastic, but no one can replace that person
and how she made me feel. I've just got to get used to the
memories, and as time goes on, the memories will make me happier
and happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of good times, and I feel very lucky that I knew
her. The time we spent together was really good quality, and I
don't have any regrets. I feel she was the first prize of a raffle,
and I was lucky enough to win her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's changed me and my life. She's changed a lot of people's
lives. She obviously was only here for a short time, but she had a
very big impact on a lot of people. It was sort of tough to decide
whether I was going to come back and how quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby, who hasn't returned to his home in Isleworth, Fla.,
since Renay's death July 23, remembers the details vividly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two parked cars,'' he said. ``And we were sort of
double-parked next to each other. We were in a taxi. We were
getting luggage out. We already had some luggage out. I was just
finishing the last items and paying the cab when the driver
opposite us reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt Renay was near me when the car backed up and hit her. I
turned to see the car still reversing. The car stopped when it hit
the other car. Then obviously, the car went forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called for an ambulance. I was there with another
gentleman, and we were doing CPR and heart massage and were trying
to find a pulse. It wasn't that scary at the time. I didn't feel
very upset. I was very surprised at how calm I felt. I knew it was
a serious situation, but I felt like I had it under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, a neighbor of Appleby in Ilseworth, also talked
about the tragedy Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad time,'' Woods said. ``I saw him for the first
time yesterday, and it was tough to even talk to him. I almost
teared up on the spot. I get a little choked up talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a player's standpoint, everyone here has been open arms,
open heart. We welcome him back and we just want to say if he ever
needs us, he can find us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
